<DATE_TIME> 1999-01-08 00:03 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4200 &Cx1f; tab-z
r a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-DOLLAR-DANGER-ECONOMI     01-08 0972
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-DOLLAR-DANGER-ECONOMIST-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THE GREENBACK'S SCARY SLIDE AGAINST THE YEN AND EURO  
 
</HEADLINE>
   (This excellent 750-word ``separate buy'' article is from the
current (week beginning 9 Jan. 1999) Economist magazine.)  
  
 (EDITORS: We regret that this material is NOT available to clients
in Canada except to The Toronto Globe &AMP; Mail.)  
  
 (To publish this article, it must be purchased from the New York
Times Syndicate in New York at 1-800-972-3550 or 212-499-3333, or
fax us at 212-499-3382.)  
  
 (PLEASE NOTE: This article has been transmitted into the ``f''
financial news, ``a'' domestic/general news and ``k'' commentary
news files.)  
  
 c.1999 Economist Newspaper Ltd.  
 (Distributed by the New York Times Special Features)  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Like all parents, European politicians were this week proudly
showing off their new baby. The birth of the euro, Europe's single
currency, was superbly smooth. How strong the new currency was,
they boasted, as it crept up against the dollar.
</P>
<P>
   Yet the world's focus on the euro makes it easy to miss an even
bigger currency development.
</P>
<P>
   The slide in the dollar against the yen could, if it persists,
have serious consequences for the world economy.
</P>
<P>
   On the surface, the dollar's fall is bizarre. Japan's economy is
depressed; America's is booming. But for how long?
</P>
<P>
   The dollar fell below YEN 110 this week, after Eisuke
Sakakibara, a top Japanese official, suggested that the American
economy looked ``bubble-like.'' Who better to judge than the
Japanese? They experienced a bubble themselves in the late 1980s _
with severe economic costs ever since.
</P>
<P>
   America's record-breaking expansion has been overly dependent on
unsustainable forces, leaving the economy with an overvalued stock
market, a negative personal-savings rate, and a big current-account
deficit that will entail almost $300 billion-worth of foreign
borrowing this year.
</P>
<P>
   The three are linked: cheap money and surging shares have
encouraged consumers to save less and to spend more; rampant
spending has sucked in imports, swelling the current-account
deficit.
</P>
<P>
   The dollar has shrugged off the deficit over the past few years
as foreign savings have flooded into America.
</P>
<P>
   In turn, the dollar's strength has not only made American assets
appear more attractive to foreign investors; it has also helped to
hold down inflation and has lent support to the theory that America
was undergoing an economic miracle that justified ever rising share
prices. The snag is that virtuous circles can easily turn vicious.
</P>
<P>
   At some point, foreign investors will no longer be prepared to
finance America's current-account hole. That leaves the economy
vulnerable.
</P>
<P>
   Weakness in corporate investment or sagging consumer spending
could make shares collapse, in turn hitting consumer and business
spending even harder; a simultaneously tumbling dollar might prompt
the Fed to raise interest rates.
</P>
<P>
   The world would suffer too: an American recession would not only
dent global growth, it would also encourage protectionist pressures
at home.
</P>
<P>
   While America is saving too little and spending too much, Japan
has the opposite problem: it is saving too much and spending too
little.
</P>
<P>
   The way to correct these imbalances is not through massive
exchange-rate movements of the sort that might be under way, but by
policy changes in both Japan and the United States. Indeed, recent
exchange-rate swings are a signal that current policies are flawed.
</P>
<P>
   To reflate its sick economy, the Bank of Japan needs to print
massive quantities of money. By fostering the expectation of future
inflation, that might get consumers to start spending again.
</P>
<P>
   In America, by contrast, monetary policy has been too loose over
the past couple of years. If interest rates had been raised earlier
to check the stock market and to curb the growth in consumer
spending, America's economy might now be in better balance.
</P>
<P>
   True, the fragile state of the world economy argues against a
rise in American rates right now; but in retrospect the Fed was
probably wrong to cut rates so eagerly last year. The bubble will
eventually burst anyway, but it would have been better to prick it
sooner at the cost of a mild recession than to risk a deeper
recession later.
</P>
<P>
   In the medium term, the beneficiary of dollar weakness may be
the euro, not the yen.
</P>
<P>
   This is already generating fears that it might make European
exports uncompetitive. So many European (and even some Japanese)
politicians have been floating the notion of target zones to
stabilize the world's three big currencies.
</P>
<P>
   Such zones would oblige central banks to set interest rates to
keep their currencies within fixed bands.
</P>
<P>
   All central banks, including the European Central Bank, take
account of the exchange rate when setting interest rates. An
appreciation is equivalent to a tightening of monetary conditions _
it reduces growth and pushes down prices _ and may justify lower
interest rates, and vice versa. But going further and setting
precise targets for exchange rates would be a bad idea.
</P>
<P>
   If the target zones were too narrow they would quickly break
down; or, worse, they might undermine the overriding goal of price
stability. If they were too broad, they would be irrelevant.
</P>
<P>
   Politicians and central bankers should focus on getting their
policies right _ leaving currencies, even new ones, to crawl, sink
or swim. &QL; 
 &UR; ___________________ &LR;  &QC; 
 &UR; (To publish this 750-word article, it must be purchased from the
New York Times Syndicate in New York at 1-800-972-3550 or
212-499-3333, or fax us at 212-499-3382.) &LR;  &QL; 
