<HEADER>
A4204 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BKN-BLINEBURYCOL-HNS &LR;      01-08 0774
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKN-BLINEBURYCOL-HNS </SLUG>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
FranBlinebury
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR; c. 1998, Houston Chronicle &LR;  &QL; 
THEY saved the season.
</P>
<P>
   Now it's time to save the NBA.
</P>
<P>
   Not from the labor mess, from owners vs. players, from talk of
salary caps, percentage of basketball-related income or
middle-class exceptions. Fans have long grown accustomed to the
bickering between whining millionaires and greedy billionaires.
It's just an ugly fact of life these days in all sports, like
personal seat licenses, the $6 cup of beer and the $7 shriveled hot
dog.
</P>
<P>
   The more troubling problems facing the self-proclaimed world
game of the new millennium have to do with the game and the players
in it, both of which have become increasingly easy to dislike.
</P>
<P>
   In short, much of the hard work of the past two decades, when
commissioner David Stern's marketing genius enabled the NBA's
popularity to soar like a rocket, is in danger of crashing and
burning from the weight of its success.
</P>
<P>
   What used to be a street game, dictated by deep rhythms of the
soul, free and flowing like a jazz riff, has become sanitized,
homogenized and anesthetized from a combination of corporate
packaging and blatant overcoaching by a group of runway models in
designer suits trying to justify their large salaries and clothing
endorsement deals.
</P>
<P>
   What at one time captured our imaginations with its fast pace,
free form and expressions of individuality on the court has become
too often an exercise in brute strength and mind-numbing sameness.
It is like going to the circus for all of its different sights,
sounds and colors and getting a gray tug of war between elephants.
</P>
<P>
   With the rarest exceptions from the transcendent moves of
Michael Jordan and the still-dazzling footwork of Hakeem Olajuwon,
the games _ when you strip away the wiggling dancers, furry mascots
and indoor fireworks _ are too often unwatchable.
</P>
<P>
   There are not nearly enough fast breaks and improvisations from
the world's greatest athletes. There are far too many
thrust-and-parry mind games in a two- and three-man offense, where
half a team stands off to one side, away from the ball, pointing
and arguing over who is playing an illegal zone defense. Who cares
if it will do anything at all to loosen up an NBA that looks like
it's being played in a corset?
</P>
<P>
   The coaches are exerting too much control on the game, calling
every play on every possession, keeping offenses on a choking
leash, stifling the artistry that used to separate the NBA from
other sports. What's next? Point guards wearing helmets and getting
instructions radioed from the bench?
</P>
<P>
   The game needs the players. The players need freedom. But the
players are also a large part of the problem.
</P>
<P>
   Too many people don't like them.
</P>
<P>
   They don't like reading or hearing about Allen Iverson's posse,
his latest legal scuffle or that he doesn't respect anybody or
anything that came before him in the NBA.
</P>
<P>
   They don't like listening to Kenny Anderson cry over having to
give up one of his eight cars during the lockout. They don't like
punks named Isaiah Rider missing practices, Robert Horry throwing
towels at his coach or Latrell Sprewell choking his coach. They
don't like crotch-grabbing, trash-talking Dennis Rodman kicking
cameramen or Shawn Kemp leaving illegitimate children like bread
crumbs from coast to coast.
</P>
<P>
   They definitely don't like Kevin Garnett, just two years out of
high school, telling his team to stuff a $100 million contract
offer, threatening to jump to another city and then claiming it
never was about money.
</P>
<P>
   Fans like Jordan, but he'll be gone soon. If not immediately in
this truncated season, then in the near future, and the NBA has not
identified a new torch-bearer to carry the flame. Olajuwon, Karl
Malone, Scottie Pippen, Patrick Ewing and Charles Barkley are
graybeard short-timers as well.
</P>
<P>
   The NBA would like to sell Grant Hill as the next best thing,
but his team doesn't seem to get better. Shaq mumbles. Penny
Hardaway always seems to be broken.
</P>
<P>
   There is no Magic Johnson, no Larry Bird, no Isiah Thomas, no
Jordan, none of the standard-bearers from the magical '80s who
built the modern NBA by being individually brilliant and yet
committed to their teams. They played their whole careers with the
same franchises. They didn't complain about salaries. They played
hard, loved the game and nurtured it.
</P>
<P>
   Today, the league is filled with takers, users, spoiled young
pseudo-stars who are sucking the marrow from a withering game.
</P>
<P>
   Saving the season was difficult.
</P>
<P>
   Saving the soul of the NBA will be much, much harder.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
