<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-01-08 00:07 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4205 &Cx1f; tab-z
r a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-KHMER-EYE-FOR-EYE-ECO     01-08 1057
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-KHMER-EYE-FOR-EYE-ECONOMIST-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TRY THE KHMER BUTCHERS; CAMBODIA'S FUTURE DEMANDS NOTHING LESS  
 
</HEADLINE>
   (This excellent 875-word ``separate buy'' article is from the
current (week beginning 9 Jan. 1999) Economist magazine.)  
  
 (EDITORS: We regret that this material is NOT available to clients
in Canada except to The Toronto Globe &AMP; Mail.)  
  
 (To publish this article, it must be purchased from the New York
Times Syndicate in New York at 1-800-972-3550 or 212-499-3333, or
fax us at 212-499-3382.)  
  
 (PLEASE NOTE: This article has been transmitted twice _ into the
``a'' domestic/general news and ``k'' commentary news files.)  
  
 c.1999 Economist Newspaper Ltd.  
 (Distributed by the New York Times Special Features)  
<TEXT>
<P>
   The two aging Khmer Rouge leaders had a message for their
countrymen. ``Let bygones be bygones,'' said Khieu Samphan, head of
state between 1975 and 1979, when the savage rule of the Khmers
Rouges over Cambodia resulted in nearly 2 million deaths.
</P>
<P>
   Nuon Chea, ``Brother Number 2'' to the late Khmer Rouge leader
Pol Pot, offered similar advice: ``This is an old story. Please
leave it to the past.''
</P>
<P>
   The two men were speaking in Phnom Penh at the end of December
after surrendering to Cambodia's current leader, Hun Sen, who
welcomed them with bouquets of flowers and said that Cambodians
``should dig a hole and bury the past.''
</P>
<P>
   This ill-phrased plea for reconciliation was such a brazen
political fix that it sparked outrage both inside and outside
Cambodia. Hun Sen quickly backtracked, denying that he had ruled
out some sort of trial for the two leaders. But his intentions had
been clear.
</P>
<P>
   Burying the past might suit him, and other politicians tainted
by old associations with the Khmers Rouges. They are more intent on
clinging to power than seeing justice done. But an ignominious
burial of this kind would be yet another disaster for the
Cambodians.
</P>
<P>
   The Khmers Rouges were among the 20th century's more relentless
mass murderers. Letting them off scot-free would be a blow to
recent international efforts to bring to justice those who have
committed systematic murder and torture.
</P>
<P>
   More damaging for Cambodians, however, it would also reinforce a
culture of impunity that has crippled efforts to bring some
semblance of normality to their country.
</P>
<P>
   Cambodia remains haunted by its blood-drenched history. Every
family lost someone in the killings. People have accepted the need
to forgive Khmer Rouge foot-soldiers in order to end a chronic
civil war. But asking Cambodians to embrace the architects of mass
slaughter with bouquets of flowers turns the idea of reconciliation
into a sick joke.
</P>
<P>
   Moreover, 20 years after the Khmers Rouges were ousted from
power, Cambodia still struggles on the brink of chaos, ruled by the
gun, not by law.
</P>
<P>
   Hun Sen's own government stands accused of murdering political
opponents. He booted his coalition partners out of government in a
bloody coup in 1997 and only reluctantly accepted them back last
year under foreign pressure and an election marred by intimidation
and violence. Much of the aid given to Cambodia has been siphoned
off by Hun Sen and his cronies.
</P>
<P>
   Unless some start is made on introducing the rule of law,
Cambodia seems doomed to another generation of violence and
corruption. Putting Khmer Rouge leaders on trial is the first
essential step towards creating any credible legal system, and
restraining the country's current leaders.
</P>
<P>
   The case of the Khmers Rouges illustrates the need for a
permanent international criminal court, though the court now being
planned will not be able to deal with crimes committed before its
creation. There are, however, other ways a trial could be held,
none of them perfect, but all better than nothing.
</P>
<P>
   The U.N. Security Council could set up an ad hoc tribunal
similar to the Yugoslav and Rwandan ones. The United States
suggested something along these lines last year, confining the
tribunal's scope to acts committed from 1975 to 1979, the years the
Khmers Rouges held power.
</P>
<P>
   This would also conveniently avoid any investigations of the
earlier American bombing campaign or later American and Chinese
backing of the Khmers Rouges against the Vietnamese in the civil
war that followed.
</P>
<P>
   Even with these restrictions, though, China might not agree to
Security Council support for such a tribunal. An alternative would
be a tribunal set up by the U.N. General Assembly, or by a group of
nations, following the precedent of the Nuremberg trials, to be
held either in Cambodia or abroad, staffed by international judges.
</P>
<P>
   A third option would be for some country with the appropriate
domestic legislation in place _ Canada or Australia have been
suggested _ to ask Cambodia to extradite Khmer Rouge leaders for
trial in its courts for crimes against humanity.
</P>
<P>
   A Spanish magistrate has paved the way for this kind of
proceeding with his pursuit of Chile's former dictator, General
Augusto Pinochet, who is still detained in Britain fighting his
extradition to Spain.
</P>
<P>
   A U.N.-appointed team of jurists is due to recommend a way
forward at the end of this month. Whatever it suggests, a means
should be found to stage trials that are indisputably fair, before
a panel of independent judges, administering international law.
</P>
<P>
   The obstacles in the way of such trials have been removed.
Though most Khmer Rouge leaders are living in Pailin, a border town
where the government's grip is tenuous, they no longer have an
army. A determined effort to catch them is likely to succeed
eventually.
</P>
<P>
   As for Hun Sen, he is desperate for recognition and the
resumption of aid, most of which was suspended after his 1997 coup.
Concerted pressure from aid donors would win his cooperation,
however reluctant, in bringing Khmer Rouge leaders to trial.
</P>
<P>
   This might really help Cambodians to put their terrible past to
rest. &QL; 
 &UR; ___________________ &LR;  &QC; 
