<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKN-CLIPPERS-LBPT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BAYLOR: COACHING SEARCH NEARLY OVER
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By RANDY HILL  
 Long Beach Press-Telegram  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ During his 13-year career as the Clippers vice
president of basketball operations, Elgin Baylor has been known to
deflect a reporter's relatively harmless question with the
following rejoinder:
</P>
<P>
   ``Now you're wanting an answer.''
</P>
<P>
   Thursday, the NBA untied its lockout post-mortem gag order. Not
coincidentally, reporters were wanting answers to obvious inquiries
regarding Planet Clipper. The Hall of Fame forward, surrounded by
what resembled an illegal zone of pens and microphones at the
Sports Arena, did what he could to oblige.
</P>
<P>
   One issue that has basketball watchdogs talking is the team's
coaching vacancy.
</P>
<P>
   ``We will have a coach,'' said Baylor, not bothering to throw a
single head fake, ``at the beginning of next week.''
</P>
<P>
   He confirmed that former Clippers assistant Jim Brewer is on a
list of three finalists, joined by Chris Ford and Eddie Jordan, who
were relieved of duty in Milwaukee and Sacramento, respectively.
</P>
<P>
   This list has been trotted out for months, so what's with the
delay?
</P>
<P>
   ``There are details,'' Baylor said, ``that have to be worked
out.''
</P>
<P>
   He also declined to validate public opinion that defines Brewer
as the favorite, a status the one-time Laker has been granted in
speculative stories over the last several weeks. Brewer's knowledge
of Clippers personnel doesn't exactly hurt his chances, but his
prospective boss refused to admit this familiarity clinches
anything.
</P>
<P>
   ``Any advantage you have might help,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Any chronological disadvantage the winner of this derby might
have is not an issue, according to Baylor.
</P>
<P>
   ``Some of the other teams have new coaches, too. And those we're
considering already have their stuff (coaching styles and
strategies) together.''
</P>
<P>
   To become physically fit for their new coach, Clippers players
will begin working out Monday at the team's training facility in
Carson. When the new labor deal is finalized and the NBA gives the
all-clear, training camp will be held at College of the Desert in
Palm Desert.
</P>
<P>
   From there, Baylor fielded questions on the following Clippers
issues:
</P>
<P>
   _The European evacuation of Michael Olowokandi, the 7-foot-1
center chosen by the Clippers with the first pick in the 1998 NBA
draft.
</P>
<P>
   Thursday, Olowokandi played the first game for Kinder Bologna in
his expected five-week tour of the Euro League. Had Olowokandi
waited two days, he could open training camp with the Clippers.
</P>
<P>
   ``Michael said he wishes it (the NBA's new deal) had happened a
couple of days earlier,'' Baylor said. ``He's committed until the
15th (of February). But he's looking forward to joining us at that
time.''
</P>
<P>
   _Point guard. Baylor wouldn't mention any names to fill this
vacancy, but it is believed the team would prefer a
defensive-and-playmaking upgrade from last year's starter Darrick
Martin, who's a free agent.
</P>
<P>
   Available suspects who fit that description include Eric Murdock
from Miami, Sherman Douglas (a New Jersey Net last season) and
Travis Best, who's expected to re-sign with Indiana.
</P>
<P>
   How about a trade?
</P>
<P>
   ``You have to look at everything,'' Baylor said. ``Everybody's
looking for a great deal.''
</P>
<P>
   Is there a deal cookin'? For that, we retreat to what the vice
prez said when the press conference began:
</P>
<P>
   ``Some things I cannot talk about.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
