<DATE_TIME> 1999-01-08 00:11 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4210 &Cx1f; tab-z
r a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-JUSTICE-REHNQUISITOR-     01-08 1151
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-JUSTICE-REHNQUISITOR-ECONOMIST-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
JUSTICE REHNQUIST: CLINTON'S _ AND AMERICA'S _ LAST HOPE FOR
CLOSURE  
 
</HEADLINE>
   (This excellent, timely 950-word ``separate buy'' article is from
the current (week beginning 9 Jan. 1999) Economist magazine.)  
  
 (EDITORS: We regret that this material is NOT available to clients
in Canada except to The Toronto Globe &AMP; Mail.)  
  
 (To publish this article, it must be purchased from the New York
Times Syndicate in New York at 1-800-972-3550 or 212-499-3333, or
fax us at 212-499-3382.)  
  
 (PLEASE NOTE: This article has been transmitted twice _ into the
``a'' domestic/general news and ``k'' commentary news files.)  
  
 c.1999 Economist Newspaper Ltd.  
 (Distributed by the New York Times Special Features)  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Back in the 1950s, William Rehnquist packed up his life in
Washington, where he had been a clerk at the Supreme Court, and
headed southwest to Arizona to start out in private practice.
</P>
<P>
   As he passed through Arkansas he made an intriguing stopover.
There, rummaging through old court records and news clippings, he
began to research the life of Isaac Parker, a 19th-century judge
notorious for handing out 164 death sentences.
</P>
<P>
   Years later, when Rehnquist had risen to eminence as a Supreme
Court justice, he reflected on his youthful fascination with that
stern figure. ``Judge Parker's trials were swift, and there was no
appeal,'' he said by way of explanation.
</P>
<P>
   Now Rehnquist is America's chief justice, and therefore the man
who presides over the Senate as it embarks on the impeachment trial
of Bill Clinton.
</P>
<P>
   Rehnquist's taste for swiftness and finality, though not
necessarily for the ultimate sanction, seems to suit him to this
job perfectly.
</P>
<P>
   Americans, and more especially the senators who must stand in
judgment over the president, long for a quick end to the Lewinsky
scandal: in the days of hectic pre-trial negotiation, the Senate
leaders scrambled to come up with a formula that would get the
whole business over with, and prevent the impeachment proceedings
from jamming up government.
</P>
<P>
   But senators are slow to agree on things, except their own right
to pontificate. And so the country is left hoping that Rehnquist
will be the provider of dispatch and order once the trial gets
going.
</P>
<P>
   That is what he has already provided to the deliberations of the
Supreme Court. Before Rehnquist's elevation to the chief
justiceship in 1986, the court's denizens sometimes succumbed to a
professorial disdain for deadlines. No longer.
</P>
<P>
   Rehnquist is brisk and businesslike, and he demands as much from
his colleagues. He keeps the same hours at work each day; he sticks
to a fixed swimming schedule; his clerks appear before him at
regular times, to brief him or play tennis. No meeting is allowed
to drag on; lawyers who exhaust their allotted time in court get
cut off in mid-sentence.
</P>
<P>
   Rehnquist is more than just brisk. In another way too he seems
to answer his countrymen's yearnings as the Senate trial opens: he
has tried throughout his career to keep politics distinct from the
judicial process.
</P>
<P>
   As a young clerk on the Supreme Court, he argued against rulings
that would force racial desegregation, not because he is a racist
but because he opposed the making of political decisions through
the judiciary.
</P>
<P>
   Once elevated to the bench, Rehnquist continued to make this
argument. Courts, he believes, should stick to their basic function
of applying laws, even unpleasant ones; they should not stray into
politics or policymaking.
</P>
<P>
   Because of these views, it is tempting to hope that Rehnquist
will insist on a straightforward impeachment trial, uncontaminated
by partisanship. And this tempting thought is redoubled by
Rehnquist's writings on impeachment.
</P>
<P>
   Thanks to his efficient scheduling, the chief justice has time
for hobbies: he is fond of painting and of writing books.
</P>
<P>
   As it happens, one of these books (now swiftly reprinted)
describes two 19th-century impeachment trials, including that of
President Andrew Johnson in 1868. Rehnquist's account is mostly
sympathetic to Johnson, and attacks the pro-impeachment side as
irresponsibly partisan.
</P>
<P>
   The most important lesson of the Johnson episode, the chief
justice argues, is that impeachment trials should be ``a judicial
type of inquiry,'' in which senators ``decide whether or not the
charges were proven.'' They should not resemble the political votes
of no-confidence held in parliamentary systems.
</P>
<P>
   The question is whether Rehnquist will have the power to deliver
such a dignified, properly judicial, trial of Clinton. He will not
be able to control it as a judge usually controls his courtroom.
</P>
<P>
   He may wish to impose strict discipline on the impeachment
proceedings; but the Constitution allows the senators to overrule
him at any time, and on any matter, by a simple majority vote.
</P>
<P>
   He may wish to exclude irrelevant arguments; but the Federal
Rules of Evidence, which judges use to rule bits of testimony
admissible or otherwise, do not necessarily apply in an impeachment
trial.
</P>
<P>
   In short, the usual legal guidelines that judges enforce do not
exist: the chief justice is about to take on a role in which he
will be neither chief nor particularly judicial.
</P>
<P>
   Yet Rehnquist may prove surprisingly important all the same. In
their eagerness to conduct an orderly trial, the senators may
choose to defer to him rather than squabble over procedural rules;
knowing this, Rehnquist may press his advantage.
</P>
<P>
   If he really wants to get his way, the chief justice can
threaten to walk out, and so rob the trial of the legitimacy
conferred by his presence. During Johnson's trial, Salmon Chase,
the chief justice of the time, resorted to such threats on more
than one occasion.
</P>
<P>
   Besides, Rehnquist's influence has been dismissed before, almost
always wrongly. Richard Nixon, who appointed him to the Supreme
Court, could not remember his name: ``Renchburg,'' he once called
him.
</P>
<P>
   In his early years on the court, Rehnquist seemed so marginal
that his clerks gave him a Lone Ranger doll; even now, most
Americans could not name him. A quarter of a century on, however,
he has deserted the court's margins to become its respected leader.
</P>
<P>
   And, as the impeachment trial gets under way, the anonymous
Rehnquist will become the focus of American hopes for a dignified
process. That in itself should give him the authority he needs to
quell senatorial squabbles. &QL; 
 &UR; ___________________ &LR;  &QC; 
