<DOCNO> NYT19990108.0011 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-01-08 00:14 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4215 &Cx1f; tab-z
r a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-WHITEHOUSE-WANNABES-E     01-08 1376
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-WHITEHOUSE-WANNABES-ECONOMIST-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ON YOUR MARK!...: THE HOPEFULS LINE UP, PALMS OUTSTRETCHED  
 
</HEADLINE>
   (This excellent 1,175-word ``separate buy'' article is from the
current (week beginning 9 Jan. 1999) Economist magazine.)  
  
 (EDITORS: We regret that this material is NOT available to clients
in Canada except to The Toronto Globe &AMP; Mail.)  
  
 (To publish this article, it must be purchased from the New York
Times Syndicate in New York at 1-800-972-3550 or 212-499-3333, or
fax us at 212-499-3382.)  
  
 (PLEASE NOTE: This article has been transmitted twice _ into the
``a'' domestic/general news and ``k'' commentary news files.)  
  
 c.1999 Economist Newspaper Ltd.  
 (Distributed by the New York Times Special Features)  
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Is America ready for its first woman president,
Elizabeth Dole, wife of a man who publicly endorses Viagra? Or for
George W. Bush, who admits to a misspent youth of women and booze?
Or for John McCain, a brave prisoner of war in Vietnam who
celebrated freedom by betraying his faithful wife?
</P>
<P>
   ``My movements to the chair of government,'' wrote George
Washington some 210 years ago, ``will be accompanied by feelings
not unlike those of a culprit who is going to his place of
execution.''
</P>
<P>
   In an age of televisual inquisition, perhaps such feelings
explain why Senator Bob Kerrey _ another Vietnam war hero,
handsome, divorced, and with serious ideas for social policy _ last
month said that he would not, after all, try to be the Democrats'
presidential candidate in 2000.
</P>
<P>
   They may also partly explain this week's decision by Senator
John Ashcroft, darling of the religious right, not to seek the
Republican nomination.
</P>
<P>
   Yet there is scarcely a senator or a state governor in America
who does not look in the mirror and see a worthy denizen of the
White House. Just as Washington overcame his qualms, so clearly
will many others.
</P>
<P>
   For the Democrats, Vice-President Al Gore has already declared
himself on the starting-line, filing papers with the Federal
Election Commission on New Year's Eve to create a money-raising
``Gore 2000'' committee.
</P>
<P>
   So too with Bill Bradley, a former senator for New Jersey who is
still buoyed by his reputation as a 1970s basketball star with the
New York Knicks, and Paul Wellstone, a liberal senator from
Minnesota.
</P>
<P>
   Both have formed the ``exploratory committees'' that, under FEC
regulations, are a first step in a bid for the presidency.
</P>
<P>
   Other Democrats musing on their chances include Dick Gephardt,
minority leader in the House of Representatives, Senator John Kerry
of Massachusetts and the Reverend Jesse Jackson, perennial
standard-bearer for America's minorities.
</P>
<P>
   As for the Republicans, it is conventional wisdom that the
nomination is there for the asking of George W. Bush, son of a
president and newly reelected as governor of Texas.
</P>
<P>
   But there are plenty ready to challenge this wisdom. At the end
of December McCain, now a third-term senator for Arizona (with a
Vietnam record to match Kerrey's), formed his exploratory committee
and so became the first Republican to take a place on the official
starting-line.
</P>
<P>
   This week Senator Bob Smith of New Hampshire followed suit. And
Mrs. Dole, wife of Clinton's 1996 opponent, has told Americans to
watch this space (``Soon, I will be considering new paths, and
there are exciting possibilities'') by resigning as head of the
American Red Cross.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, the wealthy publisher Steve Forbes, former
Vice-President Dan Quayle and a former Tennessee governor, Lamar
Alexander, are pressing on with national campaigns that, officially
undeclared, have already taken them through months of bad meals and
repetitive speeches to the party faithful.
</P>
<P>
   Doubtless others, such as Gary Bauer, who champions Christian
beliefs and family values, and Pat Buchanan, a right-wing
television host, will soon throw their hats in the ring.
</P>
<P>
   Although Newt Gingrich, now-resigned speaker of the House, has
ruled himself out, other long shots _ say, Mayor Rudy Giuliani of
New York _ could yet rule themselves in.
</P>
<P>
   Why the early start for an election almost two years hence? The
simple answer is money.
</P>
<P>
   Such is the cost of television advertising that by most
calculations a candidate needs at least $20 million to mount a
primary campaign. More to the point, he (or she) needs it soon.
</P>
<P>
   Because California and New York, with big populations and votes
to match, have brought their primaries forward to March 2000, the
party nominations could be virtually decided by the end of that
month _ which would mean no candidate could emulate Presidents
Carter and Clinton, who used surprise early successes in the
primary season to raise money for their later victories.
</P>
<P>
   In other words, unless a candidate is wealthy enough to rely
entirely on his own money (Ross Perot spent $60 million from his
own pocket in his 1992 bid for the presidency), he must spend the
whole of this year raising money at the rate of about $60,000 a
day.
</P>
<P>
   That is quite a task given that campaign-finance rules brought
in to stop past abuses (Robert Vesco in 1972 allegedly gave Richard
Nixon a suitcase with $200,000 in cash), limit donations to $1,000
an individual.
</P>
<P>
   Such financial logic will surely doom some candidates,
Republican and Democrat alike, to early exits from the race. Smith,
for example, is a favorite son of New Hampshire, but scarcely known
elsewhere.
</P>
<P>
   Wellstone will have difficulty converting liberal ideals into
money (particularly since the campaign regulations that he favors
outlaw large donations). Even Bradley may fall short of what is
needed.
</P>
<P>
   Among the Democratic candidates more or less certain to have the
money are Gore, Kerry (after all, he has a very rich wife, Teresa
Heinz), and Gephardt, who may decide, given that the House could
turn Democratic in 2000, that being the prospective speaker is a
better bet than being a rival to Gore.
</P>
<P>
   The good financial bets for the Republicans are Bush, Forbes
and, probably, McCain and Mrs. Dole.
</P>
<P>
   Assume the money is found, what then? A successful candidate
must also project a message and appear electable. On those counts
only the most unexpected stumble could deprive Gore, with his
careful preparation and ideas for the environment, education and so
on, of the Democratic nomination (after all, in post-1945 America
it has been the reward for almost every vice-president who wanted
it).
</P>
<P>
   But what of the Republicans? Bush is clearly electable (and
outscores Gore in most polls), but he is yet to reveal his message,
let alone his candidacy. Perhaps he has none, or perhaps he is
biding his time.
</P>
<P>
   Many think that the Republican Party, through its narrow-minded
pursuit of Clinton, may have hurt itself electorally.
</P>
<P>
   Some Republicans reckon not just that the Democrats will win
back the House and Senate in 2000, but that Gore will win the White
House as a virtual ``third-term Clinton'' (rather as George Bush
senior became president as a ``third-term Reagan'').
</P>
<P>
   Their advice to Bush junior is to wait until 2004, when the
country will again want to swing right.
</P>
<P>
   That would leave the Democrats to fear McCain in 2000, to pray
that the Republicans will snub him for his cross-party advocacy of
campaign-finance reform and tobacco legislation _ and perhaps to
worry most of all about a Republican ticket that links, in
whichever order, McCain with Mrs. Dole.
</P>
<P>
   Such a ticket may seem a long shot, not least because there
could be a surfeit of vote-delivering running-mates (for example,
George Pataki, governor of New York, or Pete Wilson, former
governor of California, or Pennsylvania's governor, Tom Ridge).
</P>
<P>
   On the other hand, winning the presidency is all about playing
the odds _ and, if possible, fixing them early. &QL; 
 &UR; ___________________ &LR;  &QC; 
 &UR; (To publish this 1,175-word article, it must be purchased from the
New York Times Syndicate in New York at 1-800-972-3550 or
212-499-3333, or fax us at 212-499-3382.) &LR;  &QL; 
 &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; (EDITORS: Please note that this article is NOT available to clients
in Canada EXCEPT to The Toronto Globe &AMP; Mail.) &LR;  &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-01-08-99 0014EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990108.0012 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-01-08 00:15 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4216 &Cx1f; tab-z
r k &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-WHITEHOUSE-WANNABES-E     01-08 1375
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-WHITEHOUSE-WANNABES-ECONOMIST-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ON YOUR MARK!...: THE HOPEFULS LINE UP, PALMS OUTSTRETCHED  
 
</HEADLINE>
   (This excellent 1,175-word ``separate buy'' article is from the
current (week beginning 9 Jan. 1999) Economist magazine.)  
  
 (EDITORS: We regret that this material is NOT available to clients
in Canada except to The Toronto Globe &AMP; Mail.)  
  
 (To publish this article, it must be purchased from the New York
Times Syndicate in New York at 1-800-972-3550 or 212-499-3333, or
fax us at 212-499-3382.)  
  
 (PLEASE NOTE: This article has been transmitted twice _ into the
``a'' domestic/general news and ``k'' commentary news files.)  
  
 c.1999 Economist Newspaper Ltd.  
 (Distributed by the New York Times Special Features)  
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Is America ready for its first woman president,
Elizabeth Dole, wife of a man who publicly endorses Viagra? Or for
George W. Bush, who admits to a misspent youth of women and booze?
Or for John McCain, a brave prisoner of war in Vietnam who
