</P>
<P>
   Their advice to Bush junior is to wait until 2004, when the
country will again want to swing right.
</P>
<P>
   That would leave the Democrats to fear McCain in 2000, to pray
that the Republicans will snub him for his cross-party advocacy of
campaign-finance reform and tobacco legislation _ and perhaps to
worry most of all about a Republican ticket that links, in
whichever order, McCain with Mrs. Dole.
</P>
<P>
   Such a ticket may seem a long shot, not least because there
could be a surfeit of vote-delivering running-mates (for example,
George Pataki, governor of New York, or Pete Wilson, former
governor of California, or Pennsylvania's governor, Tom Ridge).
</P>
<P>
   On the other hand, winning the presidency is all about playing
the odds _ and, if possible, fixing them early. &QL; 
 &UR; ___________________ &LR;  &QC; 
 &UR; (To publish this 1,175-word article, it must be purchased from the
New York Times Syndicate in New York at 1-800-972-3550 or
212-499-3333, or fax us at 212-499-3382.) &LR;  &QL; 
