A4220 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BKN-NBA-LADN     01-08 0725
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKN-NBA-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NBA TAKES STEPS TO WIN BACK FANS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By HOWARD BECK  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ Jack Nicholson and Spike Lee presumably won't need
any arm-twisting to take their courtside seats Feb. 5, when the NBA
returns. As for everyone else? They've just become the league's No.
1 priority.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have some winning back of fans to do, and we're going to do
it,'' commissioner David Stern said Thursday, after owners
unanimously approved a new labor deal that ended a bitter six-month
lockout.
</P>
<P>
   Apathy reigned during the league's first two months of canceled
games. Stern hopes to rekindle fans' interest by offering free
admission to exhibition games later this month and blocks of $10
seats to regular-season games next season.
</P>
<P>
   But perhaps it won't really take much effort. Phones have been
ringing for two straight days at the Forum, where season tickets
are going fast, and no less an authority than Jerry West says the
game will thrive again.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm really prejudiced, but I happen to think the NBA is the
best game of all,'' said West, the Lakers' top executive and a
league institution since his playing days 30 years ago. ``I think
for young kids, who admire some of our players, hopefully they'll
know this is kind of a blip on the screen, and we'll get back to
doing what everyone would like to do, and that's play basketball.''
</P>
<P>
   But bet on this: the Lakers and every other team will be ordered
to make nice with the fans. That means more community service and
more time signing autographs.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've always felt our players have been very good about those
things,'' West said.
</P>
<P>
   Union director Billy Hunter, sitting next to Stern at a New York
press conference, pledged players' cooperation.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our players are anxious to play, and we're anxious to join
hands with David, Russ (Granik, deputy commissioner) and the owners
of the 29 teams to really create a strong and familial relationship
_ one that will take the NBA to another level and to bring back the
fans,'' Hunter said.
</P>
<P>
   But there was no understating the damage created by forcing
cancellation of games due to labor conflict for the first time in
league history.
</P>
<P>
   ``I hope the league doesn't fine me, but I am embarrassed,''
West said. ``I never thought in my wildest dreams that I would see
this happen to basketball, because I felt we had a wonderful
working relationship with our players and enormous growth of the
league.
</P>
<P>
   ``But I do feel . . . both sides understand that for everyone to
prosper in this league, you need a healthy league. You don't need
one or two players making every dollar that teams can provide under
the cap.''
</P>
<P>
   Just days ago, the NBA appeared on the verge of ruin. Stern was
recommending owners cancel the season, and high-powered agents were
possibly planning a rival league.
</P>
<P>
   Now the NBA is not only back in business, but arguably much
better off for the experience. It is the first pro league in North
America to place absolute limits on salaries _ $14 million per
season for 10-year veterans _ and the labor deal contains numerous
new controls to keep salaries from spiraling out of control.
</P>
<P>
   It comes at a time when Major League Baseball is reportedly
losing $300 million a year and $100-million player contracts are
suddenly the norm. New Dodgers pitcher Kevin Brown's $15
million-a-year deal is more than the entire payroll of the Montreal
Expos.
</P>
<P>
   ``I look at baseball and I look at (the NHL), and I would be
concerned for other sports if (they) don't get some control over
it,'' West said. ``And still the (NBA) salaries are enormous, but
hopefully this will give everyone a better idea of maybe how we can
make a league that will be healthy and allow every team to compete
equally.''
</P>
<P>
   It took the threat of a canceled season to force the NBA's 400
players to agree to the unprecedented limits. It was a threat the
union and player agents claimed all along was a bluff, but which
nevertheless rattled rank-and-file players.
</P>
<P>
   Stern's gambit worked, and only he knows if he would have
followed through.
</P>
<P>
   West, asked if he thought the season would be canceled,
responded with a terse, ``No.''
</P>
<P>
   In New York, Stern wore a sly grin when asked if he was bluffing
and said, ``You didn't pay to find out.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-01-08-99 0021EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
