<HEADER>
A4225 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-LOCAL-GALLERY-LADN     01-08 0807
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-LOCAL-GALLERY-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ARTISTS CELEBRATE NONPROFIT GALLERY'S OPENING
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
(Editors: Dennis McCarthy is a columnist for the Los Angeles Daily
News.) 
BY DENNIS MCCARTHY  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES -- For most of the past 30 years, their artwork has
been relegated to the walls of banks, restaurants, libraries, hair
salons -- any place in the San Fernando Valley area of Los Angeles
where someone would give them a little space to hang for a while.
</P>
<P>
   But that all changes Saturday. The stepchild of the arts is
finally getting its own gallery in the valley. It isn't fancy or
uptown like the Getty.
</P>
<P>
   It's behind a Burger King in Northridge. But who cares? It's a
home.
</P>
<P>
   No more competing with waitresses, hairstylists, librarians and
bank tellers for attention. No more insults to their
professionalism when some kid in a restaurant highchair flings his
spaghetti and hits one of their paintings.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's been degrading,'' says Connie Larson, president of the
Valley Institute of Visual Art. ``You feel like you're a decorator
for bank or restaurant walls, instead of an artist displaying your
work.''
</P>
<P>
   Not anymore.
</P>
<P>
   VIVA is an outgrowth of four local arts groups -- the Valley
Watercolor Society, the Collage Artists of America, Valley Artists
Guild and Women Painters West -- all of them sick and tired of
having to go, hat in hand, to local businesses and libraries to get
their work displayed for a few weeks.
</P>
<P>
   Aside from the Art Space in Warner Center in nearby Woodland
Hills, which was closed after five years when the building was sold
a few years ago, and the Lankershim Art Center across town in North
Hollywood, which houses performing arts and print-making societies,
there has been no permanent gallery space in the valley for these
VIVA artists to show their wares.
</P>
<P>
   ``This will be the only permanent home in the valley for paint
artists like this,'' said Earl Sherburn, community arts director
for the city's Department of Cultural Affairs, which is helping the
nonprofit VIVA open its doors.
</P>
<P>
   It's a big event for these visual artists, who are tired of
taking a back seat to the performing arts, and people who think of
the valley as a cultural wasteland.
</P>
<P>
   ``People think that all art in this city is located on the
Westside -- baloney,'' says Betty Beam of the Collage Artists of
America. ``We have over 600 fine artists in our four groups. The
valley isn't a desert.''
</P>
<P>
   No, but it's been a long, tough fight convincing the right
people of that.
</P>
<P>
   The first time I met Beam she was out knocking on doors to find
space in the valley for her group after Art Space lost its
building. She was not alone out there.
</P>
<P>
   Artists in the other groups that would later come together to
form VIVA were out doing the same thing. Looking for a place to
hang. None of them was having any luck.
</P>
<P>
   They all knew each other from the local schools where they
volunteered their time and expertise to bring art to kids in the
valley.
</P>
<P>
   When push came to shove at budget time, art never seemed to make
the cut in the schools. So, it was up to these local artists to
bring art to our kids.
</P>
<P>
   The way I see it, that alone should have given these talented
people dibs on the biggest, best building we could find for them to
hang their art. They certainly deserved their own gallery for
bailing out the school district and parents in opening the eyes of
kids to art.
</P>
<P>
   But that's not how things like this work. Good deeds don't
necessarily translate into good things.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was mind boggling to us that there was no real voice out
there for the visual artists, but plenty for the performance arts
people,'' Larson said.
</P>
<P>
   ``We felt like the stepchild. We were doing all this for the
community, and had no home base. We had to make some noise, and
that's what we finally did.''
</P>
<P>
   Betty Breuer of the Valley Watercolor Society kicked it off by
enlisting the help of the city's Department of Cultural Affairs.
Art patron Elisabeth Waldo-Detzel, who owns the Northridge strip
mall where the VIVA gallery is located, stepped in as a major
benefactor.
</P>
<P>
   Mike Donegan of Valley Artists Guild spent months turning an
empty store into a beautiful art gallery. A year of fund-raisers,
scrimping and saving later, VIVA officially opens its doors to the
public for a reception at 2 p.m. Sunday at its new home.
</P>
<P>
   As Larson says, it isn't a museum or a traditional gallery for
profit. It's a municipal gallery and educational center offering a
``comprehensive look at the vibrant and vital visual art scene in
the San Fernando Valley.''
</P>
<P>
   It may not be the Getty, but it's still pretty darn good.
</P>
<P>
   And if you get hungry, you can walk across the parking lot to
the Burger King.
</P>
<P>
   Try that at the Getty.
</P>
<P>
   X X X &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
