<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-01-08 00:30 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4228 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-LAZY-CALIFORNIA-LADN     01-08 0950
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-LAZY-CALIFORNIA-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
STUDY FINDS EXERCISE DOWN, OBESITY UP
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
BY SHERRY JOE CROSBY  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES -- Get off that couch!
</P>
<P>
   A new survey finds that significantly more state residents are
leading sedentary lifestyles and are much fatter on average than
Californians used to be.
</P>
<P>
   Obesity rates have increased 50 percent in the past 13 years,
according to a report released Thursday by the University of
California, San Francisco, and the California Department of Health
Services on a study of 36,004 Californians.
</P>
<P>
   Rates of physical inactivity are high, something that was little
surprise to 23-year-old Darlene Martinez.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think there are more lazy people now,'' said the mother and
student from suburban Granada Hills in the San Fernando Valley area
of Los Angeles. ``It's more convenient. There are cell phones and
valet parking. Everyone is so pampered and spoiled.''
</P>
<P>
   The survey examined five cardiovascular risk factors in 10
regions throughout the state, including Los Angeles County:
cigarette smoking, diabetes, high blood pressure, weight and
physical inactivity. The survey covers a 12-year period from 1984
to 1996.
</P>
<P>
   According to the report, more than one in four Californians had
an overweight problem in 1996 -- 50 percent more than in 1984.
</P>
<P>
   Californians also are less physically active off the job,
according to the study in which participants were asked whether
they did any running, walking, biking or other vigorous physical
activity in the past month.
</P>
<P>
   The report showed the prevalence of inactivity among men
increased significantly, from 45 percent in 1984 to 54.3 percent in
1996.
</P>
<P>
   About 55 percent of women led inactive lives in 1996, virtually
unchanged since 1984.
</P>
<P>
   ``This study shows us we (have) a lot of room for improvement,''
said Jeannie Gazzaniga, an epidemiologist at the Institute for
Health and Aging, UCSF School of Nursing, and lead author of the
study.
</P>
<P>
   ``California as a whole, like the rest of the nation, could
stand to lose some weight and become more physically active.''
</P>
<P>
   Shawn Noorparvar, 20, of Reseda in the San Fernando Valley said
he knows firsthand how much lazier society is. He sells cell phones
and pagers for a living.
</P>
<P>
   ``It used to be you'd go over to a friend's house to see if he
was home. Now you just give him a call or you can page him,''
Noorparvar said.
</P>
<P>
   As for himself?
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm lazy. I'm not motivated, I'm much less active,'' he said.
``I used to be involved in basketball and the swim team. I haven't
done that in months -- I mean months and months.''
</P>
<P>
   The report findings surprised others.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think people are lazier. I think they're more active.
Everything's more fitness-oriented,'' said Randi Piedrahita, 29, a
mother from West Hills in the valley.
</P>
<P>
   Viola Sarkozy, 25, a resident of North Hills in the San Fernando
Valley and recent college graduate, said Californians should be
healthier and trimmer than others.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's January, and we're still wearing shorts. You can go bike
riding and go outdoors, whereas back East right now there's a foot
of snow,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   But as Californians' take-home pay increases, they tend to eat
out more and cook fewer low-fat, nutritious meals at home, said Dr.
Raed Fahmy, a board-certified cardiologist at Kaiser Permanente
Woodland Hills Medical Center in suburban Woodland Hills in the
valley.
</P>
<P>
   ``They're eating out more and becoming more sedentary,'' Fahmy
said. ``Fewer people are learning how to cook properly. That skill
of cooking at home is vanishing.''
</P>
<P>
   Statewide, the study found Latino women were the most likely to
be overweight (42.7 percent). Among women, whites were the least
likely to be (24.2 percent).
</P>
<P>
   In Los Angeles County, African-American women were the most
likely to be overweight (44.6 percent), while white men were the
least likely (18.2 percent).
</P>
<P>
   About half of the African-Americans and whites in the study were
sedentary in 1996.
</P>
<P>
   Latinos -- 70.4 percent of the men and 66.2 percent of the women
-- were most likely to be sedentary statewide.
</P>
<P>
   Latinos also were the least physically active off the job in Los
Angeles County, followed by African-American women,
African-American men, white women and white men.
</P>
<P>
   Gazzaniga said the findings could paint a misleading portrait of
Latinos.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have to keep in mind that we're talking about physical
activity outside work,'' she said. ``A lot of times, Hispanic men
and women are very busy, and their jobs are very labor intensive.
They may be very active, but we may not be picking that up as
leisure activity.''
</P>
<P>
   Gazzaniga also said that Latinos surveyed in the study could
live in high-crime areas where they fear going outside to run, walk
or bike. And she said that immigrant Latino women may not see
walking as a form of exercise and mention it in a survey.
</P>
<P>
   ``They're used to walking to get someplace, rather than seeing
it as exercise,'' Gazzaniga said. ``We're dealing with some
cultural factors.''
</P>
<P>
   Researchers identified no significant differences in activity
across age groups in the study, but found leisure inactivity among
fewer Californians with college education, 44.2 percent, than among
those with only a high school diploma or less education, 62.9
percent.
</P>
<P>
   ``We wanted to find out where we have the highest prevalence of
the major contributors to heart disease,'' Gazzaniga said. ``The
report tells us where we should better target our prevention
efforts.''
</P>
<P>
   The study was conducted in the state's Cardiovascular Disease
Outreach, Resources and Epidemiology Program.
</P>
<P>
   X X X &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
