<HEADER>
A4232 &Cx1f; tab-z
r i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-MEXICO-POVERTY-PICADO     01-08 0860
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MEXICO-POVERTY-PICADORS-ECONOMIST-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
AIDING MEXICANS SUFFERING SLINGS AND ARROWS OF OUTRAGEOUS FORTUNE  
 
</HEADLINE>
   (This excellent 675-word ``separate buy'' article is from the
current (week beginning XXXXX) Economist magazine.)  
  
 (EDITORS: We regret that this material is NOT available to clients
in Canada except to The Toronto Globe &AMP; Mail.)  
  
 (To publish this article, it must be purchased from the New York
Times Syndicate in New York at 1-800-972-3550 or 212-499-3333, or
fax us at 212-499-3382.)  
  
 (PLEASE NOTE: This article has been transmitted twice _ into the
``i'' international news and ``k'' commentary news files.)  
  
 c.1999 Economist Newspaper Ltd.  
 (Distributed by the New York Times Special Features)  
<TEXT>
<P>
   MEXICO CITY _ Ask him whether Mexico might not help its poor
citizens by taxing its rich ones more, and Jose Angel Gurria, the
finance minister, looks mildly irritated.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're not practicing the Robin Hood theory here.'' Indeed not.
</P>
<P>
   Gurria had to cut spending three times in 1998. For 1999 he
presented the most austere budget in nearly two decades. Then he
told Congress it would need slicing even further, as oil prices, a
mainstay of government revenue, continued to plummet; and the
opposition refused to let him ease the pain with a higher telephone
tax.
</P>
<P>
   In spite of it all, he did not take from the rich. The budget
that bleary-eyed legislators waved through in the last hours of
1998 even included a lower profits tax for businesses. Yet the
government claims proudly that it is spending more _ in real terms
_ on fighting poverty than ever before.
</P>
<P>
   Someone should tell the poor. Social spending has indeed
increased fairly steadily over the past ten years, but the Robin
Hood effect has been conspicuously absent.
</P>
<P>
   During much of the 1980s Mexico's Gini coefficient, a measure of
income inequality (going from nil, egalitarian paradise, to 1,
feudal hell), rose significantly.
</P>
<P>
   It has changed little during the 1990s, but the poorest continue
to do badly: 36 percent of workers were paid less than the minimum
wage in 1997, compared with 30 percent in 1991.
</P>
<P>
   The minimum wage itself has been falling for over two decades _
it is now just under 35 pesos ($3.55) a day _ while basic supplies
have gone up in price as one subsidy after another has been
abolished.
</P>
<P>
   The last and most basic one of all vanished on Jan. 1: on
tortillas, the maize pancakes that keep most Mexican bellies full.
</P>
<P>
   Their price, which the government had nudged up to what it
thought the market level during 1998, promptly jumped again, until
public rage this week compelled the suppliers to accept a ceiling
of 3.50 pesos per kilo _ which (even if it holds) is still nearly
double the 1.90 of a year ago.
</P>
<P>
   So what, apart from throwing more money at the problem, is the
government intending to do? Answer: throw money more accurately.
</P>
<P>
   Generalized subsidies are being replaced with carefully directed
ones: for instance, some 1.5 million of the poorest families can
get a free tortilla ration by swiping cards through an electronic
reader at their local tortilleria, where previously the height of
technology was the gas-powered tortilla-squashing machine.
</P>
<P>
   But the highlight of the 57 assorted anti-poverty schemes is
rather more ambitious.
</P>
<P>
   This is a scheme called Progresa. Started in mid-1997, it aims
to help the rural poor escape the vicious circle of low income, bad
nutrition, poor health and lack of education.
</P>
<P>
   It offers the neediest rural families a package of benefits _
with strings. Thus pregnant women and toddlers can get extra food,
so long as they go or are taken for regular free health checks.
</P>
<P>
   Families get paid to send their children to school, instead of
to work in the fields, but only so long as the children actually
attend.
</P>
<P>
   And to make sure the money is spent properly, Progresa's
payments go, in defiance of traditional Mexican values, to the
women of the family rather than the men.
</P>
<P>
   So far, independent analysts are cautiously impressed. There are
some criticisms: for instance, that the poorest communities of all,
ones that have no school or clinic nearby, cannot take part.
</P>
<P>
   But some 2 million families, about a tenth of the population,
are now under Progresa's umbrella, and their ranks are growing.
Where Progresa operates, more children have registered for school,
more people are visiting their medics, and malnutrition is down.
</P>
<P>
   The scheme, however, will have to support many children for many
years before anyone can be sure that it really improves their lives
rather than just maintaining them.
</P>
<P>
   And, of course, Progresa cannot create the jobs that all these
well-nourished, well-educated young people will need. &QL; 
 &UR; ___________________ &LR;  &QC; 
 &UR; (To publish this excellent 675-word article, it must be purchased
from the New York Times Syndicate in New York at 1-800-972-3550 or
212-499-3333, or fax us at 212-499-3382.) &LR;  &QL; 
 &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; (EDITORS: Please note that this article is NOT available to clients
in Canada EXCEPT to The Toronto Globe &AMP; Mail.) &LR;  &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-01-08-99 0034EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990108.0020 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-01-08 00:34 </DATE_TIME>
