<SLUG> BC-COMPUTER-OUTSOURCING-ECONOMIST-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THE RED-HOT BUSINESS OF COMPUTER SERVICES OUTSOURCING  
 
</HEADLINE>
   (This excellent 1,100-word ``separate buy'' article is from the
current (week beginning 9 Jan. 1999) Economist magazine.)  
  
 (EDITORS: We regret that this material is NOT available to clients
in Canada except to The Toronto Globe &AMP; Mail.)  
  
 (To publish this article, it must be purchased from the New York
Times Syndicate in New York at 1-800-972-3550 or 212-499-3333, or
fax us at 212-499-3382.)  
  
 (PLEASE NOTE: This article has been transmitted into the ``f''
financial news, ``a'' domestic/general news and ``k'' commentary
news files.)  
  
 c.1999 Economist Newspaper Ltd.  
 (Distributed by the New York Times Special Features)  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Few firms would consider supplying their own electricity and
water. So why do they struggle with computer equipment and
software?
</P>
<P>
   In recent years the outsourcing of computer services has been a
huge and fast-growing business. At a price, the likes of IBM and
EDS will provide an ``end-to-end'' package of solutions for big
companies who want to wish their technology worries away.
</P>
<P>
   But thanks to the Internet and improvements in communications
technology, another type of outsourcing is now afoot. It is more
like a utility that rents out data storage, processing capacity and
applications.
</P>
<P>
   If end-to-end outsourcing is the computing equivalent of
limousines with chauffeurs, the new version is a fleet of taxis _
less luxurious, but much cheaper and for hire to businesses
anywhere.
</P>
<P>
   The charge is being led by some of the software firms that
provide ``enterprise resource planning'' (ERP), which big companies
increasingly rely on for their main business processes.
</P>
<P>
   Working with hardware makers and Internet service providers
(ISPs), they want to make the latest business software available on
monthly subscription. Initially, their aim is to extend ERP to
firms with revenues of less than $500 million a year, including
legal partnerships and even doctors' surgeries.
</P>
<P>
   Many analysts are convinced that even large firms will
eventually follow. Forrester Research, a consultancy, thinks that
by 2002 the applications-rental market, currently almost
nonexistent, will be worth about $6 billion, and will be doubling
every year.
</P>
<P>
   Established ERP suppliers are in the vanguard. J.D. Edwards is
working with IBM Global Services; PeopleSoft is leasing its
human-resource and financial packages to a start-up, called
Usinternetworking.
</P>
<P>
   But there are also new firms, such as Employease which is using
the Internet to help companies to outsource their payroll and
benefits processing.
</P>
<P>
   Even Microsoft is dipping a fairly fat toe in the water. It has
just linked with Qwest, a new telecoms firm that is building a
high-capacity long-distance network along old railway lines.
</P>
<P>
   Microsoft has invested $200 million in Qwest, in exchange for a
1.3 percent stake plus a share of revenues from Qwest's Internet
services. This will provide upgrades and maintenance of Microsoft's
software for a regular fee.
</P>
<P>
   These will also compete with large ISPs such as UUNET, ANS and
Exodus, which already run firms' Internet sites for them.
</P>
<P>
   Forrester's Tom Gormley argues that such service providers could
become the utilities of the next century, providing an essential
service with all the reliability and security of the electricity or
telephone company.
</P>
<P>
   The most determined firm is Oracle, which leads the market for
corporate databases and is the number two ERP firm (after Germany's
SAP). Oracle Business OnLine has been running as a pilot since
October, and early this year it will be launched commercially,
first in America and some months later in Europe and Asia.
</P>
<P>
   All of its latest ``Release 11'' suite of applications _
finance, distribution, manufacturing, front office and human
resources _ will be for rent. In time, Oracle will also include
other firms' software, providing what it calls ``best of breed''
solutions.
</P>
<P>
   Oracle reckons this could become a $2 billion-a-year
money-spinner, accounting for as much as 50 percent of its
packaged-applications revenue in five years' time.
</P>
<P>
   By teaming up with its Silicon Valley neighbors, Sun
Microsystems and Hewlett-Packard, two of the biggest makers of
powerful Unix servers, Oracle's new data centers are able to supply
the gamut of hardware and services.
</P>
<P>
   Rented applications fit beautifully with Oracle's vision of a
simpler and more reliable form of computing based on the open
standards of the Internet and the Java programming language.
</P>
<P>
   Unlike its rivals' products, Oracle's Release 11 is not designed
to run on conventional PC clients linked to lots of servers on a
local-area network. Instead, Oracle favors three tiers, with a huge
database server (possibly a mainframe) at the center.
</P>
<P>
   This links smaller servers working for thousands of different
users. Users need only a Java-compatible web browser and a network
connection.
</P>
<P>
   In this way, elderly PCs can be given a new lease of life. Cheap
and simple Internet appliances will be able to perform most tasks.
Larger companies may prefer to operate their own network, but, with
encryption, smaller companies can safely make use of the public
Internet.
</P>
<P>
   Nobody is sure how to charge for renting computing power. One
idea is a monthly subscription, related to the number of named
users. Another, strongly supported at a recent Oracle users'
conference, is to ``meter'' the units of computing that a customer
uses.
</P>
<P>
   USi is charging monthly fees of $10,000-75,000 for its
PeopleSoft rented applications, depending on client numbers and the
software chosen.
</P>
<P>
   J.D. Edwards, using IBM's costly network (recently sold to
AT&AMP;T), is charging $550-850 a month for each user.
</P>
<P>
   A one-off fee of up to $50,000 should cover the cost of setting
up the system for each new customer. Contracts are for a minimum of
three years _ somewhat longer than Oracle is planning.
</P>
<P>
   That is a bargain. One drawback of ERP is the cost of getting it
up and running. Even though the software is ``off the shelf,'' it
works only if businesses adopt the ``best practices'' prescribed by
armies of expensive consultants.
</P>
<P>
   As one joke has it: how many SAP consultants does it take to
screw in a light bulb? None; they just declare darkness a best
practice.
</P>
<P>
   With prices pared to the bone, the emphasis in the rental market
will be on contracts based on implementation in six months or less.
That should actually suit small and medium-sized companies who need
ERP to make them more efficient, rather than to gain unique
competitive advantage.
</P>
<P>
   According to Katherine Jones, an analyst with the Aberdeen
Group, an IT consultancy, another attraction is that renting is
much less risky: ``It's not a win-or-lose-all decision for
businesses in the gut-wrenching way that most ERP decisions are.''
If you are renting the wrong package, you can probably change it,
or pull out.
</P>
<P>
   This is not to say that rental is all bad news for the
consultants who have made so much money from customizing ERP. Even
rapid implementation will call for their experience. Indeed, some
are likely to go into the utility business themselves, establishing
their own data centers.
</P>
<P>
   Some companies will feel uneasy about giving their most valuable
data to hired guns half a continent away. But for others, leaving
the management of the network, systems, data and applications to
contracted professionals is an idea whose time has come. &QL; 
