<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-IMAC-ULATE-APPLE-ECONOMIST-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
STEVE JOB'S IMAC-ULATE NEW APPLE FOR CHIC GEEKS  
 
</HEADLINE>
   (This excellent 750-word ``separate buy'' article is from the
current (week beginning 9 Jan. 1999) Economist magazine.)  
  
 (EDITORS: We regret that this material is NOT available to clients
in Canada except to The Toronto Globe &AMP; Mail.)  
  
 (To publish this article, it must be purchased from the New York
Times Syndicate in New York at 1-800-972-3550 or 212-499-3333, or
fax us at 212-499-3382.)  
  
 (PLEASE NOTE: This article has been transmitted into the ``f''
financial news, ``a'' domestic/general news and ``k'' commentary
news files.)  
  
 c.1999 Economist Newspaper Ltd.  
 (Distributed by the New York Times Special Features)  
<TEXT>
<P>
   CUPERTINO, CALIF. _ Ask the Silicon Valley elite what they think
of Steve Jobs and the company he helped to found 22 years ago, and
they exude admiration.
</P>
<P>
   As Netscape's Marc Andreessen (no stranger to lionization
himself) puts it: ``Right now, there's no question that Steve is
the man.''
</P>
<P>
   Jobs has certainly achieved remarkable things in the 16 months
since being installed as ``interim'' chief executive at Apple, the
company he was squeezed out of in 1985.
</P>
<P>
   Apple will declare a profit for the fifth quarter in a row next
week, after racking up losses of more than $1 billion; its share
price has tripled.
</P>
<P>
   The stunning-looking iMac, launched in August, was the
best-selling home computer in the run-up to Christmas, almost
tripling Apple's share of the desktop retail market in November, to
5.3 percent.
</P>
<P>
   Yet despite his hero's welcome at this week's MacWorld trade
show in San Francisco, a cautious assessment of Jobs's prospects is
in order.
</P>
<P>
   That he has given the Apple faithful back their hope, and
restored glamour to a once-great brand, is not in doubt. The
question is whether the Cupertino-based company is seeing a new
dawn or a false one.
</P>
<P>
   So far, Jobs seems not to have put a foot wrong. Hard decisions
came first. He concluded a peace pact with the old enemy,
Microsoft, to ensure that the latest version of Microsoft's Office
software would run on Apple's Macintosh operating system. He
terminated the licensing agreements that had allowed other
manufacturers to make Apple ``clones.''
</P>
<P>
   Had Apple licensed its brilliant operating system in the 1980s,
it might have been Apple and not Microsoft that became the colossus
of the personal-computer industry. But doing so a decade too late
merely let clone-makers undercut Apple's own products, while doing
little to expand the Apple universe.
</P>
<P>
   Even harder was the decision to kill projects such as the
hand-held Newton. Apple just did not have the money to dabble in
risky new technologies. Survival meant reviving the brand and
ensuring that manufacturing and distribution did not let Apple down
as they had in the past.
</P>
<P>
   Much of the effort has been geared towards the iMac. Although
the machine is not a technical tour de force, its compactness,
glowing green transparent shell, absence of conventional cables and
simplicity appeal to both traditional Macophiles and computer
virgins.
</P>
<P>
   This week, Jobs announced five tangy new colors (strawberry,
blueberry, tangerine, grape and lime) and a slightly upgraded
design. Substance, as well as style, is promised by new versions of
the Power Macintosh.
</P>
<P>
   Encased in ice-blue plastic, they come with processors as fast
as any made by Intel, and they include excellent 3D graphics.
</P>
<P>
   With his slogan ``chic, not geek,'' Jobs may well be on to
something. If Apple can provide customers with the same ``delight''
that came from the original Mac operating system's graphical user
interface, the firm has a good future.
</P>
<P>
   Jobs will have succeeded if the sort of people who pay more for
an Audi than for a Ford also prefer an Apple to a Compaq.
</P>
<P>
   In the recent past, his chances would have been slim, because of
the dominance of Windows. But that is to reckon without the shift
towards Internet-based computing, and the growing success of the
Java programming language, which allows applications to run on a
variety of platforms.
</P>
<P>
   Yet that is both good and bad for Apple. Good, because it offers
an escape from the charming but decaying Mac ghetto. Bad, because
owning its operating system is what differentiates Apple from the
rest.
</P>
<P>
   There are other uncertainties as well. Jobs dismisses the threat
of imitators: ``if they could do all these things, why aren't they
doing them now?''
</P>
<P>
   Apple may eventually find itself stunted by the move towards
simple Internet computing devices and information appliances, such
as smart mobile phones and television set-top boxes.
</P>
<P>
   These will appeal to technophobes and will bring
consumer-electronics firms, such as Sony and Philips, into
competition with the computer industry.
</P>
<P>
   Despite an abortive bid to buy Palm from 3Com last year, Jobs
affects a lack of concern. His message is that the PC will remain
king of the hill and Apple's task is to make its computers nicer to
use and more beautiful than anyone else's.
</P>
<P>
   A company that lost its way as badly as Apple needs that kind of
unrelenting focus. But at what point does focus become blinkered? &QL; 
 &UR; ___________________ &LR;  &QC; 
 &UR; (To publish this 750-word article, it must be purchased from the
New York Times Syndicate in New York at 1-800-972-3550 or
212-499-3333, or fax us at 212-499-3382.) &LR;  &QL; 
 &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; (EDITORS: Please note that this article is NOT available to clients
in Canada EXCEPT to The Toronto Globe &AMP; Mail.) &LR;  &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-01-08-99 0042EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990108.0027 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-01-08 00:43 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4241 &Cx1f; tab-z
r k &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-IMAC-ULATE-APPLE-ECON     01-08 0934
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-IMAC-ULATE-APPLE-ECONOMIST-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
STEVE JOB'S IMAC-ULATE NEW APPLE FOR CHIC GEEKS  
 
</HEADLINE>
   (This excellent 750-word ``separate buy'' article is from the
current (week beginning 9 Jan. 1999) Economist magazine.)  
  
 (EDITORS: We regret that this material is NOT available to clients
in Canada except to The Toronto Globe &AMP; Mail.)  
  
 (To publish this article, it must be purchased from the New York
Times Syndicate in New York at 1-800-972-3550 or 212-499-3333, or
fax us at 212-499-3382.)  
  
