<HEADER>
A4243 &Cx1f; tic-z
r a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-IMPEACH-AZR &LR;      01-08 1137
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-IMPEACH-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SENATE OPENS HISTORIC IMPEACHMENT TRIAL AMID PARTISAN FIGHTING 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By JEFF BARKER  
 c.1999 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ The Senate opened the first presidential
impeachment trial in 131 years by solemnly pledging to render
``impartial justice,'' but the body soon was struggling to overcome
partisan divisions it had hoped to avoid on such a historic day.
</P>
<P>
   Republicans, unable to agree with their Democratic colleagues on
procedures to govern the trial of President Clinton, were prepared
in the afternoon to use their Senate majority to pass their own
rules. Those rules would allow witness testimony and could extend
the trial well into February.
</P>
<P>
   By the end of the day, however, GOP party leaders had pledged to
meet again today in the hope of adopting a trial format that both
Democrats and Republicans could endorse.
</P>
<P>
   The main sticking point was whether to summon witnesses.
</P>
<P>
   At the White House, spokesman Joe Lockhart told reporters, ``We
are convinced we can make a compelling case that will lead the
United States Senate not to remove the president.''
</P>
<P>
   Lockhart said the president's lawyers are ``ready to go'' and
ready to stipulate to evidence in the case in exchange for a ban on
witnesses. But, he added, if the House insists on calling
witnesses, it will cause a delay ``because bringing witnesses in
and not stipulating to a record opens up a whole area of motions,
discovery and depositions. And that takes time.''
</P>
<P>
   As of Thursday evening, White House aides said they had not
received a response from the Senate.
</P>
<P>
   Democrats said that new testimony was unnecessary because the
record was well established; Republicans argued that members of the
House of Representatives required witnesses to make their case that
Clinton is guilty of ``high crimes and misdemeanors.''
</P>
<P>
   The Constitution offered little procedural help. Although the
Senate has tried 14 federal officials _ most of them judges _ the
only presidential trial was of Andrew Johnson in 1868. It ended in
narrow acquittal after a little more than a month of evidence.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are in uncharted waters,'' said Senate Majority Leader
Trent Lott, R-Miss.
</P>
<P>
   Under the GOP plan, the trial witnesses could include former
White House intern Monica Lewinsky, Clinton confidant Vernon Jordan
or anyone else the Senate voted to summon. Because Republicans hold
55 of the 100 Senate seats, the GOP could control the agenda if the
votes were cast along party lines.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think it's wrong to say at the beginning, `Absolutely no
witnesses,' '' Lott said. ``I also think it's wrong to say at the
beginning that there are going to be `X number' of witnesses.
</P>
<P>
   ``Any witness request that gets 51 votes, that witness will
come. That's fair. We'll have to vote on every witness.''
</P>
<P>
   Lott said he had not been presented a list of specific witnesses
by the House of Representatives.
</P>
<P>
   But House Judiciary Committee Chairman Henry Hyde, R-Ill., and
other Republicans have prepared a list of potential witnesses,
including Lewinsky, Jordan and White House secretary Betty Currie.
</P>
<P>
   New reports quoted Republican sources as saying that GOP
lawmakers may also want to have several current and former White
House officials subpoenaed, including John Podesta, the chief of
staff; Harold Ickes, a former aide; and adviser Sidney Blumenthal.
</P>
<P>
   The Republican plan would give first the House and then the
White House up to 24 hours each _ three eight-hour days, for
example _ to present evidence, after which senators would have 16
hours for questions to lawyers. After that, the Democrats would be
permitted to seek adjournment of the trial, and the House or White
House free to seek permission to call witnesses. A final vote would
occur by mid-February.
</P>
<P>
   Earlier, frustrated Democrats skipped an afternoon meeting in
which they had been scheduled to caucus with Republicans about the
trial blueprint.
</P>
<P>
   ``(Senate Minority Leader) Tom Daschle pulled the plug,'' said
Sen. Jon Kyl, R-Ariz. ``He said there would be no more discussions
with this (bipartisan) group.''
</P>
<P>
   Kyl insisted that ``Republicans understand that we need to make
this bipartisan for it to be credible.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Democrats have used that leverage to extract concession after
concession after concession,'' Kyl said. ``This is an attempt to
use partisanship to gain advantage.''
</P>
<P>
   The Democrats said witnesses weren't needed because the White
House was already prepared to concede, or stipulate to, the facts
in independent counsel Kenneth Starr's report to Congress.
</P>
<P>
   Starr accused Clinton of covering up a sexual affair with
Lewinsky. The House forwarded two articles of impeachment to the
Senate last month on perjury and obstruction of justice.
</P>
<P>
   Although the House debate was rancorous, it was expected that
events in the Senate would unfold more calmly. The founding fathers
believed the Senate, because of members' six-year terms of office
and deliberative nature, would be more collegial and detached than
the House. It remained to be seen whether that would be the case.
</P>
<P>
   On Thursday, many Democrats continued to back a plan, rejected
by GOP conservatives, in which each side would present its case,
followed by a ``test vote'' that could end the trial if a majority
believed Clinton's offenses weren't clearly impeachable.
</P>
<P>
   ``For some reason, unbeknownst to me, the Republican caucus
rejected that,'' said a frustrated Sen. Charles Schumer, D-N.Y., as
he ducked into an elevator. ``And why any other proposed solution
is better _ that would have to be answered, I think, to a lot of
folks on our side.''
</P>
<P>
   In the ceremony that signaled the formal opening of the
impeachment trial, the federal government's legislative and
judicial branches, at least for a moment, merged into one.
</P>
<P>
   There was a hush as Chief Justice William Rehnquist, wearing a
black robe embellished with gold stripes, was led into the Senate
chamber to be sworn in as the presiding officer. His dark-suited
Senate escorts marched silently ahead of him, like pallbearers at a
funeral.
</P>
<P>
   ``Hear ye! Hear ye! Hear ye!'' shouted the sergeant at arms.
``All persons are commanded to keep silent, on pain of
imprisonment, while the House of Representatives is exhibiting to
the Senate articles of impeachment against William Jefferson
Clinton.''
</P>
<P>
   One by one, the senators stood to take an oath affirming their
``impartial justice according to the Constitution and laws: So help
me God.''
</P>
<P>
   Sen. Ted Stevens, R-Alaska, said afterward, ``This is a jury,
and I hope we can get finally get them (senators) to think as
jurors and act like jurors.'' &QL; 
The Associated Press contributed to this article. &QL; 
Jeff Barker can be reached at (202) 662-7264 or
jeff.barker(at)pni.com via e-mail. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
