<DOCNO> NYT19990108.0029 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-01-08 00:56 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4244 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-HKN-BRUINS-MAPLELEAFS     01-08 0750
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HKN-BRUINS-MAPLE </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DAFOE, BRUINS SHAKE OFF LEAFS 
</HEADLINE>
 LEAFS-BOS   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By NANCY L. MARRAPESE  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ He didn't have his full team. Six regulars were
missing. There was no Tim Taylor, no Grant Led-yard, no Dave
Ellett, no Anson Carter, no Chris Taylor, no Peter Ferraro.
</P>
<P>
   And two of his players were making their National Hockey League
debuts _ Andre Savage and Eric Nickulas.
</P>
<P>
   This was hardly the ideal situation for Bruins coach Pat Burns,
which was why he approached this home-and-home series against
Toronto with some trepidation.
</P>
<P>
   Not to worry. After a very strong effort by goalie Byron Dafoe
in the last seven-plus minutes of the second period, the Bruins
came out firing in the third, earning a 2-1 victory over the Maple
Leafs Thursday night at the FleetCenter.
</P>
<P>
   Dafoe was at his best while the Bruins were being outshot, 9-0,
late in the second, helping them keep Toronto winless in Boston
since Oct. 24, 1996.
</P>
<P>
   The game wasn't without some exasperating moments for Burns. His
top line of Jason Allison, Dmitri Khristich, and Sergei Samsonov
produced a roller-coaster ride of giveaways and recoveries,
prompting the coach to take them aside after the second period and
beg them not to make him old before his time.
</P>
<P>
   ``We were giving them the puck too much,'' said Burns of the
trio that wound up scoring both Boston goals. ``You can't skate 164
feet and give them the puck. Then your defense gets the puck and
gives it back to the forwards and they go another 160-odd-feet and
give up the puck and come back ... Sooner or later, the puck's
going to end up behind you.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our top line has to be at their best. If they don't play (at
top form), we don't stand much of a chance to win. I told them we
can play this type of hockey all night but it's wearing on the
defense, it's wearing on the goaltender, and it's wearing on me.''
</P>
<P>
   Burns said he tries to allow his skilled players to make their
own decisions out on the ice, but he admits that when they're doing
so, he's afraid to look.
</P>
<P>
   ``It'll probably kill me,'' said Burns. ``They're like that,
though. They try to make a play at the right time. Sometimes you're
all happy when they do make it. When they don't make it, you get
frustrated. You have to bite your tongue sometimes. Other times you
say, `Maybe you shouldn't pass up that shot.' If you go out there
and say, `Shoot the puck,' maybe that's not them. Maybe they'd have
less points.''
</P>
<P>
   Toronto took a 1-0 lead at 18:31 of the first period on a
backhander by Todd Warriner from the slot.
</P>
<P>
   Boston pulled even at 3:26 of the second when Allison set up
Samsonov for his 15th goal of the year. Allison, at the blue line,
carried the puck from the right point down the slot and found
Samsonov near the crease. Samsonov skated right to left, curling
arond the edge of the crease and beating Glenn Healy with a
backhander from near the left post.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't like to carry it across the blue line when there are
three guys there,'' said Allison. ``I kind of ran out of room. I
wanted to cycle it back down to somebody, and no one was there.
(Defenseman Hal Gill) was up a bit, so I had a little room to go
behind him and it ended up working well. You get that high, it
confuses people, and Sergei was wide open.''
</P>
<P>
   After the Bruins weathered the Maple Leafs' storm in the second
half of the period, Khristich potted the winner at 7:13 of the
third with his 17th of the year. After Allison took a chip shot
from the right circle, Healy made the stop and Sylvain Cote tried
to clear the puck out from in front of his goalie. But he couldn't
control the puck, and Khristich came charging in, banging in the
rebound.
</P>
<P>
   It was clear early in the third that the line had taken to heart
Burns's message.
</P>
<P>
   ``He mentioned something to our line about playing safer; we
have to keep things a little simpler than we do,'' said Allison.
``Sometimes we're trying to score a goal right away or force a pass
in the slot or hanging on to it too long or trying to beat a guy at
the blue line instead of getting it into the corners and getting it
wide.''
</P>
<P>
   Allison had a goal disallowed at 16:13 because the rolling puck
didn't completely cross the goal line. But it all worked out for
the depleted Bruins.
</P>
<P>
   ``You have to give this team credit tonight,'' said Burns. ``The
guys we called up worked hard. The five defense worked hard. You've
got to give them credit.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
