A4248 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-HKN-KINGS-NOTES-LBPT     01-08 0680
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HKN-KINGS-NOTES-LBPT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FOR NOW, FISET CONTENT AS NO. 2 GOALIE
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By ROGER PHILLIPS  
 Long Beach Press-Telegram  
<TEXT>
<P>
   INGLEWOOD _ Stephane Fiset, waiting to return to the lineup from
a groin injury he says was healed two weeks ago, said he is very
comfortable serving as the backup for as long as Jamie Storr
remains hot in goal.
</P>
<P>
   Asked before Thursday night's game against Buffalo what he would
do if coach Larry Robinson told him he'd be playing, Fiset said,
``I'm going to tell him, `Play Jamie, he's winning.'''
</P>
<P>
   Robinson said he is considering playing Fiset against Edmonton
on Saturday night.
</P>
<P>
   ``I still think Fizz is our main guy,'' Robinson said. ``This is
just an opportunity for Jamie to get in there and get some
much-needed games and a good opportunity for us to see him in more
than two or three games in a row.''
</P>
<P>
   Storr started his career-high 10th consecutive game against
Buffalo. He entered play Thursday with a 6-1 record in his previous
seven games.
</P>
<P>
   Of Fiset, Storr said: ``He wants to play, but he's not one to
sit there and whine. He pushes you, but he supports you, too.''
</P>
<P>
   Strange feeling: Winger Donald Audette played his first game
against Buffalo since the Sabres traded him to the Kings last month
for a second-round selection in this year's draft. Audette sat out
the first two-plus months of the season in a contract dispute.
</P>
<P>
   ``I wasn't looking to break market value,'' said Audette, who
signed a two-year, $3.6-million contract with the Kings. ``Buffalo
is a small town. They have their budget. They didn't think I was
worth what (we were) asking for.
</P>
<P>
   ``The thing I'm sorry about is it took three months to make the
trade. I'm not 22 anymore. At my age (29), this contract was very
important for my future. I lost money and I lost three months of
hockey. The trade could have been done by October.''
</P>
<P>
   Audette's salary this season is prorated for the time he missed
while in his dispute with the Sabres.
</P>
<P>
   House of pain: On the injury front, Glen Murray is as optimistic
as he can be under the circumstances, Doug Bodger seems to be
headed in the right direction, and Russ Courtnall is coming along
slowly.
</P>
<P>
   Murray, the Kings' best all-around forward, tore the medial
collateral ligament in his right knee Saturday against Colorado,
but already is walking without crutches and said his pain is gone.
</P>
<P>
   ``It hurt like hell,'' Murray said when asked about the moment
of injury, which resulted from a clean check by Colorado's Aaron
Miller. ``It was pain I've never felt before. I wouldn't wish it on
anyone.''
</P>
<P>
   As he was being carried off the ice on a stretcher, his kneecap
popped back into place, Murray said. He started flexing the knee
soon after he was hurt.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't want to let this beat me,'' Murray said. ``I want to
beat it.''
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, Bodger said he finally is starting to feel better
more than a week after a blind-side check by Phoenix's Dallas Drake
left him with a cervical strain and a bruised shoulder. Drake was
suspended for four games by the NHL for the hit. Bodger said
there's a possibility he will play Saturday against Edmonton. He's
missed four games.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's just sort of day by day,'' Bodger said. ``Some days, it's
fine. Some days, it's not as great.''
</P>
<P>
   Courtnall has been sidelined with a broken ankle since Nov. 18,
but he is hoping to play in about two weeks. He skated Thursday
morning, at times slowly working his way across the ice on one
foot, then skating the other direction across the ice on the other.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm just trying to strengthen my legs,'' Courtnall said of the
drill. ``My legs are getting weak. Once I get going, I'm fine.
Starting and stopping is hard.''
</P>
<P>
   Another injury victim, winger Eric Lacroix, played for the first
time after missing nearly a month with a fractured sternum. Center
Ian Laperriere rejoined the lineup after missing one game with
swelling in his left knee. Had Laperriere been unable to play, Dan
Bylsma would have filled in as the fourth-line center.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
