<HEADER>
A4255 &Cx1f; taf-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-HKN-RANGERS-CAPITALS-     01-08 0581
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HKN-RANGERS-CAPITALS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CAPITOLS DEFEAT RANGERS, 5-1 
</HEADLINE>
  (sw) 
 By JOE LAPOINTE   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ When the New York Rangers arrived at
Baltimore-Washington International Airport at 1:30 a.m. on
Thursday, they were hoping to leave with a .500 record and feeling
a little more secure about their playoff hopes. Their hopes went
unfulfilled in a 5-1 defeat on Thursday night.
</P>
<P>
   While the Rangers stuck with the Washington Capitals in the 1-1
first period, they came out lost and lackluster in the second
period. The Capitals scored four consecutive goals and outshot the
Rangers by 15-3 in the period. The four goals in the period matched
their season high.
</P>
<P>
   ``For some reason, we didn't have any emotion,'' said Rangers
Coach John Muckler. ``This team has to be an emotional team to
win.''
</P>
<P>
   The Capitals (13-20-3), playing before a crowd of 17,832,
entered the game knowing they have to win consistently. They are
ranked 13th in the 14-team Eastern Conference.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've got to win all the games as far as I am concerned,''
Capitals Coach Ron Wilson said before the game.
</P>
<P>
   The Capitals scored 1 minute 14 seconds into the first period.
Michal Pivonka dumped the puck to Peter Bondra, who found Steve
Konowalchuk about 20 feet in front of the net. Konowalchuk beat
goalie Mike Richter to his glove side, putting the Capitals ahead
by 1-0.
</P>
<P>
   The Rangers (15-17-7) tied the score after Sean Pronger, with
defenders all over him, made an outstanding pass to a wide-open
Manny Malhotra, who slid the puck past goalie Olaf Kolzig.
</P>
<P>
   The first period was generally fast-paced, even though the
Rangers had played four games in the last six nights.
</P>
<P>
   ``In the first period I thought we did a pretty nice job,'' said
Rangers forward Wayne Gretzky. But he said there wasn't much he
could say about the rest of the game.
</P>
<P>
   The Rangers' Brian Leetch, quiet and downcast, said, ``There are
no excuses at this point in the year.''
</P>
<P>
   The Rangers fell apart in the second period. With just 33
seconds elapsed, Jan Bulis skated around to the right of Richter.
Richter sprawled onto the ice a bit early, and a patient Bulis
found the right corner of the net for a 2-1 Capitals lead. It was
just the fourth goal of the season for Bulis, who had been out most
of the season with an ankle injury.
</P>
<P>
   The Capitals kept up the pressure, and just 2:20 later, Craig
Berube, known primarily for his penalty minutes, scored from the
top of the left circle, beating Richter on the far post for a 3-1
lead.
</P>
<P>
   Ken Klee scored his fifth goal of the season at 6:30, taking a
pass after Andrei Nikolishin got a rebound, putting the Rangers
down by three goals.
</P>
<P>
   The period was not over for the Rangers, who looked listless and
worn. Bondra slid a quick pass to Sergei Gonchar, and while Richter
was trying to slide over, Gonchar found the open part of the net at
18:13 to end the second period outburst.
</P>
<P>
   Wilson did not bask in his team's victory. ``I think our
confidence will grow a little bit,'' he said, ``but I can look on
the other hand and say we were able to take advantage of a very
tired team.''
</P>
<P>
   Kolzig also commented on how listless the Rangers seemed. ``They
were a tired hockey team,'' he said. ``It was their third game in
four nights and they looked tired out there.''
</P>
<P>
   The Rangers will have two days to regroup before they face the
Tampa Bay Lightning, which has the worst record in the National
Hockey League.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
