A4263 &Cx1f; taf-z
u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BOEING-NYT &LR;      01-08 0367
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BOEING-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BOEING RECEIVED ORDERS FOR 656 PLANES IN '96
</HEADLINE>
   (sw) 
 By LAWRENCE ZUCKERMAN   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   The Boeing Co., the world's leading commercial aircraft maker,
announced on Thursday night that it had received orders for 656
planes in 1998, 15 percent more than the 568 ordered a year
earlier.
</P>
<P>
   But the value of the 1998 orders totaled $42.1 billion, compared
with $42.8 billion in 1997, because the company sold more
narrow-body jets last year, which are less expensive than its
wide-body models.
</P>
<P>
   It was also unclear whether Boeing's orders for 1998 surpassed
those of Airbus Industrie, its only rival in the commercial
aircraft business.
</P>
<P>
   The European consortium, which is to release 1998 production and
delivery figures on Monday, had more than 500 orders as of the end
of November.
</P>
<P>
   Hurt by the economic slump in Asia and a litany of production
and delivery problems, Boeing sought to put the best face on its
annual production and delivery data. In a news release hours after
the stock market had closed, Boeing said the figures showed it
``continued to increase its presence in the worldwide fleet in
1998, delivering more than two of every three commercial airlines
of 100 seats or more.''
</P>
<P>
   Although Boeing releases airplane orders monthly, the figures
released on Thursday night are the most comprehensive for the year
and include some previously unannounced orders.
</P>
<P>
   But the figures also illustrate that while the company's order
backlog remains healthy, fewer customers are purchasing its most
expensive and profitable airplanes.
</P>
<P>
   The Seattle-based company said it expected to deliver a record
620 aircraft in 1999, surpassing the record of 563 last year.
</P>
<P>
   Boeing also said it has delivered nearly 12,500 commercial jets,
accounting for about three of every four jets in service.
</P>
<P>
   Boeing was hampered by production problems throughout 1998. Late
last year it said it expected to trim 48,000 of its 233,000
employees worldwide through 1999.
</P>
<P>
   Its share price, which hit a 1998 high of $50 in July, has
traded as low as $30.875. It closed on Thursday at $35.8125 cents,
down 25 cents, on the New York Stock Exchange.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-01-08-99 0116EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990108.0035 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-01-08 01:31 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4270 &Cx1f; taf-z
