<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-IMPEACH-CHAMBER-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
OLD SENATE CHAMBER: A SETTING FOR DEBATES AND ORATORY OF LEGEND 
</HEADLINE>
  (sw) 
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ The ceremonial Old Senate Chamber where 100
senators plan to discuss impeachment on Friday in a rare bipartisan
caucus has been the site of legendary events and debates in the
nation's history.
</P>
<P>
   The semicircular two-story chamber, designed after ancient
amphitheaters, was home to the Senate for 40 years, beginning in
1819. Within its gold-and-crimson adorned rooms, impassioned
debates about slavery and states' rights ensued, the Missouri
Compromise of 1820 was brokered and the Webster-Clay-Calhoun
orations echoed.
</P>
<P>
   The Senate's membership grew along with the country's expansion
in the 19th century, first requiring renovations of the old chamber
and then relocation of the Senate to its current wing of the
Capitol. By 1860, the Supreme Court had claimed the grand
surroundings as its own and the chamber remained the justices'
quarters for 75 years, until 1935.
</P>
<P>
   Until its restoration for the Bicentennial in 1976, the chamber
was used for meetings. Following its refurbishing, with
reproductions of 64 mahogany desks and chairs from an 1819 design,
the chamber has been open to the public as a museum. On occasion,
Congress has used it for special ceremonies.
</P>
<P>
   According to the curator's office of the Architect of the
Capitol, the east wall's gallery has eight columns of marble
quarried along the Potomac River. A portrait of George Washington
by Rembrandt Peale hangs above the east gallery. The desk for the
vice president, as president of the Senate, has a canopy with
crimson fabric hanging from a mahogany valance. A semi-circular
skylight bordered by five smaller skylights is at the center of the
half-domed ceiling. Many of the chamber's modern day furnishings
are based on period illustrations, particularly an 1842 engraving
by Thomas Doney.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
