<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HKN-KINGS-LBPT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ROBITAILLE REACHES 500-GOAL MARK
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By ROGER PHILLIPS  
 Long Beach Press-Telegram  
<TEXT>
<P>
   INGLEWOOD _ Luc Robitaille has reached 500, and the Kings
continue to creep closer to .500.
</P>
<P>
   It figured Robitaille would get there first.
</P>
<P>
   The 32-year-old left wing scored the 499th and 500th goals of
his 13-year career, becoming the 27th player in NHL history to
reach the milestone as the Kings defeated the Buffalo Sabres 4-2
Thursday night before a crowd of 10,821 at the Forum.
</P>
<P>
   Robitaille became the sixth left wing in NHL history to score
500 goals, scoring on a 3-on-2 rush by redirecting a feed from
rookie right wing Pavel Rosa past Buffalo goalie Dwayne Roloson
with 1:46 to play in the game.
</P>
<P>
   He had scored his 499th goal 2:48 into the game, when he
one-timed a cross-ice feed from Rob Blake past Roloson with the
Kings enjoying a two-man advantage. Robitaille leads the Kings with
22 goals and has scored 12 in his last 15 games.
</P>
<P>
   Robitaille reached the 500-goal mark in 928 games, 12th fastest
among those to reach the milestone.
</P>
<P>
   As for the Kings (15-21-3), the victory was their seventh in the
last eight games, and their season-high fifth in a row. Rosa and
Sandy Moger also scored for the Kings, who are as close to the .500
mark as they've been since they were 6-12-3 on Nov. 21.
</P>
<P>
   The Kings caught a break when coach Lindy Ruff of the Sabres
(21-10-5) opted to start Dwayne Roloson in goal rather than
two-time Most Valuable Player Dominik Hasek, who was given a rare
night off 24 hours after recording an overtime victory over the
Mighty Ducks at the Pond. It was just the fifth appearance for
Roloson this season.
</P>
<P>
   There was nothing Roloson could have done to prevent
Robitaille's first goal, and with 1:37 to play in the first period,
Rosa padded the Kings' lead, tapping a weak shot by Jozef Stumpel
into the net after Roloson was unable to control the puck. With the
goal, Rosa drew to within 497 of Robitaille, and he has 10 points
in 10 games since the Kings recalled him last month from the Long
Beach Ice Dogs.
</P>
<P>
   But 11 seconds later, Kings goalie Jamie Storr got caught
wandering out of his net, and Vaclav Varada cut Buffalo's deficit
to one goal, scoring on a wraparound.
</P>
<P>
   The Kings regained the two-goal lead 5:52 into the second period
when Moger scored from the slot off a centering feed from Ian
Laperriere. Referee Dennis LaRue was signaling a delayed penalty on
Buffalo when Moger scored his second goal this season and his first
since Oct. 25 at Carolina. It was Moger's second game back in the
lineup after missing 17 games with a strained lower back.
</P>
<P>
   Once again, though, the Sabres rallied, getting a power-play
goal from Michael Peca, who scored the game-winner Wednesday over
the Mighty Ducks. Peca scored 8:01 into the second period when he
picked a centering feed from ex-King Dixon Ward out of the air and
bunted it past Storr from point-blank range.
</P>
<P>
   The Sabres got an excellent opportunity to even the score less
than a minute later when Rosa received a double-minor penalty for
high-sticking Buffalo defenseman Jay McKee. But the Sabres were
unable to generate much offense during the four-minute advantage,
and shortly after Rosa's penalty expired, Storr made a sprawling
save on a wraparound attempt by Miroslav Satan, enabling the Kings
to carry their tenuous 3-2 lead into the third period.
</P>
<P>
   With eight minutes remaining in the game, Storr again stopped
Satan on a wraparound, and with less than six minutes to play, a
Matt Johnson deflection came within a goal post of giving the Kings
a 4-2 lead.
</P>
<P>
   Robitaille, however, didn't miss when given his opportunity, and
his 500th goal sealed the victory for the Kings. &UR; !end! &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
