<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-QUAYLE-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
QUAYLE MUM ON FUTURE, OUTCOME OF CLINTON TRIAL 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By BARBARA YOST  
 c.1999 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Dan Quayle says he has ``a campaign or two left in me.''
</P>
<P>
   But at a dinner in Tempe on Thursday night honoring the founders
of Kids Voting Arizona, the former vice president remained coy,
saying, ``That's a subject for another time.''
</P>
<P>
   That other time likely would be mid-April, Quayle said. If he
finds the political waters favorable, he would announce his
presidential candidacy for 2000 then and in his home state of
Indiana, despite recently reclaiming his Arizona roots.
</P>
<P>
   Quayle spent his school years in the Valley. He and wife Marilyn
now live in Paradise Valley with their three children. He also is a
member of the board of directors of Central Newspapers Inc., which
publishes ``The Arizona Republic'' and two daily newspapers in
Indianapolis, among others.
</P>
<P>
   The awards ceremony honored Max Jennings, R.R. ``Bob'' Evans and
Charles Wahlheim for their creation 10 years ago of the pilot
program that brings schoolchildren into the voting booth at each
national election. It has since spread to nearly every other state
as Kids Voting USA.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Republic'' this year joined the Kids Voting coalition and
co-sponsored Thursday's event with the East Valley Partnership.
</P>
<P>
   Other individuals honored were business volunteer Carolyn
Parrish; Susan Harrison, principal of Islands Elementary School in
Gilbert; and former Gov. Rose Mofford.
</P>
<P>
   In his keynote speech, Quayle emphasized the importance of
enthusiastic voters within a democracy and said that programs such
as Kids Voting promote such values.
</P>
<P>
   ``We need that spirit today more than ever in the history of our
republic,'' Quayle said, looking boyish, rested and ready to run
again for national office _ with Marilyn's blessing.
</P>
<P>
   ``Bad politicians are sent to Washington by good people who
don't vote,'' he said, noting that through Kids Voting children are
inspiring their parents to return to the polling booth.
</P>
<P>
   Quayle said he has learned from his students at Thunderbird _
The American Graduate School of International Management in
Glendale that ``people want to believe in the system.
</P>
<P>
   ``We need to reclaim the value and virtue of integrity,'' he
added.
</P>
<P>
   On the day when the U.S. Senate opened the impeachment trial of
President Clinton, Quayle _ once mocked for his unabashed stand on
family values _ predicted ``honesty and integrity are poised for a
big comeback in politics.''
</P>
<P>
   After his remarks, he told reporters that he does not miss the
Senate, even during such historic times.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's beyond me,'' he said. ``I've moved on in my life.''
</P>
<P>
   Quayle did say he never would have believed that only the second
impeachment of a U.S. president would occur in his lifetime. He had
no prediction for the outcome of the trial.
</P>
<P>
   Banking that the electorate will vote for change in the White
House in 2000, looking for someone with more traditional moral
values, Quayle said he just might be that candidate. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
