</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKC-UCLA-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
UCLA TRIPPED BY OREGON STATE
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JON WILNER  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   CORVALLIS, Ore. _ This was supposed to be the easy game, the
easiest road game of the Pac-10 season. Instead, bad shooting, bad
defense, freshman jitters and sophomore sloppiness turned it into
one of UCLA's worst losses in recent memory.
</P>
<P>
   Worse than Princeton? Without a doubt.
</P>
<P>
   Worse than the Massacre in Maples? Absolutely.
</P>
<P>
   This was Oregon State, after all, the Pac-10's perennial cellar
dwellar with a November loss to Athletes in Action on its resume.
</P>
<P>
   ``I never imagined losing to Oregon State,'' UCLA senior guard
Brandon Loyd said after a 65-63 loss to the Beavers on Thursday,
before 7,232 at Gill Coliseum.
</P>
<P>
   And here's the thing: Oregon State didn't muster a performance
for the ages or stun UCLA with good breaks and lucky shots. Time
and again, the bumbling Beavers (22 turnovers) tried to hand UCLA
the game. The Bruins were so bad, they couldn't take it.
</P>
<P>
   ``This was our first real test in terms of going on the road in
conference, and obviously, we failed,'' said UCLA coach Steve
Lavin. ``We showed lack of discipline on defense and lack of
discipline on offense.''
</P>
<P>
   In losing to Oregon State for the first time since 1993, the
Bruins (10-3, 2-1) wasted the competitive advantage gained when
they defeated Arizona last weekend. In the roughest Pac-10 ever,
their margin for error is microscopic. This was a game they had to
win to keep pace with Stanford.
</P>
<P>
   Now, stunned and staggered, they have two days to regroup before
facing Oregon in McArthur Court, the Pac-10's rowdiest arena.
</P>
<P>
   By then, perhaps, freshmen JaRon Rush, Dan Gadzuric and Jerome
Moiso will have found their composure and their shooting strokes.
Combined, they made 4 of 28 shots. Moiso and Gadzuric were so
ineffective the Bruins played long stretches without either,
leaving 6-6 Travis Reed to play center.
</P>
<P>
   But the freshmen were not totally at fault. Far from it.
Sophomore guards Baron Davis and Earl Watson played like rookies as
well, making 11 of 36 shots and committing 10 turnovers.
</P>
<P>
   Despite shooting 28.4 percent (a season low) and committing 29
fouls, UCLA had a chance to win until Davis committed two turnovers
in the final 30 seconds.
</P>
<P>
   ``They were giving us the game,'' Davis said. ``But, in the
clutch, I had two turnovers.
</P>
<P>
   ``On the road, you have to be at the top of your game, and we
played terrible. I lost the game. I take complete responsibility.''
</P>
<P>
   Flustered and frustrated throughout the first half, UCLA
appeared to regain its poise early in the second, when Ryan Bailey
buried a jumper and found Rush for a layup that narrowed Oregon
State's lead to 41-40. A timeout calmed the Beavers, and they
ambushed the Bruins out of the break. Josh Steinthal hit two
3-pointers _ the second coming with 8:30 left and giving Oregon
State a 49-41 lead.
</P>
<P>
   Bailey temporarily quieted the crowd with a 3-pointer, then Rush
converted an offensive rebound. But the Beavers did not wilt.
Deaundra Tanner found Clifton Jones for a layup, then scored from
the right baseline with five minutes left to give Oregon State a
56-46 lead, its biggest of the game.
</P>
<P>
   But the Bruins had time for a final lunge. Watson stroked a
3-pointer from the right wing, and, two possessions later, Davis
made a hanging jumper from the lane, slicing the deficit to 57-51.
</P>
<P>
   Instead of attacking, the Beavers backed out and worked the shot
clock to single digits. Five seconds remained when Tanner made a
3-pointer from the top of the key, in Watson's face, with 2:40
left.
</P>
<P>
   Ray Young hit two free throws, then Rush kept the Bruins alive
with an offensive rebound. As he stumbled out of bounds, he somehow
passed to Davis underneath for a basket. He was fouled, and the
three-point play pulled UCLA within 61-56.
</P>
<P>
   With 1:27 left, Young struck again, driving hard through the
right side of Oregon State's defense for a layup. Over the next
minute, the Beavers would make just two free throws, and when Loyd
hit a 3-pointer from the left corner, UCLA trailed 64-61.
</P>
<P>
   Clifton Jones missed two free throws with 36 seconds left, but
Davis, hurried and out of control, lost the ball twice. At the
buzzer, UCLA watched helplessly as Oregon State fans stormed the
court.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have to flush this out,'' Reed said. ``Because we're going
to face a far better team in Oregon.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
