<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-THIEL-COLUMN-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SEAHAWKS SHOULD HIRE HOLMGREN, AND END DECADE OF DECAY 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By ART THIEL  
 c.1999 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SEATTLE _ Much has been made of the rare playoff appearances
this year of the Arizona Cardinals, Atlanta Falcons and New York
Jets, franchises that have broken out this century with the
frequency of bubonic plague.
</P>
<P>
   But the NFL pity party has not been entirely forsaken.
</P>
<P>
   There remains the Seattle Seahawks. They do not lead the NFL
futility race, but trail only by the flare of a nostril.
</P>
<P>
   Excepting recent expansion teams Carolina and Jacksonville, only
Tampa Bay and New Orleans have played fewer postseason games than
the Seahawks.
</P>
<P>
   Lucy hadn't even met Ricky the last time the Cardinals won a
playoff game. But after beating the Dallas Cowboys, the most
prolific postseason team in history last weekend, the Cardinals
have surrendered the lead in consecutive seasons without playoffs
to the Seahawks.
</P>
<P>
   The decade of decay needs to stop.
</P>
<P>
   Hire Mike Holmgren.
</P>
<P>
   Now.
</P>
<P>
   The Head Cheese spent Thursday in the company of Seahawks
president Bob Whitsitt, who squired him around Seattle and Kirkland
before dining with owner Paul Allen. But the swarming media horde
at the team's headquarters went away storyless Thursday night,
because no deal had been concluded, fueling skepticism that the
Seahawks would again let one slip off the fingertips.
</P>
<P>
   If Whitsitt blows this one, he should make history _ the first
pro sports executive to be fired by two teams in the same city.
</P>
<P>
   Everyone knows Holmgren took the Green Bay Packers to the last
two Super Bowls, winning one. Consider also that he and John Madden
are the only coaches in NFL history to win at least one playoff
game in five straight seasons.
</P>
<P>
   In fact, the man has not been connected with a losing record
since coaching in high school more than 20 years ago. He has been a
winner in his pro jobs in Green Bay and San Francisco, and in his
college career at BYU and San Francisco State.
</P>
<P>
   Nobody around the Seahawks can say that kind of thing. Mostly
because they've been around the Seahawks.
</P>
<P>
   Losing is the Seahawks' legacy. It has become part of the
franchise fabric. The last two years are good examples. A decent
coach, good talent and a high payroll could do no better than break
even.
</P>
<P>
   It will take a man of Holmgren's resume and accomplishments to
end decisively the culture of mediocrity that makes the Seahawks
such a non-entity in the NFL.
</P>
<P>
   Not since Bill Russell, a champion as player and coach and
another San Franciscan, was hired by the Sonics in the early 1970s
has Seattle sports seen such a luminous national figure check out a
local sideline.
</P>
<P>
   Lenny Wilkens' second tenure as Sonics coach brought Seattle its
only major pro sports championship in 1979, but his appointment
early in the 1977-78 season was an unheralded patch job after he
was already in the Sonic front office.
</P>
<P>
   The Mariners' 1993 hiring of Lou Piniella had cachet after his
Cincinnati Reds won the 1990 World Series, which followed modest
success as one of dozens of managers under George Steinbrenner in
New York. But Piniella has never been held in the same regard among
his peers as Holmgren is in football.
</P>
<P>
   Only one other time have the Seahawks hired a head coach in his
prime. Chuck Knox had playoff teams in Los Angeles and Buffalo, and
he took the Seahawks to all the postseason wins in their history
(three). But he never reached the Super Bowl.
</P>
<P>
   Tom Flores won the 1984 Super Bowl with the Oakland Raiders, but
that was also when Al Davis had his wits about him and called most
of the shots. By the time Flores was hired by the Seahawks in 1992,
he was well past his prime.
</P>
<P>
   Of course, a buff resume merely gets a coach through the door.
Immediate job performance gets them out the door, as Russell,
Wilkens, Knox and Flores all found out.
</P>
<P>
   Holmgren represents about as sure a bet on immediate job success
as can be made in the freakish world of big-time coaching. The only
issue is whether he can co-exist with Whitsitt, a man of massive
ego himself who has about the same control issues as Holmgren.
</P>
<P>
   The complexity of pro football in an era of genuine free agency
mitigates against success in what Holmgren wants _ the dual role of
coach and general manager. But the fact that Denver's Mike
Shanahan, Miami's Jimmy Johnson and New York's Bill Parcells have
pulled off the two-headed beast suggests the task is less than
impossible.
</P>
<P>
   The Seahawks' vice president of football operations, Randy
Mueller, is willing and able to take a lesser role in deference to
Holmgren. Allen will be happy to make him the game's highest-paid
coach.
</P>
<P>
   The largest remaining issue is whether Whitsitt can give up some
ground as Allen's sports general. It's a risk, because Holmgren's
obsessive need to run it his way can chase the franchise into yet
another blind alley.
</P>
<P>
   But Whitsitt doesn't know football, and doesn't have a better
option. The risk is well worth the reward.
</P>
<P>
   Hey, the worst that can happen is that the Seahawks flop, he
gets fired and takes over the Mariners, which is as close to
permanent sports employment as it gets around here.
</P>
<P>
   Art Thiel is a P-I columnist.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-01-08-99 0223EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
