<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKN-SONICS-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SONICS DROP PLANS TO PURSE JAYSON WILLIAMS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By RONALD TILLERY  
 c.1999 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ A day to absorb the finer points of the NBA's new
collective bargaining agreement brought about a sharp dose of
reality for the Sonics.
</P>
<P>
   The retooling plan team president Wally Walker and his staff
spent sixth months formulating is as good as a $3 bill. Because of
unexpected limitations with the new salary cap system, the prospect
of the Sonics signing an impact front line player, let alone New
Jersey's Jayson Williams, is about as real as a pro wrestler's
elbow smash.
</P>
<P>
   In effect, the Sonics must change their strategy for free-agent
shopping. Their priority now is retaining most of their own free
agents and filling in gaps at guard and small forward.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our front line is in good shape both depth wise and skill
wise,'' said Walker, regretfully acknowledging that certain players
are off his most-wanted list.
</P>
<P>
   ``If the right player appears to fill our (rebounding) needs, of
course, we're going to look at them. But we have some other needs,
too. We definitely need some ballhandling. We've got only two
guards under contract. We need another player who can backup
(Detlef Schrempf).
</P>
<P>
   The Sonics have six players under contract _ Schrempf, Jim
McIlvaine, Vin Baker, Hersey Hawkins, Gary Payton and Aaron
Williams. The team drafted 7-footer Vladimir Stepania, 6-11 Rashard
Lewis and 6-11 Jelani McCoy _ each of whom Walker says is skilled
enough to contribute.
</P>
<P>
   The Sonics, though, clearly anticipated having enough cap room
to go after an established front-line player.
</P>
<P>
   The team was counting on a salary cap of $32 million. The
league's new labor agreement calls for a $30 million cap, and the
Sonics already have a payroll that exceeds $25 million.
</P>
<P>
   That figure is likely to go up considering the league's newest
cap rule: For each roster spot open, $300,000 is applied to a
team's cap figure. With six players signed and one first-round
draft pick, the Sonics will see an additional $1.5 million
($300,000 multiplied by five) added to their cap before they spend
$1.
</P>
<P>
   The Sonics could be less than $3 million under the cap _ nearly
$5 million less than they anticipated.
</P>
<P>
   ``The agreement is a fair deal for everyone. There are some
changes that don't give us as much flexibility that we thought we
had a couple of days ago,'' Walker said. ``But long-term, it will
all come out in the wash. What won't help us near-term will help us
in a couple of years. We'll just make the best of it.''
</P>
<P>
   The Sonics would have to consider a trade in order to clear
enough cap room to lure a top-notch free agent such as Williams.
According to sources, Hawkins' name is again at the center of
several trade scenarios involving the Sonics.
</P>
<P>
   Walker said nothing is in the works.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have absolutely nothing working on a trade front,'' Walker
said. ``(Coach) Paul (Westphal) has looked at a lot of tape and
likes what he's heard and seen of guys coming back. I would
anticipate going to camp with that group, figuring we'll add around
them.''
</P>
<P>
   Westphal said his wish is to secure veteran players, who are
versatile and can handle the ball. A main priority will be finding
a guard who can dribble and distribute well enough to allow Payton
to play without the ball.
</P>
<P>
   ``Manipulation of the cap is going to be huge,'' Westphal said.
`` ... It's fun to read about, but realistically a lot of these
people we can't pursue. It's fun to talk about, but it doesn't mean
anything. The salary cap has tied our hands in some respect.''
</P>
<P>
   The Sonics would like to retain small forwards Dale Ellis and
James Cotton, and backup point guard Greg Anthony. They also are
interested in keeping power forward Jerome Kersey.
</P>
<P>
   Except for Cotton, each of those players falls under the Larry
Bird Exception _ a clause that allows teams to sign its own players
without regard to the salary cap.
</P>
<P>
   The new agreement also includes a ``middle class'' exception,
which can be used by teams each year that exceed the salary cap.
There is a $1 million exception that can be used every other year
by teams over the cap.
</P>
<P>
   The Sonics cannot benefit from the $1 million exception because
they used it last year to sign Williams and Kersey. The team will
have the $1.75 million available should it go over the cap.
</P>
<P>
   If the Sonics want to keep their own free agents, they will
likely compete with the clock and offers from other teams.
</P>
<P>
   Milwaukee, Portland and New York are said to be interested in
Cotton. San Antonio is prepared to give Ellis its $1.75 million
exception _ something Ellis may jump at considering the Sonics did
not pick up his $1.9 million option after last season.
</P>
<P>
   Anthony, who had a solid year as Payton's backup, might be
looking for a starting position and the pay that goes with it.
</P>
<P>
   Once the Sonics go over the cap, they can sign any number of
players at the league minimum.
</P>
<P>
   The way the new agreement is configured will force some tough
decisions for Walker. The Sonics can still fill their rebounding
void in free agency, although it will have to be with a second- or
third-tier player.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're getting more realistic about what free agents fit where
we are cap-wise,'' Walker said. ``I think we'll be able to narrow
it down rather quickly. We'll definitely be aggressive. But we want
to be realistic about who we can sign with the amount of cap room
we have. We're not going to have a lot of time to waste.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-01-08-99 0226EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
