A4338 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-HKN-KINGS-WRITETHRU &LR; -     01-08 0644
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HKN-KINGS-WRITETHRU </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ROBITAILLE REACHES MILESTONE
</HEADLINE>
 - LBPT (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By ROGER PHILLIPS  
 Long Beach Press-Telegram  
<TEXT>
<P>
   INGLEWOOD _ It was exactly the type of goal it was supposed to
be, a late-game pressure situation, the Kings clinging to a lead,
and Luc Robitaille driving to the net.
</P>
<P>
   The pass came from rookie Pavel Rosa, and the 32-year-old
Robitaille made little more than a subtle deflection, but that was
all that was needed for his second goal Thursday night, his 22nd of
the season, and the 500th of his 13-year National Hockey League
career.
</P>
<P>
   Robitaille was mobbed by his teammates, and the goal, with 1:46
to play, secured the Kings' 4-2 victory over goalie Dwayne Roloson
and the Buffalo Sabres before a Forum crowd of 10,821.
</P>
<P>
   ``It feels good to get it out of the way,'' Robitaille said
after becoming the 27th player and sixth left wing in NHL history
to score 500 goals. ``But most important is the victory.''
</P>
<P>
   Robitaille then showed he was human after all when asked if he
felt he had proven wrong those who had discounted his talents
throughout a career that began when he was selected by the Kings
with the 171st choice in the 1984 draft.
</P>
<P>
   ``Whoever didn't believe in me,'' Robitaille said, ``well, screw
them today.''
</P>
<P>
   Kings coach Larry Robinson added, ``In Luc's case, a lot of
people don't give him enough credit for how hard he's worked on his
skating. You don't get 500 goals by being lucky, no pun intended.''
</P>
<P>
   Rosa, 21, counted himself among the fortunate. In his 10th NHL
game, Rosa came close to saying that assisting on the historic goal
was on a par with scoring two goals in his first game last month.
</P>
<P>
   ``He was my hero growing up,'' said Rosa, a native of the Czech
Republic. ``Sure, I was following Wayne Gretzky and Jaromir Jagr,
but I had Luc's picture on the wall. The only thing I can say is I
wish I could go as far as him. He has a lot of passion for the
sport, and he's a great guy.''
</P>
<P>
   As for the Kings (15-21-3), the victory was their seventh in the
last eight games, and their season-high fifth in a row. Rosa and
Sandy Moger scored the Kings' other goals.
</P>
<P>
   Vaclav Varada and Michael Peca scored for the Sabres (21-10-5),
who used Roloson in goal rather than two-time Most Valuable Player
Dominik Hasek, who was given a rare night off 24 hours after
recording an overtime victory over the Mighty Ducks at the Pond. It
was just the fifth appearance for Roloson this season.
</P>
<P>
   There was nothing Roloson could have done to prevent
Robitaille's first goal, a one-timer from the right faceoff circle
off a cross-ice feed from Rob Blake with the Kings enjoying a
two-man advantage 2:48 into the game.
</P>
<P>
   ``When I got the first one, you know some nights, you're on,''
said Robitaille, who has scored 12 goals in the last 15 games and
has scored 430 of his goals during two stints with the Kings. ``I
felt good the whole night.''
</P>
<P>
   He felt even better later, and was asked if he planned to send
the puck with which he scored No. 500 to the Hockey Hall of Fame.
</P>
<P>
   Robitaille held the puck aloft and said, ``I'll keep it. They'll
have to come get it. I've got kids. I have to keep it.''
</P>
<P>
   But Robitaille was not ready to attempt to put the historic goal
into any sort of perspective. His resurgence this season - he
already has scored six more goals than all of last season - has him
thinking loftier thoughts, of more goals and maybe even a Stanley
Cup before he retires.
</P>
<P>
   Last year, the Kings re-acquired Robitaille after he spent three
difficult years away, with Pittsburgh and the New York Rangers.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is the team that started me and this is the team that
wanted me back,'' Robitaille said. ``It's been great. The whole
comeback here has been great. I feel I'm lucky to be in the NHL.
I'll never take it for granted.''
</P>
</TEXT>
