<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-01-08 09:51 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4508 &Cx1f; tad-z
u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CONGRESS-AGENDA09-COX     01-08 0813
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CONGRESS-AGENDA09-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    CLINTON TRIAL IMPERILS REST OF CONGRESSIONAL AGENDA
 &HT;    With CONGRESS-LIST.
 &HT;    By ANDREW MOLLISON
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ The Senate impeachment trial of President Clinton
will slow efforts by leaders of the new Congress to pass major
legislation, members and outside analysts agree.
</P>
<P>
   The delay won't necessarily kill chances of passing proposals to
save Social Security and Medicare, or reaching compromises on
issues such as defense and education spending, but it certainly
won't help, the experts said.
</P>
<P>
   ``You have a presidential election coming up in 2000, and that
usually freezes parties into positions that showcase their
stands,'' said political scientist Joseph Cooper at Johns Hopkins
University in Baltimore.
</P>
<P>
   ``So the window for getting things done is probably nine or 10
months at most,'' Cooper said. ``The most likely result is that
nothing important will happen.''
</P>
<P>
   Congress-watcher Sarah Binder at the Brookings Institution, a
nonpartisan research center in Washington, was slightly more
optimistic.
</P>
<P>
   ``Strangely enough, (incumbents in) both parties might have
incentives to reach agreement on Social Security in 2000, so they
won't have to face the voters without anything to brag about,'' she
said.
</P>
<P>
   Still, she agreed that ``productivity is unlikely'' for other
reasons, such as the ``terribly slim majority margin'' that
Republicans have in the House and sincere differences between
Republicans and Democrats over the best way to handle such
challenges as education, managed health care, tobacco, trade and
banking.
</P>
<P>
   Binder said the effect of impeachment-related delays will be
minimized by the fact that the trial is coming just as a new
Congress convenes.
</P>
<P>
   ``Nothing much of substance comes to the Senate floor in January
or February anyway,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Committees must get organized, fill out their staffs, hold
hearings and draft bills before the Senate or House even considers
a bill. The process, which involves both chambers and the White
House, is so complex and time-consuming that only eight of the 394
laws enacted in the last Congress were completed during the first
three months of 1997.
</P>
<P>
   Nobody disputes that action on matters other than impeachment
will be slowed down.
</P>
<P>
   Senate Minority Leader Tom Daschle, D-S.D., said that until the
impeachment trial is over, the 45 Democrats will block Senate
action on ``important legislative work on matters like education,
health care, Medicare and Social Security.'' That should encourage
senators who want to tackle those issues to concentrate on
finishing the trial as soon as possible, he said.
</P>
<P>
   Even if the Democrats block floor votes on legislation, the 55
Republicans can push for progress at the committee level, replied
Senate Majority Leader Trent Lott, R-Miss.
</P>
<P>
   ``Now we may not be having debate and votes on the floor of the
Senate on bills or on changes in the budget procedures around
here,'' Lott conceded. But he predicted that committee hearings and
meetings held before or after the trial sessions will let senators
``do our very best to get prepared for the regular legislative
process while we're doing our duty with regard to impeachment.''
</P>
<P>
   However, it would be hard for senators to concentrate on other
things while they are deciding whether to oust a president,
predicted Rep. Jim McDermott, D-Wash. For example, Senate and House
committees won't even consider Medicare until Congress receives a
report from the National Bipartisan Commission on the Future of
Medicare.
</P>
<P>
   Because the 17-member commission includes five senators, it will
probably miss its March 1 deadline for finding a bipartisan
compromise, McDermott said. ``For anybody to think that senators
are going to be able to spend much time thinking about this issue
... is overly optimistic to say the least,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   With 13 senior House Republicans preoccupied with their role as
managers prosecuting Clinton in the Senate trial, action in the
House also could be slowed.
</P>
<P>
   The trial's effects will persist after it ends, political
scientist Cooper said.
</P>
<P>
   ``This isn't Watergate, where there was a public consensus,''
Cooper said. ``No matter what happens, one-third or more of the
country is going to be mad.''
</P>
<P>
   That will make it harder to unify public sentiment around big
changes in either Social Security or Medicare, he said.
</P>
<P>
   If Clinton stays in office, Republicans in Congress still won't
trust him, Cooper said.
</P>
<P>
   On the other hand, he said, If Clinton is ousted, any honeymoon
period for Vice President Al Gore, who would succeed Clinton, is
likely to be short. ``You're going to be coming into an election,
and Republicans won't want Gore to look too good,'' he explained.
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
