<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    REPUBLICANS, DEMOCRATS IN CONGRESS HAVE SIMILAR GOALS
 &HT;    With CONGRESS-AGENDA.
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   SENATE
</P>
<P>
   PRIORITIES OF MAJORITY LEADER TRENT LOTT, R-MISS.
</P>
<P>
   _ Long-term fiscal solutions for Social Security and Medicare.
</P>
<P>
   _ Timely passage of regular spending bills.
</P>
<P>
   _ Higher defense spending.
</P>
<P>
   _ Lower income and Social Security payroll taxes.
</P>
<P>
   _ Simpler income taxes.
</P>
<P>
   _ Bigger portion of education aid channeled into classrooms.
</P>
<P>
   _ Lower auto and health insurance premiums.
</P>
<P>
   _ Softer regulations for small businesses.
</P>
<P>
   PRIORITIES OF MINORITY LEADER TOM DASCHLE, D-S.D.
</P>
<P>
   _ Save Social Security.
</P>
<P>
   _ Save Medicare.
</P>
<P>
   _ Aid education.
</P>
<P>
   _ Improve health care.
</P>
<P>
   HOUSE
</P>
<P>
   PRIORITIES OF SPEAKER DENNIS HASTERT, R-ILL.
</P>
<P>
   _ Long-term fiscal solutions for Social Security and Medicare.
</P>
<P>
   _ Timely passage of regular spending bills.
</P>
<P>
   _ Bigger portion of education aid channeled into classrooms.
</P>
<P>
   _ Better defense capability.
</P>
<P>
   _ Smaller, more efficient government and taxes.
</P>
<P>
   PRIORITIES OF DEMOCRATIC CAUCUS
</P>
<P>
   _ Offer bipartisan cooperation on Social Security, education,
health care.
</P>
<P>
   _ Seek bipartisan support for President Clinton's agenda.
</P>
<P>
   Sources: Floor speeches by Lott, Daschle and Hastert; news
conference by House Democratic Caucus Chairman Martin Frost.
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
