<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TAMMEUS-EXTREME-KAN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PRO FOOTBALL COULD USE MORE RAZZMATAZZ 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By BILL TAMMEUS  
 c. 1999 KANSAS CITY STAR 
<TEXT>
<P>
   As the country gets increasingly football crazy with the
approach of Super Bowl MCIV.V _ if that's the number _ it seems to
me the game at the professional level is overrated. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Which is to say its reputation for being violent, full of wild,
hulking men willing to whip their opponents to a pulp because it
feels good and entertains slack-jawed Americans isn't enough
anymore. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Oh, I know you can see lots of National Football League games in
which people get hurt and get carted off in wheelbarrows and placed
in institutions until they remember what their name is. But, on the
whole, pro football could be much more extreme. In fact, unless it
gets that way it will begin to lose fans and fall on hard times. My
thinking here is influenced by the new-found popularity of
so-called extreme games seen now and then on TV. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Well, maybe YOU see them on TV. I don't. I've only heard about
them. So I'll have to make up what some of them might be. If you
know anything about these extreme games on TV and find that my
description of them isn't accurate, I'd be grateful if you'd keep
quiet. Many folks out in newspaperland think I know what I'm
talking about. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Anyway, in these extreme TV games, you have half-naked people
skiing down icy cliffs while wearing blindfolds. Or billiards
players who, for a cue ball, use a hand-grenade. Or horseback
riders who are Scotch-taped to bucking broncos and given points for
how many arrows they can shoot into a target's bull's-eye while
hanging on. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   So what about pro football? Well, the hulking men are all
dressed up in pads, for heaven's sake. It's hard to imagine how any
part of them ever gets injured, as wrapped up as they are in wads
of plastic and Nerf. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   I say it's time to force players in this year's Super Bowl to
dress as ruggedly as your average rugby player, which is to say in
nothing but shorts and a rugby shirt. No helmets. No padding. Strap
it on, boys. Be men. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   I'd change the field, too. What, these days, is 100 yards? Why,
it's hardly anything. I'd stretch the field out to at least 300
yards and make it 100 yards wide, too. If touchdowns and field
goals are to be admired for the skill required to score them, let's
raise the level of difficulty. Touchdowns have become way too cheap
in today's NFL games. A 300-yard field would give the offense a
real sense of accomplishment when scoring. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   I'd also do away with the level playing field. How difficult is
it to run 300 yards on a flat surface? Heck, even I can do that,
although it might take me the better part of an afternoon. No, I'd
redesign the field to give it a rather large hill near the 150-yard
line and several moguls, creeks and valleys elsewhere. Think of the
fun of breaking tackles to rush up a steep embankment and being
able, eventually, to speed pell-mell down the other side toward the
goal line way off in the distance. Now we're talking some skill,
some endurance and some serious fan interest. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   I'd add other difficulties, too, like making part of the field
an ice rink and another part a sand dune. I'd bring in your
occasional bomber to drop water balloons on the field while the
game is on. Or pumpkins. Or anything else that would liven up the
competition. Jell-O, maybe. And I'd allow the cheerleaders on the
sidelines to leap around on trampolines nude. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   I'm telling you, if you put the future of the NFL in my hands,
I'll rescue it from the predictability that now plagues both it and
the stupid pre-game shows. In fact, I'd make it a rule that
pre-game shows cannot run until after the game. Between 2 and 4
a.m. On ESPN-6. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Bill Tammeus is a columnist for The Kansas City Star. This
article was distributed by The New York Times News Service. E-mail:
tammeus(at)kcstar.com.) &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-01-08-99 0959EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
