<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-01-08 10:12 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4524 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-HKN-STARS-TEX     01-08 0699
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HKN-STARS-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
STARS STAY ON TRACK WHEN ON ROAD
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By SIMON GONZALEZ 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   DALLAS _ The Stars' franchise-record 15-game winning streak is
expected to face its toughest test since it began with a victory
against the Edmonton Oilers on Dec. 6.
</P>
<P>
   The rugged opponent isn't Phoenix, New Jersey, Detroit or one of
the other elite NHL teams. It's the schedule-maker.
</P>
<P>
   The Stars departed yesterday for a five-game journey to Calgary,
Vancouver, Edmonton, San Jose and Anaheim, their longest road trip
of the season.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's really tough,'' Stars coach Ken Hitchcock said. ``This is
the toughest road trip we're going to have all year. I don't think
there's one that's even close to it.''
</P>
<P>
   At a glance it doesn't appear that difficult. None of the five
teams has a winning record overall, although the Mighty Ducks,
Canucks and Sharks are at .500 or better at home. However, it's the
logistics more than the teams that make it a challenge.
</P>
<P>
   After a 1,500-mile flight across one time zone, the Stars are in
Calgary, Alberta, today for a game against the Flames.
</P>
<P>
   Afterward, they'll leave the cold climate of Calgary (forecast
high: 10 degrees) and head to the west coast of Canada across
another time zone for a Sunday night game in Vancouver, the last
place they lost.
</P>
<P>
   Then they'll say goodbye to a moderate climate (highs in the
40s) and go back to Alberta for a Tuesday night game in frigid
Edmonton, where the forecast high yesterday was minus-2 with a low
of minus-19.
</P>
<P>
   The Stars leave immediately after the game for the warm climes
of San Jose. After a 1,200-mile flight across another time zone,
going through customs and arriving at about 3:30 a.m., they have a
game that night against the Sharks, who have no trouble getting up
to play the team that knocked them out of the playoffs last season.
</P>
<P>
   Then it's down the coast to Anaheim for a Friday night game
against the Mighty Ducks.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's the zig-zagging, it's the back-to-back over the border,
it's cold-warm-cold-warm,'' Hitchcock said. ``There's a lot of
built in excuses if we want to use them. They're legit. But I think
our group won't do that.''
</P>
<P>
   The Stars rarely need an excuse when it comes to road games.
It's supposed to be tough to play in an opponents' arena, but
Hitchcock's players have won 72 percent of their contests away from
home, best in the league. They lead the NHL with 26 road points.
</P>
<P>
   The 15-game unbeaten streak includes seven victories and two
ties away from Reunion Arena. They've lost once in their past 15
road games. That includes victories in Detroit, Toronto, Colorado
and Phoenix.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think our team has a lot of fun in winning in other team's
buildings,'' Hitchcock said.
</P>
<P>
   Obviously, talent is a factor. But there's more to success away
from home than that.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's the leadership and the experience we have,'' veteran
center Guy Carbonneau said. ``The core of this team has been
together for a long time, and everybody, when they step on the ice,
they know what they have to do. We're a patient team. We don't take
chances, but when we have chances, we're able to put some goals on
the board. Some other teams push too hard and make mistakes and get
out of their game too early. We're not that way. We have a lot of
patience.''
</P>
<P>
   Stars center Mike Modano is more productive away from home.
Eight of his 13 goals and 14 of his 26 assists have come in road
games.
</P>
<P>
   ``When you're on the road you're not trying to put on a show,
you're not trying to be entertaining,'' Modano said. ``At home you
can get caught up in being a little too flashy to get the home
crowd into it. You're not there to be fancy or cute, you just want
to get the job done. That's what sets us apart. We play real
patient, real smart, and we try to grind out those 2-1, 3-2
games.''
</P>
<P>
   The logistics of this journey could make it difficult to return
home with the unbeaten streak intact. However, the road warriors
won't give it up without a fight.
</P>
<P>
   ``Teams that are mature recognize that you're usually gauged by
your ability to win on the road,'' Hitchcock said. ``We want to be
gauged as a good team.''
</P>
</TEXT>
