<HEADLINE>
DID BAYLOR LOSE PLAYER, GAIN A TEAM
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By MIKE JONES 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   FORT WORTH, Texas _ Maybe it was Kansas.
</P>
<P>
   Maybe that's why Baylor played at the level it did in losing a
four-point game to the 18th-ranked team in the land Wednesday
night.
</P>
<P>
   Maybe the all-out effort had nothing to do with the fact that,
according to several accounts, this beleaguered team has bonded in
the aftermath of the loss of leading scorer Tevis Stukes, who
decided that life was sweeter without coach Harry Miller in it,
even though it meant giving up the game he loves for the time
being.
</P>
<P>
   Personally, I can't imagine anyone not being able to get along
with Miller. Therein lies another story, which we may never know
and maybe isn't really any of our business.
</P>
<P>
   Some of the questions may be answered as the season progresses.
Maybe even tomorrow when another ranked team _ No. 23 Oklahoma
State _ comes into the Ferrell Center. But for the time being, we
know at least one thing _ even if he has lost Stukes, Harry Miller
doesn't appear to have lost the rest of his team.
</P>
<P>
   Someone asked Miller the other night where the team that was on
the floor against the Jayhawks had been all season.
</P>
<P>
   ``Well,'' he said, ``I just think this team is very, very
focused right now.''
</P>
<P>
   Asked again if he believed Stukes' exit was part of the cause,
Miller honestly replied, ``I don't know. All I know is I like what
I saw.
</P>
<P>
   ``I had some guys come into my office and tell me they were
rededicating themselves to what we were doing. That the commitment
was going to go to another level and that, from what I was told,
they were speaking for the entire team. And that's what they did _
to a man.''
</P>
<P>
   Ironically, the man who most exemplified the commitment was
Stukes' roommate _ center Kish Lewis.
</P>
<P>
   Lewis conceded the Kansas' presence may have provided extra
juice and then gave strong testament to the rededication factor.
</P>
<P>
   ``When we go out to play a game, we all hold hands and pray,''
Lewis said. ``If you're not in that circle, there's not a whole lot
you can do for us when we go out that door.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think the guys who are in \Rthe circle\S need to keep
working hard. Close is not good enough for me. I'm not going to
accept not working hard and trying to win games. Whatever the
situation may be _ whether we drew a positive from a negative or
whether we just put together a good basketball game, I'm not sure.
But I know we're going to stick together and keep fighting. We're
going to give teams a game every night we play if I have anything
to do with it _ and I do.''
</P>
<P>
   Whether this team can save this coach after the player who
appeared to give him the best chance of saving himself deserted is
conjecture. Miller has a year after this one left on his contract,
which the odds are against his completing. Though Miller refuses to
say, I suspect his dispute with his star player was based on an
issue of character. I'm convinced Miller's remains intact.
</P>
<P>
   ``Harry's in a tough deal right now,'' Kansas coach Roy Williams
said. ``He needs some help. But we're both lucky. We could have to
work for a living.''
DON'T LOOK NOW So. Rick Barnes' Texas Longhorns (6-8) have won
three consecutive games, four of their past five and have opened
2-0 for the first time in the Big 12. But Barnes, who takes his
team to Nebraska on Sunday, would just as soon not talk about the
rebound from an 0-4 start. Yet.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm afraid to talk about it,'' he confessed. ``I just want to
sit back and hope it keeps on going, you know?''
</P>
<P>
   If not for a 56-46 loss to Princeton in Hawaii on Dec. 29, Texas
would be on a five-game winning streak. But Barnes said that loss,
coupled with some two-a-day work on the offense before leaving for
the Outrigger Rainbow Classic, was instrumental in the three
victories hence (Hawaii, Colorado, Iowa State).
</P>
<P>
   ``I told the team after the Princeton game that that game proved
one thing that I'd told them all along _ the mental part of this
game is equal to or more important than the physical part,'' Barnes
said. ``Physically, Princeton shouldn't match up. But they knew
what they were doing, what they wanted to do, and they never
deviated.''
</P>
<P>
   Barnes cautiously believes the message has gotten through.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're not by any means a great offensive team yet,'' Barnes
said. ``But even our turnovers are coming within our offense. We've
gotten away from a lot of our circus shots and those type things.
Guys are looking one, two passes ahead.''
</P>
<P>
   Turnovers are down more than five a game. Chris Mihm and Gabe
Muoneke have been dominant inside in conference wins over Colorado
and Iowa State. In the past six games, Kris Clack is averaging 18
points and eight rebounds and _ get this _ shooting 55 percent from
the floor, 10 percentage points higher than his career average.
</P>
<P>
   Wonder what's going on in the Burnt Orange room these days?
HILL CLIMBER FOR CONRADT Texas' women have a big game tomorrow when
No. 20 Nebraska (13-2, 2-0) visits. And surprisingly, one of the
Cornhuskers' major concerns will be stopping Jody Conradt's new
off-the-bench, instant-offense machine _ Del Valle freshman Asha
Hill. In the past four game, the 5-foot-9 guard has averaged 17.4
points and netted 11 of 18 3-pointers. Previously, she carried a
1.3-point average. But it was defense _ not her offense _ that has
gotten her into the lineup.
</P>
<P>
   ``When the lights turn on, Asha is pretty amazing,'' Conradt
said. ``It's taken her a while to learn that you have to play both
ends. But she's talented and has a great understanding of the game.
She'll be a big part of what we do from now on.''
</P>
<P>
   Better guard depth from her still-young club has enabled Conradt
to shift emphasis to the pressing defensive style she loves, which
has triggered a much-improved transition game that in turn has led
to offensive production.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've been trying to establish our personality, to become the
transition team that will get in your face defensively,'' Conradt
said. ``Our intensity has picked up and, hopefully, that will be
the Texas team people see from now on. We're taking giant steps now
instead of baby ones.''
</P>
<P>
   The Longhorns (7-5, 1-1) won their Big 12 opener over Colorado
(83-65), then lost Tuesday night at No. 16 Iowa State (71-68), when
Megan Taylor hit a last-second, 3-point prayer off an inbounds
play. Some good news, though. When Conradt received her courtesy
game tape, Taylor's shot wasn't on it.
</P>
<P>
   ``They didn't get,'' Conradt said. ``But it's just as well. I
don't think I wanted to see it again anyway.''
POINTS AFTER Lady Raiders player Rene Hanebutt set a team mark with
seven 3-point shots in the victory over Oklahoma on Wednesday,
breaking a tie between herself and two others at six.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's probably one of the only records I could hold at
Tech,'' Hanebutt said. ``It's a nice one to have. But records are
made to be broken. I can't wait to see who breaks it.''
</P>
<P>
   She leads the Big 12 in 3-pointers made (42), attempted (91) and
percentage made (.461). And is closing on another Tech record. Her
career 3-point totals (217 of 521) trail only former guard Noel
Johnson (256 of 603). Hanebutt needs an average of only three per
game to pass Johnson in the regular season.
</P>
<P>
   No one has started conference play hotter than Kansas' Lynn
Pride, who has scored 57 points and pulled down 19 rebounds in
games against Texas A&AMP;M and Baylor _ the top two consecutive games
of her career. Lady Bears coach Sonja Hogg compared her to
Tennessee's Chamique Holdsclaw, a similarity not undeserved, says
coach Marian Washington.
</P>
<P>
   ``Lynn is truly one of the top players in the country,''
Washington said.
</P>
<P>
   Not a bad performance by Texas A&AMP;M guard Clifton Cook (25
points, five 3-pointers, eight rebounds) against a guard-oriented
team like Oklahoma State, as the Aggies reversed dismal efforts in
losses to Southern and Kansas. The killer in four consecutive
losses _ 70 turnovers.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's important we play hard and beat Missouri \Rtomorrow at
home\S to regain some confidence,'' Cook said. ``To do that, we
have to eliminate turnovers and execute.''
</P>
<P>
   A&AMP;M got only 18 combined minutes vs. Oklahoma State from injured
inside players Paul Jacobs and Aaron Jack.
</P>
<P>
   Less pressure, lower expectations for Kansas' men?
</P>
<P>
   ``Two different words,'' Roy Williams said. ``There are not as
many expectations, but there's still a lot of pressure on this
team.''
</P>
