<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-GALLOWAY-COLUMN-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CHAN'S VOICE NEEDS TO CHANGE PERSONNEL TONE
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By RANDY GALLOWAY 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   FORT WORTH, Texas _ A medical update on honored colleague Gil
LeBreton _ Gil is out of intensive care and recovering nicely after
flinging himself against a Valley Ranch windmill earlier this week.
</P>
<P>
   In a 911 column on the current state of the Cowboys, LeBreton
strongly urged Jerry Jones to cease immediately with the general
manager charade and hire a proven football guy to lead the way in
personnel decisions.
</P>
<P>
   Structural damage to the windmill was nil.
</P>
<P>
   Of course, this particular common sense battle with Jones is not
winnable, no matter how many Arizona disasters are presented as
evidence. Many of us, like LeBreton, carry multiple windmill scars
because of it.
</P>
<P>
   But in this first week of Valley Ranch off-season hibernation,
the prime topic of concentration has immediately shifted to
on-the-field personnel. Between now and the April draft, the
Cowboys will be deciding what's right and wrong about current
players, what free agents to pursue, and what help will be
available through the college pipeline.
</P>
<P>
   Based on existing trends in all these areas, failure has been
rampant for, oh, what's it been now ... five years, right? Or ever
since The Jimster scooted out of town.
</P>
<P>
   Nothing haunts the Cowboys of today like the past five years of
personnel decisions, starting with the college draft but certainly
including the evaluation of their own players.
</P>
<P>
   Give this much to Jones. He is not making these personnel
decisions on his own. Jones is mostly listening. And behind closed
doors, when Jones' pride and ego is not on public display, the
constant claim of respected coaches and scouts is that Jerry
qualifies as a good listener.
</P>
<P>
   But what he's been hearing has not been valid. An Arizona thing
happens partly because outside of the free-agent signing of Deion
and the drafting of Larry Allen, there hasn't been an impact
upgrade to the roster in five long years.
</P>
<P>
   For example, compare the college draft with the five years Jimmy
Johnson was in charge, as opposed to the past five years. And to
even the odds, throw out Johnson's first-round picks, while
comparing all rounds without Johnson.
</P>
<P>
   NFL starters drafted under Johnson _ Daryl Johnston, Mark
Stepnoski, Tony Tolbert, Dixon Edwards, Erik Williams, Leon Lett,
Larry Brown, Jimmy Smith, Darren Woodson, Kevin Williams, Darrin
Smith, Ron Stone and Brock Marion. Remember, that's minus the first
round.
</P>
<P>
   And the five years since Johnson, including the first round _
Larry Allen, Kavika Pittman, Clay Shiver, Randall Godfrey, David
LaFleur, Dexter Coakley, Greg Ellis and Flozell Adams.
</P>
<P>
   Another downer about the past five years _ basically the same
people have been Jones advisers. Earlier, it was the coaching staff
that had the most say. Lately, it's been Larry Lacewell and the
scouting staff. Improved drafts have come under the scouting
department, but it's still not enough.
</P>
<P>
   Then, for four years, there was also an unwrapped mummy of a
head coach, meaning what should have been the loudest voice in the
draft had no vocal cords. Last year, Chan Gailey took over as head
coach, but with barely two months on the job, Gailey's opinion was
not given top priority.
</P>
<P>
   Which brings us to the potential sunshine-and-daffodils portion
of this column.
</P>
<P>
   Gailey now represents a new lead voice in the Cowboys'
decision-making choir. There is no question Jones respects his
coach, and maybe just as important to Jerry, is also comfortable
working alongside Gailey. There will be no tug-of-egos over who is
in charge. All personnel decisions in this off-season will be based
on football-minded decisions.
</P>
<P>
   Is Gailey a good personnel man?
</P>
<P>
   Don't know yet. And neither does Jerry.
</P>
<P>
   But in Gailey's 10 years of previous NFL experience, he worked
under Dan Reeves in Denver and Bill Cowher in Pittsburgh. Reeves is
as good as it gets in personnel, and has proved that again in
Atlanta. Year in and year out, the Steelers are recognized as one
of the NFL's strongest organizations in personnel decisions.
</P>
<P>
   If nothing else, Gailey has certainly been schooled by the right
people.
</P>
<P>
   For like five straight years, it's been popular and accurate to
say a critical off-season on personnel awaits the Cowboys. That now
goes double. But the difference this time is the Gailey influence.
</P>
<P>
   Will Chan make a difference? He'd better.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
