<HEADER>
A4558 &Cx1f; tad-z
u l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-WARNER-ON-WOOD09-COX     01-08 0619
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-WARNER-ON-WOOD09-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Cutting a tension easier than a mortise
 &HT;    By Jack Warner
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Since we discussed the cutting of mortises last week,
we may as well look at ways of making the second half of the joint,
the tenon.
</P>
<P>
   Tenons, generally, are easier and quicker to make than mortises
because they are cut and not dug out. They are nearly always done
with a saw _ hand saw, table saw or band saw.
</P>
<P>
   I have never cut a tenon with a hand saw, and I don't suppose I
ever will. It requires more skill than I possess, and cutting them
by hand when every kind of power saw is available falls into the
category of mere exercise.
</P>
<P>
   I've cut them on the table saw and on the band saw, and even
used a router table. Sometimes you will want to use a combination
of tools, depending on their dimensions and the available
equipment.
</P>
<P>
   The quick way of cutting fairly short tenons is using a tenoning
jig on the table saw. A tenoning jig holds the workpiece upright,
end grain on the table, as it is passsed over the blade. A good jig
can be set so that the first pass cuts one side of the tenon, and
after the tighterning screw is used and the jig moved to a preset
stop, the other side is cut. Depending on the size of your blade,
you can cut tenons about three inches long this way, and if you
have your fence properly adjusted, they'll be very accurate.
</P>
<P>
   Usually you'll have to cut the shoulders of the tenons
separately, because there'll still be some waste adhering to the
work piece after the initial cuts.
</P>
<P>
   To get a good sharp shoulder, it's best to finish all the cuts
with the tenoning jig, then set it aside and set up for a repeated
cross cut operation. This involves both the miter square and the
rip fence. Put one of the workpieces on the miter square and adjust
it so that the cut will take off the waste exactly where the
shoulder ought to be.
</P>
<P>
   Drop the blade so that it will cut off only the waste. Now clamp
a small piece of scrap to the rip fence at a point well ahead of
the blade. Bring the fence up so that the scrap just touches the
workpiece when it is positioned properly on the miter square. Dog
the fence down.
</P>
<P>
   Now, assuming that the tenon cuts left the tenon exactly in the
center of the workpiece, all you need to do is slap the workpiece
down at the miter square, run it over until it meets the scrap
piece on the fence, and then run it through the saw. Lift off the
workpiece, bring the miter square back, flip the workpiece over and
repeat the operation. This gives you a complete tenon with
absolutely square shoulders, assuming you checked the squareness of
the blade to the table and to the miter square.
</P>
<P>
   Novices will ask why they should use a small piece of scrap on
the fence, rather than just moving the fence up to touch the
workpiece.
</P>
<P>
   This is a safety matter. You never want to create a setup in
which a cut-off piece of wood can be jammed between the blade and
the fence. Really nasty things can result when that happens.
</P>
<P>
   If your tenon needs to be longer than the full height of your
table saw blade, you have two options. The quicker will be to set
up the band saw carefully and cut the tenons there, returning to
the table saw to cut the shoulders. Lacking a bandsaw, you can
waste the wood off the tenons with repeated cuts on the table saw,
using a dado set to speed things up. The drawback here is that
you'll have relatively rough sides on the tenons, since I've yet to
see a dado set that will make a perfectly smooth cut, but if the
roughness is minimal it won't be a problem.
</P>
<P>
   E-mail: jwarner(at)ajc.com.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
