<HEADER>
A4561 &Cx1f; tad-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-LOTTERY-PR09-COX     01-08 0822
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-LOTTERY-PR09-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Lottery officials push press for winners
 &HT;    By Ken Herman
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   AUSTIN, Texas _ State lottery officials eager to enlist their
most satisfied customers in the war on declining ticket sales are
pitching this message:
</P>
<P>
   Talking to reporters is good, clean fun.
</P>
<P>
   It's conveyed in a new, four-minute video aimed at enticing
winners to hold news conferences that garner the kind of positive
PR the lottery covets.
</P>
<P>
   Winners, said Lottery Director Linda Cloud, have become
increasingly camera shy. And she said lawyers are to blame.
</P>
<P>
   ``Their attorneys are getting more educated, so when they come
in to file their claim for their jackpot they are very reluctant to
be interviewed by any of our staff or, especially, do a press
conference,'' Cloud told the Texas Lottery Commission on Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   For jackpot winners, news conferences _ complete with a
ceremonial, oversized check _ are strictly optional. State law
requires the lottery to release minimal information about winners _
just name, hometown, prize amount and where the winning ticket was
purchased.
</P>
<P>
   But for the lottery, no news conference means no TV stories
featuring shiny, happy, suddenly-rich people talking about new
houses, new pickup trucks and what their soon-to-be-former-bosses
can do with their jobs.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's very important to the lottery that we have the exposure
that we do have winners out there,'' said Cloud, complaining that
the number of winners willing to do news conferences has dwindled
in the past year or so.
</P>
<P>
   The video to be shown to winners addresses stagefright in a
direct, if low-key, manner.
</P>
<P>
   ``Although most winners feel comfortable during the news
conference, they're still apprehensive early on about working with
the media due to images of persistent reporters and
photographers,'' the narrator says. ``However, winners who have
taken part in a news conference find that the experience is quite
painless and a lot of fun.''
</P>
<P>
   Austin lawyer Walker Arensen, who has represented three lotto
winners, said he advises them against a news conference.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's simply because of privacy,'' he said. ``A lottery winner
becomes a very popular person, and the news conference just
advertises that fact.''
</P>
<P>
   Arensen said all three of his clients ignored his advice and had
news conferences.
</P>
<P>
   ``They are proud of what they did. It is the thrill of the
moment,'' he said, ``Most of them probably look back and wish they
might not have done it.''
</P>
<P>
   Marcy Goodfleisch, the lottery's public information director,
said most winners have the normal fear of press.
</P>
<P>
   ``People who don't deal with the media on a regular basis have
fears that I find unfounded,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   The tape includes happy winners who survived news conferences.
</P>
<P>
   ``After doing it, it's fun to look at the video,'' said John
McGee of Corpus Christi, a $4.8 million winner.
</P>
<P>
   McGee also discovered another upside _ perhaps not too
surprising _ of suddenly showing up on TV with a few million bucks.
</P>
<P>
   ``People that you haven't seen in a long time, friends you just
lose touch with over time, will call you on the phone and say, `We
just saw you on TV last night,' '' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Imagine that.
</P>
<P>
   The new effort to persuade winners to meet the press was
previewed as lottery officials reported that the ticket sales slump
that coincided with the September 1997 cut in prize payouts is
continuing. Since the Sept. 1 start of the current fiscal year,
sales are down 18 percent compared to the same period last year.
</P>
<P>
   Lottery officials will ask the Texas Legislature, which convenes
Tuesday, to undo the prize cut.
</P>
<P>
   The airwaves attack on the sales slump now includes new ads
telling Texans that they shouldn't wait for lotto fever, induced by
high jackpots, to set in before they buy tickets.
</P>
<P>
   ``Hey, $4 million is a lot of money,'' say the ads, referring to
the starting point for lotto prizes.
</P>
<P>
   ``No one wants $4 million,'' Cloud said.
</P>
<P>
   The odds of winning a large prize are the same as winning a
smaller one, a mathematical fact that argues in favor of saving up
for big jackpot weeks.
</P>
<P>
   The sales decrease also is reflected in a demographic study
presented to state officials this week. The latest version of the
biannual report says about 68 percent of adult Texans bought at
least one ticket in the past year, down from 70 percent in the 1997
study.
</P>
<P>
   The new report also says lottery spending was down 28 percent
since the previous report. The ``typical player'' spent $457 on
lottery tickets in 1998, according to the report.
</P>
<P>
   In a preface, Cloud said the new report continues to show that
people ``with the lowest levels of education and income were the
least likely to play the games of the Texas Lottery,'' a result she
said disproves ``myths'' about who buys tickets.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
