<HEADER>
A4562 &Cx1f; tad-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-LOW-BUILDING-SUPPLIES     01-08 0973
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-LOW-BUILDING-SUPPLIES09-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    High demand has builders scrambling for materials
 &HT;    By R. Michelle Breyer
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   AUSTIN, Texas _ Custom home builder Brian Bailey is rushing to
finish the roof on the spacious house he is building.
</P>
<P>
   He needs the roof to provide shelter for the drywall he bought
ahead of schedule _ while he could.
</P>
<P>
   ``It may not be available in three to four weeks,'' Bailey said.
``We take it when we can get it.''
</P>
<P>
   With new home construction at a record high, builders such as
Bailey are having trouble getting the materials they need to build
houses. The nationwide demand for drywall, insulation, concrete and
man-made stone have outstripped the supply.
</P>
<P>
   As a result, builders and others say, anyone building a home may
want to brace themselves for delays _ and higher prices.
</P>
<P>
   ``These are the basic building elements of most walls and
ceilings in residential and commercial projects,'' said Craig
Weisbruch, senior vice president of sales and marketing for
National Gypsum Co., a Charlotte, N.C.-based company that is the
nation's second-largest drywall manufacturer. ``When they are
difficult to get, jobs stop.''
</P>
<P>
   Bailey, who builds houses ranging from 6,000 square feet to more
than 20,000 square feet, said these material shortages and the
resulting price increases, can add more than $10,000 to the price
of a large home _ costs that have been passed on the homebuyer.
</P>
<P>
   It's a situation that shows few signs of letting up.
</P>
<P>
   In a June survey by the National Association of Homebuilders,
respondents ranked a shortage of materials as one of the biggest
problems. The materials shortage probably is even worse now, given
a particularly strong housing market in the final months of last
year, said Michael Carliner, an economist with the Washington,
D.C.-based association. As a result, builders are being forced to
place orders weeks and sometimes months in advance to ensure
they'll have what they need. In the past, they need two to three
days' notice.
</P>
<P>
   Bailey said he snatches up building materials as soon as he can
get them. He is even considering renting warehouse space to store
drywall and other materials for future houses.
</P>
<P>
   Other builders and suppliers are taking other steps.
</P>
<P>
   Robert Sullivan, general manager of Williams Insulation in
Austin, said his company and others have been forced to buy
insulation from home improvement retailers such as The Home Depot
when they can't get it from their own suppliers.
</P>
<P>
   ``You can't count on what you're going to receive,'' Sullivan
said. ``You're living day-to-day.''
</P>
<P>
   Cycles of shortages
</P>
<P>
   Over the years, there have been shortages of one building
material or another, especially during times of economic prosperity
when commercial and residential construction deplete resources.
</P>
<P>
   During the early 1970s, there was a shortage of insulation.
During the mid-1990s, lumber prices shot skyward because of
cutbacks in national forest logging in the Pacific Northwest, home
to the endangered northern spotted owl. And over the past year,
railroad delays and a warm winter for building create a severe
statewide cement shortage. But ``never has there been a situation
when so many key ingredients of a house are in such short supply.''
Sullivan said.
</P>
<P>
   For only the second time in its 40-year history, Williams
Insulation has been forced to import insulation from Mexico and
Europe because of the limited U.S. supply. The shortage has pushed
up the price of insulation 30 percent to 40 percent over the past
year, Sullivan said. Insulation accounts for 1 percent to 2 percent
of the construction cost of a home, he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``As long as housing starts stay strong, the material will
remain in short supply,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Usually drywall and insulation companies build up inventories
during winter when construction projects traditionally slow down.
But last year, it never slowed down because of an unusually warm,
dry winter, low interest rates and the healthy economy.
</P>
<P>
   Manufacturers say they are producing as much as they can.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're running every single plant, three shifts a day, seven
days a week,'' said Weisbruch of National Gypsum.
</P>
<P>
   He said every gypsum manufacturer, including his, is building
new plants. But most won't be open until next year, providing
little immediate relief. Drywall, used to make walls and ceilings,
is made from crushed gypsum sandwiched between paper.
</P>
<P>
   In the meantime, builders are left on their own to find supply
where they can. ``Our supply problems have been minimal so far, but
we're definitely concerned,'' said Nedda Brown, vice president of
operations for Clark Wilson Homes. ``When they say they'll only
make so much, there's limited places you can go.''
</P>
<P>
   Cement hard to find
</P>
<P>
   Although the supply of drywall and insulation has reached a
crisis level during the past eight months, cement has been in short
supply for more than a year.
</P>
<P>
   Since early 1997, the cement industry has been operating at
capacity. While the demand for cement last year was 96.5 million
tons, U.S. capacity was 81 million tons, according to the Portland
Cement Association.
</P>
<P>
   Cement consumption in Texas reached its highest level in 13
years last year, driven by a strong housing market and big public
works projects.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's still very tight,'' said Bill Toal, chief economist at
the cement association.
</P>
<P>
   A temporary solution for companies has been to import cement. In
the long term, cement companies have over 30 expansion projects
across the United States. Texas companies, including Capital
Aggregate, Holnam Inc. and Texas Industries, are increasing
capacity by expanding or adding new plants.
</P>
<P>
   ``It just takes time,'' Toal said.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
