<HEADER>
A4563 &Cx1f; tad-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-RAILROAD-AGENCY-MERGE     01-08 0693
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-RAILROAD-AGENCY-MERGER09-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Legislator considers merging utility, railroad commissions
 &HT;    By Bruce Hight
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   AUSTIN, Texas _ Another legislator will take another run at
merging the Public Utility Commission into the Texas Railroad
Commission, creating one agency to regulate the state's electric,
natural gas and local telephone utilities, as well as the oil
production industry.
</P>
<P>
   Rep. Bill Siebert (R-San Antonio) hopes he'll have more luck
than did state Sen. David Cain (D-Dallas), who didn't get far in
the last legislative session with the same proposal.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm not taking anything away from the commissioners at the
PUC,'' said Siebert, who plans to file a bill that could merge the
commissions soon. ``They're very intelligent, they're very
motivated people. But we are at that time when deregulation is upon
us and we need to be considering down-sizing that agency.''
</P>
<P>
   Siebert will have a tough time.
</P>
<P>
   Gov. George W. Bush ``does not support the idea of merging the
Public Utility Commission into the Railroad Commission,'' said
spokeswoman Karen Hughes. She said he did not elaborate.
</P>
<P>
   Siebert said an elected agency like the railroad commission is
more responsive to the people. And a merged agency would be more
administratively efficient and could better deal with changes
within the electric and natural gas industries, he said.
</P>
<P>
   Siebert, whose hometown is the corporate headquarters for one of
the nation's largest telephone companies, also said that he had
been disappointed that the PUC has been slow to deregulate
telecommunications in Texas.
</P>
<P>
   Southwestern Bell Telephone Co., whose political action
committee has given Siebert at least $3,000 in campaign
contributions since the last legislative session, has been
frustrated by the PUC's refusal so far to let it into the
long-distance business. The commission has said that the company
has not yet done enough to open its own network to local
competition.
</P>
<P>
   Siebert said any suggestion that he was acting on behalf of
Southwestern Bell was ``totally untrue.''
</P>
<P>
   Glenn Smith, a spokesman for Southwestern Bell, said the company
had no position on the bill and had not asked for it.
</P>
<P>
   Merging the agencies has gotten some support previously from
others. Cain plans to introduce similar legislation again, said his
legislative aide, Kristie Flippo Niemeyer. Cain's bill in 1997
cleared the Senate State Affairs Committee, but the senator never
brought up it up for a Senate vote because he appeared to lack
support, Niemeyer said.
</P>
<P>
   Charles Matthews, a member of the Railroad Commission who first
suggested a merger in 1996, said he still supports the idea.
</P>
<P>
   The state's two biggest electric utility holding companies,
Texas Utilities Inc. of Dallas and Houston Industries Inc., also
own the state's two biggest natural gas utilities, Matthews noted.
And Texas Utilities also has bought a local phone provider, the
Lufkin Conroe Communications Co.
</P>
<P>
   But the electric utility industry thinks it ``can probably
function best with the (regulatory) situation as it is,'' said John
Fainter, president of the Association of Electric Companies of
Texas.
</P>
<P>
   Under the state constitution, the three members of the Railroad
Commission are elected to six-year terms. Although its principal
function when it was founded more than a century ago was to
regulate the state's railroad industry, it evolved in the 20th
century into the state's primary agency for regulating the
production of oil and natural gas. The agency has a budget of about
$58 million and 850 employees.
</P>
<P>
   The smaller PUC, created by the Legislature in 1975, regulates
the state's electric and telephone utilities. It too is run by
three commissioners, but they are appointed by the governor,
subject to confirmation by the Texas Senate. (Currently, however,
only two commission seats are occupied.) The agency has a budget of
$12.3 million and about 240 employees.
</P>
<P>
   Neither Chairman Pat Wood or Commissioner Judy Walsh of the PUC
were available for comment Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
