<SLUG> BC-BIG-BROTHER09-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    COMMENTARY: Who's afraid of big brother
 &HT;    By Gregory Kallenberg
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   AUSTIN, Texas _ The quote struck fear in the hearts of humanity
when George Orwell introduced it in 1949 in his ground-quaking tome
``1984.'' It meant we were being watched, our every move
scrutinized by a large, sinister, omniscient entity. Big Brother, a
judge-and-jury-like government institution, was monitoring,
charting and tracking. It was a frightening thought that made us
all look around more than once in our lives and ask, Why me? Why is
Big Brother watching me?
</P>
<P>
   Then came the actual 1984. The year was introduced to us with a
commercial. In 60 seconds, Apple Computer's ``1984,'' which ran
during the year's Super Bowl, showed us our greatest fears and, at
the same time, gave us hope. The future was to be a gray world
where clean-shaven heads prevailed and an anonymous, raspy-voiced,
Big Brother filled us with totalitarian ideals from a big, glowing,
screen. But then, out of the dusty halls, came a blond woman in red
running shorts, hurling a sledgehammer and launching a subsequent
rebellion. ``You'll see why 1984 won't be like `1984,' '' a
reassuring voice said at the end of the ad.
</P>
<P>
   The year sparked our rebellion. We looked around and saw we were
being watched everywhere we went, from every angle, and it
disgusted us. We were outraged to see the tiny cameras as we
banked, or the swiveling lens as we bought our Slurpees at 7-11.
This would not do, we told ourselves, so we shook our fists to the
heavens and cried, ``Just who does this Big Brother think he is?''
</P>
<P>
   But then we got used to it, complacent. Those still whining
about the loss of privacy and the omnipresence of surveillance
cameras were written off as the lunatic fringe. Being watched made
us feel more secure. Big Brother no longer was perceived as being
there to hurt; he was there to help.
</P>
<P>
   Technology got smaller, and cameras got as convenient to carry
as an oversized wallet. The cameras, now our friends, became our
obsession. They saw everything. Our lives were no longer private,
no intimate moments. We plugged our trips, trials and tribulations
into our televisions and made our friends watch them over Martha
Stewart-inspired dinners and home-brewed beers.
</P>
<P>
   We soon found ourselves happy to live inside the camera and,
when necessary, to play the part of Big Brother when it came to
recording others. To be on tape validated us; to tape others gave
us power. We watched as this new, innocuous, voyeurism leaked into
the mainstream. Bob Saget and his benchmark ``America's Funniest
Home Videos'' made us chortle as kids fell into toilets, and grooms
passed out at altars.
</P>
<P>
   Now we've turned it up a notch. It's not enough to see people's
foibles; we are demanding more. We want to see people's
inadequacies. We want to see others' mistakes. People in terror,
people on the run, people in trouble. Now we plan our evenings
around ``reality shows.'' We tune into ``Cops'' to see police
embarrass drunkards and rough up wife beaters. We watch the Fox
network to see real people attacked by real animals or to view a
``wild and woolly'' car chase that we watch while ``this crackhead
criminal crushes cars!''
</P>
<P>
   We even began utilizing other means of communications to show
ourselves to the world. The Internet, with its tiny CUCMe cameras,
provided a way for us to turn the camera on ourselves and let
anyone interested see us sleep, eat and love: 24-seven of
self-imposed surveillance.
</P>
<P>
   As time passes, there are few things we can't see or find out
about our neighbor, very little information we can't acquire. From
the Internet to the television set and the home video camera, there
is nowhere to hide. Which leads us to reassess exactly whom Big
Brother is and whom, exactly, he is watching anymore.
</P>
<P>
   And then, in an Orwellian irony, you realize it. The very entity
you're afraid of, the one you've fought so long against _ Big
Brother _ is someone you know and live with. He is as familiar as
family but as distant as the talking face on the glowing screen.
Because we all have seen Big Brother, and, ironically, it is us.
</P>
<P>
   Send questions, comments, ideas, products, graft and fan mail to
Gregory Kallenberg at gkallenbergstatesman.com or write him at P.O.
Box 670, Austin, TX, 78767.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
