<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    COMMENTARY: How to build a $120 chair for $400
 &HT;    By Gary Borders
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   NACOGDOCHES, Texas _ I spent my Christmas vacation trying not to
cut off my fingers, taking a late-night trip to the emergency room
to get a mote out of my eye, and inhaling massive amounts of
sawdust. It was great.
</P>
<P>
   Santa brought several power tools with which I can risk my
precious digits. I have built nothing of note to date, just some
shelves in the workshop and the World's Most Expensive Cassette
Tape Cabinet, discussed in an earlier column. It now sits proudly
in my study. Total cost, including lumber, tools purchased, and the
aforementioned trip to the emergency room: about $300. That comes
out to about $3.15 per tape. Oh, well. It's cheaper than therapy.
</P>
<P>
   I've discovered since embarking on this new hobby that
woodworking is a common avocation among newspaper editors. One
colleague's theory is that it
</P>
<P>
   allows editors _ who by nature of their job spend much of their
time getting
</P>
<P>
   yelled at by people _ to take out their frustrations on
inanimate objects. The same theory explains why so many of us
green-visored wretches play golf, I suppose. I have the same level
of mediocrity at both pastimes, and the fact that I've
enthusiastically if ineptly taken to both says something about me,
I guess. Mainly that I get yelled at a lot. Lucky I have a thick
skin.
</P>
<P>
   It's too wet and cold to play much golf, and besides it gets
dark early these days, so here I am several nights a week, out in
my shop still trying to unlock the mysteries of the router,
checking out woodworking books by the armload from the library,
flipping through catalogs of power tools and woodworking supplies.
I am slowly learning enough to realize how little I know about all
this stuff.
</P>
<P>
   The most valuable lesson I've learned so far: wear goggles.
While putzing around with the router one night a few weeks ago, I
managed to lodge a piece of wood in my eye that refused to come
out. Since I wear glasses, I haven't worried about goggles. Dumb. I
used a whole bottle of eyedrops, took a shower, stuck my head under
a faucet and muttered many imprecations before breaking down and
driving myself to the emergency room, one hand on the steering
wheel and the other clasped over the injured eye.
</P>
<P>
   The nurse clucked, and the doctor shook his head. Everybody was
very friendly and helpful. A gallon of eyewash, some deadening
solution and a Q-tip later, I was good as new, save for a few minor
scratches on my cornea and a blurry eye that didn't clear up for a
few days. I got a bill for $140, which I richly deserved for being
so dumb. I bought goggles the next day. They cost $3.99.
</P>
<P>
   Building furniture is a major step beyond restoring existing
pieces, which I've done for years. Unless one has to replace parts
that have been damaged beyond repair, restoring furniture mainly
involves lots of elbow grease and a willingness to sniff solvents
and sawdust for hours on end. Learning how to build something, even
from a plan, is a whole new ballgame to someone with as little
aptitude as I have. My major project now is an Adirondack chair,
which is a high-backed, wide-planked outside chair. I saw a nice
one in a local building supply store on sale for $119.95. I figure
I can build one for, oh, maybe $400, by the time I tally up wasted
lumber and purchase of tools I need. This doesn't count labor and
future possible emergency medical care, which could send the price
into the Chippendale strata.
</P>
<P>
   I spend hours staring dumbly at the chair's plans and
instructions, trying to figure out what all these exotic terms
mean: dado, mortise and tenon, dovetail and Roman ogee. First time
I saw the latter, which is a type of router bit, I thought it said
Roman orgy. That seemed like a strange name for a bit.
</P>
<P>
   Now I know differently, but it's a slow process. It took an
entire day to build five back slats for the chair, and part of
another day to stand back and contemplate my handiwork and figure
out what to do next.
</P>
<P>
   The Adirondack chair made it necessary to buy a bandsaw, which
is a very cool tool that allows you to cut out curved patterns. I
could make those charmingly goofy Christmas cutouts of Santa and
his elves if I had a mind to with a bandsaw, but we already own a
set so there's no need. The bandsaw is disarmingly quiet, unlike my
table saw which screams out at you to be careful less you leave a
finger lying on the concrete. The bandsaw whispers its warning, in
a seductive hiss like a snake. Have no doubt. It will whack off an
errant protuberance in a heartbeat.
</P>
<P>
   In between building, I sit in my blue recliner and flip through
tool catalogs. This is getting expensive. But at least I'm not
spending time on a couch talking about my childhood traumas. As if
I could remember them.
</P>
<P>
   Gary Borders is editor and publisher of The Nacogdoches Daily
Sentinel. His
</P>
<P>
   e-mail address is gborders(at)coxnews.com.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
