<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-LATHAM-COLUMN09-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    It's time to outlaw the practice of beating our kids in school
 &HT;    By Phil Latham
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   MARSHALL, Texas _ It probably will surprise no one to hear that
I got whacked a lot in school.
</P>
<P>
   Back in the '60s, sound educational policy included teachers
whacking students. Every male teacher I was assigned had a paddle
hanging on his wall and some had more, allowing them to choose the
instrument of pain.
</P>
<P>
   Some of the teachers were from the old school and had paddles
made of oak or some other hard _ very hard _ wood. Those who were
with the times had switched to the high-tech models, sleek
fiberglass babies that allowed for a faster swing with less effort.
</P>
<P>
   The fiberglass models were especially popular with coaches _
they would have been the same guys who first tried out graphite
golf clubs _ who found it necessary to administer multiple
paddlings in one day. More pain, less effort.
</P>
<P>
   I deserved every single last one of those paddlings and I
probably deserved many more.
</P>
<P>
   But if I were to tell you the sum total of what I learned
getting hit on the butt all those times from seventh grade forward
it would be this: Nothing.
</P>
<P>
   Not one thing. Well, that isn't exactly true. I learned that
paddling is a useless form of school punishment.
</P>
<P>
   I believed that as a student getting whacked and I believe it
now as a parent of four children whom I had occasion to spank in
their younger years. But that was me paddling them, not a
near-stranger. There is a big difference.
</P>
<P>
   In my experience as a student, whacking did no good because the
student never had a way of knowing what would get you whacked. One
day it might be arriving after the tardy bell. The next day the
same teacher would say nothing. One day it might be because you
were caught holding hands in the hallway. The next day the same
teacher would say nothing. One day you might be able to tell a joke
in one class where the teacher laughed and get whacked for telling
exactly the same joke in the very next class.
</P>
<P>
   Each of those things happened to me.
</P>
<P>
   So it became clear as a student that you got whacked just
whenever someone
</P>
<P>
   felt like whacking you. You learned to just get through it
because, if a teacher wanted to paddle you they had to get it out
of their system. Unfortunately, I gave my teachers plenty of
reasons to cleanse their systems.
</P>
<P>
   Still, after a while, my bottom pretty well got accustomed to
the hitting, I was probably near having calluses. Wood hurt less
than fiberglass, but I could endure any of it.
</P>
<P>
   Well, almost any of it.
</P>
<P>
   One day I ran cross-wise with a coach. I don't remember what I
did, though I'm sure it was something pretty terrible. I know it
was bad enough to make him angry. I could hear it in his voice and
see it in his eyes.
</P>
<P>
   He told me to assume the position and get ready for three
``pops,'' as he called them.
</P>
<P>
   The first whack was almost always the worst. No matter how well
you prepared, your butt just never was quite ready for the sting.
The second whack, as usual, was much easier to bear. The nerves in
the butt weren't feeling all the pain.
</P>
<P>
   Typically, the third whack was the easiest of all to take.
Typically.
</P>
<P>
   But in this case, the third swing of that fiberglass paddle
landed squarely on my legs. I was 17 years old and not a weakling,
but it almost took my breath away.
</P>
<P>
   As I turned around to look at him the pain must have been
obvious on my face.
</P>
<P>
   ``Oops,'' he said. ``I missed.''
</P>
<P>
   For the next week I was in excruciating pain as my legs turned,
blue, then purple, then yellow. I have no doubt he hit me on
purpose. It wasn't exactly a lasting injury, but it didn't change
my attitude, either. If anything, I was a worse student for that
coach.
</P>
<P>
   Of course, I never told my parents for fear they would punish me
even more.
</P>
<P>
   When you go to parenting classes, they'll tell you that the best
way to avoid physical child abuse, even the accidental kind, is to
never hit your child in anger. Punish them properly when you are in
a rational state of mind.
</P>
<P>
   Furthermore, if you do hit you child in anger and leave bruises
across his legs, you can expect your child's teacher to make a call
to Child Protective Services. They are, in fact, required by law to
do so.
</P>
<P>
   But Texas hasn't outlawed angry school administrators from
putting bruises on children in the name of education and it is high
time we did so.
</P>
<P>
   This isn't about discipline at all. It is about hitting children
on a whim and it just isn't right.
</P>
<P>
   Latham is editor and publisher of the Marshall (TX) News
Messenger. He can
</P>
<P>
   be reached by e-mail at platham(at)coxnews.com.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
