<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MCCARTY-COLUMN09-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    By Mary McCarty
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   DAYTON, Ohio _ As long as Mona Lisa smiled, serene, undisturbed,
Bill Daniels took heart. It was a symbol: Doing business in the
city could work, despite the hassles. Artist Rick Van Horn
airbrushed the Mona Lisa in a four-hour burst of inspiration, and
there she reposes, on the storefront side of the Pizza Factory on
Salem Avenue, a beacon of neighborhood pride and stability. Much
like Daniels himself, come to think of it, who has tirelessly
supported neighborhood events during the 12 years he has been in
business.
</P>
<P>
   Recently, though, more mustaches have popped up on the Mona
Lisa, more vandalism disturbed her serene surface. That seemed a
bad sign to Daniels, because for years, ``nobody vandalized it,
nobody painted over it, and we thought, `Maybe we're getting a
little bit of respect.' ''
</P>
<P>
   The problems have been a lot worse than mustaches on the Mona
Lisa. Drivers have been held up. ``Last year a guy pointed gun at
the driver and said, `Give me the pizza,' '' Daniels said,
incredulous. ``He pulled a gun on the guy just for the pizza.''
</P>
<P>
   Another time, a teen-ager who had previously robbed a driver
called from the same phone number. When a police officer arrived,
garbed in a pizza delivery outfit, the 15-year-old pointed a weapon
at the officer that turned out to be a BB gun.
</P>
<P>
   On two occasions, a stolen car has smashed through the wooden
fence surrounding the parking lot, quashing plans for another mural
_ an outfielder on one side of the fence, a kid peeping through a
knothole on the other side.
</P>
<P>
   Daniels and a former partner opened the Salem Avenue store 12
years ago, the first in the chain that has locations on Wayne
Avenue and Patterson Road. ``We encountered crime problems from the
beginning,'' he acknowledges. ``It was one of those situations
where you either get out or dig in and try to effect positive
change.''
</P>
<P>
   But times change; priorities change. ``I'm married now, with two
babies in diapers, and my focus is shifting toward taking care of
my family,'' said Daniels, 35. ``That's not leaving me time to do
the community things I used to do. I feel I should be home with my
boys, because the absence of family is the root of the problems I
see in the neighborhood.''
</P>
<P>
   And it has gotten harder to recruit qualified, insured drivers;
they didn't feel safe. With two more stores, Daniels couldn't fill
in as a driver, as he did in the past.
</P>
<P>
   So, as of last weekend, the Salem Avenue Pizza Factory _ which
previously delivered throughout a wide area in Dayton _ will no
longer be making deliveries. Daniels is optimistic the store can
succeed as a carry-out business only.
</P>
<P>
   We learned the bad news Wednesday night, when we decided to
treat ourselves after a week of near-hibernation.
</P>
<P>
   ``Pizza Factory, no deliveries,'' a man answered the phone.
</P>
<P>
   Roads are bad, I figured. No, he said. Too many drivers being
robbed.
</P>
<P>
   I got off
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
