<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BARBIE09-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Combining Barbie anniversary, Women's History Month makes for
debated exhibit
 &HT;    By Mary Lou Pickel
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   DELRAY BEACH, Fla. _ Call it a not-so-harmonic convergence.
</P>
<P>
   Button-nosed pop icon and feminist whipping girl Barbie turns 40
in March, a.k.a. Women's History Month.
</P>
<P>
   To celebrate both, a local museum will festoon itself in pink
fabric and display Barbie dolls under glass amid life-size Barbie
furniture _ ``a greater Barbie experience,'' exhibit organizer Lori
J. Durante says.
</P>
<P>
   ``40 Years of the Barbie Doll'' will feature more than 80
Barbies shipped from dollmaker Mattel, including Engineer and
Veterinarian Barbie; Designer Clothes Barbie; the first
African-American Barbie, from 1980 and a large batch of
international Barbies, including Thai Barbie, Nigerian Barbie and
Arctic Barbie.
</P>
<P>
   The exhibit, to run from March 18 through June 6 at Old School
Square's Cornell Museum, has won praise from local politicos. In
letters of support, Mayor Jay Alperin called Barbie a positive
career role model for young girls, and Palm Beach County
Commissioner Mary McCarty said the exhibit demonstrates women's
advancement and contributions to society.
</P>
<P>
   Alperin, a dentist, even gave ``Dentist Barbie'' to his dental
associate as a holiday gift, he noted.
</P>
<P>
   But not everybody is ready to transform the Cornell into
Barbie's Dream House: National Association for Women member and
Delray Beach resident Rosalind Murray says Barbie is not the first
figure that comes to mind when she thinks of exceptional women in
history.
</P>
<P>
   ``Of all the things,'' Murray said.
</P>
<P>
   ``Having Betsy Ross's flag is more historical and more important
to me,'' she said. ``Or an exhibit on women astronauts, or of black
women in the arts.''
</P>
<P>
   In fact, the museum usually displays a poster-board exhibit on
black women's achievements through the ages in February or March to
celebrate Black History Month or Women's History Month, museum
director Gloria Adams said.
</P>
<P>
   The exhibit, which the museum bought from the Smithsonian
Institution, features photos of prominent black women in history,
from suffragette Sojourner Truth to opera diva Marian Anderson.
</P>
<P>
   But this year, because of Barbie and previously planned
photography exhibits, there probably won't be room for the
poster-board display, Adams said.
</P>
<P>
   Barbie's detractors say the problem isn't just that Barbie's a
doll, not a real-life heroine. It's her size-0 waist and legs up to
here that insidiously reinforce an unrealistic standard of female
beauty and even contribute to eating disorders like anorexia nd
bulimia.
</P>
<P>
   Durante, 27, a fashion consultant and stylist, says Barbie's
just not that complicated.
</P>
<P>
   ``People develop insecurities about themselves long before and
after Barbie,'' she said. ``Yes, maybe she does have a body that's
incredible, but to me, it was clay, and I could mold Barbie into my
dreams and into whatever I wanted to be.''
</P>
<P>
   Undaunted, Durante is still looking for vintage Barbies from
1959 to 1981. Old School Square is ``Calling All Barbies,'' asking
private collectors to loan their Barbies to the show. In exchange,
donors' names will be included in the exhibit.
</P>
<P>
   So far, no one has come forward.
</P>
<P>
   But there's likely plenty of Barbies stuck in closets and under
beds: Since Barbie's 1959 debut, Mattel has sold more than 1
billion of the dolls and her pals.
</P>
<P>
   And Barbie has climbed several career ladders, seamlessly
switching from nurse to doctor to astronaut, gymnast,
paleontologist, NASCAR driver and boutique owner, to name a few.
</P>
<P>
   It's that level of career success, combined with her beauty and
glamour that make Barbie particularly appealing to girls from
lower-income families, said Professor Mary Rogers of the University
of West Florida, whose book, ``Barbie Culture,'' is due out this
month.
</P>
<P>
   For those girls, Barbie has everything, Rogers said _ the dream
house, sports cars, campers and more. She's traveled everywhere and
done everything.
</P>
<P>
   ``She's not an oppressed woman, lugging three kids and two
diaper bags around,'' Rogers said. ``Barbie says, `Hey look, I'm
having fun _ I can be an astronaut or a school teacher','' Rogers
said.
</P>
<P>
   In fact, Barbie is the ultimate consumer.
</P>
<P>
   ``If we wanted to blame Barbie for anything, it's that she's ...
an icon of `Shop til you drop, get as much as you can.' ''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
