<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    COMMENTARY: A poignant open letter about my thrills-a -minute
year
 &HT;    By Jim Minter
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   FAYETTE COUNTY, Ga. _
</P>
<P>
   Dear Friends:
</P>
<P>
   It has come to my attention that those of us too lazy and/or too
cheap to address Christmas cards can make amends by sending a
newsletter to those of you who are breathlessly awaiting to hear
all the interesting things that happened to the Minter family in
1998.
</P>
<P>
   On the whole it was a pretty good year, if you don't count the
fungus that hit the tomatoes and English peas that rolled over and
died before they filled out.
</P>
<P>
   Once again all of our children are doing wonderfully and will
soon get fantastic raises and promotions if they don't decide to
enroll in Harvard and Yale for their Ph.D.s or some other
prestigious degrees that will keep them ahead of any of your
children.
</P>
<P>
   We continue to be amazed by our granddaughter. She gets
prettier, smarter and more adorable every year. She feels really
bad about having so little time for her grandfather now that she's
captain of the cheerleaders, singing in the church choir, doing a
lot of stuff at school and hiring out to baby-sit. Her dad and I
are so happy that although she'll be 14 next month she has no
interest in silly boys who call on the telephone.
</P>
<P>
   Sometime around the Fourth of July another cat took up with us.
This one is yellow with mean eyes and fights with the one that took
up with us several years ago. They fight all the time. So far
neither one has been able to make the other leave the premises so
we have asked our neighbor, Stan Thain, not to shoot any more of
the coyotes who live behind our house and prey on household pets.
</P>
<P>
   Last spring, in what was not a unanimous decision, we enrolled
in a line-dancing class. For those of you not familiar with line
dancing, it is an offshoot of the old daily dozen routine used by
the Army to condition recruits in World War II. There is very
little bodily contact but there is a lot of sweat. After several
pulled muscles and a knee injury that may require major surgery, I
got myself excused from line-dancing class a few days before I
would have been forced to file for divorce.
</P>
<P>
   Despite my reservations about venturing beyond Woolsey and Harps
Crossing, Mrs. Marco Polo again conducted an extensive tour of
foreign lands, visiting Rome (Italy) in the spring and Paris
(France) and environs in the fall, which generated enough frequent
flier points for both of us to visit Australia, New Zealand, Fiji
and perhaps Tibet and Sri Lanka in 1999, unless I can come down
with some sort of disease she can't get past immigration
authorities.
</P>
<P>
   We also toured the Northwestern United States and great chunks
of Canada with Alex and Judy Moye in their Nimitz-class motor home.
I can't say for sure, but I think Alex may be planning to enter the
1999 Daytona 500 if he can get the motor coach past NASCAR
inspectors.
</P>
<P>
   The big event in our neck of the woods was the second annual
Inman Farm Heritage Days celebration put on by our semi-farmer son
and his semi-farmer wife with help from a cast of hundreds. The
good news is the weekend drew an estimated 10,000 visitors, up from
6,000 a year ago. The bad news is the semi-farmer son was
discovered to have in his possession upward of 40 old tractors,
including some that actually have a motor and all their wheels and
actually run. Although we hate to brag, we are proud to report he
is in discussions with Time Warner and several other television
studios about a remake of ''Sanford and Son'' to be shot on
location.
</P>
<P>
   Possibly because of an attack of temporary insanity, I ignored
God's admonition about squandering paper made from pine trees and
wrote a book, the title of which cannot be mentioned here because
if I put it in, the newspaper's editors would take it out and tell
me to buy an ad.
</P>
<P>
   Some of you may have heard that my Christmas gift was a set of
super-duper computerized hearing aids, one for each ear. The
audiologist assured me my slight hearing loss was from being in the
Army and hearing a lot of guns being shot, and not from old age.
Hearing aids are wonderful. Although I still have trouble carrying
on a conversation with people in the same room with me, I can hear
the first raindrops falling in Carrollton whenever a front moves in
from Alabama.
</P>
<P>
   Jim Minter is a former editor in chief of The Atlanta
Journal-Constitution.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
