<SLUG> BC-NETHAWAY-COLUMN09-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    COMMENTARY: Remember the Alamo, factually
 &HT;    By Rowland Nethaway
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WACO, Texas _ The winners get to write the history. That's
natural.
</P>
<P>
   It's hard to imagine how history books today would read if
Hitler, Mussolini and Hirohito had conquered the world.
</P>
<P>
   There certainly wouldn't be a Holocaust museum or stories about
Japan's sneak attack on Pearl Harbor.
</P>
<P>
   It must be galling, however, to be on the losing side of both a
war and history.
</P>
<P>
   Americans wouldn't know since we have never lost an armed
conflict.
</P>
<P>
   Vietnam was close. But there's a difference between losing and
not winning.
</P>
<P>
   The sons and daughters of the Confederacy know something about
the experience the vanquished endure at the hands of their
history-writing conquerors.
</P>
<P>
   It's equally difficult to picture how history books would read
today had the Confederacy prevailed in the War of Northern
Aggression. Frankly, I have no quarrel with the outcome of that war
even though my relatives fought on the losing side.
</P>
<P>
   As a native Texan, I've been distressed by the way some people
are attempting to rewrite the history of the Alamo.
</P>
<P>
   For Texans, the Alamo is more than a historical building. For
Texans, the Alamo is sacred symbol of freedom, independence and
courage. It is a shrine.
</P>
<P>
   ``Be quiet and take off your hat, son,'' my grandfather
instructed me on my first visit to the Alamo. ``A lot of brave men
died here.''
</P>
<P>
   Technically, the 187 Texans who defended the Alamo against Gen.
Antonio Lopez de Santa Anna's 5,000 Mexican troops were not the
winners. The flag they flew over the Alamo now is under lock and
key in Mexico City.
</P>
<P>
   But the bravery of these men in the face of overwhelming odds,
and their willingness to sacrifice themselves for freedom, made
them more than winners of a single battle. It made them legends.
</P>
<P>
   By fighting off Santa Anna's assault for 13 days, they bought
time for Gen. Sam Houston to gather his forces. ``Remember the
Alamo'' became a battle cry used by Houston's forces as they
vanquished Santa Anna's army at San Jacinto, thereby giving birth
to a new nation _ the Republic of Texas.
</P>
<P>
   Mexican historians have a slightly different view of the events
at the Alamo. They question whether Santa Anna, Mexico's dictator,
really had 5,000 men under arms during the 13-day siege and whether
all Alamo defenders died in battle.
</P>
<P>
   An eyewitness account written by Lt. Col. Jose Enrique de la
Pena defies the popular legend that frontier hero Davy Crockett
died with his ``Tennessee boys'' while wielding his long-rifle,
Betsy, before he was finally felled near the doors of the Alamo's
chapel.
</P>
<P>
   The diary of the Mexican officer, recently donated to the
University of Texas, reports that Crockett was captured when the
Mexicans finally overwhelmed the mission and executed later that
day, March 6, 1836.
</P>
<P>
   Technically, the defenders of the Alamo were not fighting for
Texas independence. They were fighting as part of a struggle to
re-establish Mexico's 1824 Constitution that had been repudiated by
Santa Anna. They flew a red-white-and-green Mexican flag over the
Alamo with ``1824'' on it.
</P>
<P>
   After the Alamo battle, the struggle shifted to one of Texas
independence.
</P>
<P>
   Hispanics fought and died alongside Anglo defenders of the Alamo
and later in the struggle for Texas independence.
</P>
<P>
   The keepers of the Alamo, the Daughters of the Republic of
Texas, have the right attitude. Whatever is factual is fine. The
Alamo will always be an inspiration for Texans and freedom-loving
people worldwide.
</P>
<P>
   Rowland Nethaway is senior editor of the Waco (Texas)
Tribune-Herald. E-mail: RNethaol.com.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
