<SLUG> BC-RESOLUTIONS09-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    I will not make fun, I will not be rude. Busy or not, this year
I will be civil
 &HT;    By Loretta Grantham
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WEST PALM BEACH, Fla. _ As we enter this, the final year of the
20th century, let us vow to take the higher road, to grasp the
greater good ...
</P>
<P>
   To not be such jerks.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's not that people today mean to be less considerate than
they were decades ago,'' says Peggy Post,
great-granddaughter-in-law of manners maven Emily Post and author
of the most recent edition of ``Etiquette.'' ``We're just busier
and more crowded and less likely to think about it.''
</P>
<P>
   Far be it from us to cram decorum down your throat (that would
be rude). But please, may we at least offer some reminders to
gently steer you on the path to civility?
</P>
<P>
   Thank you so much.
</P>
<P>
   I WILL NOT ... 1. Check my voice mail on speaker phone. 2. Swipe
newspapers from my condo lobby. 3. Secretly alter the thermostat
after my spouse and I agree on a setting. 4. Act like a famine's
approaching while at all-you-can-eat buffets. 5. Discuss my most
recent surgery at cocktail parties. 6. Make fun of Barry Manilow
fans. (Ditto John Denver.) 7. Leave fast-food debris in my
co-worker's car after he drives to lunch. 8. Leap to the front of
the line when another cash register opens. 9. Jangle the change in
my pocket. 10. Razz fans of the losing team (OK, maybe not much).
</P>
<P>
   I WILL ... 1. Say thank you even when I can't see the
drive-through teller. 2. Let folks with a handful of items go ahead
of me when I have a tractor-trailer of groceries. 3. Leave a decent
amount of milk in the carton. 4. Ignore call-waiting unless I have
a sick mother or a kid who needs to be picked up. 5. Listen to a
colleague's idea without rolling my eyes. 6. Wear less perfume. 7.
Turn off my cell phone during movies, church services, PTA meetings
and so forth unless I'm a doctor awaiting news on an organ for
transplant. 8. Mail birthday cards on time. 9. Retain my sense of
compassion (and humor), especially when elderly drivers meander in
the fast lane. 10. Do unto others as I'd have them do unto me
(cynicism not included).
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
