<HEADER>
A4580 &Cx1f; tad-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-MARS-VENUS-GAME09-COX     01-08 0931
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MARS-VENUS-GAME09-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Longest we've gone without sex? None of your business, Dr. Gray
 &HT;    By Frank Cerabino
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WEST PALM BEACH, Fla. _ Let's take a quick look around John
Gray's solar system.
</P>
<P>
   You've got your ``Men are from Mars, Women are from Venus'' book
that started it all, spawning such sequels as Mars and Venus on a
date ... in the bedroom ... starting over ... together forever ...
and of course, the runaway bestseller, Mars and Venus Fixing a Flat
Tire.
</P>
<P>
   Uh, that was a joke. About the flat tire. The other ones are
real, though. And there seems to be no end to pop psychologist
Gray's ability to repackage his relationship shtick. You've got
your six-pack video series based on his books, the interactive
Mars-Venus workshops and even places called Mars &AMP; Venus Counseling
Centers.
</P>
<P>
   So, I guess it was just a matter of time before we'd get the
board game version of his Mars-Venus meal ticket.
</P>
<P>
   ``This game is an entertaining, illuminating way to find out
what you know about the differences between men and women _ or what
you thought you knew,'' the game instructions say.
</P>
<P>
   Before I go any further, I think it's fair to disclose that
while I started reading Gray's seminal tome several years ago, I
never got all the way through it _ although it did remain on top of
the toilet tank for a solid year.
</P>
<P>
   Anyway, back to the game, which I decided to play because (a)
I've been married for 18 years and (b) The Palm Beach Post agreed
to pay for a babysitter and truth serum (beer) if I could round up
some other married couples to play the game with my wife and me.
</P>
<P>
   So, on a recent Saturday night, after a requisite dose of truth
serum, we sat down with four friends to play the game.
</P>
<P>
   Men play from the red cards. Women get the green. Both teams
start on their respective planets and try to make it to planet
Earth first.
</P>
<P>
   The goal is to guess how the players who take turns reading
multiple-choice questions from a deck of cards would honestly
answer the questions themselves.
</P>
<P>
   The women sat on one side of the table, facing the men. Women go
first, pulling one of the green cards from the deck.
</P>
<P>
   There are some questions in the deck that require more truth
serum than others.
</P>
<P>
   ``The longest time I've gone without sex is (a) several weeks
(b) several months (c) more than several months,'' one question
reads.
</P>
<P>
   If you're too embarrassed to answer questions, you can go into
your ``well'' if you're a woman, or your ``cave'' if you're a man.
(If you want to know why women don't go in caves and men don't go
in wells, it's explained in the directions.)
</P>
<P>
   But what often happens with the game is that somebody picks up a
card, goes to read the question on it, shakes his or her head and
mutters, ``No,'' then reaches for another card.
</P>
<P>
   The problem is that the choices on many cards are either too
obvious, too irrelevant. Or, they require more honesty than seems
necessary among friends, who don't really need to know or probably
don't want to know your preferences on cuddling after lovemaking.
Or what body part you prefer to have rubbed.
</P>
<P>
   As we played the game, I couldn't help thinking that this game
would be more valuable among people who just began dating, rather
than married couples together for years.
</P>
<P>
   For example, a man would be better off hearing a woman answer
the question ``I am most likely to make love (a) in a car, (b) on a
train, (c) at the park'' in the beginning of their relationship,
rather than later on, say, after squandering dozens of uneventful
train trips.
</P>
<P>
   Or how about this one:
</P>
<P>
   ``My partner earns the most points for being (a) practical (b)
punctual (c) sensual.''
</P>
<P>
   It would be nice knowing that up front, to judge whether you
want to keep dating somebody who's unduly fixated with you being on
time.
</P>
<P>
   The questions fall in different categories: communication,
family, dating, ``gender benders,'' ones that ask how the opposite
sex can score more points with you, and ``island fantasy''
questions, as in ``I would love it most if I could change my (a)
wardrobe (b) body (c) job.''
</P>
<P>
   Which brings up another problem with the game. There you are
sitting across the table from a woman friend _ not your wife, mind
you _ just a friend. And you have to decide whether she's most
unhappy with her body, her job, or her clothes.
</P>
<P>
   Is this a question you really want to answer? If you chose a
response that agrees with her evaluation, she will think that her
deficiency must be obvious to others. If you pick something else,
she'll wonder why you would find fault with some aspect of her life
that doesn't bother her.
</P>
<P>
   Any way you slice it, you're a loser.
</P>
<P>
   So what happened, as we played the game, is that everyone would
wait and see how the spouse of the question-reader voted. The safe
thing would be to just say what the spouse said.
</P>
<P>
   But then the game wasn't as fun. So we instituted a
spouse-votes-last rule, which brought on another round of truth
serum.
</P>
<P>
   Eventually, we just suspended moving the little tokens. Instead,
we just pulled cards until we found one that was intriguing, yet
not too grotesquely personal, to ask.
</P>
<P>
   Like the question that says, ``If all my fantasies were
fulfilled, I'd be (a) admired (b) despised (c) imprisoned.''
</P>
<P>
   Well, come to think of it, that might not be a great question.
</P>
<P>
   Let's pick another one.
</P>
<P>
   Hmm. No, not that one either.
</P>
<P>
   How about another one?
</P>
<P>
   More truth serum, anyone?
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
