<DOCNO> NYT19990108.0083 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-01-08 11:02 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4581 &Cx1f; tad-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-RATHER-60MINUTES09-CO     01-08 1103
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-RATHER-60MINUTES09-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Rather rides again
 &HT;    EDs: Embargoed for Jan. 10
 &HT;    By Diane Holloway
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   AUSTIN, Texas _ Noted news hound Dan Rather likes nothing more
than donning a slicker, grabbing a microphone and rushing
head-first into a hurricane. He's about to perform a similar, if
drier and slightly less dangerous, feat this week.
</P>
<P>
   Starting Wednesday at 8 p.m., he'll anchor ``60 Minutes II,'' a
spinoff of the program that launched the newsmagazine genre three
decades ago and has been unsurpassed in quality and popularity ever
since. Rather, 67, will add the new anchoring duties to his already
busy job anchoring ``The CBS Evening News'' and another
newsmagazine, ``48 Hours.'' Even for the James Brown of news
anchors, it's a mighty load.
</P>
<P>
   ``I had an hour to fill on my work schedule and along came `60
Minutes.' Fit right in,'' Rather said with a chuckle in a phone
interview. ``Seriously, you find time for the things you love to
do, and I love the news and I love reporting. This is an
opportunity I couldn't pass up.''
</P>
<P>
   But won't this cut into his fishing time? Rather and his wife,
Jean, both native Texans, have a house on Lake Travis and enjoy
relaxing there when they can escape from New York. They just ended
a two-week respite in the Hill Country.
</P>
<P>
   ``Oh, believe me, fishing is not at risk,'' Rather said. ``I
actually caught some bass this last time. ... Mostly I catch
suicidal fish, though.''
</P>
<P>
   Rather insists he's got time for everything and plans to cut
back on nothing. They don't call him Gunga Dan for nothing. And
adding a duty that could afford him the luxury of in-depth
reporting _ Rather's first love _ probably seems like a worthwhile
squeeze.
</P>
<P>
   While critics sneer at exploding pickups on ``Dateline NBC'' and
celebrity puff pieces on ``20/20,'' the landmark news show has been
treated with near-reverence. It's been a mainstay on Sunday nights
and has a sterling reputation for memorable reports from veterans
like Mike Wallace, Morley Safer, Ed Bradley and, from 1975-81,
Rather, before he inherited the ``Evening News'' anchor chair from
Walter Cronkite.
</P>
<P>
   Trying to copy the best is a noble but challenging goal. Even
Don Hewitt, executive producer of the original ``60 Minutes,'' has
lamented the proliferation of newsmagazines and initially objected
to the cloning of his program. ``60 Minutes'' is a huge success,
some say a one-of-a-kind. Why try to copy it?
</P>
<P>
   ``Because it is the best,'' said Rather. ``We want to make this
broadcast as close to `60 Minutes' as we can. If we're going to do
another newsmagazine, we ought to do what works, and `60 Minutes'
is the best brand name among newsmagazines. It invented the form.
And I don't mean to irritate Don Hewitt, but I think we can make it
better.''
</P>
<P>
   Competitive taunts notwithstanding, Hewitt backed off his
opposition to ``60 Minutes II'' when Jeff Fager, who worked on ``60
Minutes'' and the ``Evening News,'' was brought on to produce it.
Once Fager was aboard, Rather soon followed, and Hewitt was
convinced that CBS wasn't trying to slap his sterling title onto a
tabloid sleaze.
</P>
<P>
   Hewitt even suggested one of the new show's more unusual
elements _ a full-blown weekly update of a story from the original
program, with ``60 Minutes'' reporters crossing over from the old
to the new broadcast to do them. Wallace will update one of his for
this week's premiere. The other two stories in the new show's
three-story format will be originals by anchor/reporter Rather and
correspondents Vicki Mabrey, Bob Simon and Charlie Rose.
</P>
<P>
   ``Part of my mantra is you don't have to dumb it down and sleaze
it up to attract an audience,'' Rather said.
</P>
<P>
   CBS, which currently has two newsmagazines (``48 Hours'' and
``60 Minutes''), apparently was dead-set on having another one. ABC
has three editions of ``20/20'' and is about to have a fourth
edition of ``20/20,'' and NBC has ``Dateline'' spread over five
nights. By next month, there will be a whopping 13 hours of
newsmagazines gobbling up the 22-hour prime-time schedule. Most of
them do well in the ratings and cost a fraction of the price of
dramas and sitcoms.
</P>
<P>
   But isn't there a newsmagazine saturation point? Aren't viewers
finally going to say enough is enough?
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think so,'' Rather countered adamantly. ``There's
always room for quality. If it isn't good journalism, it gets to be
clutter pretty quickly, but I don't know of anybody who argues that
TV is cluttered with too much quality journalism.''
</P>
<P>
   Both Rather and Fager are reluctant to criticize their
competitors, but they make it clear they believe they are
practicing a higher form of journalism. No exploding pickups there.
Fager, 44, who has a reputation for producing hard-hitting news,
insists CBS has committed the time and money necessary for strong
reporting. Most stories on ``60 Minutes'' take an average of two
months to report and produce. Fager expects similar thoroughness on
``60 Minutes II.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Nobody else is doing what `60 Minutes' does, and that's why I
think there's room for us with that kind of reporting,'' Fager
said. ``We won't jump on stories just because they're happening
this week. We do spend a lot of time on reporting and collecting
research. You have to be prepared for that kind of investment of
time and money.''
</P>
<P>
   But Rather says that doesn't mean ``60 Minutes II'' won't be
timely and newsworthy.
</P>
<P>
   ``We want to be timely, but we won't be prisoners of
timeliness,'' Rather said. ``If we can do something timely and meet
our standards of quality, we'll jump all over it ... We've spent
years looking into Russia's secret cities, the ones that were
designed to build atomic weapons, and very little of it has wound
up on the `Evening News.' We're going to do something on that on
our broadcast. I think people will be surprised to learn that some
of those activities are still going on. Now, that's pretty timely,
but it's not the latest celebrity or the Senate impeachment
trial.''
</P>
<P>
   And speaking of impeachment, this bulldog reporter, who
salivates at the thought of breaking news, is sick to death of the
White House scandal that has consumed the news for more than a year
now.
</P>
<P>
   ``I hate it, I really do,'' Rather said softly. ``I think
there's a misunderstanding that reporters love this story, and
that's not my experience. I love a big story, but I hate this one.
... It has far too many farcical aspects, and they tend to get
overcovered, but it is a tragedy all the way around.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
