<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-01-08 11:06 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4585 &Cx1f; tad-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CONDO-KING-BOOK09-COX     01-08 1494
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CONDO-KING-BOOK09-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    The condo king
 &HT;    EDs: Embargoed until Monday, Jan. 11
 &HT;    By Jeff Houck
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WEST PALM BEACH, Fla. _ ``Watch this.''
</P>
<P>
   Tom Madden is smirking like a cat about to eat a prize canary.
</P>
<P>
   He's walking toward ``The Gantlet,'' a narrow stretch of deck
between the turquoise swimming pool and the long line of lounge
chairs where residents sun bathe at the Dune Deck condominium in
South Palm Beach. Madden, the condo association's president,
usually takes the long way around the pool during the day because
disgruntled owners tend to leap to their feet and bend his ear
about any number of piddling issues.
</P>
<P>
   Today, Madden sees one of his frequent critics, a tan man in his
60s, who is lying in the sun. Every building improvement Madden
suggests to the condo's governing board, this man opposes. Madden
playfully launches a cannonball over his neighbor's bow.
</P>
<P>
   ``Hey there, how about that barbecue! It's really coming
along!'' Madden says, his booming voice echoing in the honeycomb of
balconies that overlooks the pool. He's pointing to a permanent,
concrete-and-tile barbecue pit being built next to the pool cabana.
``It's almost done! You'll be cooking steaks on it by January.''
</P>
<P>
   The man snaps at the bait.
</P>
<P>
   ``Awww, nooooo,'' the tan retiree moans. He props himself up on
his lounge chair, as if a different position will boost the power
of his complaint. ``I don't believe it. It's never going to get
done.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Nope, it's almost done,'' Madden says, continuing his brisk
pace.
</P>
<P>
   ``No, it's not. Nothing around here works right, I swear.'' The
man is waving his arms now, twisting his body to face Madden as he
walks. ``Nothing works right!''
</P>
<P>
   Madden ducks into a nearby entrance that leads to the condo's
elevators.
</P>
<P>
   He's giggling now, aware of the emotional terrorism he's
launched, chortling at having pushed his adversary's buttons.
</P>
<P>
   ``That was almost too easy,'' he says.
</P>
<P>
   Some days, it's good to be the king.
</P>
<P>
   Exchanges such as those, well, they're the kind that belong in a
book.
</P>
<P>
   So after almost two years of trying to refurbish and revitalize
the condominium he shares with 130 residents, after dozens of
goofball confrontations with owners and battles with board members
present and past, Madden drew on the experiences to write a
tell-all ``fictional'' novel called ``King of the Condo''
(TransMedia Publishing, $9.95).
</P>
<P>
   The plot follows the headaches and heartaches of Edward J.
Malardi, a cigar vendor from the rough side of Philadelphia who
made his money and retired to Florida, only to find himself at the
helm of an oceanfront condo. When he tries to push the residents to
renovate their decaying building, things go haywire. Threats are
made. Bullets zing through sliding glass doors. Hate notes are
slipped under his door. A turtle lover tries to run him over on the
beach with a tractor. Lawsuits sprout like weeds.
</P>
<P>
   Madden describes his book as ``thinly veiled,'' but consider
these dead-on similarities:
</P>
<P>
   _ Malardi is elected after complaining at a condo board meeting
about the sad condition of the building's lobby. The board quits en
masse one night, clearing the way for him to campaign for the job.
</P>
<P>
   Madden complained about the building's dungeon-like lobby and _
you got it _ The Dune Deck board quit en masse one night, leading
him to campaign for the job.
</P>
<P>
   _ Malardi campaigns to hire a full-time manager and overhaul the
fire alarm and sprinkler system.
</P>
<P>
   Madden campaigned to improve the management and fire safety of
the building.
</P>
<P>
   _ Malardi's wife, Rita, is described in the book as a curvaceous
Italian.
</P>
<P>
   Ditto Madden's wife, Angela, who is from Bari in southern Italy.
</P>
<P>
   With these and other similarities, Madden is coy.
</P>
<P>
   ``Let's just say it's very loosely based,'' he said while
sitting on the balcony of his third-floor home and watching the
waves lap at the shore. ``If anyone sees themselves, it's not by
design.''
</P>
<P>
   But Terry Rains, Dune Deck's full-time manager, said the book is
plenty accurate. She easily recognized the traits of some
characters in the book that matched with tenants she deals with.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've worked at a couple of facilities, and what's funny is
that the characters in Tom's book can be found at any building you
go to,'' Rains said. ``They're universal characters.''
</P>
<P>
   Madden has made a good living pushing people's buttons. He did
it for years as a public relations executive at the ABC and NBC
television networks, and later as head of his own PR firm in
Manhattan.
</P>
<P>
   After he sold his agency, he moved south to Boca Raton and
started another firm, TransMedia. Besides public relations, the
agency has branched into publishing. Which is where King of the
Condo comes in. His first book, Spin Man, took a look at the
promotions industry.
</P>
<P>
   ``I look at this book, though, as a form of therapy,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   He moved to Dune Deck about five years ago, attending a few
condo board meetings but mostly keeping a low profile. (He once
received a written reprimand for not wearing a shirt while emptying
the trash into a communal bin and was threatened with a fine, but
did not contest the letter.)
</P>
<P>
   But he realized that the building needed sprucing up. People had
pledged for years to do something, but nothing ever happened.
</P>
<P>
   Campaigning on a platform that stressed the protection of the
building's assets, Madden was elected to the condo's board and made
president.
</P>
<P>
   ``Two days in, a woman I call the Diva of the Dumpster comes to
me crying that I threw her Christmas tree away,'' Madden said. The
tree, which the woman donated for display in the lobby, looked
shabby, so he pitched it.
</P>
<P>
   ``She told me, `I didn't donate it, I loaned it. I want it
back,''' he said. ``So two guys helped her fish it out. It was then
that I felt there might be some material for a whodunnit.''
</P>
<P>
   To residents' dismay, he soon started streamlining. Meetings
that took hours and were held weekly were trimmed back to once a
month or less often. Public comment was limited. Residents accused
him of railroading issues.
</P>
<P>
   Rebuilding the lobby, though, was the ultimate sin. The project
cost thousands and included knocking down walls, replacing
furniture and wiring, and building new quarters for the concierge.
</P>
<P>
   Everyone in the building, it seemed, wanted a say on the
project. Sensing chaos, Madden insisted the board select everything
with limited comment from residents.
</P>
<P>
   ``You have to act like the king, you really do, or else it all
breaks down,'' he said. ``How can 130 people design a lobby? What
would that look like?''
</P>
<P>
   The lobby was rebuilt. And Madden made enemies.
</P>
<P>
   ``When I go out to the pool, all the conversation stops,'' he
says.
</P>
<P>
   Some days it's not good to be the king. Like the day earlier
this week when Madden returned from a long holiday trip to New
York, only to find that his brand-new black Jaguar sedan had been
vandalized. He had parked the car in another owner's spot after
getting permission from the condo manager, he said.
</P>
<P>
   When he got home he found glue smeared over the windows. And on
the car, a note:
</P>
<P>
   Spin Jerk,
</P>
<P>
   It is no wonder that you and your wife are considered the least
liked residents of this condominium. Only a total (expletive) like
you would park his car in another owner's designated space during
an entire vacation week and leave town without leaving a car key
with the door man so your car could be moved.
</P>
<P>
   I am giving you fair warning, if you ever park your car in my
space again, you will do so at your peril.
</P>
<P>
   The funny part: The note was signed and dated. Below the
signature was the person's unit number, just so there would be no
mistake.
</P>
<P>
   ``These people are humorless,'' Madden said Monday. ``Maybe he's
read my book and doesn't like it.''
</P>
<P>
   The king's reign is just about over. Opting not to run for
another two-year term, Madden says he's had enough.
</P>
<P>
   ``One night I'm sitting on the couch,'' he says. ``Out of the
corner of my eye I see something slide under the door. I go over,
pick it up and read it and it's someone complaining about this or
that. I mean, what are we, in high school or something?''
</P>
<P>
   One of the residents has hired an investigator and an accountant
to make sure the condo's pool of assessment money was spent
legally.
</P>
<P>
   ``I cannot make it 30 or 40 yards sometimes without being
assaulted,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Soon it will be all over for Madden. Just like it was for
Malardi. In the book, the King of the Condo disappears into a haze
of cigar smoke, following a board vote that the whole tale had just
been a bad dream.
</P>
<P>
   The way Madden talks, there aren't enough cigars in the world to
make his bad dream go away.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's something deep in the primordial sense of human
beings,'' he concludes. ``When you mess with their shelter, people
get upset.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
