<DATE_TIME> 1999-01-08 11:07 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4586 &Cx1f; tad-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-IMPEACH-LEGAL09-COX     01-08 0646
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-IMPEACH-LEGAL09-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    BOTH SIDES ASSEMBLE BIG LEGAL TEAMS
 &HT;    Repeating from Thursday's file for all needing.
 &HT;    By JULIA MALONE
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ If the impeachment of President Clinton becomes the
trial of the century in the U.S. Senate, both sides will be ready
with large teams of courtroom-tested lawyers.
</P>
<P>
   At the start, the attorney advantage goes to the president. His
defenders can draw both from a White House that's chockablock with
lawyers and from Clinton's private attorney David Kendall, whose
firm of Williams &AMP; Connolly is famous among local prosecutors for
saving clients with scorched-earth legal tactics.
</P>
<P>
   White House spokesmen refused Thursday to say how many
government lawyers have been mobilized for the task of defending
the president.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton's office of counsel has about 35 lawyers, paralegals and
support staffers, working at a combined annual salary budget of
more than $2 million. Jim Kennedy, the president's legal spokesman,
said that ``relatively few members of the staff'' were working on
the impeachment case, and many of them only part time.
</P>
<P>
   Even so, the public-private effort to save this presidency is a
major undertaking. A White House legal response to the impeachment
charges last Dec. 14 listed no fewer than eight attorneys' names,
led by Gregory Craig, the special counsel who was summoned from the
State Department to coordinate Clinton's defense, and by Charles
Ruff, the president's chief counsel.
</P>
<P>
   Costs for the president's government lawyers will be paid by the
taxpayers. Republicans in the past loudly objected to Clinton's use
of his staff to defend him in the various Whitewater
investigations, but they are not complaining now.
</P>
<P>
   ``Once it gets to impeachment, I think the issue is joined,''
said C. Boyden Gray, who was chief counsel in the Bush White House.
``It's OK to defend impeachment with taxpayer funds.''
</P>
<P>
   However, Clinton will also mount up more IOUs to Kendall, whose
scowling visage has been prominent throughout Clinton's legal
difficulties. Kendall's $400-an-hour rates are paid by the
president's legal defense fund, which has consistently fallen
behind as legal costs have soared.
</P>
<P>
   By contrast, when President Andrew Johnson was impeached 130
years ago, he paid his own team of five lawyers. The fee was $2,000
each.
</P>
<P>
   On the other side of the Clinton impeachment, the president will
face 13 House ``managers,'' members of the House Judiciary
Committee who will conduct the case in the Senate. The
all-Republican team led by House Judiciary Committee Chairman Henry
J. Hyde of Illinois is made up of lawyers, several of whom are
experienced prosecutors who frequently speak of their own trial
experiences.
</P>
<P>
   The House committee has a backup team of 18 attorneys, including
eight hired to deal with the impeachment investigation, who will
help develop the case in the Senate. David Schippers, the blunt
Chicago Democrat brought in to lead the House investigation, is
coordinating the prosecution staff.
</P>
<P>
   The House investigation, budgeted for $1.2 million, cost an
estimated $900,000 last year. For the Senate trial, the House this
week voted to spend money ``as needed'' for legal expenses.
</P>
<P>
   If the trial grows into a lengthy proceeding with witnesses to
depose and cross-examine, Senate Democrats may also seek legal
advice.
</P>
<P>
   Abbe Lowell, the Washington lawyer who was the lead attorney for
the Democrats in the House investigation, said Thursday that
``Democrats could use help in learning about the evidence'' if the
trial is prolonged.
</P>
<P>
   Lowell said he has been providing Democratic senators and their
staff with information about the case.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're all waiting'' to see what happens next, he said.
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
