<P>
   These columns for release Saturday, January 9, and Sunday,
January 10, 1999 are moving today to clients of the New York Times
News Service.
</P>
<P>
   All columns have moved, in the commentary (k) category. If you
have questions or need a resend, please call CoxNet, the Cox News
Service, at 404-526-5456.
</P>
<P>
   BIG-BROTHER _ AUSTIN, Texas _ As time passes, there are few
things we can't see or find out about our neighbor, very little
information we can't acquire. From the Internet to the television
set and the home video camera, there is nowhere to hide. Which
leads us to reassess exactly whom Big Brother is and whom, exactly,
he is watching anymore. (Kallenberg, Austin American-Statesman)
MOVED FOR SATURDAY
</P>
<P>
   BORDERS-COLUMN _ NACOGDOCHES, Texas _ I spent my Christmas
vacation trying not to cut off my fingers, taking a late-night trip
to the emergency room to get a mote out of my eye, and inhaling
massive amounts of sawdust. It was great. (Borders, Nacogdoches
Daily Sentinel) MOVED FOR SATURDAY
</P>
<P>
   LATHAM-COLUMN _ MARSHALL, Texas _ Texas hasn't outlawed angry
school administrators from putting bruises on children in the name
of education and it is high time we did so. This isn't about
discipline at all. It is about hitting children on a whim and it
just isn't right. (Latham, Marshall News Messenger) MOVED FOR
SATURDAY
</P>
<P>
   MCCARTY-COLUMN _ DAYTON, Ohio _ As of last weekend, the Salem
Avenue Pizza Factory _ which previously delivered throughout a wide
area in Dayton _ will no longer be making deliveries. ``Pizza
Factory, no deliveries,'' a man answered the phone. Roads are bad,
I figured. No, he said. Too many drivers being robbed. I got off
the phone with a sick feeling. Once again, a small handful of
people had made city living a little less pleasant for rest of us.
(McCarty, Dayton Daily News) MOVES FRIDAY FOR SATURDAY
</P>
