<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    COX NEWS SERVICE FEATURES BUDGET
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   These feature stories for release Saturday, January 9 and
Sunday, January 10, 1999, are moving today to clients of the New
York Times News Service.
</P>
<P>
   Separate budgets move daily with spot news, sports, business and
commentary.
</P>
<P>
   Stories are moving in the category they're listed under. Stories
moving to duplicate categories are marked. All stories have moved
except those with an ETA.
</P>
<P>
   If you have questions or need a resend, please call CoxNet, the
Cox News Service, at 404-526-5456.
</P>
<P>
   LOOK ON THE WEB: Some of these stories are available in
paginated form: www.nytsyn.com/pageexpress.
</P>
<P>
   LIFESTYLE
</P>
<P>
   WARNER-ON-WOOD _ ATLANTA _ Since we discussed the cutting of
mortises last week, we may as well look at ways of making the
second half of the joint, the tenon. (Warner, Atlanta
Journal-Constitution) MOVES FRIDAY FOR SATURDAY
</P>
<P>
   BARBIE _ DELRAY BEACH, Fla. _ Barbie turns 40 in March, but
Delray Beach, Fla., isn't waiting until then to celebrate: As part
of its observance of Women's History Month, Old School Square will
have an exhibition of lots of Barbies, including some sent
specially from Mattel. We talk with the exhibit's ``curator'' (a
Delray Beach woman), weave in a bit of history and also talk about
how this fits _ or doesn't _ with Women's History Month. (Pickel,
Palm Beach Post) MOVED FOR SATURDAY
</P>
<P>
   RESOLUTIONS _ WEST PALM BEACH, Fla. _ As we enter this, the
final year of the 20th century, let us vow to take the higher road,
to grasp the greater good ... . To not be such jerks. A list of
``wills'' and ``will nots.'' (Grantham, Palm Beach Post) MOVED FOR
SATURDAY
</P>
<P>
   COFFEE _ GAINESVILLE, Ga. _ Gainesville, Georgia may be most
well known for its poultry plants. But Don Wilson wants to make it
synonymous with gourmet coffee. A reformed drinker who traded in
booze for gourmet coffees, he eventually found it wasn't enough to
discover and enjoy: He wanted to import, roast and run his own
coffee company. Since 1995, his St. Ives Coffee Roasters of
Gainesville has been building business, and its name. Some diehard
Atlantans drive up weekly for freshly roasted beans, and his
mail-order business has taken off. (Guthrie, Atlanta
Journal-Constitution). WITH PHOTO. FOR SUNDAY
</P>
<P>
   STYLE
</P>
<P>
   HANDBAGS _ They come in everything from tiny canister-shaped
evening bag _ big enough for lipstick, mirror and $20 bill _ to a
soft, casual tote that holds keys, a billfold and cell phone. The
new hand-held pocketbook are replacing shoulder bags as the most
stylish way for women to tote their belongings. (MJohnson, Atlanta
Journal-Constitution). WITH PHOTOS . FOR SUNDAY
</P>
<P>
   ARTS/ENTERTAINMENT
</P>
<P>
   CONDO-KING-BOOK _ WEST PALM BEACH, Fla. _ The life, loves, and
witty and sometimes anger-filled exchanges of condo association
president Tom Madden are included in new book ``loosely-based'' in
reality, ``King of the Condo.'' (Houck, Palm Beach Post) MOVED.
EDs: Embargoed until Monday, Jan. 11.
</P>
<P>
   MARS-VENUS-GAME _ WEST PALM BEACH, Fla. _ Making a go with Dr.
Gray's board game isn't all that bad _ if you can find a question
whose answer isn't too obvious or too personal to share with
friends. (Cerabino, Palm Beach Post) MOVED FOR SATURDAY
</P>
<P>
   RATHER-60MINUTES _ AUSTIN, Texas _ Noted news hound Dan Rather
likes nothing more than donning a slicker, grabbing a microphone
and rushing head-first into a hurricane. He's about to perform a
similar, if drier and slightly less dangerous, feat this week.
Starting Wednesday at 8 p.m., he'll anchor ``60 Minutes II.'' An
interview. (Holloway, Austin American-Statesman) MOVED. EDs:
Embargoed until Sunday, Jan. 10
</P>
<P>
   OPRY _ It's the oldest running live radio show in America, and
the temple of country music. But the Grand Ole Opry is facing a
challenge. Most of the members are well into their `70s, and
management is finding it difficult to interest the young, suburban
country fan in the graying institution. Opry members (many of whom
have no other venue for their music) are incredibly protective of
their fiefdom, and reluctant to change the show in any way. This
weekend, the Opry returns to the Ryman auditorium for the first
time in 25 years, which could be test run for how to keep the
tradition alive into the 21st century. A look at the Opry, its
current status and the challenges it faces as a Southern arts
institution, through the words and insights of performers and
owners. (MLongino, Atlanta Journal-Constitution). WITH PHOTOS. FOR
SUNDAY
</P>
<P>
   MUSICAL-BLOCKBUSTERS _ Chart on the musical blockbusters
returning to Atlanta (Cats, Les Miz, Saigon, Evita) through
mid-Feb. (Hulbert, Atlanta Journal-Constitution). FOR SUNDAY
</P>
<P>
   TRAVEL
</P>
<P>
   STREAMBOAT _ It's easy to get carried away by the natural beauty
of this relatively remote ski resort, far from the hipster crowds
of Aspen and Vail. Steamboat Springs is further out from Denver (a
three-hour drive) than most of the state's ski areas and sits on a
fascinating climactic divide. From some canyon roads you can throw
a rock and hit snow-covered spruce on the shadowed, north-facing
slope, then turn around and peg one against sun-baked boulders and
sagebrush on the southern exposure. ``Steamboat's just a country
town at heart, not a lot of fur coats but hey _ those are OK too,
anything goes,'' says Kay Sullins, 46, whose Windwalker Tours
specializes in towing people around with horses _ by sleigh in
winter, chuckwagons in summer. (DHulbert, Atlanta
Journal-Constitution). WITH COLOR PHOTOS. FOR SUNDAY
</P>
<P>
   WITH
</P>
<P>
   STEAMBOAT-TIPS _ Ski tips from a spouse skiing for the first
time: I'll admit it. Until my husband suggested that I try snow
skiing, I figured that it wasn't going to happen for me in this
lifetime. Having already climbed my way to that summit called
Mature Adulthood, I wasn't sure that I wanted to risk it all for
the sensation of sliding down a mountain. But faster than you can
say ``How about a beach trip?'' I found myself getting measured for
ski boots in Steamboat Springs, Colo. (CHulbert, Atlanta
Journal-Constitution). FOR SUNDAY
</P>
<P>
   TRAVEL-NOTES _ Going Places (travel notes) column. (Thrasher,
Atlanta Journal-Constitution). FOR SUNDAY
</P>
<P>
   RELIGION
</P>
<P>
   GAGOV-BELIEFS _ Georgia governor-elect Roy Barnes, a United
Methodist layman like his two immediate predecessors, talks about
his faith and the role it plays in shaping his positions and
determining his political career. (GWhite, Atlanta
Journal-Constitution). WITH COLOR PHOTO. FOR SATURDAY
</P>
<P>
   SCIENCE-MEDICINE
</P>
<P>
   FITNESS _ Now that the last binge weekend of holidays is over,
it's time for winter navel gazing, and it's not a pretty sight. Get
the whole family involved in fitness, and the best place to do it
still is the local YMCA. (Kim, Atlanta Journal-Constitution). WITH
PHOTOS. FOR SATURDAY
</P>
<P>
   CALORIES-PORTIONS _ Come January, everyone's looking at how to
cut calories, but lots of people don't consider portion size. What
does four ounces of fish look like? A mere deck of cards. Some
simple rules for portion control. (Walker, Atlanta
Journal-Constitution). FOR SATURDAY
</P>
<P>
   ABBY _ A day with Abby Banks to update how the 4-year-old
Franklin, Ohio, girl is getting along with life in a spacesuit,
which was donated by supermodel Christy Turlington. Abby has a rare
skin disorder that made it impossible for her to be outside in
daylight. We follow her at play outside, with her friends, with her
pony. (Budd, Dayton Daily News). 22. WITH PHOTOS. FOR SUNDAY
</P>
<P>
   HOME &AMP; GARDEN
</P>
<P>
   ACCESSORIES _ Decorating accessories _ lamps, pictures, pillows,
books _ are considered the icing on the cake when it comes to
creating attractive interiors. But it's not just a matter of having
the right things. It's knowing how to arrange them so that
complement furniture with the appropriate color, scale and texture.
(Flanders, Atlanta Journal-Constitution) WITH PHOTOS. FOR SATURDAY
</P>
<P>
   WITH
</P>
<P>
   ACCESSORIES-TIPS _ Tips on displaying accessories. (Flanders,
Atlanta Journal-Constitution). FOR SATURDAY
</P>
