<HEADER>
A4594 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u v &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-HEARST-FEATURE-BUDGET     01-08 1017
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HEARST-FEATURE-BUDGET-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EDITORS:
</HEADLINE>
  
 Friday, Jan. 8, 1999      The Hearst News Service will file the following stories for
Saturday and Sunday. If you have questions, please call Mark Helm
at 202-298-6920.  
    (Slugline includes the ``HNS'' tag.)
   
<TEXT>
<P>
   INTERNATIONAL (``i'' category)
</P>
<P>
   JOURNALIST-AUTOPSY (Mexico City) _ A medical expert has
concluded that Philip True, the San Antonio Express-News bureau
chief in Mexico, was murdered last month and that he could have
died from having the equivalent of 50 drinks of alcohol poured into
him. By DANE SCHILLER.
</P>
<P>
   FEATURES/LIFESTYLE (``l'' category)
</P>
<P>
   DEADLY-MONTHS (Albany, N.Y.) _ More people, particularly the
elderly, die in December and January than at any other time of the
year. Experts attribute the seasonal rise in mortality to several
factors. By SYLVIA WOOD.
</P>
<P>
   COACH-GRADES (Richmond, Calif.) _ Basketball coach Ken Carter is
more concerned about grades and citizenship than records and
trophies for his high school team. On Monday, he padlocked the gym
and canceled practices and games indefinitely, citing a lack of
academic focus by some of his players. By ROBERT SELNA.
</P>
<P>
   SNOWBOARDING (Albany, N.Y.) _ If current trends continue,
snowboarders will outnumber skiers on the slopes within a decade.
By BUZZ GRAY.
</P>
<P>
   O'HAIR-DIARIES (Austin, Texas) _ Professional atheist Madalyn
Murray O'Hair disappeared more than three years ago and is presumed
dead. Her handwritten diaries, covering 1953 to 1995, plus some
personal papers and letters, will soon be sold to help pay some of
the debts she left behind. Foremost is a bill from the Internal
Revenue Service for $250,000. By JOHN MacCORMACK.
</P>
<P>
   HELOISE (San Antonio) _ It's a weekday afternoon and the
best-known name in American housekeeping isn't doing any. Instead,
Heloise is hunkered down at a computer, answering questions from
inquiring minds on the Internet. This is a day set aside for
Heloise's monthly online chat. Heloise's hints have made her a
global, multimedia entity. She is identifiable by a single name,
just like Cher and Madonna, and that name is synonymous with
household hints. By ROY BRAGG. (For release Sunday, Jan. 10.)
</P>
<P>
   MUSSOLINI-BOAT (Galveston, Texas) _ A Texas couple is about to
open a bed-and-breakfast inn in Galveston aboard the ``Chryseis,''
a two-masted schooner once owned by Italian dictator Benito
Mussolini. The boat, built in 1906, has a colorful history,
including roles in the movie ``Chitty, Chitty, Bang Bang.'' By
KEVIN MORAN (Photos available on NYT database. (For release Sunday,
Jan. 10.)
</P>
<P>
   NATIONAL NEWS (``a'' category)
</P>
<P>
   SINGER-CHARGED (Uvalde, Texas) _ Country singer Johnny Rodriguez
was charged with murder in connection with the Aug. 29 shooting
death of am acquaintance. By RALPH WINNINGHAM.
</P>
<P>
   MONEY (``f'' category)
</P>
<P>
   KIDS-INVESTING (San Francisco) _ Wall Street investors could
learn something from the kids at Westborough Middle School. A
four-member team of students from the school beat out more than
3,000 teams from across the country to win first place in the CNBC
Student Stock Tournament. By VICTORIA COLLIVER.
</P>
<P>
   TRAVEL (``t'' category)
</P>
<P>
   TRAVEL-COLUMN (Undated) _ Refreshed after the holidays, I tore
into the first parcel of mail as if it were a leftover Christmas
present. The book's title stared me squarely in the face: ``The
Complete Idiot's Travel Guide to Cruise Vacations.'' I opened a
second package. Another book: ``Travel Planning Online for
Dummies.'' A look at these books. By HARRY SHATTUCK. (For release
Sunday, Jan. 10.)
</P>
<P>
   ENTERTAINMENT (``e'' category)
</P>
<P>
   TV-REVIEW-SOPRANO (Undated) _ Being a mobster is tough. No
benefits, no pension, high risk, a dwindling job market and those
pesky Feds with telephoto lenses. That's not to mention family
problems. Or The Family problems. This is the world of Anthony
``Tony'' Soprano. There are times you'll crack up, laughing that
is, at the new HBO series, ``The Sopranos'' (Sunday at 9 p.m.). By
MARK McGUIRE
</P>
<P>
   FILM-REVIEW-DEVINE (Undated) _ Not to scare you off, but naked
old men on motorcycles figure prominently in ``Waking Ned Devine.''
So does a days-old corpse. And dentures. And pig stench, which has
nothing to do with the corpse. But this film a puckish little
pleasure, a movie so adamantly (and, most of the time,
successfully) sweet-natured that you all but forget the twisted
amorality at its core. By AMY BIANCOLLI.
</P>
<P>
   FILM-REVIEW-CIVIL (Undated) _ If I were in the legal racket, I
might think about suing the makers of ``A Civil Action.'' Few
mainstream pictures have offered such a devastatingly negative
portrayal of the practice of law in modern America _ and this is a
movie where the morally dubious main character turns into a hero
with a worthy cause. By WALTER ADDIEGO.
</P>
<P>
   TV-WB-KELLNER (Pasadena, Calif.) _ The man running The WB, at
this moment the only network to show any viewership gains and, more
importantly, the one to watch, has no problem owning up to his
life. Jamie Kellner, the CEO of The WB, claims to be ``over 50''
but probably isn't by more than a year. By TIM GOODMAN.
</P>
<P>
   SPORTS (``s'' category)
</P>
<P>
   FBN-GARRISON-HEARST (San Francisco) _ Bobb McKittrick, the San
Francisco 49ers line coach, got a little gleam in his eye when
Garrison Hearst's name came up. He talked about how Hearst blocks,
how he goes directly at linebackers and defensive linemen, doesn't
just nick them on the shoulder to slow them down. ``I don't think a
running back can be tougher,'' McKittrick said. By GWEN KNAPP.
</P>
<P>
   COMMENTARY (``k'' category)
</P>
<P>
   MORSE-COLUMN (San Francisco) _ Chief Justice William Rehnquist
of the Supreme Court arrived in a gown with gold stripes on the
arms, a fashion statement he borrowed from the Lord Chancellor in
``Iolanthe,'' a Gilbert and Sullivan comic opera. If the Senate
Republicans had to be cast in a Gilbert and Sullivan production,
they'd be auditioning for the role of the Lord High Executioner
from ``The Mikado.'' By ROB MORSE.
</P>
</TEXT>
