<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-01-08 11:30 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4601 &Cx1f; tad-z
u l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-WARNER-ON-WOOD02-COX     01-08 0559
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-WARNER-ON-WOOD02-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    EDITORS: RESENDING FOR THOSE WHO NEED IT
 &HT;    Cutting mortises by hand requires some expertise
 &HT;    
 &HT;    By Jack Warner
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   The question of how to cut mortises, especially by hand, has
been bandied about on the Internet.
</P>
<P>
   To begin with, I'll say that mortises are not something you want
to cut entirely by hand unless you are merely trying to pass time.
It is extremely tedious, and of course one never cuts only one
mortise. They generally come in bunches.
</P>
<P>
   If you have to cut them by hand, then you'll need a good chisel
of the same width as the mortise. You can generally get by with
cabinetmaker's chisels, although firmer chisels would be nice.
</P>
<P>
   Lay out the mortise carefully, using a marking knife to scribe
the lines. Then use the chisel with a good wooden or rubber mallet
to deepen the scribe lines. Be careful to keep the flat side of the
chisel on the outside, and don't let it thicken the line to the
outside.
</P>
<P>
   Then begin wasting the wood in the center by cutting a V shape,
gradually widening it until you are near both ends of the mortise.
Now trim it down until you're at the marks. Some woodworkers like
to undercut their mortises just a little to allow room for glue and
make for a smooth fit.
</P>
<P>
   Now, assuming you own an electric drill, you can make life much
easier by wasting most of the wood with a bit a little smaller than
the width of the mortise. A drill press is best for this, since you
have to be careful to keep the bit square to the sides, but you can
do it if you're careful.
</P>
<P>
   A lot of folks are really happy with the chisel attachments you
put on a drill press. These use a drill bit on the inside to waste
most of the wood and chisel-like knives on all four sides to smooth
and square the cut. The drawback here is that they're rather
expensive and the chisels must be kept very sharp. Relatively
recently dedicated machines using these devices have appeared on
the market. They are very expensive for what they do.
</P>
<P>
   The happiest mortising I've ever done was on my old Inca table
saw, which had a mortising table attached to it. This made a
believer of me _ the best kind of dedicated mortising machine is a
horizontal mortiser. These use standard, relatively inexpensive
cutters rotating at high speed. The cutter is fixed. The work is
attached to a table which can be adjusted very finely for height.
There is one lever for side to side movement of the table and
another for depth. Stops can be set to limit all the travel, and
the mortise is quickly cut in an ever-deeper series of passes.
</P>
<P>
   The only drawback here is a round shoulder. Fussbudgets can use
a chisel, or even buy a tool, to square the shoulder. I always
round over the edges of the tenon.
</P>
<P>
   Unfortunately, there are very few horizontal mortisers on the
market, but they can be shop-made.
</P>
<P>
   Since the departure of my Inca saw, I've used a homemade router
jig to cut mortises. You can find instructions for making one in
almost any book on routing or shop jigs. It works very well; it's
just not as quick for cutting a whole series of mortises as a
dedicated machine. n
</P>
<P>
   E-mail: jwarner(at)ajc.com
</P>
<P>
   We want to hear from you but are unable to acknowledge every
message.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
