<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ALBANY-PUBLISHER-APPOINT-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DAVID WHITE NAMED PUBLISHER OF THE ALBANY TIMES UNION 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 c.1999 Hearst Newspapers  
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ David P. White, advertising director of the Albany
Times Union, has been named publisher of the Times Union. He
succeeds Timothy O. White, who has been named publisher and editor
of the San Francisco Examiner.
</P>
<P>
   The appointment, effective immediately, was announced Friday by
George B. Irish, president of Hearst Newspapers and vice president
of The Hearst Corporation. Both the Times Union and the Examiner
are Hearst newspapers.
</P>
<P>
   ``Over the past decade, Dave White has led the Times Union
advertising team to a record performance,'' Irish said. ``I know
that he will continue to carry out the impressive journalistic and
business course that Tim White had charted for the newspaper for
the past nine years.'' David White and Tim White are not related.
</P>
<P>
   Additionally, George R. Hearst III, 43, director of operations
for the Times Union, has been appointed associate publisher and
vice president. He has two decades of experience in the newspaper
industry, including positions in finance, advertising sales,
information systems and manufacturing at three Hearst newspapers.
George Hearst III, who joined the Times Union in 1989, is a
great-grandson of The Hearst Corporation's founder, William
Randolph Hearst.
</P>
<P>
   Also promoted to vice president at the Times Union were Jeff
Cohen, editor, and Robert S. Wilson, general manager. Cohen, Hearst
and Wilson will report directly to David White.
</P>
<P>
   Cohen, 44, joined the Times Union in 1994 as editor, and has
spent 22 years with Hearst Newspapers.
</P>
<P>
   Wilson, 49, joined Hearst in 1980, and has served in various
newspaper management positions during his 26 years in the industry.
</P>
<P>
   David White, 56, joined the Times Union as advertising director
in 1988. A 37-year veteran of the newspaper industry, White spent
the first seven years of his career in classified advertising sales
and sales management at the Cleveland Plain Dealer. He later moved
into various advertising management positions at the Newark (N.J.)
Star-Ledger, the Detroit Free Press and the Orlando Sentinel.
</P>
<P>
   Hearst Newspapers is an operating group of The Hearst
Corporation.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
