NYT-01-08-99 1159EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990108.0104 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-01-08 12:00 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4648 &Cx1f; tad-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-WEALTH-GAP-$ADV10-COX     01-08 1281
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-WEALTH-GAP-$ADV10-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    APPALACHIAN TOWN A SYMBOL OF WORKING POOR'S STRUGGLE
 &HT;    With WEALTH-DATA. Moving in (w) Washington and (a) national
categories For release Sunday, Jan. 10. Story is good for use until
Thursday, Jan. 14.
 &HT;    By SCOTT SHEPARD
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   NELSONVILLE, Ohio _ The snow drifts against the historic
passenger coaches of the Hocking Valley Scenic Railway, parked in
the downtown of this scenic Appalachian foothill community. The
railroad won't haul tourists again until Memorial Day. Now is the
winter of discontent and economic worry.
</P>
<P>
   True, times are not as tough as they once were. The new Taco
Bell and Burger King down the road from the train depot and the
signs advertising unlimited Internet access for $12.95 a month
suggest this is not the Appalachia that moved America three decades
ago to wage a ``war on poverty.''
</P>
<P>
   But while the economic gains in Appalachia blaze in fluorescent
and neon lights all along U.S. 33, this town of about 5,000 also
illustrates a not-so-glaring truth: the national economic boom of
the 1990s has largely benefited the well-to-do, and has actually
widened the gap between the have and have-nots.
</P>
<P>
   ``It seems like you're either rich or poor, and if they want to
make us the poster child _ and it gets the rest of the country
talking about the forgotten towns of America _ well, that's all
right with me,'' said Charlie Smith, whose restaurant, The Coffee
Cup, is a popular gathering place.
</P>
<P>
   Smith is talking about a political odd couple, the Rev. Jesse
Jackson and the Rev. Jerry Falwell, who led a rally in Nelsonville
last fall to focus national attention on poverty and the growing
gap between the rich and poor in America.
</P>
<P>
   Smith's family moved here from West Virginia in 1968 when he was
a year old. Smith's father had lost his job there. He later lost
his job here, and the family relied on public assistance until his
father started The Coffee Cup ``with only a can of beans and a
pound of meat,'' Smith boasted.
</P>
<P>
   The folks around here are proud of Nelsonville. ``It's a
close-knit town, and it's safe,'' said 23-year-old Deedra Dupler, a
native and mother of two little girls. She works as a waitress. Her
husband, Bryan, is a foreman at the Rocky Boot factory, one of the
few remaining manufacturing plants in the area.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're just too dependent on tourism, and that's the first
thing to feel a recession,'' said Smith.
</P>
<P>
   To attract tourists, Nelsonville has gone to great lengths to
preserve its history. The Hocking Valley Scenic Railway gives
tourists a glimpse of the past, passing shut-down brick kilns and
mines that were once the mainstays of the local economy.
</P>
<P>
   The restored Drew Hotel, which once played host to a campaigning
Teddy Roosevelt, is a popular attraction. The town's Victorian-era
public square, with its turn-of-the-century fountain, was the
backdrop for scenes in the 1985 movie ``Mischief,'' about teen life
in the 1950s.
</P>
<P>
   For Jackson, though, Nelsonville is the perfect setting to get
Americans thinking anew about poverty and income inequality. It is
overwhelmingly white, and it is surrounded by the picturesque Wayne
National Forest, not the blight of the inner city.
</P>
<P>
   His Appalachian effort is the flip side to his ``Wall Street
Project,'' which promotes increased investment in minority-owned
businesses and predominantly black neighborhoods.
</P>
<P>
   The ``Wall Street Project'' will hold its second annual
gathering starting Thursday in New York, with President Clinton and
numerous top business executives scheduled to attend. At the
conference, the president is expected to announce initiatives to
promote minority business access to capital, Jackson aides said.
</P>
<P>
   Poverty has not been an integral part of the presidential
dialogue since 1980, except in the context of reforming welfare.
And no politician today, except Jackson, seems very concerned about
it, or the widening income inequality that economists have been
tracking for decades.
</P>
<P>
   That partly reflects an American belief that people bear primary
responsibility for supporting themselves. Opinion polls
consistently show that only about a quarter of Americans believe
that the government should guarantee each citizen a minimum
standard of living.
</P>
<P>
   But Jackson, with the help of Falwell, has set about trying to
get the next batch of presidential candidates and the country to
see what the globalized economy has wrought, and to change the
debate on poverty from one of race to one of class.
</P>
<P>
   ``When John F. Kennedy went to Harlem and held a poor black baby
in his arms, it was dismissed as something liberals do,'' Jackson
said. ``But when Bobby Kennedy went to Appalachia and held a white
baby with a bloated stomach in his arms, America was forced to pay
attention.''
</P>
<P>
   Jackson has challenged the presidential candidates in the 2000
campaign to come to Appalachia and explain what they will do to
reverse the 20-year decline in earnings for the poorest 40 percent
of American households.
</P>
<P>
   Thirty years of anti-poverty spending has, for the most part,
alleviated the kind of spirit-killing poverty that Bobby Kennedy
encountered in Appalachia during his presidential campaign in 1968.
The region's problem now is the same as the rest of America:
high-paying manufacturing and mining jobs have been replaced by
lower-paying service sector jobs.
</P>
<P>
   ``Good-paying jobs are just hard to find around here,'' said
Lauren Oliver, an admissions counselor at Hocking College, a
two-year technical school founded in 1968 and occupying 1,600 acres
in the eastern end of Nelsonville.
</P>
<P>
   ``People tend to think of Appalachian poverty in terms of old
folks sitting on the porch of a log cabin whittling away,'' she
said. ``You still have some of that. But for the most part, it is
people who are working, but not making enough to support their
families.''
</P>
<P>
   Oliver, a recent graduate of Ohio University in nearby Athens,
speaks from personal experience. Her job at Hocking was ``a
godsend,'' she said. Before landing it several months ago, she was
working for $7 an hour at the local newspaper.
</P>
<P>
   Since 1988, 1.3 million new jobs have been added to the
Appalachian economy, according to a study done last fall by the
Appalachian Regional Commission (ARC), the agency created by
Congress in 1966 to improve living conditions in the 406 rural
counties in the 13 states that make up the Appalachian region.
</P>
<P>
   While politicians and bureaucrats hailed the new jobs as
evidence of the success of their policies, they largely ignored the
fact that more than 1 million of the new jobs were in lower-wage
service sectors rather than manufacturing.
</P>
<P>
   In fact, according to the ARC study, the Appalachian region has
lost more than 260,000 manufacturing and mining jobs during the
past decade. And Greg Bischak, the ARC's senior economist who did
the study, warns of ``continued erosion'' of manufacturing jobs due
to global competition.
</P>
<P>
   ``In Appalachia, we see a reflection _ magnified _ of the crisis
affecting working Americans across our nation,'' said John Sweeney,
president of the AFL-CIO, who helped Jackson organize the rally in
Nelsonville last fall.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's not just Appalachia, it's not just Nelsonville, it's
every small town,'' said Smith. ``We've been forgot. We're
hard-working people, and we should be rewarded. But we're not a big
block of voters, so the politicians don't see us or hear us.''
</P>
<P>
   Recalling Teddy Roosevelt's campaign stop, Smith mused. ``Maybe
another presidential candidate will come to and listen to us.''
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
