A4734 &Cx1f; ttj-z
r i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-JOURNALIST-AUTOPSY-HN     01-08 0634
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-JOURNALIST-AUTOPSY-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SECOND AUTOPSY ON AMERICAN JOURNALIST SAID TO DIFFER FROM FIRST 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By DANE SCHILLER  
 c.1999 San Antonio Express-News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   MEXICO CITY _ A medical expert has concluded that Philip True,
the San Antonio Express-News Mexico City bureau chief, was murdered
last month and that he could have died from having the equivalent
of 50 drinks of alcohol poured into him, sources say.
</P>
<P>
   Dr. Emma Lew, a Miami-based pathologist who works with the FBI,
says True's death could have been caused four ways: strangulation,
a blow on the head, intoxication poisoning and a pulmonary edema _
abnormal fluid in his lungs _ from having ethanol (grain alcohol)
poured into him, says a source who spoke on condition of anonymity.
</P>
<P>
   True's widow, Martha, confirmed she had been told the same thing
in a mid-afternoon call from Guadalajara, where Lew met with
federal and Jalisco state officials.
</P>
<P>
   ``My understanding is it was a combination of those things,''
Martha True said.
</P>
<P>
   While agreeing that True was murdered, Lew disputed earlier
conclusions by a veteran Jalisco coroner who ruled True had been
strangled with his bandana. She also dismissed that he'd likely
been brutalized.
</P>
<P>
   Lew also found that True's body had been dragged about 600 yards
from where he was killed to where it was dumped in a shallow grave.
</P>
<P>
   Lew was asked by the U.S. Embassy to observe the second autopsy.
</P>
<P>
   A spokesman for Mexican President Ernesto Zedillo confirmed the
Guadalajara meeting, but said he did not have access to Lew's
findings.
</P>
<P>
   True disappeared halfway through a 10-day hiking trip last month
through the Sierra Madre Occidental, where he was researching the
Huichol Indians.
</P>
<P>
   Two Huichols have been charged with murder and robbery in the
case.
</P>
<P>
   The two suspects originally told state prosecutors they killed
True for taking photos without permission. They later changed their
story and told a judge they killed True because he was threatening
their family and appeared drunk.
</P>
<P>
   A Zedillo spokesman said authorities were working to ensure they
had as much information as possible before making public any
conclusions.
</P>
<P>
   ``The intention is to make everything clear, but for judicial
reasons, some information must be reserved,'' the spokesman said.
</P>
<P>
   Dr. Mario Rivas Souza, chief coroner for the state of Jalisco,
said earlier this week that he stands firmly by his finding that
True was strangled to death.
</P>
<P>
   He did concede that other medical examiners might reach their
own conclusions in the case. ``Medicine is not mathematics. Two and
two does not equal four,'' Rivas said Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   ``If someone else has another conclusion, they should have to
defend it,'' said Rivas.
</P>
<P>
   Rivas said True also had abrasions on his head and that tests
showed True's blood alcohol level was 0.26 percent. That is more
than twice the 0.1 percent drunken-driving limit in Texas.
</P>
<P>
   But he noted there was no proof True had been drinking since the
alcohol could have been produced by bacteria from the decomposing
body.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't know if he was drunk, only that he had that level of
alcohol,'' Rivas said.
</P>
<P>
   Some Mexican newspapers had speculated that True may have
slipped and fallen to his death while intoxicated. But the findings
by Lew and Rivas that the death was a homicide would dispute that
scenario.
</P>
<P>
   True had been dead for several days when his body was found on
Dec. 14 in the Chapalagana Canyon by a Huichol Indian who was
hunting.
</P>
<P>
   But when officials went to recover the body, they found it had
been moved to a shallow grave and wrapped in a sleeping bag and a
ground cloth.
</P>
<P>
   True, 50, had been employed by the Express-News since 1992 and
was the Mexico City bureau chief since 1996.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
