<SLUG> BC-DEADLY-MONTHS-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DECEMBER AND JANUARY ARE DEADLIEST MONTHS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By SYLVIA WOOD  
 c.1999 Albany Times Union  
<TEXT>
<P>
   ALBANY, N.Y. _ It's been a busy winter so far for Roy Bordeau.
Last month, the Schenectady funeral director got 42 calls, the
highest monthly total he can recall in more than two decades of
dealing with death.
</P>
<P>
   A quick glance at the obituary pages this week promises another
hectic month. The grim reality is this: more people, particularly
the elderly, die in December and January than at any other time of
the year.
</P>
<P>
   Experts attribute the seasonal rise in mortality to several
factors. This time of year marks the onset of the annual flu and
pneumonia season with the elderly being among the most vulnerable.
Every year, an estimated 20,000 people die nationwide from
flu-related complications.
</P>
<P>
   ``What tends to kill people isn't flu itself, but bacterial
pneumonia on top of that,'' said Dr. Michael Wolff, the medical
director of the Eddy Care Plus Center, an Albany clinic which
specializes in geriatric medicine.
</P>
<P>
   So far this year, some 21 flu outbreaks have been reported in
New York, about half as many as last year at this time, according
to the state health department.
</P>
<P>
   Another theory for the increased death rates is more difficult
to quantify: those who work with the elderly believe that winter,
with its short and cold days is an especially difficult time, both
physically and psychologically.
</P>
<P>
   Besides being susceptible to flu, pneumonia and a host of other
viral infections, the elderly also face an additional challenge
with the weather. ``People with cardiovascular disease often go out
and shovel which puts extra strain on their heart,'' said Dr.
Richard Gullott, the medical director at St. Clare's Hospital in
Schenectady.
</P>
<P>
   ``Another issue is it's slippery. The elderly fall and break
their hips in the winter and then they come into the hospital.''
There, they face additional exposure to illness, which puts
increased strain on their already compromised immune systems. ``The
elderly have very little reserve,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   If all of this talk about death and dying depresses you, that's
another problem this time of year.
</P>
<P>
   Studies have shown that depression rates tend to increase in the
winter months and around the holidays. Bordeau believes the theory
that some elderly hang on through the holidays and then let go.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think there's some validity to that,'' he said. Yet Bordeau
also attributes his busier-than-usual winter this year to another
factor. ``I had the slowest summer in 1998 that I've ever had. July
and August were dead, no pun intended,'' he said. ``Everything
evens itself out.'' Psychologically, a mental balance this time of
year can be elusive among the elderly, especially if family doesn't
live nearby or if many friends have already died.
</P>
<P>
   ``A lot of people just give up,'' said Lois Siegel, the
community services coordinator for the Senior Resources Department
in Colonie. ``A lot of people get depressed when it's so dark.''
According to the latest state Health Department figures, 15,686 New
Yorkers died in December 1996 and 16,190 New Yorkers died in
January of that year, more than during any other time of the year.
</P>
<P>
   In 1995, the pattern was the same: 16,260 died in January and
15,223 died in December. Across the country, the story is similar.
In January 1996, 220,000 people died. The least deadly month was
August with 176,000 deaths.
</P>
<P>
   Despite those grim numbers, Bordeau believes most people,
especially the elderly, keep winter and all those newspaper obits
in perspective.
</P>
<P>
   ``People tend not to relate it to themselves,'' he said.
``People never quite think it's going to happen to them.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
