<DATE_TIME> 1999-01-08 13:27 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4754 &Cx1f; ttj-z
r l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-COACH-GRADES-HNS &LR;      01-08 0707
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-COACH-GRADES-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
COACH SCORES POINTS WITH MANY EDUCATORS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By MACKENZIE WARREN  
 c.1999 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   RICHMOND, Calif. _ Many San Francisco-area school administrators
were amazed to hear that a basketball coach was willing to risk so
much on the court for so much off it.
</P>
<P>
   Nonetheless, local principals and athletic directors endorse
Richmond High School basketball coach Ken Carter's decision to
forfeit upcoming games until his players start working on their
books as hard as they work on their jump shots.
</P>
<P>
   They hail the coach of the undefeated and highly touted Oilers
for taking a stand on academics in a time when winning at all costs
has become the goal of many.
</P>
<P>
   ``This coach's actions are very appropriate, and I think
expected,'' says Paul Gaddini, commissioner of athletics for the
North Coast Section of the California Interscholastic Federation.
</P>
<P>
   But those expectations may be a bit optimistic. Even Richmond
Principal Haidee Foust-Whitmore admits Carter's timing is strange,
but backs his decision.
</P>
<P>
   All California students competing in CIF-sanctioned sports are
required to meet a minimum grade point average of 2.0, a C-average.
What observers find so unusual in the Richmond case is that all the
players on the team are above that bar.
</P>
<P>
   ``The timing was prompted by the progress reports that come
before grade cards,'' said Linda LaNere, area director of the West
Contra Costa Unified School District, of which Richmond is a part.
</P>
<P>
   ``This sends a clear message to the student-athletes before the
grade cards come out,'' said LaNere, who is in charge of athletic
administration. ``I have a feeling there's going to be a lot of
improvement.''
</P>
<P>
   LaNere, who said she is firmly behind Carter's decision, said,
``It's about time academics came before athletics. This may seem
drastic right now, but participation in sports is a privilege. The
priority certainly is in the classroom.''
</P>
<P>
   Susan Saunders, athletic director at George Washington High
School in the same district, said it's not uncommon for coaches to
set standards for their players that are higher than the
state-mandated minimums. But, she said she's never heard of a coach
taking steps as decisive as Carter's.
</P>
<P>
   ``For the players, they have to realize that they're part of a
team and they have to take responsibility for that,'' said
Saunders, who has coached volleyball, tennis and badminton for nine
years.
</P>
<P>
   Coaches and administrators stress the importance of seeing
athletics as a co-curricular activity meant to complement the
classroom experience, not take precedence over it.
</P>
<P>
   ``Through sports, students learn hard work, discipline and
teamwork,'' said Leo LaRocca, athletic director at San Francisco's
St. Ignatius Prep, home of The Examiner's No. 1-ranked high school
team. ``They have to go together.''
</P>
<P>
   But not every administrator agrees with the Richmond coach's
decision. At Lowell High School, the city's elite public school,
there are no plans to raise the 2.0 standard.
</P>
<P>
   ``We couldn't get away with that,'' said Gloria Bogdanoff,
assistant principal for pupil personnel. ``We already ask our
students to do more than other schools. To change the rule on them
wouldn't be equitable; it would be double-jeopardy.''
</P>
<P>
   Gaddini said CIF uses carrots, not just sticks like the minimum
gpa eligibility rule, to encourage students to concentrate on their
books. He said in the North Coast Section alone, an area that
includes areas north of the Bay to the Oregon line, CIF distributes
20,000 certificates a year to recognize students who either earned
a 3.0 GPA during the season, or were a part of a team with a
collective average of 3.0. He also said students can receive a
one-time probationary exemption from the 2.0 rule if local
officials deem that appropriate.
</P>
<P>
   Often, it's participation in the sports themselves that
encourage better studying habits, administrators said. ``All across
the country, studies have shown that kids do better in school when
they're playing a sport,'' LaRocca said. ``They have to budget
their time, they have more responsibilities. The co-curriculars
really cross over into the classroom.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
