<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TRAVEL-COLUMN-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
INTERNET IS FOR US `DUMMIES,' TOO 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  (For advance Sunday, Jan. 10) 
 
By HARRY SHATTUCK 
c.1998 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Refreshed after the holidays, I tore into the first parcel of
mail as if it were a leftover Christmas present.
</P>
<P>
   The book's title stared me squarely in the face: ``The Complete
Idiot's Travel Guide to Cruise Vacations.''
</P>
<P>
   I opened a second package. Another book: ``Travel Planning
Online for Dummies.''
</P>
<P>
   By now, I was acquiring a complex. What's next? ``Column Writing
for Morons?''
</P>
<P>
   Actually, both publications are volumes within popular series.
``Complete idiots'' also can learn about Walt Disney World, Hawaii,
Europe, New Orleans and other travel destinations. That series is
expected to include about 30 titles within two years. And the ``for
dummies'' books, which cover more than 20 topics, offer a useful
introduction to computers and the Internet.
</P>
<P>
   I did get a chuckle, though, when the back cover of ``Travel
Planning Online for Dummies'' referred to www.dummies.com for
information.
</P>
<P>
   Of course, these books aren't really aimed at ``dummies'' and
``idiots.'' A lot of smart people were _ or are _ slow to embrace
the online revolution (or at least that's what I keep telling
myself each time I become hopelessly tangled on the Web). The ``for
dummies'' series describes its target readership as ``frustrated
computer users who know they aren't really dumb but find that PC
hardware, software and indeed the entire vocabulary of computing
make them feel helpless.''
</P>
<P>
   Travelers can benefit greatly from a basic knowledge of
computers and online procedures for several reasons:
</P>
<P>
   _ The Internet is the fastest-growing source for information
about almost any aspect of a trip.
</P>
<P>
   _ E-mail is often the easiest and most economical form of
communication while away from home.
</P>
<P>
   _ Bargains are available online that don't exist elsewhere.
</P>
<P>
   And none of us is too dumb to appreciate a bargain, right?
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, the biggest travel-related trend I've witnessed in the
past year is the growing curiosity about online services by
individuals who previously were disinterested or _ let's be honest
_ intimidated by this new technology.
</P>
<P>
   I recall the first time I touched on Internet travel sites
during a luncheon gathering with a group of readers. Eyes glazed
over, an epidemic of coughing ensued, and I quickly changed the
subject _ not bothering to confide that I, too, barely understood
the process.
</P>
<P>
   Now, I receive more correspondences and questions about online
travel than any other topic. Rarely does a day pass when someone
doesn't inquire about ``that site where you name your own price for
an airline ticket'' (www.priceline.com; read instructions carefully
before making any commitment).
</P>
<P>
   Cruise lines are capitalizing on this increased thirst for
online knowledge as a lure. When I sailed aboard Celebrity's
Galaxy, passengers could learn on the ship's own Intranet. On the
Crystal Symphony, I joined about 150 fellow travelers who
``enrolled'' in the Computer University at Sea.
</P>
<P>
   Crystal's program, inspired by a suggestion from a frequent
passenger, was inaugurated two years ago and is now almost as
popular as bingo and midnight buffets. Through a relationship with
Compaq, the Crystal Symphony and Crystal Harmony each offers more
than 20 computers for passenger use in a dedicated space.
</P>
<P>
   Passengers pay nothing (beyond the basic cruise fare) to take
hourlong classes that cover basics of computer usage and sending
e-mail. On my cruise, virtually every class was filled to capacity.
Depending on the itinerary, advanced classes are offered.
</P>
<P>
   Passengers also can open an e-mail account and send and receive
messages worldwide for $3. Some expand on their new knowledge after
a voyage and transmit e-mail to the ship.
</P>
<P>
   Seniors are especially attracted to the Computer University at
Sea. ``We knew that a lot of people age 55-60 and older who cruise
with us thought at first that it (computer usage) wasn't relevant
to their lives,'' says Crystal president Joseph A. Watters. ``Then
they realized it wasn't going to go away. Now they want to learn.''
</P>
<P>
   Separate computers are available for staff and crew aboard
Crystal ships. Each crew member is given an e-mail address. ``We've
got 32 nationalities represented, and they've all learned how to
send e-mail home,'' says Watters.
</P>
<P>
   For those on land, the new ``Travel Planning Online for
Dummies'' is the best resource I've seen for pointing the way to
valuable travel-related Internet sites and candidly evaluating
contents.
</P>
<P>
   Vadnai's 330-page book covers not only the standard airline and
hotel Web sites but others that focus on kosher restaurants, home
exchanges, North American road construction, ways to obtain
passports and visas and almost any other topic important to the
traveler. One chapter is devoted to ``chat rooms'' _ a good way to
share information with fellow travelers.
</P>
<P>
   Area bookstores stock or can order ``Travel Planning Online for
Dummies'' (IDG Books, $24.95), ``The Complete Idiot's Travel Guide
to Cruise Vacations'' (Alpha Books/Macmillian, $16.95) by Fran
Wenograd Golden and other books in each series.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-01-08-99 1328EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
