<DOCNO> NYT19990108.0114 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-01-08 13:32 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4760 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-COMPUTER-COLUMN-HNS &LR;      01-08 0820
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-COMPUTER-COLUMN-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FAST PACE OF CHANGE WON'T LET UP IN 1999 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By DWIGHT SILVERMAN 
c.1998 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   In personal computing, change has been the only constant.
Everyone who's enjoyed setting up and running a shiny new PC knows
the feeling when the next generation of technology renders it
obsolete.
</P>
<P>
   And the pace is not going to let up anytime soon. There are many
changes coming in 1999 that will affect both future PC buyers and
current owners in many ways.
</P>
<P>
   Some of them will make you glad you bought a PC recently. Others
will make you wish you'd waited. And others will make it easier to
afford your next machine.
</P>
<P>
   _ Chips, chips and more chips. In late 1996 and early 1997, PC
sales slowed as buyers awaited a highly touted new version of the
Pentium chip from Intel. The processor included some instructions,
dubbed MMX, that purported to speed up multimedia applications.
</P>
<P>
   Intel's legendary marketing machine shot itself in the foot.
Although MMX was a big hit, the hype nuked sales of the non-MMX
Pentium processors.
</P>
<P>
   Now, Intel is in a similar situation. In March, the company will
release a new version of the Pentium II chip, code-named Katmai,
that includes beefed-up MMX features. As with the original MMX,
software will be immediately available that takes advantage of the
Katmai code.
</P>
<P>
   But perhaps a bigger draw is that the first Katmai chips will
run at speeds up to 500 megahertz. While not everyone understands
multimedia instruction sets, everyone does understand that faster
is better.
</P>
<P>
   Intel has been quiet about Katmai, so as not to deep-six current
sales. But savvy PC buyers who want the latest and greatest will
wait to buy until these new chips are available _ apparently in
affordable high-end PCs _ in March.
</P>
<P>
   _ And even more chips. &UR;  &LR; Intel also will be cutting prices on its
processors in a big way. The company will be pushing faster
versions of its low-cost Celeron chips _ new, faster ones were just
released _ and slashing prices on them.
</P>
<P>
   This is to compete with low-cost, high-powered processors aimed
at the consumer market from Advanced Micro Devices and National
Semiconductor/Cyrix. Some analysts are predicting a price war in
the chip arena, which is good news for consumers.
</P>
<P>
   In addition, the introduction of the Katmai processors means
Intel will cut prices on its standard Pentium II chips. There will
be some incredible bargains.
</P>
<P>
   But tempering these plummeting prices will be the fact that
memory chip prices will bottom out, and possibly go up, as demand
matches and then exceeds supply. The same goes for portable PC and
flat-panel displays, as well as traditional monitors.
</P>
<P>
   _ Go faster. It's been a long time coming, but 1999 appears to
be the year when home users finally will have wide access to
Internet connections that are faster than pokey ol' phone lines.
</P>
<P>
   Both cable TV modems and digital telephone lines are expected to
be deployed on a widespread basis, though not necessarily at prices
that everyone can afford. If you want big bandwidth, you'll have to
pay big bucks.
</P>
<P>
   _ Suite wars redux. &UR;  &LR; You may have thought the battle over
productivity software suites was over, with Microsoft's Office the
clear winner.
</P>
<P>
   However, expect the war to reignite this year with new entries
from both Microsoft and Corel, which owns the WordPerfect
franchise. Microsoft will introduce in the second quarter of the
year a major reworking of its suite called Office 2000. Corel's
entry, due also at the end of the second quarter, will be
WordPerfect Office 2000.
</P>
<P>
   Microsoft's suite makes it easier to work collaboratively on a
document, with better tracking of versions and a simplified method
of turning all kinds of documents into Web pages.
</P>
<P>
   Early reviews of beta copies indicate that Corel's WordPerfect
Suite also emphasizes collaboration, and that the applications in
the suite _ which have various origins _ are better integrated. It
also will come with voice recognition software as a standard
feature.
</P>
<P>
   Both suites try to save disk space with a feature that lets you
install components as you need them. For example, if you don't need
the equation editor in Word or WordPerfect, you can leave it out.
Then, if you suddenly need it and try to call it from a menu,
stand-alone PC users will be prompted to insert their installation
CD. On a network, a full installation can be placed on a server and
individual PCs can pull components via the network.
</P>
<P>
   I suspect corporate computer system managers will love this
feature, but those on stand-alone PCs who must keep reinserting
their install CDs to add features will hate it.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
Dwight Silverman can receive electronic mail via the Internet.
Address your comments and questions to
dwight.silverman(at)chron.com, or call (713) 220-2000 and enter
access code 1001. &QL; 
