<SLUG> BC-COMPUTER-HELPLINE-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FAULT LIES NOT WITH YOUR CARD BUT WITH FACTORY-INSTALLED SOUND 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By DWIGHT SILVERMAN 
c.1998 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Q: I play a lot of games on my computer, a Dell Dimension. I had
great success installing a Voodoo 2 graphics card along with my
other card, and I was so happy about it that I went out and got a
Diamond Monster Sound MX300 card. Big mistake! Now I have no sound
at all! What's the problem?
</P>
<P>
   A. Your problem is not that you added a Monster Sound card _
they're pretty amazing, when they are working _ but that you failed
to turn off the existing sound capabilities.
</P>
<P>
   On a Dimension, the sound feature is built onto the main system
board, or the motherboard. That's why, when you put the new sound
card in, you didn't find another one to remove.
</P>
<P>
   The Dimension is not unusual. Many modern PCs have sound built
into the motherboard. But this makes it tricky if you don't know
how to turn off the existing sound feature when you upgrade.
</P>
<P>
   Here's how you do it with your Dell:
</P>
<P>
   First, go into the Device Manager in Windows 95 or 98.
(Right-click on My Computer, choose Properties, then Device
Manager.) Find your sound card under ``Sound, video and game
controllers.'' Delete all the sound-related entries you find there
_ and there may be some that are not sound-related, so be careful.
</P>
<P>
   Then, shut down your system. Install the new card, and turn the
machine back on.
</P>
<P>
   As the system boots up, you'll see a message on the screen that
says ``Hit DEL to enter setup.'' Hit the Delete key _ there will be
a pause, and you'll soon see a menu screen. From here, find the
page that contains the sound settings, and turn onboard sound off.
Save the settings and exit setup.
</P>
<P>
   The system will reboot once more, and when Windows launches and
you get the desktop, you'll be prompted for any driver disks you
may have. After this, the sound should work.
</P>
<P>
   This process should work for most PCs that have onboard sound
that is controlled through the BIOS setup procedure. In some PCs,
you may have to adjust physical jumpers on the motherboard. Check
the manual for your PC or motherboard for more information.
</P>
<P>
   Q: I am thinking about adding a removable mass-storage drive to
my system. I've narrowed it down to either an LS-120 Superdisk or
an Iomega Zip drive. (I was thinking about a SyQuest Sparq drive,
until the company went away.) Can you talk about the pros and cons
of each type of drive?
</P>
<P>
   A: Iomega's Zip drive, while it is not quite as omnipresent as
the traditional floppy drive, is the most common type of
big-megabyte removable device. That means you are going to be most
apt to find others who are also using it if you want to exchange
large data files.
</P>
<P>
   The Zip also is very speedy, at least in its internal EIDE and
SCSI configurations. If you choose the external parallel port
version, it's agonizingly slow.
</P>
<P>
   However, the Zip drive cannot read from or write to traditional,
1.44-megabyte floppy disks. The new, 250-megabyte version of the
Zip, which will be out shortly, will be able to read the original
100-megabyte Zip disks, however.
</P>
<P>
   The LS-120 disk can hold 120 megabytes of data, 20 percent more
than the original Zip. It also is compatible with traditional
floppies, and in fact an LS-120 drive can effectively replace your
floppy drive.
</P>
<P>
   But the LS-120 is slow. Newer models are zippier than older
ones, but they still don't approach the speed of a Zip drive.
</P>
<P>
   You might want to go back and read a story about floppy
alternatives that ran in the Sept. 25 Houston Chronicle Technology
section: www.chron.com/content/chronicle/tech/98/09/25/main.html.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
Got a question about your computer? Dwight Silverman can receive
electronic mail via the Internet. Address your comments and
questions to dwight.silverman(at)chron.com, or call (713) 220-2000
and enter access code 1001. &UR;  &QL; 
 &LR;  &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY &QL;
</P>
