<SLUG> BC-SNOWBOARDING-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SKIING BRANCHES OUT 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By BUZZ GRAY  
 c.1999 Albany Times Union  
<TEXT>
<P>
   ALBANY, N.Y. _ Once, when life was simple and the snow pure,
skiers were romantic daredevils. If they weren't rich and famous,
then they associated with those who were.
</P>
<P>
   It was all so clear cut. Mountains were created for the
privileged to enjoy. Chairlifts were built for the Jean-Claude
Killys to ride. St. Moritz arose with royalty in mind.
</P>
<P>
   The rest of us looked on with confused envy. Those days, even
with their $3 tickets and rope tows for the pathetic paupers, are
gone with the Twelfth of Never.
</P>
<P>
   ``You're still skiing?,'' asked Brad Delano, a student at
Franklin and Marshall University and co-tenant of a high-speed,
detachable quad over the man-made, groomed terrain at Okemo in
Vermont. ``Man, aren't you bored?''
</P>
<P>
   He didn't look clever enough to intend the pun, even though a
snowboard dangled from one of his soft brown, furry boots with the
smart logo.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'd never go back (to skiing). It's too confining.'' Welcome
to the revolution. Going from top to bottom has become as
individualistic as one's goggles.
</P>
<P>
   The day isn't far off when skiers won't even be the majority. If
current trends continue, snowboarders will outnumber skiers on the
slopes within a decade. And that's not counting the freestylers
boogeying to rap on strobe-lighted half pipes at most major
centers.
</P>
<P>
   ``You can really get whacked out on it,'' said Kavin Dupont
about the new park and pipe at Whiteface near Lake Placid.
``Carving turns on the trail doesn't do it for me. I gotta be
catching air and absorbing the good sound vibes.''
</P>
<P>
   Traversing trails is becoming less and less about skiing and
more and more about sliding. Almost every year, somebody comes up
with a new idea on how to get from the summit to base with more
grace. Check out skiboards. They're miniature snow-sliding tools
that feature elements of both traditional skis and snowboards.
</P>
<P>
   ``They're a natural evolution of skiing, snowboarding and
skateboarding,'' said Albany's Jason Levinthal, founder of Line
Skiboards. ``There are no limits.'' One size fits all and they're
easy to adjust for boot sizes. And, unlike skiing, skiboarding can
be picked up in two days or less. They probably resemble inline
skating the most.
</P>
<P>
   ``We see it as yet another way to get people interested in
winter sports without feeling intimidated by snowboarding or
skiing,'' said Al Marino, alpine hardgoods manager at Salomon, a
major manufacturer.
</P>
<P>
   What intimidation? Anyone who has been on the slopes recently
has learned to be surprised at nothing. The person next to you on
the lift or colored gondola with piped-in music is just as likely
to be wearing polyurathene wash tubs as telemark slats with a
five-day growth as moon boots and a walkman.
</P>
<P>
   Throw in Michael Jordan hightops, too, because some downhill
plants are offering rubber routes to adventure.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's been a huge success,'' said Cary Metivier of West
Mountain in Glens Falls about the new enlarged tubing park there.
``You don't need a lot of snow. And people don't have to buy a lot
of expensive equipment.''
</P>
<P>
   Just show up. Pick your pleasure and pay your money. Think of
these mountains as winter amusement parks.
</P>
<P>
   ``Gravity is free,'' said Nancy Oliver, a snowboarder at Jiminy
Peak in the Berkshires. ``I like to think of these places as
transportation centers. They get us to the top and we decide how
we're going to come down.''
</P>
<P>
   Many alpine centers even rent snowshoes for those who like to
bushwhack their way through the routes less traveled. Picture a
bloak grunting his way back to sea level through the woods as some
dude with pierced eyebrows blows by on a board and a prayer.
</P>
<P>
   Times Square comes to the wilderness. Anything goes, including
your sensibilities.
</P>
<P>
   And what about the true skiers, those rakish originals who
spawned the entire industry half a cenutry ago? ``They'll always be
around,'' said Geoff Curtis of Volkl Sport America.
</P>
<P>
   The new shaped skis have made a powerful impact, representing
more than half of current sales.
</P>
<P>
   ``They have been the most significant equipment development
since the introduction of the plastic ski boot,'' Curtis said.
``The reason is simple. They make skiing at any level easier and
more fun.'' Which is what the whole thing is about. Only now,
anything, including your imagination, goes.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
