<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TV-REVIEW-SOPRANO-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`THE SOPRANOS' IS DEADLY FUNNY 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By MARK McGUIRE  
 c.1999 Albany Times Union  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Being a mobster is a tough job. No benefits, no pension, high
risk, a dwindling job market and those pesky Feds with telephoto
lenses. That's not to mention family problems.
</P>
<P>
   Or The Family problems.
</P>
<P>
   This is the world of Anthony ``Tony'' Soprano. The man has
issues _ wife issues, daughter issues, duck issues (too complicated
to explain) and the mother of all mother issues. Plus there are the
hassles that go with being the mob boss of North Jersey.
</P>
<P>
   No wonder he suffers crushing anxiety attacks, takes Prozac and,
rest the soul of Al Capone, sees a shrink. When he is not cracking
skulls, he's cracking up.
</P>
<P>
   There are times you'll crack up, laughing that is, at the new
HBO series, ``The Sopranos'' (Sunday at 9 p.m.). Mix a little Woody
Allen in with a slab of Mario Puzo, and you get this funny/deadly
serious one-hour drama from creator David Chase (``I'll Fly
Away'').
</P>
<P>
   This season the networks went ethnic with the Irish (``To Have
and to Hold,'' ``Trinity,'' ``Costello,'' among others) to mostly
disappointing results. ``The Sopranos'' focuses on New Jersey
Italians, and despite centering on the mob does not settle for a
condescending collection of paesan cliches.
</P>
<P>
   Rather, ``The Sopranos'' (no, there is no singing) joins
powerhouse ``Oz'' in giving HBO a dramatic one-two punch
over-the-air networks should envy.
</P>
<P>
   James Gandolfini (``A Civil Action'') plays the conflicted Tony
Soprano. A ``waste management consultant,'' he pangs for the good
old days of honor and values and omerta in the face of a new time
and breed that does not pay heed to traditions. Forget the foot
soldiers; that's goes for his kids, too.
</P>
<P>
   Soprano is a problem solver. He is the one everyone turns to,
whether it be his wife or his mother or every wise guy in Essex
County. He mostly tries to help _ who but a friend would burn a
buddy's restaurant down without asking? _ but in his complex world
things don't always work out.
</P>
<P>
   Emotionally crumbling, he goes over the line to where no mobster
has gone before: to a psychiatrist. It's a lethal risk (bad guys
don't see head doctors; it's seen as a weakness by rivals), but it
is only in the office of Dr. Jennifer Melfi (Lorraine Bracco, of
``GoodFellas'') that Soprano can let his guard down and his
feelings out.
</P>
<P>
   And he does. Cold-blooded yet sentimental, this is one
compartmentalized guy.
</P>
<P>
   And yet you root for him. He may be a Boss, but he is also a
caring father, son, and husband (despite his infidelities). He is a
lovable lug, except per chance he is bashing you with a lug wrench.
</P>
<P>
   If you are not cheering Tony on, you will be after you seeing
him deal with his mother from hell, played in terrifyingly
realistic fashion by Nancy Marchand (publisher Margaret Pynchon of
``Lou Grant''). Livia Soprano is a mean-spirited, bitter widow who
ladles out daily helpings of guilt with a backhoe. She is the
patron saint of high-maintenance moms.
</P>
<P>
   Other recognizable faces include Michael Imperioli
(``GoodFellas''), the nephew wanting to make his bones, and Edie
Falco (``Oz'') as Soprano's loyal yet defiant wife, Carmela. A
barely recognizable face is newcomer Stevie Van Zandt, who is
making his acting debut after years on stage as the guitarist in
Bruce Springsteen's E Street Band.
</P>
<P>
   The show gets the North Jersey patter down (I should know; I
lived there two years), which is sort of a flatter Brooklyn accent.
And the names and places ring true as well, although in an early
episode a local college is referred to as Glassboro State, even
though it changed its name to Rowan University several years ago.
</P>
<P>
   No matter. It's not a mistake worth killing anybody over.
</P>
<P>
   &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Mark McGuire is the television and radio writer for the Albany
Times Union, P.O. Box 15000, Albany, NY 12212. E-mail:
mmcguire(at)timesunion.com)
</P>
</TEXT>
