<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-01-08 13:54 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4778 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-IMPEACH-LEGAL-BOS &LR;      01-08 1010
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-IMPEACH-LEGAL-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
AS TRIAL BEGINS IN SENATE, PARTIES' INTERESTS FLIP-FLOP 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By ADAM PERTMAN  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Even to many criminal attorneys and law professors well-versed
in legal sleights-of-hand and expedient pretrial maneuvers, these
were an extraordinary pair of flip-flops:
</P>
<P>
   House Republicans, who argued during the impeachment process
that it was not necessary to call witnesses to present a strong
case against President Clinton, now say it is essential. And the
White House, whose lawyers and allies thundered against the House's
lack of live testimony, now are maneuvering mightily to keep Monica
Lewinsky and company from taking the stand.
</P>
<P>
   The changes are plainly rooted in politics. Republicans knew
they could win in the House but think they need help now, while
Democrats want to avoid any surprises that might chip away at the
vote margin that could save the president in the Senate.
</P>
<P>
   But the drama about to unfold in the Senate is a trial as well
as a political event. And legal scholars and trial attorneys warn
that the procedures created in a fusion of partisan and legal
motives could ultimately dictate the outcome for the president _
and help shape history's view of the fairness of the process.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's not really a criminal case or a civil case, so there are
no rules that directly apply,'' said Carol Chase, a former federal
prosecutor who teaches criminal law at Pepperdine University in
California. ``That means they're essentially creating a legal
structure as they go along . . . with obviously large implications
for the short and long terms.''
</P>
<P>
   Norman Zalkind, a criminal defense attorney in Boston, and other
legal specialists said that any agreement to call witnesses _ as
House Republicans, acting as prosecutors, want to do _ would have
the most profound legal impact. That is because, for the first time
in this case, it would open both the president's defenders and
accusers to cross-examination.
</P>
<P>
   ``Cross-examination throws uncertainty into a proceeding,'' said
Lawrence Walsh, the special prosecutor in the Iran-contra case.
``You can smear, you can make a witness look foolish, you can hurt
someone in many ways.''
</P>
<P>
   Most certainly, the presentation of witnesses will extend the
life of a proceeding that most Americans and many politicians in
both parties apparently don't want at all.
</P>
<P>
   And, of course, the questioning of people under oath offers the
opportunity for a surprise twist in a case that has a sustained
record of delivering the unexpected.
</P>
<P>
   ``You have trials all the time in which there's a 99 percent
chance of one verdict, but you still go to trial,'' said Zalkind.
``Why? Because you know something might happen in the middle of the
trial that nobody could have foreseen,'' and that changes its
outcome.
</P>
<P>
   All those interviewed Thursday said that appears to be the
overriding hope of GOP members who favor calling witnesses.
</P>
<P>
   The specialists pointed out that all the material witnesses
already have been questioned and all the key evidence has been
accumulated by the special prosecutor, Kenneth Starr. At the same
time, it seems clear that the Senate's 55-45 split among
Republicans and Democrats all but ensures that there won't be a
two-thirds vote for conviction.
</P>
<P>
   So politically, the House Republicans likely feel compelled to
proceed, at least partly, to underscore that their past efforts
were based on constitutional considerations. Legally, they
presumably want to call witnesses in the hope that something fresh
arises to change the political dynamic.
</P>
<P>
   ``From the House point of view, as things now stand, they're
going to lose . . . so they need to do something,'' said David
Stewart, who represented Walter Nixon when he was impeached and
removed from office as a federal judge in 1989. ``They don't want
to be dismissed as ill-mannered children who didn't know how to
behave on a major constitutional issue.''
</P>
<P>
   F. Dennis Saylor, who was chief of staff at the Justice
Department criminal division under President Bush, pointed to the
negotiations over calling witnesses as a stark example of how
different a Senate trial probably would be from any court
proceeding Americans have ever seen. The fact that the ground rules
are being created on an ongoing basis, he and others said, provides
a preview of things to come.
</P>
<P>
   ``Basically, the Senate can do whatever the Senate chooses to do
at the time it wants to do it,'' said Saylor, now a defense
attorney in Boston. Noting that no other judicial venue exists in
which, for instance, the jury can overrule the judge, he added,
``They will want to look fair, but that's a subjective judgment and
it could be hard . . . since the Senate is going to write the
rules, conduct the trial, and deliver the verdict.''
</P>
<P>
   Nearly all those interviewed agreed on one other potentially
privotal point: that Republicans would be taking a far bigger
gamble than Democrats in opting for a prolonged, witness-filled
trial. On this point, too, they said it was difficult to separate
the political reasons from the legal.
</P>
<P>
   With most Americans telling pollsters they oppose an impeachment
trial, the specialists said, the prospect of a voter backlash would
increase with every day that the trial continued. They added that
the lawyers for the president are seasoned trial attorneys, while
the House members questioning witnesses _ even any with courtroom
backgrounds _ are likely to be rusty.
</P>
<P>
   Finally, the lawyers and scholars said that if the Republicans
don't elicit a giant-killing surprise during witnesses' testimony
and just review widely known information, they risk appearing to
both constituents and historians as partisans willing to use the
Constitution for their own gain.
</P>
<P>
   ``The truth . . . barring a major revelation, is that it really
can't get much worse for the president,'' said Martin Flaherty, a
professor of constitutional law at Fordham University. ``It can get
much, much worse for the Republicans.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
