<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FILM-REVIEW-DEVINE-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`NED DEVINE' IS WORTH THE PRICE OF A LOTTERY TICKET 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By AMY BIANCOLLI  
 c.1999 Albany Times Union  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Not to scare you off, but naked old men on motorcycles figure
prominently in ``Waking Ned Devine.'' So does a days-old corpse.
And dentures. And pig stench, which has nothing to do with the
corpse.
</P>
<P>
   But before you plunk down money for the cuddly ``Patch Adams,''
consider this: ``Waking Ned Devine'' is a puckish little pleasure,
a movie so adamantly (and, most of the time, successfully)
sweet-natured that you all but forget the twisted amorality at its
core. Even a climax of outrageous mean-spiritedness comes across as
a bit of Irish whimsy.
</P>
<P>
   Written and directed by Kirk Jones, who made his mark with
British television commercials, ``Ned'' is reminiscent of Bill
Forysth's ``Local Hero,'' the flaky 1983 tale about a wee Scottish
town that bands against an American oil executive.
</P>
<P>
   ``Waking Ned Devine'' is set in a wee Irish town, and the
stuffed-shirt visitor is a Dublin lottery official rather than an
arrogant Yank. But the idea's the same: a bunch of country-mice
locals put their noggins together to outwit a city-mouse outsider,
mining gentle chuckles along the way.
</P>
<P>
   The film opens endearingly, with a mock-cosmic commentary on
lotteries and the ``lucky sods'' who win them. The camera then
turns on the twinkly Jackie O'Shea (Ian Bannen, later transformed
into one the naked bikers mentioned above), who clutches a lottery
ticket as numbered ping-pong balls swirl on the TV before him.
</P>
<P>
   He doesn't win, but someone he knows apparently does _ the
winning ticket is tracked to the Irish village of Tullymore,
population 52.
</P>
<P>
   Jackie, his wife (a fiesty Fionnula Flanagan) and best friend
Michael (David Kelly, imperturbable and chicken-like) become
obsessed with finding the winner. They think they might wangle
their way into the good graces of a millionaire.
</P>
<P>
   Early suspects include a marmish shopkeeper and Finn, the
resident pig farmer (``I've brought you some expensive fruity
soaps,'' says Jackie to the odiferous young man), who spends a
minor subplot pining for the village beauty.
</P>
<P>
   Eventually, they find the winner: Ned Devine, ``the sweetest
soul as ever was blessed,'' who is, unfortunately, dead. It seems
he died from the shock of winning; Jackie finds him, ticket in
hand, a smile spread wide on his rigor mortis face. Several comic
moments, some involving dentures, emerge from interaction with the
corpse.
</P>
<P>
   It isn't giving away much to say that Jackie and Michael resolve
to cash in the winning ticket, that Michael assumes Ned's identity
to fool the visiting ``Lotto Man'' (Brendan F. Dempsey, suitably
gummy), or that their ruse is fraught with delightfully funny
mishaps.
</P>
<P>
   As the Official Cute Irish Movie of the season, there's an
inevitable, aww-shucks adorability to it all, even when a cloud of
blackness _ they're stealing money from a dead guy _ threatens to
encroach on the light. ``Oh, Lord, this is gettin' awful serious,''
says Jackie, contemplating prison.
</P>
<P>
   Not for long. There isn't much room for serious drama _ you
can't have that, and geriatric vehicular nudity and pigs and a
leading man (i.e., Bannen) who looks like Smokey the Bear with a
pint of Guinness.
</P>
<P>
   Even the romantic sub-plot entwining the smelly Finn (James
Nesbitt) and his dark-maned Maggie (Susan Lynch) is blissfully free
of glop; their big moments are discourses on personal hygiene
(``I've been usin' some fruity soaps, Maggie'').
</P>
<P>
   In a film about the giddy side of fraud, that's about as earnest
as it gets.
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Amy Biancolli is the film critic for the Albany Times Union,
P.O. Box 15000, Albany, NY 12212. E-mail:
abiancolli(at)timesunion.com.)
</P>
</TEXT>
