<P>
   Entertainment and culture stories from The N.Y. Times News
Service for Saturday, Jan. 9.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; IDEAS PAGE &LR;
</P>
<P>
   `Cold War' Series on CNN
</P>
<P>
   On Sunday night, CNN will begin broadcasting the second half of
its 24-part documentary series ``Cold War.'' The first half has
already brought several angry critiques from historians and
commentators over how it interprets the Cold War and how it assigns
blame.
</P>
<P>
   The Times asked three historians with different perspectives to
assess the series:
</P>
<P>
   TV-COLDWAR-RADOSH (Undated) _ An appraisal of the CNN ``Cold
War'' series by Ronald Radosh, co-author of ``The Amerasia Spy
Case: Prelude to McCarthyism'' and ``The Rosenberg File,'' a Senior
Research Associate at the Center for Communitarian Policy Studies,
George Washington University. While he says that overall the series
does a good job of portraying the evils of the Soviet system
compared with the democratic Western allies, he argues that it too
often equates the Soviet Union's moral failings with those of the
United States. (1100 words)
</P>
<P>
   TV-COLDWAR-GARDNER (Undated) _ An appraisal of the CNN ``Cold
War'' series by Lloyd Gardner, who teaches history at Rutgers
University and is the author most recently of ``Pay Any Price:
Lyndon Johnson and the Wars for Vietnam'' (Ivan C. Dee, 1995). He
questions just how inevitable the Cold War was as well as the
series' European focus. (1150 words)
</P>
<P>
   TV-COLDWAR-GADDIS (Undated) _ An appraisal of the CNN ``Cold
War'' series by John Lewis Gaddis, who teaches history at Yale
University and is most recently the author of ``We Now Know:
Rethinking Cold War History'' (Oxford University Press, 1997). He
was a consultant to CNN on the three-year project and gives an
insider's account of putting together a documentary of this scope,
arguing that the series explores the era's moral ambiguities
without asserting any moral equivalency. (1000 words)
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Other Culture and Entertainment &LR;
</P>
<P>
   TV-PURGATORY-REVIEW (Undated) _ Sunday on TNT, ``Purgatory.'' a
TV film. Reviewed by Anita Gates.
</P>
<P>
   TV-MURDER-REVIEW (Undated) _ Sunday on A&AMP;E, ``Murder in a Small
Town.'' Reviewed by Ron Wertheimer.
</P>
