<HEADER>
A4784 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u k &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-NYHAN-COLUMN-BOS &LR;      01-08 0864
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NYHAN-COLUMN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SUN   BELT SENATORS PLAY DANGEROUS GAMES 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By DAVID NYHAN  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   For those in the Northeast who are aghast at the rolling coup
unfolding in Washington, the prospect of President Clinton being
driven from power by a consortium of right-wing Sun Belt
Republicans is a nasty shock.
</P>
<P>
   We've heard for two decades the demographers' dirge, that
population, wealth, and influence were drifting south and west to
the sun. But after six years of unrelenting effort by the
Republican Party's right wing to overturn Clinton's election, the
Northeast is hunkering down in the White House bunker with Bill &AMP;
Hillary. Save for two GOP conservatives from New Hampshire, the
odd-state-out in the region, there appear to be no senators from
Maine to New Jersey who will cast their lot with the oust-Clinton
cabal. All it takes is 37 senators to say ``no,'' and Clinton
remains in office for his last two years.
</P>
<P>
   And while the 100 senators parade before the cameras in gravest
mien, vowing sober-sided examination of all the issues from all the
angles, it is difficult to imagine any Northeasterner not from New
Hampshire knuckling under to the Republican impeachment chorus
baying from south and west.
</P>
<P>
   At risk almost to the same degree as Clinton's imperiled
presidency is the future of the Republican Party in the Northeast,
where substantial gains in governorships in the past decade
(Massachusetts, New York, New Jersey, Connecticut, Rhode Island) by
Republicans have not been matched in Senate elections. The GOP has
been a party of the Sun Belt since Nixon, whose choice as Supreme
Court head, William Rehnquist, presides over the Senate trial.
Nixon's infamous Southern strategy cracked the formerly Democratic
south in the 1968 election, driving most black votes to Democrats,
and most white voters into the GOP column for federal elections.
</P>
<P>
   Until the little-known backbencher Dennis Hastert of Illinois
was elected speaker of the House Wednesday, nine out of 10 GOP
leaders in the two branches hailed from Southern or Western states,
where Clinton is unpopular, the religious right controls the party
machinery, and right-wing clergymen and talk-show hosts exercise
broad sway. The House right-wingers, who refused to call witnesses
themselves, now demand the Senate do what the House, for political
and tactical reasons, chose not to do.
</P>
<P>
   Only three congressmen from New England voted for impeachment,
Representatives Sununu and Bass from, you guessed it, New
Hampshire, and Nancy Johnson of Connecticut. For any or all, that
vote may be a career-ender.
</P>
<P>
   Now coming under the kind of fierce pressure that may guarantee
strong and well-financed challenges to their own political survival
are the four moderate Republican senators from New England.
Senators Olympia Snowe and Susan Collins of Maine. Jim Jeffords of
Vermont and John Chafee of Rhode Island, are caught between a rock
(public opinion against impeachment) and a hard place (Senate
Majority Leader Trent Lott). All but Collins are up next year.
</P>
<P>
   Senators Judd Gregg and Bob Smith of New Hampshire are for
impeachment. But it is very hard to see any New England Democrat,
or New York's Moynihan and Schumer, or New Jersey's Torricelli and
Lautenberg, voting to convict.
</P>
<P>
   Lott's reputation as a weak and ineffective leader of what is
hilarously self-titled as ``the world's greatest deliberative
body'' seems to be justified. As of noon Thursday, Lott was unable
to locate the center of gravity needed to structure a deal to
censure Clinton.
</P>
<P>
   The right-wingers intimidated Lott. In an audacious display of
dictating terms to the once-lordly Senate, the anti-Clinton gang of
Sun Belt conservatives in the House has muscled Lott and his, to
put it too kindly, followers putting him on notice that nothing
short of a full-blown trial with lots of witnesses will suffice.
</P>
<P>
   Never in this century has the once-proud Senate been horsed
around by such a collection of clucks and congressional claghorns.
Lott's unctuous protestations about proceeding with ``decency and
dignity'' do not mask his impotence. Lott was unable to muster the
gumption to face down his Sun Belt backers. By caving in to the
Clinton-killers, he sets those New England moderates up as targets.
</P>
<P>
   The New Hampshire pair aside, not till you get to Pennsylvania,
and GOP Senators Arlen Spector and Rick Santorum of Pennsylvania,
do you find Republicans ready to remove Clinton. Of 19 GOP senators
up for re-election next year, 13 are from states Clinton won.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton will never be on the ballot again, but his ghost may
haunt these Northeast Republicans when next they face the voters.
Those who go under will have Trent (Thanksa) Lott to thank for
their demise. But he may not be majority leader two years from this
week. Given the GOP's poll ratings, the Republicans can lose the
Senate as well as the House next time around.
</P>
<P>
   The Sun Belt senators are in the driver's seat, but they risk
taking the GOP's fragile 10-seat majority right over the cliff into
voter fury.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (David Nyhan is a Globe columnist.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
