<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-01-08 13:56 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4787 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u k &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-MCGRORY-COLUMN-BOS &LR;      01-08 0820
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MCGRORY-COLUMN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LIVING SIMPLY, AND COMPLETELY 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By BRIAN MCGRORY  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ It's been 50 years since Mr. Wai Y. Tye arrived at
South Station, 50 years since he found himself in Boston with no
place to go, no one to see, nothing to do, 50 years since he
wandered up Huntington Avenue in search of a place to hang his hat
and came across the hulking structure that was and is the YMCA.
</P>
<P>
   Mr. Tye planned to stay in the small, spare room for a few days,
maybe a couple of weeks. Instead, he got comfortable. He got his
bearings. He got a well-paying job.
</P>
<P>
   And he stayed. He stayed for the Truman administration, then
Dwight Eisenhower's presidency. He stayed for the social upheaval
of the 1960s, which turned into the 1970s, and by then, why move,
so Mr. Tye stayed for the '80s, which led to the '90s. This marks
his 50th year at the Y.
</P>
<P>
   Asked for an explanation, Mr. Tye, 82 years old now, flashes
that easy smile of his and says, ``It's convenient to town.''
</P>
<P>
   And for that, for his resistance to materialism, Mr. Tye is an
American anomaly. In a society obsessed with wealth and the
accoutrements that go with it, he continues to live in a drab
200-square-foot room with exposed pipes, a linoleum floor, a single
bed and a dim overhead light, even though he could afford so much
more. He has found a home in the most unlikely of places _ a YMCA,
which by its very nature, is meant for those passing through.
</P>
<P>
   But don't accuse Mr. Tye of being crazy. He is college educated,
a chemist by training. For 32 years, he worked for Raytheon, rising
steadily through the ranks. He played tennis with the company
president at exclusive clubs, then returned home to his room at the
Y. He packed an auditorium at his retirement gala in 1982, then
returned home to his room at the Y. He has traveled abroad, to
Paris, to Singapore, to Bali, then headed from Logan Airport to his
room at the Y.
</P>
<P>
   Why? Well, Mr. Tye doesn't need much. Sitting in his room on an
institutional-quality chair, wearing striped pants, a muted,
patterned shirt, a cardigan sweater and slippers, he is nothing if
not proud. His hair, still black, is carefully combed. His teeth
are unusually straight, his hands folded in his lap. His English is
just shy of perfect.
</P>
<P>
   ``When you're busy working and playing tennis, when you come
home, you don't have much time to take care of an apartment,'' he
says. ``There was no objection, so I just kept staying on.''
</P>
<P>
   So simple, but so complete, like his life. He pays $90 a week
for his unrenovated room. The bathrooms and showers are down the
hallway, the sinks so old they're stained by paint and time, and
all of that is just fine. The kitchen is the other way, though he
prefers to use an ancient Corning hot plate in his room. He has two
small closets, one more than he needs. His most prized possession
is an old Smith-Corona manual typewriter, which he uses each day to
compile notes from science journals.
</P>
<P>
   When you're 82, so much has inevitably come and so much has
gone, and Mr. Tye can be excused for harking back to the glory days
of the Y. It used to have an outing club in full force, with
canoeing trips to New Hampshire and hikes to Vermont. And it used
to have a drama club that sponsored plays and Mr. Tye would work
the stage lights. But no more.
</P>
<P>
   These days, the Y's overnight rooms are used more by formerly
homeless men looking for a new start or by families trying to break
the bonds of state assistance. Mr. Tye, known and loved by the
staff, prefers to just close the door to his room and read the many
medical journals that come in the mail each month to keep abreast
of his field, then sit at his typewriter and catalog what he has
learned. He waits for science programs to appear on Channel 2, and
has an eager appetite for the nightly news.
</P>
<P>
   He has traveled the world to make this tiny room his home. Born
in Boston of Malaysian and Chinese parents who had come to attend
MIT, his father drowned off the Cape when Mr. Tye was 2 years old,
and his mother took him back to Asia. He went to school in England,
grew tired of the postwar rationing and boarded a Dutch passenger
ship for the states in 1949. He chose Boston because it was what he
knew, even if he really didn't know it at all. He never married,
and he has no regrets.
</P>
<P>
   Actually, in the twilight of his life, he doesn't seem to regret
anything. He loved his work, he loved his tennis before arthritis
caused him to give it up, and he loves his home.
</P>
<P>
   ``Nothing's perfect,'' he says with a smile, looking around his
room, from the stained walls to the scratched counter that is his
desk. And as his visitor leaves down the long, dank hall to the
elevator, Mr. Tye clicks his door quietly shut, returning to his
own good fortune.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(Brian McGrory is a columnist with The Boston Globe.)
</P>
</TEXT>
