<SLUG> BC-MOVIE-THIN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MALICK DRAWS A DETACHED `THIN RED LINE' 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JAY CARR  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
THE THIN RED LINE 
Written and directed by: Terrence Malick (based on James Jones'
novel) 
Starring: Sean Penn, Adrien Brody, Jim Caviezel, Ben CXhaplin,
George Clooney, John Cusack, Woody Harrelson, Elias Koteas, Nick
Nolte, John C. Reilly, Larry Romano, John Savage, John Travolta,
Arie Verveen 
Running time: 170 minutes 
Rated: R (realistic war violence and language) 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Much has been made of the 20-year gap between Terrence Malick's
last film, ``Days of Heaven,'' and his long-gestating war epic,
``The Thin Red Line.'' Remarkably, though, it's as if Malick has
never been away. ``The Thin Red Line'' seems to take up where
``Days of Heaven'' left off. That film, which began in a Chicago
slum, then moved to a wheat field and stayed there, seemed mostly
to amount to a screenful of cinematography so gorgeous it became
idyllic as the characters became part of the scenery. ``The Thin
Red Line'' demonstrates that Malick hasn't lost his knack for
impressive visuals, although he still has trouble summoning
emotional or visceral immediacy.
</P>
<P>
   It's not for lack of trying. The conception at work in ``The
Thin Red Line'' is grand enough. Malick, following the lead of
James Jones's novel, wants to inscribe an intimate epic, giving the
battle scenes their jolting due, but alternating them with what's
going on in the minds and hearts and memories of the soldiers.
Those thoughts are expressed in voice-overs, when the soldiers are
not killing or being killed by the dug-in Japanese troops they're
attacking on the island of Guadalcanal during World War II. Beyond
that, Malick wants to introduce an anthropological dimension,
starting with an Edenic prologue that shows the gentle Melanesian
way of life before the invaders' firepower shreds it.
</P>
<P>
   But where James's unruly novel stuck our noses into the
experience of war, Malick's film is more standoffish and
self-conscious. It's detached where Jones was down and dirty. What
saves it from declining into the first big-screen World War II art
movie is the quality of some of the performances. Sean Penn is
especially arresting as the tough but controlled first sergeant who
keeps himself and his troops alive by focusing on the task at hand
and maintaining discipline. ``In this world, a man ain't nothing by
himself,'' he says, ``and there ain't nothing but this world.''
He's talking to Jim Caviezel's hillbilly sharpshooter, a character
who can't quite support the job the film lays on him of serving as
Christ-like spiritual beacon from the moment he replies, ``I've
seen another world.''
</P>
<P>
   Furthermore, he drags Penn's character into cliche by turning
him into the other end of a sacred-vs.-profane equation. In
contrast with ``Saving Private Ryan,'' which set a new standard for
invasion scenes with its D-day landing sequence, this film
deliberately begins quietly. The hell doesn't start breaking loose
until the rifle company has moved inland and happens upon a
Japanese bunker dug into a grassy hilltop. But as intense as the
sequence is, it, too, is beset by cliches, especially the one
involving a clash between a bitter, passed-over colonel (Nick
Nolte) who doubts his own manhood and tries to cover for it with
bluster and a sensitive but pragmatic captain (Elias Koteas) who
resists a frontal-attack order he sees as suicidal.
</P>
<P>
   The film gains a lot from the obvious commitment of the actors,
who throw themselves into their work and project something like
relief at being able to spend themselves on a project they believe
has stature and importance. There's more eloquence in one of Adrien
Brody's worried looks than in anything Malick's script gives him to
say, to give only one example of the way intention keeps outrunning
achievement here. It's not always apparent whose reverie we're
listening to in a given voice-over, although we quickly enough
identify Ben Chaplin as the private who stays sane with gossamer
memories of his pretty wife _ intended as contrast, one guesses,
with the way Nolte's neck veins seem ready to burst as he
apoplectically orders the troops to assault the hill no matter what
the cost.
</P>
<P>
   There certainly are things to admire about ``The Thin Red
Line,'' including Malick's ambition to transcend the usual war
movie by bravely making the combat share screen time with the
combatants' interior monologues. But their distribution among a
handful of insufficiently differentiated voices calls attention to
the film's lack of narrative coherence. While it may be argued that
the film's scattered flavor echoes the chaos and confusion of war,
it comes at a certain price in dramatic potency. So does Malick's
tendency to go overboard with close-ups of tropical birds or leaves
or fronds in the lush vegetation being shredded by the shells and
bullets.
</P>
<P>
   To be fair, Malick doesn't always sentimentalize nature,
although he does stay heavy-handed. When Penn's survivor says,
``War don't ennoble men, it turns them into dogs,'' sure enough, we
recall a vignette of wild dogs chewing on bullet-riddled corpses.
In short, Malick conceived a film that has lit a fire under a lot
of first-rate actors. But then he keeps getting in its way with
cliched exchanges, sophomoric philosophizing, and visuals that
appear an end in themselves, extraneous to the story. ``The Thin
Red Line'' seems, finally, to be a screenful of the ingredients of
a great film, rather than the great film into which they could have
been forged.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
