<SLUG> BC-TV-WB-NETWORK-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
IN A VOLATILE YEAR, THE WB SOARS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By DON AUCOIN  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   PASADENA, Calif. _ For the surging WB network, these are the
best of times and potentially the most risky of times.
</P>
<P>
   From the standpoint of ratings and sheer buzz, the WB is on an
indisputable roll. For the second year in a row, the WB ranks as
the top-rated network among teenagers, and can boast the most
talked-about (and satirized) new show, ``Felicity.''
</P>
<P>
   Moreover, during a season that has ranged from dismal to
catastrophic for the other networks, the WB has increased its
audience, largely on the strength of teen-oriented shows like
``Felicity,'' ``Buffy the Vampire Slayer'' (which made it onto many
TV critics' list of the 10 best shows) and ``Dawson's Creek,''
along with two of the top-rated shows among African-American
viewers, ``The Steve Harvey Show'' and ``The Jamie Foxx Show.''
</P>
<P>
   But will the momentum last? The programming whiz who helped
develop the WB into the force it has become, former entertainment
president Garth Ancier, is leaving the network soon and widely
expected to take his Midas touch to NBC. Can his replacement,
Susanne Daniels, fill his shoes? Teen viewers are notoriously
fickle; will they still want to slosh around in the soapy suds of
``Dawson's Creek'' at this time next year? And can the WB grow from
a larger viewer base as steadily as it did from a small one?
</P>
<P>
   Not surprisingly, the answers to those questions Thursday were
yes, yes, and yes, from Jamie Kellner, the WB's founder and top
executive.
</P>
<P>
   In an appearance before TV critics gathered here for their
annual midwinter meeting, Kellner wore the look of a man holding a
winning hand. The network he founded just four years ago is hot,
and he didn't mind calibrating its temperature as precisely and as
often as he could.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're now attracting some of the brightest minds in the
creative community, who now want to work at this funky little
network,'' Kellner proclaimed.
</P>
<P>
   However, one of that community's brightest minds, Ancier, is
moving on, apparently to try to work his magic at NBC, the onetime
front-runner whose fortunes have faltered this season. And WB
executives Thursday got a taste of the hotter spotlight now shining
on the network when critics, in an echo of the rap on ``Seinfeld''
and ``Friends,'' demanded to know why there are so few minority
characters in ``Zoe, Duncan, Jack &AMP; Jane,'' a new sitcom set in New
York City. Another wanted to know why so many WB shows are about
teenagers having, or at least talking about having, sex.
</P>
<P>
   But Kellner, who built the Fox network with the help of
hot-button shows like ``Married With Children'' before founding the
WB network, made clear that his network will not shy away from
controversy. Daniels, for her part, seemed to invite it.
</P>
<P>
   ``We hope for some boycotting,'' she said. ``It's good for a
network. We need more boycotting.'' Seated next to her, Kellner
chuckled and said approvingly, ``She's so feisty.''
</P>
<P>
   Kellner made a point of championing his new entertainment
president, a Harvard graduate who formerly held the number two
position and has been called one of the most powerful women in
entertainment by The Hollywood Reporter.
</P>
<P>
   ``Susanne Daniels in 10 years is going to be the most important
programmer in the business,'' he said. ``I have incredible
confidence in her.''
</P>
<P>
   If recent history is any guide, Daniels is going to need that
kind of support. It has been a volatile year for those who pick
prime-time lineups for a living. As NBC began to slump, longtime
entertainment president Warren Littlefield stepped aside. The next
to go was Fox entertainment president Peter Roth. The ground has
shifted so rapidly that ABC's Jamie Tarses, considered doomed just
two years ago, now holds seniority among network programmers.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's always hard to develop a hit show,'' said Daniels, who is
married to Greg Daniels, executive producer of Fox's ``King of the
Hill.'' ``It's about taking chances and investing in good
writers.''
</P>
<P>
   Ancier, who opted in September not to renew his WB contract
(though he will be an ``executive consultant'' till spring) is
leaving the network in good shape. The WB was up 13 percent in the
number of viewers from November 1997 to November 1998. By contrast,
NBC and CBS were each down 8 percent, ABC dropped 5 percent, Fox
dipped 4 percent, and the UPN network plummeted 39 percent. At the
beginning of 1998, the WB and UPN, the two upstart networks, were
still considered rivals; by year's end,the WB had beaten UPN in the
ratings 51 out of 52 weeks.
</P>
<P>
   Responding to questions about pinning his hopes on teenagers,
Kellner pointed out that half of the WB's viewers are ages 18 to
49, meaning that many adults watch the teen-oriented shows on the
WB. But he insisted that the WB's identity as a young person's
network will not change, casting it as both a programming
philosophy and a business strategy in an era of fragmented
viewership.
</P>
<P>
   ``If it's going to be a fragmented marketplace, make sure the
fragment you're hanging onto is the most valuable to advertisers,''
Kellner said. ``Our goal is to remain with a median age under 30.
That is a long-term set-in-stone goal for this network.''
</P>
<P>
   On the matter of teen lust, WB-style, Kellner maintained that
the network's shows are simply striving for realism, while being
``careful and responsible'' as well. (He noted that Dawson, of
``Dawson's Creek,'' has steadfastly remained a virgin). On the
question of diversity on ``Zoe, Duncan, Jack &AMP; Jane,'' creators and
stars of the show, which debuts Jan. 17, said that future episodes
will incorporate minority characters.
</P>
<P>
   The network overall cannot be fairly accused of overlooking
diversity. In addition to ``The Steve Harvey Show'' and ``The Jamie
Foxx Show,'' the programs rated first and second among
African-American viewers, the network has also aired other shows
aimed at black audiences such as ``The Wayans Bros.'' and ``The
Parent 'Hood.''
</P>
<P>
   As for ``Felicity,'' which was hilariously lampooned recently in
a skit on Fox's ``Mad TV'' called ``Intensity,'' it is about to
acquire a lighter, less earnest tone, according to Daniels.
</P>
<P>
   In the past year, the WB has expanded its lineup and its number
of local affiliates.
</P>
<P>
   As for the WB's goals, Kellner said he wants the network to pull
in more male viewers and develop more family shows. One offbeat
family show the network showcased Thursday is ``Movie Stars,'' a
sitcom to premiere this spring about the home life of movie stars
played by Harry Hamlin of ``L.A. Law'' fame and Jennifer Grant.
</P>
<P>
   Grant knows a thing or two about movie-star households: She is
the daughter of Cary Grant and Dyan Cannon.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
