<SLUG> BC-BEAM-COLUMN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BEATING A PATH AWAY FROM THE FREEDOM TRAIL 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By ALEX BEAM  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   The Literary Trail, the first of several pre-millennial
``theme'' trails aimed at making Boston a more visitor-friendly
tourist destination, will open for business in the spring. The
trail is the brainchild of the Boston History Collaborative, a
year-old alliance of corporations (including Liberty Mutual,
BankBoston, the Don Law Co.), historians (Brandeis's David Hackett
Fischer, Northeastern's Richard Freeland), and city types (Pat
Moscaritolo, Tom O'Brien, et al.). ``The goal is to make Boston's
history more fun and fascinating while keeping to our
preservationist tradition,'' explains collaborative director Robert
Krim.
</P>
<P>
   The sense among the downtown types is that the 45-year-old
Freedom Trail _ even the ``new, improved'' Freedom Trail, and its
latter-day brand extensions, e.g., the Women's Heritage Trail _ is
getting old. So the collaborative is cooking up several new tours,
like the Maritime Trail, the Immigrant Trail, and the Innovation
Trail (did you know the microwave oven was invented here?) to suck
visitors into and around the city that Oliver Wendell Holmes
called, without apparent irony, ``the Hub of the solar system.''
</P>
<P>
   The Literary Trail sounds like plenty of fun. It will start out
near the Omni Parker House (Charles Dickens slept here), then swing
over to the Boston Athenaeum (many an Atlantic Monthly editor slept
here). Ticknor &AMP; Fields, a precursor of publisher Houghton Mifflin,
where executives still call Henry Wadsworth Longfellow ``our
author,'' was domiciled nearby.
</P>
<P>
   Trailees then board a trolley for Cambridge (World's Greatest
University, Longfellow, et al.) and on to Concord, to stare at the
Japanese tourists mobbing the Louisa May Alcott house. Emerson;
Thoreau; Hawthorne; the dotty, absurd Bronson Alcott; to say
nothing of mystery writer Kate Flora and bodybuilding scribe Miriam
Nelson. They're breathing literature out there in Concord.
</P>
<P>
   The tours will start up on Saturdays and Sundays in March. The
round trip from the Parker House will take about 4 1/2 hours, and
cost $19. More information is available at 617-574-5950, or at the
Web site that I am assured will be ready by early next week:
www.lit-trail.org.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
----- &QC; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   My new best friend, lawyer-at-large Harvey Silverglate, has been
pestering me: a) to promote his recently published book, and b) to
mention the untimely demise of one of his favorite Harvard Square
bookstores, McIntyre &AMP; Moore. Ix-nay on item a, Harvey. Maybe if
you had refrained from calling me a ``bigot'' a few weeks ago, your
request might have carried more weight. (Yes, I accept your
apology.) But I did wander down to used booksellers McIntyre &AMP;
Moore, lured in part by their press release, which said theirs was
``probably the first closing in Harvard Square that is not due to
increasing rent but because Harvard Square is getting boring.''
</P>
<P>
   Co-owners Dan Moore and Mike McIntyre both remember when the
square had five used bookstores, of the kind that tend to spring up
around major universities: Pangloss, Starr, Cambridge Scholarly
Books, the Bookcase, and Temple Bar Books, in addition to M&AMP;M.
Since 1983, all of them except Starr have closed down. As things
go, M&AMP;M is lucky. It was between leases with its landlord, WGU, and
found a larger, cheaper space up in Davis Square, which still
retains a modicum of the funk once associated with the Harvard
area.
</P>
<P>
   There are those who blame the Gap-ification of the square on the
WGU real-estate arm, Harvard Planning and Real Estate.
(Headquartered directly upstairs from M&AMP;M, by the way.) But Moore
and McIntyre said Harvard was an OK landlord. M&AMP;M got five-year
leases, with moderately beneath-market rates. Moore said Harvard
helped out Pangloss before it went out of business. After
considerable squawking from the likes of Seamus Heaney,
photographer Elsa Dorfman, and others, Harvard has cut several rent
breaks for the Grolier Poetry Book Shop, one of only two all-poetry
bookshops in the country.
</P>
<P>
   But there is no denying that all the rents in the square are
rising, and, as McIntyre says, ``if someone pays a lot of rent they
can't afford to be interesting.''
</P>
<P>
   (Alex Beam's e-mail address is beam(at)globe.com)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-01-08-99 1404EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990108.0131 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-01-08 14:06 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4808 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-MUSIC-ROCK-BOS &LR;      01-08 1051
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MUSIC-ROCK-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WAYNE KRAMER: ROCK 'N ROLL SURVIVOR 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JIM SULLIVAN  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   As pedigrees go, you can't beat Wayne Kramer's:
Guitarist-songwriter with the incendiary proto-punk/metal band of
the late '60s/early '70s, the MC5. But, as Joey Ramone sang in
``Rock and Roll High School,'' ``I don't care about history/That's
not where I wanna be.''
</P>
<P>
   Says Kramer: ``The fact is: It's great to be recognized for the
work you've done and I'm proud to have been a member of the MC5. It
was one of the greatest rock bands of all time. But the legend
business don't pay all that well. It has not left me independently
wealthy. My favorite record is the one I'm gonna make.''
</P>
<P>
   Kramer has seen a revitalization of his career during the '90s.
The nadir came in the late-'70s, when he spent more than two years
in prison for dealing cocaine, or, as he puts it, ``trying to make
a lot of money in the party-favors business, which I wasn't very
good at.'' The upside of jail?
</P>
<P>
   ``It probably saved my life. The road I was on, I probably
wouldn't have lived much longer. It plucked me out of a negative
situation. It was one of those wake-up calls, where I would wake
(in jail) and look out at the freeway, the same freeway we used to
travel during the MC5 days, in Detroit. And I remember then,
looking at the prison saying, `I've done stupid (stuff), but never
enough to be in there.' Yo, bro! Word to the brother. There was a
lot of self-examination. What led me to that point?''
</P>
<P>
   While jailed, Kramer was feted by the Clash (``Jail Guitar
Doors'') and the Patti Smith Group (``Free Wayne Kramer''), and
cited as a seminal influence by many a punk band. As he was leaving
prison, he got a boost from Elvis Costello's manager Jake Riviera,
who peddled a limited edition Kramer demo disc in England, netting
him $3,000 _ enough to start him on the road back. Since, then he's
recorded four albums _ the latest a live disc called ``LLAMF'' _
and he's not shy about drawing from his experience. ``Count Time''
is about that period on the inside. ``Junkie Romance'' refers to
his days with the notorious late junkie guitarist Johnny Thunders
in the band Gang War and the junkie myth. Sings Kramer: ``So you
wanna look like Johnny?/And you wanna act like Keith?/And you crave
some soft cocoon boy/For your Charlie Parker kind of grief.'' It's
a grim, gritty, powerful ballad.
</P>
<P>
   ``I wanted to deal with the dope scene/musician issue,'' Kramer
says, who's been drug-free for 11 years, ``but not to continue to
romanticize it, and the best way to do it was just hit it right on
the head. This is a myth in rock 'n' roll, that shooting dope makes
you sexy or a better guitar player. All it does it is make you
broke, annoy all your friends, get you kicked out of your
apartment, and make you sick. I'm trying to tell the truth.''
</P>
<P>
   No, Kramer is not a taciturn chap. In ``Bad Seed,'' he sings,
with sarcasm dripping, ``Zero tolerance?/Let the bastard bleed/No
big thing/'cause he's just a bad seed.'' In ``Something Broken in
the Promised Land,'' he crafts an anthemic rocker in the
Springsteen mode where ``the dream is sold out in the promised
land.'' Kramer likes to call the music he's making _ mostly hard
rock with speedy riffs, with an occasional foray into free jazz _
music for adults.
</P>
<P>
   ``The ideas I'm presenting are fundamental, humanist thoughts.
The things I care about are grown-up concerns. I don't appeal to
your average Korn fan or Beastie Boys fan because I'm an adult.
It's a lived life. I'm less ill at ease at 50, than I was in my
20s. I'm more relaxed being Wayne Kramer; I understand him much
better now.''
</P>
<P>
   More than most rock musicians, Kramer's music is lyric driven.
``I'm most interested in the literary value of the lyric _ telling
a good story, crafting a good lyric, something that sounds good and
hopefully has some meaning to it. I have to keep reminding myself
to work on the music end of it.''
</P>
<P>
   Kramer's take on the biz: ``The industry promotes the mythology
of the rock star and the mythology of fame, success and wealth and
glamour. The reality of it is very few people get to share in that.
For most musicians, it's hard work. The entertainment industry
knows that and that's why they'll sign a band, spend a million on
them and if the record doesn't become a hit, they dump 'em and
couldn't care less. (For them) the music on the CDs is the
necessity of doing business _ all these bands and their stupid
ideas and songs!''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
----- &QC; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Plan 9, Take 50: Years ago, the gnarly Rhode Island band Plan 9
crashed the stage with four electric guitars a-blazing and one
organ a-pumping, jamming on long psychedelic/punk songs. They still
muck about in that world, but the stripped-down Plan 9 _ a quartet
with just one guitarist, singer Eric Stumpo _ is crafting hookier,
tighter songs with shades of country and jazz. All in evidence on
its latest CD, ``Pleasure Farm.''
</P>
<P>
   ``It's an evolution from our roots of '60s psychedelic stuff,''
says Stumpo, who co-fronts the band with his wife,
signer-keyboardist Deb DeMarco. ``A lot of different styles started
to creep into what I was writing. I like to think of the music as
little more self-assured.'' Stumpo estimates Plan 9 as having about
50 lineups _ some guys have gone in and out up to five times.
Today's Plan 9 includes bassist Roger Vaughn and drummer Norman
Wrigley.
</P>
<P>
   Why so many Plan Niners? Is Stumpo a hard guy to work with?
``I'm easy to get along with,'' he says. ``But it can be just a
wrong project for someone. Basically, we've never been a real
commercial commodity. We get money to make records, we sell some,
we make a little money, we spent years on the road. Now, we just
play every so often _ I don't wanna ride around in a van. But,
beyond that, the independent scene is not very healthy. You're
being presented with major label stuff that's trash, played by kids
playing for two weeks.
</P>
<P>
   ``The level of success we've achieved is because we've done what
we wanted to do, and the level of failure is a result of same
thing. Let the chips fell where they may.'' As to the more sculpted
sound, he adds, ``I like to be abrasive sometimes, but I like to
run the whole gaumut in terms of emotion.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-01-08-99 1406EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
