<HEADER>
A4809 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-MUSIC-TUPAC-BOS &LR;      01-08 0693
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MUSIC-TUPAC-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THE MANY SIDES OF TUPAC SHAKUR 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By CINDY RODRIGUEZ  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Anyone who ever doubted that Tupac Shakur was one of the best
artists of our time needs to sit down with his greatest hits album,
kick back, and listen.
</P>
<P>
   Notice there's no qualifier to the word artist. That's because
his artistry goes beyond the realm of rap. He was a poet, a quasi
urban sociologist _ even without a PhD.
</P>
<P>
   Yes, he was a self-proclaimed gangsta, the words ``Thug Life''
tattooed across his chest. And like many rappers who rose in the
early '90s, he spoke obsessively about violence and revenge. With
raw grit, he talked about keeping his finger on a trigger, but that
was his tough-man side talking.
</P>
<P>
   When Tupac opened up, he was deep _ revealing the thoughtful,
caring man who wanted desperately to change the violent world
squeezing the life of people around him.
</P>
<P>
   This two disc CD, simply titled ``Greatest Hits,'' contains his
most acclaimed work. On ``Life Goes On,'' he raps about the death
of friends, too many to count. He moans, ``Imagine life as a
convict. That's getting old.''
</P>
<P>
   On ``Dear Mama,'' a tribute to his mother, Afeni Shakur, he says
he realizes how much he hurt his mother, blaming her because his
father wasn't around. ``I finally realize it's not easy for a woman
to raise a man,'' he writes.
</P>
<P>
   ``Brenda's Got A Baby,'' one of his best songs, chronicles what
happens to a 12-year-old girl who is impregnated by an older man, a
``molester,'' the only person who shows her love. But as her belly
grows, he runs off and the baby is born _ on the cold bathroom
floor. Not sure what to do, she dumps the baby in the trash.
</P>
<P>
   Though these are not everyday occurances in the ghetto, Tupac
wanted to say his peace, not letting newscasters on the 11 o'clock
news have the last word on these gruesome realities.
</P>
<P>
   Beyond his lyrics, Tupac had a unique rap style, rolling his
vowels, emphasizing the last word in a rhyme scheme. His voice was
deep, thick like molasses.
</P>
<P>
   He was a striking figure, with imposing eyes that, in one
glance, gave away his fears, his saddness.
</P>
<P>
   Tupac died a young man, shot to death after a drive-by shooting
in September 1996. Police still haven't caught his killer. Some
people say the killer was aiming for Suge Knight, the owner of
Death Row Records, a man with reputed ties to organized crime.
</P>
<P>
   Others say it was revenge, because Tupac ranked on rappers like
the Notorious BIG, stoking flames in what people began calling the
East Coast-West Coast rap wars.
</P>
<P>
   Others swear he's still alive, that his death was a hoax
designed to sell billions of his records. The conspirists don't
want to let go of him.
</P>
<P>
   But with modern technology, even in his grave he can continute
to speak to us. Many of his recorded songs _ Afeni says she has
rights to more than 400 unreleased tracks _ will be remastered,
adding an updated sound to his poignant raps.
</P>
<P>
   No one knows what kind of person Tupac would have become, but it
was clear that in the good-versus-eveil battle waging inside him,
good was winning.
</P>
<P>
   ``Changes,'' one of the previously unreleased songs on the
album, asks drug dealers to walk away from that empty lifestyle.
Set to Bruce Hornsby's ``The Way It Is,'' he chastises a young man,
saysing, ``You gotta operate the easy way.`` The young voice
answers, ``I made a G (grand) today.'' Tupac retorts: ``But you
made it in a sleezy way, selling crack to the kids.''
</P>
<P>
   In another new song, ``Unconditional Love,'' Tupac asks: ``How
many caskets can we witness before we see it's hard to live this
life without God? So we must ask forgiveness.''
</P>
<P>
   This past June, when Shakur would have turned 27, Afeni Shakur
threw a two-day party for her son in Mayfield, Ga. If her son were
still alive, she told reporters, he would still be focusing
attention on inner-city issues that most people would rather not
think about.
</P>
<P>
   ``Tupac was a boat rocker,'' she said. ``And at 27, I think he
still would have been rocking the boat. I don't think there's any
reason for us to think otherwise.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
