<HEADER>
A4814 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-MUSIC-MASUR-BOS &LR;      01-08 1082
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MUSIC-MASUR-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
KURT MASUR HITS THE ROAD 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By RICHARD DYER  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Kurt Masur is bringing the New York Philharmonic to Boston for
its first appearance in 20 years with the BankBoston Celebrity
Series. Next Friday, the orchestra and its music director report to
Symphony Hall to perform Beethoven's Fifth Symphony and
Shostakovich's Fifth.
</P>
<P>
   For decades, the New York Philharmonic has suffered from the
worst reputation of any of the major American orchestras. It must
have come as a relief to the players to read last month in The Wall
Street Journal that the Boston Symphony now holds that dubious
distinction. Speaking recently by phone from his office in New
York's Avery Fisher Hall, Masur was astounded to hear of this
evaluation. ``Who wrote that?'' he asked. ``And who paid him to
write something like that?''
</P>
<P>
   Then he leapt to the defense of his own orchestra _ and of the
Boston Symphony. Masur has won accolades for turning the
Philharmonic around since his appointment as music director in
1991. ``I must say at first that the New York Philharmonic can
fulfill any wish of a conductor. It is a brilliant orchestra;
everything is played very clear, very clean, and very polished. The
Philharmonic can enter into very different styles, always with
power, energy, and brilliance associated with American orchestras,
but in Beethoven they sound European and in Shostakovich they can
sound very much Russian. The orchestra is very flexible and it will
deliver the message of both symphonies to Boston. But, of course,
you yourself have a great orchestra, and the flexibility of the
Boston Symphony is on a very high level all the time.''
</P>
<P>
   Masur spoke during a break between rehearsals for the
Philharmonic's New Year's Eve concert and preparations for the
orchestra's 10-day coast-to-coast tour. ``This is the orchestra's
first American tour since 1990, and the first since I became music
director. We are always playing in New York _ and so is every other
important orchestra in America _ but somehow it seemed we could
never play in the other important musical centers in this country
ourselves. So this idea came for the tour.''
</P>
<P>
   The program reflects an idea that Masur came up with during his
26-year tenure as music director of the Gewandhausorchester in
Leipzig in the former East Germany. ``What we did was to play all
the Beethoven symphonies on programs with all the Shostakovich
symphonies, as a kind of confrontation. I met Shostakovich before
he died and discussed this with him, and he was very happy about
this idea. Both composers were very concerned with history, with
politics, with the happenings of their times. In the
confrontations, you can hear many similarities _ it is very
interesting to hear Beethoven's First Symphony and Shostakovich's
First Symphony together, for example.''
</P>
<P>
   Masur feels there is a particular connection between the Fifth
symphonies of both composers. ``Both have the same kind of force
and fire; both symphonies mark a kind of breakthrough for the
composers. For Beethoven it was the idea of night giving way to
light, `Nacht zum Licht.' Shostakovich cannot end his symphony this
positively; there is desperation in his ending. Of course, he had
been criticized by Stalin; the symphony is a kind of document of
his kind of confidence in himself. Despite Stalin, he will write
only what he wants to write.''
</P>
<P>
   (Leonard Bernstein made the most famous recording of the
Shostakovich Fifth with the New York Philharmonic in 1959, after
returning from a celebrated tour to the former Soviet Union, where
Shostakovich embraced the conductor with tears running down his
cheeks. Following the triumph of the tour, Bernstein was in a
position to throw his weight around, so he did, insisting that the
recording of the Shostakovich be made by his New York orchestra in
Boston's Symphony Hall _ and it was. So next week, the Philharmonic
will be returning to the scene of one of its legendary recorded
achievements.)
</P>
<P>
   Masur, now 71, celebrated 50 years as a professional conductor
last year. He made his belated American debut in Cleveland in 1974;
before that, he had been confined to appearances in the former East
Germany and Soviet bloc. In the early '80s, he was one of the most
regular and highly regarded guests on the BSO podium. He felt
particularly attached to Symphony Hall because one of the models
for its architects and acousticians was the old Gewandhaus in
Leipzig, which was bombed during World War II.
</P>
<P>
   Since relinquishing his post with the Gewandhausorchester in
1996, Masur has continued to be active in Europe, conducting the
Berlin Philharmonic, the Bayerischer Rundfunk, the London
Philharmonic, and the Dresden Philharmonic, among other orchestras.
He has kept away from Leipzig. ``I've been avoiding that so that
Herbert Blomstedt can establish himself. They need time to forget
about Masur _ and then I can come back later.''
</P>
<P>
   Opera played a major role in the early part of Masur's career;
he spent four seasons as music director at Walter Felsenstein's
fabled Komische Oper in East Berlin, but few conductors of Masur's
stature have recorded less opera. ``My love for opera is still
there, but the calendar is very resistant, and after working with
Felsenstein, I am very sensitive about the stage director. I need
to find the right person with whom I could do something and the
right circumstances.''
</P>
<P>
   Masur's tenure in New York, like that of every music director
before him, has brought controversy, although not much of it has
been on an artistic level. Fortunately, he is an old hand at
musical politics. Not long ago, a lot of ink was spilled over the
question of whether he was being forced out of his position because
of his age. Questioned about this matter, Masur is polite. ``My
current contract runs through 2002. Things are going on
successfully now, and I don't think anyone wants to make important
changes. If the orchestra can find someone to become a successor,
we will talk about it. But, at the moment, there has been no
decision. For me, this time in New York has been very enjoyable.
Before, I was conducting all around America _ in Philadelphia and
San Francisco as well as Boston _ so I was ready for the
opportunity to build up a relationship and a repertory with a
single orchestra, and one that can play so perfectly, technically
speaking, as the New York Philharmonic does.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
