A4834 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FBN-DOLPHINS-BOS &LR;      01-08 0949
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-DOLPHINS-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TRACE'S STRONGARM STRATEGY 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By MICHAEL VEGA  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   MIAMI _ The mangled sod separating the Bills from the Dolphins'
end zone was shrinking fast. So, too, were Miami's hopes of
surviving its wild and woolly AFC wild-card game against Buffalo.
</P>
<P>
   Fifteen years removed from his Hail Mary heave to Gerard Phelan
that lifted Boston College to a 47-45 victory over the University
of Miami, Bills quarterback Doug Flutie was in the process of
orchestrating another Miracle in Miami.
</P>
<P>
   With 17 seconds remaining and his team trailing by a touchdown,
Flutie capitalized on an onside kick recovery and had the Bills
knocking on the door at the Miami 5. The Dolphin defense was left
panting while the crowd of 72,698 in Pro Player Stadium clutched
their crucifixes, dreading yet another Hail Flutie finish.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was like a horror movie,'' said Miami linebacker Robert
Jones. ``You're sitting there and your heart is pounding. Here they
are, they got the onside kick, and they're marching down.''
</P>
<P>
   Hands on hips and gasping for air, Trace Armstrong stood wearily
on the field and took stock of the situation. As he crouched into
his three-point stance, Miami's 33-year-old defensive end, whom his
younger teammates call ``Grandpa,'' kept telling himself that his
team needed someone to come up with a play.
</P>
<P>
   A big play. No, something bigger than that. A HUGE play.
</P>
<P>
   Armstrong wasn't quite sure he was capable. He wasn't even sure
he could summon the strength to unfurl his aching body from its
stance, let alone the will to register the fumble-causing sack of
Flutie that cemented Miami's 24-17 victory last Saturday.
</P>
<P>
   But he did.
</P>
<P>
   As Flutie took a three-step drop, Armstrong came crashing around
the end, beating Thurman Thomas to penetrate the pocket. Flutie
stood there . . . looking for go-to guy Eric Moulds . . . then for
tight end Jay Riemersma . . . looking, looking . . . When he saw
that nobody was open, Flutie tried to get rid of the ball by
throwing it out of the end zone.
</P>
<P>
   But as he reared back, he didn't see Armstrong bearing down from
the blind side. A locomotive in teal and white and orange. He wore
No. 93.
</P>
<P>
   ``You're just straining to get there and I was just saying,
`Hold it, hold it, hold it,' '' Armstrong said, soaked in sweat as
he stood before reporters in the Dolphins' locker room. ``I got the
hit on him and I saw the ball come out, but I wasn't sure how the
officials were going to call it.''
</P>
<P>
   It was a fumble. Shane Burton recovered for the Dolphins,
triggering a celebration that took place over the flattened Flutie,
who was laid out on the Pro Player sod.
</P>
<P>
   ``Jerry (Wilson) and some of the guys dove on top of me and said
it was a fumble,'' said Armstrong, who as a reserve this season led
the Dolphins with 10 1/2 sacks. ``I was glad that it was, because I
didn't know if I could go another play.''
</P>
<P>
   He was spent. Physically exhausted.
</P>
<P>
   That much was evident to Armstrong's euphoric teammates when
they mobbed him on the field. ``I tried to go up and hug him,''
said linebacker Zach Thomas. ``But I stopped when I saw he had a
hard time breathing.''
</P>
<P>
   Gramps needed some air after causing Buffalo's fifth turnover of
the game. It propelled Miami to its first playoff victory in four
tries against the Bills and set the stage for a rematch with the
Denver Broncos in the AFC divisional playoffs Saturday at Mile High
Stadium.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think we know a little something about them, having seen
them once this year,'' Armstrong said, referring to Miami's 31-21
victory over the Broncos in a Monday night game Dec. 21 at Pro
Player. ``But I don't think we'll see the same Denver team that we
saw down here. We're going to see the world champions with a week
off and two weeks to prepare for us, so we're going to see them at
their absolute best and we're going to have to be better than we
were the last time we saw them.''
</P>
<P>
   Of that the Dolphins are certain. The defensive line will have
to summon an extraordinary effort to make up not only for the loss
of end Jason Taylor, who fractured his clavicle in a 38-16 loss at
Atlanta Dec. 27, but also Pro Bowl tackle Tim Bowens, who suffered
a season-ending tear of his right biceps tendon against the Bills.
</P>
<P>
   Still, Miami's defense was able to overcome those setbacks to
survive Flutie's furious rally.
</P>
<P>
   ``It feels good that we did,'' said Armstrong, whose role is not
likely to change because of the injuries. ``I don't know how well
we played as a group, but ultimately, we had guys that stepped up
and made plays when we needed them to.''
</P>
<P>
   Brock Marion had a fumble recovery on the first play of the
game, then a goal-line interception late in the second quarter.
Terrell Buckley, who caused a fumble, also had a fumble recovery,
as did Thomas and Burton. But it was Armstrong's sack that ranked
as the game's biggest play.
</P>
<P>
   Asked if he ever had a bigger play, Armstrong started to say,
``Yeah, I think so,'' then stopped and stammered, ``Well, as big? .
. . I mean, there were a lot of big plays today. Let's not make too
much of this. There were so many big plays. It was just a play.''
</P>
<P>
   But in coach Jimmy Johnson's estimation, it was more than that.
</P>
<P>
   ``Trace has come up big for us all year long,'' Johnson said.
``He's a veteran. I think that says something. Trace has been
through the battles before. He realizes the importance of somebody,
somehow, some way making a play. It's not just another play.''
</P>
<P>
   It was an important stand. One on which Trace Armstrong and the
Dolphins held their ground, even as it was shrinking beneath their
feet.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
