<HEADLINE>
JOHN TRAVOLTA: DOUBLE OSCAR CANDIDATE 
</HEADLINE>
  World rights except Great Britain and Australia 
 Color slides and black and white photos of John Travolta and
Kathleen Quinlan in ``A Civil Action.''
 (This ``separate buy'' article is from this week's Hollywood Stars
feature.) 
 (To publish this article, contact New York Times Syndicate sales
representative DEBRA WEYDERT at 1-732-390-4480, or by fax at
732-390-4697.) 
 (She also has information on how to subscribe to Hollywood Stars, a
weekly column with color art.) 
 By IVOR DAVIS 
 Distributed by New York Times Special Features)  
 &HT;    In early January, John Travolta climbed into one his four jets
and flew himself to Palm Springs, Calif., for the night. The star
of such diverse movies as ``Grease'' (1978) and ``Face Off'' (1997)
picked up the career achievement award at the Palm Springs
International Film Festival.
 &HT;    Next morning, he was back in the cockpit speeding home to his
actress-wife Kelly Preston and their son Jett.
 &HT;    Travolta is a real action man these days--on and off the screen,
flying high in jets and in the very top of the top reaches of
Hollywood.
 &HT;    This year Travolta has two chances to go home with the best
actor Oscar which has eluded him in two previous nominations. In
the past 12 months audiences have seen Travolta in what are
arguably his best roles ever: a Clintonesque presidential candidate
in Mike Nichols' savage political satire ``Primary Colors,'' and an
elegant shark of a civil lawyer in ``A Civil Action.''
 &HT;    Based on Jonathan Harr's dynamite best seller, ``Civil Action''
is the true story of a tenacious personal injury lawyer who battles
corporate America over the pollution of ground water in Woburn,
Mass., and its terrible effect on neighboring families.
 &HT;    Many insiders felt Travolta couldn't handle the role of Jan
Schlichtmann, an odious bad guy; not for the first time, Travolta
proved them wrong. He says he's proud of both the roles. (He can
also be seen in Terrence Malick's World War II film ``The Thin Red
Line''--a cameo he played as a favor to Malick whose latest film is
his first in 21 years.)
 &HT;    Meeting the Los Angeles press in a cashmere turtleneck, sports
coat and slacks, Travolta, 45, looked comfortable with himself. ``I
relished the opportunity to play a man who is cynical, arrogant,
detached and abrasive because these are not the roles usually
offered to me,'' he said.
 &HT;    ``I also like the fact that this movie doesn't preach--and that
it's a movie like 'Philadelphia' (Tom Hanks' Oscar-winning picture
about a lawyer dying of AIDS.) This was a movie about character
rather than issues. I saw Jan as a bit of a blackmailer who had
been corrupted by power so he's actually a villain at the beginning
and is transformed through the experience of working with these
families.''
 &HT;    Travolta got the part in ``Primary Colors,'' opposite Emma
Thompson, after Tom Hanks dropped out. Though the movie was not a
box office success, most critics agreed Travolta did an uncanny
job. ``I was very proud of 'Primary Colors,' he said. ``I think it
will hold up as one of the best political films ever made and
certainly the most informative about how politics really work.''
 &HT;    Although Travolta has been a frequent visitor to the White
House--on one famous occasion he danced with Princess Diana--he
claims he personally never got any feedback from the current
occupant of the Oval Office.
 &HT;    ``I did hear from Roger Clinton (the president's brother) that
the president really did like it and thought I had a heartfelt
feeling about the interpretation. And that was nice.''
 &HT;    So from the first family on down Travolta is the flavor of the
year. Even today, he said, he marvels at the twists and turns his
career has taken.
 &HT;    First there was ``Saturday Night Fever'' (1977) and then there
came a time--a long time--when he couldn't get arrested in
Hollywood.
 &HT;    ``I was afraid and confused in those days,'' he said, ``but I
wouldn't admit it. I tried to put on a brave face when really I was
having ulcers because of the pressure to make films that didn't
exploit my image.''
 &HT;    He started taking risks, pushing himself beyond the conventional
Travolta type roles and before long, after comeback films like
``Pulp Fiction'' (1994), ``Get Shorty'' (1995) and ``Broken Arrow''
(1996), he was pulling in the same kind of salary as Tom Cruise,
Bruce Willis and Mel Gibson. Today his price is $20 million a film.
 &HT;    He has magnificent homes in California, the East Coast and
Florida, and with his four jets and his love of flying, it's a
breeze to get from one to the other. He's also very proud of the
fact that in l998 he completed a training course that certifies him
to fly a Boeing 707.
 &HT;    And he keeps up a phenomenal work schedule. He's just finished
``The General's Daughter'' opposite Madeleine Stowe and this year
he will star opposite his actress wife in ``Shipping News,'' a
picture he calls ``a funny eccentric piece.''
 &HT;    The pair married in 1991. ``I think we have good chemistry on
film,'' he said.
 &HT;    Travolta's confidence in himself and the absolute inevitability
of his success comes, he is the first to tell you, from his
membership since 1975 in the controversial Church of Scientology.
 &HT;    In tribute to his religion, in l999 he also plans to star in the
science fiction film ``Battlefield Earth,'' written by the church's
founder, the late L. Ron Hubbard.
 &HT;    ``In the '70s it helped me avoid drugs and drinking--that's
where everybody in those days was leaning. Without them, '' he said
``I wouldn't have lived any longer than John Belushi. It gave me
the strength to survive all those years when no one wanted to work
with me, and it helped me overcome a lot of anguish in my personal
life.
 &HT;    ``I've always been so proud of what it's done for me and my
family. I learned the organizational skills that are the basis of
L. Ron Hubbard's beliefs. It's necessary to make sure that Kelly
and Jett and I can have an ordered proper happy life in a home
where both parents are out working almost nonstop.''
 c.1999 Ivor Davis 
<TEXT>
<P>
   (Ivor Davis is a Hollywood-based reporter.) &LR;  &QL;
</P>
