<HEADLINE>
JETTA AD AVOIDS HARD-DRIVING APPROACH 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By CHRIS REIDY  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Looking perhaps to recapture some of the magic of its
award-winning ``Da, da, da'' TV ad for Volkswagen of America Inc.,
Arnold Communications has just created a 60-second spot for VW's
redesigned Jetta.
</P>
<P>
   The latest installment of the ``Drivers wanted'' campaign, a
soft-sell ad dubbed ``Synchronicity'' features a nothing-happens
plot worthy of a ``Seinfeld'' episode.
</P>
<P>
   Seemingly with no particular place to go, a couple slowly drives
a new Jetta down a rainy New Orleans street, taking in sidewalk
scenes as down-tempo music plays on the car's tapedeck.
</P>
<P>
   Viewers see a man sweeping the street; a kid dribbling a
basketball. Then a van crosses the Jetta's path, sending heavy
spray from a puddle onto the Jetta's windshield.
</P>
<P>
   The laidback Jetta driver turns to his female sidekick and says,
``That was interesting.'' As the Jetta drives away, a voiceover
says, ``Sometimes everything comes together.''
</P>
<P>
   Most car ads feature sedans speeding down scenic highways. If
shining seas aren't in the background, then majestic mountains are.
When it comes to camera closeups, the car's racing lines get the
kind of star treatment normally reserved for Hollywood ingenues or
a burger chain's new whopper.
</P>
<P>
   ``Unlike many traditional car ads, this new campaign doesn't
brag about how fast or luxurious our cars are,'' said Liz Vanzura,
Volkswagen's director of marketing and advertising. ``Instead, it's
intended to show how the new Jetta fits into some people's
lifestyle and how some things in life just happen to come together
in perfect harmony.''
</P>
<P>
   The spot breaks this weekend during the National Football League
playoffs. Plans call for ``Synchronicity'' to also air on such
shows as ``Ally McBeal,'' ``NYPD Blue,'' and ``Dharma &AMP; Greg.''
</P>
<P>
   VW's fortunes have turned around sharply since the early 1990s,
when sales reached a low. The hiring of Arnold in 1995 was part of
that comeback story.
</P>
<P>
   Even without a sport utility vehicle in the lineup, Volkwagen's
US sales rose 59.3 percent in 1998 to 219,679. Thanks partly to the
reintroduced Beetle, 1998 was the best year for Volkswagen of
America since 1981. Now VW is debuting redesigned versions of its
workhorse models, the Jetta and the Golf.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
