<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-APPLE-FIREWIRE-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`FIREWIRE' SPARKS EXCITEMENT AT MACWORLD 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By HIAWATHA BRAY  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ Perhaps the most impressive technology
demonstration at the MacWorld trade show involved a bright red box.
The paperback-sized box was a hard drive made by VST Technologies
Inc. of Acton, Mass. The small device could hold up to six
gigabytes of computer data _ or, in this case, a rock-music video.
</P>
<P>
   Apple chief executive Steve Jobs simply plugged a wire into the
red box and touched the keyboard of a Macintosh computer. The video
began to play in less than 10 seconds.
</P>
<P>
   The audience went wild, and with good reason. Connecting
external hard drives to Macs or PCs can be a frustrating task.
There are drivers to load, electrical connections to check, and of
course the computer must be shut down and restarted.
</P>
<P>
   Apple aims to change that with a computer interface called
FireWire, that allows instant connections between computers and
sophisticated external devices like disk drives and scanners.
Apple's new line of Power Mac G3 computers will come with built-in
FireWire support. And 20 companies, including VST, announced that
they will begin producing FireWire-compatible devices for use with
PCs as well as Macs.
</P>
<P>
   Apple invented FireWire in the early 1990s as a replacement for
the Small Computer System Interface, or SCSI, a method for
connecting external devices to Macintoshes. SCSI transmits data
much faster than the parallel and serial ports found on the typical
PC. But Apple wanted to develop a better system for connecting even
faster disk drives, as well as a new generation of digital
camcorders and still cameras.
</P>
<P>
   The fastest SCSI connections now available can transmit up to 40
megabytes of data per second. FireWire ups the ante to 50 megabytes
per second. And future versions will be even faster.
</P>
<P>
   ``Where FireWire really stands out is in ease of use,'' said Jai
Chulani, Apple's FireWire technology manager. SCSI systems can
require fiddling with special termination plugs and switch
settings. With FireWire, the user just plugs in the device, and it
works.
</P>
<P>
   Up to 63 FireWire devices can be ``daisy-chained'' together. So
why is hardly anyone using FireWire?
</P>
<P>
   ``It was a chicken-and-the-egg thing,'' said Chulani. Few
computer makers would include FireWire technology until there were
hard drives and other devices that used FireWire connections. But
the makers of external devices didn't want to make FireWire
products until FireWire computers began hitting the market.
</P>
<P>
   James Giarrusso, president of VST, says he got the word late
last year that Apple was moving to abandon SCSI and go for
FireWire. In November, the company began a crash program to create
a pocket-sized FireWire drive . ``We pulled this together in an
incredibly short length of time,'' said Giarrusso.
</P>
<P>
   Future versions of the VST FireWire drive will hold up to 24
gigabytes of data. A smaller version, about the size of a deck of
cards, will hold up to 14 gigabytes. Pricing and availability dates
haven't been set.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-01-08-99 1414EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990108.0149 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-01-08 14:15 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4849 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FINANCE-HOOKER-$ADV10     01-08 1648
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FINANCE-HOOKER-$ADV10-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
40-YEAR-OLD NEEDS HOTTER ACTION THAN BOND FUNDS 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (For release Sunday, January 10, 1999)   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By KENNETH HOOKER  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Q. I read your column regularly looking for someone whose life
parallels mine, but have had no luck. Investing is very foreign to
me. I am a single 40-year-old woman. I have been a server in the
restaurant business for 20 years. My income of $20,000 to $30,000 a
year -- give or take -- relies mainly on tips and I will not have
much of a secure retirement plan down the road. I rent and I have
no outstanding bills. I bank most of my income weekly. I started
investing two years ago when I transferred my IRAs from the bank to
mutual funds. The investments presently consist of $10,300 in
Fidelity Equity Income II, $13,500 in Fidelity Growth and Income,
$16,000 in Vanguard Index 500, and $2,000 in Janus Worldwide. I
plan to add the maximum allowed each year to one or two of these
funds. From savings, I invested $23,000 in Vanguard Growth and
Income fund and $10,000 in Vanguard Specialized Health Care. I
still have about $60,000 in the bank. I plan on buying a new car
and paying about $25,000 cash, and I thought I would leave $10,000
in the bank for emergencies. I am thinking of investing the
remaining $25,000 in Vanguard Windsor II. Is that a good idea, or
should I be looking into balanced or bond funds? You suggested a
36-month dollar cost averaging program to another reader -- what is
that? Finally, should I transfer my IRAs to Roth IRA accounts?
</P>
<P>
   J.M., Newburyport, Mass.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   A. The answer to your first question -- Windsor II, balanced or
bond funds? -- is none of the above. At your tender age, bond funds
are simply too tame, and even the 35 percent or 40 percent of a
balanced fund that's on the fixed income side is likely, in the
long run, to prove a drag to long-term growth. Windsor II is an
excellent fund, but it's too much like your other funds. I tally
that nearly 84 percent of your fund portfolio is invested primarily
in domestic large-cap stocks -- only Janus Worldwide and Vangaurd
Health Care fall into different sectors. What I suggest is that you
venture into different territories -- increasing your international
exposure by building the Janus Worldwide position to about $10,000
and investing the additional $17.000 in the mid-cap and small-cap
stock sectors. Within the fund families you're now using, solid
examples might be Fidelity Mid-Cap Stock or Vanguard Mid-Cap Index,
and in the latter, Janus Venture and Vanguard Explorer.
</P>
<P>
   Dollar cost averaging is a strategy designed to protect
investors who are building a market position from a short-term
market decline. The discipline involves spreading an investment out
over a number of months; in the example, you cite, the investor
would make 36 equal monthly investments. If the market suffers a
sharp decline during that period, the investor can bring his or her
average purchase cost down through later investments made at lower
costs. (Of course, if the market goes nowhere but up, dollar cost
averaging mitigates your gains, just as it mitigates your losses in
the event of a decline.) Typically, an investor puts most of the
cash in a money market fund and directs the fund family to move
equal payments into the target funds each month.
</P>
<P>
   For example, if we presume average 5 percent returns from a
money fund, it would entail monthly investments of $747 to get a
$25,000 nest egg fully invested over the course of 36 months.
</P>
<P>
   (Frequently, minimum initial investments are a complicating
factor, requiring recalculation.
</P>
<P>
   For example, if you used Fidelity funds, you might start with a
$2,500 minimum investment in one fund on the first month, skip two
months entirely and then make a similar investment in the fourth.
After that, you would move $673 a month to the target funds.) As
for the question of transferring existing IRAs to Roth accounts, my
guess is that you'd be better off sticking with what you have.
Let's suppose that you leave your existing IRA accounts as is until
age 65. If we presume 10 percent average annual growth for 25
years, the pool would grow from the current $41,800 to $452,881.
</P>
<P>
   Withdrawing the income from such a tax-deferred portfolio in
retirement would not, in all likelihood, put you in an onerous tax
situation. But if you transferred the accounts to Roths now, it
would doubtless have a nasty effect on your current tax bill --
even moving you into a higher bracket if you moved most of the
money.
</P>
<P>
   But making future IRA investments in Roths is a different
question, Let's suppose that you're paying 15 percent of your total
income in taxes. If you chose a Roth IRA over a traditional
deductible IRA, you will bypass about $300 in tax savings on a
$2,000 IRA contribution. But in 25 years, presuming once again 10
percent average annual growth, the investment would be worth
$21,668, and the entire amount could be withdrawn anytime you like
with no tax liability. So I'd use a strategy of making ongoing IRA
contributions into Roth accounts, without changing the traditional
IRAs.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Q. In a column late last month you advised a person earning
$27,000 a year to start a traditional IRA for retirement savings.
Her current tax liability is only 15 percent or less. Why didn't
you suggest a Roth?
</P>
<P>
   R.M., Fallbrook, Calif.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   A. The person's situation was a bit similar to that of the
writer above -- except that at age 40 this person had just begun to
save for retirement. It seemed to me likely that if her savings
didn't go beyond the IRA maximums, the total amassed by the age of
retirement would not be sufficient to drive her into a higher tax
bracket -- in fact, with an orderly withdrawal schedule it would
likely be lower. So why not take the tax savings now?
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Q. I retired from my job as a Portland city employee on Jan. 1,
1998. Since I wanted to leave something for my daughter and
grandchildren I rolled half of my retirement money into an IRA. I
know nothing about stocks or mutual funds, but I tagged along with
a couple of other people who were doing this. The IRA money is
invested in a growth and income portfolio of State Street Research
funds and I get a monthly check of $1,950 from them, plus $2,000 a
month from the state on the other half of my pension. The
investments consist of $101,347 in State Street Research Investment
Trust Class A and $152,021 in State Street Research Managed Assets
Class A. How do you feel about these funds? I went into these
investment for the long run, but since March of last year I have
developed serious, and perhaps life-threatening, health problems.
My wife, who is my beneficiary, knows even less about this than I
do. What do you recommend for us? I feel good about the Investment
Trust fund, but Managed Assets has dragged a little. If something
should happen to me, should she stay with what I have, or go into
bonds or something else? Or should I get something else now?
</P>
<P>
   J.C., Portland, Ore.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   A. Your rollover IRA portfolio is a bit aggressive for a person
your age -- but only a bit.
</P>
<P>
   You should expect results from State Street Research's
Investment Trust fund to exceed those of the Managed Assets fund --
the former is entirely invested in large-cap stocks, while the
latter is a balanced fund, tempering a 59 percent stock position
with the remainder of the portfolio in bonds and other fixed-income
assets. Last year, the Investment Rust holding produced better than
29 percent returns, compared to a little more than 8 percent total
returns from Managed Assets. Your schedule of withdrawals
represents 9.2 percent of the fund portfolio, so the strategy
worked nicely for you last year.
</P>
<P>
   And, if you can afford to ride out the bumps, it's a strategy
that would probably work over the long haul, although it might
deliver some gut-wrenching bumps along the way.
</P>
<P>
   But since the yields of the two funds are fairly negligible --
0.6 percent for Investment Trust and 1.9 percent for Managed Assets
-- the strategy relies upon stock market gains to produce the bulk
of your income stream. As you should know, stock market gains are
far from assured. I would have been much happier had you reduced
the level of withdrawals by about half -- or increased the
fixed-income holdings, perhaps putting a significant part of the
portfolio in State Street Research's Government Income fund, and a
tad in its High Income fund as well.
</P>
<P>
   But before we can go into what to do now, since there's a
substantive change in your health, a different question poses
itself. Will your state pension continue to pay benefits for your
wife during her lifetime? If so, I would advise a fairly moderate
adjustment in the portfolio -- perhaps putting a total of 40
percent of the portfolio on the fixed-income side.
</P>
<P>
   You could achieve this a number of ways. You could simply
transfer $39,000 from the Investment Trust account to the two fixed
income funds -- perhaps putting $20,000 in the High-Income fund and
the balance in Government Income. Or you could reduce the portfolio
in Managed Assets to $82,000, moving the proceeds to a fixed-income
portfolio.
</P>
<P>
   Etcetera -- there are almost limitless variations, but the point
is to get about 40 percent of the portfolio on the fixed-income
side, and no more than 20 percent of that in the High- Income (and
therefore higher-risk) investment.
</P>
<P>
   Now, the situation changes entirely if your state pension
payments end upon your death. In that event, you or your wife can
afford very very little risk, and you would be best off, in my
opinion, moving the entire rollover IRA to the fixed-income side.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Send letters, including your name, address and telephone
number, to: Kenneth Hooker, The Boston Globe, Boston, Mass. 02107.)
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
