<HEADLINE>
IT'S WAIT AND SEE ON THE NBA 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By HOWARD MANLY  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   NBC Sports president Dick Ebersol said he is not too worried
about the league repaying the networks for canceled telecasts but
is more concerned about recapturing the interest of casual fans in
the wake of the six-month lockout.
</P>
<P>
   ``It would be crazy for me to say that there wasn't damage
caused by the lockout,'' Ebersol told reporters Thursday. ``There
is no question in my mind that the real, longtime fans will be back
immediately. But we have a lot of work to do to bring back the
casual fans to our game.''
</P>
<P>
   Ebersol said he has been encouraged by his talks with players'
union executive director Billy Hunter and Lakers star Shaquille
O'Neal about having more interaction between players and fans
throughout the shortened season.
</P>
<P>
   Though the schedule is not final, Ebersol said the first game is
expected to be aired on TNT Feb. 5, while NBC will broadcast a
doubleheader two days later. The regular season of 50 games would
end the first week of May, with the playoffs _ involving 16 teams,
as usual _ starting May 8.
</P>
<P>
   NBC signed a four-year, $1.75 billion deal last year with the
NBA and is expected to get its money back for the nine games,
including the All-Star Game, it had to cancel because of the
lockout. Turner paid the NBA $178 million a year for four seasons
and had to cancel about 50 games.
</P>
<P>
   Fox, which owns the cable rights to 26 of the NBA's 29 teams,
lost about 500 games. Tracy Dolgin, chief operating officer for Fox
Liberty Networks, said he couldn't be happier that the league is
back. Fox Sports Net is built on a combination of regional and
national programming, and the NBA was one of its prized
possessions, expected not only to generate ratings in local markets
but also to promote its national shows, such as the new one hosted
by Keith Olbermann.
</P>
<P>
   ``The lockout gave us a big void,'' Dolgin said. ``But we'll
have about five-eighths of the season. We don't have it as easy as
NBC, which can simply place a game into a certain time slot. We
will have to do a lot more scrambling and suffer a little more pain
in the short run. But in the long run, we'll have a healthier NBA
and a full season next year.''
</P>
<P>
   Of course, the assumption is that people still care about the
NBA. An ESPN poll of 91,265 respondents suggests otherwise.
Fifty-four percent said they were not interested, 27.5 percent said
they were mildly interested, 12.1 percent said they were excited,
and 6.3 percent said they were very interested.
</P>
<P>
   But Ebersol remains undaunted. With or without Michael Jordan.
NBC's NBA trademark was showcasing the Chicago Bulls. That could be
a risky bet this season. Jordan hasn't decided whether to retire,
Scottie Pippen and Dennis Rodman are unsigned, and the team has a
new coach right out of the college ranks.
</P>
<P>
   Ebersol said that depending on how good the Bulls are, they
could still merit national appearances. If not, NBC would show them
only in regional markets.
</P>
<P>
   ``We knew when we signed our deal that having Micahel was never
going to be a sure thing,'' Ebersol said. ``It's not something that
brigns a smile to my face. But when we first acquired the NBA
rights in 1989 for the 1990 season, everyone said then that it was
the end of the era of Magic (Johnson) and (Larry) Bird. And then
Michael appeared. Whether Michael emerges or not this season,
another great player or two will.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
Cowher in studio &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Pittsburgh Steelers coach Bill Cowher joins the CBS pregame show
team for this weekend's NFL playoff games . . . CNN/SI's Fred
Hickman and Vince Cellini planned to shave their beards off during
``Sports Tonight'' on CNN Friday. The two have been growing them
since November and vowed to remain unshaven until the NBA returned
. . . USA Today reported that Sterling Sharpe may replace Dan
Dierdorf next year on ``Monday Night Football.''
</P>
</TEXT>
