<SLUG> BC-OUTDOORS-SNOWSHOES-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
IF THE SHOES FIT, THEN TREK ONWARD 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By TONY CHAMBERLAIN  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   OK, so cross-country skiing wasn't the biggest hit in the world.
</P>
<P>
   Hard to say why Europeans, especially Scandinavians and most
especially Finns, are so crazy for the sport, as common there as
bike riding is here.
</P>
<P>
   Sure, maybe they have more winter to work with, but just north
of here, there's not much climate difference.
</P>
<P>
   Cross-country skiing _ called at different times ``Nordic'' and
``ski touring'' _ once was much more popular in this country than
it is now. At the height of the fitness boom in the '80s, in fact,
cross-country skiing was twice as popular as it is now.
</P>
<P>
   According to the annual study done by the National Sporting
Goods Association, some 5.1 million Americans participated in
cross-country skiing in 1990, and by last year, that figure had
dropped to 2.5 million.
</P>
<P>
   It has been almost 20 years since America's only recognizable
cross-country ski racer, Bill Koch, was on the scene, racing in
Olympics and winning the World Cup title one year.
</P>
<P>
   That may have something to do with it, but it's doubtful that
there's much connection between star performers and recreational
participants.
</P>
<P>
   Well, the news has to be better somewhere, and if cross-country
skiing is just a bit too heavy on technique for you and a bit too
crunchy and hard to break into, consider big feet _ the return of
the snowshoe.
</P>
<P>
   When cross-country was in its prime in the United States,
snowshoeing wasn't even considered a sport unto itself, merely an
extension of walking. Snowshoes themselves, cumbersome wooden
frames strung with rawhide nets, were tough to learn and hard to
get enthusiastic about.
</P>
<P>
   But all that changed when, in the last decade, snowshoes went
lighter, smaller, just as effective in buoying snow travelers in
every condition from loose, deep powder to hard pack to solid ice.
The modern snowshoe is crafted with a pivoting crampon that can
bite into a glacier wall.
</P>
<P>
   The same study by the NSGA shows that snowshoeing has taken off
in the last part of this decade. In 1996, retailers sold 13,397
pair of snowshoes, and last year that number had ballooned nearly
tenfold to 112,121 pair. Most of the snowshoers are male (2-1
majority), and 47 percent are between the ages of 25 and 45.
</P>
<P>
   As any dealer will tell you, the most appealing things about
snowshoes _ aside from all the aesthetic and athletic benefits _ is
the appeal to minimalism.
</P>
<P>
   ``With cross-country skis, it takes you a few days to get the
hang of it,'' says George DeLorey, who sells snowshoes to trekkers
in upstate New York, ``But with snowshoes, people begin as
intermediates.''
</P>
<P>
   It's true. The most challenging thing to learn about snowshoes
is how to strap in the foot. From there, with new lightweight
aluminum and plastic frames, the first move is to put one foot in
front of the other. Bingo, you're a seasoned intermediate.
</P>
<P>
   In the right conditions, the right snow _ well-tracked (trackset
for striders) or in new powder across golf courses or woods _
cross-country skiing can be as pleasant a way to spend a winter day
as there is.
</P>
<P>
   But snowshoeing is simply more versatile. It needs no paths, no
uniformity of snow or terrain, nor does the competence level matter
very much, within reason.
</P>
<P>
   A low-end intermediate on skinny skis cresting even a moderate
hilltop with a turn around a tree halfway down presents what seems
like a life-or-death challenge.
</P>
<P>
   One of a skier's newfound techniques at such moments is grabbing
bushes to slow down and possibly steer the body around the corner,
or at least away from the tree. The ultimate survival technique,
however, is the bail-out. Tree coming, Martha, better hit it! And
down we go, another butt plant.
</P>
<P>
   Real skiing technique does take a few years to master, though
there's no detracting from the great sport that cross-country
skiing is. Still, we're Americans. We like instant success, and
during the first walk on snowshoes, the walker can be going up
steep slopes like a mountain goat _ and down again. Broken powder,
deep drifts, rocks, and stumps _ no problem. Ski poles are highly
recommended.
</P>
<P>
   The good news? According to computations on the Tubbs website,
which allows you to calculate your activity level, a 175-pound man
walking on snowshoes with poles on hilly terrain for an hour burns
around 1,000 calories.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
