<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKC-NOTEBOOK-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HARRICK, FLINT SEEK A CURE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By MARK BLAUDSCHUN  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   They might be different, but he problems problems at the
University of Rhode Island and the University of Massachusetts are
equally frustrating for coaches Jim Harrick and Bruiser Flint.
</P>
<P>
   And both boil down to leadership _ senior leadership.
</P>
<P>
   At UMass, it's not so much what the Minutemen can do, it's what
they can't do. It has become painfully obvious that the Minutemen
cannot shoot with any consistency.
</P>
<P>
   Add the Minutemen's softness _ losing to Davidson and then by 19
to Iona at home? _ and you have problems. People like Charlton
Clarke can take on leadership roles on the court, but pep talks and
players meetings can carry you only so far.
</P>
<P>
   UMass athletic director Bob Marcum took a leap of faith when he
gave Flint a two-year contract extension earlier this season.
Already the critics and cynics are moaning about that.
</P>
<P>
   Was it a wise move? Probably not. Flint needs to prove himself
more, especially in March. It could have waited.
</P>
<P>
   Was it a bad move? Probably not. With the security of that
extension, Flint can smile through losing streaks and streaky play.
But he knows as much as anybody that eventually he will be held
accountable for what UMass does.
</P>
<P>
   Right now there is a sense of panic in Amherst. We're not ready
to do that _ at least not yet. Seasons can get turned around
quickly with a long winning streak. And there still is time, but
the margin for error is rapidly diminishing.
</P>
<P>
   As for URI: It seems simple. Last year, the Rams had guards _
senior guards _ who could solve problems in close games. This
season they don't. There also seems to be an underlying feeling of
discontentment. Is everybody happy?
</P>
<P>
   Of course not. Nor should they be. URI had expectations of a Top
20 finish and an NCAA tournament bid. Now it may have to be scaled
down to above .500 and NIT.
</P>
<P>
   Harrick now must prove he can coach on a different level, which
means finding a way to put back together the psyche of a team that
has had it rattled, if not shattered.
</P>
<P>
   As the Atlantic 10 season moves into its showdown stage in the
next few weeks, the Rams and the Minutemen will have to solve their
problems quickly.
</P>
<P>
   But can they? Various problems and transfers have cut the URI
roster down to 10, and Lamar Odom may be a good one, but he cannot
carry a team on his back for an entire season, nor should he be
asked to do so.
</P>
<P>
   UMass? Who knows. The Minutemen are one of the enigmas of the
season. Maybe it's time to make this assessment: They're just not
that good. &QL; 
 &QL; 
Davis's boffo finale &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Tom Davis is certainly making his final season at Iowa
interesting. Going into Thursday night's game against Illinois, the
Hawkeyes had been beaten only once (by Creighton in November) and
looked very much like a team that could win the Big 10 . . . At
14-0, Cincinnati is off to its best start in history. Give coach
Bob Huggins credit. No one knows how to rebuild a team quicker or
better . . . Sometimes when we get caught up in the bright lights
of college basketball's star system, we forget we're still dealing
with kids. Take the case of UCLA's JaRon Rush. He came back late
from Christmas break in Kansas City and was suspended for a game by
coach Steve Lavin. It's not hard to see both points of view. With a
key game against Arizona approaching him, Lavin could not afford to
lose one of his better recruits. But Rush, feeling homesick, did
not want to leave his family. This was a case of no harm, no foul
on both sides. &QL; 
 &QL; 
Meaningful schedule &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Much has made of the growing lack of meaning the regular season
seems to have. Not in the ``mid-major'' conferences such as the
America East, which is why Boston University's 1-point overtime
loss to Delaware Tuesday night was a vital win for the Blue Hens
and a tough loss for the Terriers. Here's why. With only one NCAA
tournament bid a near-certainty in America East, winning the
postseason tournament is vital. But unlike the major conferences,
America East plays its championship game on the home court of the
highest-seeded remaining team. Thus finishing first _ or as high as
possible _ means everything. A BU win at Delaware would have given
coach Dennis Wolff's team an early edge in what is essentially a
home-court league . . . It's only early January and only three
Division 1 teams remain unbeaten _ UConn, Cincinnati and Auburn. &QL; 
 &QL; 
UConn's `home' game &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Things are tough enough at Boston College, but to play at Conte
Forum Wednesday night against UConn and find the place filled with
Huskies fans made it doubly tough on coach Al Skinner's Eagles, who
gave the No. 1 ranked Huskies a surprisingly tough time. But
there's not much BC can do about the fan composition . . . Like him
or not, Fresno State's Jerry Tarkanian deserves some recognition
for winning his 700th game this week. Only 12 major coaches have
reached that milestone . . . Going into the first full week of
conference play, the Pac-10 and the ACC were the only conferences
with every team above .500 . . . It's good to know that college
basketball pollsters are as wacky as their football brethren.
Explain this glitch in this week's polls. Wisconsin and Ohio State
are 12-3. Ohio State had just come into Madison and pulled off an
upset, had a better Big Ten record and yet Wisconsin is No. 24 and
Ohio State unranked. Thank heaven basketball settles its
championship with a tournament . . . One of bigger disappointments
thus far has been South Carolina. A solid SEC contender the past
few seasons, the Gamecocks are a mediocre 5-8 after losing to
Kentucky at home Tuesday night . . . The Big Ten might not have a
Super team, but it's just as hard to find a bad team among its 11
members. at the beginning of the week, Michigan had the worst
overall record at 7-8, but then the Wolverines went out and beat
No. 13 Indiana to get back to .500 . . . Let's get it over with
early this season. ESPN is simply wrong when it has a TCU-SMU game
for its Big Monday show, necessitating an 11 p.m. local time
tipoff. Both schools also are wrong for allowing the game to be
played at such a ridiculous time. With all the yammering about
concern for the well-being of college athletes, isn't it time
someone really had some consideration for the players _ and for the
fans? But it's all about the money, of course, which is why schools
sell their souls for exposure, even if it comes when most people
are asleep.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
