<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SOC-COLUMN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
REVOLUTION MAY LOSE A KEEPER 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By FRANK DELL'APA  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   The Revolution could be in danger of losing goalkeeper Ian
Feuer, who is playing for Rushden and Diamonds in the Vauxhall
Conference, the equivalent of the fifth division in England. He
helped the Diamonds hold Premier League power Leeds United to a 0-0
tie in an FA Cup match, setting up a replay at Elland Road next
Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   Feuer is on loan and could be recalled by the Revolution for
training camp later this month. But Rushden and Diamonds could be
in position to offer a decent contract, since the team chairman is
Doc Martens shoe baron Max Griggs.
</P>
<P>
   The team is the product of a merger of Rushden Town and
Irthlingborough Diamonds, and Griggs's goal is to advance to the
Football League, which comprises England's top 92 clubs, in two
years. Griggs is worth 325 million pounds sterling, making him the
61st-richest person in Britain.
</P>
<P>
   Feuer was added to the team after the starting goalkeeper was
injured and is residing with friends in Belgium, where he played
before going to Luton Town and West Ham United in England, then to
the Revolution.
</P>
<P>
   ``I went back to the States six months ago for a number of
reasons, but mainly because of pressure from the US federation to
get their best players back to help the domestic league to
prosper,'' Feuer told the Daily Mail. ``I quickly realized I had
made the wrong decision to go back. I was biting my fingernails and
thinking that I didn't want to be 35 having never given myself the
chance of playing in the Premiership.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's not about money. It's about the honor of playing in
England. My wife and I have a daughter who was born over here, and
we wanted to come back. We found out the hard way that this is
where we want to be. Going back to the States toughened me up
mentally, though.''
</P>
<P>
   Feuer apparently has a better chance to start for Diamonds and
to be scouted by top-level clubs there than he would with the
Revolution.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
Power struggle &QL;
</P>
<P>
   FIFA president Sepp Blatter has proposed holding the World Cup
every two years, starting in 2006. It will not likely happen, but
Blatter is playing a strong hand in the battle for control of
soccer.
</P>
<P>
   ``We had 40 billion spectators with television and in the stands
at France '98,'' Blatter told the weekly Sonnstags Blick. ``It's a
figure that no other sporting event can even come close to matching
and a testimony to the great bond which the national teams enjoy
with the public. A World Cup every two years could reestablish the
status they merit, that of an enormous promotional vehicle for all
of soccer.''
</P>
<P>
   Blatter noted that the proposal would actually reduce the
demands on players, since meaningless friendlies and mismatch
qualifiers would be eliminated. Continental championships, for
instance, also would serve as World Cup qualifiers. And FIFA could
double its money, though at the risk of devaluing the competition.
</P>
<P>
   But Blatter's main purpose here is to fight attempts to usurp
FIFA's control of world soccer.
</P>
<P>
   Elite clubs, along with television moguls Silvio Berlusconi, Leo
Kirch, and Rupert Murdoch, have attempted to establish a Super
League in Europe. And now the International Olympic Committee is
attempting to apply drug testing and disciplinary standards to
soccer. FIFA officials have noted that many drugs banned by the IOC
do not have performance-enhancing qualities for soccer players.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
