<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-01-08 14:23 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4861 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FBN-REEVES-BOS &LR;      01-08 1536
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-REEVES-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DAN REEVES GETS BACK TO WORK 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By RON BORGES  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Dan Reeves hasn't been wrong about many things since
he came to Atlanta two years ago, but he was wrong about one thing.
On Dec. 13, he was nearly dead wrong about himself.
</P>
<P>
   That afternoon, he felt the burning sensation in his chest and
pain in his throat that he'd become too familiar with over the past
few weeks and knew it was time to tell someone. Until that day, he
had ignored the sensations, but this time the burning was too hot
and it lasted too long, and even prowling the sidelines directing
his Falcons to another victory could not make it go away.
</P>
<P>
   So when the game was over _ and not until _ Reeves took team
physician Charles Harrison aside in the locker room and told him
what he had been feeling, prefacing his words with ``I know I'm
overreacting.''
</P>
<P>
   Harrison immediately gave him two aspirin to help thin his blood
and ordered a heart catheterization and angiogram the next morning.
Less than 24 hours after taking those aspirin, the Falcons'
54-year-old coach underwent four hours of open-heart surgery, a
quadruple bypass that probably saved his life.
</P>
<P>
   The doctors found that one coronary artery was 100 percent
blocked, another was 90 percent blocked, and a third was 80-90
percent blocked. Blood was moving through Reeves's heart the way
his running back, Jamal Anderson, moves through a defense. It was
battering its way through small holes, struggling for every inch.
According to Harrison, it wouldn't have been much longer before it
would have been like the Patriots' running game _ it wouldn't have
gotten anywhere.
</P>
<P>
   Another day or two, another week, who knows when, but soon
enough, Reeves would have suffered a massive heart attack, because
when the left circumflex artery closed completely, it would have
resulted in what Harrison called ``a catastrophe.'' Nobody needed a
definition of what that would have meant.
</P>
<P>
   ``If we had waited any longer, there would have been damage to
the heart muscle,'' Harrison said after the operation. ``A heart
attack.''
</P>
<P>
   Reeves is no stranger to illness and recovery, the latter of
which began anew only days after he was released from Piedmont
Hospital and is scheduled to continue Saturday when he expects to
return to the sideline in a reduced role for the first time since
the operation.
</P>
<P>
   This is a man who had five knee operations by his mid-20s, yet
played seven years in the NFL, a man who had two angioplasty
procedures (in which a balloon is inserted into the artery to open
a blockage) in 1990 and 1991 without missing a game as coach of the
Denver Broncos. But this time it was different.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
----- &QC; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   This was something both lifesaving and life-shattering, and
Reeves showed its effects at a packed press conference several days
after the operation. He broke down in tears as he held the hand of
his former high school sweetheart and wife of 33 years and said,
``I understand how precious life is. You do break down a little bit
more. You do cry a little bit more.''
</P>
<P>
   Yet until he went through the near collapse, Reeves didn't
listen. He didn't listen to his doctors and he didn't listen to his
body. Not until Dr. Charlie Brown said, ``We'll have to do a
bypass,'' the morning after the Saints game did Dan Reeves
understand what he was now facing.
</P>
<P>
   As Reeves described it, ``Bypass hits you in the head and starts
ringing in your ears.''
</P>
<P>
   That is especially true if you consider yourself a tough guy
both by inclination and temperament. Then you do what Reeves did
for nearly too long, which was to ignore the signs for four months,
right up to the day his idea of toughness nearly killed him.
</P>
<P>
   ``I made up my mind about three or four months ago,'' Reeves
said at a postoperation press conference. ``I had those symptoms
(and) I wasn't going to mention. I didn't want to do anything to
distract the football team. You try to be so tough.''
</P>
<P>
   Reeves will try to be that again as the remarkable Falcon team
he has rebuilt in just two years tries to qualify for the NFC
Champonship Game when it takes on an old nemesis, the San Francisco
49ers. When Reeves came to Atlanta last season after being fired in
New York during a power struggle with then Giants general manager
George Young, the Falcons were coming off a 3-13 season. They had
not won a division title since 1980 and opened the Reeves Regime by
going 1-7, sorely testing both his heart and his patience.
</P>
<P>
   But then the toughness he had been trying to instill in them
through a power running game and scrappy defense began to take
hold. The Falcons went 6-2 in the second half of 1997 and set the
stage for a turnaround so remarkable this season that it brought
Reeves a landslide victory in the Coach of the Year balloting.
</P>
<P>
   That honor came because today his Falcons are 14-2, are the NFC
West champions for the first time in 18 years, and are favored to
beat the Niners at the Georgia Dome, in part because they are 8-0
at home and 20-4 in their last 24 games.
</P>
<P>
   Yet Reeves acknowledged this week that he probably won Coach of
the Year honors for more than what his team has done, although he
wouldn't endorse it as the best strategy.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm sure the sympathy vote helped,'' Reeves joked. ``I
wouldn't recommend that anybody go through heart bypass surgery to
try to get Coach of the Year, though.''
</P>
<P>
   Certainly, it wasn't Reeves's idea, and Thursday he seemed
almost embarrassed to still be answering questions about his heart
instead of the heart of his team or that of the 49ers, who have
beaten Atlanta 13 of the last 18 times they've met.
</P>
<P>
   But Reeves understood this affair of the heart could not be
ignored, so he talked softly and patiently of the past two days,
his first back on the practice field at the Georgia Dome, and of
his plans to be on the sideline in the spot where he feels he
belongs but no one knows for sure he is ready to handle.
</P>
<P>
   ``Unless I have some sort of setback in the next 48 hours, I
plan to be there,'' Reeves said. ``You get very tired going through
something like this, but I've been able to stand up the whole time
(at practice).
</P>
<P>
   ``Taking into consideration what the doctors said, it's up to me
how much I can do. I want to be as much a part of it as I can.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
----- &QC; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Reeves has worked on the game plan as the Falcons prepare for
the 49ers, attended meetings, and run practice as always, although
he said, ``I'm about 50 percent involved. It's not anything like
what it was.''
</P>
<P>
   The proof came Thursday during the 30-minute drive from the
Falcons' training camp in Suwanee to the Dome in downtown Atlanta.
During that ride, Reeves leaned his head against a car window and
simply fell asleep, a concession to fatigue he would not have made
a month or two ago.
</P>
<P>
   Yet for all his willingness to listen to his body and do what is
best, Dan Reeves still is putting the Falcons first. That is why he
said the plays will continue to be called from upstairs by
quarterback coach Jack Burns but instead of going through him and
out to quarterback Chris Chandler, they will go through offensive
coordinator George Sefcik. Although Reeves will retain the right to
overrule them, he won't be transmitting the plays to anyone on this
game day.
</P>
<P>
   ``I won't be giving Chris the plays,'' Reeves joked. ``I'll just
call the ones that work.''
</P>
<P>
   The way things have gone this season, that would be the majority
of them.
</P>
<P>
   When Reeves left New York, he went out the way Bill Parcells
left New England. He left saying he wanted to control the personnel
side of his operation as well as the football side, and that he has
done.
</P>
<P>
   It was he who decided to trade for Chandler, who is 17-4 in
Atlanta in games he has started and finished. It was he who signed
Ray Buchanan, although the free agent cornerback had been an
expensive transitional player with the Colts; Buchanan finished
second in the NFC in interceptions this season with seven. It was
he who hired Rich Brooks as defensive coordinator and Art Shell as
offensive line coach and told them to teach his team what toughness
is all about. It was he who drafted players like tight end O.J.
Santiago and guard Calvin Collins to give his offense that
toughness, which allowed Anderson to rush for 1,846 yards this
season.
</P>
<P>
   And now it is Reeves who is trying to decide if his presence on
the sideline and on the practice field this week will detract from
his team's efforts or bolster them. The decision he has made, at
least for the moment, is simple. This is his team, and Dan Reeves
doesn't have the heart not to be with it if he can be.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't want to hurt them,'' Reeves said. ``I won't let me
being around hurt them. I put my team first and me second.''
</P>
<P>
   That attitude, of course, is what led to the foot-long scar
running down his chest. Then again, it's also what led the Atlanta
Falcons to this moment, a game away from earning the right to play
for the NFC championship.
</P>
<P>
   When they play that game against their oldest and most
dominating rival, Dan Reeves's heart has told him to be there with
them.
</P>
<P>
   And so he will be.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
