<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-01-08 14:25 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4864 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FBN-BRONCOS-BOS &LR;      01-08 1230
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-BRONCOS-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BRONCOS HOPING TO DUPLICATE SINGULAR SENSATION 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By BOB RYAN  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   DENVER _ You want to win the Super Bowl. Everyone in
professional football wants to win the Super Bowl.
</P>
<P>
   But aside from getting a laughable amount of money that doesn't
come close to what baseball and basketball players get for winning
their championships, what does it mean?
</P>
<P>
   The Denver Broncos know. It's about a truly indescribable
feeling. And because they know about that feeling, they want very
much to experience it again.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's an even greater feeling than what I expected,'' confides
fullback Howard Griffith. ``And after a couple of days, it really
settles in. You say, `Wow, I really won a Super Bowl!' ''
</P>
<P>
   They are all team championships, but there is an extra dimension
shared by football and hockey players because they are
body-sacrifice sports. And with all due deference to the grit and
spunk of the pucksters, when it comes to laying the body on the
line for the sake of the unit, there really is football and then
there is everything else.
</P>
<P>
   There is no training camp like football training camp. There is
no physical exercise like a football game. These guys get together
in early July and they put those bodies through torture through
four or five exhibitions, 16 regular-season games, and either two
or three playoff games before arriving at the designated Super Bowl
site more than six months later. The shared experience of pain,
misery, and a perverse sort of joy is immeasurable, and so when all
that blood, toil, tears, and sweat culminates in a championship,
the feeling is so exquisite as to be, yes, indescribable. The only
thing you can be sure of at that point is that you want to
experience it again.
</P>
<P>
   ``Definitely,'' confirms cornerback/punt returner Darrien
Gordon. ``That's why we dedicated ourselves during the offseason,
working out hard. We know what it takes. Now we've gone through all
those exhibitions and regular-season games just to get to the point
where we can win another Super Bowl and get that feeling all over
again.''
</P>
<P>
   Phase I of the quest will take place Saturday when the AFC West
champion Broncos meet the Miami Dolphins at celebrated Mile High
Stadium, where they have gone undefeated during the last two
regular seasons. With the home-field advantage guaranteed
throughout the playoffs, the Broncos find themselves clear
favorites to be the AFC representative Jan. 31 in Miami's Pro
Player Stadium.
</P>
<P>
   Now that the regular season is over, the truth can be told. The
hoo-hah over becoming the first undefeated team since the 1972
Dolphins was a pain in the butt. The Bronocs like entering the
postseason without that extra burden.
</P>
<P>
   ``It had become a big distraction,'' says Griffith. ``It wasn't
something that we had focused on, but we couldn't avoid it. It was
in everyone's conversation, and so inevitably, it became part of
ours. We fell into a little trap, and we were no longer having fun.
Here we had good things happening like producing a 2,000-yard
runner (Terrell Davis) and a 50,000-yard passer (John Elway), and
the talk was all about being undefeated. We had gotten away from
our original goal.''
</P>
<P>
   That goal, of course, was to recapture The Feeling.
</P>
<P>
   The Feeling has gradations. There is the overall feeling, the
one you carry every day. When you have won the championship, the
offseason is exquisite. ``Several times during the offseason,''
explains veteran safety Steve Atwater, one of the few Broncos who
had played in the 1990 Super Bowl loss, ``I would wake up and just
start thinking about the fact that we had won. I would see that
final score, 31-24, in my head. That's a feeling I'll carry with me
the rest of my life.''
</P>
<P>
   There is another aspect of The Feeling. Call it the feeling
within the feeling. Just about everyone agrees there comes a moment
in time when you are so ecstatic, you just about explode. It is a
degree of professional happiness you could not possibly imagine, or
describe.
</P>
<P>
   ``That feeling for me came once we had secured the game and the
offense went back on the field to end it,'' says Griffith. ``And
then when the game ended, you couldn't see any grass _ just
people.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I can tell you the best moment,'' says Gordon. ``When John
Mobley knocked down that ball, a rush of adrenaline went through my
body. At that point, I knew we had the game.''
</P>
<P>
   ``When John Mobley knocked that pass down,'' agrees Atwater, ``I
said, `Fourth down! We're champs!' ''
</P>
<P>
   Mobley is a soft-spoken third-year linebacker out of Kutztown
State. The Fates lined him up as the hero when Brett Favre fired
the last bullet in his gun, a fourth-down pass that was trying to
keep the Packers' fading hopes alive.
</P>
<P>
   ``That play was definitely the big moment for me,'' he says.
``You realize you've finally got the game in hand. And to know that
you were such a big part of it is a great feeling. It's definitely
something I'll remember as long as I'm alive.''
</P>
<P>
   When you are the champion and when your goal is to recreate The
Feeling and The Moment, there are two ways of looking at the
process. Either you can say you own something and it's yours until
someone comes to take it away, or you reason that what got you
there the first time was wanting the prize with all your heart and
acting as if you are going after it for the first time.
</P>
<P>
   Put Griffith down as someone who regards the championship as
personal property. ``It is definitely ours to defend,'' he says.
``Now is our opportunity to defend our title.''
</P>
<P>
   ``It's ours,'' says Gordon. ``We know the feeling. We know the
whole experience. It's a great ride. You get to go to a nice place
and have all that media attention. Then you get to play for the
championship. Who wouldn't want to do it every year?''
</P>
<P>
   Atwater is more cautious, possibly because he is older and
wiser. ``I don't look at it as if it's ours,'' he says. ``It's
something to go after, one game at a time. I mean that. Right now I
am only thinking about Miami. After that, it will be the winner of
the Jets-Jaguars game. And after that, it will be the NFC team in
the Super Bowl. We haven't won anything yet.''
</P>
<P>
   Nine years ago, rookie Atwater suffered through Super Bowl XXIV
in New Orleans. His Broncos were the docile O's to the dominant X's
of the San Francisco 49ers, whose 55-10 triumph remains a classic
example of How To Play Football.
</P>
<P>
   ``I thought, `Well, we were in the Super Bowl, and the worst
that will happen is that we'll be in the AFC title game every
year,' '' Atwater explains. They were back the next year, all
right, but they lost to Buffalo. Atwater would not participate in a
winning playoff game for nearly seven years, or until the Broncos
blasted Jacksonville in the wild-card game Dec. 27, 1997. So he
takes nothing for granted.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm closer to the end of my career than to the beginning,'' he
says. ``If there's a chance I'll get another championship, this
looks like the year. But you have to go out and play the games.''
</P>
<P>
   The regular season is over. The Denver Broncos won't go
undefeated. The finished 14-2, so they won't set any records. They
aren't even thinking of a repeat championship as making some sort
of historical statement. They are thinking of one thing _ The
Feeling, and how to get it back.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-01-08-99 1425EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
