<HEADER>
A4867 &Cx1f; tab-z
r e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-NYTBOOK-CRIME-NYTSF     01-08 1052
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NYTBOOK-CRIME-NYTSF </SLUG>
 
 CRIME
<TEXT>
<P>
   BY MARILYN STASIO &QL; 
 &UR; (Distributed by New York Times Special Features) &LR;  &QC;
</P>
<P>
   Here it is, just in time for those read-for-your-life months in
the dead of winter: a new 87th Precinct novel from Ed McBain. It
happens to be a good one, too, from its swaggering title, THE BIG
BAD CITY (Simon &AMP; Schuster, $25), to the ending that leaves Steve
Carella, the detective who has been on duty in this series since
1956, weak in the knees.
</P>
<P>
   It's just another day in the city that McBain calls Isola. But
``in this city, you had to pay attention. In this city, things were
happening all the time, all over the place.'' In a heartbeat,
Carella and his partner, Artie Brown, are out on the street,
investigating the homicide of a young woman who was strangled in
the park, a case that becomes complicated when it turns out that
the victim was a nun and the nun had breast implants. Nonplused,
the cops have no time to spare for the Cookie Boy, a burglar who
leaves home-baked goodies behind for his victims. Carella is so
distracted, he doesn't even notice that he's being stalked by the
heartless psycho who killed his father in an earlier novel.
</P>
<P>
   Although he's not above a few nun jokes, McBain does his usual
high-wire act of balancing the tone and content of his separate
plot lines: respectful of the nun and her sad little secret, amused
by the cookie monster, vengeful toward the psycho. It's not done by
brute force, either, but with dialogue. When it comes to the voices
of this city, McBain is the man with the golden ear.
</P>
<P>
   Everybody hates Judy Hammer, which gives the former Charlotte,
N.C., police chief a bit of an edge in SOUTHERN CROSS (Putnam,
$25.95), the second book in a new series by Patricia Cornwell, when
Hammer is hired out to Richmond to shape up its sloppy operations.
``The timing was right for a woman to come along and clean house,''
Cornwell observes of the once-proud capital of the Confederacy, now
plagued by soaring homicide rates, marauding drug dealers, nasty
teen-agers, bothersome robberies and other uncivil forces of change
that the natives perceive as a further erosion of their dignity.
</P>
<P>
   Given Hammer's prickly character and the author's storytelling
skills, Cornwell might have come up with some sharp insights into
the criminal corruption that thrives on the social decay of old
cities. But instead of dealing with the big issues, she adopts a
meanspirited satirical tone that makes all the townies look like
Bubbas and boobies. (One prototypical boobie is even named Bubba.)
The only characters who don't come off too badly (and that includes
the sour, paranoid Hammer) are a sadistic young criminal called
Smoke and the teen-age misfit known as Weed whom he torments. ``He
had diagnosed himself as a psychopath,'' we learn about Smoke. ``He
worked hard to be a good one.'' And he succeeds -- to the point of
making us wonder what Cornwell might have done with the Bubbas of
Richmond had she respected them enough to take them seriously.
</P>
<P>
   The best road trips are the ones you take on lost highways.
That's the way it plays, anyway, in CASES (Mysterious Press/Warner,
$23), a quasi-autobiographical novel by Joe Gores about the golden
summer of 1953, when he crossed the country in the company of
various disreputable strangers and ended up in San Francisco
working for a slick private eye. As related by Pierce Duncan, a
college kid who read too much Hemingway at Notre Dame, the
adventure bounds along with the unquenchable energy of youth, its
reckless spirit only slightly tempered by a touch of authorial
wistfulness.
</P>
<P>
   The trip almost ends before it begins, when Dunc gets picked up
for vagrancy in Georgia and spends a month on a chain gang. To
recuperate from that brutalizing experience, which ends in a savage
act of violence, Dunc goes on a roaring drunk in Juarez. Then it's
off to Las Vegas, where he helps an honest boxer train for a
crooked match, and on to California to soak up more life and learn
more lessons in betrayal from people he has come to trust.
</P>
<P>
   Writing with a young man's sense of wonder, Gores seizes a
moment, savors it and then catches the next ride out of town before
the pleasure fades, a style that runs to vivid characters and short
verbs. Dunc, who wants to be a writer, thinks he's got it all
figured out: life is what you do in order to write. (``You went,
you watched, you learned, until you knew, like Hemingway said, that
you had something to write about.'') But the way Gores goes at it,
it seems to be the other way around: writing is what the writer
does to give himself an excuse for living.
</P>
<P>
   With kidnapped children so commonplace in suspense thrillers
that writers have to snatch them by the busload to get any
attention, it's gratifying to watch Craig Holden, in FOUR CORNERS
OF NIGHT (Delacorte, $23.95), find enough meaning in the loss of
one child to support a multilayered morality tale about the
breakdown of trust between husband and wife, parent and child,
friend and friend.
</P>
<P>
   To the narrator, a sensitive cop everybody calls Mack, the
kidnapping of a 12-year-old girl in an unnamed Ohio city is an
invitation to examine a friendship that ended seven years earlier,
when his partner's 11-year-old daughter left the house for softball
practice and was never seen again. The partner, a raging-bull kind
of guy everybody calls Bank, went a little crazy at the time,
dragging Mack into the vortex with him, and things have never been
the same between them. Now, as all the old issues resurface, so
does all the old craziness.
</P>
<P>
   Holden doesn't write a conventional story line. As Mack's mind
races back and forth from the past to the present, the two time
frames intersect and characters collide, sometimes with their own
younger selves. It's a difficult narrative to follow, and it's
disastrous if you lose sympathy for Mack, whose hero worship of
Bank (``He acted at times as my conscience and my spine'') strains
patience. But in the end, it's worth hanging on, if only to see how
far beyond its conventions a talented writer can take the genre.
</P>
<P>
   ----------
</P>
<P>
   (Nonsubscribers: To publish this article, call a New York Times
Syndicate sales representative, Bob Farnell, Olivia Vasquez or
Connie White, at (888) 2-NYTSYN (888-269-8796).
</P>
