<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-01-08 14:27 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4869 &Cx1f; tab-z
r e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-NYTBOOK-FEAR-NYTSF     01-08 0772
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NYTBOOK-FEAR-NYTSF </SLUG>
 
 FEAR
<TEXT>
<P>
   By Irini Spanidou.
</P>
<P>
   182 pp. New York:
</P>
<P>
   Alfred A. Knopf. $21.
</P>
<P>
   ------
 &UR; FATAL ATTRACTIONS
</P>
<P>
   BY BARBARA FISHER
</P>
<P>
   (Distributed by New York Times Special Features) &LR;
</P>
<P>
   FEAR is not only the title but also the explicit theme of Irini
Spanidou's tightly focused second novel. In a series of vignettes
covering a few months of her 14th year, Spanidou's heroine, Anna
Karystinou, recalls and reveals her adolescent terrors.
</P>
<P>
   The daughter of a Greek Army officer, Anna has spent her
childhood being shunted from base to base throughout Greece. The
military has shaped the movements as well as the values of her
family. Strict and Spartan rules govern the household; discipline
and courage are deeply admired. Anna is encouraged to be manly.
(For her 13th birthday, her father presents her with his own copy
of Marcus Aurelius'
</P>
<P>
   ``Meditations,'' with the original inscription intact: ``To my
only son. We are born animals; we learn to be men.'') Approaching
new people and places, Anna anticipates and perhaps even invites
situations that will test her mettle. She is always conscious of
fear. It is the emotion that grips her heart and dominates her
thoughts.
</P>
<P>
   In the first section of the novel, Anna and her family have just
moved to Thessaloniki. It is St. John's Eve, June 1959, and
neighborhood children are jumping through a holiday bonfire burning
in the street. Anna approaches the fire but cannot jump; naturally,
her performance provokes irritation, ridicule and scorn. She
understands that it is not really the fire she fears: ``The sudden
fury, the wild beauty of the flames were a burst of joy in her
heart -- a joy she was too frightened to let out, that tore like
pain.''
</P>
<P>
   Not surprisingly, Anna's father is responsible for her emotional
vigilance. When he challenges her to snuff out the household
candles with her fingers, he insists that it is the fright, not the
fire, that stings. When he takes her to a tavern, she drinks ouzo,
just as he does, until she becomes sick. Although she is nauseated
when she rides in her father's car, he never eases up on the gas
pedal.
</P>
<P>
   At her new school, Anna meets Vera, a girl of her own age but of
greater experience. Arrogant, bold and reckless, Vera proves
frighteningly attractive. While Anna's father constructs lessons
about life, Vera impulsively plunges her new comrade into the thick
of things. The trials within the girls' friendship cannot be
located and described as neatly as the elements of Anna's father's
tests. Indeed, the friendship seems to happen almost against Anna's
will; she is overtaken and overwhelmed by it.
</P>
<P>
   All through this time, the town is in a state of anxiety over a
serial killer called the Dragon, who violates and murders young
women. When Anna is asked by her teacher to write an essay on the
meaning of the killer's name, she focuses on the people's need to
demonize and dehumanize him. ``We hate him,'' she explains,
``because we're not honest enough to hate our fear. We make a
monster of him, so as not to face the monstrous cowardice in us.''
Needless to say, her essay is not appreciated by the teacher or the
class.
</P>
<P>
   In the final scene of the novel, Anna confronts a man she
believes to be the Dragon -- and she doesn't fear being devoured.
In her own way, she has triumphed: ``She felt light, as though a
weight had lifted off, a burden she'd been carrying her whole
life.''
</P>
<P>
   While Spanidou's depiction of Anna's uncertain friendship with
Vera is initially sharp and original, much else in the novel feels
artificial, and thus the whole is less moving than it should be.
Too often Anna's fear feels like an artifact to be isolated and
examined; the events of the novel cluster too neatly around this
central concern. As Anna's story proceeds, the reader longs for it
to embrace something uncontrolled, vague, mysterious -- a fear that
cannot be seen or named or known. There is much more to fear in
life than Anna experiences or imagines; even when she is at the
precarious age of 13, her world seems too small and safe.
</P>
<P>
   The whole novel, from its title onward, feels overcontrolled.
And so, despite the occasional risks Spanidou takes with her
characters, this seems in some ways a fearful performance --
inhibited, contrived, constrained.
</P>
<P>
   --
</P>
<P>
   Barbara Fisher writes Short Takes, a book column, for The Boston
Globe.
</P>
<P>
   ----------
</P>
<P>
   (Nonsubscribers: To publish this article, call a New York Times
Syndicate sales representative, Bob Farnell, Olivia Vasquez or
Connie White, at (888) 2-NYTSYN (888-269-8796).
</P>
