<HEADER>
A4870 &Cx1f; tab-z
r e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-NYTBOOK-WIFE-NYTSF     01-08 0767
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NYTBOOK-WIFE-NYTSF </SLUG>
 
 HEART OF A WIFE
<TEXT>
<P>
   The Diary of a Southern Jewish Woman.
</P>
<P>
   By Helen Jacobus Apte.
</P>
<P>
   222 pp. Wilmington, Del.: SR Books/
</P>
<P>
   $55.
</P>
<P>
   ------
 &UR; DEAR DIARY
</P>
<P>
   BY MARGALIT FOX
</P>
<P>
   (Distributed by New York Times Special Features) &LR;
</P>
<P>
   ``This morning, I picked up The American Grocer,'' a Southern
matron wrote in her diary in 1924. ``Dry reading, yes, but listen
to this under Import Prices: . . . Pepper, Singapore /
</P>
<P>
   Pepper, Zanzibar /
</P>
<P>
   Pepper, Mombasa /
</P>
<P>
   Ginger, Cochin /
</P>
<P>
   Mace, Batavia. . . . If I can get drunk on that, it is surely a
harmless dissipation.''
</P>
<P>
   The intoxicated writer was Helen Jacobus Apte, who from her
marriage in 1909 until shortly before her death in 1946 kept a
diary that furnishes an insightful record of Southern Jewish
bourgeois life in the first half of the 20th century. Discovered by
Apte's family in 1995, ``Heart of a Wife'' (the title was Apte's
own) has been intelligently edited by her grandson Marcus D.
Rosenbaum, a journalist formerly with National Public Radio.
</P>
<P>
   From the start, Apte displays the gifts of a first-rate
memoirist: a contemplative, probing mind; an impassioned, often
elegant prose style; Austenesque powers of social observation; and
a self-analytic bent tempered by an awareness of the wider world
and a wry humor. ``Wouldn't it be funny if I were like those women
I've heard say, 'I could stake my life on my husband's constancy,'
'' she writes in 1911, ``and everyone else begins to talk very fast
about something else?''
</P>
<P>
   Born in Hawkinsville, Ga., in 1886 and brought up mostly in
Atlanta, Helen was raised with her five siblings by their
indomitable mother following the death of their father, a probable
suicide, when Helen was 11. At 22 Helen married another Jewish
Southerner, Day Apte (pronounced ``apt''), who became a prosperous
grocery broker; they spent most of their life together in Florida
and Atlanta.
</P>
<P>
   Swept up in the Victorian ideal of marriage and motherhood, Apte
opens with a dewy-eyed account of wedded bliss. ``These days since
my marriage have been as a string of pearls to me,'' she writes in
1909. ``Here the clear stone of duty, here is fidelity and here the
great flaming gem of passion.'' The marriage was happy, but Apte,
an attractive dark-haired woman, relished male attention, and the
diary hints tantalizingly of dalliances -- but modesty prevented
her disclosing whether any was in fact consummated. (Rosenbaum, who
was born three years after Apte's death, thinks not.)
</P>
<P>
   She was a recorder of history, writing of watching Halley's
comet, witnessing an attempt on F.D.R.'s life, sending her brothers
off to World War I and their sons off to World War II. She was
proud in equal measure to be an American, a Southerner and a Jew,
stirred as deeply by children singing ``Dixie'' as by the blowing
of the ram's horn at Rosh ha-Shanah. ``The sound of the shofar
thrills me more than any aria from grand opera,'' she writes. ``In
me burns the ancient pride of race.''
</P>
<P>
   Apte, who as a girl dreamed of becoming a writer, movingly
articulates the predicament of so many women of her era. As a
social document, the diary can be read as a deeply intelligent
woman's search for fulfillment in an age that promised little
beyond marriage, motherhood and mah-jongg. ``If I only could do
things that really interest me,'' Apte writes in her 40's. ``I have
everything to make a woman happy, yet always there is that vague
unrest, that faint nostalgia -- for what? I don't even know.''
</P>
<P>
   Permeating Apte's chronicle is her battle with a persistent,
inadequately diagnosed illness -- a ``nervous condition of the
organs'' -- that had forced her to leave school at 16. In an
appendix, Rosenbaum convenes a round table of medical experts to
analyze her symptoms. And in informative essays throughout the
book, he places the diary's prevailing themes -- race, religion,
childbearing -- in a broader social context.
</P>
<P>
   The diary's last years, in which Apte makes a conscious effort
to set down ``a record of these momentous times,'' are less
personal, and less satisfying. But the reader's only real regret on
finishing this lovely volume is that Helen Apte lacked the
self-assurance, and the encouragement of her times, to write a real
memoir, filling in the echoing spaces left hauntingly empty here.
</P>
<P>
   --
</P>
<P>
   Margalit Fox is an editor at the Book Review.
</P>
<P>
   ----------
</P>
<P>
   (Nonsubscribers: To publish this article, call a New York Times
Syndicate sales representative, Bob Farnell, Olivia Vasquez or
Connie White, at (888) 2-NYTSYN (888-269-8796).
</P>
