<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-01-08 14:27 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4871 &Cx1f; tab-z
r e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-NYTBOOK-RABIN-1000&AMP;AD     01-08 1553
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NYTBOOK-RABIN-1000&AMP;ADD-NYTSF </SLUG>
 
 MURDER IN THE NAME OF GOD
<TEXT>
<P>
   The Plot to Kill Yitzhak Rabin.
</P>
<P>
   By Michael Karpin and Ina Friedman.
</P>
<P>
   292 pp. N.Y: Metropolitan Books/Holt &AMP; Co. $24.95.
 &UR; BROTHER AGAINST BROTHER
</P>
<P>
   Violence and Extremism in Israeli Politics From Altalena to the
Rabin Assassination.
</P>
<P>
   By Ehud Sprinzak.
</P>
<P>
   366 pp. New York:
</P>
<P>
   The Free Press. $27.50.
</P>
<P>
   ------
 &UR; A POLITICAL ACT
</P>
<P>
   BY DAVID B. GREEN
</P>
<P>
   (Distributed by New York Times Special Features) &LR;
</P>
<P>
   Israelis still have a lot of questions about the assassination
of Yitzhak Rabin by Yigal Amir on Nov. 4, 1995. Often a question
betrays the political leanings of the questioner, hardly surprising
since the murder was nothing if not a political one. Amir, a
25-year-old Orthodox Jewish law student, believed, like many other
Israelis, that in agreeing to give up to the Palestinians land
taken by Israel in the 1967 war, Rabin was not only endangering the
country's security but breaking God's law as well. He was
delivering into the hands of enemies land promised by God to the
people of the covenant. Amir himself told Michael Karpin and Ina
Friedman, the authors of the trenchant ``Murder in the Name of
God'': ``My deed will be understood in the future. I saved the
people of Israel from destruction.''
</P>
<P>
   So although most Israelis accept that Amir was alone when he
pulled the trigger, there are those who still ask if he wasn't
decisively encouraged to act by the national-religious circles he
moved in, and specifically if he didn't have rabbinical sanction to
murder the Prime Minister. Others ask what responsibility Rabin
bore for his own killing, in particular by treating his political
enemies in the national-religious camp with a contempt that verged
on provocation. That the Shin Bet security service, entrusted with
protecting Rabin, failed at its job is a given, but many Israelis
wonder whether the failure included advance knowledge of Amir's
plans, and even his incitement by one of the service's operatives.
Then there are those who have taken refuge in far-fetched
conspiracy theories that see Rabin's No. 2, Shimon Peres,
engineering the murder so that he could assume power.
</P>
<P>
   Karpin, an Israeli journalist, and Friedman, an American-born
Dutch correspondent, attempt, with significant success, not only to
answer most of these questions but also to describe the social,
religious and political background against which the murder took
place. But it is Ehud Sprinzak, a political scientist at the Hebrew
University of Jerusalem, who steps back even farther to provide the
historical context. Examining the left-right, religious-secular,
Sephardi-Ashkenazi and Jewish-Palestinian battlefields over a
50-year period, he reminds us that the threat of internecine
violence has always bubbled near the surface. Occasionally it
erupts, but Sprinzak suggests that wiser heads nearly always seem
to prevail. This is because he sees an ``instinctive Israeli
rejection of civil war,'' whose origins he traces back to a
reaction to the destruction of the Second Temple in A.D. 70, which
Jewish tradition attributes not to the Romans but rather to
``baseless hatred'' among Jews.
</P>
<P>
   Sprinzak reminds us, for example, of several showdowns between
two of Israel's founding fathers, David Ben-Gurion and Menachem
Begin. Though Ben-Gurion, as the country's first Prime Minister,
did not hesitate to humiliate Begin and even use violence against
what he perceived as challenges to his authority, Begin never
picked up the gauntlet of insurrection, committed as he was to
preventing violence among Jews at almost all cost.
</P>
<P>
   But if Sprinzak's book is meant to be mildly reassuring, I found
it unsatisfying, despite his considerable expertise. It is not only
because he writes vaguely of the ``restraining effect'' of Rabin's
murder, which is said to have ``shocked the Israeli extreme right
almost as much as it stunned the left'' -- this, despite the fact
that right-wing demonstrators against the Wye River agreement today
refer to Prime Minister Benjamin Netanyahu as a traitor, just as
they did to Rabin before one right-winger killed him. It is also
because, by limiting his purview to political violence, Sprinzak
disregards the country's growing nonpolitical violence. Crime is on
the rise, and one in every seven women is a victim of physical
abuse at home, according to the Israeli press. Take to the roads
for an hour, listen to a parliamentary debate or a radio call-in
show or simply stand in line at the bank for a few minutes.
Empirically, it would be hard to avoid concluding that this is a
country on a short collective fuse. But none of this merits mention
in ``Brother Against Brother,'' and so the picture is left
incomplete.
</P>
<P>
   Furthermore, if the Rabin murder so shook up Israeli society,
what changes do Israelis have to show for it? It seems instead that
the trauma led to a circling of the wagons, on both right and left.
As Karpin and Friedman write, ``Before Yitzhak Rabin had even been
laid to rest, the Israeli right began complaining that it was the
object of a cynical campaign'' to hold it responsible for his
death. The left, in turn, ``fought back by portraying itself,
rather than Israeli society and democracy, as the injured party.''
But in place of any serious, binding discussion of the issues that
are splitting the country into a loose federation of partisan
camps, Israelis are being treated to costly public-service ads
insipidly depicting pairs of celebrities, one Orthodox, the other
secular, smiling under the slogan ``Different opinions, Yes. Civil
war, No.''
</P>
<P>
   As to those questions that won't go away: Karpin and Friedman
make a convincing case that Yigal Amir was anything but a ``lone
gunman.'' After the Oslo accords were signed, Uri Elitsur, then an
official in the Yesha Council (the political leadership of the West
Bank and Gaza settlers) and today the head of the Prime Minister's
Bureau, called for the attacks on Rabin to be ``aggressive, on the
border of violent.'' Ariel Sharon, then a member of the opposition
Likud party and today Israel's Foreign Minister, said that the
peace agreement was ``graver than what Petain did,'' and Marshal
Petain, it will be recalled, was initially sentenced to death for
collaborating with the Germans. Rabbi Nachum Rabinovitch, a
formidable figure in the Israeli yeshiva world, compared Rabin's
Government to the Nazis themselves, and was taped explaining why he
thought that settlements that might be evacuated under a peace
treaty (something Rabin never proposed) should line their
perimeters with explosives to deter Israeli soldiers from carrying
out the mission. The examples could fill a book, and in fact have.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; BC-NYTBOOK-RABIN-2NDTAKE-NYTSF &QL; 
 &UR; UNDATED: in fact have.) &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The authors are persuasive in piecing together available
information, much of it previously reported, to portray an
environment that should have left Amir feeling secure that his
plans had not only moral support but also support by religious law.
Yet Karpin and Friedman are unable to point to a specific rabbi by
name as responsible for giving the assassin the all-important
sanction that would have served as a green light to Amir's actually
pulling the trigger.
</P>
<P>
   Still, there remains the case of Avishai Raviv, the right-wing
activist and Shin Bet informant, who knew Amir. Conspiracy
theorists have latched on to revelations about Raviv, who
personally set up organizations that attacked Arabs and incited
protests against the Government, as proof that he was an agent
provocateur. What seems more likely is that he was truly a double
agent, providing crucial information to the security services about
the extreme right but also acting on his own as part of that
fringe. Karpin and Friedman seem ready to leave it at that.
</P>
<P>
   But the Israeli public isn't. And though the Attorney General
announced in November that he would seek to have Raviv indicted on
a number of charges, many unanswered questions continue to surround
him. For one, how could Shin Bet, which knew of his outside
initiatives, have kept him on its payroll? And how to explain the
early December bombshell, reported in the newspaper Haaretz, that
Raviv revealed to his Shin Bet interrogators, within days of the
assassination, that he had heard Amir say on at least four
occasions that Rabin had to be assassinated; that he had told Amir
he agreed with him; and that he knew of an earlier attempt by Amir,
in January 1995, to kill Rabin.
</P>
<P>
   If Raviv related these things to his handlers at the time they
happened, then the Shin Bet, by not following up on the
information, was fatally negligent. Finally, there is the biggest
question of all: If the Shin Bet knew about all this three years
ago, why did it take until the autumn of 1998 for charges to be
brought against Raviv? It's enough to make a conspiracy theorist
dance a jig.
</P>
<P>
   --
</P>
<P>
   David B. Green is the literary editor of The Jerusalem Report
and a co-author of ``Shalom, Friend: The Life and Legacy of Yitzhak
Rabin.''
</P>
<P>
   ----------
</P>
<P>
   (Nonsubscribers: To publish this article, call a New York Times
Syndicate sales representative, Bob Farnell, Olivia Vasquez or
Connie White, at (888) 2-NYTSYN (888-269-8796).
</P>
