<HEADER>
A4872 &Cx1f; tab-z
r e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-NYTBOOK-HUNGER-NYTSF     01-08 0771
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NYTBOOK-HUNGER-NYTSF </SLUG>
 
 HOLY HUNGER
<TEXT>
<P>
   A Memoir of Desire.
</P>
<P>
   By Margaret Bullitt-Jonas.
</P>
<P>
   252 pp. New York: Alfred A. Knopf. $23.
</P>
<P>
   ------
 &UR; PIGGING OUT
</P>
<P>
   BY ALEXANDRA HALL
</P>
<P>
   (Distributed by New York Times Special Features) &LR;
</P>
<P>
   ADDICTION is a disease of loneliness, Margaret Bullitt-Jonas
declares. It is a distraction from isolation. ``Holy Hunger'' is
Bullitt-Jonas's memoir of descent into and recovery from her
addiction to overeating.
</P>
<P>
   Growing up with two perfectionist, repressed parents -- an
aggressive, alcoholic father and a passive mother -- the young
Margaret learned her own form of repression: filling herself with
food instead of speaking up for herself. Describing the separate
but equally harsh demands placed on her by her mother (to be
virtuous and noble) and by her father (to overachieve),
Bullitt-Jonas interweaves memories of how food numbed her to those
pressures -- and to the cold relationships that came with them. By
the time she reached adulthood, any negative event, from a romantic
breakup to worry over an unfinished dissertation, could spark a
binge.
</P>
<P>
   Bullitt-Jonas writes that her lowest point came in early
adulthood as a direct result of watching her father being forced to
enter into treatment for alcoholism. ``Healing begins with the end
of illusion, but the fire of truth burns even as it heals. I ran
from its pain. . . . In the months after the intervention, I ate as
I never had before, in binges so frenzied that I was frightened.''
</P>
<P>
   Some of the book's most revealing passages center on the binges
themselves: her anxiety while food shopping for a late-night eating
spree (``I disguise my urgent, anxious greed; I keep my face
calm''), her repentance afterward (``Tomorrow, maybe I won't eat
anything to speak of. I'll go for a long run, maybe plan another
diet''). She describes her overwhelming sense of invisibility while
bingeing and her premeal internal debates over whether to eat at
all, for fear a few bites will turn into a binge.
</P>
<P>
   Bullitt-Jonas's first steps toward recovery came in an Anglican
church, at the foot of the cross. Directly afterward, she attended
her first Overeaters Anonymous meeting, where she found
``community, a network of relationships that penetrated the hard
shell of my isolation.'' And though the concept of a ``higher
power'' is a part of spiritual healing at the organization,
Bullitt-Jonas says she also pursued a more traditional deity, using
meditative prayer to focus on her relationship with God whenever
she felt the urge to binge. ``When I stand my ground and refuse to
overeat, I'm saying yes to a life that is lived in relationship,''
she writes. ``I will listen to my body, and I will listen to its
needs. I will live in connection with others, without closing up,
shutting down, or hiding out.''
</P>
<P>
   It is this ``saying yes to life'' that distinguishes ``Holy
Hunger.'' The emphasis on communicative relationships (with humans
and with God) and on individual responsibility seems to have
allowed Bullitt-Jonas not just to forgive her parents but to accept
partial responsibility for her disease. That is a refreshing change
from the stale blame game of so many memoirs.
</P>
<P>
   Unfortunately, too much of Bullitt-Jonas's prose is repetitive
and heavy-handed, and overflows with flaccid emotion. Transparent
and flat comparisons -- many of them cliches -- litter the book. At
one point, she acknowledges the mundanity of her story, writing,
``Spiritual recovery in O.A. is characterized by humble stories
like this one: stories that aren't glamorous, spectacular or
heroic.'' Then why try to add glamour and melodrama with
overwrought similes like: ``To resist the internal pressure of
anxiety, you must be fierce. Like a warrior on the battlefield, you
must stand fast''? So much for subtlety.
</P>
<P>
   What keeps ``Holy Hunger'' from adding to the pile of memoirs
that are too full of misery to find answers is the author's
relative refusal to find fault. In doing so, she offers an example
of self-examination that is indeed insightful and instructive.
However, though her conclusions may sound mature, Bullitt-Jonas's
endless referrals to the misery of her condition, not to mention
her sentimental and overblown language, undercut that maturity and
therefore ultimately limit how much the book can teach us.
</P>
<P>
   --
</P>
<P>
   Alexandra Hall writes frequently about religious subjects.
</P>
<P>
   ----------
</P>
<P>
   (Nonsubscribers: To publish this article, call a New York Times
Syndicate sales representative, Bob Farnell, Olivia Vasquez or
Connie White, at (888) 2-NYTSYN (888-269-8796).
</P>
</TEXT>
