</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990108.0164 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-01-08 14:27 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4873 &Cx1f; tab-z
r e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-NYTBOOK-NEWYORK-NYTSF     01-08 1195
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NYTBOOK-NEWYORK-NYTSF </SLUG>
 
 THE JEW OF NEW YORK
<TEXT>
<P>
   By Ben Katchor.
</P>
<P>
   Illustrated. 100 pp.
</P>
<P>
   New York: Pantheon Books. $20.
</P>
<P>
   ------
 &UR; GASLIGHT
</P>
<P>
   BY J. HOBERMAN
</P>
<P>
   (Distributed by New York Times Special Features) &LR;
</P>
<P>
   Readers of the comic strip ``Julius Knipl, Real Estate
Photographer,'' published in The Forward as well as in various
alternative weeklies, recognize its creator, Ben Katchor, to be a
unique walker in the city, one who perambulates in time as well as
space.
</P>
<P>
   Katchor's subject is an imaginary, vanished Manhattan -- an
urban museum of musty, haphazard relics. (His first Knipl
collection was subtitled ``The Pleasures of Urban Decay.'') This
alternative New York is a noirish conglomeration of all-night
drugstores, S.R.O.'s, industrial lofts and wholesale novelty
emporiums. The characteristic Katchor neighborhood is the Cheap
Merchandise District -- streets populated mainly by stolid
middle-aged males in battered fedoras and rendered additionally
melancholy with a delicate gray wash that has intimations of
newsprint, soot and overcast skies.
</P>
<P>
   In his new graphic novel, ``The Jew of New York,'' parts of
which appeared in The Forward in 1992 and 1993, Katchor excavates
an even earlier metropolis -- older, more American. More
elaborately plotted than his Knipl adventures, the story is set in
the New York of 1830. Its inspiration is an obscure incident in
Jewish American history -- the attempt in 1825 by the
journalist-politician Maj. Mordecai Manuel Noah to establish the
city of Ararat as a refuge for the world's Jews on an island in the
Niagara River between the United States and Canada.
</P>
<P>
   In Katchor's drawings, reality typically has the quality of a
facade put up to conceal the ruins of some fantastic scheme, and
Noah's bizarre enterprise is more alluded to than represented. A
disgraced kosher slaughterer named Nathan Kishon returns to New
York after a brief stay in Ararat and five years wandering in the
upstate wilderness. His arrival in the city coincides with the New
World Theater's preparations for ``The Jew of New York,'' a
burlesque of Major Noah's utopia written by Prof. Solidus, an
anti-Semitic pamphleteer (who conceals his identity behind a
sinister veil). Katchor introduces a large cast and a half-dozen
subplots while spending nearly a quarter of the narrative on
Kishon's upstate adventures, as recounted over beers in the
Chaldean Gardens to an unscrupulous importer of religious objects,
Mr. Marah. Some concentration is required to follow the skein of
Katchor's plot -- which is rendered all the more tangled by his
talkative characters.
</P>
<P>
   After leaving Ararat, Kishon spent most of his time in the
company of an eccentric trapper who made an erotic fetish of Miss
Patella, the (secretly) one-legged diva and former Noah associate
who is to star in ``The Jew of New York.'' Such occult connections
are commonplace. Katchor's novel is set during the Second Great
Awakening, a period of religious enthusiasm in the United States
vividly evoked in Paul E. Johnson and Sean Wilentz's book ``The
Kingdom of Matthias.'' New sects are proliferating. Many speculate
the Indians are the 10 lost tribes of Israel. (Joseph Smith had
only just made public the divine revelation he called the Book of
Mormon.) Kishon and the trapper pass through New Afflatus -- a
commune that regards oxygen as a holy sacrament and, in the search
for a more indigenously American English, has adopted the Hebrew
alphabet.
</P>
<P>
   Down in the city, however, the main religion is commerce. The
Erie Canal has been open for five years, and New York is booming.
Kishon notes this ``wondrous transformation'' in a series of
panels: ``Fewer pigs are foraging on Broadway. . . . There is a new
mystery to women's clothing. And the Jews' burial ground is now a
sizable necropolis.'' The button merchant Isaac Azarael, awaiting a
lost shipment of abalone shell and pearl oyster, is Katchor's lone
fixed point. The rest of his obsessed cranks and mad businessmen
engage in a series of shifting alliances, promoting elixirs ranging
from Castoreum -- a beaver secretion comparable to Viagra -- to
pickled herring and, most ambitiously, seltzer. A visionary
entrepreneur dreams of carbonating Lake Erie and piping soda water
directly into the city's houses.
</P>
<P>
   More than one character wanders around New York half-naked, as
if in a dream. That many, if not most, of Katchor's principals are
Jews adds another surreal aspect to the mix. Newly arrived from
Jerusalem, a dealer in authentic Holy Land soil ponders a city
where a Hebrew-reciting Indian, Elim-Min-Nopee, appears each Friday
night at Hiram's Museum in a tableau called Welcoming the Sabbath
and -- thanks to the visions of an indigent Jewish scholar -- the
fashionable blow their noses in handkerchiefs of kabbalist design.
Periodically, a character identified only as the Man in an India
Rubber Suit (unofficially representing the Berlin-based Society for
Culture and Science of the Jews) surfaces out of the North River --
as the Hudson was then known -- and into the plot to make his own
ethnographic study of New York's Jews.
</P>
<P>
   Set only a few years before the development of photography,
``The Jew of New York'' mixes actual sites, like the American Hotel
on Broadway, with entirely imaginary ones. However understated his
graphic style, Katchor has an extravagantly assemblagist
imagination. At one point he interrupts the narrative simply to
catalogue the contents of Mr. Marah's desk drawer -- ``assorted
leather straps, a Haggadah in the Iroquois language, a Masonic pin,
a half-dozen miniature scrolls of black parchment, a series of
French boudoir prints in a phylactery bag, a wax esrog, a map of
Odessa.'' It is the mission of ``The Jew of New York'' to connect
these dots.
</P>
<P>
   Throughout, Katchor revels in the strangeness of a self-invented
New World that is also an antiquarian's old one. Nothing is exactly
what it seems. (``He affected the dress and manners of a woodsman,
but was, in fact, no more than an open-air accountant,'' Kishon
explains of his trapper friend.) Gradually accelerating, the
narrative builds to a series of interlocking and disquietingly
comic disasters. Even the most lurid is presented as though behind
glass. The blocky, grimacing figures in Katchor's carefully staged
panels suggest a series of constructed dioramas in some abandoned
municipal historical society.
</P>
<P>
   A word about the physical book itself: The spidery drawings of
Katchor's ``historical romance'' are elegantly bound between two
pieces of embossed but unfinished cardboard and augmented
throughout by an assortment of fake documents, facsimile handbills
and period maps. ``The Jew of New York'' is not only something to
read but to ponder -- an object nearly as strange and striking as
the story it contains.
</P>
<P>
   --
</P>
<P>
   J. Hoberman's most recent book is ``The Red Atlantis: Communist
Culture in the Absence of Communism.''
</P>
<P>
   ----------
</P>
<P>
   (Nonsubscribers: To publish this article, call a New York Times
Syndicate sales representative, Bob Farnell, Olivia Vasquez or
Connie White, at (888) 2-NYTSYN (888-269-8796).
</P>
</TEXT>
