<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-01-08 14:27 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4874 &Cx1f; tab-z
r e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-NYTBOOK-DOLLARS-NYTSF     01-08 0846
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NYTBOOK-DOLLARS-NYTSF </SLUG>
 
 THE NEW DOLLARS AND DREAMS
<TEXT>
<P>
   American Incomes and Economic Change.
</P>
<P>
   By Frank Levy.
</P>
<P>
   248 pp. New York: Russell Sage Foundation. $39.95.
</P>
<P>
   ------
 &UR; SHOW ME THE MONEY!
</P>
<P>
   BY MARK LEVINSON
</P>
<P>
   (Distributed by New York Times Special Features) &LR;
</P>
<P>
   THIS volume is an update of Frank Levy's 1987 book ``Dollars and
Dreams.'' In both, Levy, the Daniel Rose Professor of Urban
Economics at the Massachusetts Institute of Technology, analyzes
the performance of the American economy since World War II,
explaining that for a quarter-century after the war most Americans
enjoyed steadily rising living standards. This began to change in
1973, when OPEC ended an era of inexpensive energy. In addition,
productivity gains, which had averaged 2.5 percent to 3 percent a
year until 1973, have fallen to little more than 1 percent, for
reasons that remain puzzling to Levy and other experts. Since
rising incomes depend on gains in efficiency, income growth
stagnated and inequality worsened.
</P>
<P>
   But in ``The New Dollars and Dreams'' Levy goes beyond his first
book in two ways. First, he updates his analysis to include the
economic recovery of the 1990's. This is done brilliantly. Second,
he attempts to explain the causes of growing inequality. Here, I
believe, he is less successful.
</P>
<P>
   One of the merits of Levy's book is that he provides a framework
for answering the question: How is the economy doing? According to
some criteria -- inflation, unemployment, the Government deficit
and the stock market -- the economy is in great shape. But Levy has
a different focus.
</P>
<P>
   He shows that despite economic expansion in the 1990's,
inequality has been growing. In 1969 the wealthiest 5 percent of
families had 15.6 percent of the income. In 1996 it had 20.3
percent. Meanwhile the poorest 20 percent of families had 5.6
percent of the income in 1969 and only 4.2 percent in 1996. Levy is
at his best when he looks behind these numbers. If, for example,
you want to know why inequality has such a different feel today
than it did several decades ago (the answer: because the nation's
regions are more alike while differences within regions have grown
larger), or how the changing occupational structure affects white
male workers compared with black female workers, Levy's book is the
place to look.
</P>
<P>
   The main reason for growing inequality, according to Levy, is
that since the late 1970's there has been a shift in the economy's
demand for skills, leading to a collapse in opportunities and wages
for low-skilled workers. Levy attributes the shift to technological
changes. Likewise, there is greater demand for workers with
advanced training or education. Thus the main policy suggestion
that emerges from Levy's book is to improve schools, especially in
communities with large numbers of unskilled workers.
</P>
<P>
   When he is tracking income distribution Levy is meticulous. Each
particular fact is documented. It is therefore strange that he
never presents evidence to support his broader claim that
technological change is occurring at a faster rate now than in the
past. He simply takes it as self-evident. He is not alone in this
view. It is probably the predominant view among economists. But is
it true?
</P>
<P>
   Several economists (most notably David Howell, James Galbraith,
Lawrence Mishel and Jared Bernstein) have presented strong evidence
contradicting the notion that inequality or falling wages can be
explained by technological change. First, throughout most of the
1990's, the real earnings of skilled workers (college graduates)
were falling. The earnings gap between college-educated workers and
workers without a college degree has been getting larger only
because the real wages of the latter are falling faster than those
of the former. Second, if technological change is accelerating in a
way that requires greater skill it should be reflected in growing
productivity. But productivity growth in this period has been
meager. Third, and most important, there is no evidence that the
pace of technological change has accelerated since the late 1970's.
</P>
<P>
   At the end of his book Levy hints at another explanation for
growing inequality. There has been, he states, a ``shift of power
away from the average worker and toward a firm's shareholders.
Deregulation, globalization and technology have reduced the typical
employee's bargaining power, and no countervailing institution has
arisen to exert an opposite force.'' Levy's failure to pursue the
implications of this statement -- that the problem is not that
workers lack skills, but that they lack power -- is the main flaw
in an otherwise thoughtful and meticulously researched book.
</P>
<P>
   --
</P>
<P>
   Mark Levinson is the chief economist at the Union of
Needletrades, Industrial and Textile Employees and the book review
editor of Dissent magazine.
</P>
<P>
   ----------
</P>
<P>
   (Nonsubscribers: To publish this article, call a New York Times
Syndicate sales representative, Bob Farnell, Olivia Vasquez or
Connie White, at (888) 2-NYTSYN (888-269-8796).
</P>
