<HEADER>
A4875 &Cx1f; tab-z
r e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-NYTBOOK-STRANGERS-NYT     01-08 0756
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NYTBOOK-STRANGERS-NYTSF </SLUG>
 
 STRANGERS TO THE LAW
<TEXT>
<P>
   Gay People on Trial.
</P>
<P>
   By Lisa Keen and Suzanne B. Goldberg.
</P>
<P>
   272 pp. Ann Arbor: U. of Michigan Press. $34.50.
</P>
<P>
   ------
 &UR; COURT V. COURT
</P>
<P>
   BY ROGER PARLOFF
</P>
<P>
   (Distributed by New York Times Special Features) &LR;
</P>
<P>
   SOLDIERS in America's gay and lesbian rights movement plot their
operations from treacherous legal terrain. In Bowers v. Hardwick in
1986, a 5-4 majority of the Supreme Court upheld a Georgia felony
statute that punished consensual homosexual sodomy with up to 20
years' imprisonment. As a matter of logic, the decision signaled
few restraints on what the heterosexual majority could do to the
homosexual minority at the ballot box. For, as Justice Antonin
Scalia later wrote, ``If it is constitutionally permissible for a
state to make homosexual conduct criminal, surely it is
constitutionally permissible for a state to enact other laws merely
disfavoring homosexual conduct.''
</P>
<P>
   Until, that is, May 1996, when the gay rights movement won a
stunning, if enigmatic, constitutional victory in Romer v. Evans,
the subject of Lisa Keen and Suzanne Goldberg's ``Strangers to the
Law.'' In Romer, the Supreme Court recognized for the first time
that the equal protection clause does bar at least some laws that
disadvantage homosexuals as a class.
</P>
<P>
   Writing for the 6-3 majority, Justice Anthony M. Kennedy struck
down a Colorado ballot initiative passed in 1992 as an amendment to
the state constitution. Kennedy found that the amendment (known as
Amendment 2), barring the state or local government from forbidding
discrimination on the basis of sexual orientation, effectively
disqualified ``a class of persons from the right to seek specific
protection from the law'' and was ``inexplicable by anything but
animus toward the class that it affects.'' ``A state cannot so deem
a class of persons a stranger to its laws,'' he concluded. In an
apoplectic dissent, Scalia protested Kennedy's failure even to
mention Bowers. Since Romer did not overrule Bowers, both
precedents survive today, in great and unexplained tension.
</P>
<P>
   Keen covered the case for two gay newspapers; Goldberg was an
attorney on the legal team that challenged the amendment in court.
Though the authors are hardly neutrals in the Kulturkampf between
homosexuals and the religious right, they display admirable
emotional restraint and objectivity in recounting the case.
</P>
<P>
   In an effort to strengthen the analogy between homosexuality and
race, the advocates for the gay cause presented scientific evidence
at trial of the immutability of sexual orientation, its likely
genetic component and the history of unsuccessful attempts to
``cure'' it medically and psychiatrically, through lobotomy,
electroshock and nausea-inducing drugs for ``aversion'' therapy.
They also recounted the history of discrimination homosexuals have
faced, including an executive order President Dwight D. Eisenhower
signed in 1953 that had the effect of firing homosexuals not only
from Federal jobs but from all private companies with Federal
contracts -- that is, from an estimated one-fifth of the nation's
jobs. The lawyers outlined the early history of gay rights
societies in America, which were invariably suppressed. In 1924,
for instance, a gay rights newsletter in Chicago was shut down by
police acting under pornography laws, notwithstanding that the
newsletter's content was entirely political.
</P>
<P>
   Yet while the book contains some fascinating material, it will
never become the ``Gideon's Trumpet'' of the gay rights movement.
The authors ultimately succeed too well at muting their own -- or
anyone's -- emotional investment in the case. The key lawyers or
parties in the case never become more than names affixed to a
collection of credentials. The sequential listing of the legal
arguments made by each side, followed by the opposing side's
retorts, are more arid than most nonlawyers will probably be able
to endure. Ironically, the bristling, intemperate, antipodal
opinions that compose the Supreme Court ruling in the case, set out
in an appendix at the end, easily make for the most engaging
reading in the entire volume.
</P>
<P>
   --
</P>
<P>
   Roger Parloff, an attorney and a senior writer at The American
Lawyer magazine, is the author of ``Triple Jeopardy.''
</P>
<P>
   ----------
</P>
<P>
   (Nonsubscribers: To publish this article, call a New York Times
Syndicate sales representative, Bob Farnell, Olivia Vasquez or
Connie White, at (888) 2-NYTSYN (888-269-8796).
</P>
