<HEADER>
A4877 &Cx1f; tab-z
r e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-NYTBOOK-BELL-NYTSF     01-08 0741
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NYTBOOK-BELL-NYTSF </SLUG>
 
 SELECTED LETTERS OF VANESSA BELL
<TEXT>
<P>
   Edited by Regina Marler.
</P>
<P>
   Illustrated. 593 pp. Wakefield, R.I.:
</P>
<P>
   Moyer Bell. Paper, $14.95.
</P>
<P>
   ------
 &UR; MRS. BOHEMIAN
</P>
<P>
   BY MARGOT PETERS
</P>
<P>
   (Distributed by New York Times Special Features) &LR;
</P>
<P>
   BOHEMIAN, liberated Bloomsbury was tougher on its women than its
men. While young Vanessa and Virginia Stephen relished pronouncing
forbidden words involving the male anatomy, Bloomsbury men hardly
got the same charge from those involving females, many having
little interest in women's privates anyway. Lytton Strachey, Adrian
Stephen and Duncan Grant rewarded Vanessa's penchant for explicit
talk with accounts of their homosexual activities -- not always
entertaining, considering she was in love with Duncan.
</P>
<P>
   Another reward of sexual freedom was Virginia's flirtation with
Clive Bell shortly after he and Vanessa married, a betrayal that
put an end to the deep intimacy of the sisters forever. It hardly
mattered that Clive had dozens of affairs, since Vanessa fell in
love with Roger Fry and then with Duncan, reducing her marriage to
a formality. It did matter to her that she had to accept Duncan's
male lovers; in fact, two weeks after her death in 1961, Paul Roche
left his wife to return permanently to him. Little wonder that
reading ``Selected Letters of Vanessa Bell,'' expertly edited by
Regina Marler, author of ``Bloomsbury Pie: The Making of the
Bloomsbury Boom,'' one is as conscious of the pain of a liberated
woman's life as of its pleasures.
</P>
<P>
   Though more women might have strengthened their hand, Vanessa
and Virginia resisted female intruders into the circle. Dora
Carrington was tolerated at a distance, Lady Ottoline Morrell
humored (and mercilessly made fun of). But let Clive attempt to
incorporate Mary Hutchinson, or Roger Fry Helen Anrep, or Maynard
Keynes Lydia Lopokova, or Clive (again) Barbara Bagenal -- and
slamming doors echoed from Surrey to Gordon Square. The sisters
jealously guarded the power they possessed as insiders privy to
minutest Bloomsbury gossip.
</P>
<P>
   To be sure, Vanessa the painter is less obsessed with gossip
than Virginia the novelist: color, light, texture and pattern,
rather than intricate personal relationships, are her stock in
trade. She doesn't dwell on emotions -- ``I'm always being told I
don't understand my own feelings'' -- while Virginia constantly
takes hers over to the window to examine them. But of course
reading Vanessa Bell is not reading Virginia Woolf. Vanessa's
letters have none of Virginia's subtle reasoning, sly innuendo,
skittish rhythms and divine wit. At the same time they have little
of Virginia's snobbery, arch self-consciousness and teasing
cruelty. Never could Vanessa have written, ``Kiss her, most
passionately, in all my private places -- neck -- , and arm, and
eyeball, and tell her -- what new thing is there to tell her? how
fond I am of her husband?'' as Virginia wrote Clive -- not only
because Vanessa preferred men, but because she was innocent of such
subtle bitchery.
</P>
<P>
   ``Maternal instincts'' were generally scorned by iconoclastic
Bloomsbury; they are one of Vanessa's strong suits. She bore three
children -- Julian and Quentin with Clive, Angelica with Duncan --
and was, as her letters testify, a more devoted mother than
Bloomsbury could credit. It is endearing when she not only hauls
her children along to St.-Tropez on a painting trip but
requisitions jam and oatmeal for them from home. For all her
bohemianism, Vanessa could be conventional: she remained Mrs. Bell
all her life, called her daughter ``Bell,'' did not tell Angelica
that Duncan was her father until she was 17.
</P>
<P>
   Yet far more than maternity, art was Vanessa's calling. Many of
her letters are about painting, which she discusses, if not with
Roger Fry's erudition, still with passion and perception. Her chief
concern is finding light and landscape; her chief bond with Duncan
became their mutual passion for canvas and brush. Virginia looked
inward, Vanessa outward. If she was not a genius like her sister,
her appealing letters reveal a larger person.
</P>
<P>
   --
</P>
<P>
   Margot Peters's most recent books are ``Wild Justice'' and ``May
Sarton: A Biography.''
</P>
<P>
   ----------
</P>
<P>
   (Nonsubscribers: To publish this article, call a New York Times
Syndicate sales representative, Bob Farnell, Olivia Vasquez or
Connie White, at (888) 2-NYTSYN (888-269-8796).
</P>
</TEXT>
