<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-01-08 14:28 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4878 &Cx1f; tab-z
r e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-NYTBOOK-DREAM-NYTSF     01-08 0756
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NYTBOOK-DREAM-NYTSF </SLUG>
 
 THE DREAM MISTRESS
<TEXT>
<P>
   By Jenny Diski.
</P>
<P>
   186 pp. Hopewell, N.J.:
</P>
<P>
   The Ecco Press. $23.95.
</P>
<P>
   ------
 &UR; DREAM WEAVER
</P>
<P>
   BY DIANA POSTLETHWAITE
</P>
<P>
   (Distributed by New York Times Special Features) &LR;
</P>
<P>
   JENNY DISKI'S elegantly wrought and unsettling novel ``The Dream
Mistress'' is prefaced by an epigraph from Sigmund Freud: ``Those
dreams best fulfill their function about which one knows nothing
after waking.'' As the book opens, the 46-year-old Mimi awakens
suddenly in a London movie theater to find herself facing both a
blank screen and the abusive rage of her lover, Jack. Like Anne
Sexton's disturbed and disturbing Briar Rose, Mimi is ``a trance
girl'' who ``keeps slipping off'' uncontrollably, at odd times and
places, into seemingly dreamless sleep.
</P>
<P>
   Mimi turns on Jack, walking away from the empty theater and his
obliterating anger, and quickly loses her bearings: ``It was
impossible to grasp where the corridor was finally leading.'' In a
dark alley, she comes upon the ``immobile shadow'' of an
unconscious bag woman: ``Half a face, the part not concealed by
shrouding rags and matted clumps of hair, was visible.'' Instead of
turning away in disgust, Mimi summons help. ``Bella!'' the
ambulance medic exclaims sardonically, christening the nameless
woman toward whom Mimi is inexplicably drawn.
</P>
<P>
   Diski's heroine, it seems, is wandering the landscape of the
Freudian uncanny: that place where we oxymoronically find ourselves
lost and everything is strangely familiar; where (in Freud's own
words) all roads inexorably ``lead back to something long known to
us.''
</P>
<P>
   Who is ``Bella,'' unknown to herself as well as to Mimi? ``A
face without features offered no story, and above all else it was a
story that Bella ached for. She closed her eyes . . . and searched
the darkness for something with a narrative.'' Like a Freudian
analyst, the reader of Diski's novel must connect the dots,
excavate the hidden links that will give Bella a face, a voice --
and a story.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Dream Mistress'' weaves narrative, dream and memory into a
teasing web of resonant interconnections. Seven of the book's
intermingled sections are numbered, four are named and one, without
number or name, is preceded by a blank page. The numbered sections
are conventional chapters following Mimi and Bella, introduced in
Chapter 1. The named sections (``Mask,'' ``Bella'') are, I think,
Mimi's ``unknown'' dreams about two other women, both also called
Bella: the faceless survivor of a bomb blast who lives in a white
room without mirrors (a dream version of Mimi herself?) and a
speechless religious fanatic who abandons her past (a dream version
of the bag lady?).
</P>
<P>
   That numberless, nameless section is the key: it introduces us
to Miriam, a 10-year-old girl cruelly abandoned by her deeply
disturbed mother. This chapter (Mimi's repressed memories?)
directly links the damaged child Miriam to the damaged adult Mimi,
the unremembering narcoleptic drawn to lovers who abandon her. It
also suggests that Bella the bag lady (metaphorically speaking, at
least) is Mimi-Miriam's missing mother.
</P>
<P>
   Cracking the ingenious (and at times, baffling) code of ``The
Dream Mistress'' provides a challenge for any reader who fancies a
psychological game of Clue. But the distinctive power of Diski's
novel lies in the striking way she intermingles a tone of
steel-trap rationality with potent images from the oozy underbelly
of the subconscious.
</P>
<P>
   The final chapter of ``The Dream Mistress'' consists of the
first dream Mimi had ever recollected: a woman sits in a tower
above the sea, ``concentrated on a large notebook on the bed, in
which she is writing.'' Readers of Diski's
autobiography-cum-travelogue, ``Skating to Antarctica: A Journey to
the End of the World,'' will recognize in Mimi-Miriam many
similarities with the nonfictional Jenny-Jennifer of that book, an
abandoned daughter who feels most comfortable in blank white
spaces. Jenny-Jennifer, I suggest, also appears in Mimi's final
dream: she is the writing woman. In truth, that woman has been
present throughout the novel, artfully spinning painful memory and
vivid dream into the redemptive gold of story.
</P>
<P>
   --
</P>
<P>
   Diana Postlethwaite teaches English literature at St. Olaf
College in Northfield, Minn.
</P>
<P>
   ----------
</P>
<P>
   (Nonsubscribers: To publish this article, call a New York Times
Syndicate sales representative, Bob Farnell, Olivia Vasquez or
Connie White, at (888) 2-NYTSYN (888-269-8796).
</P>
</TEXT>
