<HEADER>
A4879 &Cx1f; tab-z
r e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-NYTBOOK-VIETNAM-1000&AMP;     01-08 2723
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NYTBOOK-VIETNAM-1000&AMP;ADD-NYTSF </SLUG>
 
 REPORTING VIETNAM
<TEXT>
<P>
   Part One: American Journalism 1959-1969.
</P>
<P>
   Illustrated. 858 pp. New York:
</P>
<P>
   The Library of America. $35.
 &UR; REPORTING VIETNAM
</P>
<P>
   Part Two: American Journalism 1969-1975.
</P>
<P>
   Illustrated. 857 pp. New York:
</P>
<P>
   The Library of America. $35.
</P>
<P>
   ------
 &UR; OH, WHAT AN UGLY WAR
</P>
<P>
   BY THOMAS POWERS
</P>
<P>
   (Distributed by New York Times Special Features) &LR;
</P>
<P>
   THE sad truth that confronts the serious reader at the end of
1,500 pages of journalism about America's longest war, as beautiful
to hold in these two Library of America volumes as they are painful
to read, is best stated in its simplest form: we lost.
</P>
<P>
   Not all have agreed on this point over the years. The armed
services like to say we quit and left, maybe, but we weren't beaten
in the field, and the reporter Stanley Karnow, represented by two
pieces in Volume 1 and author of a successful 1983 book about the
war, ``Vietnam: A History,'' entitled his first chapter ``The War
That Nobody Won.'' There is a sense in which that is partly true,
perhaps, of all wars, but even those too young to have lived
through the losing of the war either on the ground or on television
won't have much trouble recognizing defeat when they see it in the
11 pieces recounting the collapse of Saigon's Army and Government
in April 1975, and especially in those describing the harrowing
scene at the American Embassy on the night of April 30. That night
and into the following morning, the last Americans clambered aboard
helicopters on the embassy roof and took off for Navy ships in the
South China Sea while thousands of Vietnamese who had been promised
rescue waited in orderly lines in the embassy compound searching
the sky for helicopters that never returned.
</P>
<P>
   Who won the war is not a trivial point. War is painful and
expensive for winners and losers alike. The great achievement of
many of the writers collected in these two volumes -- Gloria
Emerson, Michael Herr, James Sterba, Jonathan Randal, Kevin
Buckley, Jonathan Schell, Lee Lescaze and others who followed the
war out into the boondocks -- was precisely to capture what the war
did to people. Read Specialist 4 Jack P. Smith on the unbelievable
savagery of the battle of the Ia Drang Valley in November 1965, or
John Saar's description of the havoc wreaked in February 1971 by an
accidental bombing of an American unit near Laos with a new type of
ordnance known as a cluster bomb -- one big bomb that separates
into many smaller bombs spewing out ``a blizzard of steel'' over a
wide area. Saar writes, ``If one plane on one run can inflict such
savage hurt, I think, what unimaginable suffering has been
inflicted by thousands of planes on thousands of runs?''
</P>
<P>
   Saar was giving a typically fleeting thought to those on the
other side, but his question goes to the heart of the war as a
whole. What the war did to people physically was horrific to
experience and terrifying to witness. What it did to them
psychologically was often just as crippling and just as permament.
Tot that all up, if there is any meaningful way such things can be
quantified, and call it he price of the war. Forget the money. The
Americans and their North Vietnamese and Vietcong adversaries each
paid a high price in blood for their effort to assert control over
the territory of South Vietnam by force of arms, but the Vietnamese
won -- they got something -- while the Americans lost, and got
nothing. That is why the Vietnam War occupies a special place in
American history and in the American psyche, and why these two
volumes reek of pain, anger, sadness, failure and the despair that
accompanies the recognition that suffering will never be redeemed.
</P>
<P>
   The two volumes of ``Reporting Vietnam'' are very different from
the Library of America's earlier collection of reporting about the
Second World War. Getting shot or blown up in World War II hurt
just as much, the dead were just as dead, but the writing about
that war was infused with a conviction that the suffering was not
stupid and futile. The men who said the sacrifice was important and
would end with success were right. Vietnam, on the other hand,
represents no American triumph of any kind, just a long, slow,
bitter, expensive, inexorable failure ending in sudden, dramatic
and irreversible loss.
</P>
<P>
   The odd thing, hidden from the correspondents who reported on
the war as it unfolded but made clear from the work of historians
over the subsequent decades, is that the American leaders directing
the war from Washington had only the frailest confidence in success
themselves, and took each fatal step mainly in the hope of avoiding
defeat in the near term -- that is, before the next election. From
the beginning, which surely came no later than the late 1950's,
they received prescient warnings and advice from those who knew
something about the history of the French experience in what had
been called Indochina. No witness of the French agony assured
Washington that it should expect an easy success where Paris over
eight years of war had failed. Bernard B. Fall, who wrote a classic
book about the crushing French defeat in a set-piece battle at Dien
Bien Phu, ``Hell in a Very Small Place,'' reported a telling remark
by the Vietnamese Communist leader Ho Chi Minh in The Saturday
Evening Post in November 1962, one of the first pieces reprinted in
``Reporting Vietnam.'' ``I think the Americans greatly
underestimate the determination of the Vietnamese people,'' said
Ho. His Prime Minister, Pham Van Dong, expanded upon this simple
theme. ``Americans do not like long, inconclusive wars -- and this
is going to be a long, inconclusive war,'' he told Fall. ``Thus we
are sure to win in the end.'' As American soldiers often said
later, that was the whole story right there.
</P>
<P>
   Yet the whole story is too big even for the two volumes of
``Reporting Vietnam.'' With few exceptions, the 116 pieces and two
entire books -- Daniel Lang's ``Casualties of War'' and Michael
Herr's ``Dispatches'' -- reprinted here were written at the time
and confine themselves to the American experience of the war in
Vietnam. A few pieces (Michael Kinsley's funny and revealing
account of the night some Harvard profs gave hell to Henry
Kissinger; Doris Kearns's essay, based on interviews with Lyndon
Baines Johnson two years after he left the White House, on what was
going through his mind as he took the plunge) touch on the politics
of the war in Washington; others (Francine du Plessix Gray on the
politics of the New Mobilization Committee to End the War in
Vietnam, James A. Michener on the shooting of students at Kent
State University in Ohio by the National Guard in May 1970) tip the
hat to the domestic upheaval commonly referred to as the student
movement, the antiwar movement, ``the movement'' or simply ``the
Sixties.''
</P>
<P>
   Mostly, though, the war in ``Reporting Vietnam'' is the war of
soldiers in the field, not the one at home, or the one described in
Saigon by American military spokesmen at a daily briefing reporters
called ``the 5 o'clock follies'' -- a war of units, numbers,
objectives, initiatives, programs, targets, enemy body counts given
in exact numbers and American casualties described as ``light'' or
``moderate.'' It's the war that kids had been drafted to fight for
12-month tours of duty (13 months for marines, whose officers, on
the evidence presented here, took pride in doing more and taking
higher casualties than the Army), and the war that newspaper
correspondents visited in the field knowing that they were a
helicopter ride away from comfortable beds and hot meals. Just
about every writer represented in these two volumes seemed to have
a lively apprehension of the moral complexity of reporting on a war
other men had to fight, and very, very few betray any appetite for
geopolitical arguments that Vietnam was the linchpin of defense
against the global creep of Communism.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; BC-NYTBOOK-VIETNAM-2NDTAKE-NYTSF &QL; 
 &UR; UNDATED: creep of Communism.) &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Until pretty late in the game the precise outcome, if not the
general drift, of the war was hidden from those who wrote about it
under the pressure of editors and deadlines, so their work is best
judged now as writing -- that is, for the vividness, the human
warmth, the sharpness of eye and the freedom from illusion of the
correspondents' take on what they were seeing and hearing. How does
it hold up as writing all these years later?
</P>
<P>
   The range is wide. At the bottom is a piece by Stewart Alsop, a
decent man who wrote a fine book about the approach of his own
death, ``Stay of Execution,'' but is represented here by a June
1970 Newsweek column on the draft that manages to be both obtuse
and mean. At the very top is the complete text of Michael Herr's
``Dispatches,'' a book that would shine in any company, in which
Herr hunts down the innermost heart of the war with a passion for
the right connection of thinking and feeling that makes you think
of Kierkegaard. For those who tried to sell some theory of the war
Herr has fathomless contempt. Of the way in which he was
simultaneously observing and in the war, Herr, speaking about some
American soldiers, says, ``I stood as close to them as I could
without actually being one of them, and then I stood as far back as
I could without leaving the planet.''
</P>
<P>
   What Herr saw was dark and poisonous in the way of slow poisons.
Some escaped the war any way they could, some embraced it. An
example of the latter took such cold pleasure in combat that he
frightened even the war lovers on a team of long-range patrollers
who stalked the Vietcong in their jungles like scalp hunters in the
old West. '' 'No man, I'm sorry, he's just too crazy for me,' one
of the men in his team said. 'All's you got to do is look in his
eyes, that's the whole . . . story right there.' ''
</P>
<P>
   ``Al1 I ever managed,'' Herr comments, ``was one quick look in,
and that was like looking at the floor of an ocean.''
</P>
<P>
   My guess is that ``Dispatches'' is the book every correspondent
dreamed of writing -- an utterly unsoftened, unillusioned account
of what the war was like, what it was like to travel back and forth
between the inanities of Military Assistance Command Vietnam
headquarters in Saigon and the field where the soldiers counted the
days till departure, what all that sorrow, excitement and fear did
to alter young reporters, many of whom had gentle upbringings and
expensive educations. ``Dispatches'' is the one piece of writing in
``Reporting Vietnam'' that, denied a natural early home in this
collection, probably would have found its way into the Library of
America on its own merits in due time.
</P>
<P>
   But Herr was far from the only reporter to write well about
Vietnam. Having a way with words was the smaller part of it. What
seems to have opened the door to getting it right was putting aside
all care for what the war was about as defined in Washington or
Hanoi, and judging the war instead by what it was and did. Almost
everything collected in ``Reporting Vietnam'' captures some part of
that reality, mostly in the form of short, sharp vignettes or
apposite remarks. Some examples:
</P>
<P>
   Ward Just, from his book ``To What End,'' published in 1968:
``The basic and most useful question is not and never has been the
effect of American firepower on the Vietnamese -- it is the effect
on the Americans, who bear responsibility for its use. . . . What
the hell does it take to win this thing? asked a general late one
night. What do we have to do to them?''
</P>
<P>
   Michael J. Arlen, in an article in The New Yorker in September
1967, quoting a Marine corporal at Con Thien: '' 'When we first
came up here, we used to call the enemy Victor Charlie,' he said.
'But now we call him Charles. Mister Charles.' ''
</P>
<P>
   H. D. S. Greenway, quoting a Vietcong leader following the Paris
peace accords in The Washington Post, March 1973: ``Today you see
us in the forest but tomorrow you will see us in the cities.''
</P>
<P>
   Every word from a piece by James Sterba in The New York Times
Magazine, Oct. 18, 1970. The words mostly belong to others --
soldiers describing battles, the transcript of radio conversations,
officers issuing orders, an Army news release, ``an irreverent song
of unknown origin,'' and much else. But in this piece, a kind of
collage, Sterba captures the weird dissonance of a war in which
almost every attempt to communicate conveyed a subversive message
of recoil and despair, as in the following exchange between a
hospital lab technician and a voice that must be Sterba's:
</P>
<P>
   '' 'We use just about all the blood we get. We're in sort of a
slump now -- not much action -- so we got quite a bit on hand.'
</P>
<P>
   '' 'What do you do with it when it gets too old?'
</P>
<P>
   '' 'Give it to the gook hospitals.' ''
</P>
<P>
   And with that, of course, we touch at last, if glancingly, what
is almost entirely missing from this book, as it was almost
entirely missing from the thinking of the global strategists in
Washington: the gooks, Mister Charles, the Vietcong, Hanoi, the
enemy. The first rule of war is to know your enemy, but Americans
above a certain Government grade --colonel and its civilian
equivalent, say -- have tended to blame almost everything but the
enemy for the loss of the war.
</P>
<P>
   ``Sooner or later,'' Herr writes, ``all of us heard one version
or another of 'My marines are winning this war, and you people are
losing it for us in your papers.' '' What these officers ``with the
teeth shut behind the smiles'' were seeking was some explanation
why the other side didn't give up, but they were looking in the
wrong place. What drove the Vietnamese to fight for 30 years more
or less nonstop -- from 1946 until the last Americans left Saigon
in 1975 -- wasn't faith that negativism at The New York Times would
bail them out in the end, but some much deeper combination of
national character and political organization hidden from most
Americans.
</P>
<P>
   One of the few to attempt to understand it was Frances
FitzGerald, whose account of the cycles of revolution in Vietnamese
national history, ``Fire in the Lake,'' won a National Book Award
in 1973. Her record of the happy-talk Rotary Club optimism of
Americans trying to pacify the Mekong Delta, published originally
in Vogue in January 1967, is one of only a handful of pieces in
``Reporting Vietnam'' that might be said to be about the other
side. Others print letters and diaries taken from the bodies of
North Vietnamese soldiers (Fox Butterfield, The New York Times
Magazine, February 1973); quote Vietcong prisoners (Bernard B.
Fall, The New Republic, February 1967, in the last piece Fall wrote
before he was killed by a boobytrap near Hue); describe the years
of moral struggle between American P.O.W.'s and their North
Vietnamese jailers (Lieut. Comdr. John S. McCain 3d, U.S. News &AMP;
World Report, May 1973). But it was the American war reporters were
sent to cover, that is what they mainly wrote about, and that is
what we get in ``Reporting Vietnam.'' A great many Americans live
or live again in these pages, but most of the Vietnamese who appear
are trying to please, are running for cover, or are dead.
</P>
<P>
   So coming to understand the character of the men who won the war
in Vietnam, or why we lost, is not the reward for reading these two
volumes. What they deliver instead is a sense of what the war was
like, and why so many people feel about it the way they do.
</P>
<P>
   If you are wondering if the war looks different now, after the
end of the cold war and the passage of so many years, I can only
say, not to me. If anything, the mistakes seem even clearer, the
failure more inevitable. Those reporters were there, and they
weren't making it up. But if you are of a certain age, and if you
are wondering if reading all this stuff, much of it no doubt for
the second time, will bring back what it was like to live through
the first time, the answer is yes -- in a muted way, perhaps, but
yes.
</P>
<P>
   --
</P>
<P>
   Thomas Powers is the author, most recently, of ``Heisenberg's
War: The Secret History of the German Bomb.''
</P>
<P>
   ----------
</P>
<P>
   (Nonsubscribers: To publish this article, call a New York Times
Syndicate sales representative, Bob Farnell, Olivia Vasquez or
Connie White, at (888) 2-NYTSYN (888-269-8796).
</P>
