<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NYTBOOK-BOTTLE-NYTSF </SLUG>
 
 NOTE FOUND IN A BOTTLE
<TEXT>
<P>
   My Life as a Drinker.
</P>
<P>
   By Susan Cheever.
</P>
<P>
   192 pp. New York: Simon &AMP; Schuster. $23.
</P>
<P>
   ------
 &UR; A WOMAN UNDER THE INFLUENCE
</P>
<P>
   BY SARAH PAYNE STUART
</P>
<P>
   (Distributed by New York Times Special Features) &LR;
</P>
<P>
   I grew up in the 1960s, when, if you were lucky, you could
refuse to go to classes and lie on top of your bed all day smoking
cigarettes and be called the hope of a new generation. We were
revered for being brutally frank before we were old enough to have
anything to be brutally frank about, and when the memoir craze hit
my contemporaries, I stuck to Trollope. Then one day I read Susanna
Kaysen's ``Girl, Interrupted,'' about the writer's experience at a
mental hospital, and found it thoroughly satisfying in a way I
wouldn't have if it had been fiction. The fact that it was true,
that it was a document (it was even illustrated with documents),
infused it with a power not found in the author's earlier novels.
</P>
<P>
   Suddenly I understood that the new memoirs, the good ones
anyway, weren't about confession, they were about history. And that
behind the writer's words was the thought, ``Well, I may be
invading people's privacy and possibly ruining lives, but at least
what I am saying is important to the larger picture.''
</P>
<P>
   The early chapters of Susan Cheever's third memoir, ``Note Found
in a Bottle,'' carry this power because in them she is writing
about her own alcoholism as part of a long heritage -- a heritage
dating as far back as the Pilgrims (who, with beer as their staple
drink, got through their Puritanical life the same way I got
through my 20s -- buzzed). Cheever's own beer-hauling ancestors
came over in 1630, not, as her father used to say, with ``the
trash'' who came over on the Mayflower.
</P>
<P>
   Drinking was more than an accepted vice when Cheever was growing
up in the 1950s, it was a virtue. ``Every evening at 6 o'clock,
right on schedule -- because almost everything in those days was
right on schedule -- the grown-ups in the suburbs would prepare for
what they called their preprandial libation.''
</P>
<P>
   I did not need to look up ``preprandial'' in the dictionary
because I am a WASP. A WASP is allowed to drink all the libations
she wants as long as she does it at the proper time (when ``the sun
is over the yardarm''), and with the proper euphemisms (``May I
freshen that for you?'' or ``Would you care for a little
soupcon?''). Cheever paints this culture with a loving nostalgia,
quite generous for a reformed alcoholic, allowing one to ignore,
for a moment, the noble but less-than-romantic prospect of A.A.
beckoning in the distance, which lent a grim inevitability even to
Caroline Knapp's elegant memoir, ``Drinking: A Love Story.''
</P>
<P>
   Cheever lyrically evokes the suburban '50s, when the grown-ups
dressed like grown-ups -- the men in ``brimmed felt hats,'' the
women in frocks and high heels -- when the men didn't seem to work
too hard and the women didn't work at all, when, in short, it
looked awfully good to be a grown-up, especially at cocktail hour.
``I loved the paraphernalia of drinking, the slippery ice trays
that I was allowed to refill and the pungent olives, which were my
first childhood treat, and I loved the way the adults got loose and
happy and forgot that I was just a child.'' Cheever looked forward
to the day when she too would join the ranks and ``greet my
homecoming hubby with the ice bucket and the martini shaker.'' The
rest of this memoir recounts a series of alcohol-fueled affairs,
marriages and fresh starts that Cheever embarked upon before
finally relinquishing this dream.
</P>
<P>
   Unfortunately, as Cheever ticks off disaster after disaster --
which she attributes to drinking or, occasionally, to the bond of
true love -- she loses her larger context and writes from the more
limited field of her own inner feelings, soggy ground for any
writer: ``A lot of my old feelings started bumping around in the
attic where I had put them. There were crashing sounds as if
someone was going wild up there, and rattling sounds as if someone
was trying to escape into my conscious mind.'' There is a certain
bravery to her brutal frankness; at the same time, she lacks a
basic self-awareness. She confesses to sometimes sleeping with
three men on the same day (while she is married with a child), but
then maintains it couldn't be helped. She recounts how she and one
lover (and later husband) sent a beautifully wrapped box of dog
excrement to William Styron, postmarked from her parents' hometown,
because he gave a friend's book a bad review. We learn how she
taught another married lover (and later husband) how to cheat on
his wife, and in the midst of it all we are told, ``I had three
amazing marriages to three exceptional men.''
</P>
<P>
   Phrases like ``life's great tapestry'' and ``the ebb and flow of
human quirkiness and eccentricity'' crop up. Cheever treads a field
best left untrodden by even the most gifted WASP's (one has only to
glance at Edith Wharton's pornographic forays), the sex scene: ``We
explored each other's bodies inch by inch as if we were discovering
a hidden treasure.'' And most perilous of all, she writes about the
process of writing: ``Most of the time I just typed away without
thinking. Story after story floated to the surface of my mind. The
prose seemed to burn right on the page. I reread each page over and
over again, amazed at how stirring the words seemed to me.'' Or, a
few pages later: ``As I've become a more accomplished writer with
each book, I have relinquished more control over my writing. It's
true I have to sit down and spend the time writing, but beyond
that, what happens doesn't seem to be up to me.''
</P>
<P>
   But the truth is, it's when Cheever takes control, as she does
in the earlier parts of this memoir, that her writing has true
resonance.
</P>
<P>
   --
</P>
<P>
   Sarah Payne Stuart's latest book is ``My First Cousin Once
Removed: Money, Madness and the Family of Robert Lowell.''
</P>
<P>
   ----------
</P>
<P>
   (Nonsubscribers: To publish this article, call a New York Times
Syndicate sales representative, Bob Farnell, Olivia Vasquez or
Connie White, at (888) 2-NYTSYN (888-269-8796).
</P>
</TEXT>
