<HEADER>
A4883 &Cx1f; tab-z
r e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-NYTBOOK-MARA-NYTSF     01-08 1137
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NYTBOOK-MARA-NYTSF </SLUG>
 
 MARA AND DANN
<TEXT>
<P>
   An Adventure.
</P>
<P>
   By Doris Lessing.
</P>
<P>
   407 pp. New York: Harper Flamingo. $25.
</P>
<P>
   ------
 &UR; BACK TO IFRIK
</P>
<P>
   BY MICHAEL UPCHURCH
</P>
<P>
   (Distributed by New York Times Special Features) &LR;
</P>
<P>
   THE last time Doris Lessing visited the future, the news wasn't
good. In her science fiction quintet, ``Canopus in Argos:
Archives,'' she predicted nuclear holocaust for Planet Earth -- and
a name change too. Once Lessing's star-hopping do-gooders saw the
writing on the wall, they mothballed their euphonious-sounding name
for us, Rohanda, and substituted Shikasta. (That's Canopean for
``the unfortunate one'' or ``the afflicted.'') Place names have
been changed in Lessing's latest novel as well, but not so
drastically as to be unrecognizable. Ifrik, she tells us in an
author's note, is Africa (where Lessing grew up). Cong and Nilus
are the continent's two great rivers, the Congo and the Nile. Even
the bustling metropolis of Bilma can be found in the atlas,
although it appears to be a mere camel stop in the Sahara. Other
places -- Rustam, Chelops -- won't ring any bells.
</P>
<P>
   As for the news, it's still not good. ``Mara and Dann'' is set
thousands of years in the future, during an ice age that has
redrawn the geopolitical map. The book opens briskly enough with
two young children being spirited away from their home in a time of
turmoil. Given new names to protect them from their family's
enemies, they take refuge with an older woman of their tribe, the
Mahondis. Seven-year-old Mara keeps her eyes wide open in this
unsettled world -- her favorite girlhood game is What Did You See?
-- and her curiosity about what she is and where she is proves
persistent. Vague memories of a ``great, airy palace'' where she
and her younger brother once lived provide one clue. So do the 50
gold pieces that her protectress bequeaths her and Dann.
</P>
<P>
   As brother and sister grow up, however, Mara's thirst for
knowledge takes second place to her thirst for water, her hunger
for food and her yearning for safety. Drought is spreading in Ifrik
as seasonal rains become ever more unpredictable, and by the time
the siblings reach their teens, they are forced to join the hordes
of refugees heading north. En route they meet every kind of danger:
beasts of prey, wildfires, slave traders and aspiring rapists. All
the while, they're teased by an intense carnal awareness of each
other, and by suspicions that they've been set apart for a special
destiny. Indeed, both the enemies and the (surprisingly
well-informed) friends they repeatedly encounter suggest that
several parties are monitoring every step of their ordeal.
</P>
<P>
   ``Mara and Dann'' has the shape of a myth or a folk tale in
which a humble foundling's illustrious origins are eventually
revealed after much hardship. But the book's proportions are those
of an epic; at more than 400 pages, it feels inflated, repetitious
and strangely devoid of surprise. All the necessary elements are
here, often dazzling in their invention, but only intermittently do
they coalesce into tension-filled narrative. Mara herself describes
her ``adventure'' as a ``slog of endurance,'' and those same words,
unfortunately, sometimes apply to the book itself.
</P>
<P>
   It need not have been that way. In a more compressed form --
Lessing's own novel ``The Fifth Child'' offers a possible model --
``Mara and Dann'' could have worked. With greater attention to
character detail, especially that of Dann, it could perhaps have
sustained its length. Dann is clearly meant to be the mercurial
companion who adds a sense of danger and unpredictability to Mara's
journey. But his changes of mood are so mechanically rendered that
they fail to convince, either as legend-in-the-making or
psychological case history. Lacking any interior logic of his own,
he simply feels like a puppet.
</P>
<P>
   MARA, with her eagerness to see and understand the world, works
more to Lessing's purpose, especially in the book's first half,
when her losses yield grim lessons. (``If you're going to feel sad
every time someone dies or goes away,'' she tells herself, ``then
that is all you'll ever do.'') Survival plainly demands a numbing
of feelings -- but in later, safer circumstances, Mara finds it
impossible to describe this brutalizing knowledge or the perils
that gave rise to it. The distance between disaster-struck refugees
and complacent communities that can't see disaster coming is
vividly rendered.
</P>
<P>
   Vivid too are the hand-me-down aspects of Mara's world.
Everywhere she and Dann go, they find themselves stepping through
the detritus of previous civilizations, some unfamiliar, others
more recognizable. (Oral tradition, for example, has preserved
Flaubert's novel as the tale of ``Mam Bova, who hated her husband,
tried to seduce a handsome youth, who rejected her, so she took
poison and died.'') Other special effects include a whole catalogue
of mutated reptiles, along with oversize scorpions and
pincer-wielding beetles; the dispatch with which Lessing consigns
various human victims to these creatures can make certain passages
read like outtakes from ``Starship Troopers.'' A similarly sinister
note is sounded with the appearance of a tribe of look-alikes,
perhaps the result of 21st-century cloning experiments. These
clone-people and other menacing racial varieties convey a chilling
message: no matter what we look like after thousands of years of
evolution, we'll still be fighting.
</P>
<P>
   Such flourishes are fine as far as they go, but they can't make
up for the book's slack pace or lack of involving characters. Like
much of ``Canopus in Argos,'' ``Mara and Dann'' suggests that
Lessing can sometimes be oblivious of her greatest strength as a
writer: her ability to dissect the vacillations and delusions of
20th-century people living in a 20th-century world. Her best books
of the 1990's have been her two volumes of autobiography, in which
Lessing herself emerges as a more engagingly problematic character
than any fictional creation she has come up with lately.
</P>
<P>
   Surely the author of such memorable novels as ``The Golden
Notebook,'' ``The Memoirs of a Survivor'' and ``The Good
Terrorist'' has little left to prove in fiction. Here's hoping she
will soon carry on with her self-portrait -- which, with its
meticulous observation of her African and English worlds and its
withering reading of our century's ideological cant (and her own
susceptibility to it), is the superlative capstone to an
illustrious career.
</P>
<P>
   --
</P>
<P>
   Michael Upchurch's novels include ``Passive Intruder'' and ``The
Flame Forest.''
</P>
<P>
   ----------
</P>
<P>
   (Nonsubscribers: To publish this article, call a New York Times
Syndicate sales representative, Bob Farnell, Olivia Vasquez or
Connie White, at (888) 2-NYTSYN (888-269-8796).
</P>
