<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NYTBOOK-PAPERBACKS-NYTSF </SLUG>
 
 NEW &AMP; NOTEWORTHY PAPERBACKS
<TEXT>
<P>
   BY SCOTT VEALE
 &UR; (Distributed by New York Times Special Features) &LR;  &QC;
</P>
<P>
   WOLF SOLENT
</P>
<P>
   By John Cowper Powys.
</P>
<P>
   Vintage International, $15.
</P>
<P>
   This British novel, recently restored to print, follows a
sensitive young Londoner who returns to an insulated village in his
native Dorset and becomes romantically entwined with two vastly
different women. '' 'Wolf Solent' is a modern prose 'Hamlet,' ''
Percy Hutchison wrote here in 1929. ``The novel is a momentous
piece of work . . . of transcendent interest and great beauty.''
</P>
<P>
   GOD &AMP; THE AMERICAN WRITER
</P>
<P>
   By Alfred Kazin.
</P>
<P>
   Vintage, $14.
</P>
<P>
   A renowned critic and impassioned reader, in his final book
before his death last year at the age of 83, argues that classic
American writers from Hawthorne to Frost to Faulkner were driven by
spiritual passion and a yearning for something like faith,
motivations that echo the author's own emotional approach to his
subject. ``He strolls from writer to writer as if through the rooms
of his own house, occasionally shaking hands, by means of an
anecdote, with someone he has known personally,'' Paul Berman wrote
in the Book Review in 1997, adding that when Kazin hits his target
squarely, ``the effect is spectacular and brilliant.''
</P>
<P>
   FLYING LEAP: STORIES
</P>
<P>
   By Judy Budnitz.
</P>
<P>
   Picador USA, $12.
</P>
<P>
   These tales twist familiar middle-class terrain into strange new
shapes, creating a world where a local baker creates babies from
dough and high school cheerleaders get so charged up at a pep rally
that they set themselves on fire. In 1998 our reviewer, J. D.
Biersdorfer, called this ``a consistently impressive debut.''
</P>
<P>
   FATHER, SOLDIER, SON:
</P>
<P>
   Memoir of a Platoon Leader in Vietnam
</P>
<P>
   By Nathaniel Tripp.
</P>
<P>
   Steerforth, $14.
</P>
<P>
   In his unflinching account of the horrors of war, an ex-
infantry lieutenant also describes his efforts to confront his
guilt and achieve manhood through love and family. ``The writing is
cathartic, an expiation by a middle-aged man haunted by everything
that went wrong in war, in youth, in country,'' David D. Gilmore
wrote here in 1997. In Patches of Fire: A Story of War and
Redemption, by Albert French (Anchor/Doubleday, $12.95), a black
novelist tells how his Vietnam experiences became a wellspring he
tapped into after years of struggle in civilian life. ``It is a
classic tale, life-affirming and updated for the modern age,''
Terrence Maitland said here in 1997.
</P>
<P>
   THE GUN SELLER
</P>
<P>
   By Hugh Laurie.
</P>
<P>
   Washington Square/Pocket, $14.
</P>
<P>
   The hero of this tongue-in-cheek techno-spy thriller is a
dissolute ex-military man who gets sucked into international
intrigue involving money launderers, terrorists, arms dealers and,
of course, beautiful babes. The result is ``a genuinely witty and
sophisticated entertainment,'' Christopher Buckley wrote here in
1997.
</P>
<P>
   UTOPIA PARKWAY:
</P>
<P>
   The Life and Work of Joseph Cornell
</P>
<P>
   By Deborah Solomon.
</P>
<P>
   Noonday/Farrar, Straus &AMP; Giroux, $16.
</P>
<P>
   The author maintains that the secretive artist known for his
boxes filled with scraps, cutouts and trinkets was primarily an
iconographer and archivist with a basement full of ``source
material,'' including files on movie actresses and 19th-century
ballerinas. In 1997 our reviewer, James R. Mellow, called this a
``thoroughly detailed, highly informative biography.'' Mary
Cassatt: A Life, by Nancy Mowll Mathews (Yale University, $18),
shows how the American-born Mary Cassatt (1844-1926) blended her
love of painting with a desire for financial success. In 1994 in
these pages, Carol Armstrong cited some shortcomings in the
author's straight-ahead approach, but said the book was
``thoroughgoing in its resurrection of the contexts and
conditions'' of the artist's life.
</P>
<P>
   WHERE TROUBLE SLEEPS
</P>
<P>
   By Clyde Edgerton.
</P>
<P>
   Ballantine, $12.95.
</P>
<P>
   Much of this novel is told by a 6-year-old boy who describes
what happens when a stranger in a stolen Buick rolls into sleepy
Listre, N.C., in 1950. The book is ``as much the story of a man who
brings random badness into a good place as it is the story of a
boy's search for his own salvation,'' Mark Childress wrote here in
1997. Rural North Carolina circa 1950 is also the setting for The
Big Ballad Jamboree, by Donald Davidson (University Press of
Mississippi, $17), which follows the fortunes of a country singer
and his sweetheart, who is collecting folk songs for her M.A.
thesis. In 1996 in these pages, George Garrett called this ``a
lighthearted and (in a musical sense) light-fingered'' novel.
</P>
<P>
   THE REICHMANNS:
</P>
<P>
   Family, Faith, Fortune, and the Empire of Olympia &AMP; York
</P>
<P>
   By Anthony Bianco.
</P>
<P>
   Times Books/Random House, $20.
</P>
<P>
   This large-scale chronicle tracks the rise and fall of an
Orthodox Jewish family that at its peak in the 1980's amassed
phenomenal wealth through its international property holdings. In
1997 our reviewer, Mordecai Richler, called the book ``a nicely
balanced study.''
</P>
<P>
   THE VOICE IMITATOR
</P>
<P>
   By Thomas Bernhard. Translated by Kenneth J.
</P>
<P>
   Northcott.
</P>
<P>
   University of Chicago, $10.
</P>
<P>
   The tiny stories in this 1978 collection showcase the Austrian
writer's obsessions with hypocrisy, corruption, murder and lunacy
-- and especially his contempt for his homeland. ``Bernhard's rage
against society'' is ``a highly artistic undertaking,'' Peter
Filkins wrote here in 1997.
</P>
<P>
   ----------
</P>
<P>
   (Nonsubscribers: To publish this article, call a New York Times
Syndicate sales representative, Bob Farnell, Olivia Vasquez or
Connie White, at (888) 2-NYTSYN (888-269-8796).
</P>
