<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990108.0174 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-01-08 14:29 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4885 &Cx1f; tab-z
r e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-NYTBOOK-FICTION-BRIEF     01-08 1542
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NYTBOOK-FICTION-BRIEFS-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BOOKS IN BRIEF: FICTION
</HEADLINE>
  (Distributed by New York Times Special Features)  
<TEXT>
<P>
   In modern fiction about the lives of women in middle age, or
fast approaching it, there seems to be one overarching goal -- to
create fresh, quirky types with attention-grabbing jobs and wacky
lives, characters who make at least three crackling quips per page.
Writers will do anything, in other words, to avoid the cliche of
the aging woman who fears she'll either lose -- or never find --
the right man. What's remarkable about Toni Graham's first book,
THE DAIQUIRI GIRLS (University of Massachusetts, $24.95), a
collection of short stories about four 30-something or older women,
is that Graham takes characters who could easily become dreary
stereotypes -- characters left feeling insecure by failed marriages
and failing health, by the realities of aging, by men who treat
them badly -- and fleshes them out beautifully, without doing the
literary equivalent of a rain dance to convince us they're
``interesting.'' Graham doesn't wallow in these women's
vulnerability, but she doesn't apologize for it either. She uses
their loneliness and confusion as backdrops for the action, not as
personality traits. And her prose is entertaining without being
forced: Graham allows a good deal of brainy good humor to flow
naturally. (One woman, who gets a chilly reception from her lover's
progressive, liberal-thinking family because she's a WASP, notes
dryly: ``I saw Phillip's sister Lenore last Sunday night at the
family party. Her smile reminded me of the grille of an old Buick,
except mean.'') Graham's characters aren't spunky role models, cozy
potential best friends or women who run with the wolves. They're
the sort who keep the wolves on their toes. _ STEPHANIE ZACHAREK
</P>
<P>
   IN THE PRESENCE OF HORSES
</P>
<P>
   By Barbara Dimmick.
</P>
<P>
   Doubleday, $23.95.
</P>
<P>
   All the traditional lingo and lore tucked into Barbara Dimmick's
first novel is evidence of her inspired pursuit of her favorite
animal, the horse. Luckily, she's equally good at depicting human
characters. Natalie Baxter, the protagonist of ``In the Presence of
Horses,'' is a peripatetic trainer whose worldly goods include a
pickup truck, three saddles, a good tea set and a ladylike pistol.
Newly installed as the head of a tiny riding academy in rural
Pennsylvania, the mysteriously shell-shocked Natalie seems
oblivious of everything, including the obsessions of her
increasingly creepy new boss. In fact, the only focus of her
attention is her favorite project, the education of an unruly black
horse called Twister. Natalie's schooling of him builds to a
crucial encounter, but while the ensuing incident begs for nothing
more than a quiet coda, Dimmick takes the novel farther. Without
giving anything away, it's safe to reveal that the action includes
a scene in Natalie's boss's bedroom -- and another in an old
Moravian church on a Christmas Eve paralyzed by snow. _ SALLY
ECKHOFF
</P>
<P>
   OUT OF THE DARK
</P>
<P>
   By Patrick Modiano.
</P>
<P>
   Translated by Jordan Stump.
</P>
<P>
   University of Nebraska Press, cloth, $40; paper, $12.
</P>
<P>
   The unnamed narrator of the French novelist Patrick Modiano's
latest book is so successful at escaping his past that he barely
remembers he has one. Only Jacqueline, a fellow drifter whom he met
on the Left Bank in Paris when they were both very young, remains
vivid in his memory. As the action flashes back, the narrator, a
university dropout, is selling used art books for a living.
Jacqueline, who intently plays pinball at the Cafe Dante, is living
in a seedy hotel with a small-time gambler named Gerard. Bent on
going to Majorca, where she and Gerard know an American who writes
detective novels, Jacqueline hatches a plan to steal money from a
gambling friend of Gerard's. Soon enough, a suitcase full of
banknotes is in her possession, and she and the narrator are in
full flight, passing through London on their way south. But they
fall in with a shady crowd, and one night Jacqueline simply
disappears. Fifteen years later, her life and the narrator's
intersect once again when he sees her on the street in Paris and
follows her home. Although Jacqueline pretends not to recognize
him, they spend a few hours together; the next day, he discovers
that she and her husband have suddenly gone to Majorca. Another 15
years pass, and Jacqueline reappears -- but this time the narrator
avoids an encounter. In working through these comings and goings,
Modiano's existential noir novel employs a moody, atmospheric prose
(smoothly translated by Jordan Stump) to create a strange love
story that somehow manages to be both suspenseful and
contemplative. _ JENNY MCPHEE
</P>
<P>
   FROM A SEALED ROOM
</P>
<P>
   By Rachel Kadish.
</P>
<P>
   Putnam, $25.95.
</P>
<P>
   Out of a fictional landscape informed by the gulf war, the Los
Angeles riots, the Holocaust, the back streets of Brooklyn and
strife-torn Israel hurtles Rachel Kadish's first novel, an intense,
ambitious story that explores the chasms between truth and
falsehood, past and present. The plot circles around three women,
each of whom struggles to admit light into the sealed room of her
inner life. Tami is so accustomed to being ignored by her husband
that it's just a matter of time before her silence curdles into
vitriolic hatred. Her cousin Maya, an American studying at Hebrew
University, moves to a ``religious area'' of Jerusalem and starts
to lose control of her life. At the same time, Maya's neighbor,
Shifra, a Holocaust survivor from Poland, clings ferociously to
memories of the family she has lost -- and develops a curious
devotion to Maya. Most of the action in the book is Maya's, and it
is her future that seems most at stake. But the novel's soul is
found in Shifra. _ MAGGIE GALEHOUSE
</P>
<P>
   SELENE OF THE SPIRITS
</P>
<P>
   By Melissa Pritchard.
</P>
<P>
   Ontario Review Press,
</P>
<P>
   cloth, $22; paper, $14.
</P>
<P>
   At first, Melissa Pritchard's second novel seems like little
more than an episodic portrait of Victorian England with a bit of
romance tucked inside. But as it unfolds, ``Selene of the Spirits''
becomes much more: a commentary on the social landscape of an era
and a rumination on the consequences of forbidden love. The novel
is loosely based on the story of Florence Cook, a popular
spiritualist in late-19th-century London. Her fictional
counterpart, Selene Cook, is a beautiful but poor young woman who
initially seems to want little more than public recognition of her
distinctive psychic gifts. Yet Selene's talents also attract a
wealthy benefactor who supports her family, takes her on trips and
showers her with expensive presents. All this comes to an end when
a member of the London Dialectical Society attends a seance led by
Selene and publicly declares her a fraud. Determined to save both
her reputation and her family, Selene calls on William Herapath, a
respected (and respectably married) scientist, to verify her talent
-- but even as he begins to doubt her, he also begins to fall in
love with her. It is at this point that the novel moves beyond
historical pastiche and becomes a full-blown -- if somewhat
melodramatic -- love story. Selene's happiness unravels quickly and
irrevocably, her only salvation her own unwavering belief in her
spiritual gifts. From these unfortunate circumstances, Selene
emerges as a heroine in the mold of Sarah Woodruff of ``The French
Lieutenant's Woman'': a willful and deceptive woman who nonetheless
earns our sympathy. _ NORA KRUG
</P>
<P>
   ARCADE
</P>
<P>
   Or, How to Write a Novel.
</P>
<P>
   By Gordon Lish.
</P>
<P>
   Four Walls Eight Windows, $22.
</P>
<P>
   Self-indulgent, full of cute verbal games played to scant point,
stuffed with aimless wandering and empty speculating, with the
barest hint of plot or purpose, ``Arcade'' is nevertheless a
surprisingly funny bit of fiction. Rather than tell us a story,
Gordon Lish has chosen to let readers in on a kind of psychotherapy
session in which he -- or the character who shares his name -- lies
on the couch spewing out disordered memories, fears and obsessions
while we act as his collective shrink. The novel challenges us to
add up its twists and turns because, at first glance anyway, Lish
sure doesn't. Instead, the narrator -- ``I Gordon'' -- wanders
through childhood vacations at a sort of bungalow colony, pausing
every now and then to wonder about such things as flowers, strudel,
the expression ``consider yourself kissed'' and words ending in
-ade. This is all entertaining, but as I Gordon moves on to his
later years, he begins to rant. A novelist now, he berates the
members of his fickle public (``I pour out my heart to you''),
treating them to ridicule, insults and blank pages before revealing
that the whole performance has been something of a private joke
played on us, his therapist/readers: ``Everything in this book, it
is all of it made up.'' For Lish's many acolytes, ``Arcade'' will
carry a lot of weight; for his equally numerous detractors, it will
be weightless. The rest of us can just read and enjoy it. _ JAMES
POLK
</P>
<P>
   ----------
</P>
<P>
   (Nonsubscribers: To publish this article, call a New York Times
Syndicate sales representative, Bob Farnell, Olivia Vasquez or
Connie White, at (888) 2-NYTSYN (888-269-8796).
</P>
