<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990108.0175 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-01-08 14:29 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4886 &Cx1f; tab-z
r e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-NYTBOOK-NONFICTION-BR     01-08 1459
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NYTBOOK-NONFICTION-BRIEFS-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BOOKS IN BRIEF: FICTION
</HEADLINE>
  (Distributed by New York Times Special Features)  
<TEXT>
<P>
   ``How . . . could the much-studied Impressionist revolution . .
. espouse a genre which . . . might be considered the least
amenable to any divergence from accepted practice?'' asks Colin B.
Bailey, the chief curator of the National Gallery of Canada, at the
beginning of RENOIR'S PORTRAITS: Impressions of an Age (Yale
University/National Gallery of Canada, $30). Financial necessity is
the primary answer: commissioned portraits paid the rent. Moreover,
we learn that Renoir was the only Impressionist to achieve
financial security through the practice of portraiture. ``Yet, just
as the Impressionists catered, at one level, to the conventional
requirements for bourgeois representation -- namely, portrait
painting -- so did they also expand and redefine the genre,''
Bailey writes. During the years of his greatest demand as a
portraitist, between 1878 and 1883, Renoir painted his most
ambitious compositions of contemporary life, including ``Luncheon
of the Boating Party,'' ``Ball at the Moulin de la Galette,''
``Dance in the City'' and ``Dance in the Country.'' Anne Distel,
the chief conservator at the Musee d'Orsay in Paris, contributes a
cogent essay about the Impressionist patron and collector Leon
Clapisson. But it is the art historian Linda Nochlin who offers the
sharpest and most perceptive essay in the book, giving the social
context for Impressionist portraiture and offering a fascinating
explication of Degas's ``Place de la Concorde,'' among other
paintings. Nochlin's essay, which scarcely mentions Renoir, is
accompanied by reproductions of portraits by fellow Impressionists
like Manet, Degas and Cassatt that invite comparison with Renoir
and present an odd disjunction; some readers may feel that the
detailed, psychologically oriented and less romanticized portraits
by these painters are more successful than Renoir's. Nevertheless,
Renoir's portraits, Bailey believes, are distinguished by ``the
extraordinary light with which they are imbued.'' _ ROBIN
LIPPINCOTT
</P>
<P>
   COLLUSION
</P>
<P>
   Memoir of a Young Girl and Her Ballet Master.
</P>
<P>
   By Evan Zimroth.
</P>
<P>
   Harper Flamingo, $23.
</P>
<P>
   Mothers, don't let your daughters grow up to be dancers. Unless
you want them -- like Evan Zimroth -- to participate in a ``gavotte
of power and submission'' with a Svengali-like expatriate Russian
ballet master. From the time he chose her for advanced training at
the age of 12 (``Do you want to be a great dancer?'') until he
expelled her from his ballet school three years later for
insubordination, the teacher (whom Zimroth identifies only as F.)
challenged, taught, manipulated, occasionally struck and ultimately
made a dancer of an innocent, determined and remarkably
self-centered little girl. Now a poet and novelist but still
seemingly carrying a torch for her impossible ideal of a ``revered
teacher,'' Zimroth writes about training in a ``Darwinian'' world
where, she says, ``normal'' values are reversed. Brutality and
sadism are teaching tools, dancers starve themselves into thinness,
rehearsal studio mirrors give back only images of imperfection,
superstition is rampant and nondancers are the ``real'' people. All
this pain is for the ``focus of all ballet training,'' for ``what
is seen on stage -- the human body in all its breathtaking
loveliness.'' It's enough to make you think of Narcissus as a guy
who didn't much care how he looked. _ MARY GRACE BUTLER
</P>
<P>
   BAD MAN BLUES
</P>
<P>
   A Portable George Garrett.
</P>
<P>
   Southern Methodist University, $19.95.
</P>
<P>
   For a writer less formidably gifted than George Garrett, the act
of publishing an assortment of seemingly unrelated recent stories,
autobiographical fragments and essays might seem mere hubris. But
Garrett, who has published more than 25 volumes of fiction, essays,
poetry and plays, is a mesmerizing storyteller. His humane voice,
sly humor and persistent fascination with the origins of extreme,
even self-destructive, behavior serve to weave the disparate pieces
in ``Bad Man Blues'' into a lively and entertaining whole.
Garrett's accounts from his 40 years as a peripatetic English
professor nicely skewer academic foibles (and offer startling
glimpses of luminaries like Bernard Malamud). And a concluding
section of personal essays -- on his resilient family, on his
admiration for Joe Louis, on the brother he never had -- offer more
somber but equally vivid meditations on the ways in which we strive
to come to grips with the world. For Garrett that striving has
usually focused on the act of creation, and in the essay ``Going to
See the Elephant'' he offers a ringing defense of the necessity of
storytellers, who ``speak for and of the wounds and sorrows of . .
. our people. We act as spiritual treasurers for their stories.''
``Bad Man Blues'' offers further evidence of just how well, and
with what skill and imagination, Garrett has shouldered that
responsibility. _ RICHARD E. NICHOLLS
</P>
<P>
   IN THE GARDEN OF OUR DREAMS
</P>
<P>
   Memoirs of a Marriage.
</P>
<P>
   By Shirlee Taylor Haizlip and Harold C. Haizlip.
</P>
<P>
   Kodansha, $24.
</P>
<P>
   ``For better or for worse'' is the undoing of most couples. For
Shirlee Taylor Haizlip and Harold C. Haizlip, however, it is the
whole point. Their marriage is enviable, and luckily for us they
have chosen to write about it in their richly detailed memoir, ``In
the Garden of Our Dreams.'' It begins with their blind date in
1957, when Shirlee was at Wellesley College and Harold was a
graduate student at Harvard. They tell the story in alternating
accounts, their voices as different as their backgrounds. Shirlee
was brought up in an upper-middle-class black home in Ansonia,
Conn., a beloved and much-indulged child of a Baptist pastor and
his beautiful and adored wife; Harold, also black, grew up in much
less gilded circumstances in Washington with his mother; his father
died when the boy was 10. ``My goal after high school,'' says
Shirlee, whose tone is more silken than her straightforward
husband's, was ``continuing the family role of 'uplifting the
race.''' This the couple did, together and separately, in
education, community fund-raising and the arts. Though by any
standard their lives are charmed -- filled with love, two talented
daughters and professional success -- the Haizlips have always been
a ``happily ever after,'' but in a separate world. ``Freedom was an
illusion,'' Harold writes. ``We were not free. No black people we
knew were.'' _ ANDREA HIGBIE
</P>
<P>
   THE BIRTH OF EMPIRE
</P>
<P>
   DeWitt Clinton and the American Experience, 1769-1828.
</P>
<P>
   By Evan Cornog.
</P>
<P>
   Oxford University, $35.
</P>
<P>
   ``Even the most admiring biographers of DeWitt Clinton have
conceded that he was a difficult man to be around,'' Evan Cornog
writes of the man he credits with the two transforming developments
in the early-19th-century American Republic: the spoils system in
politics and the construction of the Erie Canal. Haughty and
unbending, Clinton was born at a time when three families -- the
Schuylers, Clintons and Livingstons -- presided over New York state
politics. At the age of 14, he watched his father and uncle ride
with Washington in the New York victory parade of 1783. At 17, with
both houses of Congress looking on, he delivered (in Latin) the
commencement address for the first graduating class of Columbia
College. After serving as Senator, Mayor and Governor and very
nearly beating James Madison for the Presidency in 1812, Clinton
``could scarcely enter a public room in New York or Albany without
seeing someone he had offended,'' Cornog writes. By 1815, he had
been stripped of all powers and offices except an unsalaried seat
on the state canal commission -- which, with untiring
resourcefulness and vision, and what many saw as characteristic
opportunism, he used to push through a plan to build the Erie Canal
-- and reposition himself in the Governor's seat. ``The Birth of
Empire'' shows how rapidly the canal opened the old Northwest to
migration, established New York as the nation's metropolis and
replaced the power of ``distinguished individuals'' like Clinton
with the democratic enthusiasms of the Age of Jackson. But Clinton,
who emulated the Roman republican ideal of civilis -- the idea that
the virtuous citizen is useful -- may, Cornog writes, ``have
understood better than most the harsh lesson of imperial glory --
that it contained within its success the seeds of its ultimate
failure.'' _ DAVID WALTON
</P>
<P>
   ----------
</P>
