<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    The Cox News Service spot news budget for Saturday, Jan. 9,
1999.
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   Photo and graphics information and editors' names can be found
at the end of this budget.
</P>
<P>
   WASHINGTON
</P>
<P>
   IMPEACH _ WASHINGTON _ Senate meets in private to try to come up
with guidelines for the impeachment trial. (Foskett, Atlanta
Journal-Constitution).
</P>
<P>
   WITH
</P>
<P>
   IMPEACH-SCENE _ WASHINGTON _ Reax and color from the Senate.
(Carr, Atlanta Journal-Constitution).
</P>
<P>
   IMPEACH-DEAL _ WASHINGTON _ How the deal was reached. (Sherman,
Atlanta Journal-Constitution).
</P>
<P>
   IMPEACH-JURORS _ WASHINGTON _ Even on the day they swore to ``do
impartial justice,'' senators who will serve on President Clinton's
impeachment jury were appearing on television to give their
opinions about the case and even try to influence their fellow
jurors. What makes these jurors so different from those in an
ordinary civil or criminal trial. (Dart, Cox News Service).
</P>
<P>
   IMPEACH-LEGAL _ WASHINGTON _ If the impeachment of President
Clinton becomes the trial of the century in the U.S. Senate, both
sides will be ready with large teams of courtroom-tested lawyers.
(Malone, Cox News Service 550).
</P>
<P>
   CONGRESS-AGENDA _ WASHINGTON _ Undeterred by the distractions of
the impeachment process, each party in the new Congress has
signaled its priorities for the next two years. Democratic and
Republican leaders alike put four concerns _ Social Security,
Medicare, education and health care for children and working-age
adults _ on their must-do lists, though hard compromises would be
needed in each area to pass a law. In any case, members and
political scientists alike expect any progress to be slowed by the
Senate's impeachment duties, House Speaker Dennis Hastert's
inexperience, deep partisan rancor in the House, and uncertainty in
Congress about whether it will be dealing with President Clinton or
President Gore when the bills introduced this winter reach the
final stages of the legislative machinery next fall. (Mollison, Cox
News Service).
</P>
<P>
   CONGRESS-LISTS _ List of the GOP priorities and list of
Democratic priorities, as outlined by congressional leaders this
week. (Cox News Service).
</P>
<P>
   EDs: Moving Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   NATIONAL
</P>
<P>
   SCHOOL-SUICIDE _ Two Carroll County, Ga., teens _ a boy and a
girl _ are shot, apparently carrying out a suicide pact at Central
High School this morning. It appears the 17-year-old boy, Jeff
Miller shot the 15-year-old girl, Andrea Garrett and then himself.
Andrea died and Miller is reportedly on life support. Apparently
happened in girls bathroom at the school. (Ellis/Cowles, Atlanta
Journal-Constitution). WITH PHOTO.
</P>
<P>
   INAUG _ Preview of Gov. Elect-Bob Taft inauguration. Festivities
begin Sunday night with performances by Mary Wilson and the
Supremes and The Capitol Steps; and continue all day Monday, ending
w/ $1,000 a tix inaugural ball. Dayton area involvement includes
dance performances by a developmentally disabled group and by our
Kid's Voting Troupe. (Jasper, Daytoin Daily News). 25. WITH PHOTOS.
</P>
<P>
   WEALTH-GAP _ NELSONVILLE, Ohio _ This southeastern Ohio town on
the edge of Appalachia has become an outpost in a 1990s version of
class warfare. The Rev. Jesse Jackson and others are using its
poverty-scarred face to rally support for measures to bridge the
widening gap between wealthy suburbia and poorer inner cities and
rural areas. Next Thursday and Friday, Jackson takes will take the
story of Nelsonville to the very epicenter of wealth, Wall Street,
for a two-day rally. (Shepard, Cox News Service).
</P>
<P>
   EDs: WITH COX PHOTOS.
</P>
<P>
   NCGUV _ GREENSBORO, N.C. _In the latest sign that the North
Carolina governor's race is heating up well in advance of the Nov.
7, 2000, election, state Attorney General Mike Easley is pulling
together his campaign team that probably will include Greensboro
Chamber of Commerce chief Peter Reichard as finance director.
Another top contender, state Lt. Gov. Dennis Wicker, recently
pulled together his fund-raising committee, while several prominent
Democrats and Republicans contemplate entering the race. Former
White House Chief of Staff Erskine Bowles decided last month not to
seek the governor's office. (Burritt, Atlanta
Journal-Constitution).
</P>
<P>
   SHEIKH _ WEST PALM BEACH, Fla. _ Sheikh Abdus Qureshi says he
runs a management consulting company, but the people who have filed
some 20 lawsuits against him claim Qureshi has made a hobby out of
orchestrating frauds _ like selling 42 polo ponies he never owned
or bilking Chinese immigrants out of $300,000 they had saved to
open a U.S. restaurant. How does Qureshi make his money? His
company, Escue Management, is no longer listed as an active firm in
state records. According to the suits, Qureshi _ a native of
Pakistan who has Swedish citizenship _ is exceptionally skilled at
persuading people to lend him large amounts of money that he later
fails to pay back. In the past, Qureshi has said people are simply
getting upset because they invested in deals that went bad.
(Ellicott, Palm Beach Post). 55. WITH PHOTOS.
</P>
<P>
   UT-MINORITY-HIRING _ AUSTIN, Texas _ University of Texas
officials quietly dismantled a $300,000 a year minority-hiring
program that helped lure record numbers of black and Hispanic
professors to the Austin campus between 1988 and 1997. (Roser,
Austin American-Statesman) MOVED
</P>
<P>
   RAILROAD-AGENCY-MERGER _ AUSTIN, Texas _ A legislator will take
another run at merging the Public Utility Commission into the Texas
Railroad Commission, creating one agency to regulate the state's
electric, natural gas and local telephone utilities, as well as the
oil production industry. Rep. Bill Siebert (R-San Antonio) hopes
he'll have more luck than did state Sen. David Cain (D-Dallas), who
didn't get far in the last legislative session with the same
proposal. (Hight, Austin American-Statesman) MOVED
</P>
<P>
   LOW-BUILDING-SUPPLIES _ AUSTIN, Texas _ With new home
construction at a record high, builders such as Bailey are having
trouble getting the materials they need to build houses. The
nationwide demand for drywall, insulation, concrete and man-made
stone have outstripped the supply. As a result, builders and others
say, anyone building a home may want to brace themselves for delays
_ and higher prices. It's a situation that shows few signs of
letting up. (Breyer, Austin American-Statesman) MOVED
</P>
<P>
   LOTTERY-PR _ AUSTIN, Texas _ State lottery officials eager to
enlist their most satisfied customers in the war on declining
ticket sales are pitching this message: Talking to reporters is
good, clean fun. It's conveyed in a new, four-minute video aimed at
enticing winners to hold news conferences that garner the kind of
positive PR the lottery covets. (Herman, Austin American-Statesman)
MOVED
</P>
