<HEADER>
A4913 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-TEXAS-HISTORICAL-PAPE     01-08 1121
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TEXAS-HISTORICAL-PAPERS-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
STEPHEN F. AUSTIN LETTERS TO BE AUCTIONED
</HEADLINE>
 (Repeating for all needing) 
(For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By ART CHAPMAN 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   A collection of Stephen F. Austin's letters that offer a window
into Texas history and detail Austin's changing attitudes toward
Mexico and Texas independence will be offered for sale at a New
York antique show this month. The asking price is $1.25 million.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is the only collection I've had with this historical
importance,'' said Kenneth Rendell, a Boston-based rare document
dealer who owns the letters. ``These letters show the story of the
fight for Texas independence all along the way. You see the whole
thought process for what is the founding of Texas.''
</P>
<P>
   There are 13 letters, the majority written from Austin's home at
San Felipe de Austin, west of present-day Houston. Austin, an early
colony leader known as the ``Father of Texas,'' headed the
colonists' first convention and carried their demands to the
Mexican president, Antonio Lopez de Santa Anna, in 1833.
</P>
<P>
   Other letters were sent from Mexico; Louisville, Ky.; and New
York. All but two were written to Austin's close friend David G.
Burnet, who became the first president of the Republic of Texas.
The others were written by Austin in his role as commander in chief
of the Texas army at the beginning of the revolution. One is to
James Bowie, who would become a hero at the Alamo.
</P>
<P>
   The letters from Austin show that his first wish was for Texas
to become an independent state within Mexico. But he eventually
came to believe that independent-nation status was the only course.
</P>
<P>
   On Jan. 16, 1830, after nine years of living under Mexican rule,
Austin wrote to Burnet that he doubted that Mexico would ever sell
Texas to the United States.
</P>
<P>
   ``I believe it to be the settled policy of this government to
make Texas a state as soon as possible,'' Austin wrote of Mexico's
views, ``and it will be the best, the brightest star in the Mexican
constellation.''
</P>
<P>
   Austin wrote often of his desire to make Texas a separate and
independent state within Mexico, but finally, after years of
turmoil and civil war in Mexico, he altered his views.
</P>
<P>
   From San Felipe, he wrote to Burnet on Oct. 5, 1835, ``I hope
you will enter ardently and warmly in the cause _ now is the time _
no more doubts _ no submission _ I hope to see Texas forever free
from Mexican domination of any kind.''
</P>
<P>
   Rendell calls the letters the ``most remarkable group of
manuscripts relating to the foundation of the Republic of Texas
ever to be offered for sale.''
</P>
<P>
   But from a historian's standpoint, they might be less enticing,
said Stephen F. Hardin, a Texas historian at Victoria College and
the author of ``Texian Iliad,'' a military history of the Texas
Revolution.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are really two things on the block,'' Hardin said. ``The
old paper is one. The old paper is valuable to people who want to
own it, and there are a lot of people who do. And there is the
information on the paper. That is what is of interest to people
like me.''
</P>
<P>
   Hardin said the collection is less valuable to historians if the
information contained in the letters is already known. Most of the
letters were published by Trinity University Press in a 1981 book
titled ``The Fugitive Papers.''
</P>
<P>
   Michael Heaston, a rare book and manuscript dealer in Austin,
said collectors would be pleased to own the kind of history
displayed in the Austin letters.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think you could ask for more outstanding content,'' he
said. ``Just because they have been published doesn't diminish
them. Stephen F. Austin is the premier individual in Texas history,
and a collector would want his works. I would think an institution
would also.''
</P>
<P>
   The letters will go on sale Jan. 15 at the 45th Annual Winter
Antiques Show in New York City. They are on display at Rendell's
New York City gallery.
</P>
<P>
   Rendell said his company acquired the letters from ``an
assiduous collector of Texana.'' He said he could not name the
collector because it would betray a confidence.
</P>
<P>
   ``A lot of times people who appear to have a lot of money
suddenly need a lot of money and they don't want other people to
know,'' Rendell said. ``Many times these collectibles remain in a
family until they hit a generation where the financial value
exceeds the sentimental value.''
</P>
<P>
   Ron Tyler, director of the Texas State Historical Association in
Austin, said he had no idea what the collection will bring, but he
said there are ``people out there interested in Texas material who
have a lot of money.''
</P>
<P>
   Last month, the controversial Alamo diary of Mexican officer Lt.
Col. Jose Enrique de la Pena was sold for $350,000 to Tom Hicks,
who owns the Texas Rangers baseball club and the Dallas Stars
hockey team, and his business partner Charles Tate. The diary was
given to the University of Texas.
</P>
<P>
   Tyler said the Winter Antiques Show, where the letters will be
offered for sale, is recognized as a big event. ``It is a
tradition,'' he said. ``People come with their pocketbooks open.
The dealers put on a good show; it's a big deal.''
</P>
<P>
   The collector market is always fluctuating, he said. ``There are
some new people involved in it now. The field goes up and down. A
few collectors dominate the market, then they get tired of maps or
letters and decide to collect something else. The field seems to be
very active right now.''
</P>
<P>
   Like Hardin, Tyler said his interest would be more in the
information in the letters, rather than in their value as
collectibles. Austin letters, he said, are not that rare
individually, but a collection of this size is unusual.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Austin letters are a momentous event in American
history,'' Rendell stressed. ``You're reading it as it happened. I
loved the drawing of the first flag.''
</P>
<P>
   In a letter dated March 4, 1836, Austin described for Burnet the
flag he envisioned for the new republic. It was not the Lone Star
emblem that would eventually fly.
</P>
<P>
   In April 1836, while in New York to gather support for Texas
within the United States, Austin finally received word of Col.
Bowie and Col. William B. Travis, commanders at the Alamo.
</P>
<P>
   On March 6, Santa Anna's army had ended its 13-day siege by
storming the mission and killing all 169 defenders. But on April
21, a band of Texans led by Gen. Sam Houston won the republic's
freedom at the battle of San Jacinto.
</P>
<P>
   In another letter to Burnet, Austin wrote: ``Travis, brave
Travis &AMP; his historic band _ but my feeling will not permit me to
dwell. Farewell, heaven help &AMP; defend Texas &AMP; give you all
wisdom.''
</P>
<P>
   (Visit the Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide
Web: www.star-telegram.com) &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
