<HEADER>
A4920 &Cx1f; ttj-z
r e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FILM-REVIEW-CIVIL-HNS     01-08 0749
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FILM-REVIEW-CIVIL-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`A CIVIL ACTION' IS A GOOD, BUT PREDICTABLE THRILLER 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By WALTER ADDIEGO  
 c.1999 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   If I were in the legal racket, I might think about suing the
makers of ``A Civil Action.''
</P>
<P>
   Few mainstream pictures have offered such a devastatingly
negative portrayal of the practice of law in modern America _ and
this is a movie where the morally dubious main character turns into
a hero with a worthy cause.
</P>
<P>
   The film is based on a 1980s lawsuit over water pollution that
may have caused the deaths of eight children in a small
Massachusetts town. An arrogant Boston lawyer, Jan Schlichtmann
(John Travolta), isn't interested in the issue until he learns that
deep-pockets corporations are involved.
</P>
<P>
   Though scorned by snotty colleagues as an ``ambulance chaser,''
Schlichtmann nonetheless becomes so consumed by the case that he
ruins himself financially.
</P>
<P>
   This sounds very Hollywood _ cocky legal ace hears the celestial
music and, against huge odds, starts fighting the good fight. But
the context is different.
</P>
<P>
   For instance, the working-class people of Woburn, Mass., for
whom Schlichtmann is ostensibly battling, aren't all victims.
What's more, the legal profession is a rigid hierarchy where class
and money are the main issues, the corporations are ethical
pragmatists (to be polite about it) and the court system all but
guarantees that truth has very little to do with deciding a case.
</P>
<P>
   These are all good, liberal, populist _ though not very
startling _ observations (one of the film's producers is Robert
Redford). And the film has the moxie to name the corporations
involved in the actual case (W.R. Grace &AMP; Co. and Beatrice Foods).
</P>
<P>
   But this is a big-time picture with a major star in the lead,
and we're never allowed to forget it. The film begins by making fun
of the Porsche-driving Schlichtmann _ he's been named one of
Boston's 10 most eligible bachelors _ and after a rather
unbelievable jolt of conscience, he hocks his firm and beggars his
partners to take up the noble cause of the victims of Woburn.
</P>
<P>
   Writer-director Steven Zaillian (``Searching for Bobby
Fischer'') does a pretty decent job of working these contradictory
modes: the ``issues'' picture about a flawed legal system and the
traditional ``hero'' movie. But that doesn't mean he's solved the
problem. The film never really takes an unexpected turn; Zaillian
uses a no-risk style of story-telling, and you never feel fully
drawn in or compelled by the material.
</P>
<P>
   This isn't to say that the Travolta character is completely
one-dimensional. Even after he decides to take the case,
Schlichtmann is depicted as fallible, both as a lawyer and as a
human being. Once he's decided that the cause is just, he has
little sense of what he's doing to his colleagues, and he also
makes professional errors. And can he really be expected to beat a
system that's portrayed as a monstrous machine consuming and
excreting vast amounts of money?
</P>
<P>
   If justice is done in the courtrooms we observe here, it's
sheerly incidental, and the picture is clearly designed to tap into
popular resentment of the legal profession.
</P>
<P>
   Since Travolta's much-heralded comeback, I've enjoyed some of
his comic efforts, and even his crazy action villain in ``Broken
Arrow.'' While his work here is fine, considered as a ``star''
turn, I have to wonder if another actor might have made
Schlichtmann's transformation more convincing.
</P>
<P>
   Where the film excels is when the camera turns away from
Travolta. Robert Duvall plays a sly, Southern lawyer for one of the
corporations, and it's a highly enjoyable performance: a good ol'
boy front covering up a razor-sharp intellect.
</P>
<P>
   There's fine comic work from William H. Macy as the accountant
who comes up with ever more desperate ways for Schlichtmann's firm
to keep subsidizing the case.
</P>
<P>
   Kathleen Quinlan stands out as the broken-hearted mother who
first brings Schlichtmann to Woburn, and John Lithgow is memorable
as the judge who falls victim to the Duvall character's cunning.
</P>
<P>
   Zaillian is a good director, but here he's trying to squeeze
himself into a more conventional framework than he's comfortable
with. I hope his next film gives him the chance to follow his muse.
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; CAST: John Travolta, Robert Duvall, William H. Macy
</P>
<P>
   &UR; DIRECTOR: Steve Zaillian
</P>
<P>
   &UR; WRITER Zaillian, based on the book by Jonathan Harr
</P>
<P>
   &UR; RATING PG-13
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-01-08-99 1441EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
