<DOCNO> NYT19990108.0184 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-01-08 14:43 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4923 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-AUTO-REVIEW-$ADV10-BO     01-08 1045
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-AUTO-REVIEW-$ADV10-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
'99 CONVERTIBLE COUPE AS A 190-HORSE OPEN SLEIGH 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (l and f coding)  
 (For release Sunday, January 10, 1999)   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By BILL GRIFFITH  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Who cares if it snows? We're about to ring out the final days of
1998 in a new 1999 Mustang convertible.
</P>
<P>
   It's First Night: No, not New Year's Eve. This first night is
five days before the end of the year. It's the first trip in this
Ford, the driver getting into the unfamiliar vehicle at 2 a.m.
after putting to bed a Sports section containing the sad details of
the Patriots' crushing loss to the Jets.
</P>
<P>
   The V6 starts with a nice growl, but, to a tired leg, the clutch
feels stiff at first push (maybe I should have been in the gym
doing those clutch exercises that VW is featuring in its ads). Off
we go onto well-soaked roads with a little early-morning mist
guaranteeing to keep them good and greasy.
</P>
<P>
   It's immediately apparent that this is the little brother (or
sister) to the Mustang GTs and Cobras. The 3.8-liter V6 puts out
190 horsepower, plenty to merge and pass and give you a nice power
curve through second and third gears, but none of the neck-snapping
giddy-up of the V8s. And the clutch turns out to be not too stiff
at all. It's just right . . . and coupled to a gearbox that clicks
nicely into all five speeds.
</P>
<P>
   Still, this first trip is about to become one to remember as I
play John White-for-a-night.
</P>
<P>
   Taking the ``long way home'' brings this Mustang along the
network of Fellsway roads north of Boston where the traction
control light starts flashing with every touch of the gas pedal and
the handling becomes squirrelly. ``Can't this thing grip the
road?'' I wonder. ``Is rear-wheel drive the problem?''
</P>
<P>
   Nope, just the opposite.
</P>
<P>
   Even though the air temperature is mild, it turns out we're
dealing with the beginnings of icy roads, and the traction control
system (a $230 option) is kicking in _ cutting back on the power
and teaming with the ABS system ($500) to cut torque to the
spinning wheel and restore even traction. Given the conditions, the
system does a fine job, and we climb the final steep hills to home
with no problem.
</P>
<P>
   This is a likable car, and some of the things that aren't so
likable can be attributed to driving a summer car in winter. The
basic Mustang convertible lists for $21,070 _ plus the irritating
$525 destination charge, aforementioned ABS and traction control
plus cruise control ($550) for a $22,875 total.
</P>
<P>
   The full instrumentation is striking at night, red on a greenish
background. The one gauge worth watching this night _ the heat
gauge _ takes about a half-mile longer to reach operating
temperature (and get the heater cranking) than I've become
accustomed to in 30 winters of making this nocturnal drive in
everything from a '54 Ford (also a convertible) to my present '97
Camry.
</P>
<P>
   Another winter/summer contradiction of the Mustang is the
narrowness of the front seats. (You want to know about the back
seats? Better your back than mine.) This driver is hardly a giant,
but, wearing a winter coat means the front seat wraps me too
tightly for comfort. Shed the jacket and it's fine . . . barely. A
summer night with the top down is just a dream this week.
</P>
<P>
   Heading out to find gas the next morning brings the realization
that this silver and black car gets second glances, including one
from a passing patrol car.
</P>
<P>
   Storage space is lean consisting of a small glovebox, center
box, and bins on the doors. A standard CD player fills what would
otherwise be a dashboard shelf.
</P>
<P>
   The sound is worth the lack of space. Even a confirmed Mr. AM
Radio quickly learns there's much to like with the CD system,
finding Alabama's No. 1 hits soothing company as the early
afternoon traffic rolls slowly along the Lower Deck back to another
day of work. The rear speakers are right behind the doors because,
this being a convertible, there's no rear deck for them.
</P>
<P>
   Sitting in traffic gives me time to check out some of the little
things. I immediately wonder why Ford settles for such a pedestrian
shift knob (it's not even particularly comfortable) as finial
adornment for a five-speed that's one of the car's big attractions.
</P>
<P>
   It's also time to admire Ford's cleverness.
</P>
<P>
   With the soft top, there's no dome light; instead, a pair of
built-in lights (with separate switches) in the rearview mirror
make it easy to read the owner's manual in the Globe parking lot in
the middle of the night.
</P>
<P>
   Coming home that second night, it's a little drier, and the
Mustang nicely handles the Mass. Highway Department's Expressway
North chicane _ that nasty right-left turn combo approaching the
Mass. Turnpike exit and South Station tunnel.
</P>
<P>
   Rolling down the window a tad (remember, it's winter), I have a
sound idea. There's an absence of the exhaust tone that makes the
big brother Mustangs so unmistakable. Of course, I admit to being a
fan of the original Mustang GT's tuned exhausts.
</P>
<P>
   Fuel mileage on this 300-mile winter tour averaged 21.3 miles
per gallon in mostly city driving, much of it in heavy traffic and
rain, with cold starts _ all the ingredients for hitting the EPA's
minimum number. Or maybe not even that.
</P>
<P>
   I asked Mrs. G if she'd like to celebrate First Night by parking
along the Charles with the top down and watching the fireworks.
</P>
<P>
   She in turn asked if we could test drive the car on the Fourth
of July instead.
</P>
<P>
   That sounds like a plan to me.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
----- &QC; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   A word or two from Mrs. G.
</P>
<P>
   Mrs. G fell in love with the Mustang immediately.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is a woman's car. The size is perfect,'' said she.
</P>
<P>
   And, hardly surprising, she had the opposite view of the seats
that I had found uncomfortable.
</P>
<P>
   ``I love the seats. They're just right,'' she said, a thought
seconded by number one daughter on her first ride in the car.
</P>
<P>
   The only drawback in Mrs. G's eyes was the five-speed
transmission.
</P>
<P>
   ``Too bad it didn't have an automatic. I'd love to drive it if
it did. I really like this car all the way back to the
taillights.''
</P>
<P>
   ``And the doors aren't too heavy. A lot of times you get in a
two-door car and the doors are real hard to swing. These are nice
and light.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
