<HEADLINE>
EXTREME MEASURES FOR EXTREME TEENS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By DR. EMILIO BOMBAY 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Dear Dr. Bombay: I am having problems with my children accessing
undesirable areas by signing onto America Online under ``Guest''
and using a friend's name and password. How can I prevent this? _
Worried Mom
</P>
<P>
   Dear Mom: Got a pair of scissors? Start with the modem line.
</P>
<P>
   Look, you're never going to stop the kiddos from trolling for
smut just by hoping they won't do it. And it may not be practical
for you to be around playing porn cop whenever the kids are messing
around on the 'puter. You'll have to be more devious than that.
</P>
<P>
   If you're truly worried about what they're doing, try locking up
the computer in your bedroom or home office. If that's not
possible, unhook the keyboard and mouse and throw them in the trunk
of your car. As a last resort, drop your subscription to AOL.
</P>
<P>
   AOL puts that ``Guest'' log-in in their software for your
convenience, so you can connect and check your e-mail from somebody
else's computer just in case Tom Hanks is trying to get in touch
with you while you're on the road. They're not responsible for
hormone-happy teen-agers abusing their Internet access.
</P>
<P>
   You could try an Internet provider that screens out the dirty
stuff, except there's no guarantee the people running it won't
think Gaugin was some sex-crazed hippie pervert. Or you could get
filtering software like NetNanny, SurfWatch or CyberSitter, but a
determined kid can always find ways around them.
</P>
<P>
   Be a parent. Make a hard choice, even if it deprives you of your
online fun. Just realize that if they can't find naked stuff at
your house, they'll go over to the neighbor's house. At least
that's what we did after Mama Bombay found my ``Playboy'' stash.
</P>
<P>
   Dear Dr. Bombay: I get this message: ``Error loading
Explorer.exe. You must reinstall Windows.'' Then things freeze. How
can I reinstall when the CD-ROM isn't working? _ Stuck
</P>
<P>
   Dear Stuck: Now's your big chance to go back to DOS. Not
interested? If you have Win98 and you made a start-up disk like you
were supposed to, boot with it and that'll make the CD live again.
</P>
<P>
   If you have Win95, hold down the F8 key when you see ``Starting
Windows 95.'' Choose Command Prompt Only from the menu you'll get
and use a DOS text editor (such as Edit.exe) to open the System.ini
file. Look for a line that starts Shell and edit to read
ShellWinfile.exe, which abandons Windows Explorer in favor of the
Windows 3.1 File Manager. Yes, it really is still there. That
should get you through the boot process. Don't forget to change
things back after you reload whatever it is you need to reload.
</P>
<P>
   Dear Dr. Bombay: Bill Gates belongs to the same category as
Hitler, Bonaparte and company. All had the same goals: to rule the
world. It's against the basic principles of democracy. You seem to
have a very communist way of thinking by wanting all computers to
speak the same language. _ Righteously Indignant
</P>
<P>
   Dear Indig: You've cleverly unmasked yet another fiendish plot
by the International Communist Conspiracy to help people everywhere
communicate more efficiently. Curses! Foiled again!
</P>
<P>
   Comrade Emilio Bombay wants to sap and impurify the precious
bodily fluids of capitalist lackeys everywhere. He can be reached
at drbombay\Nstar-telegram.com or via snail-mail at Pravda, (a k a
the Star-Telegram) Box 1870, Fort Worth, TX 76101. Fax: 390-7257.
His real name is Michael Gerst, editorial systems manager for the
Fort Worth Star-Telegram.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
