<HEADER>
A4949 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CARS-WILLIAMS-COLUMN-     01-08 1288
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CARS-WILLIAMS-COLUMN-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
VILLAGER IS IN THE MINIVANGUARD
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By G. CHAMBERS WILLIAMS III 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Minivan sales have slowed from their frenetic pace of the late
1980s and early '90s, thanks to booming sales of sport-utility
vehicles.
</P>
<P>
   But the minivan market is far from dead; consumers are still
buying them, and manufacturers are continuing to improve them.
</P>
<P>
   Two years ago, General Motors rolled out three all-new models to
replace its previous Oldsmobile, Pontiac and Chevrolet vans. Last
year, Toyota introduced the Sienna to replace its popular Previa,
and Honda, Nissan and Mercury have all-new models for 1999.
</P>
<P>
   We tested the '99 Mercury Villager, a product that is
essentially the same as the Nissan Quest but with some styling and
interior differences.
</P>
<P>
   The Villager and Quest are assembled at a Ford Motor Co. plant
in Avon Lake, Ohio, from body panels and engines built by Nissan in
Smyrna, Tenn.
</P>
<P>
   Originally introduced in 1992 as '93 models, the Villager and
Quest have undergone only minor changes until this year's complete
remake. We haven't driven the Quest, so we'll talk about the
Villager. The two vans use the same engine, transmission and other
mechanical components, however, so they will drive and ride
virtually identically.
</P>
<P>
   Our test vehicle was the uplevel Villager Estate model, with a
base price of $25,015 plus $580 transportation. The entry-level
model, called simply the Villager, lists for $22,415 plus
transportation, and a Sport model is offered for the same price as
the Estate. Because of changes and additions, including
air-conditioning as standard equipment, the entry-level price is up
about $2,100 from last year, but the high-end model is just a few
dollars more than it was last year.
</P>
<P>
   With a bunch of extras, including a luxury package ($995) that
added leather seats and a memory for the driver's seat and outside
mirrors, our test vehicle's sticker totaled $30,355, including
transportation.
</P>
<P>
   The '99 Villager has an all-new body but is built on the same
chassis as before. The biggest difference for consumers is the
addition of a second rear sliding door, this one on the driver's
side. Villager and Quest are the last to add the second sliding
door. Unfortunately, the designers didn't see fit to give either
sliding door the electric-powered option that is available on the
Oldsmobile Silhouette, Chevrolet Venture, Pontiac Montana and now
the Ford Windstar and Honda Odyssey (which is the only van that
offers dual electric sliding doors).
</P>
<P>
   Although the chassis remains essentially the same as last
year's, there are some improvements in the suspension system
designed to give the Villager a softer ride.
</P>
<P>
   Under the hood, there is a big change, however. The engine is
brand-new. This year, power comes from a 3.3-liter Nissan V-6 rated
at 170 horsepower and 200 foot-pounds of torque. This is the same
engine Nissan uses in the updated Pathfinder sport-utility, and it
replaces last year's 3.0-liter V-6 that was taken from the previous
generation Nissan Maxima sedan (151 horspower and 174 foot-pounds
of torque).
</P>
<P>
   Although this isn't the most powerful minivan on the market,
there is plenty of zip even on hills and freeway on-ramps. Unlike
the segment leaders, the Plymouth Voyager/Dodge Caravan, the
Villager is not offered with a four-cylinder engine, which is one
reason the base price is higher than that of those Daimler Chrysler
products.
</P>
<P>
   That's OK, though. The Villager isn't designed to be a
mass-market minivan like the Plymouth and Dodge models; it's aimed
at more upscale buyers.
</P>
<P>
   Our test vehicle was so plush and comfortable that it felt like
a luxury sedan. The six-way power driver's seat was as soft and
comfy as an expensive leather recliner, but even the backseat
riders enjoyed a cushy ride.
</P>
<P>
   The Villager is roomier inside than the regular-length Chrysler
vans, but not quite as roomy as the extended vans. Seating for
seven includes two buckets up front, two bucket seats in the center
and a three-person bench seat in the rear. A center bench seat with
two integrated child safety seats is optional.
</P>
<P>
   The engine is paired with a very smooth-shifting, four-speed
automatic transmission that is the only major part of the power
train carried over from the previous generation.
</P>
<P>
   I especially liked the new aircraft-cockpit-style wraparound
instrument panel with electronic instruments (a $245 upgrade on our
vehicle). Instruments and controls have been repositioned to make
them easier to reach and view from the driver's seat. The
AM/FM/cassette unit has been moved above the heating and
air-conditioning controls to bring it closer to the driver, and the
sound system is outstanding.
</P>
<P>
   Our van had the optional six-disc CD changer ($370). Headphone
outlets and stereo controls in the rear let passengers listen to
something different from what the folks up front are grooving on.
This makes trips with teens a lot more pleasant.
</P>
<P>
   New standard features for 1999 besides air-conditioning include
power windows/mirrors and door locks, cruise control, luggage rack,
second-generation dual front air bags, a cargo net on the floor
between the two front seats, a rear parcel shelf (Estate and Sport
models only) and machined aluminum wheels (also Estate and Sport
only).
</P>
<P>
   Other options on our test car included a new antilock braking
system ($590), power moon roof ($775), automatic temperature
control ($180), anti-theft system ($100), and two special packages:
a ``comfort group'' ($995) that includes an odor/particulate air
filter, power driver's seat and privacy glass; and a ``convenience
group'' ($495) that adds a flip-open rear lift-gate window, extra
interior lighting, an overhead console and remote keyless entry.
</P>
<P>
   Included in the luxury package is a universal garage-door
opener, as well as a rather silly memo recorder mounted in the
driver's sun visor that allows someone to record up to three
minutes of remarks or thoughts or whatever. I imagine this will be
mostly something the kids play with when they are left alone in the
car.
</P>
<P>
   EPA fuel-economy ratings are 17 miles per gallon in the city and
24 mpg on the highway. The tank holds 20 gallons of gasoline,
giving the Villager decent cruising range.  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   At A Glance:
</P>
<P>
   1999 Mercury Villager Estate minivan
</P>
<P>
   The Package: Five-door, seven-passenger, V-6 powered,
front-drive minivan, a completely revised model for 1999
(essentially the same vehicle as the Nissan Quest).
</P>
<P>
   Highlights: This is one of the nicest minivans on the market,
and has more power and a new sliding door on the driver's side for
1999. It offers an excellent ride and interior comfort, good power
and outstanding quality.
</P>
<P>
   Negatives: No power sliding door available; no engine upgrades
offered.
</P>
<P>
   Major competitors: Honda Odyssey, Toyota Sienna, Mazda MPV,
Chevrolet Venture/Oldsmobile Silhouette/Pontiac Montana, Chrysler
Town &AMP; Country/Plymouth Voyager/Dodge Caravan, Ford Windstar.
</P>
<P>
   EPA fuel economy: 17 miles per gallon city, 24 highway.
</P>
<P>
   Base price: $25,015 plus $580 transportation.
</P>
<P>
   Price as tested: $30,355, including transportation.
</P>
<P>
   On The Road rating: A-minus.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (G. Chambers Williams III writes on transportation issues for
the Fort Worth Star-Telegram. His mailing address is
Star-Telegram/Northeast, 3201 Airport Freeway, Suite 108, Bedford,
Texas 76021; his E-mail address is chambers(at)star-telegram.com.
Fax: (817) 685-3883. Check out his Wheelin' new-car review column
weekly on the Internet at
ww.netarrant.net/today/news/opinions/necol.htm. Visit the
Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide Web:
www.star-telegram.com)  &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
