<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ELLIS-COLUMN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ANNAN'S GIFT TO SADDAM'S CHEMICAL WEAPON MACHINE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JOHN ELLIS  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   There are three grave threats to the national security of the
United States. They are, in order of their lethality, biological
and chemical warfare, ``loose'' nuclear weapons, and technological
terrorism. The most worrisome of these, in terms of strategic
defense, is biological and chemical weaponry.
</P>
<P>
   It would be insane for Saddam Hussein to launch a nuclear
missile attack on the United States or one of its allies. Advanced
radar would almost immediately establish the attack's point of
origin, track its trajectories, and predict its targets.
</P>
<P>
   Before the warhead detonated, US planes would be on their way to
a retaliatory nuclear strike. Every major city in Iraq would be
sand in a matter of minutes.
</P>
<P>
   It would be difficult for terrorist computer hackers to crash
the global financial and communications system. Firewalls would
contain the virus's spread. AT&AMP;T and other companies have secondary
systems that would meet the nation's essential telecommunications
needs. Emergency planners would quiet the initial panic. Markets
would be closed for a time while investigators hunted down the
perpetrators. But life would go on.
</P>
<P>
   Biological and chemical weaponry is different. Ten suitcases of
strategically placed anthrax could kill, on a cloudy day, millions
of people and cause something close to complete panic. Once
airborne, it would pass from person to person with every sneeze,
every breath taken. Sunshine would be the only defense.
</P>
<P>
   It is tasteless, odorless, and easily assembled, and the origin
and intent of a multicity anthrax attack would be unknown until
declared. By then, the functionality of the US government would be
very much in doubt.
</P>
<P>
   The purpose of the United Nations Special Commission (UNSCOM)
for the disarmament of Iraq, established after the Persian Gulf
War, is to prevent Saddam from acquiring such weaponry. Since the
United Nations does not have its own intelligence capabilities,
UNSCOM relies on member states to provide such assistance.
</P>
<P>
   The most sophisticated intelligence capabilities in the world
reside at the National Security Agency, the Pentagon, and the
Central Intelligence Agency. Since 1991, UNSCOM has worked closely
with all three in a sustained effort to shut down (or at least
impede) Iraq's development of chemical and biological weaponry.
</P>
<P>
   As well they should. There is little, if any doubt that Saddam
has used such weaponry in the past _ on his own people and in the
war against Iran during the 1980s. There is no doubt that he is
trying to develop an ever more lethal chemical and biological
warfare capability.
</P>
<P>
   Judith Miller and William Broad of The New York Times and other
journalists have reported extensively on this effort and others
like it. Their reports have been chilling. This is a kind of
warfare that can eliminate entire populations.
</P>
<P>
   This week, UN Secretary General Kofi Annan threw a huge monkey
wrench into the UNSCOM machinery.
</P>
<P>
   Wednesday, The Boston Globe and The Washington Post reported
that, to quote the Post account: ``Annan has obtained what he
regards as convincing evidence that (UNSCOM) inspectors helped
collect eavesdropping intelligence used in American efforts to
undermine the Iraqi regime.'' The Post reported that Annan was
``deeply alarmed by the implications of the relationship for the
(UN).''
</P>
<P>
   The key sources for these accounts were ``confidants'' of Annan.
Which is to say Annan himself. It is believed that he leaked this
story to send a message of displeasure to the US government and to
assuage other members of the UN Security Council (notably Russia
and France), who opposed the recent US attacks on Iraq.
</P>
<P>
   Annan's ``message'' has done incalculable damage to UNSCOM's
mission and to US intelligence-gathering efforts. Worse, Annan has
delivered unto Saddam a public relations bonanza.
</P>
<P>
   Despite the firm denials of UNSCOM officials, Saddam can now
cite the secretary general of the United Nations as his ``source''
when he accuses UNSCOM weapons inspectors of being nothing more
than American ``spies.''
</P>
<P>
   It is worth remembering, as the Washington Post editorial page
pointed out, that the United Nations itself has demanded, ``through
solemn resolutions,'' that Saddam cease development of chemical and
biological weaponry. It also bears repeating that scientists who
once worked at the Biopreparat _ the former Soviet Union's vast
biological and chemical weapons program _ believe that some number
of their former colleagues now work for Saddam.
</P>
<P>
   The spread of chemical and biological weapons is an issue of
terrifying importance to every man, woman, and child on the planet.
Annan's petulant political game set back efforts to contain those
weapons immeasurably.
</P>
<P>
   If he needed to express displeasure with President Clinton's
bombing of Iraq, he should have gone through private channels. If
he did it to ingratiate himself with pro-Iraqi governments, he is
guilty of the worst kind of appeasement.
</P>
<P>
   Anyone who stands in the way of containing biological and
chemical warfare is on the wrong side of humanity and the evil side
of history.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (John Ellis is a Globe columnist.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
