A4956 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-AUTOS-COLUMN-BOS &LR;      01-08 0939
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-AUTOS-COLUMN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LIVING A LIE, THANKS TO MOTHER NATURE 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (l and f coding)   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JOHN R. WHITE  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   DETROIT _ The dateline is a lie _ it's where I should have been
most of this week, traipsing the vast interior of Cobo Hall with
6,000 or so other journalists (that's the number claimed to have
been invited) at the North American International Auto Show.
Better, I was to get an award of some kind or other as a finalist
in the Detroit Press Foundation International Wheel Awards
competition for automotive journalists.
</P>
<P>
   I was looking forward to seeing the new Ford Thunderbird, the
two-seater Millennium Car _ especially so since I do believe I was
first to ferret out Ford's plan for it. Hell, I know I was.
</P>
<P>
   But I didn't get to see it, nor did I get to eyeball the five
Chrysler concepts, nor any of the other concepts, nor any of the
new production vehicles. Nada.
</P>
<P>
   Instead, I have been living life as airport refugee, and
practicing to become proficient with a chain saw.
</P>
<P>
   The first mistake was scheduling comfort, a noon flight allowing
for sleep and breakfast before the long trek to Logan rather than
the daybreak special that would have gotten me to the Detroit
International Airport _ but maybe only in time to be a refugee
there.
</P>
<P>
   I hit the airport at 11 a.m. after dropping a car at the Globe
for pickup by another writer, slide my bag on the security belt,
get through the metal detector without a single alarm bell, and
check in _ flight's delayed, I am told, and your bag's too big. It
gets checked at the gate. I sit, watch the Patriots getting
whacked. The boarding announcement is a cancellation; Detroit is
buried in snow. Retrieve the bag, queue up, make a Sunday
reservation. So far, $45 in taxis, 80 miles driving, a couple of
hours or more at the airport, and I'm nowhere and on my way home.
</P>
<P>
   Sunday, no one answers airline telephone. Head for the gate,
lift the bag _ ``That bag's too big,'' the uniform says. ``It won't
fit. Take it downstairs.''
</P>
<P>
   ``It fit Friday,'' I say.
</P>
<P>
   Uniform calls chief uniform. ``Bag too big,'' he intones.
``Downstairs.''
</P>
<P>
   ``It fit Friday.'' This triggers an unfruitful discussion over
what was possible Friday but impossible today because it really was
never possible but only seemed that way to me. I am dealing with
the impossible.
</P>
<P>
   Downstairs. Flights are canceled and 500 or so people are on
standby ahead of me for the two, maybe four, open seats on the last
scheduled flight, which, if it gets aloft, may have nowhere to go
anyway.
</P>
<P>
   I am assured that Monday will be no problem.
</P>
<P>
   By now it is pouring rain in Boston and icing up north and west
of the Hub _ did I mention I am now driving a rear-drive
convertible?
</P>
<P>
   By Portsmouth, N.H., stuff is accumulating on the roadway. By
Somersworth to the north, the stuff has become glaze. The coupe is
hit by a gust of wind and slides across lanes, causing a police
cruiser to speed up, probably so its pilot could ascertain if I
were in trouble or possibly drunk and in bigger trouble.
</P>
<P>
   Rochester, the Lilac City, is a giant Popsicle, and I am
steering by body English as much as anything. Home at last, it is
time to start telephoning people in Detroit; I will not make the
opening press events nor the awards presentation.
</P>
<P>
   Cobo Hall has a media center set up for the event with a
gazillion telephone lines. Detroit information can't find any of
them but does give me a bogus number for Cobo Hall. I try Detroit
info again and am told they are too busy, call back some other
time. Is this the benefit of deregulation and the retirment of ol'
Ma Bell?
</P>
<P>
   I try again. A voice identifies itself as a police department.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm trying to get Detroit information,'' I say.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're that, too,'' he assures me, but can't find the media
center, gets me a number for Cobo Hall that is attached to a
recording.
</P>
<P>
   I rummage around to locate ``Show Talk 99,'' the glossy
publication of the Detroit Dealers Association that puts on the
auto show _ big story on the media center. But no number. But there
is a number for the public relations firm . . . which is attached
to another recording.
</P>
<P>
   More rummaging. I find a number for an employee of said firm,
which triggers another recording _ but, hallelujah, this guy's
recording offers a number where he can be reached. At the media
center where the telephone company couldn't find its own
telephones.
</P>
<P>
   ``Why do you want to come?'' he asks. ``We have two feet of
snow, nobody can move, and there are 2,000 people stranded at the
airport sleeping on emergency blankets.'' He will convey my
messages as best he can. For the record, he is Joe Rohatynski _ or
at least he was answering JR's telephone.
</P>
<P>
   The radio casts doubt on tomorrow's chances . . . suddenly there
is a thundering and clattering on the roof and I know it's too late
for Santa Claus. I rush to the window and where once was a clear
view of the street is now only evergreen foliage. The huge
ice-encrusted pine out front is not quite so big now because 30
feet of it is blocking both front doors, but it has missed the car
and the power lines. Monday, I may be too busy with the chain saw
to think about flying.
</P>
<P>
   I pick up the telephone; time to change the hotel reservation.
Again. Marriott at least answers its telephones.
</P>
<P>
   Monday, I try the airline, just in case. Maybe the tree can
wait. ``Due to weather conditions, we are too busy to take your
call. . . .''
</P>
<P>
   With deep longing in my heart for Ma Bell, I pick up the chain
saw. It is a very big piece of tree.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-01-08-99 1459EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990108.0195 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-01-08 15:03 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4963 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-AUTOS-COLUMN-BOS &LR;      01-08 0939
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-AUTOS-COLUMN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LIVING A LIE, THANKS TO MOTHER NATURE 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (l and f coding)   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JOHN R. WHITE  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   DETROIT _ The dateline is a lie _ it's where I should have been
