</P>
<P>
   I am assured that Monday will be no problem.
</P>
<P>
   By now it is pouring rain in Boston and icing up north and west
of the Hub _ did I mention I am now driving a rear-drive
convertible?
</P>
<P>
   By Portsmouth, N.H., stuff is accumulating on the roadway. By
Somersworth to the north, the stuff has become glaze. The coupe is
hit by a gust of wind and slides across lanes, causing a police
cruiser to speed up, probably so its pilot could ascertain if I
were in trouble or possibly drunk and in bigger trouble.
</P>
<P>
   Rochester, the Lilac City, is a giant Popsicle, and I am
steering by body English as much as anything. Home at last, it is
time to start telephoning people in Detroit; I will not make the
opening press events nor the awards presentation.
</P>
<P>
   Cobo Hall has a media center set up for the event with a
gazillion telephone lines. Detroit information can't find any of
them but does give me a bogus number for Cobo Hall. I try Detroit
info again and am told they are too busy, call back some other
time. Is this the benefit of deregulation and the retirment of ol'
Ma Bell?
</P>
<P>
   I try again. A voice identifies itself as a police department.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm trying to get Detroit information,'' I say.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're that, too,'' he assures me, but can't find the media
center, gets me a number for Cobo Hall that is attached to a
recording.
</P>
<P>
   I rummage around to locate ``Show Talk 99,'' the glossy
publication of the Detroit Dealers Association that puts on the
auto show _ big story on the media center. But no number. But there
is a number for the public relations firm . . . which is attached
to another recording.
</P>
<P>
   More rummaging. I find a number for an employee of said firm,
which triggers another recording _ but, hallelujah, this guy's
recording offers a number where he can be reached. At the media
center where the telephone company couldn't find its own
telephones.
</P>
<P>
   ``Why do you want to come?'' he asks. ``We have two feet of
snow, nobody can move, and there are 2,000 people stranded at the
airport sleeping on emergency blankets.'' He will convey my
messages as best he can. For the record, he is Joe Rohatynski _ or
at least he was answering JR's telephone.
</P>
<P>
   The radio casts doubt on tomorrow's chances . . . suddenly there
is a thundering and clattering on the roof and I know it's too late
for Santa Claus. I rush to the window and where once was a clear
view of the street is now only evergreen foliage. The huge
ice-encrusted pine out front is not quite so big now because 30
feet of it is blocking both front doors, but it has missed the car
and the power lines. Monday, I may be too busy with the chain saw
to think about flying.
</P>
<P>
   I pick up the telephone; time to change the hotel reservation.
Again. Marriott at least answers its telephones.
</P>
<P>
   Monday, I try the airline, just in case. Maybe the tree can
wait. ``Due to weather conditions, we are too busy to take your
call. . . .''
</P>
<P>
   With deep longing in my heart for Ma Bell, I pick up the chain
saw. It is a very big piece of tree.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
