A5051 &Cx1f; taf-z
u l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-GARDEN-COLUMN-$ADV10-     01-08 0879
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GARDEN-COLUMN-$ADV10-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TOO RARE TO GROW ANYWHERE BUT IN A CATALOGUE 
</HEADLINE>
  (For release Sun., Jan. 10) 
(JT) 
 By CASS PETERSON   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Tomatoes do not grow on trees. It's an immutable fact. It's also
a fact that some nursery catalogs ballyhoo the ``tree tomato,''
often with a drawing of a roundish, tree-shaped plant laden with
what look to be fat, red-ripe tomatoes.
</P>
<P>
   I like the idea. The drawing conjures up the image of a tomato
orchard, with row upon row of nicely pruned trees that bear bushels
of love apples every year without the bother of starting tomato
seedlings, planting them and staking them.
</P>
<P>
   Alas, the tree tomato is one of those beguiling novelties that
the nursery trade is so fond of. It's not a tomato at all, although
it's a member of the same family, the Solanaceae. It is a tropical
shrub with the botanical name Cyphomandra betacea. Its fruit _
which is usually yellowish-orange rather than red _ is edible, but
it doesn't taste like a tomato. (It's pulpier than a tomato, and
tart.) It can be eaten fresh, but more often it's stewed or made
into jam.
</P>
<P>
   It also takes a couple of years for a tree tomato to start
bearing that fruit, meaning that you'll need a place to protect the
plant (which can grow to 12 feet tall) in winter if the temperature
drops below freezing. The easy convenience of a tomato-bearing tree
starts to sound like work.
</P>
<P>
   I have no quarrel with garden novelties. Some of the most
interesting plants in my flower and vegetable gardens were
initially experiments, purchased as seed or seedlings from an
irresistible catalog description. Occasionally, but not often, the
description was borne out by performance.
</P>
<P>
   Several years ago, I tried the Cherokee toothache plant
(Spilanthes oleracea), described as a good salad ingredient and
palate cleanser. Actually, it's more like a palate para-lyzer.
Nibbling a leaf or flower bud numbs the tongue and mouth so
thoroughly that nothing eaten for an hour or so afterward is likely
to be tasted at all. But the plant is attractive, covered most of
the summer with orange-yellow blossoms that look like fat gumdrops.
And sampling it once clears up any confusion about the origins of
its name.
</P>
<P>
   I've grown a number of flowers that are supposed to be black _
pansies, hollyhocks, tulips, irises. The idea of black flowers
isn't all that appealing esthetically, but I can't help myself. I
have to know if it's really black or just deep purple, which is
more often the case. Black pansies are really black, and sometimes
I grow them in combination with orange-flowered ones as a Halloween
novelty.
</P>
<P>
   I don't really care if there's a blue rose. The colors available
seem more than adequate. But if I were a rose grower, I probably
couldn't resist trying every supposedly blue rose that appeared in
a catalog.
</P>
<P>
   I might not even be disappointed when it turned out to be dull
lavender instead, as long as it bloomed well and smelled good. None
of the white marigolds I've tried were really white, but very pale
yellow is still a nice color.
</P>
<P>
   I'm a sucker, too, for vegetables of an unusual hue, like purple
brussels sprouts, red celery, yellow beets, pink-fleshed potatoes,
white pumpkins and green eggplant. The latest rage in Swiss chard
is a variety called Bright Lights, a mixture that has pink, yellow,
red, orange and white stems. It tastes just like regular Swiss
chard, but it's prettier.
</P>
<P>
   It's worth remembering that many common vegetables and flowers
were once novelties in American gardens, and that many plants once
widely known are now grown mostly as novelties. Thomas Jefferson
considered kale a novelty and thought it would be useful to feed
sheep in the winter. Salsify, once a staple in kitchen gardens, is
now offered as an unusual root crop under its common name, oyster
plant. I half expect to see drawings of plants sprouting little
shellfish.
</P>
<P>
   A little hyperbole in the introduction of a plant or variety is
to be expected. When the marvelous vining petunias known as Wave
petunias first appeared, catalogs enthusiastically called them
four-season plants that were impervious to weather extremes and
would bloom even indoors in the winter, in sun or in shade.
</P>
<P>
   Not much chance of that. They're terrific petunias, but they're
still petunias. They need sun and they resent being dragged indoors
in the winter.
</P>
<P>
   When hyperbole reaches the level of the ridiculous, though, it's
time for the gardener to beware. It's possible for fruit trees to
bear several varieties of fruit on the same tree, thanks to the art
of grafting, so a six-in-one apple tree is within the realm of
possibility. But butterfly bushes don't bear blossoms of three
colors on one plant. A neighbor who believed a catalog's claim of a
tricolor butterfly bush last spring received a package containing
three small plants bundled together. Two were dead.
</P>
<P>
   And what of the tree tomato? I still want one, knowing full well
that it is not a tomato and not a tree of the sort I can add to the
landscape. But I also want to try some of those other fascinating
novelties splashed all over the covers of the latest crop of
catalogs.
</P>
<P>
   At such times it's good to remember that money, like tomatoes,
does not grow on trees.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
