 &HT;    (--Europe and Asia: KARL HORWITZ in Paris at 47-42-17-11; fax,
47-42-80-44 or 47-42-18-81; telex, 282-942. 
 &HT;    (--Latin America: OLIVIA VASQUEZ in Los Angeles, 310-798-0970;
fax, 310-798-7338.) 
 &HT;    
 By FLORA LEWIS  
 (Distributed by New York Times Special Features)  
 &HT;     EDITORS: On Jan. 22 Flora Lewis will be honored in New York by
the OVERSEAS PRESS CLUB, with its coveted ``Lifetime Recognition
Award.'' For more information and a bio, contact John Stickney, New
York Times Syndicate, 212-499-3341.) 
 &HT;    
 &HT;    PARIS _ Of course, there was never any doubt that it was coming,
but it's still hard to believe that this is really 1999. It's been
out there, waiting for us, for a long time, but more like one of
those things that are always to be expected but never actually
happen.
 &HT;    The year 2000 is something else, the start of a new century, a
new millennium, full of questions, predictions, new decisions. But
1999 is supposed to mark an ending, a long closure that after all
turns out to be uncertain and indecisive.
 &HT;    In terms of world affairs, the 20th century was particularly
short, from 1914, when the 19th century's balance of power and
faith in progress broke down, to 1991 when the Soviet Union and the
reign of ideology collapsed.
 &HT;    It was also particularly monstrous, and yet the very disasters
man wreaked upon man and nature provoked measures to break a
pattern of human horror. The illusion of the 1920s that war could
simply be outlawed was gone, but so was the myth of war as glory,
the noblest calling.
 &HT;    The failure of communism left democracy as the political system
and the market as the economic system _ in both cases, the clearly
preferred concepts. But the new doesn't just slip into place when
the old systems are gone. What is coming instead out of confusion
and greed in the afflicted countries looks totally unforeseeable.
 &HT;    Even democracy, if validated by the end of dictatorships, has
lost self-confidence. There are debates about whether or not it is
still relevant, in fact, about whether there's any need to be
concerned about government.
 &HT;    In the United States, 37 percent of voters cast ballots in the
last national election, slightly more than one in three, though the
Clinton sex scandal had provided all the spectacular drama that
crowd-pullers could wish.
 &HT;    Europe found a way to organize itself to make its worst
traditional enmities obsolete. Now, 11 Western European countries
have pooled their currencies in a single new one, the Euro. It is
not really the first because gold once served as the common measure
of value; yet the Euro is a huge step toward continued integration.
The participating nations will surely be joined by most of the
holdouts in a few years.
 &HT;    The idea that economies can and should be managed, born of the
savage excesses and wild cyclical swings in the rise of capitalism,
has been challenged once more by proof of the market's superior
performance. But at the same time, the market's arbitrary cruelties
spawn new demands for constraining limits, for protection of
workers and the environment. There has to be balance.
 &HT;    There was a vast increase in poverty, primarily because there
was such a vast increase in the world's population. And yet, like
war, poverty no longer seemed inevitable, decreed by nature and to
be endured. It has become possible to provide adequate food for the
world's population and to eliminate famine. It takes human will and
agreement, which exist in some measure, although far from enough.
 &HT;    In terms of changes in the way large numbers of people live, the
20th century was as long as the previous 500 or even 1,000 years.
People fly to outer space. They communicate, with sound and image,
in total defiance of time and space. They can conserve food and
make themselves comfortable despite the climate. They suppress much
disease and swallow pills so that the biblical old age of
threescore and ten is far less than the ordinary life expectancy in
the developed world.
 &HT;    Technological advance has achieved the momentum of a chain
reaction. People adjust surprisingly quickly. Change always has
costs and drawbacks, but it is welcomed for the extraordinary
improvements in material welfare and even just in convenience.
Science is admired and encouraged for its own sake, not only for
love of knowledge but because there's every reason to think that
sooner or later, new discoveries will bring new benefits.
 &HT;    Yet, science no longer provides the reassurance it once did that
the future can only get better and better. It poses weighty new
moral and ethical questions, about the beginnings of life and the
certainty of death, which it cannot even presume to answer. The new
capacities it offers are in many ways also new burdens, new
challenges that nothing has prepared the existing societies to
confront.
 &HT;    With the arrival of 1999, it is now clear where this century has
been, lots to be ashamed of, some things to be quite proud of _ a
lesson and a preparation, one has to hope, for doing better. It did
show that no invention, no trick, no blind belief will solve the
problems people face. For that, it takes people of good heart and
good will.
 &HT;    That seems so obvious that it's odd it took until 1999 for the
century to define itself.
 &HT;     (Flora Lewis is the former foreign-affairs columnist for The
New York Times.) 
 &HT;     c.1999 Flora Lewis 
