<SLUG> BC-O'HAIR-DIARIES-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
O'HAIR'S DIARY, LETTERS PRESENT NEW SIDE TO MISSING ATHEIST 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By JOHN MacCORMACK  
 c.1999 San Antonio Express-News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   AUSTIN, Texas _ In the public arena, she was a tough and profane
atheist battle-ax, quick with a lawsuit or an irreverent curse,
battling always the forces of organized religion.
</P>
<P>
   In private, she spoke tenderly of lovers and children, cherished
family gatherings at Christmas, and complained endlessly about
money, her waistline and the dreary burdens of the atheist cause.
</P>
<P>
   She also pined endlessly for the finer things in life.
</P>
<P>
   ``You, dear diary, are the only one who listens to me, so I'll
tell you what I want to do,'' Madalyn Murray O'Hair wrote Jan. 6,
1973, in her resolutions for the new year.
</P>
<P>
   ``File at least a couple of suits and win one of them, get a
building, get a Bible chair at University of Texas, get a mink coat
and a Cadillac, humiliate Billy Graham for money and move into a
bigger and better home,'' O'Hair wrote.
</P>
<P>
   O'Hair disappeared more than three years ago and is presumed
dead.
</P>
<P>
   Her handwritten diaries, covering 1953 to 1995, plus some
personal papers and letters, will soon be sold to help pay some of
the debts she left behind. Foremost is a bill from the Internal
Revenue Service for $250,000.
</P>
<P>
   ``My job is to get whatever assets Madalyn Murray O'Hair had and
turn them into cash, so her creditors can be paid,'' said Ron
Ingalls, an Austin lawyer serving as bankruptcy trustee.
</P>
<P>
   The diaries are the only thing of possible significant value she
left behind.
</P>
<P>
   But there are two significant gaps: from 1959 to 1972, during
the court battle over school prayer, and from 1990 to late 1995, a
period that could hold clues to her disappearance.
</P>
<P>
   It is not known if those volumes are missing or never were
written.
</P>
<P>
   Now secured in an Austin bank vault, the diaries never have been
read closely by outsiders. Their market value is unknown.
</P>
<P>
   ``My first goal is to get the word out and see what response
there is,'' Ingalls said.
</P>
<P>
   He has no personal theory of what happened to O'Hair; her son,
Jon Garth Murray; and granddaughter, Robin Murray O'Hair.
</P>
<P>
   The three vanished in San Antonio in late September 1995 along
with $500,000 in gold coins and a Florida con man, also presumed
dead.
</P>
<P>
   ``My thought is, if she is alive and reading the newspapers, and
sees her diaries are up for sale, she might all of a sudden pop up
with a lawyer and enjoin me from selling them,'' Ingalls said.
</P>
<P>
   When she vanished at age 76, O'Hair was an aging, marginal
cultural figure, decades removed from her prominence as the
self-proclaimed ``most-hated woman in America.''
</P>
<P>
   Her rise from obscurity as a Maryland housewife began in 1959
when she filed a suit against the Baltimore school district seeking
to remove prayer and Bible reading from public school.
</P>
<P>
   Four years later, the U.S. Supreme Court did just that in a
landmark ruling.
</P>
<P>
   And although O'Hair's suit was a secondary one in the case, she
had found her cause in the battle against organized religion.
</P>
<P>
   She quickly founded American Atheists, moved to Austin, and ran
the group and related atheist organizations until her
disappearance.
</P>
<P>
   Her sense of herself always was that of a historic figure.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm convinced now there was for 30 years an enormous
conspiracy for Christianization of our nation as part of the
assault on Godless communism,'' she wrote in a Sept. 15, 1975,
diary entry.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think the spying on me for my church-state activities
substantiates this beyond question. I want this exposed as
Watergate was, and how do I get it? I want it impactfully brought
home to everyone. I can't get TV time which means everything. I am
brought on to bullbait or bounce off some religious zealot, as a
show person, the irascible Mrs. O'Hair. A freak or token atheist,''
she wrote.
</P>
</TEXT>
