<HEADER>
A5099 &Cx1f; tad-z
u t &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-STEAMBOAT10-1stTAKE-C     01-08 1033
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-STEAMBOAT10-1stTAKE-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    EMBARGOED UNTIL JANUARY 10
 &HT;    Despite growing sophistication, ski resort remains a friendly
`country town at heart'
 &HT;    By Dan Hulbert
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   STEAMBOAT SPRINGS, Colo., _ As soon as I slung my body into an
empty chairlift, headed to a dizzying 10,600-foot mountaintop that
was never meant for ``intermediate'' skiers like me, I knew that I
had made the most boneheaded move of my life.
</P>
<P>
   Ah, but I was carried away! Figuratively, by the natural beauty
of this relatively remote ski resort, far from the hipster crowds
of Aspen and Vail; then literally, by a lift that no one else was
riding. I was at the midpoint, where the first tier of lifts ends
and the second tier begins, carrying the skilled (and the
foolhardy) to four peaks that offer the second longest vertical
drop (3,668 feet) among Colorado ski areas.
</P>
<P>
   I drank in a heady vista: craggy, forested steeps falling away
on all sides, aspen trunks as white and sharply etched as
rattlesnake fangs against the deep green of spruce. Far below,
beneath an expanse of violet-blue sky, undulant prairies of
dusty-green sagebrush and scrub pine spilled into the valley of the
Yampa River. Somewhere down there my wife Cathy was taking a ski
lesson.
</P>
<P>
   As soon as my chair hoisted away into cold, silent space, part
of me wished I were down there too. . . .
</P>
<P>
   We'd arrived the previous day to a gloomy prospect. What little
snow had been manufactured for the lower slopes was dissolving
under drizzle. It was one of the barest starts of the season ever
at Steamboat (there's no ``Springs'' in the resort name). We had
lunch in the Tugboat Grill, drawing minimal solace from its huge
juicy burgers and rugged saloon ambience (there's a 100-year-old
bar with a real bullet hole in it), gazing gloomily at the melting
slush and a vacation trickling down the drain.
</P>
<P>
   But next morning, when we stepped out of our hotel in town, we
looked up and saw that fresh powder had fallen overnight on the
higher slopes: Mother Nature had rolled out the white carpets
between jagged knobs of rock and swaths of green conifers. As we
drove the few miles up to the resort, the sun lifted above the
front range of the Rockies to our east and beams fell first upon
this slope, then upon that one, as if a theatrical spotlight
operator with a painterly eye were pointing out individual glories.
</P>
<P>
   We were greeted at the lifts by a statue of Billy Kidd, Olympic
silver medalist of the 1960s who's the resident pro here. Wearing
his familiar cowboy hat, Kidd's statue could be nicknamed the
Spirit of Steamboat in bronze.
</P>
<P>
   Steamboat Springs is the cow town that's the ``now'' town.
</P>
<P>
   Cow town: Ranchers in pickups still tool down Lincoln Avenue,
the main drag, trusty sheep dogs in back. One of the West's biggest
rodeos is held beside the Yampa every summer. Longhorns graze near
town, nostrils shooting steam on a frosty morn.
</P>
<P>
   Now town: A store called Old Tibet offers a selection of Hindu
and Buddhist art objects, and Nandu advertises ``tribal area rugs
and eclectic world imports.'' Gastronomic options include
Yama-Chans sushi bar and Antares restaurant, celebrated for its
cashew ice cream with warm mango fondue. Balloons Over Steamboat
offers even better views than Mount Werner.
</P>
<P>
   Steamboat's delightfully split personality stems partly from its
location, three hours northwest of Denver on a fascinating climatic
divide. From some canyon roads you can throw a rock and hit
snow-covered spruce on the shadowed, north-facing slope, then turn
around and peg one against sun-baked boulders and sagebrush on the
southern exposure. Despite heavy development around the ski area,
there are vast unspoiled spaces to explore on foot, snowshoe,
cross-country ski, snowmobile and horseback.
</P>
<P>
   ``Steamboat's just a country town at heart. Not a lot of fur
coats, but hey _ those are OK too. Anything goes,'' says Kay
Sullins, 46, whose Windwalker Tours specializes in towing people
around with horses _ by sleigh in winter, chuckwagons in summer.
</P>
<P>
   Lift operator Karen Vail (she's a bit chagrined by the name),
33, is quick to list the qualities that define the town and resort:
``There's a strong year-round community, which means a lot; we
cater to families, a lot; our champagne powder is renowned; our
Western flavor is unique; and as you can tell, we have an
unbelievably friendly staff!''
</P>
<P>
   With Vail's parting yell, ``Have a good run!'' fading behind me,
I rode the first lift; then, as previously described, rashly
boarded the second.
</P>
<P>
   Except for the occasional creak of the lift cables the whisper
of a cold wind, the ride to the top of Mount Werner is deliciously
silent. Snow gets deeper on spruce branches with each minute of
ascent. The boundary between whitened sky and quilted, wind-whipped
slopes grows less distinct, as if I were entering a dreamland in
the clouds.
</P>
<P>
   Then, suddenly, my chair clears the last ridge, the wisps of
cloud dissolve and I glide onto what seems the rooftop of the
world. Even IMAX can't top this astounding 360-degree view. To the
south and west, behind ice-tipped peaks, an ocean of desert begins;
reddish flattop mesas march into infinity. To the north and east
are mountains so titanic, so savagely beautiful with their
knifelike flanks and gleaming icecaps that they might as well be in
Nepal.
</P>
<P>
   Mark Twain, crossing Colorado by stagecoach, described in
``Roughing It'' exactly what I see: ``These sultans of the
fastnesses were turbaned with tumbled volumes of cloud, which
shredded away and drifted off fringed and torn, trailing their
continents of shadow after them.''
</P>
<P>
   ``At least,'' I think, turning my skis nervously toward the long
ride down, ``having seen this, I will not have died in vain.''
</P>
<P>
   Getting down Mount Werner is no walk in the park, but it is
exhilarating even for someone like me, struggling just to stay
alive. The high empty steeps slowly segued into the peopled lower
slopes, where skiers hooted their enjoyment and shouted greetings
(``Lunch at Tugboat _ 15 minutes!'') into the pristine air.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
