<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-01-08 16:39 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5100 &Cx1f; tad-z
u t &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-STEAMBOAT10-2NDTAKE-C     01-08 0987
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-STEAMBOAT10-2NDTAKE-COX </SLUG>

<TEXT>
<P>
   STEAMBOAT SPRINGS, Colo.,: pristine air.
</P>
<P>
   A river runs through it
</P>
<P>
   The legend about the town's name goes like this: French
trappers, following the Yampa in the early 19th century, heard a
chugging noise that they took as a steamboat. It turned out to be a
mineral spring spouting water and steam 15 feet in the air, one of
150 local springs that Ute Indians had visited for centuries.
Dynamite used to build the railroad in 1908 is believed to have
caused the mysterious disappearance of the ``chug.''
</P>
<P>
   The Yampa tumbles smack through town, so clean that fishermen
pull in trout just a few steps off Lincoln Avenue. Sullins'
favorite moments are dawn sleigh rides on the river path, ``the
beautiful, eerie sight of mist over the water.'' The town has a
sprinkling of stone Victorian buildings from which you may expect
to see a bowler-hatted Bat Masterson emerge. At the Tread of
Pioneers Museum, a houseful of Indian and pioneer artifacts, you
can get a free map for a self-guided, historical walking tour.
</P>
<P>
   From the outside, the 1940 Harbor Hotel, our first
accommodations, does not qualify under ``charm.'' But by the
standards of new motels and condos spilling across the foothills
south of town, the Harbor is a rare intown pocket of homeyness and
a bargain ($85 double occupancy, off-peak) to boot. In the spa, we
encountered a party of Germans apparently quite pleased to be
there: singing the Seven Dwarfs' ``Heigh Ho, Heigh Ho!'' song in
their native tongue.
</P>
<P>
   The Harbor has a strategic location for walking to restaurants,
and one of the best is the cozy, clubby Steamboat Yacht Club,
occupying an old fish hatchery on the river. We sampled classic
high-country fare: trout, which was fine and fresh, and elk, which
we found delicious, less gamy than venison and very close to steak.
</P>
<P>
   Ski jumps, waterfalls
</P>
<P>
   An easy walk from downtown across the Yampa bridge is Howelsen
Hill Park, home of the nation's first Olympic-scale ski jump, built
in 1915 by well-known ski jumper Carl Howelsen.
</P>
<P>
   Now, is it just me or is there something irresistibly wacky
about a man called the Flying Norseman (his stage name with the
Barnum &AMP; Bailey circus) landing here at a time when automobiles,
let alone Norwegian celebrities, were rare? International Olympians
still train here. Locals say it's the best show in town: You can
actually hear the contestants whistling down the wind. Howelsen
Park is a good outing with younger kids because there's a skating
rink and kiddie-sized ski slope.
</P>
<P>
   You know you're in Steamboat Springs when the person who runs
the arts center previously worked as a veterinarian's assistant,
birthing calves and once ``tending an eagle with a bum wing _
mountain lion probably got at him.'' Tami Jenkins, 33, runs the
Depot Arts Center (piano concerts, painting exhibits, other
attractions) in a handsomely redone 1908 train depot.
</P>
<P>
   A great hiking site, Fish Creek Falls, is four miles northeast
of town. Paths are strewn with the tarnished bronze coins of aspen
leaves. A few hundred yards from the parking lot you can view the
spectacular 285-foot falls. Water shoots down into the falls'
self-made cathedral _ flying icicle buttresses, wild scrollworks of
frozen spray _ and gushes out the bottom into a deep gorge.
</P>
<P>
   On the slopes
</P>
<P>
   The Steamboat resort opened in the early 1960s and has never
stopped expanding: Today there are 21 lifts (including an
eight-passenger enclosed gondola) serving 140 trails across 3,000
acres.
</P>
<P>
   There are reportedly 43 former or current Olympic skiers living
in the Steamboat area, more than any other town, so there must be
some truth to the boasts about ``champagne powder.'' Steamboat gets
330 inches of the fizzy manna annually. The base area, Gondola
Village, is designed so you can park your skis, have lunch, shop
and sip a hot drink on a sun deck without having to mess with a
car.
</P>
<P>
   There is plenty of child care, including a ski school for the
tykes. And yet there's far more apres-ski than watching ``Barney.''
The resort's bar scene includes the Inferno (a dance club you could
almost ski into, and someone probably has) as well as Dos Amigos,
which serves outstanding Mexican food.
</P>
<P>
   A certain bravado, an esprit de Steamboat, prevails among
hot-shot skiers and snowboarders. As if the old-time swagger of the
cowboy has been reincarnated in today's snow dudes and snow babes.
I heard the following exchange between two buckos of about 20:
</P>
<P>
   ``Hey, man, how's yer face?''
</P>
<P>
   ``Great, man! (pointing to his teeth) See, you can't even tell
which ones they replaced!''
</P>
<P>
   ``Excellent! Coulda been worse _ at least you didn't lose
consciousness, man!''
</P>
<P>
   (No, don't fret about dentist bills: There are plenty of
beginner and intermediate slopes, too.)
</P>
<P>
   Goodnight to Steamboat
</P>
<P>
   Our final evening was spent in charming quarters: Steamboat Bed
and Breakfast.
</P>
<P>
   The early-1900s house, white with blue-green trim and a steep
tin roof to shed the snows, was originally the parsonage of a
Congregational church that stood next door before it was burned
down by a lightning strike (legend says the event was not
coincidental: the preacher was a rover). There are only five guest
rooms, airy and immaculate, and a big living/dining area full of
plants, antiques and books.
</P>
<P>
   From our Sunset Room, cozily tucked under the eaves, I looked
down on the twinkling lights of town, just a few blocks away; the
faint outline of the Yampa winding through the dusk; the Howelsen
ski jump lit up with spotlights like a runway of the gods.
</P>
<P>
   True, I hadn't taken in the night view from Hazie's Restaurant
on Mount Werner, known as the Steamboat experience. Maybe next
time. For now, I was still reliving the view from that lofty spot
in broad daylight, and I couldn't imagine anything grander.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
