<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-COFFEE10-1stTAKE-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    EMBARGOED UNTIL JANUARY 10
 &HT;    Bean entrepreneur Don Wilson traded the fast track for a more
measured life
 &HT;    By Patricia Guthrie
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   GAINESVILLE, Ga. _ Don Wilson had sipped and stirred his future
for years.
</P>
<P>
   It just took him a while to figure it out.
</P>
<P>
   He knew he liked this North Georgia town, having moved to the
self-proclaimed Poultry Capital of the World from Scotland in 1986
as an animal science researcher. (``I like the climate and Lake
Lanier(Ga.),'' he says in a dancing Highland lilt, ``and I find the
people to be very natural and very friendly.'') After that, he
climbed the ranks as an animal industry veterinarian at Hoffmann-La
Roche, an international pharmaceutical company that had its
subsidiary, Agri-Bio, based here.
</P>
<P>
   But that big-money job developing antibiotics for farm animals
meant constant travel away from his wife and children, and a
growing reliance on alcohol to smooth out the rough edges.
</P>
<P>
   In 1994, he gave up the hard stuff and immersed himself in the
world of coffee. Always a connoisseur of the bean _ even back home,
among the tea and biscuit crowd of Edinburgh _ he became addicted
to learning its finer points.
</P>
<P>
   And one day, he looked up from his daily cup of joe at
Gainesville's homegrown haven _ St. Ives Coffeehouse tucked into a
quirky 1912 house just down from the town's fashionable mansions _
and pondered its brightly painted walls and funky lampshades.
</P>
<P>
   He stopped, yes, and smelled the coffee. He'd been looking for a
new way to bring home the bacon; why not something he already
loved?
</P>
<P>
   ``I suddenly realized,'' says Wilson, ``this looked like a much
better way of life than hanging out in planes and airports.''
</P>
<P>
   So he bought the small retail business _ lock, stock and bags of
beans in the basement _ from Gil and Barbara Johnson, who wanted to
trade the company they'd founded in 1989 for a chance to sail the
Caribbean.
</P>
<P>
   ``A lot of people say they want to be their own boss and do
something more fulfilling,'' he says. ``But they don't. More
important than money, power and position is personal contentment.''
</P>
<P>
   With its divided rooms where students study for hours in one
corner while others smoke and chat in another, the coffeehouse
already had plenty of atmosphere. Wilson added colorful displays
from local artists, antique lamps with various shapes to the light,
grazing menu.
</P>
<P>
   It wasn't long before he plunged into the wholesale side of the
coffee business in early 1997, turning a warehouse tucked in
between the chicken-processing plants into the headquarters of St.
Ives Coffee Roasters Inc. The jewel of the expanded operation is a
roasting plant capable of turning out 2,000 pounds a day, 20 tons a
week.
</P>
<P>
   It's not hard to find.
</P>
<P>
   Just take a whiff.
</P>
<P>
   ``I am a rose among the thorns,'' jokes Wilson, pulling up to
his warehouse in a blue Dodge pickup. ``It's kind of ironic I ended
up right across the street from the poultry business. In fact, the
building I am in now was where we marketed antibiotics for the
chicken industry.''
</P>
<P>
   His 5,000-square-foot building is chock-full of all things java:
flavored syrups, hefty 100-pound burlap sacks full of raw beans,
rows and rows of roasted bagged beans waiting to be shipped to
gourmet shops and, of course, a coffee room where he samples new
brews.
</P>
<P>
   ``Zimbabwe Pinnacle,'' he says, dipping his hand into a sample
bag. ``That's my new favorite up-and-coming bean. We're delighted
with it. Look at its beautiful pastel shade and how round and
perfect the shape is. It has good acidity, too. Some people think
it has an aftertaste like burgundy wine.''
</P>
<P>
   A better cup
</P>
<P>
   Not that he'd know firsthand anymore.
</P>
<P>
   Wilson, 44, understands there are no guarantees in the highly
competitive wholesale coffee market, but he never regrets walking
away from his old job _ lucrative and secure as it was.
</P>
<P>
   ``I reviewed my whole life and where it was leading,'' he says,
sitting in an office full of boxes, labels and product information.
``I decided I didn't like where it was leading. I felt I was at
grave risk for alcohol dependence and decided to do everything I
could do to break it.''
</P>
<P>
   He checked himself into Smyrna's (Ga.) Ridgeview Institute and
emerged sober and committed to helping others, agreeing to be part
of Bill Moyers' public television series, ``Moyers on Addiction:
Close to Home'' that aired last spring.
</P>
<P>
   Whenever he's not working or with his family, Wilson helps
others in recovery. ``I want to be brutally honest about it,'' he
says. ``I want people to know it's soul-destroying. I want people
to know there is help. And it works.''
</P>
<P>
   Equally passionate about beans, Wilson traveled to the mountains
of Costa Rica in 1997 to visit La Minita, one of the world's most
discerning coffee estates, home to 175,000 coffee trees. There, he
and his master roaster, Scott Tyre, toured the factory and fields,
picked beans by hand and studied the subtle complexities of
harvesting, milling, processing and roasting.
</P>
<P>
   He also learned the fine art of sorting La Minita's beans. The
100 workers appear to be playing solitaire as they carefully
inspect each bean; only a select 5 percent of each crop is deemed
worthy of La Minita's label.
</P>
<P>
   ``They are the highest quality in the world,'' Wilson says.
``Every single bean is perfect because every single bean is
hand-selected.''
</P>
<P>
   Wilson sells La Minita coffee beans for $13.99 a pound; the
brand is one of his best sellers. By comparison, Jamaican Blue
Mountain is his most expensive coffee at $29.99 a pound.
</P>
<P>
   What St. Ives specializes in, he says, is known as specialty
coffee _ ``the king of the coffee lineage.'' The highest grade of
coffee available, it's made from Class 1 beans (on a scale of 1 to
5).
</P>
<P>
   Atlanta's J. Martinez &AMP; Co., which supplies coffee to fine
restaurants and stores such as Williams-Sonoma, sells only estate
coffee, grown on family-run Jamaican estates. (Specialty coffees
can also be estate coffees, if they come from a single plantation _
such as La Minita.)
</P>
<P>
   Wilson's imported beans come from all over the world to be
roasted and packaged on-site, and he claims they're the finest and
freshest in Georgia. Or maybe the entire Southeast, he boasts,
after steaming a perfect cup to give a quick lesson on color,
texture and taste.
</P>
<P>
   ``See this espresso,'' he says, pouring off the dark, thick
liquid from a tiny silver pitcher. ``A good espresso should have a
red flash to it, a reddish-brown tint to it and a perfect `crema'
at the top. Our espresso blend is a big seller. It's a mix of
French Italian, Vienna and Costa Rican Tarrazu beans.''
</P>
<P>
   Many of the locals agree with his assessment.
</P>
<P>
   ``I go every morning at 8 a.m., after I drop off my kids at
school and before I go to work,'' says Doyle Johnson, 47, who owns
his own clothing business. ``They roast and brew different coffee
every day. It's always fresh.'' Sandy Easterbrooks, a massage
therapist at the nearby Relaxation Center, unwinds in the pleasant
patio area. Here, the business' namesake, ivy, trickles down the
white and green-trimmed house.
</P>
<P>
   ``I especially like to sit under the trees outside when the
weather is nice and talk to friends,'' Easterbrooks says.
</P>
<P>
   Former Gainesville residents who've moved on but still desire
the St. Ives taste (packaged in bright blue bags adorned with the
logo: ``The closest you can get to the coffee tree'') order it by
mail from as far away as Alaska, Australia and Hawaii (really).
Even a just-passing-through New Yorker took a shine to Wilson's
beans last year. He sent the St. Ives retail staff an e-mail saying
how impressed he was with the ``great coffee in Gainesville.'' The
letter hangs above the sink in the small kitchen where salads and
quiches are prepared.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
