<DOCNO> NYT19990108.0211 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-01-08 16:40 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5106 &Cx1f; tad-z
u l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-COFFEE10-2ndTAKE-COX     01-08 1299
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-COFFEE10-2ndTAKE-COX </SLUG>

<TEXT>
<P>
   GAINESVILLE, Ga.: are prepared.
</P>
<P>
   The beans, baby
</P>
<P>
   But all St. Ives beans arrive green. They must be roasted _ and
roasted right _ to end up as a fine cup of coffee, espresso,
cappuccino or cafe fortissimo (an original St. Ives creation of
espresso over ice with cream and brandy extracts.)
</P>
<P>
   ``The worst thing you can do with specialty coffee is roast it
wrong,'' Wilson says. ``Every single bean has its own protocol as
to how we roast it.''
</P>
<P>
   Enter his mean green Diedrich C-180 Coffee Roaster with its
rocketlike dimensions and a control panel of silver knobs, buzzers
and lights. ``This baby can do 300 pounds at a pop,'' Wilson says,
patting his $100,000 investment with pride. ``There's no other
roaster like it in Georgia.''
</P>
<P>
   In fact, there's only one other roaster like it in the world.
``This is the prototype for a roaster this big,'' Wilson says.
``They then went ahead and built a second one after mine.''
</P>
<P>
   The mighty machine is gas-fired with a spinning drum the size of
a kiddie wading pool. Wilson and Tyre, who's also in charge of
production, usually roast a few mornings a week at the wholesale
site. The retail store cooks up smaller batches nearly every
morning in a mini-roaster.
</P>
<P>
   After roasting, the now-darkened beans are blown by a vacuum-air
system to a packing machine where they're measured and poured warm
into the bright blue St. Ives bags. Wilson uses a state-of-the-art
bag (lined in aluminum with a one-way valve that minimizes
oxidation) that gives the coffee a shelf life of at least nine
months.
</P>
<P>
   St. Ives also caters to those who like their coffee flavored,
preferring such concoctions as Chocolate Hazelnut or Pralines and
Cream over the purebred Kona, Sumatra and Vienna Roast.
</P>
<P>
   ``Of course, y'know Southern'rs, wot they like, Southh'rn Peecan
fla'vr,'' Wilson says, rolling his Highland lilt so far it crosses
into the next county. St. Ives' flavored creations are sold under
the Hawthorne Hills Gourmet Coffee name; two-ounce sample packs are
typically sold in gift stores around the Southeast.
</P>
<P>
   Wilson supplies St. Ives coffee to coffeehouses around the
state, including his own competition, a downtown coffee shop called
Penny University. (He chuckles when customers tell him the coffee
seems to have improved down the street.) He also stages frequent
tastings of his coffee, ever in search of converts.
</P>
<P>
   ``What we try and do is get people to taste it,'' Wilson says.
``The usual reaction is, `Wow, that's wonderful coffee,' and we
hope they are hooked after that.
</P>
<P>
   ``Teaching the consumer there is a difference about specialty
coffee is important. These are not blends. They are the genuine
arabicas, and they do cost a bit more. But we are bringing the
highest level of coffee to the supermarket customer.''
</P>
<P>
   For Wilson, waking up and smelling the coffee, then jumping into
it, hasn't been easy. Perhaps most difficult, says Dennis MacArdle,
Wilson's wholesale director, is the challenge of getting people to
change the coffee they'v always brewed at home.
</P>
<P>
   ``Most people, when they buy specialty coffee, they usually go
right to the brand they already know and drink,'' says MacArdle, a
former children's dentist who also made a midlife career switch.
``Name recognition and deep pockets is what it takes in this
business. If you have that, you might be successful.''
</P>
<P>
   Wilson's determined not to give up too soon like many small
coffee business ventures. ``There are coffee-roasting shops and
kiosks opening monthly everywhere, including in Georgia,'' MacArdle
says. ``We know because we supply some of them. I went to one in
Alpharetta (Ga.) the other day, and it was gone. Ace Hardware next
door had expanded into it. ''
</P>
<P>
   A measured life
</P>
<P>
   John Martinez, who's operated Atlanta's J. Martinez &AMP; Co. coffee
business the past 10 years, calls the smaller roasting enterprises
such as St. Ives the microbreweries of the coffee world.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm amazed at the number of coffee roasters popping up in and
around Georgia,'' Martinez says. ``And they have potential to sell
to the local market.''
</P>
<P>
   Martinez's own beans range in price from $10 to $300 a pound and
come directly from his Jamaican homestead and coffee plantation.
</P>
<P>
   His critique on St. Ives: ``Not bad. It's a typical generic
coffee that one would buy from a broker.''
</P>
<P>
   Well, you can't impress everybody.
</P>
<P>
   Even so, the judges at the 1998 Atlanta National Gourmet Show
awarded a blue ribbon for best overall beverage to St. Ives'
entered drink _ an ice-cold espresso-based potion called St. Ives
China Bianco, made from coffee, chocolate, English Toffee Cream and
China Bianco flavored syrup. ``That's our only prize so far, ''
Wilson says, peering up at the award above the jars upon jars of
brown beauties. ``We were slightly amazed by it, actually. It was
our first attempt at any contest.''
</P>
<P>
   Although it may seem crowded in corporate coffee land, with a
Starbucks or Caribou Coffee on every other corner and a Barnie's
Coffee &AMP; Tea in every mall, Wilson sees room for small, home-grown
businesses.
</P>
<P>
   ``Those Starbucks, I don't know how people can stand to go
there,'' he says, setting down a cup of coffee (cream and sugar) on
a lace tablecloth at his coffeehouse. Whenever he gets on a coffee
rant, his accent thickens: ``They 'ave abso-lootely no characktar.
They'ara so damn sterile. They'ara like the McDonalds of tha coffee
world.''
</P>
<P>
   Then he turns philosophical.
</P>
<P>
   ``I just want to build a nice, viable, medium-size company and
be able to stop once in awhile to take a vacation with my kids,''
he says, taking a sip before peering into the bottom of the cup and
beyond. (So far, so good: He estimates last year's sales at
$450,000 from the retail and wholesale businesses, which is twice
what he made the year before; he says he hopes to double that
figure this year.)
</P>
<P>
   ``The pressure of life in the year 2000 and beyond is going to
be unbelievable,'' Wilson reflects, reaching for a Vantage
cigarette he'll wait to smoke till he gets outside. ``Already, the
time for reflection and private thought is almost nonexistent. I
see highly intelligent people coming in here all the time really in
need of a break.''
</P>
<P>
   Which is ultimately where he thinks he comes in.
</P>
<P>
   ``I guess my contribution is making a coffee that customers say
is bloody good,'' he says. ``At least it will help put them in a
better mood.''
</P>
<P>
   The man himself
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Born: Edinburgh, Scotland, in 1954.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Family: Married to Virginia; one son, Euan, 14 (who loves
coffee but only drinks the high-priced La Minita), and one
daughter, Natasha, 11 (who has not yet developed a taste for java).
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Education: Doctorate of veterinary medicine, Edinburgh
University, 1977; member of the Royal College of Veterinary
Surgeons, 1977; and the British equivalent of an MBA, Bradford
University, England.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Guilty pleasure: Tennis, weight lifting and salmon fishing in
British Columbia. Holds the unofficial world record for catching a
``a cock and a hen King salmon back-to-back,'' he says, which
weighed a total of 107 pounds.
</P>
<P>
   The whole bean
</P>
<P>
   You can find the St. Ives Coffeehouse in Gainesville(Ga) at 915
Green St. N.W., opposite the Gainesville Civic Center. The retail
shop sits at the intersection of U.S.State Highway 129 and Ga.State
Highway 60.
</P>
<P>
   To order by phone, call
</P>
<P>
   1-800-767-5282 or 770-287-3200 or visit the Web site to learn
about specialty coffee or order: http://www.stivescoffee.com
</P>
<P>
   St. Ives beans are at Harris Teeter grocery stores in Atlanta
and at Bell's, IGA and Quality markets in North Georgia.
</P>
<P>
   Patricia Guthrie writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
