<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-01-08 16:40 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5107 &Cx1f; tad-z
u l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-HANDBAGS10-COX     01-08 0403
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HANDBAGS10-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    EMBARGOED UNTIL JANUARY 10
 &HT;    Holding the bag
 &HT;    By Marylin Johnson
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   You handbag lovers have a reason to carry on.
</P>
<P>
   The bags of the moment are smaller, hand-held styles,
reminiscent of ones carried in the '40s and '50s, such as Chanel's
quilted bag and Hermes structured Kelly bag, named for the late
actress Grace Kelly.
</P>
<P>
   Today's hand-held versions range from a tiny canister-shaped
evening bag _ big enough for lipstick, mirror and a $20 bill _ to a
soft, casual tote that holds keys, a billfold and cell phone. They
come in leathers, knits, straws and a variety of linens and silks,
in a bonanza of shapes and colors.
</P>
<P>
   The return of hand-held bags, also called top-handle bags, is
attributed to femininity in fashion ready-to-wear.
</P>
<P>
   ``With fashion designers like Stella McCartney of Chloe and the
team of Dolce and Gabbana pushing ladylike clothes, bags needed to
be less serious and heavy-looking,'' says New York handbag designer
Marcia Sherrill. ``A satchel that you hold is less cumbersome than,
say, a shoulder bag and fits into the mood of today's dressing.''
</P>
<P>
   Evening bag designer Mary Norton of Charleston, S.C., says her
customers, who include actress Julia Louis-Dreyfus, like to carry
her colorful, whimsical bags to add a dash of glamour to that
little black dress. The eye-catching bags are decorated with
feathers, flowers or stones, whatever strikes Norton's fancy.
</P>
<P>
   It's not surprising that Americans spent $4.4 billion on
handbags last year, according to Accessories magazine's fashion
market editor Canty Gross. ``All ages are carrying these types of
bags,'' Gross says. ``Someone older, who is used to this style,
might opt for a more expensive Kleinberg Sherrill straw while a
younger woman would carry the woven nylon Sak, a trendy, less
expensive casual bag.''
</P>
<P>
   Many career women are also carrying these top-handle bags.
``It's a subtle trend,'' says New York trend tracker Ellen
Campuzano, ``yet a fresh approach to handbags.''
</P>
<P>
   And she points out one important selling point for those who
still love their shoulder bags: Many bags have long enough handles
_ or they come with a removable shoulder strap _ so they can be
slung over your shoulder.
</P>
<P>
   Marylin Johnson writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution.
</P>
<P>
