<DOCNO> NYT19990108.0213 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-01-08 16:40 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5108 &Cx1f; tad-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-OPRY10-1stTAKE-COX     01-08 1471
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-OPRY10-1stTAKE-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    EMBARGOED UNTIL JANUARY 10
 &HT;    Opry faces its future
 &HT;    By Miriam Longino
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   NASHVILLE _ Twenty-five years after it moved to the suburbs, the
Grand Ole Opry is coming home. This Friday and Saturday, America's
longest-running live radio show returns to the halls of the
restored Ryman Auditorium _ its home for 31 years _ for three
shows. Few would have imagined this moment back on March 15, 1974,
when Johnny Cash and a cast of country music stars took the Ryman
stage for the last time and tearfully wailed ``Will the Circle Be
Unbroken,'' delivered as the building's eulogy.
</P>
<P>
   But on the eve of this historic homecoming, today's Grand Ole
Opry finds itself at a major crossroads.
</P>
<P>
   Over the past 10 years, and especially since the closing of the
Opryland theme park in December 1997, management concedes that
ticket sales to Opry shows, now performed at the ``new''
glass-and-wood Opry House on the outskirts of town, have been down.
While the country music audience grows younger, spending millions
on pop-oriented acts such as Shania Twain, Garth Brooks and Faith
Hill, the Opry's cast of regulars is graying. Of the mainstay
performers, for example, Little Jimmy Dickens is 78, Jeannie Seely
is 58, Skeeter Davis is 67 and Bill Carlisle is 90. Many haven't
had a hit record in decades.
</P>
<P>
   ``My folks grew up listening to this all their life; it takes
them back to their childhoods,'' says 21-year-old Joseph Ibrahim
after a recent Opry performance. ``But I kind of see it fading away
with my generation. I didn't know the people on the show. It would
be great if they could somehow let this generation know about
this.''
</P>
<P>
   In an effort to continue the Opry tradition, a passel of newer
artists such as Brooks, Travis Tritt, Clint Black, Alan Jackson and
Patty Loveless have joined the cast, but they appear infrequently,
some not even giving the required four performances a year. (For
decades, the Opry had a strict policy that members were expected to
make 26 appearances a year. The standard now is four, although some
artists, such as Black, have been no-shows in some years.) In the
audience on a recent Saturday night, most ticket holders appear to
be senior citizens, or fast approaching retirement age. About a
fourth of the seats (admittedly, on a holiday weekend) were empty.
</P>
<P>
   In the competitive age of corporate radio, the clear-channel
signal of Nashville station WSM-AM, which once beamed the Opry to
places as far away as Canada, has been significantly diluted by
competing frequencies.
</P>
<P>
   ``Kids (today) don't sit out in Decatur like I did with an
aerial antennae hanging out the window to listen to Hank
Williams,'' says Opry star Bill Anderson, 61. ``You can't even pick
up WSM in Atlanta anymore.''
</P>
<P>
   There's also concern in the Nashville music community that the
Opry might disappear from television. Since 1985, a half-hour of
the Saturday night show has been broadcast over the Nashville
Network, which was recently purchased by CBS Cable. The New
York-based corporation has been bold in its attempt to seek younger
demographics for the channel, and many fear the Opry broadcast will
be edged out for youth-oriented programs such as ``Roller Jam,''
TNN's new Roller Derby show.
</P>
<P>
   Brian Hughes, TNN vice president of programming, vehemently
denies the rumors. ``Our commitment to the Grand Ole Opry on
Saturday night is certainly a long-term one,'' he says, pointing
out that the show brings in 1 million viewers a week. But he also
says the network would like to see the TV broadcast become more
marketable. ``The Opry of today and the future is never one that
slights the older artists, but . . . part of the discussions we're
having (with Opry management) is to also bring young artists on
there who are getting radio play.''
</P>
<P>
   Changing times
</P>
<P>
   It would certainly be premature to sound the death knell for the
Opry, particularly when the company that owns it, Gaylord
Entertainment, says the show still makes money and is passionately
supported by artists and fans alike.
</P>
<P>
   ``We wouldn't even have country music if it weren't for the
Grand Ole Opry,'' declares newcomer Terri Clark, who has played the
Opry half a dozen times in the past two years. ``It's the heritage
and background that has made it possible for us to do what we're
doing now. We need to go there and play, to keep the Opry young,
because when this older generation goes away, who's going to come
to the Grand Ole Opry? We have the responsibility to make sure our
generation knows what's going on there. It isn't as much money as
going out and playing our own gigs, but we wouldn't be making that
money in the first place if it weren't for the Grand Ole Opry.''
</P>
<P>
   Some stars are working tenaciously for its survival. Vince Gill
appeared more than 40 times on the Opry stage in 1998, mainly out
of a deep commitment to keep the show going. Major stars such as
Brooks lend their faces to the institution, talking about their
inductions as if their names had been inked onto the roll that's
called up yonder itself. According to her manager, Ken Kragen,
Trisha Yearwood is ``thrilled'' that she has been asked to join, to
be inducted this spring. And certainly there is still nothing like
the near-spiritual feeling of watching the program live. Opry stars
such as Dickens, Jean Shepard or Charley Pride may not be on
contemporary country charts, but their historical contribution to
country music is as valuable as any of today's Top 10 tunes.
</P>
<P>
   In the '90s, however, some corporate powers on Music Row have
shown signs of dollar-induced amnesia when it comes to the Grand
Ole Opry. As country music has boomed (going from a $700
million-a-year industry in 1990 to a $1.8 billion-a-year behemoth
in 1997), the stakes and competition have gotten higher. New acts
come and go on Music Row like couriers, delivering one hit song,
and then disappearing forever. The country music culture isn't
exclusively controlled by Nashville-based acts anymore, as free
agents such as Twain and LeAnn Rimes sell millions in spite of not
being in ``the club.''
</P>
<P>
   As a result, new acts no longer have to step into the wooden
circle in the center of the Opry stage, the holy spot literally cut
out of the floor of the Ryman and transplanted into the new Opry
house in 1974, in order to make it.
</P>
<P>
   ``At one time, the Opry was the premiere radio showcase for
country music in America, but it's not anymore,'' says historian
Paul Kingsbury, author of ``The Grand Ole Opry History of Country
Music. ``It's a hallowed institution that a lot of artists and fans
revere, but the Opry is no longer in the position to make careers.
A radio show emanating from WSM is not enough to really make a
difference in the careers of people like Marty Stuart or Vince Gill
or Garth Brooks. They don't need the Opry. It needs them.''
</P>
<P>
   Even Opry vets such as Anderson are eager to entice new blood
into the fold.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think what has to be changed at the Opry more than anything
is that we have lived with the attitude that the world is going to
beat a path to our door,'' says Anderson. ``This is almost the year
2000, and things change. I think maybe we got to start meeting
folks halfway.''
</P>
<P>
   It isn't an easy task. The basic Opry format has changed little
since the days when hillbilly acts such as Uncle Dave Macon and the
Fruit Jar Drinkers were the main attraction, and that familiarity
is part of the show's appeal. Sure, the Opry has made way for
shifting tastes, such as the era of the pedal-steel singer in the
'50s, the Nashville sound of Patsy Cline in the '60s and even the
introduction of full drum kits to the stage by the mid-'70s. But
its main outlet has always been radio, specifically 650 on the
Nashville AM dial (WSM). In the age of the Internet and cable
television, that exposure is hardly a blip. And, more than just
about anything else, young country artists want exposure.
</P>
<P>
   ``I know every contemporary artist wants to be a member. It's an
honor to be involved,'' says Yearwood's manager Kragen. ``But from
a business standpoint, it really revolves around the value and
reach of TNN. It's more than the Opry; it's how much exposure do
you get by appearing on it versus doing other sorts of programs.''
</P>
<P>
   When acts appear on the Opry, they are paid union scale, which
is often no more than $500 to $1,000 an appearance. Unless they
appear on the nationally televised TNN broadcast, an entertainer
such as Brooks is only performing for an in-house audience of 3,000
and a radio audience of 100,000 during an Opry spot. In contrast,
for one night on the road, Brooks can clear a quarter of a million
dollars. And he can pack Central Park.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
