</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990108.0214 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-01-08 16:40 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5109 &Cx1f; tad-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-OPRY10-2NDTAKE-COX     01-08 0895
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-OPRY10-2NDTAKE-COX </SLUG>

<TEXT>
<P>
   NASHVILLE: Central Park.
</P>
<P>
   Also, the very thing that so endears the institution to country
fans _ its history and tradition _ may be one of the strongest
barriers to growth. The tight-knit Opry family can be notoriously
resistent to change. Though they may not be the moneymakers they
once were, their power is still strong in this town. Questioning
the Opry's future out loud seems to be a taboo, kind of like
visiting the big Baptist church downtown and pointing out that the
pews aren't full anymore. But for many of the older cast members,
it's their only prestigious performance venue; they gave up the
road years ago. Some of the members' livelihood actually depends on
the Opry check and the health benefits that come with it.
</P>
<P>
   Passing the baton
</P>
<P>
   ``I would hate to wake up in my lifetime and know there is no
more Grand Ole Opry,'' says Opry legend Porter Wagoner. ``It's a
very important cog in country music. It's the mother church, the
cornerstone of the industry.''
</P>
<P>
   Plopped in an overstuffed chair here in dressing room No. 14 at
the Grand Ole Opry house, the entertainer, 71, contemplates the
future of the Opry. His purple jacket, splashed with rhinestones,
rests on a hanger near a bright wall of dressing table lights. He's
smoking a cigarette, within earshot of the muffled sounds in the
busy hallway outside _ fiddles, bursts of laughter, people tuning
guitars and the clack-clack-clack of square dancers in their shiny
white tap shoes and red gingham skirts.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's a picture of me and Minnie Pearl made back in 1970,''
he says, surrounded by four walls of framed photographs crammed
together like mounted pages out of a country music yearbook. ``Me
and `Strang' was good friends,'' Wagoner notes, pointing to a faded
color snapshot of the late comic Stringbean. There's a
black-and-white image of a much younger Wagonmaster (as Porter has
long been called) nestled up against a girlish Dolly Parton, their
matching blond pompadours nearly as big as their toothy smiles. But
tucked in between the vintage portraits, there's also Porter with
Garth Brooks. Porter with Travis Tritt. Porter with Alan Jackson,
Patty Loveless and Vince Gill.
</P>
<P>
   The contrast is striking. These younger, slicker artists seem
out of a different time and place than Wagoner and his Hall of Fame
friends. They are the savvy, uptown acts that have turned the once
homespun country music business into a global industry. But the
star with the biggest name recognition in Nashville _ more than
Porter, more than Gill or even Garth _ is still the Grand Ole Opry
itself. Even the green-and-white city limits sign proclaims
Nashville not the center of the billion-dollar country music
recording industry but ``Home of the Grand Ole Opry.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Everybody wants the Opry to thrive for years to come, and I
think there will be a collective effort in Nashville to make sure
this happens,'' says Steve Buchanan, president of the Grand Ole
Opry Group. ``To me, the Opry has always been evolutionary. When
you look at the Grand Ole Opry today, you have to do it in context
with its entire history. It's a vital institution that provides you
with an association with people like Hank Williams and Patsy Cline,
which is still a tremendous marketing value. From a cultural
standpoint, it's important. The Opry is still very much a part of
the Nashville experience.''
</P>
<P>
   Buchanan's job is to keep it that way. Many here are hoping this
newly appointed head of the show _ a 35-year-old Vanderbilt
graduate who is devoted to the Opry and understands its tradition _
will be the one to make sure the Opry survives into the 21st
century without becoming a museum piece under glass. For the past
five years, he has overseen the resurrection of the renovated Ryman
Auditorium, pumping new life into the old building by booking not
only bluegrass and gospel shows into the venue, but rock acts as
well. It's his idea to bring the Opry back to its roots with the
two special shows this weekend, giving hundreds of fans a chance to
see the Opry in the Ryman for the first time. Buchanan's main
challenge, however, is in courting younger artists while ensuring
that the history and contributions of the older acts aren't
forgotten.
</P>
<P>
   Rather than leading the industry, the Opry seems to have become
the place where stars return when the spotlight isn't quite as hot
anymore. ``Maybe I'm old-fashioned, but I think you need a home to
come to, and that's what the Opry has been to me and my
generation,'' Anderson says.
</P>
<P>
   Wagoner agrees. ``The Opry acts as a stabilizer for your career.
Garth won't be selling out 50,000-seat arenas 20 years from now.
You have to have something to fall back on.''
</P>
<P>
   Bob Whittaker, outgoing president of the Grand Ole Opry Group,
laughs when he says, ``A lot of people would like to read the
(Opry's) obituary right now. But, hey, I've got news for them. The
Opry has more lives than Bill Clinton. Nashville isn't going to let
anything happen to this.''
</P>
<P>
   _ The Grand Ole Opry at the Ryman Auditorium, Nashville, TN
</P>
<P>
   Friday, 7:30 p.m. Saturday, 6:30 and 9 p.m. $20. 615-889-3060.
</P>
<P>
   TNN will air an hour of the early Saturday show at 8 p.m.
</P>
<P>
   Miriam Longino writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
