<SLUG> BC-SIBLEY-COLUMN10-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    EMBARGOED UNTIL JANUARY 10
 &HT;    This landlubber flags interest in boats
 &HT;    By Celestine Sibley
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ There was some talk at my house about a group of us
females going to sales and, mayhap, finding me something new to
wear.
</P>
<P>
   In theory, I was all for it. But in actuality . . . well, I
pulled up a wool throw and scrooched down in the corner of the sofa
closest to the fireplace and picked up a book.
</P>
<P>
   The girls were mystified when they saw the title. But the males
in the family who lent it to me felt that at last I was showing
respect for the important things in life: boats. At least two of
them have boats, and the others either have had boating experience
or yearn for it. They understood completely why I would opt for an
afternoon with ``Chapman Piloting: Seamanship &AMP; Small Boat
Handling,'' a volume now in its 62nd edition.
</P>
<P>
   My interest in Chapman's hefty volume centered on the Coast
Guard and storm warning flags. I had asked around _ for dark
literary purposes of my own _ whatever happened to the storm
signals they used to fly from the top of the Van Antwerp Building
in Mobile, Ala.
</P>
<P>
   Cut them out six years ago, one of my boaters told me. With
radio and television, it is no longer necessary for Mobilians to
break their necks scanning the eminence of the 24-story skyscraper
for a warning flag. I protested. You can't have a hurricane without
the Coast Guard's blood red ensigns flying, two at a time, from the
Van Antwerp Building, I told them.
</P>
<P>
   In Creola, 18 miles from the coast and the warning flags, we
managed to keep track of approaching storms by telephoning family
in Mobile who could see the sky over the old drug-store-office
building. We started keeping track the day somebody told us the
small craft warning was up _ a blood red triangular shaped flag.
</P>
<P>
   After that they got more serious: Gale warnings were two red
pennants that told us winds ranging from 39 to 54 mph were on the
way. Even the youngest child knew that two square red flags with
black centers meant trouble _ a hurricane.
</P>
<P>
   Of course, I needed the Chapman book to tell me these important
facts, but once learned, the storm signals could be stowed away by
my computer until I got back from shopping for a new dress, my
daughters told me. What they reckoned without was the fascination
of this big book.
</P>
<P>
   Although I haven't a boat now, I look at them with longing when
we pass boatyards where they are stored or for sale. Lucky people,
I think, to have a boat of their own. Lucky people to slide one
overboard at the Carrabelle, Fla., marina and take off for the
little sand and pine-clad island across the blue waters of the
sound.
</P>
<P>
   When we had a boat, during my husband's lifetime, I could run it
while he fished, and once or twice I took it out on my own to cross
the sound to the grocery store. But I was aware that if I was alone
when the engine quit, I might drift out of the sound and into the
Gulf of Mexico.
</P>
<P>
   So I have bumbled along for 10 years hitching rides on te boats
of friends and relatives. But with Chapman's big book to guide me,
who knows but what I'd be a safe mariner? (You can also take
lessons from the Coast Guard.)
</P>
<P>
   It is more interesting by far than shopping for clothes. Now
signal flags . . . if I had a boat, I'd need all kinds of flags,
for they speak the language of the sea, telling random observers
important things about you and your craft. There is one picture of
a sailing ship ``dressed,'' which means it is flag strung from
stern to bow and so beautiful.
</P>
<P>
   Needless to say, I missed the glorious holiday sales. I was deep
in the chapter headed ``Boat Handling Under Adverse Conditions.'' A
different kind of sail _ and totally interesting to a landlubber
wrapped up in a wool throw and scrooched down by a fire.
</P>
<P>
   Celestine Sibley writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
