<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    EMBARGOED UNTIL JANUARY 10
 &HT;    It's an endless New Age party at Disney's Cirque du Soleil site
 &HT;    By Paula Crouch Thrasher
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   Cirque du Soleil has folded its big blue tents in Atlanta and
taken the show ``Quidam'' back on the road. But at the new Cirque
du Soleil theater at Downtown Disney West Side in Walt Disney
World, the show never ends.
</P>
<P>
   The 1,671-seat theater will be home to twice-daily productions
of ``La Nouba'' five days a week. The theater, which features a
store with more than 300 souvenirs and products, is adjacent to
House of Blues and DisneyQuest.
</P>
<P>
   ``La Nouba'' _ a 90-minute tapestry of original music,
extraordinary costumes, surreal sets, theatrical lighting and
high-energy choreography _ is one of a dozen shows produced on four
continents by the Quebec-based Cirque since 1994. The name comes
from the French expression ``faire la Nouba,'' which means ``to
party, to live it up.''
</P>
<P>
   Shows are 5:30 and 8:30 p.m. Wednesdays-Saturdays; 2:30 and 5:30
p.m. Sundays. Tickets are $56.50 ($44.20 ages 3-9); available at
the box office or by calling 407-939-7600.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Isle and Nile: Wild Dunes Resort's Town and Country Package,
available through June 12, combines a world-class exhibit on
ancient Egypt in historic Charleston with a laid-back vacation on a
lush barrier island off South Carolina.
</P>
<P>
   The exhibit at the Charleston Museum is ``Queens and Commoners
of Egypt's New Kingdom'' from the British Museum. The package
includes exhibit admission and two nights at the four-diamond
Boardwalk Inn, full breakfast and recreational amenities. Rates are
$89-$119 per person per night. Reservations: 1-800-845-8880.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Getting mushy: Minneapolis-based Wilderness Inquiry is
offering four-day Northwoods Dogsled Adventures, which take
travelers through the backwoods of Superior National Forest.
Participants begin with a daylong crash course in dog sledding,
then embark on a series of fast-paced runs through the trail
system. Heated wall tents (yurts) provide comfy lodging at night.
Trips are Feb. 12-15 and March 4-7; cost is $745. Information:
1-800-728-0719.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Walking to London: Lord Winston's Walking Tours offers a
two-week walk beside the River Thames from the source to Richmond
via Oxford, Henley, Clivedon, Eton, Windsor and Hampton Court. As
you amble along, your baggage will be transported to the hotel or
inn where you'll stay overnight. Lunches are in historic riverside
pubs. (They'll even give you a lift if you desire a nonwalking
day.) A program of events and visits demonstrates the influence of
the river on England's history. The tour, Aug. 11-23, begins and
ends in London. Price, including all lodging, meals,
transportation, visits and events, is $2,800. Information:
011-44-1297-625512, or write Lord Winston's Walking Tours, Beer,
Devon, EX12 3AE, England.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Courier opportunities: There will be more cheap international
courier flights from the United States than ever before, says
William C. Bates, president of the International Association of Air
Travel Couriers (IAATC).
</P>
<P>
   The number of scheduled courier flights from U.S. cities will
top a record 40,000 this year, according to the IAATC's Air Courier
Bulletin, which tracks courier flights worldwide.
</P>
<P>
   What this means is that those interested in giving up their
luggage space to courier firms in exchange for a discounted air
ticket will have more opportunities. Typically, a courier will
carry shipping documents to be turned over to the courier company's
agents when the aircraft lands.
</P>
<P>
   What kind of deals are out there? How about $150 to $300 to
Europe and even Asia? You have to be flexible; you travel on the
courier's timetable, but you can expect to stay from three days to
several weeks.
</P>
<P>
   For more information, call 561-582-8320 or visit the Web site at
http://www.courier.org.
</P>
<P>
   Paula Crouch Thrasher writes for the Atlanta
Journal-Constitution.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
