<HEADER>
A5112 &Cx1f; tad-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-MUSICAL-BLOCKBUSTERS1     01-08 0720
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MUSICAL-BLOCKBUSTERS10-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    EMBARGOED UNTIL JANUARY 10
 &HT;    Music to your ears or not, some shows just work
 &HT;    By Dan Hulbert
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ The era of big British blockbusters may have peaked
with ``Miss Saigon'' on Broadway in 1991, but out here on the road
there's a powerful echo effect. We go and listen to these
BritBlocks again and again and. . . .
</P>
<P>
   ``Cats'' already has been to Atlanta 12 times, playing to
approximately 400,000 people. Its visit this week to the Fox
Theatre gives us the dubious honor of having hosted the national
tour more than any other city. The old war horse (war kitty?) will
be followed at the Fox by ``Les Miserables'' and ``Evita'' _ while
``Miss Saigon'' lands at the Atlanta Civic Center for its second
local run _ over the next eight weeks.
</P>
<P>
   Conventional wisdom says that these shows are a triumph of sets
over substance; there is some truth to that, but then the splendid
``Les Miz'' would work on a bare stage. Yes, these shows are
arguably grandiose, but one person's bombast is another's thrill.
One also hears that composers Andrew Lloyd Webber and Claude-Michel
Schonberg and their various lyricists are lightweights (again,
partly true), but the box office doesn't lie. It proclaims that
these fellows are veritable RodgersandHammersteins compared to the
milky American musical-theater writers who followed them in the
'90s.
</P>
<P>
   What explains the catniplike frenzy inspired by these shows? Why
are many critics still not sold on them? We've sketched out some
theories at right.
</P>
<P>
   `Cats'
</P>
<P>
   (Tuesday-Jan. 17, Theater of the Stars, Fox Theatre.
404-817-8700.)
</P>
<P>
   Why millions love it:
</P>
<P>
   Dazzling feline costuming/makeup and a giant, cat's-eye-view
junkyard create a fully theatrical illusion. Plus, those critters
have claimed human laps and hearts at least since ancient Egypt.
</P>
<P>
   Why some don't:
</P>
<P>
   Some strung-together poems _ even by the great T.S. Eliot _ do
not a story make. Sure, kitties dance and sing, but what happens?
</P>
<P>
   Secret to its staying power :
</P>
<P>
   From its 1982 opening until 1994, the show had no Disney stage
competition and cornered the family market. There's more good
melody to Andrew Lloyd Webber's score than the tiresomely ranted
``Memory.''
</P>
<P>
   `Les Miserables'
</P>
<P>
   (Jan. 19-24, Theater of the Stars/MasterCard Broadway Series,
Fox. 404-817-8700.)
</P>
<P>
   Why millions love it:
</P>
<P>
   The Victor Hugo saga of revolutionary France is bracingly
sweeping, the Claude-Michel Schonberg/Alain
</P>
<P>
   Boublil score a veritable melodic tapestry.
</P>
<P>
   Why some don't:
</P>
<P>
   Laughs are scarcer than showers in old Paris hotels. Tons of
plot fly past you in the lyrics: As comedian Richard Lewis said
despairingly, ``What are those people saying?''
</P>
<P>
   Secret to its staying power:
</P>
<P>
   Heroes and heroines you can really root for. For all of its
old-fashioned sentimentality, the 1987 show has a spiritual core
that never goes out of style.
</P>
<P>
   `Evita'
</P>
<P>
   (Feb. 9-14, MasterCard Series, Fox. 404-817-8700.)
</P>
<P>
   Why millions love it:
</P>
<P>
   Two words: Sex and power, driving the saga of Argentine cult
figure Eva Peron. This 1978 show foresaw the retro-'40s look. New
tour showcases Latin-born performers.
</P>
<P>
   Why some don't:
</P>
<P>
   The dark ironies of Hal Prince's direction may smack too much of
`` '70s seriousness'' for our apolitical, escapist age.
</P>
<P>
   Secret to its staying power:
</P>
<P>
   Lloyd Webber's music, and the enduring puzzle: Was Evita a saint
of the people or the devil in a white dress?
</P>
<P>
   `Miss Saigon'
</P>
<P>
   (Feb. 18-Mar. 6, MasterCard Series, Atlanta Civic Center.
404-817-8700).
</P>
<P>
   Why millions love it:
</P>
<P>
   Sure the helicopter's neat, but it's mere window dressing on a
1991 Nicholas Hytner production of tremendous, cinematic sweep.
Schonberg/Boublil score is sub-``Miz'' but still good.
</P>
<P>
   Why some don't:
</P>
<P>
   It's billed as ``Madame Butterfly'' updated to 1970s Vietnam,
but it's really ``Gone With the Wind'' with GIs and strippers. Pass
the hanky.
</P>
<P>
   Secret to its staying power:
</P>
<P>
   Same reason that some don't like it:
</P>
<P>
   Nothing beats love in wartime for pulling in the soap-opera
crowd, as Margaret Mitchell knew so well.
</P>
<P>
   Dan Hulbert writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
