<DATE_TIME> 1999-01-08 16:51 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5127 &Cx1f; taf-z
s l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-WANNABE-CELEBRITIES-$     01-08 1164
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-WANNABE-CELEBRITIES-$ADV10-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THE AD WORLD RECOGNIZES A GOOD THING: OBSCURITY 
</HEADLINE>
  (For release Sun., Jan. 10) 
(JT) 
 By STUART ELLIOTT   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Forget Michael Jordan, Cindy Crawford, Bill Cosby and the other
superstars and supermodels. Here comes a phalanx of the prefamous:
gonnabes, wannabes and whozzats peddling products in commercials,
ads and billboards as if they were instantly recognizable.
</P>
<P>
   Some are totally unknown. Others are second- or third-tier
stars. Still others are familiar only in narrowly focused fields.
For instance, here's Rufus Wainwright selling eyeglasses and
apparel. There's Alyson Hannigan and Derrick May hawking backpacks.
And look, Bryden Lando and Miguel Oca are pitching cologne.
</P>
<P>
   Who? What? Wainwright is a singer, Ms. Hannigan is an actress,
May is a musician, Lando is a surfer, Oca plays water polo.
</P>
<P>
   Madison Avenue is enthusiastically climbing down the food chain
of celebrity because the public is wearying of big names growing
richer with deal after big endorsement deal. Advertisers are
learning that the best way to cultivate a cutting-edge image may be
to sign up spokesmodels who may be known only to an in crowd.
</P>
<P>
   ``It confers on an advertiser a presumption of hipness that it
has been able to get people so cool you never heard of them,'' said
Bob Garfield, the advertising critic for the trade publication
Advertising Age.
</P>
<P>
   In other words, you don't know this guy (or gal). But you
suspect you ought to.
</P>
<P>
   The quasi celebrity first gained favor in the 1980s, when brands
like Gap, Amaretto di Saronno, Absolut, Barneys New York, L.A.
Eyeworks and Rose's Lime Juice had ads with artists (Andy Warhol,
Ed Ruscha), actors (Julian Sands, B.D. Wong), actresses (Laura
Dern, Joan Chen), performers (Sandra Bernhard, Phoebe Legere) and
writers (Tama Janowitz, Tony Kushner).
</P>
<P>
   ``It's about the discovery of the corners of our culture,'' said
Gai Gherardi, who with Barbara McReynolds is a co-owner of the L.A.
Eyeworks eyeglasses company in Los Angeles, which has run more than
160 advertisement displaying portrait photographs of lesser knowns.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're in the glorious position of being in a town with a lot
of people working toward their 15 minutes of fame,'' Ms. Gherardi
said. Her subjects have ranged from Debi Mazar, an actress, and
Phranc, a singer, to the actor Udo Kier and the Elvis Presley
impersonator known as El Vez.
</P>
<P>
   The trend favoring proto-, crypto- and neo-celebrities waned in
the early 1990s, in part because of the rise of the supermodel as
the premier peddler. But as Cindy, Naomi and Linda were declining
to mere mortal status, the prefamous were returning with renewed
strength.
</P>
<P>
   Advertisers say that consumers rarely, if ever, complain about
being puzzled or put off by studying an ad to determine who's
Justin Bond (a drag performer), Michelle Yeoh (a kung-fu star) or
Bokeem Woodbine (an actor). Rather, they may be intrigued or
impressed that the advertisers rank among the cognoscenti.
</P>
<P>
   That's the response reported by Rockport shoes for a campaign
from the Kirshenbaum Bond &AMP; Partners ad agency, which features such
semi-celebrities as Clint Rosemund, a Web site builder; James
Cramer, a financial journalist; Spalding Gray, the monologist, and
the performers RuPaul and John Leguizamo.
</P>
<P>
   ``The reaction was, `It's cool Rockport knows who that is,'''
said Linda Lewi, senior vice president for global brand marketing
at the Rockport Company in Marlborough, Mass. ``It's about
generating heat and buzz.''
</P>
<P>
   Jansport, the backpack marketer, describes a similar response to
its roster of demi-celebrities (not to be confused with Demi Moore,
a celebrity).
</P>
<P>
   ``There's a coolness to being the one who knows the person,''
said Jackie Kempher-Jones, advertising manager for Jansport in
Appleton, Wis. ``And we need to push that we're a cool, innovative
company.''
</P>
<P>
   Jansport's not-quite-stars include Ms. Hannigan, who appears on
the television series ``Buffy the Vampire Slayer'' as Buffy's
friend Willow; May, who helped popularize the music known as
techno; Boyd Tinsley, violinist for the Dave Matthews Band, and the
Olympic athletes Jonny Moseley and Jenny Thompson. The only really
recognizable face belongs to the actress Jennifer Love Hewitt, who
appears on the television series ``Party of Five.''
</P>
<P>
   Those niche celebrities, as Ms. Kempher-Jones calls them, help
Jansport reach consumers ages 14 to 22. On the other end of the
demographic spectrum, Anne Klein sponsored an advertising insert
this fall that served as a showcase for niche celebrities who would
appeal to the brand's intended audience of women ages 35 to 60.
They included Ms. Thompson; Ms. Yeoh; Ann Richards, the former
governor of Texas; the playwright and performer Anna Deavere Smith;
Julie Taymor, the director of the musical ``The Lion King''; the
actress Joan Allen, and Wendy Goodman, a style editor.
</P>
<P>
   ``They're women who have accomplished something or who are on
track to,'' said Laura Wenke, senior vice president for marketing
and communications at Anne Klein and Co. ``The legends and the
future legends.''
</P>
<P>
   The response was so positive, Ms. Wenke said, that for spring
1999 there will be a second insert with a new cast of
personalities, including the photojournalist Mary Ellen Mark; the
makeup entrepreneur Trish McEvoy; the dancer Anne Reinking, and
Caroline Paul, a San Francisco firefighter.
</P>
<P>
   The goal for the campaign, which Ms. Wenke described as
``reality-based marketing,'' is to find women to whom the Anne
Klein customer ``can relate.''
</P>
<P>
   That points out another reason for the rash of marginal
celebrities: a shift in the culture that plays down the big stars
perceived by consumers as unreachable, in favor of those who appear
more accessible.
</P>
<P>
   ``The less famous, you can more identify with,'' said Bill Lane,
partner and creative director at the McCaffery Ratner Gottlieb &AMP;
Lane ad agency. For the Punch cigar brand sold by Villazon and Co.,
McCaffery Ratner is running a campaign featuring the actor Dennis
Hopper, the author George Plimpton and Wayne Knight, who portrayed
the reviled Newman on ``Seinfeld.''
</P>
<P>
   ``The guy smoking our cigars wouldn't feel uncomfortable
striking up a conversation with Dennis Hopper or Newman,'' Lane
asserted. ``But he would feel uncomfortable if it were Paul
Newman.''
</P>
<P>
   A campaign for a new men's fragrance from Chanel, Allure Homme,
is based on a similar premise. The ads show interesting-looking men
identified only by their professions and pursuits like hockey
player, film maker, jazz musician, surfer/student (Lando) and
Olympic gold medalist (Oca).
</P>
<P>
   Marketers like Chanel that are edging toward the edgy face
rather than the celebrated one say they perceive a consumer
backlash against traditional advertising practices like lucrative
endorsement contracts and models as role models.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   In focus groups, said Laurie Palma, vice president for fragrance
marketing at Chanel Inc., men shown the Allure Homme ads described
the less famous personalities as not only more relatable but also
more believable.
</P>
<P>
   Recounting a typical comment from the men who were interviewed,
she said: `` `They're not just pretty boys paid a lot of money.'
When we were testing a variety of concepts, we asked them about
Michael Jordan, Paul Newman, and they said, `You can pay anyone a
lot of money and they will endorse anything.'''
</P>
<P>
   Garfield, the ad critic, said: ``When a celebrity is involved,
people can now see the transaction. We see the agent and lawyer and
the check being cut.''
</P>
<P>
   A campaign for Coach leather goods featured, in addition to Ms.
Yu and Ms. Kent, the writers John Irving and Gloria Steinem;
Felecia Davis, an architect; the gallery owner Holly Solomon; the
singer Cassandra Wilson, and Milla Jovovitch and Lara Flynn Boyle,
actresses.
</P>
<P>
   ``For a classic American brand like Coach,'' said Reed Krakoff,
the company's senior vice president and executive creative
director, it would be ``out of character for us to hire a very
famous person because that's not how people perceive us. I don't
think it rings true.''
</P>
<P>
   And speaking of ringing, an added benefit to hiring the hardly
famous is that the cash register rings a lot more softly when it
comes to paying them. ``To use someone extraordinarily famous can
be extraordinarily expensive,'' Krakoff said.
</P>
<P>
   The mildly celebrated usually are paid four or five figures for
their participation in campaigns compared with the six or seven
figures that can usually be commanded by the bigger stars in the
Hollywood and sports firmaments.
</P>
<P>
   Some advertisers say they plan to fine-tune their mix and become
more celebrified for 1999.
</P>
<P>
   ``Some of our names will be more mainstream,'' said Ms. Wenke at
Anne Klein, referring to the appearances of the actresses Kim
Delaney (``N.Y.P.D. Blue'') and Camryn Manheim (``The Practice'')
in the spring ad insert.
</P>
<P>
   Others, however, intend to go the other way.
</P>
<P>
   ``This next year, we'll be concentrating more on third-tier
instead of second-tier celebrities,'' said Ms. Kempher-Jones at
Jansport.
</P>
<P>
   Why? One of the Jansport unknowns has lost her ``un'': Ms.
Hewitt, who leapt from ``Party of Five'' to films like ``I Know
What You Did Last Summer.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Now she's almost overexposed,'' Ms. Kempher-Jones said
plaintively.
</P>
<P>
   If they get too hot, they'll be out of work.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
