<HEADER>
A5134 &Cx1f; taf-z
s l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-REDMAN-SHOPPING-$ADV1     01-08 1219
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-REDMAN-SHOPPING-$ADV10-ART-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A JAZZ VIRTUOSO IS PICKY ABOUT THE DETAILS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For release Sunday, Jan. 10)  
(ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchase by calling (888) 603-1036 or (888)
346-9867.) 
(lb) 
 By ERIC ASIMOV   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ As Joshua Redman would be the first to tell you, he
is a picky kind of fellow.
</P>
<P>
   Redman, the jazz saxophonist and band leader, was poring over
shirts at the Prada store on Madison Avenue last Wednesday, looking
for stagewear for his coming two-week tour of Japan.
</P>
<P>
   As his personal shopper at Prada, Ola Itani, brought in several
dozen selections, each individually boxed with a clear plastic top,
he zoomed in on defect after defect. The color was wrong on one,
the collar too long on another, the shape on a third was too boxy
and a single button on a fourth interrupted an otherwise clean line
of Velcro closures.
</P>
<P>
   ``I might see something appealing, but if there's one thing
about it I don't like, I reject it,'' Redman said. ``I'm really,
really picky.''
</P>
<P>
   Redman can afford to be exacting. He graduated summa cum laude
from Harvard in 1991 with the intention of becoming a lawyer, but
instead began a musical career that quickly turned luminous. He won
the Thelonious Monk Institute's prestigious jazz saxophone
competition in 1991, and since then has released six CDs.
</P>
<P>
   He has been on the cover of Down Beat, the jazz magazine, and is
one of the rare musicians who have both critical acclaim and
crossover appeal. He has played with old masters like Milt Jackson,
blown the saxophone with Bill Clinton on the White House lawn and
performed with the Rolling Stones.
</P>
<P>
   Yet as attuned as he is to the demands of his own taste, he says
he is uneasy with the privileges of celebrity.
</P>
<P>
   ``If my mother knew I had a personal shopper ...,'' he said,
trailing off. ``It's just a bizarre concept. I prefer to think of
Ola as my friend who gives me great style advice.''
</P>
<P>
   Redman is used to being of two worlds. He grew up in poverty in
Berkeley, Calif., with his mother, Renee Shedroff. His father,
Dewey Redman, the saxophonist who is best known for his work with
jazz greats like Ornette Coleman, Charlie Haden and Keith Jarrett,
lived in New York.
</P>
<P>
   Redman excelled academically, won a full scholarship to Harvard,
was accepted at Yale Law School and along the way exchanged the
surname Shedroff for Redman.
</P>
<P>
   He has been a jazz phenom for most of the '90s. Redman is now
29, nearing 30; he is married, to Gabrielle Armand, and has a
suburban home in the Westchester County community of Sleepy Hollow.
He is closing in on full-scale adulthood, and that, of course, can
change the way anybody dresses.
</P>
<P>
   ``I stopped wearing ties for a long time, but I started again
about six months ago after discovering Prada,'' he said. ``I felt
like I was a banker. Maybe it was my age, but for a while I felt
that anything that had the trappings of business I didn't feel
right about, as a musician.''
</P>
<P>
   But Redman hasn't completely gone over to designer wear. When
he's not working, he's most likely to wear a pair of jeans and
sneakers. And he decided to begin the day's shopping expedition at
a Gap outlet across the street from Bloomingdale's, where he hoped
to pick up some staple black T-shirts. He arrived in a black
cashmere Prada turtleneck, black DKNY slacks and zip-up black boots
from Kenneth Cole. Immediately the picky fellow emerged.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's hard to find a good T-shirt,'' he remarked as he went
over the display of choices: ribbed, crew neck, V-neck and single
pocket. ``I mean, you'd think a T-shirt is a T-shirt, but it's
not.''
</P>
<P>
   He was drawn to a lighter-bodied shirt, and he rubbed the
material between thumb and forefinger. ``It has a tiny bit of
sheen,'' he said. ``I could get away with wearing that on stage,
with a nice shirt or coat.'' A saleswoman informed him that unlike
the outerwear T-shirts, the shirt he's holding is underwear.
</P>
<P>
   ``I wish you hadn't told me that,'' he exclaimed. ``That's like
finding a great shirt and being told it's a woman's.''
</P>
<P>
   In the end, Redman bought the shirts anyway, seven of them, in
black and gray. And then, like stepping out of the subway and into
a limo, it was off to Prada, a sedate sea of rich fabrics in black
and gray with the occasional subdued color poking through.
</P>
<P>
   He began browsing through the bright, airy third-floor men's
department before Ms. Itani ushered him to a private room. He was
looking for ``not quite a suit _ a nice pair of pants, a coat and a
shirt with color.''
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Itani, who has been assisting Redman at Prada for the last
six months, brought bottles of San Pellegrino and ice, and began to
make suggestions. She knows that as a musician Redman has practical
considerations for his wardrobe. It must withstand the rigors of
the road, the constant packing and unpacking, and the demands of a
vigorous stage show.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Itani offered a pair of lightweight pale green pants made of
something she called cotton-paper. ``They crackle,'' she said,
rubbing them back and forth. Redman looked doubtful.
</P>
<P>
   ``After a few songs, those are going to look really funky,'' he
said, ``and I don't mean good funky.''
</P>
<P>
   The color, too, was a problem. ``I don't usually wear things
that light,'' he said. He was concerned that a beige shirt might be
too much of a contrast with black pants. Pale gray? No. Light
green? No. Mustard yellow? Forget it.
</P>
<P>
   Finally, he selected a couple of shiny nylon short-sleeve shirts
_ in black and gray, of course _ and a pair of black slacks made of
a techno-stretch material. ``I love this fabric,'' Redman said.
``That texture and that slight sheen make it special, and it
virtually irons itself.''
</P>
<P>
   Still, Redman would not be fully satisfied with his selections
before a visit with a tailor for alterations. Redman is very
particular about fit. ``I've got a real neurosis about things being
too short,'' he said. ``I was teased in the ninth grade about
wearing flooders.''
</P>
<P>
   A tailor arrived, but Redman, almost abashed, let it be known
that he would be happier with another man, Mostafa Mrabet, who had
altered his clothes satisfactorily before. ``I feel slightly
uncomfortable having all this attention,'' he said, ``but if you're
going to have a personal shopper, you may as well make the most of
it.''
</P>
<P>
   Later, over a meal at the Paramount Hotel, near a shop that is
repairing his saxophone, Redman reflected on the intimate
connection of clothing and jazz, a culture that places a premium on
having a strong, identifiable personal style.
</P>
<P>
   The stylistic signatures leap out _ Lester Young's porkpie hat,
Dizzy Gillespie's beret and hipster pants, Miles Davis' sharp suits
of the 1950s, Wynton Marsalis' return to formality in the 1980s.
But Redman pointed out that those musicians also had distinctive
approaches to language and all elements of style.
</P>
<P>
   Clothing, he said, is the least important. Look at Charlie
Parker, after all, the bebop genius who could barely be bothered to
uncrumple a collar or straighten a tie.
</P>
<P>
   ``When you've got such an amazingly original style musically,
what else matters?'' he said.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE _ OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   Despite his success, Redman is still searching for his own voice
on the saxophone, a quest that he feels will be lifelong. Likewise,
he is still refining his own clothing style, seeking personal
expression but avoiding anything that hints of affectation, like
that hoary jazz cliche, sunglasses after dark. ``I'd feel like an
idiot,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm attracted to a look that's a combination of hot and cool,
that's casual and elegant at the same time, something that's
subdued and understated but also intense,'' he said. ``That's one
of the key elements of the way I approach jazz, this feeling of
relaxed intensity, and in a certain sense that's what I'm looking
for in terms of the way I dress.''
</P>
<P>
   Not surprisingly for a man who places such conflicting demands
on his music and his clothing, his absolute favorite piece of
apparel is something almost no one gets a chance to see: his black
Calvin Klein button-fly knit boxer shorts. ``They're totally
comfortable. What I should have done today is bought 20 more pairs.
I've got like three pairs, and that's 17 too few.''
</P>
<P>
   He said that he has always wanted to wear a really stylish pair
of eyeglasses, but that his eyesight is too good and he can't
justify wearing nonprescription glasses just for the look. But he
accepts his cautious nature.
</P>
<P>
   ``The benefit of being picky,'' he said, ``is that I never have
any regrets.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
