<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-AUTO-REVIEW-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HONDA'S CIVIC DUTY IS CLEAN AIR 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By BOB GOLFEN  
 c.1999 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   PHOENIX - The most remarkable thing about the Honda Civic GX,
powered by compressed natural gas (CNG), is that it's so
unremarkable.
</P>
<P>
   The driveability of the natural-gas Civic feels nearly identical
to a run-of-the-mill, gasoline-powered Civic. Maybe a bit light on
torque at low engine speeds, but otherwise a normal Honda
experience.
</P>
<P>
   The big exception is that the CNG Civic produces 20 percent less
greenhouse gas emissions than an equivalent gasoline vehicle, and
emits nearly zero hydrocarbons. The flip side is that cruising
range is limited to about 200 miles per tank of CNG, and CNG can be
hard to come by.
</P>
<P>
   Powered by Honda's advanced VTEC engine, engineered to deliver a
wide range of power by varying its valve timing and lift according
to engine speed, the small four-cylinder engine in the GX actually
has a tad more muscle than the normal 1.6-liter engine: 110
horsepower in the case of the CNG engine, 106 for the gasoline
engine.
</P>
<P>
   This is not readily apparent on the road, especially saddled
with an automatic transmission, as it is in all GXs. Cruising
speeds are relaxed and comfortable, though acceleration is lax.
</P>
<P>
   The test car, borrowed for an afternoon from Showcase Honda,
came fully equipped with all the trim, comfort and convenience
upgrades, including air-conditioning, stereo system and power
windows, locks, mirrors and seats.
</P>
<P>
   The CNG package adds $4,500 to the price, but the extra cost is
largely offset by state and federal grants and breaks on taxes and
licenses.
</P>
<P>
   The Civic GX looks pretty much like any other Civic. The only
external clue is under the fuel flap, where instead of the usual
opening for the gas nozzle, there's a fitting for attaching a
pressure hose.
</P>
<P>
   The natural gas is contained in a large pressurized tank, sort
of a bulbous version of the familiar oxygen tank, or a helium tank
for filling party balloons. The tank takes up most of the trunk
space, leaving some snug space for grocery bags, but that's about
it.
</P>
<P>
   By its nature, the amount of CNG needed to be equivalent to a
10- or 12-gallon tank of gasoline requires a fairly large
container, about 4 feet wide and 1 foot across. Otherwise, the
cruising range would be even more limited.
</P>
<P>
   As it is, Honda says its CNG Civic gets a ``real-world'' range
of 175 to 200 miles per tankful, or the equivalent of 28 miles per
gallon city, and 34 miles per gallon highway. That gas mileage is
testimony to Honda's well-designed engine: Natural gas has a lower
volatility than gasoline, so getting equivalent gas mileage is
something of an engineering feat.
</P>
<P>
   Natural gas generally costs about two-thirds the price of a like
amount of gasoline. It's also plentiful, and not tied to overseas
suppliers.
</P>
<P>
   Another plus: Natural gas is easier on the mechanical parts of
an engine than gasoline. There's no liquid being squirted into the
engine, no carbon deposits, and no dilution of the motor oil with
unburned gas.
</P>
<P>
   The GX test car was classified as an Inherently Low Emission
Vehicle, or ILEV. There's also a GX model that meets California's
Ultra Low Emission Vehicle (ULEV) standard. The ILEV category is
the more stringent of the two. Honda also has a gasoline-powered
Accord that meets the ULEV standard.
</P>
<P>
   Although there are essentially no compromises required for
driving the GX, aside from the reduced trunk space, getting fueled
up is another issue. At Showcase Honda, fleet sales director Gary
Kravetz said the GX, the only one currently on their lot,
customarily is taken to be fueled up to a fuel-delivery point near
Sky Harbor International Airport, a significant distance from the
dealership in the 1400 block of East Camelback Road.
</P>
<P>
   And that's the big issue with a natural-gas car _ fuel
accessibility.
</P>
<P>
   Around Phoenix, it's not as challenging, because there are
locations in the downtown area. Also, people can get a state grant
to install a natural-gas delivery system in their homes, feeding
off the supply coming in for such things as the home-heating system
or water heater.
</P>
<P>
   A CNG car is largely tied to the urban area. With the maximum
200-mile cruising range, the GX or a similar natural-gas vehicle
would be unable to travel anywhere too far from a known supply of
natural gas. If you run out of gas in an isolated location in one
of these cars, you're (begin ital) really (end ital) out of gas.
</P>
<P>
   So despite its economic and clean-air advantages, the
natural-gas car faces a chicken-and-egg battle for acceptance.
People won't buy natural-gas cars until there are convenient places
to refuel them, but no infrastructure for refueling is likely until
there are more CNG cars on the road. &QL; 
 &QL; 
Honda Civic GX &QL; 
(natural gas)Vehicle type: Five-passenger, four-door sedan,
front-wheel drive. &QL; 
Price as tested: $20,445 (approx). &QL; 
Engine: 1.6-liter in-line 4-cylinder, 110 horsepower at 6,500 rpm,
96.2 foot-pounds of torque at 5,500 rpm. &QL; 
Transmission: Four-speed automatic. &QL; 
Curb weight: 2,599 pounds. &QL; 
Wheelbase: 103.2 inches. &QL; 
EPA fuel economy: 28 mpg city, 34 highway &QL; 
(gasoline equivalent). &QL; 
Highs: Clean air. Tax breaks. Good driveability.Lows: Finding fuel.
No trunk space. Limited range. &QL; 
 &QL; 
Bob Golfen can be reached at bob.golfen(at)pni.com via e-mail. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
