<SLUG> BC-MUSSOLINI-BOAT-ART-$ADV10-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TEXANS TO TURN FORMER MUSSOLINI YACHT INTO FLOATING INN 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  (Photos available on NYT database) 
(Attn: Florida) 
 
(Moved in ``a'' and ``i'' categories) 
 
By KEVIN MORAN 
c.1998 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   GALVESTON, Texas _ In a former life it was owned by the infamous
Fascist Italian dictator Benito Mussolini during World War II.
</P>
<P>
   In another incarnation it had a role in the 1968 children's
movie ``Chitty Chitty Bang Bang'' and several other feature films.
</P>
<P>
   Now the 120-foot yacht formerly called the ``Chryseis'' is being
prepared for yet another role: that of a floating bed-and-breakfast
inn on the waterfront of this island resort city about 50 miles
southeast of downtown Houston.
</P>
<P>
   Tied up at Pier 22, the two-masted schooner is undergoing an
extensive renovation as its latest owners prepare to open it in
early March. It has been renamed the ``Stacia Leigh'' after the
daughter of Pat and Bonnie Hicks, who are among the investors in
the bed-and-breakfast project.
</P>
<P>
   Docked just an oar's throw from the restored 1877 tall ship
Elissa, the inn will offer unusual close-up views of huge cargo
ships and the activities of a major seaport as well as close
proximity to shopping, entertainment and annual events such as
Mardi Gras in the city's downtown historic district, just a block
away.
</P>
<P>
   The bed-and-breakfast will be the latest attraction along the
stretch of waterfront from Pier 19 through Pier 22 that includes an
offshore oil industry museum, a picturesque shrimp boat fleet,
seafood restaurants, shops, a theater that features local history
documentaries and the 42-room Harbor House Hotel, the only other
inn on the busy Galveston Ship Channel.
</P>
<P>
   Dubbed the ``Chryseis'' after it was built in Le Havre, France,
in 1906, the schooner was owned until 1937 by Louis Renault, the
designer and builder of Renault automobiles. He sold the yacht to
Count Galeazzo Ciano of Livorno, Italy, who married Mussolini's
daughter, Edda.
</P>
<P>
   Ciano was Minister of Foreign Affairs from 1936 until 1943. A
philosophical split resulted in Mussolini branding him a traitor
and ordering him killed. Edda Ciano lived until 1995.
</P>
<P>
   ``Mussolini and his mistress took over the boat in 1944 and had
it about a year before Italian rebels caught up with him and killed
him in 1945,'' said Pat Hicks.
</P>
<P>
   Not much is yet known of the vessel's history between the war's
end and just a few years ago, when it ended up in Florida, said
Hicks, 52, a Beaumont, Texas, native and retired Austin excavation
firm owner.
</P>
<P>
   ``We do know it appeared in four movies and a couple of
documentaries,'' he said. ``The most well-known movie is ``Chitty
Chitty Bang Bang'' and the others are ``Seven Cities of Atlantis,''
``The Count of Monte Christo'' with Richard Chamberlain and Tony
Curtis, and also a movie called ``S.S. Commodore.''
</P>
<P>
   ``We found the boat over in Ponce Inlet in Florida back in March
of last year and were able to acquire it,'' Hicks said. ``It took
31 days to motor it back to Orange (Texas), where we put it in dry
dock.''
</P>
<P>
   Lack of care in its past few years in the Daytona Beach area in
Florida did more damage than more than 80 years in active use,
Hicks said. It left the decks and the original wheelhouse in
terrible shape, as was the cabin in which Mussolini slept, he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``But the hull, which is all riveted iron, was in really good
shape after 92 years,'' Hicks said. ``The masts are the originals,
too. We took all the decks off and completely rebuilt them.''
</P>
<P>
   Visitors will see the original windlass, which raised the
anchor, as well as the binnacle (compass stand) and ship's wheel, a
desk Mussolini is believed to have used and other original
fittings, Hicks said.
</P>
<P>
   Windows and red oak exterior panels of the cabins, dining and
salon areas are designed identically to those of the original
wheelhouse, he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's going to have 12 suites with queen-size or king-size beds
and separate bathrooms with Jacuzzi tubs,'' Hicks said. ``On the
dock, we'll have a hot tub and sauna and you can even get a massage
by appointment.''
</P>
<P>
   To prevent unpleasant odors, the boat's diesel engines have been
removed and its bilge and interior hull completely cleaned, he
said.
</P>
<P>
   Besides old photos of the boat, Hicks has other related
historical material.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've got a 1939 Life magazine with Mussolini on the cover and
it's got pictures inside of Ciano with Hitler,'' he said. ``We're
going to make a wall-hanging for each suite from that magazine.
Each suite will be named after a World War II figure like
Mussolini, Patton, Rommel, Churchill and others. We'll have a
scrapbook that people can look at, as well.''
</P>
<P>
   Room rates will run around $150 and people already have booked
rooms for the first months of operation, Hicks said. Breakfast, of
course, is included, and room service will be available throughout
the day from the neighboring Fisherman's Wharf restaurant.
</P>
<P>
   While the floating inn could be moved if Galveston's tourist
economy crashed, Hicks said he believes the ``Stacia Leigh'' will
be a permanent fixture on Galveston's waterfront.
</P>
<P>
   He said he and his wife also envision weddings, parties and
small business functions on the vessel's covered dock area, main
deck and topside 80-foot sundeck. For more information, call
409-750-8858.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
