<DATE_TIME> 1999-01-08 17:21 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5207 &Cx1f; ttj-z
r e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-TV-WB-KELLNER-HNS &LR;      01-08 0875
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TV-WB-KELLNER-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
UP HEAD DOESN'T WANT TO BE NO. 1, JUST NO. 1 WITH KIDS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By TIM GOODMAN  
 c.1999 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   PASADENA, Calif. _ The man running The WB, at this moment the
only network to show any viewership gains and, more importantly,
the one to watch, has no problem owning up to his life.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm an old man but I hang out with all these young kids all
the time,'' says Jamie Kellner, the CEO of The WB, who claims to be
``over 50'' but probably isn't by more than a year. Either way,
he's Abner Doubleday compared to the youth market he serves, as The
WB is the youngest-skewing of all the networks and has no plans to
change.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's my taste. It's my interests,'' Kellner says. ``There's
not a single show I watch on CBS.''
</P>
<P>
   That's the Old People's Network, if you haven't figured it out
yet. And though CBS pulled a coup this season and toppled
long-standing king NBC, Kellner has no interest in what the Nielsen
people call ``total households.''
</P>
<P>
   He's a demographics guy. Always has been, since he helped launch
the Fox network from scratch. He left that network when the
decision was made to make Fox more broad-based, more like The Big
Three it was chasing.
</P>
<P>
   So Kellner left and eventually started The WB, the one network
that has out-foxed Fox and taken away most of its teen and young
adult viewers.
</P>
<P>
   ``We want to be on the leading edge of what's new and
interesting and fun,'' Kellner said. And then he says, flatly,
almost coldly _ especially coming from a guy who's past 50: ``Our
goal is to remain median age under 30. And that's a long-term
goal.''
</P>
<P>
   If you're looking for the guy to watch in the TV industry _ long
term _ it's Kellner. He doesn't have the flash of other TV movers
and shakers like Les Moonves at CBS, or maybe the sense of the
spotlight like former NBC entertainment president Warren
Littlefield. But Kellner is a straight shooter and _ here's the key
_ he's right.
</P>
<P>
   When he left Fox it was because he sensed a dangerous shift at
the network, the desire to one day be No. 1. And to get to be No. 1
_ at least Nielsen ratings-wise _ you need, as Kellner says, a lot
of 50-year-old viewers. That's what CBS has. What they don't have
is a lot of cash _ the kind that pours in from Madison Avenue.
</P>
<P>
   ``Old people are not as susceptible to the ways of advertisers
and willing to change attitudes like teenagers,'' he says. There's
no condemnation or sneer in his voice when he says ``old people,''
because a second earlier he confesses to being one. He's got
nothing against old people. They're just not good for business when
your business is running a television network.
</P>
<P>
   Kellner doesn't long to be No. 1 in this town because he sees it
as a hollow dream. He believes television is becoming increasing
like radio, where niche broadcasting reigns. TV is getting
fragmented. It's clear. And when that happens, he says, your plan
should be equally clear: ``Make sure that the fragment you hold
onto is the most valuable one.''
</P>
<P>
   Before last season, at what the industry calls the ``upfront''
in New York _ where the networks show their goods to advertisers,
who look at the content, divide it by the demographic and hand out
cash accordingly _ only NBC got more money. Not bad for the No. 5
ranked network.
</P>
<P>
   Now, with ``Dawson's Creek,'' ``Charmed'' and ``Felicity'' under
the belt, not to mention ``Buffy the Vampire Slayer'' _ the
networks numbers are up across the board.
</P>
<P>
   ``We got what we did (at the upfront) without those numbers,''
Kellner says. He's got a little half-smile, half-knowing smirk on
his face. Because he knows what's going to happen at the next
upfront: The WB is going to be drowning in money.
</P>
<P>
   That won't be happening to UPN, which used to be the fifth
network and is now the sixth _ and in desperate need of a
turnaround as it fades in The WB's rear-view mirror.
</P>
<P>
   Kellner notes without much apparent glee that the network that
used to be his closest competitor has already switched management
once and has shifted its direction several times. UPN's last plan,
he says, was ``completely unfocused and had no chance for
success.''
</P>
<P>
   UPN will come here and face the nation's TV critics under a much
harsher light. As will all the major networks, come to think of it.
But The WB got away without much damage because most critics like
their shows and understand that of all six networks, it has the
brightest future.
</P>
<P>
   Not that it will ever be No. 1. Because Kellner doesn't think it
needs to be. And a lot of what he thinks is turning out to be
right.
</P>
<P>
   Kellner has become very successful being The Man Who Wouldn't Be
King. He has stuck stubbornly to the idea that the youth of America
control television. And to think that this sort of ``Logan's Run''
attitude about television comes from a guy who likes to visit Napa
because he's something of a wine connoisseur as well as being a
late-developing golfer.
</P>
<P>
   You don't have to be young, apparently. You just have to think
young.
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Tim Goodman is the television critic for the San Francisco
Examiner, P.O. Box 7260, San Francisco, CA 94120. His electronic
mail address is goodman(at)examiner.com).
</P>
</TEXT>
