</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-PLAY-GAMES-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LET THE BOARD GAMES BEGIN
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By CAROL BIDWELL 
c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ &UR;  &LR; Jonathan Lane was 14 when he came home one day,
troubled.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'd been at my friend's house, where there was constant
yelling, which I wasn't used to at all,'' said Jonathan, now 17.
``I knew it didn't have to be that way.''
</P>
<P>
   ``He said, `Mom, my friends all hate their parents, and I feel
really bad. I wish there was something I could do to help','' said
his mother, family therapist and psychologist Kathryn Nessel
Retsky. ``I thought, why not an old-fashioned board game to get
people talking to each other.''
</P>
<P>
   So the two spent nearly every evening for a year sitting at the
kitchen table in their Encino home, devising a game that encourages
players to learn a lot about each other _ their hopes, their
aspirations, their favorite experiences.
</P>
<P>
   Chatter Matters was born.
</P>
<P>
   In the past two years, the mother-and-son team has sold more
than 5,000 Chatter Matters board games and has just ordered a
second production run.
</P>
<P>
   They have yet to make a financial profit, but the real profit,
they believe, is in increased understanding for families who play
the game.
</P>
<P>
   ``People, I think, really need something like this,'' Retsky
said. ``They just don't sit down and talk to each other anymore.''
</P>
<P>
   She and her son are not alone in trying to get families to
communicate.
</P>
<P>
   You know, talk ... the sound that used to come out of people's
mouths when they sat down to dinner together every night: ``How was
your day?'' ``What did you learn in school?'' ``I remember when I
was your age ...''
</P>
<P>
   In many families today, with both parents working and children
dashing off to soccer and music lessons after school, adults and
kids don't even share a box of cornflakes or a plate of fried
chicken on most days, much less discuss their plans or their
problems. And since grandma and grandpa may be living back East or
in a retirement community miles away, there's little storytelling
about ``the old days.''
</P>
<P>
   Board games can encourage a return to family conversation, said
Drew Yellen, a Chatsworth psychologist specializing in family and
child therapy.
</P>
<P>
   ``Before there was television, easy access to the telephone,
people talked,'' Yellen said. ``You used to have time together as a
family. Now, kids can come home and pop onto the Internet from 3
o'clock to midnight and never talk to their parents but have
conversations with people all over the world.
</P>
<P>
   ``Board games can facilitate dialogue _ as long as they're fun
and kids don't see them as `square' or `uncool'.''
</P>
<P>
   Hasbro works hard to provide the fun factor, said Dale Siswick,
general manager for U.S. sales and marketing of games for Hasbro
Inc., the world's No. 1 board game manufacturer. It began in
mid-1998 to promote ``family fun night'' for game-playing, just
like families did before home computers and round-the-clock cable
TV took over.
</P>
<P>
   But despite game makers' efforts to reintroduce ``get-together
games'' to families, sales of traditional board games are running
far behind those of new electronic games and CD-ROMs, some of which
are even being marketed by traditional games makers like Hasbro.
</P>
<P>
   From December 1997 to November 1998, board game sales totaled
$1.5 billion compared to $5.2 billion in computer and video game
sales, according to the New York-based NPD Research Group marketing
firm.
</P>
<P>
   Still, the purveyors of board games aren't worried.
</P>
<P>
   ``Board games will always be as American as apple pie,'' Siswick
said. ``I think the time when the board game business might want to
look over its shoulder is when people who make computer games are
able to make computers smile.''
</P>
<P>
   It's that smile factor that keeps people collecting around a
board game, however low-tech it might be, said John D. Williams
Jr., executive director of the 10,000-member National Scrabble
Association.
</P>
<P>
   His association sponsors nearly 200 Scrabble tournaments
annually, offering prizes up to $25,000. And even 50 years after
the game first challenged players, Williams says it continues to be
a family hit.
</P>
<P>
   Monopoly, likewise, has been going strong since 1935. The Game
of Life debuted in 1960. And Clue players have been trying to
figure out who killed Col. Mustard with the lead pipe in the
library since the early 1950s.
</P>
<P>
   ``People say kids don't like board games anymore, that they're
too busy playing video games and online,'' Williams said. ``Well,
those are just new ways of playing. Playing board games is a social
thing. As long as people sit in a circle and play and talk to each
other, board games will be popular. And when you can finally get a
family playing a game together, it's a blast.''
</P>
<P>
   Retsky said playing Chatter Matters a couple of times a week has
helped her family get along.
</P>
<P>
   ``You're always finding out nice things about each other, about
the past, that you might not ever know any other way,'' said
Jonathan, student body president at Westmark School in Encino.
``Because I know more about my parents, at my age, it becomes less
parenting and more friendship.''
</P>
<P>
   Even though the game, which is available in many toy stores, had
only a modest sales rate, Jonathan and his mother aren't
discouraged.
</P>
<P>
   ``We know there's close to a 100 percent failure rate for any
new games or toys,'' Retsky said. ``You're fighting the big guys _
Parker Bros., Milton Bradley (both now owned by Hasbro). It's hard
to make it. But I have a lot of faith in us. Even if we never make
any money at it, if it gets kids and parents and grandparents
talking to each other, it's served its purpose.'' &QL; 
ENDIT &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-01-08-99 1732EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
