<DOCNO> NYT19990108.0233 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-01-08 17:34 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5227 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-PURGATORY-TV-LADN     01-08 0379
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-PURGATORY-TV-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WESTERN GETS SURREAL IN `PURGATORY'
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By DAVID BLOOM  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ Refuge is a quiet town, tucked away in a verdant
valley. No newspapers here, though, nor a telegraph. Drinks are
free at the saloon, and the doctor sure is nice about patching up
folks for nothing. The sheriff doesn't even pack a gun, though he
does look familiar.
</P>
<P>
   It is into this odd little burg that Blackjack (Eric Roberts in
dastardly good form) and his gang of about 20 bad guys ride after a
particularly bloody bank heist.
</P>
<P>
   The arrival is somewhat unexpected, for both Blackjack's boys
and the townsfolk. After escaping a posse, the gang rides through a
blinding sandstorm and a cave, only to come out by Refuge, which
looks nothing like the high desert they've left behind.
</P>
<P>
   That's the setup for ``Purgatory,'' an entertaining western cum
morality tale with a ``Twilight Zone'' edge that premieres tonight
on TNT.
</P>
<P>
   As the protagonist _ greenhorn would-be gunman Sonny &UR;  &LR; (Brad
Rowe) _ finds out, there's a reason the sheriff (Sam Shepard) looks
familiar. And the doctor (Randy Quaid). And the deputy (Mark
Wahlberg). And the shopkeeper (singer John David Souther).
</P>
<P>
   They're all featured in the dime novels Sonny reads about famous
gunfighters and other notorious figures of the Wild West. ``The
Creator'' has sent them to Refuge for one last shot, so to speak,
at redemption. If they can't resist temptations like violence and
drinking, they'll be tossed into the fires of perdition by a craggy
old Indian who camps nearby.
</P>
<P>
   That quandary sets up the film's conflicts and leads to a
climactic battle between Blackjack and some of the best gunfighters
in the West, an entertaining premise for an altogether entertaining
movie.
</P>
<P>
   It's sort of the Old West equivalent of that old Righteous
Brothers song, ``Rock and Roll Heaven,'' and just as much fun to
think about. Where else, after all, are you going to get to watch
Jesse James, Wild Bill Hickock, Billy the Kid and Doc Holliday all
in the same gunfight?
</P>
<P>
   The show's good fun and well-done. All in all, director Uli Edel
(``Last Exit to Brooklyn'') has done a bang-up job renovating the
western. &QL; 
ENDIT &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-01-08-99 1734EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
