<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-microsoft-score10-cox </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    W/MICROSOFT
 &HT;    AT HALF-TIME, WHO'S AHEAD IN THE MICROSOFT TRIAL?
 &HT;    Moving in (f) financial and (w) Washington queues.
 &HT;    By Andrew J. Glass
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox Newspapers
<TEXT>
<P>
   Here's a half-time scorecard on the Microsoft antitrust trial:
</P>
<P>
   THE GOVERNMENT'S CHARGE: Microsoft Corp. has illegally sought to
extend its Windows monopoly to Web commerce through restrictive
distribution deals for its Internet browser software.
</P>
<P>
   MICROSOFT'S REPLY: Usage of arch-rival Netscape's browsers, far
from being moribund, is actually on the rise. The Internet will
become even more competitive when a merger between America Online
Inc. and Netscape Communications Corp., announced after the trial
began, goes through.
</P>
<P>
   HALF-TIME VERDICT: The jury (actually the presiding judge) views
Microsoft as a monopolist. But the ``jury'' is still out on whether
the monopoly has spilled over into cyberspace.
</P>
<P>
   ---
</P>
<P>
   THE GOVERNMENT'S CHARGE: Microsoft has signed predatory
contracts with personal computer (PC) makers that oblige them to
offer their buyers a Microsoft-ordered ``desktop'' when they first
turn on their machines. This deprives users of the right to choose
the Web links and browser software they prefer.
</P>
<P>
   MICROSOFT'S REPLY: The latest round of deals with PC firms give
them lots of leeway to promote their own branded products,
including Netscape's browser software. The Microsoft tie-ins were
quietly aborted some weeks before the Justice Department filed its
case.
</P>
<P>
   HALF-TIME VERDICT: Since no major PC makers are complaining,
Microsoft seems to be off the hook.
</P>
<P>
   ---
</P>
<P>
   THE GOVERNMENT'S CHARGE: Microsoft ``polluted'' the Java
programming language, which poses the greatest current threat to
Microsoft's monopoly, in order to keep developers' apron strings
firmly tied to Windows. Java is produced by rival Sun Microsystems
Inc.
</P>
<P>
   MICROSOFT'S REPLY: Our flavor of Java runs better than Sun's
Java. Besides, Sun has never met its promise that a program written
in Java can run equally well on any operating system.
</P>
<P>
   HALF-TIME VERDICT: Guilty as charged.
</P>
<P>
   END
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-01-08-99 1742EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990108.0235 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-01-08 17:43 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5235 &Cx1f; tad-z
u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-microsoft10-cox     01-08 0972
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-microsoft10-cox </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    AT HALF-TIME, WHO'S AHEAD IN THE MICROSOFT TRIAL?
 &HT;    Moving in (f) financial and (w) Washington queues
 &HT;    With Microsoft scorecard
 &HT;    By ANDREW J. GLASS
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ The government plans to rest its case in the
Microsoft antitrust trial this week when a top economist from the
Massachusetts Institute of Technology leaves the stand. Microsoft
then will begin its defense by calling another top economist from
MIT to the stand.
</P>
<P>
   But the half-time symmetry ends there: the dueling witnesses
hold sharply different views on whether Microsoft Corp., the
world's largest software company, is a predator that flouts the
antitrust laws.
</P>
<P>
   According to one view, Microsoft operates in a highly
competitive, fast-moving, technology-driven business climate that
requires the software giant to grapple with competitors and to
strike deals with partners. As Richard Schmalensee, interim dean at
the Sloan School of Management at MIT, sees it, Microsoft must
innovate or eventually perish.
</P>
<P>
   Under the opposing view, Microsoft is driven by a perceived need
to protect at all costs its Windows-based monopoly in operating
systems for personal computers. Under this scenario, it misuses the
power of Windows to seek control of electronic commerce through its
bid to monopolize the market for Internet browsers. As Franklin
Fisher of MIT sees it, the courts must punish Microsoft for its
anti-competitive conduct.
</P>
<P>
   For Fisher and the government, Microsoft's 1995 decision to give
away its Internet Explorer (IE) Web browser with Windows has
blocked competitors from innovating in that critical sphere. They
see the decision to integrate IE into Windows 98 as an effort to
thwart the courts from imposing effective remedies.
</P>
<P>
   But for Schmalensee and Microsoft, the company markets one
product in response to customer demands. They sense that no real
harm has been done to Netscape Communications Corp., whose browsers
are still widely in use and which is slated to gain traction
through a pending merger with America Online Inc., a leading
gateway to the Internet.
</P>
<P>
   So who's ahead? No one is really sure.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Justice Department has presented no critical mass of
evidence against Microsoft,'' says William Neukom, Microsoft's
senior vice president of law and corporate affairs. ``There is no
monopoly. There is no predatory pricing. There is no illegal tying
of one product to another. Microsoft's contracts have not
foreclosed other companies from distributing their products.''
</P>
<P>
   Says Robert Litan, director of economic studies at Brookings
Institution, a Washington think tank:
</P>
<P>
   ``The government is ahead, but it's not a rout. If this were a
baseball game, it would be something like 2-to-0, or 3-to-0. At the
end of the day, I believe this judge will rule against Microsoft on
one or two liability issues. But remember that this is not a
one-game series. There's going to be at least one more game in the
appeals court, and maybe another one after that in the Supreme
Court.''
</P>
<P>
   Apparently, the antitrust struggle still hangs in the balance.
Surely, it still carries profound implications for the way the
nation's high-tech climate will evolve in the next century.
</P>
<P>
   In truth, the stakes in the landmark antitrust action are so
high that it's hard to find neutral observers _ save, of course,
for U.S. District Judge Thomas Penfield Jackson, who has been
trying the case without a jury since mid-October. (In mid-week,
Jackson is expected to reject a plea by Microsoft's legal team to
end the trial in midstream on the grounds that the government has
failed to make its case.)
</P>
<P>
   But an insight to Microsoft's uncompromising legal strategy may
be found from another MIT technical whiz: Michael Dertouzos,
director of the school's Laboratory for Computer Science.
Originally, Microsoft named Dertouzos as one its 12 defense
witness. But soon after he was deposed by the government in
September, Microsoft quietly dropped him.
</P>
<P>
   Last month, Department of Justice lawyers told the court that
Dertouzos sees Web browsers as optional applications, rather than
part of an operating system. Not surprisingly, that's the
government's view as well.
</P>
<P>
   But Microsoft countered that Dertouzos also envisions the merger
of browser and operating system as an inevitable trend. That
finding suggests that Microsoft competes in a benign fashion.
</P>
<P>
   Dertouzos said he agreed to testify at the trial after Microsoft
chairman Bill Gates called him and promised he wouldn't be muzzled.
But in Gates' take-no-prisoners culture, he proved to be, as
Dertouzos put it, ``a bit too independent.''
</P>
<P>
   Beyond witnesses, real and aborted, for further insights the
judge must review the huge pile of documents placed into evidence.
Taken as a whole, they offer an extraordinary view of the normally
closed world of hi-tech commerce at the highest levels.
</P>
<P>
   Take government exhibit 1016, offered last week. This is a
17-page document from mid-1995 in which Microsoft executive Ben
Slivka wrote: ``The Web is an application platform that threatens
Windows.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Microsoft has approached the Web much as the blind men
approached the elephant, with different groups 'feeling' different
parts of the beast and coming to different conclusions about the
Web as a whole,'' Slivka added.
</P>
<P>
   ``Hence, we have not had a consistent view of what the Web is,
nor determined how to exploit the Web to achieve our goal of a PC
on every desk and in every home running Microsoft software.''
</P>
<P>
   In weeks to come, as more corporate figures troop to the witness
stand, the government, in questioning them, will try to show that
in meeting that ``goal,'' Microsoft stepped over the line.
</P>
<P>
   END
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-01-08-99 1743EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990108.0236 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-01-08 17:43 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5237 &Cx1f; ttj-z
r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FBN-GARRISON-HEARST-H     01-08 0629
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-GARRISON-HEARST-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NINERS' GARRISON IS FULLY-STOCKED 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By GWEN KNAPP  
 c.1999 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ Bobb McKittrick, the line coach with the
starched jaw and rigid posture, got a little gleam in his eye when
Garrison Hearst's name came up.
</P>
<P>
   He talked about how the 49ers' running back blocks, how he goes
directly at linebackers and defensive linemen, doesn't just nick
them on the shoulder to slow them down. By the time McKittrick was
done talking, he sounded ready to sign adoption papers.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think a running back can be tougher,'' McKittrick
said, with a crowd of reporters around him. Someone pointed out
that Hearst had the opposite reputation right after college, when
he was hurt and Buddy Ryan, his coach, implied that he was soft.
</P>
<P>
   ``Yeah, well,'' McKittrick said brusquely, the friendly gleam in
his eye replaced by something more stern, ``that guy's raising
horses.''
</P>
<P>
   That same afternoon, in fact, Ryan was down on his Kentucky
farm, three years removed from his firing as the Arizona Cardinals'
coach. He answered a phone call from San Francisco and proceeded to
revise the popular version of his history with Hearst.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was always very fond of him,'' Ryan said. ``He got 1,000
yards the second year under me. He was Comeback Player of the
Year.' He continued to praise Hearst for the next five minutes,
calling him the leader of the Cardinals' offense in 1995, reminding
the caller that Ryan didn't get rid of him.
</P>
<P>
   ``He was (released) after I got fired,'' the
coach-turned-Kentucky-farmer said.
</P>
<P>
   Ryan's take on his relationship with Hearst proves one thing:
Only a fool would watch Hearst today and admit to ever overlooking
his steeliness.
</P>
<P>
   Against Green Bay last weekend, in the most important game of
his NFL career, Hearst played to the point of collapse. He
staggered off the field in the fourth quarter, in desperate need of
relief from leg cramps.
</P>
<P>
   He had rushed for 128 yards and sustained the 49ers' offense
until the passing game came to life in the final two minutes. Three
days later, with a trip Atlanta on the horizon, his teammates
reveled in remembering his 24-yard run in the third quarter, when
he knocked over safety Darren Sharper and then shoved a stiff-arm
at the Pack's hard-playing, hard-talking LeRoy Butler.
</P>
<P>
   It was a classic, old-time, NFL Films kind of play. It was the
kind of play that inspired memories of Walter Payton.
</P>
<P>
   ``He punishes people when he runs,'' Ryan said. ``I can't say
he's like Walter Payton, but he reminds me of him.''
</P>
<P>
   Funny thing _ McKittrick had made almost exactly the same remark
an hour earlier.
</P>
<P>
   To hear the line coach and his big charges tell it, Hearst is
practically one of them, an honorary lineman. They appreciate that
he does not play a glamour position as if it were all about
styling.
</P>
<P>
   ``When we're watching film, we definitely rewind to look at some
of his blocks,'' said guard Kevin Gogan, who received one of the
Rolex watches that Hearst handed out to his linemen for helping him
break the Niners' single-season rushing record.
</P>
<P>
   This week, in an exceptionally loose 49ers locker room, Hearst's
loud cackling laugh has returned, according to head coach Steve
Mariucci. His injury isn't considered as severe this time.
</P>
<P>
   But the running back has finally jumped into something that
intimidates him.
</P>
<P>
   To help his hamstring heal, he has taken treatment in hyperbaric
chamber. He has to spend two hours in the cramped space, and
claustrophobia makes it agony for him.
</P>
<P>
   ``I can't stand it,'' he said, in one of his typically brief
remarks to the media.
</P>
<P>
   It's no surprise. As the Packers can tell you, he is not easily
contained.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-01-08-99 1743EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
