<SLUG> BC-ACCESSORIES-TIPS09-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Pritchard's pointers for accessorizing
 &HT;    By Danny C. Flanders
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   Here are some tips from Atlanta interior designer Jillian
Pritchard for displaying accessories:
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Buy inexpensive items, such as candlesticks, colored glass or
picture frames from stores such as Pier 1 Imports, Crate &AMP; Barrel
or Pottery Barn, if you lack small collections.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Use old encyclopedias as platforms for displaying other items
and to fill space in bookcases. Never lean books; brace them with
bookends or lay them flat.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Vary the heights of items; avoid placing similar-size ones
together.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Stack, don't fan, magazines to create impact.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Use greenery, such as a potted plant, to add natural
materials.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Don't use candles when you want to emphasize the candlesticks.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Pile paperback books in a large basket instead of displaying
the worn copies on a shelf.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Fill gaps under side tables with large baskets or pots to draw
the eye toward the floor.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Emphasize small paintings or mirrors with interesting frames
by propping them against the wall on a table, mantel or bookshelf.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Put less significant and least-often used items on the lowest
bookshelves, saving upper ones for your best accessories.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Group items of similar color to create impact.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Mix metals within a collection, such as brass, bronze and
gold, to create interest.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Don't throw away broken objects; large pieces of a vase or pot
often make unique items.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Accent displays with small lamps or pendant fixtures that cast
intense light on a subject.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Burn new candle wicks so the candles appear used.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Don't feel obligated to decorate an attractive hearth with
fireplace tools, unless you build lots of fires. Remember: Less can
be more.
</P>
<P>
   Danny C. Flanders writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
