<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ACCESSORIES09-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Wake up a room by adding new accessories _ or just rearranging
what you have
 &HT;    By Danny C. Flanders
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Take a long hard look at your living room.
</P>
<P>
   That new sofa and armoire you got for Christmas look great but
seem cold and barren. Something's missing.
</P>
<P>
   Or maybe your end tables look less like the perfectly decorated
ones in House Beautiful and more like something from ``The Odd
Couple,'' cluttered with remote controls, CD
</P>
<P>
   cases, candy bar wrappers and month-old newspapers.
</P>
<P>
   If either case sounds familiar, your room may qualify for the
next episode of ``Jerry Springer'' _ ``People Who Need Treatment
for Accessory Disorder Syndrome.'' You know the internal disease _
too few decorating touches, such as pillows, pictures, books and
collectibles, or to the other extreme, too much stuff.
</P>
<P>
   ``More than anything else, people usually just have the wrong
things displayed in the wrong places,'' said Jillian Pritchard, an
Atlanta interior designer.
</P>
<P>
   They may own beautiful furniture, but without the right accents
their rooms look flat, she said. Accessories are the crowning
touches _ the necklace or earrings that make that little black
dress come to life. Touches that give interiors personality by
reflecting the things you like, your hobbies and interests. Touches
that inject color and texture into a room, making it intriguing and
inviting.
</P>
<P>
   So you say you're broke after buying that new sofa and armoire
and can't afford any of these precious jewels. Not to worry: Not
all accessories are expensive; a lot depends on your decorating
tastes. Designers contend clients typically already have most of
what they need; it just needs to be moved around. Other things may
just need a little spiffing up _ a new shade for that lamp, a new
fabric for that pillow, new frames for those family photos _
especially ones you suddenly inherit through marriage or death.
</P>
<P>
   ``When my mother died, I was overwhelmed as I began the process
of cleaning out her home. It was full of possessions from the late
1930s on,'' Martha Jo Katz said. ``Then I found ones from my
grandmother's home that were packed away from years before.''
</P>
<P>
   The last thing the Marietta (Ga.) resident wanted was to regret
getting rid of something special. And because she loves
contemporary art, Katz also was concerned about mixing the old with
the new. So she resolved to make the experience fun by opening her
mind to new and unconventional ways of displaying accessories.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are so many ideas to take advantage of what some people
would just consider throwing away or putting in a closet or giving
away,'' she said. ``Plus, it's so nice to be able see and use so
many of these special things every day.''
</P>
<P>
   Katz was determined to make the emotional experience of sorting
through a parent's belongings a fun adventure, and it paid off. The
additional pieces made her home so attractive that friends have
asked Katz, a cater
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Using some accessories as displays, such as books as platforms
for giving other items height or large plates placed on stands as
backgrounds for a grouping.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Emphasizing special accessories with lighting, either overhead
task fixtures or accent lamps.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Remembering that less can be more. ``You're better off
accenting a fabulous fireplace by putting no tools on the hearth
and just adding simple logs,'' Pritchard said.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Lean a painting on a mantel to lend informality.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Balance pairs of accessories, such as large hurricane lamps,
to give this vignette symmetry. The natural texture of topiaries
softens the hard look of stone.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Use furniture as an accessory _ in this case, to make the
fireplace more inviting.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Use candlesticks too small for so massive a mantel.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Be without anything to draw you into the fireplace. ``It
should play host to your home's best pieces since it's the focal
point of a room,'' Pritchard says.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Have too many competing types of items with nothing in common.
``There's no golden thread that ties the accessories together,''
she says.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Use larger pieces to add scale and create impact.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Organize elements by categories into small collections, such
as photos, crystal and magazines.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Make old encyclopedias into convenient display platforms. Line
treasured books along the shelf's edge ``supermarket style'' so
their spines can be read.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Restrict movement among the pieces. The scale of the items is
too similar.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Be without uniformity. No one element plays off another.
``It's just a lot of stuff,'' Pritchard says.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Be without any color to draw you to the bookcase.
</P>
<P>
   Danny C. Flanders writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
