<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CALORIES-PORTIONS09-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Bigger isn't better: Smaller portions mean smarter eating
 &HT;    By Reagan Walker
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ You've purged your cupboards of the double deluxe
chocolate cookies and tossed the praline dream ice cream from the
freezer.
</P>
<P>
   From now on, it's graham crackers and low-fat frozen yogurt,
lean chicken and fat-free bagels.
</P>
<P>
   Congratulations for determining to make healthy food choices.
But if you want to lose weight or feel great, you'll have to do
more than pay attention to what you eat.
</P>
<P>
   How much you eat is just as important.
</P>
<P>
   ``Portion size is key,'' said Chris Rosenbloom, a nutritionist
and professor at Georgia State University. ``Most of us have a very
distorted view of what portions are. It's triple-beef burger here
and monster-size there. If your goal is to eat healthy, you have to
pay attention.''
</P>
<P>
   Never has the message about portions been so clearly
demonstrated than a few years back when all the low-fat and no-fat
products hit the shelf. America was sure to shed pounds, right?
</P>
<P>
   Well, no. If you inhale a whole box of low-fat crackers you've
inhaled a whole lot of calories. Period.
</P>
<P>
   So rule No. 1: Read the label. While you are checking out the
fat content and the calories, be sure and look at the portion size,
Rosenbloom said.
</P>
<P>
   And if the portion size is a half cup, then measure it out.
Atlanta nutritionist Page Love recommends measuring foods in cups
and kitchen scales for a couple of weeks to train yourself on
proper portion sizes.
</P>
<P>
   ``You don't have to do this forever. If you did, you'd be
putting too much focus on food. But do it for a while until you've
learned visually what proper portions are,'' Love said. ``And if
you get off track, pull out the measuring cups and scales again to
remind yourself.''
</P>
<P>
   Some general rules for serving sizes:
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Breads usually are 1 slice of bread, 1/2 cup cooked cereal, a
2-ounce bagel (bakery size is tions are large. One idea is to keep
some visual cues in mind.
</P>
<P>
   A proper portion of meat is about the size of a deck of cards or
the palm of your hand. Bagels should be the size of a hockey puck.
Rice and pasta portions are a half cup, or a mound no bigger than a
tennis ball.
</P>
<P>
   And the next time you say, ``I only had a muffin for
breakfast,'' ask yourself if it was the size of a ``baby's head,''
as Rosenbloom described some bakery portions.
</P>
<P>
   Cut those large muffins in half. Order an appetizer as an
entree. Or ask for a doggie bag at the beginning of the meal and
set some aside before you dig in. And remember you don't have to
finish everything on your plate.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are a couple of words people need to learn, like, `I'm
full,' '' Rosenbloom said. ``If you make no other changes in your
diet than cutting portions, you will see a difference.''
</P>
<P>
   Reagan Walker writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
