<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FITNESS09-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Getting fit is important for everyone, and its an activity
families can do together
 &HT;    By Lillian Lee Kim
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ One in four American children is overweight. It's a
sobering fact disproving the belief that kids lead naturally
active, healthy lives, and that these habits only begin to
deteriorate in adulthood.
</P>
<P>
   Part of the problem is that our collective nutritional values
have suffered over the years. But another significant factor is
that _ thanks to video games and other indoor diversions _ the
Saturday morning cartoon set is anchored in front of the TV long
after cartoons are over.
</P>
<P>
   For kids, getting physical isn't always as easy as going with
mom or dad to the gym. Many gyms don't allow kids younger than 12
or 14. By that age, the damage already may be done.
</P>
<P>
   ``If they could start at a younger age, they could avoid a lot
of problems,'' said Eileen Messer, whose 12-year-old daughter is
struggling with her weight. She does step aerobics videos at home
but is looking forward to being old enough to work out with her mom
at their neighborhood clubhouse near Peachtree City.
</P>
<P>
   Options do exist, however, for families seeking fitness.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  If you already belong to a health club or gym, ask if the
management will be flexible about the age rule, for closely
supervised kids.
</P>
<P>
   ``Since obesity is increasingly a problem with very young
adolescents, they do occasionally waive that rule and let the child
work out with the parent,'' said Janie Wilson, spokeswoman for the
Australian Body Works chain.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Some clubs are starting to offer programs just for youngsters.
This week, Athletic Club Northeast in Atlanta opened a
2,500-square-foot Blast! Kids Center, a step up from the
baby-sitting services gyms usually offer.
</P>
<P>
   ``Twenty years ago this club was popular as a singles place,''
said Randy Chamberlain, the club's general manager. ``Now a lot of
members have kids. There's a real need for this.''
</P>
<P>
   In the Blast! Center, kids can do homework, arts and crafts or
exercise, with activities such as judo, tumbling and swimming.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's somewhere they can look forward to going to. Not a
pressure place, not a competitive sport, not school,'' said program
director Kirsty Lubicz-Nawrocka.
</P>
<P>
   The Blast! Center will cost parents an extra $2 or $3 per hour
on top of membership dues.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Join the Y. The YMCA offers ``lots of outlets for every
interest,'' says Randy Borden, 50, who works out at the Ashford
Dunwoody (Ga.) branch with her husband and two youngest children.
</P>
<P>
   On any given evening, Borden might be lifting weights while her
husband takes a spin class; her 11-year-old daughter might be
practicing gymnastics while her son, 15, shoots hoops.
</P>
<P>
   ``At 15 you want to get them doing something beside just going
to school and coming home,'' Borden said. ``So we're all working
out together. That's a special time for us.''
</P>
<P>
   A lot of parents take advantage of the Y's family-friendly
programs by exercising while their kids take swim, gymnastics or
karate classes.
</P>
<P>
   ``It makes the parents more regular because they know they have
to bring the kids to class,'' said Linda Spence, the Ashford
Dunwoody Y's physical education director.
</P>
<P>
   Families make up 75 percent of the membership at the recently
opened Ed Isakson/Alpharetta (Ga.) Family YMCA. Its ``Family Fun
and Fitness'' class for all ages involves slightly unusual exercise
equipment, such as Hula Hoops, and is popular among kids under 6
years and their parents.
</P>
<P>
   All YMCAs offer ``family time'' in the pool or gym; call for
times.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Kick yourself into high gear. Martial arts studios offer a
great way for parents and children to get into shape.
</P>
<P>
   Ten years ago, Ginny Csoka, alarmed by recent local rapes,
marched herself and her 3-year-old son into an American Karate Joe
Corley Studio. Today, Csoka, 58, holds a second degree black belt _
her son has a third degree black belt _ and she easily keeps pace
with the 20-year-olds in kickboxing classes.
</P>
<P>
   ``We had no idea what it would turn out to be for us,'' said
Csoka. Her son competes in karate. Two grandchildren, ages 4 and 5,
also take classes.
</P>
<P>
   Martial arts studios have long welcomed children, even the very
young, and many make it convenient for families to come together.
The Joe Corley Studios, for instance, schedule several adult and
child classes during the same time slots.
</P>
<P>
   ``We really encourage family participation,'' said Joe Corley.
``As my friend Chuck Norris says, the family that kicks together,
sticks together.''
</P>
<P>
   Most health clubs, YMCAs and martial arts studios offer
discounted family memberships.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Getting the whole family moving can be as simple as walking or
bicycling, both excellent exercises, or just running around in the
yard. The key is to spend time together and to make sure it's fun.
</P>
<P>
   ``One of the most important things adults can do is to lead by
example,'' Wilson said. ``We've got to do that in our health lives.
And one of the best ways to do that is to play with your
children.''
</P>
<P>
   Lillian Lee Kim writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
