A5244 &Cx1f; tad-z
u l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-GAGOV-BELIEFS09-COX     01-08 0892
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GAGOV-BELIEFS09-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Faith `gives you strength and peace in times of trouble,'
governor-elect finds
 &HT;    By Gayle White
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ When Roy Barnes puts his hand on his worn Ryrie Study
Bible to take the oath of office Monday as Georgia's governor,
he'll be taking another step on a lifelong road of faith.
</P>
<P>
   Barnes, 50, will be the third United Methodist in a row to live
in the state's Governor's Mansion, but he claimed Christianity
when, at 8 years of age, he walked down the aisle of Concord
Baptist Church in Mableton to the tune of an old hymn that asks
``Why Not Tonight?''
</P>
<P>
   ``You were just expected to go to Sunday school and church,
vacation Bible school, Royal Ambassadors and fall revivals,'' he
said, recalling the Baptist activities of his childhood.
</P>
<P>
   He married his wife, Marie, in 1970 at First United Methodist
Church in Marietta and has been a part of the church ever since,
sometimes teaching Sunday school and serving on congregational
boards and committees.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's a very loyal, very dedicated, involved member, and he
gives very generously,'' said former U.S. Rep. Buddy Darden, a
member of the same Sunday school class as Barnes, ``but he has very
wisely stayed out of the politics of the church. He's not someone
who tries to bring attention to himself.''
</P>
<P>
   Darden, who was defeated in 1994 by fellow church member Bob
Barr, said Barnes' family life, like his church membership, is
exemplary. ``I think Roy is one of those people who conduct his
religion by example rather than precept.''
</P>
<P>
   Barnes credits faith with helping to keep his marriage solid
after almost 29 years, while some other politicians who proclaim
``family values'' have had multiple wives.
</P>
<P>
   ``Any married couple can find an excuse to get a divorce,'' he
said. ``I don't believe a spouse should stay in a situation where a
child or spouse is harmed. But short of that, faith and dedication
will get people through.''
</P>
<P>
   He said he finds a ``healing effect'' in church, listening to
Scriptures and familiar hymns. Among his favorites: ``Amazing
Grace,'' written by a repentant slave dealer (``You talk about a
story of redemption!'' the governor-elect exclaims), and ``O For A
Thousand Tongues to Sing,'' a staple in the United Methodist
hymnal.
</P>
<P>
   Barnes admits that he takes ribbing from his wife because he's
somewhat of a connoisseur of television preachers. ``I like to hear
'em,'' he said. ``I also like to see their style. I'm a lawyer. I
like public speaking.''
</P>
<P>
   He's impressed with the Rev. T.D. Jakes, who, he says, ``can
move a crowd,'' and unimpressed with the Rev. John Hagee. ``I don't
like his condemning style.''
</P>
<P>
   Although worship is important, faith should reach well beyond
the church walls, Barnes said. He reads the Bible frequently and
finds comfort in the Psalms, but said he is on no rigid reading
schedule. ``The Bible and religion ought to be something that laps
over you, that you kind of enjoy rather than something you have to
do,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   When he has had to make difficult decisions, he has called on
his faith. ``It's what gives you strength and peace in times of
trouble,'' he said. He considers prayer ``a method of
problem-solving.''
</P>
<P>
   ``One of the hardest decisions I ever made was in 1985 when I
gave serious consideration to running for the U.S. Senate,'' he
said. ``I almost decided to run, but our oldest child was 12 and
our youngest was 6. I felt it tugging at me that I did not need to
uproot these children. I decided not to run. I believe I could have
been elected, but in the long run, it turned out to be the right
decision. We have three wonderful children.''
</P>
<P>
   Some conservative Christian groups consistently rated Barnes'
voting record unfavorably during his days in the state Legislature.
He said he is ``very hurt'' by some of the methods used in the
ratings.
</P>
<P>
   ``Christianity is based on free will and choice,'' he said.
``The idea that in politics, if you exercise free will and
judgment, you are somehow un-Christian is foreign and offensive to
me.''
</P>
<P>
   He said he also disagrees with people who claim to be Christian
but seem to be ``against everything.''
</P>
<P>
   ``In my view, the harshness and negativity of many Christians
drive away people _ particularly young people more than anything
else,'' he said. ``Christ was compassionate and loving. The whole
idea of Christianity is that we would change our lives to such an
extent that people would see that in us.''
</P>
<P>
   While running for governor, Barnes visited churches and
synagogues across the state.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think politicians should be afraid of faith,'' Barnes
said. ``Politicians confuse the legal separation of church and
state with a personal separation.''
</P>
<P>
   His understanding of his religious obligations influences his
political platform, he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``The responsibility I have as a Christian is to protect those
who are weak and to speak for those in the shadows of life,
children and the elderly,'' he said. ``That doesn't mean I have the
right to impose my view of faith on anyone, but it does mean I have
a responsibility as part of my beliefs to help protect those who
are weak and unprotected.''
</P>
<P>
   Gayle White writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
