u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-IMPEACHMENT-PENS-HNS &LR;      01-08 0501
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-IMPEACHMENT-PENS-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SENATE PENS USED IN IMPEACHMENT PROCEEDINGS HAVE SOUVENIR VALUE
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By ERIC ROSENBERG  
 c.1999 Hearst Newspapers  
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Political souvenir collectors, take note.
</P>
<P>
   The pens used by senators to sign an ``oath book'' officially
opening President Clinton's impeachment trial may ultimately fetch
over $100 on the collectors' market.
</P>
<P>
   The Parker Vector pens, with a black shaft, silver cap and
rollerball tip, retail for about $10 at stationery stores.
</P>
<P>
   The pens used Thursday at the start of the impeachment trial are
inscribed with the words ``United States Senator'' along the side
and are standard equipment in U.S. Senate offices.
</P>
<P>
   Their use in the historic opening of the impeachment trial _ the
first impeachment trial of a president in 131 years _ may
dramatically boost the value.
</P>
<P>
   Edmund Sullivan, former curator of the Museum of American
Political Life at the University of Hartford, home of the largest
private collection of political memorabilia in the country, said
the 100 pens will be sought after as collectibles.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is a good collectors' market out there for this sort of
thing,'' said Sullivan. ``My guess is they would fetch perhaps $100
or more per pen in the immediate future. Over the years, the price
would probably decline.''
</P>
<P>
   The problem for collectors is determining whether a particular
pen was actually used in the impeachment proceedings.
</P>
<P>
   The pens used at the opening of the impeachment trial didn't
have special markings commemorating the event. As a result, it
would be difficult for collectors to document a particular pen's
connection to the impeachment proceedings.
</P>
<P>
   Nancy Olson, editorial director of Pen World International, a
trade magazine that tracks the collectible pen market, said
collectors will use anecdotal evidence to establish the
authenticity of a purported impeachment pen.
</P>
<P>
   ``Basically, you have to trust the person from whom you are
buying or receiving the pen,'' said Olson.
</P>
<P>
   Roger Fischer, history professor at the Duluth campus of the
University of Minnesota, who helped authenticate pens and other
memorabilia collected by Vice President Hubert Humphrey, said many
collectors would want a signed letter from a senator attesting that
a particular pen was used at the trial.
</P>
<P>
   ``They'd be worth 20 times as much with a letter of authenticity
from the U.S. senator who got it than they would be as a Parker pen
you could have picked up at the corner drugstore,'' said Fischer.
</P>
<P>
   One bearish note was sounded by John Loring, a Chicago attorney
and avid political pen collector.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is nothing special in the imprinting to distinguish it
from a pen that would be used last month or next month,'' said
Loring.
</P>
<P>
   Even if a dealer were selling an impeachment pen accompanied by
an authenticating letter, ``I would probably go to $100,'' Loring
said. ``Pens are nice but they are not fantastic collectibles.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
