<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-01-08 17:49 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5252 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-REHNQUIST-COURT-$ADV1     01-08 0899
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-REHNQUIST-COURT-$ADV10-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
IMPEACHMENT TRIAL MAY POSE FOR REHNQUIST AND HIGH COURT 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (For release Sunday, Jan. 10)   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By DAN FREEDMAN  
 c.1999 Hearst Newspapers  
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Chief Justice William Rehnquist's role as judge at
the Senate impeachment trial of President Clinton may be a burden
for Rehnquist personally and may also affect the Supreme Court's
docket of cases to be decided, depending on how long the trial
lasts.
</P>
<P>
   ``It will impact the quality of the Supreme Court's work in
subtle ways that are nevertheless important,'' said Georgetown
University law professor Paul Rothstein, a veteran Supreme Court
watcher, who predicted that impeachment duties will rob Rehnquist
of time needed to ponder difficult cases.
</P>
<P>
   The chief justice, however, is not likely to miss oral arguments
in cases before the court because they usually take place in the
morning and impeachment trial sessions start in the afternoon,
unless the Senate sets a different time.
</P>
<P>
   High court rules do not bar justices from deciding cases if they
miss oral arguments. Those who are absent may listen to a tape
recording or read a transcript. In addition, justices and their
clerks can refer to legal briefs submitted in each case.
</P>
<P>
   The court has scheduled oral arguments in 23 cases for Mondays,
Tuesdays and Wednesdays through March 3. Rehnquist should be able
to attend them, since all but one are to be heard in the morning.
The sole afternoon argument is scheduled for Monday (Jan. 11),
which is not a hearing day in the Clinton case under trial
procedures approved by the Senate Friday.
</P>
<P>
   Among the 23 cases are a few of the biggest ones the justices
will consider this term. One is a challenge to a California law
that provides more generous welfare benefits to state residents who
have been there more than a year than it does to recent arrivals.
Another looks at whether local school boards can be sued for
damages under a federal sex-discrimination law when students harass
fellow students.
</P>
<P>
   Rehnquist also will be able to continue presiding over the
closed-door conferences that the Supreme Court holds on Friday
mornings. At those conferences the justices announce their views
and vote on most of the cases they have heard that week. They then
decide which ones to take up in the coming months. As chief
justice, Rehnquist assigns the writing of opinions in cases where
he is in the majority. When he is in the minority, the most senior
justice on the majority side performs the task.
</P>
<P>
   To lessen the justices' burden on Fridays, they also meet
Wednesday afternoons to vote on cases argued the previous Monday.
Since Rehnquist's impeachment trial duties will presumably conflict
with the Wednesday meetings, it is possible that the justices may
simply decide their entire week's caseload in their Friday morning
conferences.
</P>
<P>
   Under Chief Justice Warren Burger, who served from 1969 to 1986,
conferences were day-long affairs in which justices had free rein
to spar with one another on points of law. Under the energetic,
let's-keep-moving Rehnquist, however, conferences are fast-paced.
Each justice briefly states a view on the case at hand and after
all nine have spoken, a prompt vote is taken.
</P>
<P>
   David O'Brien, a government professor at the University of
Virginia and a close Supreme Court watcher, says Rehnquist ``is one
of the most efficient, business-like chief justices we ever had.
He's superb at compartmentalizing his life and responsibilities.''
</P>
<P>
   Most court observers say the 74-year-old Rehnquist should be
able to handle his duties in the monumental marble court as well as
those in the Senate across the street.
</P>
<P>
   Questions about his health come up from time to time. Before he
had surgery in 1995, he suffered from crippling back pain. The
surgery appears to have succeeded, and predictions that Rehnquist
might retire after the 1996 election proved false.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's is going to be a strain, but despite his age he's a
robust man,'' said Charles Cooper, a Washington lawyer and former
Reagan administration Justice Department official who served as a
law clerk to Rehnquist. ``I have no doubt he can bear up under the
additional burden. He'll make the time. The Constitution leaves no
choice in the matter.''
</P>
<P>
   But the burden would grow heavier if the trial were to go for
months. The last impeachment trial _ that of President Andrew
Johnson in 1868 _ went 2 1/2 months.
</P>
<P>
   In addition to running the Supreme Court, Rehnquist also
presides over the Judicial Conference of the United States, the
body that oversees the operations of the entire federal court
system.
</P>
<P>
   If the Clinton trial drags on through the spring, it will cut
into the court's rush to decide cases before the traditional summer
recess at the end of June or beginning of July.
</P>
<P>
   ``At that point, the justices are busy writing opinions,'' said
O'Brien. ``It could be that Rehnquist would assign more opinions to
other justices and relieve himself of that burden.''
</P>
<P>
   Few doubt the work of the court will get done, but some
observers wonder whether the quality will suffer.
</P>
<P>
   ``It takes a lot more to be a good Supreme Court justice than
just taking part in oral arguments,'' said Rothstein. ``It takes
time to read briefs and ruminate'' about how cases should be
decided. ``He wouldn't have that time.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
