<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-01-08 17:50 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5254 &Cx1f; taf-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BKC-HOYA-THOMPSON-NYT     01-08 1134
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKC-HOYA-THOMPSON-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
JOHN THOMPSON RESIGNS AS GEORGETOWN COACH  
(JT)
</HEADLINE>
   By JUDY BATTISTA   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ With his past star players along with his current
team flanking him, John Thompson ended an illustrious, influential
27-year coaching career at Georgetown on Friday.
</P>
<P>
   At a morning news conference here, Thompson cited the need to
devote more time to his personal life as the reason for his sudden
resignation. Thompson, 57, filed for divorce in October 1997 from
Gwen Thompson, his wife of 32 years. They had been separated since
a fire damaged their home three years ago.
</P>
<P>
   Thompson stressed he was not retiring _ and he would not rule
out coaching again someday. But he said he took the advice he has
long given to his players: he stepped aside to deal with private
matters when he could no longer devote the hours and attention to
his job. Georgetown has a 7-6 record, including 0-4 in Big East
Conference games.
</P>
<P>
   ''You know that I'm going through a problem with my marriage
right now,'' Thompson said. ``I owe it to my family to address
that. I would be irresponsible if I didn't address that.''
</P>
<P>
   He will be succeeded by Craig Esherick, who played for Thompson
from 1974 to 1978 and has been an assistant since 1979 (part of the
time while earning his law degree). His first game is Saturday here
against Providence. The Hoyas will face St. John's at Madison
Square Garden on Monday night.
</P>
<P>
   Thompson's decision came as a shock to almost everyone around
him. Thompson participated in Thursday's conference call of Big
East coaches without giving a clue that the announcement was less
than 24 hours away. And Esherick said he was so surprised that he
tried to talk Thompson into changing his mind.
</P>
<P>
   ''I'm not happy for myself but I'm looking forward to the
challenge of this job,'' Esherick, 42, said. ``This is a job I
tried to talk my boss out of for three days. Just like most things
I've tried to talk him out of, I was unsuccessful. He was the very
first recruit I failed to land. I'm sorry for that.''
</P>
<P>
   Thompson said he also rejected Temple Coach John Chaney's pleas
that he merely take a leave of absence.
</P>
<P>
   ''I said `Did you ever lend your toothbrush to someone?',''
Thompson said. ``Lending someone your team is like lending someone
your toothbrush.''
</P>
<P>
   Thompson will continue to work for Georgetown in what school
president Rev. Loe O'Donovan called a ``coach emeritus'' position,
helping the university on academic, athletic and community
projects.
</P>
<P>
   He was joined at the news conference by Patrick Ewing, Alonzo
Mourning and Dikembe Mutombo, three National Basketball Association
stars who gained national attention while playing for him. All
three players credit Thompson with shaping their personal lives as
well as their professional careers.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's a great individual, a great man in my eyes,'' Ewing said.
``When I was in school, he was a father figure. We've developed a
great friendship. If there was anything I ever needed, he was
always there.''
</P>
<P>
   Thompson said Mourning ``just offered me the opportunity to come
to his place and lie in the sun.'' ``I said `Fool, you are crazy if
you really think I'm retiring,' '' he recanted. ``I intend to be at
Georgetown University, getting in the way, while I deal with things
I have to deal with.''
</P>
<P>
   In leaving the bench, Thompson walks away from a glorious,
high-profile playing and coaching career. He was a member of two
NBA title teams with the Boston Celtics in the mid-1960s and was a
high school coach before joining Georgetown in 1972, taking a
moribund team and turning it into a national power. In those first
two years, though _ when Georgetown did not finish above .500 and
failed to go to a post-season tournament _ some thought Thompson
should be replaced. Before he went to the lectern to speak Friday,
Thompson hugged Mary Washington, a longtime friend who helped rally
support then.
</P>
<P>
   Thompson hasn't had to worry about job security since. He is 4
wins shy of 600 victories _ a milestone he said didn't matter to
him _ and has a .713 career winning percentage. Georgetown lost the
1982 championship to North Carolina when Michael Jordan hit a
jumper in the final seconds. Two years later, Thompson, with Ewing,
beat Houston and Akeem Olajuwon for the title. The following year,
they again reached the championship game but lost to Villanova.
Thompson was the Olympic coach in 1988, where his team won the
bronze medal, the lowest for the United States in Olympic history.
It was also the last Olympics before professional players
participated.
</P>
<P>
   But Thompson is nearly as well known for his thoughts and
accomplishments as for his trophies. Even though 17 of his players
went on the National Basketball Association, he was more proud that
97 percent of his players who stayed four years earned a degree. He
has long been outspoken about education and opportunities for
minority groups, and in 1989 walked off the floor before a home
game to protest an NCAA rule that toughened criteria under which
students could receive athletic scholarships.
</P>
<P>
   And when asked what the fondest memory of his career is,
Thompson's response had nothing to do with basketball: ``Somebody
walked up to me and told me I wore my blackness well. I thought
that was the biggest compliment I received in my life.''
</P>
<P>
   Mike Jarvis of St. John's, who coached in Thompson's long shadow
at George Washington University until this season, said: ``His
biggest contribution to the game, because of his stature and his
respect _ whether you like him or not _ is that he has brought a
lot of very positive attention to the fact that African-Americans
can be successful head coaches. ``He's made it possible for people
like me to get the opportunity to be a head coach.''
</P>
<P>
   But last season, Georgetown finished 16-15, its worst record
since 1974. This year's team is off to the worst start in the
20-year history of the conference.
</P>
<P>
   In recent years, Thompson has failed to land many of the
brightest prep stars and he has had to endure off-the-court trouble
with players. Point guard Kenny Brunner abruptly left the team in
the middle of last season only to resurface at Fresno State, where
he has had run-ins with the law. And last autumn, a former player,
Kevin Millen, was arrested twice on campus and was charged with
making threats against Thompson.
</P>
<P>
   Thompson insisted that none of the strife played into his
decision, that he, in fact, thrives on adversity. Thompson is said
to have wept when he spoke to his young team Friday morning, but
the normally voluble and emotional coach was dry-eyed during his
announcement. The man who has brought passion _ and a sharp tongue
and wit _ to battles on and off the court seemed very much at
peace.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
