<HEADER>
A5258 &Cx1f; tad-z
u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-IMPEACH-JURORS09-COX     01-08 1019
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-IMPEACH-JURORS09-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    SENATORS AREN'T ACTING LIKE REAL JURORS
 &HT;    740&AMP;add.
 &HT;    By BOB DART
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Larry King, the CNN talk show host, wondered aloud
how senators could sit as jurors in the impeachment trial of
President Clinton when most would be summarily dismissed as too
biased if the case were heard in a criminal courtroom.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's not the same rules,'' explained Sen. Kay Bailey
Hutchinson, R-Texas.
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, the fact that Hutchinson and several other senators were
opining about the case to a nationwide cable TV audience
illustrates just how different senators are from the millions of
jurors who weigh evidence and render verdicts in courthouses across
the nation.
</P>
<P>
   Just imagine a juror in the O.J. Simpson case popping up on CNBC
at the start of the trial to tell Geraldo Rivera that Mark Furhman
shouldn't be allowed to testify. But some senators _ impeachment
jurors _ openly oppose Monica Lewinsky being called as a witness in
the impeachment trial.
</P>
<P>
   ``If a juror in a civil or criminal case went on television and
expressed an opinion, he or she would be promptly removed from the
panel,'' said Bobby Lee Cook, a colorful defense attorney from
Summerville, Ga.
</P>
<P>
   This week, all 100 senators raised their right hands and took an
oath to ``do impartial justice'' in the impeachment trial of
Clinton, only the second such proceeding in the nation's history.
In hearing the impeachment case against President Andrew Johnson in
1868, senators did not have to contend with talk shows, DNA
evidence, a controversial special prosecutor, or C-SPAN.
</P>
<P>
   But those senators were no less political.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is a difference between a criminal trial and an
impeachment trial. Senators are the most unique jurors in the
world,'' said Jonathan Turley, a constitutional law professor at
George Washington University.
</P>
<P>
   Some Democratic senators ``have already announced they would
vote to acquit regardless of evidence presented,'' Turley said.
``Many are appearing regularly on programs to discuss their
thoughts and concerns before trial even begun.''
</P>
<P>
   The differences between senators and regular jurors are stark.
In addition to going on television and expressing opinions,
senators publicly try to influence their colleagues. No juror can
even discuss a case with another juror before the presiding judge
orders deliberations to begin.
</P>
<P>
   Far from being impartial, three newly elected senators have
already voted on impeachment as House members. Republicans Jim
Bunning of Kentucky and Michael Crapo of Idaho voted to impeach
Clinton, while Democrat Charles Schumer of New York voted against
impeachment. Now each will vote again on whether to remove the
president from office. This is akin to a grand juror voting on an
indictment and then on a verdict in the same case.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's also not like a jury in the sense that people will call
us and lobby us. You don't have jurors called and lobbied and
things like that,'' Schumer said on ``Larry King Live.''
</P>
<P>
   Some members of the legal profession bridle at even using
courtroom terminology to describe what they see as a purely
political process unfolding in the Senate chambers.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a sham to call this a trial. None of these people would
be qualified to sit as jurors from either side of the aisle. They'd
all be stricken for cause,'' said Gerry Spence, the buckskin-clad
lawyer from Jackson Hole, Wyo.
</P>
<P>
   A trial judge will ``strike'' or exclude a prospective juror for
having an opinion or having expressed an opinion on case, he
explained.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's like having a murder case and being asked to choose a
jury from a bunch of murderers,'' Spence said. ``Here we have a
perjury case and having a bunch of liars as jurors. As politicians,
they're all liars by virtue of their profession.''
</P>
<P>
   The difference is ``lying under oath, of course,'' Spence said,
but he judged this a distinction without a difference in a purely
political undertaking.
</P>
<P>
   ``Few of these senators would make it through a conventional
jury process,'' agreed Turley.
</P>
<P>
   Sen. Barbara Boxer, D-Calif., is even a member of the extended
presidential family, he noted. Her daughter is married to the first
lady's brother. One juror, Sen. Edward Kennedy, D-Mass., appeared
with the defendant, Clinton, at a political rally as the trial was
getting under way.
</P>
<P>
   ``The framers had no delusions about the Senate,'' Turley said.
``And history has shown that senators have a remarkably checkered
and uninspiring record on impeachment. They've often engaged in raw
partisan voting'' on cases removing judges from office.
</P>
<P>
   (Story can end here. Optional add follows.)
</P>
<P>
   On CNN, the senators defended their ability to be impartial
jurors in the impeachment trial.
</P>
<P>
   ``You can have an opinion as long as in the law it's not a fixed
opinion,'' said Sen. Arlen Specter, R-Pa. ``You have to have an
open mind to listen to the evidence.''
</P>
<P>
   Cook, the Georgia attorney who successfully defended Bert Lance
in a Carter administration scandal, said the Senate chambers cannot
be equated with a courtroom. An impeachment trial ``is a
quasi-judicial proceeding, yes, but also steeped in politics.''
</P>
<P>
   Under the Constitution, ``there is no standard of proof that is
applicable'' beyond a reasonable doubt or preponderance of proof or
whatever, he said.
</P>
<P>
   Senators ``can make their own rules'' to a large extent, he
said. For example, if a majority of senators disagree with the
ruling of the presiding judge Chief Justice of the United States
William Rehnquist _ they can vote to overrule it.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're not just the jurors,'' said Sen. John Kerry, D-Mass.
``We are also judges in this case.''
</P>
<P>
   For most, it will be a unique experience.
</P>
<P>
   ``I have been called for jury duty in Connecticut five or six
times,'' Sen. Joseph Lieberman, D-Conn., told King. ``Each time I
go in, they disqualify me because I am a lawyer and a senator. This
is the first time I have had a chance to be on a jury.''
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
