</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-RUSSIAN-ICEDANCER-ART-$ADV10-2NDTAKE-NYT </SLUG>
  
 NEW YORK: a radiator.''  
<TEXT>
<P>
   But then there is the case of the physician and his wife who
brought a male partner from Russia for their daughter and presented
him with the room and car formerly belonging to her brother, only
to see him leave after a single month with the complaint ``American
girls can't skate.''
</P>
<P>
   ``It was a nightmare,'' said the girl's mother, who spoke on
condition of anonymity. But she rejected the suggestion that she
and her husband had been victimized. ``We just got so caught up in
it,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Leslie Gamez, the team director for the U.S. Figure Skating
Association, said such situations are ``a private matter between
those two individuals.'' The association, the sport's governing
body, does not enter such disputes.
</P>
<P>
   Many parents reject any criticism about their part in the
ice-dance bachelor auction. Typically, they maintain that it is
other families who are taken advantage of, that their daughter's
partner is a hard worker with modest needs. Even when the
partnerships win no medals, some parents say they would do it
again.
</P>
<P>
   Before teaming up with Ariel Williams, Boundoukin was the
partner of Tara Modlin, whose parents, Sherry and Bobby Modlin of
Garden City, provided housing for him for two years in Lake Placid,
shopped for his groceries and covered all his training costs.
</P>
<P>
   ``Everybody I know thought I was nuts,'' said Modlin, who owns a
textile exporting business in Manhattan. He said he used to drive
600 miles round trip, with the family dog, to see his wife and
daughter in Lake Placid on weekends. But he said he has no regrets.
``It cost me a fortune, but I wouldn't give back one minute of
it,'' he said, because Tara ``earned it'' by winning medal after
medal as a novice.
</P>
<P>
   The Modlins had to do more than open their wallets. ``We got
into an adoption situation,'' Mrs. Modlin said. Until Boundoukin
turned 18, the Modlins were his legal guardians so that he and Tara
could compete in the U.S. National Figure Skating Championships.
(He needed an alien-registration card to do so, and their
guardianship ensured that he could get one.)
</P>
<P>
   After finishing last among the junior-level skaters in a field
of 13 at the 1997 nationals, the Modlin-Boundoukin team broke up.
Tara Modlin said there were tensions after an unsuccessful
competitive season capped by a last-minute change of coach and
program.
</P>
<P>
   The family said that there were also romantic problems. ``It was
uncomfortable that his attraction was bigger to me than mine to
him,'' Tara Modlin said. (Boundoukin refused repeated requests for
interviews on his skating career in the United States.)
</P>
<P>
   Her father was relieved. Although he considers Boundoukin ``a
great kid,'' he did not view him as marriage material for his
daughter, who is now 20 and is majoring in sociology at the
University of Pennsylvania. Tara, who no longer skates
competitively, said she misses Dima, as her former partner is
known, but she said he and other Russian skaters in the United
States didn't understand her interest in academics.
</P>
<P>
   ``After a while,'' Modlin said, ``I wanted him to stay away from
my daughter. I wanted her to pay attention to books.''
</P>
<P>
   The Modlins continued to pay Boundoukin's rent for a few months
until he got on his feet, around the time he teamed up with Ariel
Williams.
</P>
<P>
   In interviews last year, Mrs. Williams, Ariel's mother, said the
family at first provided sole support for Boundoukin, but
eventually a group that helps ``promising skaters'' began giving
him support. She later confirmed that the group was the New England
Amateur Skating Foundation.
</P>
<P>
   Herbert Kaplan, the president of the foundation, a charitable
trust based in Providence, R.I., said Boundoukin is one of 100
skaters for whom the foundation raised $600,000 last year.
</P>
<P>
   Ariel's father, Gary Williams, declined to be interviewed, but a
family friend, who called this reporter at what he said was
Williams' behest, said Williams was contributing to the Amateur
Skating Foundation. The friend, who refused to be quoted by name,
would not say how much.
</P>
<P>
   Some people in the sport say that the foundation provides a
funnel for families to give money to skaters while receiving a tax
deduction. For example, Ms. Clayman, the mother of Debbie Koegel,
said she and other relatives pay the nearly $60,000 annual expenses
of Ms. Koegel and Fediukov through the foundation because of the
``tax advantage.''
</P>
<P>
   Kaplan said: ``We support a lot of Russian skaters. I call it my
rent-a-Russian program.'' He said donors cannot earmark checks for
a specific skater (which would threaten the tax deductibility of
their contributions). But he said they can ``suggest'' recipients,
subject to the approval of a three-member foundation committee.
</P>
<P>
   Ninety percent of donations are under $100, he said. He would
not say if larger donations had come in with the suggestion that
they go to Boundoukin. There is ``nothing unusual or untoward''
about the grants to the young man, he said.
</P>
<P>
   Don Roberts, a spokesman in Washington for the Internal Revenue
Service, said the foundation's arrangements appeared to violate no
tax regulations, as long as it remained in control of the funds.
</P>
<P>
   So far, Boundoukin and his partners have not reached the sport's
senior ranks. The Boundoukin-Williams team, scheduled to make its
first important appearance at a regional competition in Florida
last month, withdrew at the last minute after a ``medical
emergency,'' a competition organizer said. They have not registered
for the national championships Feb. 7 to 14 in Salt Lake City.
</P>
<P>
   Within skating, people like to gossip about the Russian
partners, but few raise serious objections. Skating, they say, is
expensive, and the demands of training do not allow for a full-time
job. Dick Button, the two-time Olympic gold medalist and television
skating announcer, said it's ``perfectly fine'' for American
families to support foreign-born skaters.
</P>
<P>
   ``I am only interested in good skating,'' he said. ``I don't
care if the person comes from Boise or Vladivostok.''
</P>
<P>
   Until more American boys discover the joys of a twizzle _ a step
maneuver during a waltz _ the imbalance is not likely to change.
``I keep saying to these little hockey boys, `You know, you could
have a great future in figure skating, and all these girls in your
arms,''' Mrs. Williams said.
</P>
</TEXT>
