<HEADLINE>
CROSSOVER VEHICLES DOMINATES AUTO SHOW 
(FOR RELEASE SUNDAY, JAN. 10) 
</HEADLINE>
   (af)  
 By JAMES G. COBB   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   DETROIT _ One problem with auto makers' headlong rush to
cross-breed sedans, wagons, trucks, vans and four-by-fours is
coming up with ways to categorize the new, hybrid forms they are
creating.
</P>
<P>
   More than a dozen such crossover vehicles made their debuts here
last week at the North American International Auto Show, either as
products soon to be sold, as prototypes of future offerings or as
design studies that may _ or may not _ find their way into
showrooms in some modified form. But even those scrambling to meet
what they perceive as new, unfilled needs in private transportation
seem daunted by the semantics of their creations.
</P>
<P>
   Robert J. Eaton, chairman of DaimlerChrysler, called the
Chrysler PT Cruiser _ a high-roofed small sedan with minivan-style
cargo flexibility and a profile out of the 1930s _ a
``segment-breaker too cool to categorize.'' The car will go on sale
in about a year, starting below $20,000.
</P>
<P>
   Nissan called the design of its SUT. ``a collision of a truck
and a sport utility vehicle'' and its new Xterra sport utility ``a
tough, mobile place for stuff.''
</P>
<P>
   Toyota described its latest small car, the Echo, as having ``low
floor height with a high seating position.''
</P>
<P>
   J. Mays, Ford's vice president for design, called the (My)
Mercury a concept vehicle ``that blurs the boundaries between a
car, a truck and a sport-utility vehicle.'' And when unveiling the
Explorer Sport Trac, a twist on Ford's popular sport utility with a
pickup bed replacing the covered cargo compartment, spokesmen were
reduced to calling it ``not a car-truck, but a truck-truck.''
</P>
<P>
   While these combinations got much of the attention here, the
auto companies have not altogether abandoned the market for
car-cars. Chevrolet showed its 2000 Impala, dusting off one of
America's best-known automotive names for its new flagship, which
will replace the Lumina when it goes on sale next summer.
</P>
<P>
   Likewise, Buick showed its redesigned 2000 LeSabre, which is to
reach the market even sooner, and Lexus announced that it would
import in mid-2000 its IS sport sedan, a competitor to the BMW
3-Series and Audi A4.
</P>
<P>
   Mercedes-Benz showed its all-new S-Class, a trimmed version of
the biggest sedan it makes, while a smaller new Jaguar, the S-Type,
made its American debut.
</P>
<P>
   New small cars included Toyota's Echo, aimed at the
20-somethings Toyota calls the ``Net generation,'' with upgraded
stereos and special CD compartments; DaimlerChrysler's all-new 2000
models of its Dodge and Plymouth Neon, and Ford's Focus, which
replaces the Escort.
</P>
<P>
   Among the few announcements of environmental interest, Honda
said it plans to sell its V V gasoline-electric hybrid, which has
very low emissions and is said to go 70 miles on a gallon of gas,
in the United States. And Ford displayed a working version of a car
that runs on advanced fuel cells that convert hydrogen to energy
with no emissions, though executives acknowledged that a production
version would not come until 2004 at the earliest.
</P>
<P>
   Although nothing on display at Cobo Center generated the buzz
accorded last year to the Volkswagen New Beetle, the car that came
closest to being the show-stopper was a Ford Thunderbird that
captures the flavor of the original T-Birds of 1955-57. The
two-seat roadster has a removable roof, prominent round taillights,
porthole side windows, hooded gauges and a pastel palette. It is
likely to be sold as a 2001 model.
</P>
<P>
   Another name from the mid-50s, the Chevrolet Nomad, was revived
as a sporty retro-style wagon, also resembling a sport utility.
</P>
<P>
   Two European sports cars were also crowd pleasers. The Audi TT,
a post-industrial design with a striking Bauhaus-style interior,
made its American debut; it goes on sale in late spring. And
Mercedes showed its Vision SLR, a design study for a high-style,
super-high-performance sports car that draws on the Formula One
look.
</P>
<P>
   Another design study, from Nissan, capitalized on the nostalgia
for that company's Datsun 240Z sports car of the early 70s. The
updated Z has a similar long-hooded look and was planned to sell
for less than $25,000 _ an amount that Nissan said was equivalent,
after adjusting for inflation, to the price of the original.
</P>
<P>
   Two of the few companies without sport utilities joined the
fray. Hyundai showed a prototype, the Santa Fe, that would compete
with vehicles like the Honda CR-V and Toyota RAV4. And BMW rolled
out its first all-wheel-drive vehicle, the X5, which it insists is
a ``sport activity vehicle'' not intended for off-road use _ a
strategy intended to prevent the cannibalization of sales from its
Land Rover unit. It will be built in South Carolina and reach
market late this year. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
