<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TV-MURDER-REVIEW-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`MURDER IN A SMALL TOWN': A NEW PERSONA FOR GENE WILDER 
</HEADLINE>
  (Eds.: Production notes are at end of review. Time, channel are for
New York area. Check local listings.) 
(lb) 
 By RON WERTHEIMER   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Gene Wilder might seem an unlikely choice to play a quick-witted
sleuth. But that's just the point. Playing winningly against type,
he makes a charming and surprisingly low-key amateur detective in
``Murder in a Small Town,'' a two-hour A&AMP;E movie to be shown
Sunday.
</P>
<P>
   Wilder, the film's co-writer as well as its star, plays Cash
Carter, a successful Broadway director. (Variety gave him the
nickname Cash because of his string of moneymaking hits.) This is
1938, and he has retreated to Stamford, Conn., to run a local
theater troupe and try to get over the murder of his beloved wife.
</P>
<P>
   The secret to Carter's success as a director is his insight into
the human mind, especially the criminal variety. Guiding an actor
through a melodrama, the mop-haired Cash declares that killers have
``this psychopathic juice that flows through their blood.''
</P>
<P>
   What does that mean? Who cares? The look in those familiar
saucer eyes says he's talking from the heart. And the viewer who
engages his own heart and lets his brain idle in low gear will
enjoy the ride.
</P>
<P>
   Clearly the main order of business is establishing characters
who might return in other mysteries. So here is Cash's pal Lt. Tony
Rossini (Mike Starr), a sweet lug of a cop who tries to show his
affection for Cash with clumsy attempts to use a little Yiddish.
(See, Cash is Jewish. The family name was once Kartofsky.)
</P>
<P>
   To Tony, the solution to each investigation lies inside an
imaginary jar, and he tells Cash, ``You got a special way of
opening up that jar.'' He does, too.
</P>
<P>
   Cash also has a bright, levelheaded college-student daughter,
Sophie (Elisabeth Rosen), who tells him to move on with his life
and marry his girlfriend, Mimi (the splendid stage actress Cherry
Jones). When Ms. Jones and Wilder are on screen together, they
project a sense of goofy fun that spritzes a whiff of '30s
screwball comedy.
</P>
<P>
   You won't confuse this trifle with the works of Sturges or
Capra. But when Wilder, complete with concertina, serenades Ms.
Jones outside her window with a chorus of Rodgers and Hart's
``Mimi,'' and she gazes out at him with an expression of childlike
delight, you may find yourself grinning nearly as widely as they
are.
</P>
<P>
   What's that you say? The plot? Well, here things are back in the
realm of contemporary television, Jessica Fletcher-Lt. Columbo
Division. There's this terrible man. He's unspeakably mean to
everybody: the wife, the son, the secretary; yes, even the butler.
Then somebody kills the terrible man, and Cash figures out who.
</P>
<P>
   The story may not keep you guessing, but the film (the script's
other writer is Gilbert Pearlman; the director is Joyce Chopra)
serves as a warm introduction to Cash and his circle. And the
production, designed by Harold Thrasher, has enough period touches,
like the vintage cars and a garish Chinese restaurant interior, to
reward a close look.
</P>
<P>
   Wilder, who has sanded the edges off his usual lunatic persona,
has created an endearing hero: a little smart, a little nutsy, a
little too good to be true. And just winning enough to be invited
back.
</P>
<P>
   PRODUCTION NOTES:
</P>
<P>
   `MURDER IN A SMALL TOWN'
</P>
<P>
   8 p.m. ET Sunday on A&AMP;E
</P>
<P>
   Directed by Joyce Chopra; written by Gilbert Pearlman and Gene
Wilder; cinematography by Bruce Surtees; edited by Peter C. Frank;
production design by Harold Thrasher; costumes by Martha Mann;
original music by John Morris; produced by Fred Berner, Craig
McNeil and Steven Paul. A production of the A&AMP;E Network and Granada
Productions, in association with Fred Berner Films and Crystal Sky
Communications.
</P>
<P>
   With: Gene Wilder (Cash Carter), Mike Starr (Tony Rossini),
Terry O'Quinn (Sidney Lassiter), Cherry Jones (Mimi), Frances
Conroy (Martha Lassiter), Deirdre O'Connell (Kate Faxton), Ebon
Moss-Bachrach (Billy) and Elisabeth Rosen (Sophie Carter).
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
