u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-TV-PURGATORY-REVIEW-N     01-08 0861
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TV-PURGATORY-REVIEW-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`PURGATORY': SPEAKS SOFTLY, CARRIES NO GUN BUT PACKS A GREAT
WALLOP 
</HEADLINE>
   (Eds.: Production notes are at end of review. Time, channel are for
New York area. Check local listings.)  
 (bl)  
 By ANITA GATES   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Very few men can stand quietly in the middle of an empty street
with the authority and the tough, soft-spoken sexiness of Sam
Shepard. And the TNT movie ``Purgatory'' is Shepard's best
opportunity since he played Chuck Yeager in ``The Right Stuff'' 16
years ago to show that off.
</P>
<P>
   Shepard's character, Sheriff Forest (who turns out to be someone
far more famous), has something in common with Bill Munny, played
by Clint Eastwood in the Oscar-winning film ``Unforgiven.'' He is a
gunslinger, a really good one, who put down his weapons years ago
and became a peaceful, God-fearing man. When a situation arises
that may lead him to strap on his holster again, his decision feels
momentous. And in ``Purgatory,'' a fascinating, deceptively dark
western with more than a touch of ``The Twilight Zone,'' it is.
</P>
<P>
   As the local doctor (Randy Quaid) tells a newcomer, explaining a
fact of life in the little town of Refuge, ``A few bad choices, and
a man could lose his soul.''
</P>
<P>
   The story begins when a gang of bank robbers on the run happen
upon Refuge, an idyllic spot in a green valley bathed in golden
light. They decide to stop and stay a while, especially when the
sheriff tells them that all their drinks, their hotel rooms and the
care of their horses are free. All that is asked of them is that
they not use profanity.
</P>
<P>
   The outlaws, led by Blackjack (Eric Roberts, looking
convincingly scruffy), aren't particularly bright, so none of this
strikes them as strange. Only the young, otherwise naive Sonny
(Brad Rowe, last seen as the blond hunk in ``Billy's Hollywood
Screen Kiss''), who was talked into joining the gang by his rotten
uncle, is suspicious.
</P>
<P>
   Sonny is the only one who notices that the mild-mannered
storekeeper looks a lot like Jesse James. In fact, various
townspeople look exactly like Wild Bill Hickok, Billy the Kid and
Doc Holliday (as seen in the dime novels Sonny reads), but of
course they can't be who they look like, because all those famous
gunslingers are dead.
</P>
<P>
   Slowly, with mistaken impressions along the way, Sonny figures
out what this place really is. Gordon Dawson's script makes the
process satisfying despite the fact that any viewer who has noticed
the title of the film knows the answer from the beginning. When the
gang's rowdiness gets out of hand, Sonny is appalled that the
townspeople won't defend themselves.
</P>
<P>
   Spurred by new-found love for Rose (Amelia Heinle), a radiantly
beautiful young woman with rope burns around her neck, he decides
to fight back against the guys he rode in with. This leads the
sheriff, the deputy (Donnie Wahlberg), the doctor and the
storekeeper to reconsider their anti-gun stance. Which leads one of
the bad guys to look around at the carnage and observe, ``I guess
they ain't Mennonites'' after all. The shootout, which is
thrilling, goes on a little too long, but don't they all?
</P>
<P>
   ``Purgatory'' has a curious morality. For most of its length,
the film manages to make churchgoing and a determined pacifism look
like the manly, more difficult choices. But then it has the nerve
to make the old-fashioned western shootout exciting again.
</P>
<P>
   Members of the National Rifle Association who watch the film
will probably conclude that God wants everyone to buy and practice
using firearms. Others, it is hoped, we will realize that what
works dramatically would almost certainly be a disaster in real
life.
</P>
<P>
   The film will probably lose a lot of viewers during the first
half-hour, most of which could be from any western, with a bank
robbery, a posse and lots of horses' hooves in the dust. On the
other hand, a lot of fans of the traditional western are going to
be scratching their heads later when bad guys start getting struck
by strangely purposeful lightning and when the town's church bells,
which should be high and clear, start booming ominously like Big
Ben.
</P>
<P>
   Uli Edel, the director, best known for ``Last Exit to
Brooklyn,'' once directed episodes of ``Twin Peaks'' and ``Tales
From the Crypt.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Purgatory'' admirably resists the sentimentality of angelic
voices and diffused heavenly light, at least until the very last
scene; by then even God, it appears, has turned into an old softie.
``The Creator may be tough,'' says the craggy stagecoach driver,
who may be some sort of afterlife courier, ``but he ain't blind.''
</P>
<P>
   PRODUCTION NOTES:
</P>
<P>
   `PURGATORY'
</P>
<P>
   TNT, Sunday night at 8
</P>
<P>
   Written by Gordon Dawson and directed by Uli Edel;
cinematography by William Wages; edited by Mark Conte; Stephen
Marsh, production designer; music by Brad Fiedel; David A.
Rosemont, executive producer; Daniel Schneider and Dawson,
producers. A production of Turner Network Television.
</P>
<P>
   CAST: Sam Shepard (Sheriff Forest), Eric Roberts (Blackjack),
Randy Quaid (Doc Woods), Peter Stormare (Cavin), Brad Rowe (Sonny),
Donnie Wahlburg (Deputy Glen) and Amelia Heinle (Rose).
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
