u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-MARKETS-ASIA-600&AMP;ADD-     01-08 0982
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MARKETS-ASIA-600&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ASIAN MARKETS SETTLE DOWN AFTER A DIZZYING WEEK 
</HEADLINE>
  (Eds: See also MARKET) 
(mk) 
 By MARK LANDLER   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   HONG KONG _ The bulls finally stopped stampeding across Asia
Friday, after a week of powerful gains in stock markets from Seoul
to Singapore. Analysts seemed almost relieved, since many were
alarmed by the growing disparity between the rising markets and
Asia's still-sinking economies.
</P>
<P>
   Several experts here worry that the region could face a jolting
retrenchment when investors eventually stop for a reality check.
</P>
<P>
   ``We certainly don't think this rally will extend beyond the
second quarter,'' said Michael Sargent, head of Asia-Pacific equity
research at Salomon Smith Barney in Hong Kong. ``Asia hasn't had
its day of reckoning yet.''
</P>
<P>
   On Friday, stock markets here registered a mixture of modest
gains and losses. The relative calm came after a dizzying week in
which investors behaved as though the Asian crisis was a memory.
Emboldened by record-setting gains in the United States and a
stronger Japanese yen, they poured money into shares in Hong Kong,
Seoul, Jakarta, Singapore, Taipei and Manila.
</P>
<P>
   In Tokyo, the Nikkei index declined by 1.1 percent Friday, the
second consecutive day of losses. Some analysts said the retreat
reflected a recognition that the region's markets were out of sync
with the underlying economies.
</P>
<P>
   In most of Asia, investors have barely paused to catch their
breath since shares first began moving up in September. The
region's markets have sustained the rally in the face of a
relentless stream of dismal economic news, a situation that has
left economists and portfolio managers here baffled.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm really ready to throw in the towel and say, `Nothing
matters anymore but positive investor sentiment,''' said Mac
Overton, a portfolio manager at MBF Unit Trust in Hong Kong. ``The
stock market has continued to increase despite three straight
quarters of lower corporate earnings.''
</P>
<P>
   Overton noted that in Hong Kong, the Hang Seng index rose even
after China issued an unexpectedly bleak prognosis for its economy
in 1999. The Chinese government said lackluster demand would weaken
its domestic economy, while the regional crisis would cause its
exports to falter.
</P>
<P>
   ``The negative implications of these problems for this year's
economic performance should not be underestimated,'' the government
said.
</P>
<P>
   How did Hong Kong, which depends so heavily on China, react to
the warning? Investors drove the Hang Seng 4.5 percent higher on
Thursday and a further three-tenths of a percent Friday. Analysts
said shareholders disregarded the news from China and instead
pinned their hopes on a cut in local interest rates.
</P>
<P>
   After trading ended Friday, the Hong Kong Association of Banks
announced that it would lower its benchmark short-term savings
deposit rate to 4 percent from 4.25 percent. Some analysts said the
announcement might disappoint investors, who had been expecting a
deeper reduction.
</P>
<P>
   In Jakarta, investors were distracted from Indonesia's
continuing economic calamity by a new state budget proposed by
President B.J. Habibie. Unlike previous budgets, Habibie's
proposal, economists said, represented a realistic plan to deal
with Indonesia's stagnant economy, spiraling inflation and weak
currency.
</P>
<P>
   Beyond these local factors, experts noted that Asia's stock
markets were now largely propelled by such external forces as rate
cuts by the Federal Reserve in the United States and the
strengthening Japanese yen.
</P>
<P>
   ``The turnaround of the yen has been a big help for the rest of
Asia,'' said Dong Tao, a regional strategist at Credit Suisse First
Boston in Hong Kong. ``It has reduced the risk of currency
volatility in the rest of Asia, which has allowed markets like Hong
Kong to cut their own interest rates.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Yet some analysts wonder how much more Asian countries can rely
on rate cuts to jump-start their economies. In the last three
months, Hong Kong has cut rates five times, Singapore three times
and Thailand more than a dozen times. Even with low rates in
Thailand, economists said the government had not been able to
re-ignite consumer demand or corporate investment.
</P>
<P>
   Moreover, many experts doubt that the Japanese yen will maintain
its strength. The yen has been bolstered in recent days by the
introduction of the euro, which has diverted some investment
capital from the United States to Europe. Late Friday, the yen
traded at roughly 110 yen to the dollar. That makes the yen about
30 percent more valuable than in early August, when it traded at a
nearly eight-year low of 147.66.
</P>
<P>
   But Sargent predicted that as the novelty of the euro wore off _
and the extent of Japan's economic ills re-emerged _ the yen would
resume its downward spiral, reaching 140 to the dollar by late
summer.
</P>
<P>
   To some experts, the most damaging potential side effect of the
rally is that it could breed complacency on the part of Asian
governments, prompting them to delay or scrap needed economic
changes.
</P>
<P>
   ``Legislators and decision-makers may conclude that they don't
have to act,'' said Jim Walker, chief economist of CLSA Global
Emerging Markets in Edinburgh. ``People could start to think the
stock market is a precursor to a genuine recovery, and that's just
wrong.''
</P>
<P>
   Walker noted that the Japanese stock market experienced a
similar rebound after Japan's economic collapse in 1989 and 1990.
Several months later, after Tokyo failed to deal with the country's
growing financial crisis, the Nikkei reversed and plunged to new
lows.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're into uncharted waters here because Japan was running
huge budget surpluses before its crisis,'' Walker said. ``I don't
think the clock will keep ticking as long for the rest of Asia as
it did for Japan.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
