<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-EPISODES-DANCE-REVIEW-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`EPISODES': ALIENATION AND BEAUTY IN BALANCHINE WORK 
</HEADLINE>
  (lb) 
 By ANNA KISSELGOFF   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ For all their focus on bare movement in time and
space, George Balanchine's most experimental ballets are metaphors
for human existence. How to get through the day might be the
subliminal theme of ``Episodes,'' which Balanchine choreographed in
1959 to orchestral music by Webern.
</P>
<P>
   Revived by the New York City Ballet on Thursday night as part of
its weeklong ``Balanchine Black and White Celebration,''
``Episodes'' stands out by its strangeness even among Balanchine's
most daring works to 20th-century music.
</P>
<P>
   The choreography is unusually spare. Steps are frequently
inverted (hip and knees turned in, feet flexed) but not embroidered
upon. Ingeniously, Balanchine often choreographs in the spaces
between Webern's notes.
</P>
<P>
   There is a quaint sense of 1950s alienation and yet there is
also a gloomy beauty about the ballet. The flesh-and-bones images
of dancers in black leotards or tights eventually yield to a
spiritual respite: a stylized court dance performed to Webern's
well-known orchestration of the ``Ricercata'' section of Bach's
``Musical Offering.''
</P>
<P>
   The ``Black and White'' series may suggest old wine in new
bottles, but it has an artistic justification. The Balanchine
ballets, with one exception, are all danced in leotards and tunics,
but even those set to Bach, like ``Concerto Barocco,'' share the
same concentration on purity of movement.
</P>
<P>
   Balanchine here is the link between Bach and Webern's view of
Bach. By juxtaposing these leotard ballets in one series, Peter
Martins, City Ballet's artistic director, has made some useful
aesthetic connections.
</P>
<P>
   One is that Balanchine soon dropped the artificiality of
``Episodes.'' The quirkiness of the choreography was absorbed into
his mainstream vocabulary. Nonetheless, the performance on Thursday
was always polished.
</P>
<P>
   Miranda Weese and Philip Neal focused on hinged joints, leading
the ensemble in the brave new world of ``Symphony No. 21.'' Their
robotic, streamlined precision gave way to angst, wittily rendered
with acrobatic flair by Helene Alexopoulos and Charles Askegard in
``Five Pieces.''
</P>
<P>
   Albert Evans and Wendy Whelan looked suitably trapped, outlining
the convolutions of ``Concerto'' with clarity. They were aided by
Amanda Edge, Andrea Hecker, Carrie Lee Riggins and Jennifer
Tinsley. As for ``Ricercata,'' Darci Kistler and Jock Soto led the
female ensemble with measured grandeur.
</P>
<P>
   Hugo Fiorato conducted the program, which included ``Apollo,''
in which Nilas Martins, substituting for Peter Boal, and Yvonne
Borree were listless. But Jennie Somogyi, in a technically perfect
debut as the muse Polyhymnia, and Pascale van Kipnis as Calliope,
offered a welcome energy. Danced in tutus (the exception),
``Symphony in C'' nonetheless sported black and white costumes. The
company gave it the same commitment as on opening night in
November.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
