A5270 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-MEHLDAU-MUSIC-REVIEW-     01-08 0364
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MEHLDAU-MUSIC-REVIEW-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BRAD MEHLDAU: IMPROVISATION WITH RAPTURE AND OBSESSION 
</HEADLINE>
  (lb) 
 By PETER WATROUS   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Toward the end of his first set on Tuesday night at
the Village Vanguard, the pianist Brad Mehldau played his ``London
Blues,'' and the best aspects of his music made themselves clear.
</P>
<P>
   Mehldau can be obsessive when he improvises, stubbornly
repeating phrases, and he did just that; then he slowed the
repeated idea down, letting it jut out against the swing of the
band like a rock in the current of a river. The band slowed down,
picked up his rhythmic ideas and then was on its way.
</P>
<P>
   Mehldau's obsessions make his music tense. Throughout the set,
he took figures and mulled them over, placing them in different
registers or slowing them down or speeding them up. Sometimes he
made an idea into a sequence, but mostly he pushed it against the
sound of the trio.
</P>
<P>
   At its best, Mehldau's trio is an exceptional instrument, fluid
and graceful and fully improvising. The three musicians, Larry
Grenadier on bass and Jorge Rossy on drums, along with Mehldau, can
work at three different tempos at once, or come together in deep
swing. Rossy is responsible for much of the group's color, and he
spent a good portion of the night changing tempos behind Mehldau's
improvisations.
</P>
<P>
   Where jazz musicians traditionally are adept at doubling or
halving tempos, Mehldau and the band were working every angle of
time. And Rossy changed the density of the sound, filling up space,
or letting clarity ring. But Mehldau wasn't content to improvise
that way; he was after a different type of romanticism, and on at
least half of the material he dug deeply into the tranquillity of
an early version of the Bill Evans trio.
</P>
<P>
   Mehldau, who has strong foundations in classical music, brought
chord movements and ideas, and a classical articulation, to
ballads. With his eyes closed, his head drooping toward the
keyboard, he seemed to be in deep rapture; that the music became
static and unswinging at times didn't seem to bother him, or the
appreciative audience. (Mehldau will be performing through Sunday.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
