<SLUG> BC-CLINTON-ECONOMY-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CLINTON TOUTS THRIVING ECONOMY 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By NANCY MATHIS 
c.1998 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   DETROIT _ Leaving behind his impeachment woes, President Clinton
came to a snowy Motor City on Friday to highlight a thriving
national economy he touted as the longest in peacetime history.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton called attention to the very issue that may be keeping
his approval rating at record highs despite his impeachment by the
House and a pending trial in the Senate for perjury and obstruction
of justice, a by-product of his affair with former White House
intern Monica Lewinsky.
</P>
<P>
   ``We gather today at a time of an American economic
renaissance,'' Clinton told nearly 2,000 members and guests at the
Economic Club of Detroit.
</P>
<P>
   The president hailed an estimate by his economic advisers that
December will mark the 93rd month of the current economic
expansion, surpassing the 92-month peacetime record set under the
Reagan-Bush administrations. And, he announced new unemployment
figures showing a 4.3 percent jobless rate for December and an
average annual rate of 4.5 percent for 1998, the lowest in 29
years.
</P>
<P>
   Although Clinton never mentioned his political woes or the
pending Senate trial, congressional Democrats here helped stage a
pep rally outside Cobo Center where the president also toured the
North American International Auto Show.
</P>
<P>
   ``Leave Bill alone,'' chanted scores of Clinton supporters as
Michigan Democrats John Conyers, the ranking member of the House
Judiciary Committee, David Bonior, the House minority whip, and
John Dingell, the ranking member of the House Commerce Committee,
condemned Republicans for partisanship.
</P>
<P>
   ``The president has not committed any impeachable offense,''
Dingell contended. ``On the important issues that people are
concerned about the president is right. You are right in supporting
the president. Let's get down to the nation's business and let's
stop that silly charade in the Senate.''
</P>
<P>
   A smaller group of anti-Clinton protesters gathered across the
street calling for the president to resign.
</P>
<P>
   Joe Lockhart, the president's press secretary, said Clinton
watched none of the Senate rituals this week as its members
prepared for trial. ``The president obviously understands what's
going on in the Senate. It's in the hands of the Senate. He's
focusing on his agenda,'' Lockhart said.
</P>
<P>
   Before the Economic Club, only Detroit Mayor Dennis Archer,
recently named by Clinton as a co-chairman of the national
Democratic Party, referred to the ``challenges'' in Washington
facing the president.
</P>
<P>
   ``In view of the political challenges facing the president in
Washington, some wonder why his popularity remains so high among
average Americans, those of us here in the heartland. In Detroit,
it's no mystery. We respect and appreciate a president whose
policies put people first,'' Archer said as he introduced the
president.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton used the Economic Club forum to showcase his
administration's economic policy, which he said helped create ``the
longest economic expansion in peacetime in the history of the
United States.'' The ``peacetime'' caveat excludes the nation's
longest economic expansion, which was 1961 through 1969 during the
Vietnam War.
</P>
<P>
   ``Equally important to me, this one is different from the ones
of the last several years. It is inclusive, not exclusive,''
Clinton said. He pointed to the highest real wage growth in two
decades, the lowest jobless rates for blacks and Hispanics since
1972 and an average family income increase of $3,500.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is a rising tide that is lifting all boats,'' Clinton
said.
</P>
<P>
   But Clinton also cautioned against complacency. He said the
nation must deal with the challenges of a global economy, and
protect surpluses in order to reform Social Security, invest in
education and training programs and boost long-term health care.
</P>
<P>
   ``The main idea I want to leave you with is that the temptation
to rest on our laurels and relax because times are good must be
resisted. We will never have, in all probability, in the lifetime
of the people in this room, a better opportunity to take the long
view, to imagine how our children will live when they're our age,
to imagine how our grandchildren will live when they are our age.
These are the challenges we should be dealing with today,'' Clinton
said.
</P>
<P>
   William Halling, club president, also read written questions,
none of which referred to Clinton's political problems, but the
president turned wistful as Halling read a question from a child
asking who is the most interesting person Clinton has met.
</P>
<P>
   The answer, said Clinton, was Nelson Mandela, the South African
jailed for 27 years by the apartheid regime and freed to become the
nation's first black president. ``I don't know another human being
that suffered so much for so long and came out so much stronger and
richer and deeper than (when) he went into his period of
suffering,'' Clinton said.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton often cites Mandela, who befriended his former captors,
as his inspiration for learning how not to hate his own political
enemies.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
