<TEXT>
<P>
   Here are the stories that New York Times editors are planning
for the Page 1 of Saturday, Jan. 9. The N.Y. Times News Service
supervisor is Henry Louis Warnken. The final FRONTPAGE will move
later in the evening.
</P>
<P>
   For copy info: (888) 346-9867.
</P>
<P>
   For graphics, map, photo info: (888) 603-1036.
</P>
<P>
   IMPEACH (Washington) _ Senate Republicans and Democrats reached
agreement in an extraordinary meeting on Friday to resume Clinton's
impeachment trial next week while leaving open the question of
witnesses. By Alison Mitchell.
</P>
<P>
   IMPEACH-ASSESS (Washington) _ Bipartisan, for now. How the
Senate rules and traditions invite the sort of agreement reached
today but leave any deal fragile because of another tradition: of
power to the individual. By Adam Clymer.
</P>
<P>
   EMBASSY-BOMBS (Washington) _ A close examination of events in
the year before the terrorist assault on the Kenya embassy, based
on interviews with officials throughout the U.S. government, shows
that concerns about embassy security were more intense, more
well-founded, more specific, and more forcefully expressed than has
previously been known. By James Risen and Benjamin Weiser.
</P>
<P>
   ECON-REPORT (Undated) _ The economy added more jobs than
expected in December and the unemployment rate fell, tying a
28-year low. Payrolls increased by 378,000 jobs last month, well
above analysts' forecasts. The unemployment rate declined to 4.3
percent in December from 4.4 percent in November. By Sylvia Nasar.
</P>
<P>
   (With graphics.)
</P>
<P>
   OLY-BRIBERY (Salt Lake City) _ The president and vice president
of the Salt Lake City Olympic committee, Frank Joklik and Dave
Johnson resign as the result of the continuing investigations into
the gifts and cash payments now linked to Salt Lake's winning bid
for the 2002 Winter Olympics. By Jere Longman.
</P>
<P>
   NY-READING-TEST (New York) _ A look at New York state's new
fourth-grade English exam, known in elementary schools simply as
The Test, which is to be given for the first time next week. Unlike
other standardized tests, this one, aside from traditional
multiple-choice questions, requires students to take notes on
passages and write critiques and personal essays based on what they
heard. New York City may start using next year to determine whether
children should be held back a grade. Results may also determine if
a school is placed on the state's list of failing schools.
</P>
<P>
   (With graphic.)
</P>
</TEXT>
