<SLUG> BC-WORKING-COLUMN-$ADV10-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THE PROMOTION THAT WASN'T  
 (FOR RELEASE SUNDAY, JAN. 10) 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Attn: Wis., Tenn.)   (af)  
 By MICHELLE COTTLE   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Q. (italics)I am an engineer at a manufacturing company. When a
resignation opened up a manager's job, I held up my hand. A slate
of candidates was evaluated, and I was told that the job was mine.
At the last hour, however, the outgoing manager had a change of
heart about leaving _ and the company let him stay. I got an
apology and some vague promises about future opportunities. My
mentor's advice is to get out as soon as I can, reasoning that
these people can't be trusted. But a job change would require
relocating, which I would rather avoid. I was satisfied with the
company until this happened, and I'm tempted to use the situation
as an excuse to ask for a raise.(end italics) &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   A. Easy there. You clearly have had a roller-coaster month, and
you don't want to do anything rash while your head is still
spinning.
</P>
<P>
   First, do not assume that yours is a uniquely horrible setback
perpetrated by an insidious management. ``There isn't a month that
goes by that I don't hear of a similar incident,'' said Thomas J.
Wiltzius, chief executive of Career Development Group in Appleton,
Wis. ``Your employer's decision should not be taken as a lack of
confidence or an act of bad faith.'' By offering you the promotion,
the company has made it clear that it values your contribution,
Wiltzius said. In this case, he added, the organization simply
found it wiser to retain the existing manager.
</P>
<P>
   Just because this situation turned out badly for you does not
mean that your employer made a bad decision, agreed Bruce Barry, an
associate professor of management at Vanderbilt University in
Nashville. After all, he asked, do you really think the company
should slam the door in the outgoing manager's face? ``I would
rather work for a company that tries to keep its people and that
lets somebody change his mind than a company that doesn't,'' Barry
said. ``The fact is that people make mistakes.''
</P>
<P>
   Of course, appreciating the big picture does not necessarily
make you feel any better _ a fact that your employer needs to
grasp. You had ``a big opportunity just snatched away,'' Barry
said, and the question is how well you are being treated in light
of that. He suggested sitting down with whoever made this decision
and explaining (in a reasoned way, of course, and without whining)
how deflating this experience has been. ``Help them to understand
your situation,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Angling for a bump in salary may not be smart. ``If what you
really wanted is opportunity, don't negotiate for money,'' Barry
said. ``Going for the money could make you a little more satisfied
in the short run but have unintended negative consequences. Others
might say, `All he really wanted was more money.' '' This could
ruin your chances for future promotions.
</P>
<P>
   Taking the magnanimous route, Wiltzius said, is the better
approach. ``Thank management for the vote of confidence and extend
a sympathetic response to them, reflecting that you understand it
was difficult for them to make this choice,'' he said. And make
sure to emphasize your continued interest in advancing into
management.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
