<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-01-08 18:32 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5317 &Cx1f; ttj-z
r l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-HELOISE-2TAKES-HNS &LR;      01-08 0915
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HELOISE-2TAKES-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HELOISE MOVES FORWARD WITH THE INFORMATION AGE 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (For release Sunday, Jan. 10.)   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By ROY BRAGG  
 c.1999 San Antonio Express-News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN ANTONIO _ It's a weekday afternoon and the best-known name
in American housekeeping isn't doing any.
</P>
<P>
   Instead, Heloise is hunkered down at a computer, answering a
questions from inquiring minds on the Internet.
</P>
<P>
   This is a day set aside for Heloise's monthly online chat. As
she nibbles on a piece of pizza, there's a question about
carving-knife maintenance.
</P>
<P>
   Heloise is quick with the answer _ hand-wash it, sharpen it on a
whetstone, and if it's stored in a countertop knife holder, store
it upside down so the blade won't be dulled by rubbing against the
holder's surface.
</P>
<P>
   If this kind of advice seems insignificant to you, you've
probably got a maid, mom or spouse picking up after you.
</P>
<P>
   But if you are your own domestic, you listen to this woman.
</P>
<P>
   Heloise's hints have made her a global, multimedia entity.
</P>
<P>
   At 47, she is an icon, a part of our collective consciousness.
She is identifiable by a single name, just like Cher and Madonna,
and that name is synonymous with household hints.
</P>
<P>
   But there's more here than just great advice. Heloise has
established herself as a savvy, self-assured executive who knows
her customers and her business better than a lot of captains of
industry claim to know theirs.
</P>
<P>
   These helpful hints don't come off the top of Heloise's head.
</P>
<P>
   She gets up to 3,000 letters, faxes and e-mails a week. Some
have questions, others have hints that end up in the column.
</P>
<P>
   Heloise has a staff of five who work in a specially built suite
of offices in the corner of her home in San Antonio.
</P>
<P>
   She and her posse thoroughly test each hint in her kitchen. Each
idea is checked with state, federal, public and private consumer
and safety experts to make sure they don't contain a hidden faux
pas, says staff member Angie Dolgener.
</P>
<P>
   She's in your paper, sometimes in two different sections, every
day of the year. She's being beamed to your television set on a
regular basis. She's there every month on the magazine rack. She's
way up there on the bookshelf, too.
</P>
<P>
   Two dozen times a year, she appears in person at conventions
around the country. And now she's floating on the bandwidth of the
Internet.
</P>
<P>
   And here's the best part.
</P>
<P>
   Those hints intended to make home drudgery go easier _ vinegar
for stains, coffee grounds for odors, boric acid for roaches? They
all work as promised.
</P>
<P>
   And they've worked for a long, long time. Next month marks the
40th anniversary for the Hints from Heloise column, started by her
mother at the family's kitchen table in 1959.
</P>
<P>
   Heloise the mom wrote the column until her death in 1977.
Heloise the daughter has been writing it for 21 years, which means
she's been doing it longer.
</P>
<P>
   Hints from Heloise runs in 500 newspapers in 21 nations, says
Ted Hannah, advertising director for King Feature Syndicate, which
distributes the column.
</P>
<P>
   Her eight books have sold more than 4.5 million copies. She is
the lead columnist in venerable Good Housekeeping magazine.
</P>
<P>
   She makes regular appearances on network and cable televisions
shows, including several pet-oriented hints on the series
``Petsburgh U.S.A,'' which is airing over the winter on the Animal
Planet cable network.
</P>
<P>
   And then there's the monthly Internet chat, hosted by HomeArts,
a women's lifestyle Web site.
</P>
<P>
   Besides the knife inquiry and a few questions about spills, the
November online chat eventually strayed into the areas of
Thanksgiving etiquette and manners.
</P>
<P>
   When's the best time to serve dinner? How do you handle seating
arrangements? What do you bring when invited to dinner?
</P>
<P>
   These kinds of questions aren't on Heloise's home turf. But the
chatters looked to her for answers.
</P>
<P>
   Susan Bischoff, a Houston Chronicle assistant managing editor
and a Heloise friend, says that's because people treat the
silver-haired columnist as a close friend.
</P>
<P>
   How close?
</P>
<P>
   ``They feel like they know her so well that she gets cards and
letters and calls all the time from people (suggesting that she)
dye her hair,'' Bischoff says.
</P>
<P>
   A publicity photo of the original Heloise, which appeared in a
1963 issue of Saturday Evening Post, shows the way she connected
with her audience.
</P>
<P>
   Instead of the muted lighting and simulated perfection preached
by Martha Stewart, Heloise has always played to the masses.
</P>
<P>
   In the photo, the columnist is pictured as a figure of domestic
mythology _ six arms, each wielding some implement of homemaking,
such as a frying pan, iron, etc.
</P>
<P>
   King Features _ owned by Hearst Corp., which also owns the
Express-News _ is considering an update of the photo for a January
publicity campaign to mark the column's 40th anniversary.
</P>
<P>
   In it, today's Heloise will be wielding modern American
household necessities _ cellular phone and computer mouse, for
example _ as well as some old standard kitchen items.
</P>
<P>
   This, Heloise explains, shows how American life _ and her job _
have changed.
</P>
<P>
   ``This isn't 1950,'' she says. ``I'm not Donna Reed. What I do
is for everyone.''
</P>
<P>
   Any discussion of Heloise has to address the line of succession
and the name.
</P>
<P>
   First, her real name is Ponce Cruse Evans, married to plumbing
contractor David Evans for nearly 18 years.
</P>
<P>
   Heloise wasn't even her mom's real name.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; (MORE ... MORE)
</P>
<P>
   ``She was Eloise,'' she says of her mom. ``When they went to
King Features, they decided it would work better with an H. They
liked the alliteration.''
</P>
<P>
   The Hints From Heloise column began in the suburbs of Honolulu.
</P>
<P>
   Heloise's mom, married to a U.S. Air Force officer and living in
Hawaii in the late '50s, would gather with other military wives on
a regular basis and trade household ideas.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is what they did in the '50s,'' she says. ``Men went off
to work and the women stayed home, got together and traded ideas.''
</P>
<P>
   Her mom originally wanted to do a newsletter for her
neighborhood, but then she went to a farewell party for a retiring
general.
</P>
<P>
   She mentioned her ``helpful hints'' idea to the retiree, who
ridiculed the idea: ``You're just a housewife,'' were his damning
words that day.
</P>
<P>
   Soon afterward, Heloise says, her mom was pitching the idea to
the editor of the Honolulu Advertiser, who liked it and gave her a
shot in print.
</P>
<P>
   The column took off, expanding to a full-time business with a
research staff. Daughter Heloise was taken under her wing and
slowly learned the ropes, working during summer vacations.
</P>
<P>
   She studied math and business at Southwest Texas State
University and planned to teach after graduation, but when her
mother's health began slipping, she got back into the business.
</P>
<P>
   By the time the younger Heloise took over the column, the family
business was at a crucial point.
</P>
<P>
   ``Her mother was very smart to put her into it,'' says King
Features' Hannah. ``She introduced her in the column as Heloise II.
When Ponce took over, there was absolutely no loss of clients.
There was a smooth transition because readers had been introduced
to her. The column had a family feel to it.''
</P>
<P>
   The late 1970s were the dawn of the Information Age. Computers
were on the horizon and cable television had just come to town in
much of America.
</P>
<P>
   ``Not only did she have to take over the column, she had to
think about how she would market the column,'' Hannah says.
</P>
<P>
   The original Heloise, despite her incredible popularity, didn't
like doing television. Sure, she'd color her hair to match a dress,
but personal appearances weren't her strong suit, say Hannah and
the younger Heloise.
</P>
<P>
   ``In those days, that wasn't all that important,'' Hannah said.
``But about the time when Ponce took over, the marketing of the
column became important. Ponce had to restyle herself. She had to
do radio, television, newspaper interviews.''
</P>
<P>
   Heloise, who refuses to plug products, turned down a lucrative
offer from Hollywood producers seven years ago to do a situation
comedy based on her life, largely because it was fictionalized.
</P>
<P>
   ``I didn't need it,'' she said. ``It was very tempting, but it
wasn't me.''
</P>
<P>
   Heloise doesn't need fame. She's got that, and she got it
staying close to home. She doesn't want to monkey with the formula.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is what I do,'' she says. ``I plan on doing this the rest
of my life.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
