<DATE_TIME> 1999-01-08 18:32 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5320 &Cx1f; taf-z
s f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-MUTFUND-GLOBAL-ART-$A     01-08 1204
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MUTFUND-GLOBAL-ART-$ADV10-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
AVOIDING THE WORMS WHEN BOBBING FOR OVERSEAS INVESTMENTS
</HEADLINE>
 (For release Sunday, Jan. 10) 
(ART ADV: Photo of Lilia Clemente is being sent to NYT photo
clients. Non-subscribers can make individual purchase by calling
(888) 603-1036 or (888) 346-9867.) 
(bl) 
By RICK GLADSTONE   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   South Korea is reviving, Thailand isn't far behind, Europe may
be less sexy than it looks and Latin America is a minefield. As for
Russia, it is an investor's version of where you go after losing at
Mortal Kombat: a long, hard fall into a pit full of spikes.
</P>
<P>
   These are the themes that emerge from a sampling of some
top-performing international fund managers _ leaders both for the
fourth quarter of 1998 and longer term. Burned by bad bets the last
two years in Eastern Europe, Asia and Latin America, they are
treading carefully through the global economic uncertainties
looming this year, with few taking big gambles.
</P>
<P>
   Within the countries they deem less risky, the professionals see
some undervalued stocks, but they are concentrating mainly on
relatively strong, established businesses that appear to be in the
best positions to weather unforeseen storms.
</P>
<P>
   Finding relative safety in emerging markets is the bigger
challenge. ``There's some value to be found in the wreckage, but
it's worrisome,'' said Lilia Clemente, the chairwoman and chief
executive of Clemente Capital, a New York investment firm. She
manages Citizens Global Equity fund and other international funds.
</P>
<P>
   Although Ms. Clemente said she had seen some improvement in
Asia, ``we have just stayed away from the volatility in Russia.''
</P>
<P>
   ``We used to be overweighted in Latin America, and now we're
not,'' she said. ``All the uncertainty remains high.''
</P>
<P>
   Many managers see the best prospects in three particular
markets:
</P>
<P>
   SOUTH KOREA
</P>
<P>
   If there is any consensus area of perceived opportunity overseas
this year, it is here. A year after it verged on default, South
Korea has reduced indebtedness, upgraded its credit rating,
stabilized its currency, reduced interest rates and begun the steps
deemed necessary by the International Monetary Fund to restore
economic vitality. The government started restructuring the
unwieldy conglomerates, known as chaebols, considered largely
responsible for the country's economic problems. Many of the
businesses emerging from that streamlining are basically sound, and
their stocks trade at big discounts.
</P>
<P>
   ``Six months ago everyone assumed South Korea's restructuring
would fail, and now it's starting to dawn on everyone that it might
work,'' said Mark Headley, a co-manager of the Matthews Korea and
Matthews Pacific Tiger funds, which both ranked among the top
international stock funds in the final quarter of 1998, largely
because of a resurgence in South Korean stocks.
</P>
<P>
   Headley said he especially likes Samsung Electronics, a leading
maker and exporter of televisions, computers, memory chips and
telecommunications equipment that has benefited from the overhaul
of the chaebols. It is attractive, he said, because the electronics
business has been separated from a financially distressed sibling,
Samsung Automotive, which is no longer a drag on the stock. Its
price climbed from less than 32,600 won in September to 79,000 at
year-end.
</P>
<P>
   ``Samsung is the obvious big blue chip, but you start realizing
there are a lot of situations like that,'' Headley said.
</P>
<P>
   He also likes Hana Bank, a survivor in a drastic winnowing of
South Korean banks. Hana's stock, which finished 1998 at 13,300
won, more than doubled since early November. Even so, it still
trades at less than 12 times 1999 estimated earnings, about half
the ratio of many large U.S. commercial banks.
</P>
<P>
   Headley said he began accruing Samsung shares a number of years
ago, when they traded at roughly 100,000 won, and Hana shares in
late 1997, when they cost about 5,000. Although he declined to
specify where he thinks either stock is going this year, Headley
said, ``I think the Korean market in general has the potential to
double again.''
</P>
<P>
   THAILAND
</P>
<P>
   The first of the Asian economies to plunge into crisis in 1997
when its currency, the baht, tumbled in value, Thailand is also
among the first to show promise of a comeback.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Clemente, who recently returned from a three-week trip to
Asia, said she was impressed that the ``economic outlook for
Thailand is slowly improving, the baht has strengthened, and the
real economy is showing signs of bottoming out.''
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Clemente said she liked three Thai stocks that stood to
benefit from an economic revival: BEC World, a leading
entertainment conglomerate that has a government concession for one
of the country's four television channels; Bangkok Bank, the most
dominant of the three big Thai banks, and Siam Cement, a leading
maker of construction materials, auto accessories and
petrochemicals. BEC and Bangkok Bank shares performed poorly in
1998, but shares of Siam, which as a construction company is
considered a leading economic indicator, more than doubled in the
last quarter, to 560 baht. Ms. Clemente said the stock could reach
1,000 baht in the next 12 to 18 months.
</P>
<P>
   She said shares of BEC, which closed the year at 200 baht, could
rise to 360, and that Bangkok Bank, which finished 1998 at 52 baht,
could reach 100.
</P>
<P>
   EUROPE
</P>
<P>
   Invigorated by optimism over its new single currency, the euro,
Europe still appears to hold much promise. But some global fund
managers are restrained in their opinions, partly because the
economic effects of monetary union are not yet clear. There is also
continuing uncertainty over the Russian economy _ and how any
further deterioration could affect Germany, an important Russian
trading partner.
</P>
<P>
   Given that, some fund managers are looking mainly at big
European-based multinational businesses that can do well whether or
not Europe prospers. Steve Silverman, portfolio manager of the
Merrill Lynch Global Value C fund, said he favored a couple of big
European companies: Cadbury Schweppes of Britain and Nestle of
Switzerland. Although both are essentially in the food business,
Silverman said, Cadbury's strength is its Dr Pepper brand, one of
the world's fastest-growing soft drinks, while Nestle's is its
successful diversification away from its historical mainstay,
coffee.
</P>
<P>
   His fund has been buying both stocks in the last few years, and
they have appreciated sharply. Cadbury rose nearly 70 percent last
year and Nestle rose nearly 42 percent.
</P>
<P>
   ``Do I expect them to appreciate at the same rate? No,''
Silverman said. While he declined to speculate on their possible
appreciation this year, he said, ``what I'm looking for in the
stuff we buy is that we'd like to feel comfortable that over an
extended period, it will grow 15 percent a year.''
</P>
<P>
   Other managers are more exposed to the European economies,
betting that long-term benefits of the euro will make the current
prices of some stocks look cheap in a few years, particularly those
of the large and technologically advanced companies that will find
it more efficient to do European business in one currency instead
of 11.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
