<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TRUMP-PAGEANT-$ADV10-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PREVIEWING THE STATES OF BEAUTY 
</HEADLINE>
   (For release Sun., Jan. 10)  
(JT) 
 By BOB MORRIS    
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ On Thursday, the temperature had dropped to a
sub-freezing chill, but at Life, the nightclub on Bleecker Street
in Greenwich Village, things were heating up. Donald J. Trump was
expected at any moment for a promotional party for the Miss U.S.A.
Pageant, which will be broadcast live next month on CBS.
</P>
<P>
   In anticipation of his arrival, the contestants were all
aflutter. Or maybe they were just cold. Near the door, Miss New
York and Miss Connecticut stood around in skimpy skirts and tops
absolutely unsuitable for winter. But since they had been
instructed not to wear stockings with their BCBG designer outfits,
they stoically exposed their toes and legs (midriffs and shoulders,
too) to blasts of frigid air. The only thing that kept them warm
was the idea of a moment with Trump.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's cold, but at least it's not Buffalo,'' said Miss New
York, Kimberly Ann Pressler, a data entry specialist with glitter
in her hair, who will attend college in Buffalo this fall.
</P>
<P>
   So what did they know about Trump anyway?
</P>
<P>
   ``He makes lots of money,'' Miss Pressler said. ``And his
upstate casino helps our economy.''
</P>
<P>
   ``He owns a lot of things,'' said Miss Connecticut, Christina
D'Amico, a sales representative, who plans to pursue an MBA degree
after college, ``including some property in Bridgeport.''
</P>
<P>
   Would they consider dating him?
</P>
<P>
   With beauty queen diplomacy, they both said that he was
wonderful, but perhaps not their type.
</P>
<P>
   `I want to marry for love, not money,'' Miss D'Amico said.
</P>
<P>
   When Trump finally arrived, he dispensed two kisses to Shawnae
Jebbia, Miss U.S.A. 1998, who, with the eager tone of a child
reporting good news to father, told him about a new job she had
just nailed as a television host. ``I'm going to become a TV
personality,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   After congratulating her, he moved on to peddle his pageant to
reporters. ``What I do is successful because of the esthetics,''
said Trump, who owns part of the Miss Universe Organization
(producer of Miss USA) and is planning to start a modeling agency.
``People love my buildings and my pageants.''
</P>
<P>
   Downstairs, the self-appointed arbiter of all things beautiful
arrived to whoops and cheers. He was swamped by young women.
``Looking good,'' he said. One woman, who called him ``Donald,''
asked for a kiss. He obliged, then asked, ``Do I know you?'' It
turned out he did.
</P>
<P>
   As he posed and mingled, Trump conjured a connection, however
tenuous, to his contestants. Miss New Jersey, for example, has
parents who go to his Taj Mahal casino in Atlantic City. ``That's
what I love to hear,'' Trump said. He told Miss North Carolina that
he plays golf in Pinehurst, and Miss Colorado that he recently got
back from Aspen. ``I own property there,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   One place where he has not staked a claim yet is Rhode Island.
He regretted that. ``Look how beautiful Miss Rhode Island is,'' he
said before pressing more flesh _ hands, arms and an occasional
bare shoulder.
</P>
<P>
   ``You're all so beautiful,'' he said. Then, he was out the door,
leaving his fans to their own resources. To that end, Joy Hall,
Miss North Carolina, was seen giving her phone number to Mitch
Marrow, a defensive end for the Carolina Panthers, who had promised
her seats to a game.
</P>
<P>
   ``They better be good seats,'' Miss Hall said to a friend, after
he had moved on. ``If you give your phone number to someone, you
should at least end up on the 50-yard line.''
</P>
<P>
   Trump is not the only one to understand the art of the deal.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
