<HEADER>
A5323 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CLINTON-IMPEACHMENT-H     01-08 1207
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CLINTON-IMPEACHMENT-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SENATE UNANIMOUSLY ADOPTS TRIAL RULES BUT PUTS OFF WITNESS ISSUE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By STEWART M. POWELL and JUDY HOLLAND  
 c.1999 Hearst Newspapers  
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ The Senate, responding to a ringing appeal by Sen.
Robert Byrd for bipartisanship, unanimously adopted compromise
rules for President Clinton's impeachment trial Friday but
postponed the explosive question of calling witnesses.
</P>
<P>
   Senators emerging from the private meeting of all senators in
the museum-like Old Senate Chamber gave credit to Byrd for setting
the tone for cooperation.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was the most moving talk I've heard about preserving the
integrity of the institution,'' said Sen. Ben Nighthorse Campbell,
R-Colo., referring to the 45-minute address by Byrd, 71, a Democrat
from West Virginia and a self-educated constitutional scholar.
</P>
<P>
   Extra chairs had to be brought into the antiquated chamber to
accommodate all 100 senators. The chamber, initially used in 1810,
was last used for formal Senate deliberations in 1859, when there
were only 33 states in the Union.
</P>
<P>
   Security officers stood outside the chamber doors to insure
privacy.
</P>
<P>
   Senate Majority Leader Trent Lott, R-Miss., said the atmosphere
during the 150-minute session was ``absolutely phenomenal.''
</P>
<P>
   ``It was so positive you could feel history in the room.''
</P>
<P>
   Sen. Christopher J. Dodd, D-Conn., a former Democratic party
chairman, said the ``spirits of compromise were at work'' in the
compact chamber where lawmakers from another century struck the
Missouri Compromise of 1820 that permitted the matching admission
to the union of free states and slave states.
</P>
<P>
   ``We allowed the spirit of the Websters, Calhoun's and Clays to
infect us a bit,'' said Dodd, whose father served in the Senate in
the 1960s. ``It was divine inspiration that occurred in that
chamber.''
</P>
<P>
   Senate Democratic Leader Thomas A. Daschle, D-S.D., said
senators embraced cooperation at the last moment after days of
public and private wrangling over procedures for the first
impeachment trial of a president since 1868.
</P>
<P>
   ``Only in the final moments, there appeared to be a coming
together of ideas,'' Daschle said.
</P>
<P>
   According to participants, Byrd won the attention of his
colleagues by telling a parable known the Pardoner's tale, from
Geoffrey Chaucer, the author of the ``Canterbury Tales,'' who died
in 1400.
</P>
<P>
   Byrd recalled that three partners walking through the forest had
come upon a pot of gold. The partners split the treasure three
ways. But as each became greedy for the remainder, he plotted the
murder of his rivals until all three partners were slain.
</P>
<P>
   Byrd warned his colleagues not to follow suit in their jockeying
over procedures for trying the president.
</P>
<P>
   Sen. Evan Bayh, D-Ind., sworn in for his first Senate term just
days ago, called the speech by Byrd, a 40-year veteran, ``clearly
the highlight'' of the bipartisan meeting. Byrd received a standing
ovation, Bayh said.
</P>
<P>
   ``It seemed as if the institution walked up to the precipice,
looked over the edge and into the abyss and decided not to take
that road,'' Bayh said.
</P>
<P>
   The Senate later convened in open session in its modern chamber
and voted 100 to 0 to adopt compromise trial procedures. The
compromise responded to GOP insistence that, in principle,
witnesses would be permitted to testify, if needed. But the deal
also addressed Democrats' demands that the trial be conducted on
the basis of the public record to date, without fresh testimony
from surprise witnesses.
</P>
<P>
   White House special counsel Gregory Craig, brought in to
quarterback Clinton's impeachment defense, later predicted that
senators ``will conclude that the articles (of impeachment) do not
justify or warrant conviction or removal from office.''
</P>
<P>
   The House voted last month to impeach Clinton for alleged
perjury and obstruction of justice in the cover-up of his sexual
relationship with former White House intern Monica Lewinsky.
</P>
<P>
   The timetable adopted by the Senate Friday set the stage for a
dramatic State of the Union address by Clinton to a joint meeting
of the House and Senate on Jan. 19.
</P>
<P>
   As senators worked out compromise trial procedures, Clinton
traveled to Detroit to celebrate the milestone of the nation
completing 93 strait months of economic growth _ ``the longest
peacetime expansion in history.''
</P>
<P>
   Clinton told the Detroit Economic Club that ``most things are
going right for our country.''
</P>
<P>
   Later, after touring the North American International Auto Show
and watching a demonstration of fuel technologies for the future,
Clinton declared: ``I feel good about the future.''
</P>
<P>
   Under the terms of the deal, House prosecutors and presidential
lawyers have until 5 p.m. EST Monday to file pretrial motions. The
Senate will consider the motions on Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   House prosecutors will begin presenting their case against
Clinton on Thursday over a three-day period. Clinton's defense team
then counters with three days of rebuttal.
</P>
<P>
   The Senate, divided with 55 Republicans and 45 Democrats, would
need to muster 67 votes to remove Clinton from office.
</P>
<P>
   Senators will then have two days to submit questions to House
prosecutors and White House lawyers through presiding Chief Justice
William Rehnquist.
</P>
<P>
   At that point, the trial theoretically could end. Senators would
be free to make motions to adjourn the trial, propose censure or
call witnesses after the opening phase.
</P>
<P>
   But under the compromise adopted Friday, senators can't call any
witnesses before Jan. 26. A panel of four senators will conduct
ongoing negotiations to resolve the question of witnesses.
</P>
<P>
   Sen. Tom Harkin, D-Iowa, said he expects the bipartisan bonhomie
to ebb when senators face a decision over witnesses. ``Look out,''
said Harkin.
</P>
<P>
   Bayh concurred. ``The fundamentally important votes are yet to
come,'' said Bayh, whose father served in the Senate in the 1960s
and 1970s.
</P>
<P>
   The White House, in an effort to forestall the calling of
witnesses, agreed Thursday to accept 7,000 pages of testimony given
the Senate by the House and special prosecutor Kenneth Starr as the
basis for the trial.
</P>
<P>
   House lawmakers are urging the Senate to hear testimony from
Lewinsky, presidential secretary Betty Currie and Clinton
confidante and Washington superlawyer Vernon Jordan. House
prosecutors met on Friday to weigh whether to add to their witness
list Kathleen Willey, the former White House volunteer who alleges
that Clinton made an unwanted sexual advance in the White House.
</P>
<P>
   House Judiciary Committee Chairman Henry Hyde, R-Ill., the lead
House prosecutor, reiterated House insistence that witnesses be
permitted, saying: ``Witnesses are necessary during a trial so that
evidence may be thoroughly weighed and tested before a
conviction.''
</P>
<P>
   But as a result of Friday's compromise the House prosecutors
must now wait until after the opening phase of the trial to learn
whether senators will permit witnesses.
</P>
<P>
   The detailed compromise was struck by an improbable pair of
senators, both of whom have run for president _ conservative
Republican Sen. Phil Gramm of Texas, and Democratic Sen. Edward M.
Kennedy of Massachusetts.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
