<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TV-MARKIEWICZ-COLUMN-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NBA PICKED A GOOD TIME TO HAVE LABOR PROBLEMS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By DAVID A. MARKIEWICZ 
c.1998 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   As any smart politician knows, the best time to pass an unsavory
piece of legislation is at the beginning of a term in office; come
re-election, voters are apt to have forgotten what they'd been
forced to swallow a few years earlier.
</P>
<P>
   One smart politician, David Stern, no doubt took this into
account in his negotiations with the NBA players union.
</P>
<P>
   Stern's seeming willingness to scuttle the season made him and
his league about as popular with basketball fans as a pol pushing a
tax hike.
</P>
<P>
   In the back of his mind, though, Stern had to be aware that it
would be a few years before the most important test of the NBA's
popularity was administered. By then, he must hope, all will be
forgotten, if not entirely forgiven.
</P>
<P>
   The test we speak of will come in the form of the league's next
television contract negotiations. Those won't take place until some
time near the end of the current broadcast contract that runs
through the 2001-2002 season. By then, we'll be talking about
serious money, maybe a billion dollars or more per season in rights
fees for the league.
</P>
<P>
   If, that is, the NBA can recover all the good will that leaked
out during the lockout.
</P>
<P>
   Stern's well-calculated strategy to press the union all the way
to a season-cancellation deadline was a gamble, indeed. But it was
the right time to take such a risk.
</P>
<P>
   Had a lockout occurred in the final year of a network TV
contract, the league might not have had enough time to win back
fans _ and viewers. That would have driven down the value of that
next TV deal.
</P>
<P>
   It's a lesson Major League Baseball learned the hard way. In
1993, the year before the players' strike, baseball clubs earned an
average of $336 million a year in network TV money, sports media
analysts say. Last year, they earned $345 million, a net decline
factoring in inflation.
</P>
<P>
   In the same time, NFL rights fees increased from an average of
$925 million annually to $2.3 billion. The NBA's rights fees jumped
from $219 million to $660 million per year. Even the NHL's
broadcast rights increased from $14 million to $120 million.
</P>
<P>
   ``Major League Baseball has still not recovered in national TV
rights fees,'' observed David Marin, a sports business analyst at
Paul Kagan Associates, a sports and media research firm.
</P>
<P>
   ``The renegotiated contract coming out of the \Rbaseball\S
strike was lower than going into the strike, in stark contrast to
the NBA, the NFL and the NHL, all of whose rights fees soared.''
</P>
<P>
   Marin figures that baseball frittered away a total of about $2
billion in rights fees when it negotiated its post-strike contract.
</P>
<P>
   ``The escalation of national rights fees is a phenomenon that
baseball missed,'' Kagan said.
</P>
<P>
   Stern was not about to let that happen to his league, especially
with the NBA's popularity on TV soaring.
</P>
<P>
   Smart guy, that David Stern.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
