<SLUG> BC-BOOKS-BROKAW-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BROKAW DRAWS RAVES FOR HIS HEARTFELT NOD TO A GENERATION 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By JOHN LEVESQUE  
 c.1999 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Tom Brokaw is getting lots of fan mail these days, and it has
nothing to do with his anchorman gig on the ``NBC Nightly News.''
</P>
<P>
   ``It's very gratifying,'' he said this week as he prepared for a
West Coast swing to promote a book that hardly needs more
tub-thumping. Brokaw already is atop The New York Times'
best-seller list, and anyone who watches even a tiny amount of TV
has probably seen him on a talk show _ talking excitedly about
``The Greatest Generation.''
</P>
<P>
   After all, he's got a publisher to please. But it's a subject
Brokaw doesn't seem to tire of, even when discussing it for the
umpteenth time. And now, as America embraces this paean to a
generation that emerged from an economic depression only to face a
world war, he hopes his first book might be a catalyst, an agent
for ``creating a dialogue between generations'' that could lead to
a sort of bonding over common ground.
</P>
<P>
   If that doesn't happen, Brokaw still is happy to have told the
stories of dozens of American heroes, some of whom did
extraordinary things on the battlefield and have the medals to
prove it, but most of whom did not what their country expected of
them but simply what they expected of themselves when the chips
were down.
</P>
<P>
   Brokaw writes: ``This generation helped save the world from
fascism, returned home to marry and go to college in record
numbers, rebuild their former enemies, stand fast against
communism, give us great art, science, the interstate highway
system, Medicare, and the greatest economy the world has ever
known.''
</P>
<P>
   More to the point in an age when it's almost easier to play the
victim than to exercise personal responsibility, he adds: ``They
never whined or whimpered. I am in awe of them.''
</P>
<P>
   It shows. Though he is no spellbinder, Brokaw writes clearly and
with abiding reverence about the people who agreed to share their
``war stories'' with him _ men like Thomas Broderick, an American
paratrooper who was shot through the head during the World War II
Battle of Arnhem. Broderick survived; his eyesight didn't.
Embittered at first, he eventually accepted his blindness, married,
had seven kids and founded a successful business.
</P>
<P>
   It would seem few could match Broderick's story for sheer
courage and determination, but Brokaw's book is brimming with such
tales of personal heroism, whether it was overcoming serious
injury, watching a brother die on a bloody beach, or taking care of
business on the home front.
</P>
<P>
   It is these people who are now writing ``wonderful, handwritten
letters'' to Brokaw, appreciative of being appreciated for things
they did a half-century ago. It's hard to get through most chapters
of the book without wiping away a tear.
</P>
<P>
   ``These truly are people who never expected that other people
would take notice,'' said Brokaw, who, at 58 is old enough to
remember the final days of World War II. ``They simply lived by the
rules established early in their lives.''
</P>
<P>
   It's a code of honor that made no distinction as to class, sex
or race, even if society didn't always return the favor. As George
Bush, former president and naval aviator, points out in the book,
service in the war was more honor than duty.
</P>
<P>
   ``What are we owed?'' Bush asks. ``Nothing. Not one damn
thing.''
</P>
<P>
   It might sound suspect coming from a career politician, but one
gets the impression that each person Brokaw interviewed would utter
the same words. Indeed, a lesser-known Bush _ Bob Bush of Raymond,
Wash. _ is a genuine war hero who promised his mother that he would
enter the service to help people, not to kill them.
</P>
<P>
   Bush was an 18-year-old Navy medic on Okinawa when circumstances
forced him to hold off a band of attacking Japanese soldiers as he
administered plasma to a wounded Marine. He was hit several times,
lost an eye, and won the Congressional Medal of Honor.
</P>
<P>
   Would today's American teenager do the same? Brokaw says he's
optimistic, and several members of ``The Greatest Generation'' also
suspect today's young people would rally to a just cause. We might
never have to find out, which could very well be the greatest
legacy of the greatest generation.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
