<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR; IMPEACH &LR;  (``w'' code)
</P>
<P>
   The New York Times plans 2 pages of stories relating to
impeachment.
</P>
<P>
   The lede story will move by  &UR; 9 p.m. Eastern time &LR; :
</P>
<P>
   IMPEACH (Washington) _ Ledeall: Senate Republicans and Democrats
reached agreement in an extraordinary meeting on Friday to resume
Clinton's impeachment trial next week while leaving open the
question of witnesses. By Alison Mitchell. (1600 words)
</P>
<P>
   With photos.
</P>
<P>
   These are the other stories in the impeachment package:
</P>
<P>
   Moving by  &UR; 7:30 &LR; :
</P>
<P>
   IMPEACH-CLINTON (Detroit) _ In the glow of more terrific
economic numbers, President Clinton proclaims that all is well _
very well indeed _ showing once again just why he is popular, and
why removal from office is a very difficult goal for his opponents.
He is speaking at the Detroit Economic Club, long a must-stop for
national leaders making serious economic pronouncements. By John M.
Broder. (1000 words)
</P>
<P>
   IMMPEACH-CANING (Washington) _ As Sen. Dodd pointed out in
urging senators to avoid civil war, the Old Senate Chamber was the
site in the 1850s of the slavery-related caning of Sen. Sumner of
Massachusetts by Rep. Brooks of South Carolina. (400 words)
</P>
<P>
   Moving by  &UR; 8:00 &LR; :
</P>
<P>
   IMPEACH-ASSESS (Washington) _ Bipartisan _ for now. How the
Senate rules and traditions invite the sort of agreement reached
today but leave any deal fragile because of another tradition: of
power to the individual. By Adam Clymer. (900 words)
</P>
<P>
   IMPEACH-CAUCUS (Washington) _ The atmosphere of this unusual
session in the Old Senate Chamber. By Katharine Q. Seelye and
Lizette Alvarez.
</P>
<P>
   Moving by  &UR; 8:30 &LR; :
</P>
<P>
