<HEADLINE>
INS DEPORTS RECORD NUMBER OF UNDOCUMENTED IMMIGRANTS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By GARY MARTIN  
 c.1999 San Antonio Express-News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ A record 171,154 undocumented immigrants were
deported by the Immigration and Naturalization Service in fiscal
year 1998, and Commissioner Doris Meissner said Wednesday the
agency has ``much more to do.''
</P>
<P>
   The number deported in fiscal year 1998, which ended Sept. 30,
represents a 50 percent increase over the 114,386 removed in fiscal
1997, according to the INS.
</P>
<P>
   ``Removals play a crucial role in our effort to restore
credibility to our nation's immigration laws,'' Meissner said.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm pleased with the progress we've made in removals, but in
the interior and at our borders, we have much more to do,'' she
said.
</P>
<P>
   But Rep. Lamar Smith, chairman of the House Judiciary
subcommittee on immigration, was not as enthusiastic.
</P>
<P>
   ``I am pleased that the INS continues to increase the number of
deportations, but let's put the numbers in perspective: The INS
reports that 400,000 permanent illegal aliens arrive each year, and
there are more than 5 million already living in the United
States,'' said Smith, R-Texas.
</P>
<P>
   Nonetheless, Smith said, the record increase was ``further
proof'' that the 1996 immigration reform law ``has untied
immigration agents' hands to promptly return illegal aliens.''
</P>
<P>
   Smith said the new law ``is securing America's borders, reducing
crime, protecting jobs and saving taxpayers billions of dollars.''
</P>
<P>
   The INS, though, has reported an increase in deportations each
of the last five years.
</P>
<P>
   Deportation figures for fiscal 1998 do not include the estimated
1.5 million apprehensions and voluntary returns reported at border
ports-of-entry.
</P>
<P>
   Deportation of undocumented immigrants who served sentences for
felony convictions totalled 56,011, a 9 percent increase over the
51,272 deported in fiscal 1997, the INS said.
</P>
<P>
   Of the fiscal 1998 criminals deported, 47 percent were convicted
on narcotics charges, 15 percent violated immigration laws, 5
percent were convicted of burglary, 5 percent were convicted of
assault and 4 percent were convicted of sex crimes.
</P>
<P>
   Overall, the INS deported an average 1,077 undocumented
immigrants convicted of felonies each week in fiscal 1998.
</P>
<P>
   The surge in non-criminal deportations came from expedited
removals ordered by immigration judges. Expedited deportations
totalled 76,113, and most came in Southwest border states.
</P>
<P>
   The three Southwest border districts with the largest number of
expedited deportations were: San Diego, 40,894; El Paso, 11,129;
and San Antonio, 6,778.
</P>
<P>
   Mexican nationals accounted for 81 percent of the total number
of undocumented immigrants deported in fiscal year 1998, or
138,249.
</P>
<P>
   Mexican nationals accounted for 78 percent, or 43,451, of the
criminal deportations.
</P>
<P>
   Nationals from El Salvador, Guatemala and Honduras each
represented 3 percent of the total number of deportations.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
