</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-US-IRAQ-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`SHAKEN' SADDAM EXECUTING ARMY OFFICERS, U.S. SAYS 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By STEVE LASH 
c.1998 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Iraqi dictator Saddam Hussein, ``shaken'' by
massive U.S. and British bombing of his military last month, has
executed army officers who might have disobeyed him, the chief U.S.
military officer for the region said Friday.
</P>
<P>
   The allied campaign leveled much of Saddam's military
establishment and killed between 600 and 2,000 soldiers in the
dictator's elite Republican Guard, including senior officers, said
Marine Corps Gen. Anthony Zinni, who leads the U.S. Central
Command.
</P>
<P>
   Zinni also said the executions indicate a weakening of Saddam's
hold on his military, but the general added that he did not know
whether a coup was imminent. Citing intelligence reports, Zinni
said Saddam purged officers, including a commander in southern
Iraq, following the four-day U.S.-British assault code-named
Operation Desert Fox.
</P>
<P>
   ``He was shaken and the regime was shaken,'' Zinni said of
Saddam. ``It looks like he may have been behind some of these
executions, and there might be still some going on in military
ranks and civilians also.''
</P>
<P>
   Gen. Henry Shelton, chairman of the Joint Chiefs of Staff, said
that the Iraqi dictator ``lost a lot'' in Desert Fox because many
Republican Guard senior officers are ``no longer available to him
to advise or to lead.''
</P>
<P>
   Saddam claims the U.S. and British bombs hit mostly civilian
targets.
</P>
<P>
   In the aftermath of Desert Fox, a now ``desperate'' Saddam has
become more dangerous, challenging U.S. pilots in the no-fly zones
over northern and southern Iraq and urging Arabs to overthrow
governments that do not support him, Zinni said.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's capable of not only doing things irrational, but of
miscalculating,'' Zinni said. ``We have tried to look at every
possibility, any event, every eventuality as to what he might do
militarily in reaction to us.''
</P>
<P>
   But if Saddam opts for more serious military action, he might
find his soldiers unwilling to fight for him, Zinni contended.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think there's some confusion in the ranks and there's some
disgruntlement with ... who they answer to,'' the general added.
``I can't ... give you a feel for how serious this is, how
extensive it is, but we are certainly seeing these kinds of signs
that there are problems.''
</P>
<P>
   Within the past two weeks, U.S. jets have fired missiles at
Iraq's military on four separate occasions after Iraqi radar zeroed
in on the planes while they were on routine patrol in the no-fly
zones, the Pentagon reported. No U.S. planes were hit during these
clashes, which Saddam might have initiated in an attempt to capture
an American pilot, Zinni said.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think clearly he's trying to lure us into a possible
shoot-down situation,'' the general added. ``Our pilots are smart
enough not to fall for traps or get themselves in some sort of
maneuver or position where they're vulnerable or follow a plane
into a missile engagement zone.''
</P>
<P>
   Zinni also characterized as a failure Saddam's televised speech
Jan. 5 in which he called for the overthrow of Arab governments.
Despite the vitriol, popular uprisings in these countries have not
occurred.
</P>
<P>
   ``The language he used, his attack on all the other leaders in
the region, I think showed a degree of desperation that we hadn't
seen before,'' Zinni said. ``To us, that speech was shocking.''
</P>
<P>
   The U.S. military will continue to look for signs of Saddam's
weakening hold on power, including indications of ``disloyalty or
breaking ranks'' in Iraq's regular army, the sudden disappearance
of key Iraqi leaders and acts of sabotage against the dictator,
Zinni said.
</P>
<P>
   The general also updated U.S. damage estimates from Desert Fox,
saying it will take Saddam two years _ instead of merely one as
first thought _ to repair the military installations U.S. and
British bombs destroyed during the assault Dec. 16-19. Zinni said
the revised estimate was based in part on intelligence reports that
bombed buildings initially reported as empty contained equipment
necessary for Saddam's missile development program.
</P>
<P>
   Zinni said he had ``no knowledge'' of whether the U.S. military
chose what sites to bomb based on intelligence gathered from United
Nations weapons inspectors in Iraq. The United Nations is
investigating whether the inspectors illegally spied on Saddam for
the United States while they were examining whether he was building
outlawed weapons.
</P>
<P>
   The no-fly zones extend south from the 33rd parallel, just below
Iraq's capital city of Baghdad, and north from the 36th parallel.
The zones, which the U.S. and British military have enforced as a
condition of Iraq's surrender in the 1991 Persian Gulf War, are
designed to prevent Iraqi aircraft from attacking Kurds in the
north and Shi'ite Muslims in the south.
</P>
<P>
   Saddam refuses to recognize the no-fly zones, regarding them as
an illegal encroachment on Iraq's sovereignty. &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
