<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NEW-AGE-COSMETICS-$ADV10-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FINDING ENLIGHTENMENT IN A BOTTLE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For release Sunday, Jan. 10)  
(DW) 
 By PENELOPE GREEN   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Last week I bathed in purple water (``I Trust''
bubble bath, made by Philosophy), and powdered up with pink powder
(Rebirth, by 5S, ``to renew the spirit and recharge the soul'').
</P>
<P>
   My moisturizer was Bliss (Chakra VII by Aveda, for ``the joyful
enlightenment and soaring of the spirit''); my nail polish,
Spiritual (by Tony and Tina, ``to aid connection with the higher
self''). My teeth were clean, my heart was open _ although my
bathroom was so crowded with bottles and brochures, the latest
tools and totems from the human potential movement, that I could
hardly find my third eye (perhaps I should have purchased a bindi,
$15 from Jade on Elizabeth Street, to help me do so).
</P>
<P>
   If you are looking for enlightenment in all the wrong places,
cosmetics companies are suddenly eager to help. Because today, in
``Darwin's empty heaven,'' as the writer Chip Brown puts it in his
new book, ``Afterwards, You're a Genius: Faith, Medicine and the
Metaphysics of Healing'' (Riverhead Books), feeling good is the new
religion. Cosmetics companies are the newest of the new prophets,
turning the old notion of hope in a jar on its head. ``Oh Lord,''
Brown groaned in protest. ``They're just vendors, shouting in a
different way.''
</P>
<P>
   What marvelous shouting! ``Cosmetics are our satellite to the
divine!'' This is what you'll hear from Tony and Tina, for example.
Tony and Tina (Anthony Gillis and Cristina Bornstein) are nice
young artists. He's from London, she grew up in New York.
</P>
<P>
   Chakra nail polish, which they invented for an installation at
the Gershwin Gallery in Manhattan two years ago, was intended as an
ironic commentary on the beauty business. But then a friend
suggested they get into the beauty business, and now Tony and Tiny
have a $2 million cosmetics company with a mission statement ``to
aid in the evolution of human consciousness.''
</P>
<P>
   Their products include nail polishes (Vibrational Remedies) in
colors meant to do nice things to your chakras, as well as body
glitter and hair mascara, lipstick and eyeshadow. You can buy them
at Fred Segal, Nordstrom and Bloomingdale's, where last month they
outsold Hard Candy and Urban Decay.
</P>
<P>
   At Rialto in NoLIta the other day, Tony cupped his hands over
his spinach and Gorgonzola ravioli _ Tina said he likes to greet
his food before he eats it _ and said, ``We think color therapy is
going to be the new medicine.''
</P>
<P>
   Rainbows are proliferating as rapidly in the New Age as angels
once did. Philosophy, a three-year-old Arizona company, makes a
sort of head/ &QL; 
heart kit _ ``a self-help program,'' the company insists _ called
the Rainbow Connection, $45 for seven bottles of colored bubble
bath in a neat metal box. ``Choose your colored bath according to
the area of your emotional life that needs attention, i.e.
self-love, self-worth,'' reads the brochure. Like Tony and Tina's
nail paints, the colors work on those pesky chakras.
</P>
<P>
   ``My role as I see it,'' said Christina Carlino, Philosophy's
founder, ``is to help you stay on your destiny path. It's not about
what you look like. Beauty is defined by your deeds.''
</P>
<P>
   Here are beauty products that are not intended to make you look
better, but to make you act better, feel better and be a better
person. The product claims eclipse even the most grandiose in the
history of the notoriously grandiose beauty business. Think of it
as trend seepage: the so-called New Age _ the loose and goofy
assemblage of Eastern mysticism, psychic phenomena, astral
projection and so on that has waxed and waned for the last three
decades _ has again gained such luster that companies are slapping
the word ``chakra'' on a bottle of nail polish. Words like ``energy
system'' on a jar of face cream throb with iconic power.
</P>
<P>
   Today you don't need a month's visit to India to find your
higher self; you need only buy this bubble bath, that lipstick,
this night cream. The beauty business' old come-on _ trap your man!
_ has been swept away in favor of a new pitch. I don't have
wrinkles anymore. I've got a chakra blockage.
</P>
<P>
   5S, a new sprout of the Japanese cosmetics company Shiseido,
offers a regimen that plays, the company says, on the ``fundamental
and mythical significance of 5'' (the Five Pillars of Islam, the
Five Classics of Confucianism, and so on), and which is organized
into emotional rather than physical categories.
</P>
<P>
   At the 5S store in SoHo, which is designed with white
incandescent light, glass shelves and bottles that glow with color
_ you don't buy things for dry skin, you buy things that are
``energizing'' or ``nurturing'' or ``adoring.''
</P>
<P>
   The company also believes in color therapy. Hence, Rebirth, a
group of products tinted ``nouveau pink'' (the color of bubble
gum). A customer can achieve rebirth with 5S pink soap, pink powder
and pink toner. Into the baptismal river with you and your pink
soap!
</P>
<P>
   ``All of these things are born to some degree out of looking for
what's next,'' said Anne Gottlieb, a cosmetics industry consultant.
``Spirituality or whatever you call it is certainly going to come
after makeup lines for color, and fruits and flowers for
toiletries. I think everything is headed this way. Of course, who
knew about chakras before Aveda?''
</P>
<P>
   In 1989, the plant-based, eco-friendly cosmetics company Aveda
trademarked Chakras I through VII to use as titles for moisturizers
and scents. Chakra products were perhaps a little ahead of their
time back then; the purchase of Aveda nine months ago by the Estee
Lauder Companies, the General Motors of the cosmetics world,
suggests that the pendulum of history has finally caught up.
</P>
<P>
   ``My job is to make Aveda more Aveda,'' said Jeanette Wagner,
the vice chairman of Estee Lauder. ``Aveda isn't a marketing idea.
It is a passionately held belief.''
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Wagner said Estee Lauder intends to extend the Aveda concept
through ``life style'' stores built with sustainable woods and
nontoxic elements, selling ``beauty, health, life style, you name
it.'' Watch for 40 of them opening this spring.
</P>
<P>
   ``From my point of view,'' Ms. Wagner said, ``the appeal is
first the spirituality, and then the products. I'm passionate on
the subject.''
</P>
<P>
   Brown said that statements like this one depressed him.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's so rankly commercial, I don't see how it could possibly
have any spiritual benefit,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Still, Aveda's Chakra VII moisturizer, for instance, smells
quite lovely, kind of fizzy and clove-y, like Old Spice or root
beer. Since the folks at Aveda were smart enough to trademark what
they saw as the end result of Chakra VII moisturizer as well as the
chakra itself, you will be able to buy Bliss (from Lauder) forever.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
