<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-01-08 18:54 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5346 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-NASA-CHARTER-HNS &LR;      01-08 0740
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NASA-CHARTER-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NASA TO END CHARTER FLIGHT SERVICE BETWEEN HOUSTON, MOSCOW 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By MARK CARREAU 
c.1998 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   HOUSTON _ NASA will end a year-old, charter flight service
between Houston and Moscow for its international space station
workers after the agency's inspector general and a Senate oversight
committee declared it too costly.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was one of those things where we tried to make things more
efficient, and in the end it simply didn't yield the cost benefits
we anticipated,'' Peggy Wilhide, a spokeswoman for NASA
administrator Dan Goldin, said Friday.
</P>
<P>
   An audit completed by NASA's office of inspector general this
week uncovered a range of problems with the charter:
</P>
<P>
   _ Use of the charter through September 1998, its first nine
months of operation, cost NASA's already financially-strapped space
station program $3 million more than if it had relied on
traditional commercial airline service.
</P>
<P>
   _ The per seat cost ranged from $2,753 to $19,883 for the two
dozen charter flights during the period, largely because fewer
passengers and less cargo were on the flights than NASA had
envisioned.
</P>
<P>
   _ The agency's own travel regulations limit the use of charters
to a ``one-time'' basis _ when scheduled airline service is not
readily available between the intended destinations.
</P>
<P>
   Wilhide said the National Aeronautics and Space Administration
will revert to the use of commercial airline service between the
countries as soon as it can end the charter agreement without
incurring a penalty. ``A couple of more flights'' are likely, she
said.
</P>
<P>
   Sen. Fred Thompson, R-Tenn., chair of the Senate's Government
Affairs Committee, called on Goldin to end the use of the charter
Thursday, citing the findings of the inspector general's audit.
</P>
<P>
   ``NASA dollars should be devoted to science, not lost to
bureaucratic waste,'' Thompson said.
</P>
<P>
   According to the audit, the charter flights were initiated in
January 1998, when NASA contracted with the Pentagon's Air Mobility
Command through the Johnson Space Center, where the agency's
station program is headquartered, in far south Houston. The
military air charter service supplied a Boeing 727 with a
143-passenger capacity.
</P>
<P>
   In order to achieve a savings over traditional commercial
airline service, the space agency estimated it needed an average of
90 passengers for the flights. The flights originated at Ellington
Field in Houston and typically stopped in Huntsville, Ala., home of
NASA's Marshall Space Flight Center, and then Washington D.C.,
where the agency is headquartered.
</P>
<P>
   During the audit period, passenger loads ranged from nine to
108, but averaged only 44 people, well below NASA's goal, according
to the inspector general.
</P>
<P>
   Those eligible for passage included Russian government and
contractor personnel as well as NASA civil servants and U.S.
aerospace contractor personnel.
</P>
<P>
   The charter flights were advantageous because they allowed
workers to conduct meetings during the long flights and to hasten
their passage through customs once they reached their destinations,
something that will not be possible on traditional commercial
flights.
</P>
<P>
   The audit found that when NASA's own assessments questioned cost
effectiveness of the arrangement after three and six months of
service, it began to incorporate security and the health and
welfare of its workers into its justifications.
</P>
<P>
   The inspector general, however, took exception to those claims
and challenged a practice in which NASA allowed 41 dependents of
U.S. and Russian space agency workers to travel on the charter on a
``space available'' basis during the charter period at a cost equal
to the ``lowest coach fare'' on commercial service. That practice
allowed the dependents to reimburse the federal government an
average of $954.10 for the round trip.
</P>
<P>
   By booking their flights on a scheduled airline and charging the
expense to a credit card, station workers are eligible for $200,000
in flight insurance coverage, a benefit unavailable to them during
the charter travel, the auditors said.
</P>
<P>
   The space agency does not expect that the use of commercial
airlines for travel to Russia will jeopardize station development,
Wilhide said.
</P>
<P>
   The first large components of the orbital outpost were joined in
orbit during December. Construction will continue into 2004.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
