<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-01-08 18:58 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5350 &Cx1f; taf-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-ITALY-VATICAN-NYT &LR;      01-08 0787
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ITALY-VATICAN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
POPE MEETS COMMUNIST PRIME MINISTER  (JT)
</HEADLINE>
   By ALESSANDRA STANLEY    
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   ROME _ Prime Minister Massimo d'Alema, a former Communist, had a
private audience Friday with the pope who helped make ``former
Communist'' a common moniker throughout the world.
</P>
<P>
   Using a cane, the stooped and frail John Paul II, 78, walked
slowly to the door of his private study in the Vatican to greet
D'Alema and personally ushered him in for a 25-minute conversation.
Seated across a desk from the pope, D'Alema perched stiffly on the
edge of his seat.
</P>
<P>
   Afterward, D'Alema said that he went into the meeting ``feeling
extremely tense.'' But he said his tension quickly melted ``thanks
to the Holy Father's extraordinary capacity to engage in direct,
human contact.'' D'Alema, who brought along his wife and two
children, described himself as ``moved.''
</P>
<P>
   John Paul II has granted a formal audience to almost every
Italian prime minister since he was elected pope 20 years ago, but
the symbolism of his tete-a-tete with Italy's first former
Communist leader held a special resonance. The event was covered
live on state television, with journalists likening it to the
pope's meetings with Mikhail Gorbachev and Fidel Castro. Commenting
on the television images of their first handshake, one television
reporter excitedly described it as ``the falling of the last stone
of the Berlin wall.''
</P>
<P>
   Essentially, it was a protocol visit with a historical twist.
D'Alema, who was named prime minister in October, was for many
years a leading member of the Italian Communist Party, the largest
in Western Europe. After the fall of the Berlin wall in 1989,
followed by the collapse of the Soviet Union in 1991, the Italian
Communist Party split and D'Alema left to form a non-Marxist
movement, the Democratic Party of the Left.
</P>
<P>
   For 50 years, the Roman Catholic Church in Italy led a fierce
battle against the Italian Communist Party. In the 1948 elections,
priests warned believers that they would be excommunicated if they
joined the party. The church helped keep the left out of power for
50 years, loosening its strictures to Catholic voters only after
the ruling Christian Democrats collapsed under the weight of
corruption scandals in the early 1990s.
</P>
<P>
   Nevertheless, the selection of D'Alema as prime minister was
viewed with dismay by many in the church. The Vatican newspaper,
Osservatore Romano, published a scathing editorial against him the
day he was named. But since taking office, D'Alema, a nonbeliever,
has made a point of smoothing relations with the church. Last
month, he told El Pais, the Spanish newspaper, that ``the spiritual
void of countries ruled by Communists was real.''
</P>
<P>
   ``The pope was right,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   D'Alema has spoken in favor of a draft law to increase state
subsidies to private schools in Italy, which are mainly Catholic.
The two men discussed the issue in their meeting, according to the
Vatican spokesman, Joaquin Navarro-Valls. The pope has made state
support for private schools one of his pet projects, but it remains
a deeply contested issue within Italy's political left.
</P>
<P>
   If D'Alema succeeds in passing legislation to increase financing
for religious schools, he will have done far more for the church
than previous Christian-Democratic governments. That irony has been
a theme of journalistic commentary in Italy. This week, the news
magazine L'Espresso, dryly noted that, ``over Christmas, D'Alema
has become more Papist than the pope.''
</P>
<P>
   There are plenty of issues that still divide the Italian
government and the Vatican, from abortion to biotechnology. Most
notably, the Vatican is in a fierce diplomatic battle with Italian
law enforcement, disputing a state prosecutor's right to
investigate the archbishop of Milan, Cardinal Michele Giordano.
</P>
<P>
   The police raided the palace of Giordano last summer seeking
evidence that he had ties to an extortion and loan-sharking
operation. The cardinal's brother, Mario Giordano, was arrested on
such charges. The cardinal denied any involvement, and the Vatican
argued that the investigation violated the church's sovereignty as
laid out in the 1984 Concordat. To resolve the impasse, D'Alema's
predecessor, Romano Prodi, reached an agreement with Vatican
officials to set up a commission to examine the issue.
</P>
<P>
   Friday, the Vatican spokesman, Navarro-Valls, said that the pope
and D'Alema discussed the need for the commission to settle church
sovereignty issues. Later, after D'Alema met with the Vatican
secretary of state, Cardinal Angelo Sodano, the Italian government
issued the names of the government officials appointed to the
commission.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-01-08-99 1858EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990108.0290 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-01-08 19:03 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5354 &Cx1f; taf-z
u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-IMPEACH-CLINTON-NYT &LR;      01-08 0904
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-IMPEACH-CLINTON-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EBULLIENT CLINTON SPEAKS TO DETROIT CLUB ABOUT ECONOMY 
</HEADLINE>
   (See related: IMPEACH, IMPEACH-CANING, IMPEACH-ASSESS,
IMPEACH-CAUCUS, IMPEACH-SCENE)  
(JT) 
 By JOHN M. BRODER    
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   DETROIT _ The stock market is in record territory. The economic
expansion just hit its 93rd month, making this the longest
peacetime period of sustained growth in American history.
</P>
<P>
   And if President Clinton needed any more reason to be upbeat
when he stepped before the Economic Club of Detroit Friday, he got
it Friday morning when the Labor Department announced that the
economy had generated a resounding total of 378,000 new jobs in
December, pushing the unemployment rate down to 4.3 percent.
</P>
<P>
   As the Senate moved forward in its impeachment trial, the
confluence of good economic news was just another reminder that
this president remains either the most skillful overseer of the
economy in decades, or the luckiest. If he escapes removal from
office, it will be in no small part because of his high approval
ratings, which are rooted in the nation's long run of prosperity.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a somewhat cynical view, but the public values leaders on
outcomes, not character,'' said Thomas Gallagher, a political
analyst in Washington for Lehman Brothers. ``That's not to say that
character could never trump outcomes, but with these outcomes the
public doesn't want to change leaders now.''
</P>
<P>
   How much of the credit Clinton deserves is of course a matter of
debate. But he was not shy about claiming some Friday as he spoke
to 1,500 members and guests of the Economic Club of Detroit,
including hundreds of automobile industry executives, union leaders
and most of Michigan's Democratic congressional delegation.
</P>
<P>
   ``We meet today at a time of an American economic renaissance,''
Clinton declared. He said the current expansion was more impressive
than past ones for several reasons, among them that it had brought
higher real incomes for most Americans and minority-group
unemployment rates that are at the lowest levels since the
government began keeping those statistics in 1972.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is a rising tide that is lifting all boats,'' Clinton
said.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton spoke at Cobo Arena, also the site of the North American
International Auto Show, the world's largest new-car exhibit. The
automobile industry is celebrating its second-best sales year ever
and the region's economy is booming. Employers are having trouble
finding workers, particularly for low-wage jobs.
</P>
<P>
   The White House, clearly recognizing how important the economy's
performance is to Clinton's survival in office, is making certain
that he is seen presiding over high-profile announcements of the
latest good economic news.
</P>
<P>
   On Wednesday, he announced that the federal budget surplus for
1999 would be at least $76 billion, the highest such figure ever in
dollar terms. And Friday, Clinton braved snowy runways in both
Washington and Detroit to spotlight the latest favorable trends.
</P>
<P>
   White House aides insist these are not events stage-managed
solely to divert attention from the impeachment trial. ``The
president obviously understands what's going on in the Senate,''
said Joe Lockhart, the White House press secretary. ``It's in the
hands of the Senate. He's focusing on his agenda.''
</P>
<P>
   In his 35-minute address Friday afternoon, Clinton said that the
government still faced challenges in dealing with economic matters,
despite the steady flow of good news. He said that the
administration must still grapple with caring for the elderly and
providing an education to equip the nation's young to compete in
the global high-technology economy. He said that many inner cities
and rural areas have yet to share in the benefits of the nation's
economic boom.
</P>
<P>
   He also said that the huge volume and high speed of
international capital flows posed a threat to the stability of
nations around the world, whose problems could spread to the United
States.
</P>
<P>
   And he noted that rapid growth posed problems for the
environment that must be met with new investment in
energy-efficient technologies and a reduced dependence on fossil
fuels, which contribute to global warming.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's an interesting time in which we live, and we should feel
fortunate to be here,'' Clinton said. But he added, ``The
temptation to rest on our laurels and relax because times are good
must be resisted. Good times today can become bad times tomorrow if
you don't stay ahead of the curve.''
</P>
<P>
   Even though many of the club's members, who include a number of
auto parts company owners and executives, are Republicans, they
were interested mostly in the economy and said they wanted the
president's impeachment difficulties over as soon as possible.
Heinz Prechter, a big donor to Michigan Republicans and the
chairman and founder of ASC Inc., a manufacturer of car sun roofs,
said that while he was uncertain whether Clinton should be removed
from office, he was sure that the current political furor should be
brought to a quick conclusion.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think that most of us in leadership positions can
condone what President Clinton has done, but we can't have this
public show go on forever,'' he said. And Prechter praised Friday's
speech. ``I think President Clinton hit all the hot buttons which
are of interest to our industry and our city,'' he said. ``His
speech was outstanding.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
