<TEXT>
<P>
   The Los Angeles Daily News plans to move the following general
stories for use by NYTimes News Service clients, AMs and PMs of
Saturday, Jan. 9, and thereafter. For questions about stories,
contact Jeremy Bagott at the Daily News, (818) 713-3702.
</P>
<P>
   DISNEY-RECALL (Los Angeles) _ Walt Disney Co., the world's No. 2
entertainment company, said it has recalled copies of the video
release of its animated film ``The Rescuers'' after finding
objectionable background images in two frames. Disney is pulling
3.4 million copies of a new version of the video released on
Tuesday. The two frames, out of a total of 110,000 in the film,
normally can't be seen by viewers because the video advances at the
rate of 30 frames per second. By Dave McNary. (Will move in the
``f'' financial news file.)
</P>
<P>
   FATAL-FIRE (Los Angeles) _ A woman was killed in a house fire
after Christmas lights inside and outside blew a fuse and set an
artificial tree afire. By Lisa Van Proyen (Will move in the ``n''
California news file.)
</P>
<P>
   DOUGHBOY-HONORED (Los Angeles) _ At 100 years old, World War I
veteran William Zelnicker was pinned with his Chevalier of the
French National Honor medal. Eighty years since he suffered a gas
attack in France where he was an stretcher bearer, Zelnicker
recalled the pain and suffering. He also recalled how he loved to
dance with his fiancee. By Steve Carney. (Will move in the ``n''
California and ``a'' national news file.)
</P>
<P>
   WALKING-GRANNY (Los Angeles) _ ``GrannyD'' Doris Haddock walks
through the Morengo Valley on Friday as she wraps up her first week
on the road to campaign finance reform. With a goal of walking 10
miles a day _ and a few rides along the way _ Haddock will take the
weekend off, then pick up her coast-to-coast walk again on Monday
in Yucca Valley, where they'll throw a parade for her. Along for
the walk this first week was fellow reformer Ken Hechler, 84, the
West Virginia Secretary of State. By Michael Coit. (Will move in
the ``n'' California and ``a'' national news file.)  &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL; 
QUAD-BIRTH (Los Angeles) _ A 31-year-old Santa Clarita woman has
delivered four baby girls, each weighing about 3 1/2 to 4 1/2
pounds. A friend of Kimberly and Martin Jacobsson has organized
more than 60 volunteers from local churches to provide
around-the-clock help for the quads during the next six months. By
Mary Schubert. (Will move in the ``n'' California news file.) &QL;
</P>
