<HEADER>
A5363 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-WEATHER-MAP-NYT &LR;      01-08 0417
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-WEATHER-MAP-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WEATHER 
</HEADLINE>
  (Editors: The following text accompanies the weather map for
Saturday, Jan. 9, sent to computer graphics clients of The New York
Times News Service. For information call: 212-556-4204.) 
(bl) 
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   NATIONAL FORECAST &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Pockets of moderate to locally heavy rain will fall along the
Eastern seaboard from northern Florida to southeastern New England
on Saturday as unseasonably moist air from the Gulf of Mexico and
the Atlantic Ocean is lifted by an advancing cold front.
Thunderstorms, some heavy, will erupt along the Southeast seaboard.
An isolated storm or two will approach severe levels, with damaging
straight-line winds posing the main threat for severe weather.
</P>
<P>
   In the wake of the cold front, precipitation will change to snow
as Arctic air presses eastward. Before the front arrives, a swath
of freezing rain or sleet will be occurring in some of the deep
valleys of New England, where trapped cold air holds steady against
the advance of milder air. Snow will accumulate a few inches in the
mountains from Pennsylvania to New York and the central mountains
of New England. Nearly all of the precipitation that occurs in the
mountains of northern New England will fall as snow.
</P>
<P>
   Snow showers and snow flurries will form near the southern and
eastern shores of the Great Lakes, with moderate snowfalls in a few
areas in the western Lower Peninsula of Michigan. Farther west,
another disturbance from the Canadian province of Alberta will
plunge southeast across the border. Owing to a lack of moisture,
only broken areas of generally light snow will fall over the
northern Plains.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, snow will continue on the west-facing slopes of the
northern Rockies as a plume of high-altitude Pacific moisture is
forced to rise over the mountainous terrain.
</P>
<P>
   FOCUS: Lightning With Snow
</P>
<P>
   Lightning accompanied an area of heavy snow across southern New
Jersey early Friday, offering the first clue that much of the snow
over the Northeast would eventually change to ice or rain.
Lightning with snow implies that a layer of warm, moist air a few
thousand feet above the ground has wedged between cold air near the
ground and cold air higher up. Then, invading warm, moist air rises
to form thundery clouds. A further incursion of warm air results in
falling snowflakes melting into raindrops, which may freeze into
pellets of ice or freeze on impact with cold surface objects.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-01-08-99 1906EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
