<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990108.0297 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-01-08 19:10 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5367 &Cx1f; paxxx
u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-STATES-STEEL-PA     01-08 0821
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-STATES-STEEL-PA </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;        MURTHA SAYS CLINTON STEEL PLAN NOT STRONG ENOUGH
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;     By Lisa Fine  
 &HT;    c. 1999 States News Service  
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON, Jan. 8 -- Rep. John Murtha dismissed the Clinton
administration's new plan for curbing cheap foreign steel imports,
calling it ``not strong or fast enough'' to help save jobs in
Pennsylvania and other steel-producing states.
</P>
<P>
   ``There has to be a stop to the subsidized steel coming into
this country,'' said Murtha, who is vice chair of the House Steel
Caucus. ``We need to enforce the trade laws in place, and expedite
the enforcement of those laws.''
</P>
<P>
   Murtha, D-Johnstown, said he was disappointed with the plan that
offers tax breaks for steel companies. He said steel industry
officials would not be satisfied because the administration did not
set quotas on steel imports or force nations to adopt voluntary
limits on their exports.
</P>
<P>
   Murtha said the plan did not send a message to countries that
``they cannot subsidize imports without penalty while we accept
financial losses and job losses in our domestic industry.''
</P>
<P>
   In a report ordered by Congress last term, Clinton outlined the
plan to give $300 million in tax breaks for steel companies that
claim to be losing money because they can't compete with foreign
companies that sell their product cheaper.
</P>
<P>
   ``Clinton's budget won't be done until February, and it won't be
approved until months later,'' said Murtha's spokesman Brad
Clemenson. ``The Congressman just doesn't think companies can wait
that long for that kind of relief. And it is not addressing the
problem of the surge of imports.''
</P>
<P>
   Foreign steel industry producers sent 3.9 million net tons to
the U.S. in September -- about a 49 percent increase in imports
from the same month last year, according to the American Iron and
Steel Institute.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton also promised to name a point-person who will make sure
government benefits are doled out quickly to the thousands of
laid-off steel workers whose companies had to cut back production,
according to the report released Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   The report said the administration will expedite its
investigations and enforcement actions under the country's trade
laws.
</P>
<P>
   But Murtha was not satisfied.
</P>
<P>
   ``There doesn't seem to be anything in the report that provides
the kind of comprehensive and immediate solution we need,'' Murtha
said.
</P>
<P>
   Just days after being sworn into the new Congress, Murtha said
his immediate priority will be to help the 2,000 or so steel
workers who live in the Johnstown area and commute to work at small
steel mills.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is really a crisis,'' Murtha said in a recent interview.
``I thought the president seemed to understand the gravity of the
situation and would be impressed enough to take strong action.''
</P>
<P>
   Steel industry officials in Pennsylvania and others states have
charged that foreign steel companies are selling their product so
cheaply that domestic companies can't compete or are having to cut
back in production.
</P>
<P>
   Foreign steel industry officials say they are not to blame.
Instead, they point to an over-supply of domestic steel caused by
the General Motors strike, and other economic conditions.
</P>
<P>
   The U.S. Commerce Department is expected to issue a preliminary
decision in mid-February on whether Japan, Russia and Brazil are
engaged in steel ``dumping'' -- selling their product for below
production cost, or below what it sells for in its home market.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our American steel worker needs protection from the dumping
that's going on by Japan, Korea, and other countries,'' Murtha
said. ``We need to keep pressing the White House for a more
immediate, workable response in the quickest possible time.''
</P>
<P>
   In the new Congress, Murtha said he also hopes to work on
reforming Social Security so that it will not go bankrupt.
</P>
<P>
   Along with the steel crisis, Social Security reform promises to
be a controversial issue in the next session.
</P>
<P>
   Murtha criticized some proposals already on the table for the
government to privately invest a portion of the taxes collected by
workers. The idea of private investments, usually proposed by
conservative lawmakers and economists, is that by linking Social
Security to the profits of the stock market, more money would be
available to be payed out in benefits.
</P>
<P>
   ``Letting people invest is too risky,'' Murtha said. ``I don't
know how that could be done to make sure it was safe. If we let
individuals invest, how do we know they would use it for Social
Security?''
</P>
<P>
   Murtha also criticized proposals for raising the retirement age,
saying the plans would not be beneficial.
</P>
<P>
   ``A lot of people in my district count on Social Security
payments as their sole source of income already,'' Murtha said.
``Raising the age won't help them.''
</P>
<P>
   As for what he thinks should be done?
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't know yet,'' Murtha said. ``We have a lot of really
important work to do in this session.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-01-08-99 1910EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
