<HEADER>
A5370 &Cx1f; ttd-z
r l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-LEAH-PERSONALS-$ADV11     01-08 0819
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-LEAH-PERSONALS-$ADV11-SFCHRON </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BEAUTY IS IN THE EYE OF THE BEHELD
</HEADLINE>
  
 ADVANCE for editions of Mon. Jan 11 and thereafter  
 (Eds: This story also moved in the ``a'' national news file)  
 By LEAH GARCHIK  
 c.1999 San Francisco Chronicle
<TEXT>
<P>
   Conceptual artist  &UR; Don Celender &LR; , whose solo show at the O.K.
Harris Gallery in New York is his 30th annual, has turned his
attention to museums this year. Celender contacted 300 small and
unusual museums and asked: ``Do you think your museum contributes
to the cultural life of Americans? ... Please say how.''
</P>
<P>
   The director of Baltimore's Dr. Samuel D. Harris National Museum
of Dentistry described it as a ``treasure house dedicated to all
things dental'' and called it ``a safe and friendly environment in
which to meet or seek refuge.'' The owner of the Wonder-View Tower
&AMP; Museum in Genoa, Colo., said he ``could go on and on'' describing
its delights, including the opportunity to ``see six states, 20,000
Indian artifacts, two-headed calves and so on.'' The owner of
Hartung's License Plate and Auto Museum in Glenview, Ill., said his
museum depicts ``the history of license plates from all 50
states,'' and the president of the RV/MH Hall of Fame in Elkhart,
Ind., boasted of visits by ``thousands of consumers and industry
personnel each year.'' Meanwhile, the director of the National
Lighter Museum in Guthrie, Okla., took pains to note, ``I have been
collecting lighters for 58 years and I have never smoked. ... I
have never looked at lighters simply as a means to light a
cigarette, but as man's first invention (a way to make fire).''
</P>
<P>
   The director of the Beer Can House in Houston said the house
contributes not only to ``Americans but all people of the world.''
``As a history lesson, the museum could be Beverage Industry 101,''
writes the director of the Beverage Containers Museum in
Millersville, Ky.
</P>
<P>
   The proprietor of the Mini Cake Museum in Pasadena reminds
Celender that ``cakes touch everyone, before birth and till
death''; in Denton, Texas, a man who calls himself ``the Pecan
Picasso'' and operates the ``world's only Pecan Art Museum'' notes
that he ``uses the medium of pecan art to portray people, animals
and objects (real and/or fictional) relating to Americana past and
present.''
</P>
<P>
   The owner of Earl's Art Gallery and Store in Vicksburg, Miss.,
demonstrates his patriotism: ``Americans have been striving for
freedom and independence for years, and I believe that by building
this museum it proves my freedom to build what I like and how I
like it.''
</P>
<P>
   The curator of the Arnold B. Tofias Industrial Archives in North
Easton, Mass., noted that although his center is ``not for the most
part a place to take out-of-town visitors,'' he's hoping to turn it
into more than ``the `shovel museum,' as it is frequently called.''
</P>
<P>
   The director of the American Sanitary Plumbing Museum in
Worcester, Mass., praised plumbers, the ``professional tradesmen
who have carried out their works knowing that the very lives of our
society depend upon their efforts. ... The significance of those
contributions is great. Our efforts to preserve and trace this
history are minor.''
</P>
<P>
   Equally modest was the executive director of the Water Ski
Museum in Winter Haven, Fla. Do you think your museum contributes
to the cultural life of Americans? she was asked. ``No,'' she
answered.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; SORTING OUT WHAT'S REALLY IMPORTANT &LR;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Donald McCullough &LR; , president of the San Francisco Theological
Seminary and professor of theology and preaching, is out with ``Say
Please, Say Thank You'' (Putnam; $21.95), a new book in which he
``explores many of life's little opportunities for treating others
with decency and consideration.''
</P>
<P>
   Among the opportunities cited by McCullough: keeping one's shoes
clean. ``It's a major disappointment to see a fine suit with a
distinctive tie against a neatly starched white shirt,'' writes the
theologian, ``and then discover at the foundation a pair of shoes
that seem not to have been touched by polish since they walked out
of the store in 1962. There's a man, I say to myself, who has no
follow-through, who can't be trusted with the details. ... Clothes
count.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; MONICA'S TOLL &LR;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Peter Bleiler &LR; , whose long-ago affair with  &UR; Monica Lewinsky &LR; 
made headlines after the Clinton scandal broke, has separated from
his wife, &UR; Kathlyn &LR; . Bleiler was a stage technician at Beverly Hills
High School when he began an affair with student Lewinsky.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think this whole year has played a terrible toll on them,''
said  &UR; Michael Nason &LR; , uncle of Kathlyn. ``They're truly a casualty
of the Monica Lewinsky scandal.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; WHO SAID WHAT &LR;
</P>
<P>
   ``I think Madonna called her a c_ once, but I'm sure she meant
it in the nicest possible way.''
</P>
<P>
   _ Liz Rosenberg, publicist for both Madonna and Cher, on the
former's opinion of the latter. Rosenberg is quoted in Spin
magazine.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-01-08-99 1913EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
