<DATE_TIME> 1999-01-08 19:15 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5377 &Cx1f; tad-z
u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-IMPEACH-CLINTON09-COX     01-08 0928
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-IMPEACH-CLINTON09-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    WHITE HOUSE EXPECTS QUICK SENATE VOTE TO DISMISS CASE
 &HT;    730&AMP;add.
 &HT;    By BOB DEANS
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ President Clinton's legal team predicted Friday
that the Senate would vote to dismiss the charges against him after
the first phase of the impeachment trial procedure approved Friday.
</P>
<P>
   That procedure _ adopted by all 100 senators of both parties _
calls for presentations by House prosecutors and the White House
defense team and questioning by the senators, followed immediately
by a motion to dismiss the perjury and obstruction of justice
charges outlined in the two articles of impeachment.
</P>
<P>
   The White House expressed confidence that it would win that
motion to dismiss, which would require the support of a simple
majority, or 51 senators.
</P>
<P>
   ''We are optimistic, we are confident that the senators, once
they see and hear this defense in this opening phase of the trial,
will conclude that the articles do not justify or warrant
conviction or removal from office,'' said Gregory Craig, special
counsel to the president. ''We remain hopeful that this matter can
be resolved expeditiously and fairly.''
</P>
<P>
   While the Senate procedure left open the possibility of a
drawn-out trial that could include witnesses and new revelations
about the president _ three possibilities Clinton's lawyers
fervently hope to avoid _ the White House refrained from
criticizing a plan that arrived with the backing of every member of
the Senate.
</P>
<P>
   ''The Senate has decided how it wants to proceed. We respect
that,'' Craig said in brief remarks to reporters at the White
House. ''And in accordance with the procedures adopted by the
Senate, we plan to present on behalf of the president a vigorous,
successful and complete defense.''
</P>
<P>
   Craig predicted that, through the motion to dismiss, the defense
team would head off the prospects for an extended trial, surprise
revelations or witnesses.
</P>
<P>
   If the motion to dismiss is defeated, however, the process
agreed to by the Senate on Friday poses grave risks to Clinton.
</P>
<P>
   If the trial moves into a second phase, senators would hear
presentations as to which witnesses should be called and for what
purpose. They would then vote on whether to depose those witnesses,
or subject them to questioning under oath.
</P>
<P>
   Finally, after reviewing the results of any depositions, the
Senate would be asked to vote on whether to call witnesses to
actually testify in the trial.
</P>
<P>
   Abbe Lowell, a Washington attorney who served as chief counsel
for the Democrats during the impeachment hearings last month before
the House Judiciary Committee, praised that portion of the process.
He said it would force anyone who wants to call witnesses to first
demonstrate why they were necessary, and then to show why it was
essential that they appear before the Senate.
</P>
<P>
   ''It's a good procedure,'' said Lowell.
</P>
<P>
   With Republicans holding a 55-45 advantage over Democrats, there
is a risk that Republicans could, by themselves, determine whether
to call witnesses and, if so, which witnesses to call.
</P>
<P>
   ''If you control who will testify and who will not testify, you
control the outcome,'' said Washington attorney James M. Cole, who
was special counsel in the House ethics committee's investigation
of former House Speaker Newt Gingrich, R-Ga.
</P>
<P>
   Cole said the Senate should decide whether to hold its trial
based solely on the evidence contained in the 7,000-page report the
House sent to the Senate to document its articles of impeachment,
or open up the trial to a full evidentiary hearing, with both
prosecutors and defense attorneys having the right to call
witnesses.
</P>
<P>
   ''If you're going to have a trial, you have a trial,'' said
Cole. ''You should have the lawyers in charge of determining who
the witnesses should be.''
</P>
<P>
   In an apparent effort to deal with that dilemma, the Senate
decided to name two Democrats and two Republicans to work with
senior staff members to try to clarify the procedures for dealing
with witnesses.
</P>
<P>
   Similarly, the Senate resolution provides for a vote on whether
to allow new information beyond that in the 7,000-page House report
to be introduced. That would add another dimension of potential
uncertainty for the White House defense team.
</P>
<P>
   ''They're still unsure of exactly what the Senate procedure will
be, they still have to prepare for too many contingencies,'' said
Lowell, of the Washington firm Brand, Lowell &AMP; Ryan. On balance,
though, ''I don't think it's a terrible process,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   (Story can end here. Optional add follows.)
</P>
<P>
   In keeping with his public strategy, Clinton ignored Friday's
proceedings, traveling to Detroit, where he used a speech to
economists to highlight the latest good news on the economy.
</P>
<P>
   On a day when Wall Street surged to record highs, Clinton
announced that unemployment last year, at 4.5 percent, was the
lowest since 1969, during the height of the Vietnam War, and was
the lowest peacetime annual unemployment figure since 1957.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton said the U.S. economy has been growing for 93
consecutive months, the longest peacetime expansion in the
country's history.
</P>
<P>
   The nation's rosy economic performance has been the leading
reason cited for Clinton's ability to maintain job approval ratings
topping 60 percent ever since last January, when the
sex-and-deception scandal involving former White House intern
Monica Lewinsky first surfaced.
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
