<P>
   AT&AMP;T-ACQUIRE (Undated) _ AT&AMP;T releases financial details of its
proposed acquisition of Tele-Communications Inc. Contrary to its
original plan, AT&AMP;T will not issue a tracking stock for its
consumer business or for any of its other operations, though it
will mount a 3-for-2 split of its common stock after the deal is
completed. Also, the company says its earnings this year will
exceed expectations and that it has agreed to form joint ventures
with five small cable operators. By Seth Schiesel.
</P>
<P>
   Center displays:
</P>
<P>
   DOLLAR-DECLINE (Washington) _ Even while the stock market hits
new highs, a crucial indicator of foreign confidence in the U.S.
government and economy _ the dollar _ has been falling. No one can
agree why. By all the normal measures, it should not be happening.
By David E. Sanger. WITH GRAPHIC.
</P>
<P>
   EURO-MARKETS (Frankfurt) _ Except for a few minor procedural
glitches, the euro finished its first week as Europe's new single
currency with remarkable smoothness. By Edmund L. Andrews.
</P>
<P>
   Others:
</P>
<P>
   MARKETS-ASIA (Hong Kong) _ The bulls finally stop stampeding
across Asia, but the recent sharp gains in stock prices from Seoul
to Singapore are worrying analysts, who are alarmed by the growing
disparity between the rising markets and Asia's still-sinking
economies. By Mark Landler.
</P>
<P>
   MARKET (New York) _ The stock market took a volatile ride to new
highs, finishing a week marked by an Internet stock frenzy, a surge
in other technology stocks and new data that showed the U.S.
economy is refusing to slow down. The Dow's Friday close was a
10.56 gain. By Clyde Fuerbringer.
</P>
<P>
   The New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
