<SLUG> BC-TOBACCO-TEXAS-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BUSH QUESTIONS TRIAL LAWYERS' MOTIVES IN SEEKING TOBACCO SETTLEMENT
DELAY 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By CLAY ROBISON 
c.1998 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   AUSTIN, Texas _ Gov. George W. Bush questioned Friday whether
private trial lawyers who helped the state win a $17.3 billion
tobacco settlement will try _ at the state's expense _ to fatten
the $3.3 billion in legal fees that cigarette companies have
already agreed to pay them.
</P>
<P>
   Bush said he will fight a motion recently filed in federal court
by the five lawyers that would ``delay letting taxpayers off the
hook for legal fees.''
</P>
<P>
   John Cornyn, the new attorney general, said he shared the
governor's concerns.
</P>
<P>
   But a spokesman for the lawyers said the state had nothing to
worry about. He said the lawyers were only seeking more time so
they could meet with Cornyn before formally closing the tobacco
case.
</P>
<P>
   The outside lawyers want to ``bring this to an early and
amicable resolution,'' the spokesman said.
</P>
<P>
   Bush and Cornyn, then a candidate for attorney general, spent
much of last year fighting then-Attorney General Dan Morales, who
left office Dec. 31, over the legal fees.
</P>
<P>
   Morales hired the five private attorneys _ Walter Umphrey and
Wayne Reaud of Beaumont, John O'Quinn and John Eddie Williams of
Houston and Harold Nix of Daingerfield _ on a 15 percent
contingency contract to try the tobacco case.
</P>
<P>
   The opposing sides reached a truce last summer to give a
three-member, national arbitration panel time to set the fees. The
panel last month awarded the lawyers $3.3 billion _ more than 15
percent _ which the tobacco industry is committed to pay under the
state's settlement.
</P>
<P>
   The five lawyers received their first payment of about $200
million shortly before Christmas. It will be many years before the
Texas lawyers' entire award is paid because the industry has set a
cap of $500 million a year on lawyer payments from all states, and
most states have now settled lawsuits with the cigarette makers.
</P>
<P>
   Bush said the private attorneys had until Dec. 30 to tell U.S.
District Judge David Folsom of Texarkana, who presided over Texas'
tobacco lawsuit, that they were releasing the state from any claims
for additional payments.
</P>
<P>
   Instead, the lawyers asked Folsom for more time.
</P>
<P>
   ``I am appalled at the nerve of lawyers who have been awarded an
exorbitant fee yet refuse to honor their agreement and let our
taxpayers off the hook,'' Bush said.
</P>
<P>
   The lawyers' spokesman, who didn't want to be identified, said
the attorneys asked for the delay to give them time to meet with
Cornyn to discuss various issues, including how much the federal
government may seek from the state's settlement to cover federal
Medicaid expenditures.
</P>
<P>
   ``What this suggests to me is they are not satisfied with $3.3
billion and intend to go for more,'' Cornyn said, adding that he
would fight the lawyers if that is the case.
</P>
<P>
   Cornyn said he also is investigating what role a sixth attorney,
Marc Murr of Houston, had in the tobacco case. Murr was awarded $1
million by the national arbitration panel, although other lawyers
in the case said he did little, if any, work on the lawsuit.
</P>
<P>
   Morales, before he left office, said Murr did important work on
the case.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY &QL;
</P>
