<DATE_TIME> 1999-01-08 19:25 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5385 &Cx1f; tad-z
u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-PEPSI-STOCK09-COX     01-08 0535
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-PEPSI-STOCK09-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Pepsi strengthens No. 2 spot with bottling spinoff
 &HT;    By Mickey H. Gramig
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Pepsico Inc. on Friday filed notice with the
Securities and Exchange Commission that it will spin off its
bottling business, a move expected to raise $1 billion and make the
No. 2 soft drink maker a more formidable competitor for
Atlanta-based Coca-Cola Co.
</P>
<P>
   The lengthy filing left many questions unanswered, such as when
the Purchase, N.Y.-based company plans the initial public offering
for its bottling subsidiary, Pepsi Bottling Group, how shares will
be priced and how much of a stake Pepsico plans to keep in the
operation.
</P>
<P>
   Analysts, who say the IPO is expected this spring, have hailed
plans for the spinoff. Morgan Stanley analyst Andrew Conway has
called it ``the most positive strategic action by Pepsico since the
acquisition of Frito-Lay more than 30 years ago.''
</P>
<P>
   Pepsi's stock closed Friday at $41.37 1/2, up 62 1/2 cents,
after nearly 5.2 million shares changed hands.
</P>
<P>
   Pepsico's board approved the sale in November as a way to
separate the low margin, cash-intensive bottling business from the
company's more profitable concentrate operation. Such a strategy,
which lessens financial volatility and earnings pressures, has paid
off for Coca-Cola, which in 1986 sold 51 percent of its bottling
operation to form Coca-Cola Enterprises, now the world's largest
soft drink bottler.
</P>
<P>
   Pepsi Bottling Group, which now handles 54 percent of Pepsico's
domestic volume and 32 percent of the company's volume worldwide,
would be able to ``invest significantly'' in infrastructure after
the spin-off, according to the SEC filing.
</P>
<P>
   Currently, the bottler has 36,900 full-time employees, 72
production plants and 296 distribution facilities. It uses 16,500
vehicles and 1.3 million vending machines to sell more than 100
million 8-oz. servings of Pepsi products each day.
</P>
<P>
   The bottler makes and sells Pepsi products in 39 states, the
District of Columbia, eight Canadian provinces, Spain, Greece and
Russia, and last year accounted for $6.8 billion of Pepsico's $20.9
billion total revenue.
</P>
<P>
   The filing makes it clear that the bottler will remain indelibly
linked to Pepsico. The bottler is leasing space for its
headquarters at Pepsi-Cola Co.'s Somers, N.Y., corporate campus, a
short drive from Purchase. Pepsico executives are expected to serve
on the bottler's board.
</P>
<P>
   Furthermore, the bottler will be required to submit annual
marketing, advertising, management and financial plans to Pepsico
for review and approval.
</P>
<P>
   If Pepsico executives don't like what they see, they can
terminate their agreement to provide the bottler with soft drink
concentrate, marketing dollars and other vital means of support.
</P>
<P>
   The sale is part of Pepsico Chief Executive Roger Enrico's
efforts to compete more aggressively against rival Coca-Cola. In
the past year he's spun off the company's KFC, Taco Bell and Pizza
Hut restaurants, bought the Tropicana juice business for $3.3
billion and brought in a new management team for the beverage
division.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
