<DOCNO> NYT19990108.0310 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-01-08 19:28 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5390 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-OLY-RESIGNATIONS-BOS &LR;      01-08 0928
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-OLY-RESIGNATIONS-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TWO SALT LAKE OFFICIALS RESIGN AMID ALLEGATIONS 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Includes `big payoff' text table)   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JOHN POWERS  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   The top two heads rolled at the Salt Lake Organizing Committee
Friday as the worst scandal in modern Olympic history broadened and
deepened.
</P>
<P>
   Frank Joklik and Dave Johnson, the committee's president and
senior vice president, respectively, resigned under pressure after
admitting that SLOC officials made cash payments to International
Olympic Committee members, apparently to influence enough votes to
land the 2002 Winter Games.
</P>
<P>
   ``The actions during the Olympic bidding process that besmirch
our reputation break my heart,'' said Joklik, who was chairman of
the bid committee when the Utah capital was awarded the Games three
years ago but denied knowing about the payoffs.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was shocked and dismayed over new revelations regarding
actions of the former bid committee,'' added Joklik, who has been
involved with the Olympic bid for more than a decade. ``Although I
had no personal knowledge of these activities, it became clear that
changes must be made in order for the Games to proceed.''
</P>
<P>
   Two other senior SLOC officials _ marketing and legal affairs
vice president Kelly Flint and licensing director Rod Hamson _ were
placed on paid leave. And former president Tom Welch, who resigned
in 1997 after spousal abuse allegations, will no longer receive a
$10,000-a-month consulting fee.
</P>
<P>
   Earlier in the week, Utah Governor Mike Leavitt had urged top
SLOC officials to step down amid ongoing investigations by the IOC,
US Olympic Committee, and US Department of Justice.
</P>
<P>
   SLOC officials had already admitted to paying hundreds of
thousands of dollars in college tuition for relatives of IOC
members and providing free medical care, lavish trips, and
expensive gifts, including a pair of shotguns for IOC president
Juan Antonio Samaranch.
</P>
<P>
   When the New York Times Friday reported that individual cash
payments up to $70,000 had been made to IOC members, Joklik and
Johnson stepped down after meeting with USOC officials.
</P>
<P>
   ``We deplore it,'' Leavitt said of the scandal, which has also
rocked the august IOC, which prides itself on being beyond
financial and political influence. ``We cannot avoid the fact that
we've been injured. We will clean this wound.''
</P>
<P>
   Samaranch, who does not vote for Olympic host cities and said he
did not ask for the shotguns, said he regretted the shakeup but
that ``they had to do it.''
</P>
<P>
   The IOC, which confirmed Friday that Salt Lake City still will
be allowed to stage the Games, is conducting its own investigation
of the bribery scandal, with Samaranch vowing to expel any members
who sold their votes.
</P>
<P>
   IOC vice president Richard Pound of Canada spent two days in
Salt Lake City last month interviewing officials and gathering
documents. ``We're looking at everything that might be regarded as
inappropriate conduct,'' said Pound, who estimated that his inquiry
panel would have its findings complete in two weeks.
</P>
<P>
   After competing unsuccessfully for the Winter Games several
times and losing the 1998 bid by four votes to Nagano, Salt Lake
decided to make sure it had enough support for 2002. So the
committee focused on IOC members from Africa, who had no stake in
where the Winter Games were held.
</P>
<P>
   Besides the cash payoffs, the SLOC paid nearly $400,000 for
college tuition or athletic training for 13 people, six of them
related to IOC members.
</P>
<P>
   Committee officials also provided $28,000 of free medical
treatment, including a knee replacement, for three IOC members from
Africa at a local hospital. They helped arrange a Utah land deal
that turned a $60,000 profit for IOC member Jean-Claude Ganga of
the Republic of Congo. And they procured jobs for relatives of IOC
members with local companies.
</P>
<P>
   According to Marc Hodler of Switzerland, the IOC's
longest-serving member, the SLOC was merely doing what other bid
cities have done for years.
</P>
<P>
   ``Nobody blames Salt Lake City,'' said Hodler, who claimed that
the 1996, 1998, 2000, and 2002 Games were all tainted with
vote-buying. ``We blame those voters who can be bought. For us,
Salt Lake City was a victim of blackmail and not a villain.''
</P>
<P>
   Ironically, Salt Lake, which blew away Oestersund (Sweden) and
Sion (Switzerland) by a 54-14 margin on the first ballot, didn't
need the African votes. And since balloting is secret, the Utah
group couldn't be sure it had gotten the votes it was paying for.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is absolutely certain that Salt Lake City didn't need to do
this sort of thing to win,'' said IOC director general Francois
Carrard. ``The value of the bid was absolutely uncontestable.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(Wire service material was used to prepare this report.)
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
The BIG PAYOFF &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   What Salt Lake City allegedly did for Olympic votes:
</P>
<P>
   _Made cash payments ranging from $5,000-$70,000 to unidentified
International Olympic Committee members from Africa and Latin
America.
</P>
<P>
   _Paid nearly $400,000 for college tuition or athletic training
for 13 people, six of them related to IOC members.
</P>
<P>
   _Arranged a Utah land deal that turned a $60,000 profit for IOC
member Jean-Claude Ganga of the Republic of Congo.
</P>
<P>
   _Provided $28,000 of free medical treatment, including a knee
replacement, at a local hospital for three IOC members from Africa.
</P>
<P>
   _Procured local jobs for relatives of IOC members.
</P>
<P>
   _Offered free ski trips to Utah resorts.
</P>
<P>
   _Gave skis and shotguns to IOC members.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-01-08-99 1928EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990108.0311 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-01-08 19:28 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5391 &Cx1f; tta-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-EMBASSY-BOMBS-3RDTAKE     01-08 0888
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-EMBASSY-BOMBS-3RDTAKE-NYT </SLUG>
  
 UNDATED: the Kenyans. 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Senior officials at CIA headquarters urged the station chief to
reconsider, but they said the decision was ultimately his, and he
held his ground.
</P>
<P>
   There were no interviews. Because the documents seized from the
group's offices showed no evidence of a bombing plot, the CIA soon
dropped its investigation. Without any evidence against
Al-Haramain, the agency concluded that its informant was not
credible, officials said. Kenya washed its hands of the group,
ordering the nine deported.
</P>
<P>
   But some members of the counter-terrorism team were furious,
officials said, and complained that their investigation had been
dangerously short-circuited. They felt they were unable to conduct
a thorough investigation without talking to the suspects
themselves. Some team members blamed the decision on the station
chief's lack of field experience; he was a career analyst from the
CIA's directorate of intelligence on his first overseas espionage
assignment. Embassy officials say they were not aware of the
internal CIA dispute, and add that they assumed at the time that it
was the Kenyans who had denied access to the suspects. ``Why would
you not want to interview them?'' asked one State Department
official.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Bushnell was told of the findings of the inquiry, and
assured that the threat had been eliminated by the arrests. In
fact, there were some lingering questions. Some intelligence
officials believed at the time that members of the charity were
tied to bin Laden.
</P>
<P>
   It was, perhaps, another clue about possible terrorist activity
in Kenya. However, the CIA did not circulate any intelligence
reports throughout the rest of the government about the case.
</P>
<P>
   Today, intelligence officials insist there is no evidence
linking the group to the embassy bombings. But they say they now
have evidence that connects them to bin Laden. The agency's
inspector general is examining the case.
</P>
<P>
   A third warning surfaced in November, 1997. Mustafa Mahmoud Said
Ahmed, an Egyptian, walked into the embassy and told CIA officers
he knew of a group that was planning to detonate a bomb-laden truck
inside the diplomats' underground parking garage.
</P>
<P>
   In a separate interrogation by Kenyan security officials, which
was relayed to the Americans, Ahmed made his own involvement in the
plot clear, saying he had already taken surveillance photos of the
embassy for the attack, which he said was to involve several
vehicles and stun grenades.
</P>
<P>
   The CIA issued two intelligence reports on Ahmed's statements,
but cautioned in its reports that Ahmed may have fabricated his
story, thus downplaying the significance of the warning.
</P>
<P>
   But Ahmed is now being held in jail in Tanzania in connection
with the Dar es Salaam embassy bombing, and U.S. officials still
aren't sure what to make of his 1997 warning.
</P>
<P>
   The warnings in August and November prompted Ms. Bushnell to
renew her case for a new embassy.
</P>
<P>
   On December 15, 1997, she sent a report back to State Department
headquarters warning that the embassy's location made it
``extremely vulnerable to a terrorist attack,'' and that it had to
be replaced with a more secure building.
</P>
<P>
   Less than two weeks later, on December 24th, she sent another
cable noting again that ``the embassy's security profile, in a
congested, downtown location, is cause for serious concern,'' and
asked for a comprehensive review of the embassy's security status.
</P>
<P>
   She also asked that State Department officials go back to
Congress to ask for more money in order to fund a new Nairobi
embassy.
</P>
<P>
   Senior officials were not swayed, arguing that the dangers were
nonexistent or already dissipated. Ahmed's warning, one senior
official said, had been largely discounted as not credible. The
Kenyans had taken care of the more serious threat, he said, by
arresting members of al-Haramain.
</P>
<P>
   In a January 1998 budget review concerning embassy construction
funding, which included Undersecretary of State for Management
Bonnie Cohen and other senior officials, Ms. Bushnell's request was
not seriously considered, officials acknowledged.
</P>
<P>
   In a response to her warnings of a worsening terrorist threat,
in a January 1998 cable, Ms. Bushnell was told by headquarters that
other embassy projects had priority, and that a new Nairobi embassy
was not in the State Department's future plans.
</P>
<P>
   The cable said that headquarters agreed that a ``new chancery
would be ideal,'' but that State ``had reviewed the case and
understood her concerns'' and had turned her down. In fact, the
State Department had a long wish list of embassies it eventually
wanted to replace, and Nairobi was not on it.
</P>
<P>
   Congressional and State Department officials say that, prior to
the August embassy bombings, State asked Congress to include funds
in its fiscal 1999 budget for only two new embassies _ in Beijing
and Berlin. Those were the only new embassies the State Department
had sought congressional funding for since at least fiscal 1996.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Bushnell's increasingly insistent demands for a new embassy
were so far out of step with the State Department's plans that
officials at headquarters were beginning to see her as a nuisance
who was obsessed by security, according to one official familiar
with the matter.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-01-08-99 1928EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
