<HEADER>
A5396 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u k &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-NYHAN-COLUMN-$ADV10-B     01-08 1188
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NYHAN-COLUMN-$ADV10-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
AMERICA, THE BEAUTIFUL: FROM SEMEN TO SHINING C-SPAN 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (For release Sunday, January 10, 1999)   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By DAVID NYHAN  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   With 355 days to go before you-know-what, it is possible to make
some definitive claims about our fair country as the millennium
draws nigh:
</P>
<P>
   1. The American economy, despite everything we've learned about
burst bubbles this century, looks bulletproof. Not even the
.50-caliber Asian meltdown, the Japanese swoon, Russia's collapse
into kleptocracy or the successful advent of the euro can dampen
the planet's hottest economic volcano. New home sales, car and
truck sales, gasoline at a buck a gallon, the stock market: This
baby just keeps pouring out the good-times lava and sucking in the
investment cash.
</P>
<P>
   2. The Klown Kollege of Kongress that is the House of
Representatives is even less essential to the country's progress
than we had suspected. The tawdry descent into partisan and
prurient persecution of the presidency that has diminished the
standing of the House now threatens to engulf the more staid
Senate. The public stubbornly refuses to abandon President Clinton
despite the philandering; his job approval poll numbers persist
despite the worst efforts of his Republican enemies and the ``new''
news media.
</P>
<P>
   3. The infotainment industry formerly known as network news is
melting before the eyes for which advertisers fork over huge chunks
of money. Word that the Nielsen numbers show a 6 percent decline
for 1998 in the 18- to 34-year-old television viewing audience hit
network execs right in the old breadbasket. Standing of network
news? Right alongside Kongress's. Those ``White House in Crisis''
logos are now more than a year old.
</P>
<P>
   4. The befuddled conglomerates that paid top dollar for the
networks are turning to the oldest medium (let's hear it for
books!) or the oldest gimmick in show biz: running out the sequel.
How do the geniuses running television handle the dilemma of their
incredible shrinking audiences? You had to ask. Peter Jennings
(ABC) and Tom Brokaw (NBC) put their names on books that sold big
numbers during the Christmas gift season.
</P>
<P>
   Somehow, I just don't see the 18-to-34 crowd flocking to Barnes
&AMP; Noble or Amazon.com for the Pete and Tom tomes. I hope I'm wrong.
Over at Black Rock, CBS is cooking up ``60 Minutes II,'' a Dan
Rather-led rehash of ``60 Minutes'' (get it?), the aging
industry-standard TV news magazine.
</P>
<P>
   5. The Seasoned Six of ``60 Minutes'' _ Mike Wallace, Morley
Safer, Ed Bradley, Lesley Stahl, Steve Kroft, and cranky old Andy
Rooney _ have amassed the astonishing collective total of 127
years' service on the program, and 176 years combined at CBS. How
old was the hotshot VP who came back to the office from lunch and
said: ``Hey, how about a knockoff of that show we run Sunday nights
with all the geezers? That should yank those 18- to 34-year-olds
away from their VCRs and PCs, huh?''
</P>
<P>
   6. Not to be outdone in the obeisance to our elders is the US
Senate. To receive the articles of impeachment hand-delivered by
septuagenarian US Representative Henry Hyde, 74, the House
Judiciary foreman of the get-Clinton gang, and the nation's oldest
confessed political adulterer on record, the Senate trotted out
Strom Thurmond, Republican of South Carolina, who is 96, and a
ladies' man of note for much of this past century.
</P>
<P>
   7. It is not only the networks and the Klown Kongress that need
help with their image, and their grip on the public imagination. We
in the newspaper game (a.k.a. The Dead Pine Tree biz) struggle to
maintain circulatory health. The Monica Story, a.k.a. Devil in the
Blue Dress, turned out to be an empty-calorie fast-food fix for
what ails us. You are what you eat? Ugh! Thank God the ads still
stick to your ribs. Today's Sunday Globe help-wanted section of 162
pages of jobs begging for workers is the third-largest such section
ever. Did I say bulletproof? You can't slow down this economy with
Kryptonite.
</P>
<P>
   8. We burn through personalities in the news biz at a pace that
would make Andy Warhol proud. Who are the, ahem, journalists who
made the biggest splash in 1998? I give you _ please, I'm trying to
give these first two guys away _ the following choices:
</P>
<P>
   A. Larry Flynt. B. Matt Drudge. C. Geraldo Rivera. D. Joe
Lelyveld.
</P>
<P>
   The envelope, please?
</P>
<P>
   Flynt is the skin mag tycoon who was into pornography before
special prosecutor Ken Starr and the House Republicans discovered
the power of prurience. Drudge is the cyber-punk who trolls the
bottom of the barrel for the top of the news. Rivera is the
formerly-declasse downmarket TV hyper (i.e., one who hypes) who has
rehabilitated himself with punchy puncturing of the vast right-wing
conspiracy (Hillary is right again) to demonize Clinton. And
Lelyveld? Oh, he's only the top editor at The New York Times. You
never see him on TV. He must work for a living. While on the
subject: Anyone heard from Rush Limbaugh lately? How come no one
mentions him anymore?
</P>
<P>
   9. The collective silence of all those who would succeed Clinton
(save for his ever-present defender Al Gore) on this impeachment
stinker is deafening. They are like visitors to the bedside of the
deathly ill: shaking hands, shuffling feet, clearing throats,
shifting eyes, mouthing inanities, doing anything to avoid saying
the obvious. This is leadership?
</P>
<P>
   10. There is a way to resolve Washington's plunge into the
sheepdip. Since a vast silence engulfed my first assay on how to
resolve the Washington imbroglio, I repeat it, in truncated form:
A. The Senate vote to remove Clinton falls short of the 67 needed.
B. A harshly worded resolution of censure is adopted by a vote of
99 to 1. (I don't know who the one will be; I just know there's
always at least one.) C. The chastened president is summoned to the
floor of the House chamber, and is read the riot act by Thurmond,
which takes a long time, because he's such a slow talker.
</P>
<P>
   And, then, D. Former Presidents Ford, Carter and Bush give
10-minute declamations on the need for presidents to obey the law,
tell the truth, resist groping the help, and set an upstanding
example for the youth of America. (Maybe in the spirit of the
occasion, Bush apologizes for fibbing about Iran-contra on Rather's
show.) E. Clinton has to stand there chewing his lip, taking his
medicine, unbidden to speak.
</P>
<P>
   Being shamed in silence is a huge punishment for this guy. He's
always been able to talk his way out of everything, but the genius
of my plan is that Big Bill just has to listen; he can't wangle his
way out with mere words. F. Everyone sings ``America the
Beautiful.'' G. the Rev. Billy Graham delivers a benediction. H.
Everyone goes home for lunch. I. Next day, everyone gets back to
their regular jobs, including Clinton and the TV moguls, who call
an 8 a.m. emergency meeting to ask underlings: ``So what bright
ideas do you have for replacing all the Monica stories and
Clinton-in-crisis stuff? Anyone heard from O. J. lately?''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(David Nyhan is a Globe columnist.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-01-08-99 1929EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
