<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-RYAN-COLUMN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SHANAHAN HOPES THE CROWD IS IN IT THIS TIME 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By BOB RYAN  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   DENVER _ Here's a question for you. What do you suppose the good
people of Denver are talking about this morning? Is it the
under-.500 Avalanche, the 11-71 Nuggets going back to work, the
Rockies re-signing Curtis Leskanic, or the defending Super Bowl
champion Broncos beginning defense of their title at Mile High
Stadium against the Miami Dolphins?
</P>
<P>
   Duh.
</P>
<P>
   And as the fans are talking about the team, so the head coach is
talking about them. He holds them at least partly accountable for
the most shocking and depressing result of his four-year tenure in
Denver. On Jan. 4, 1997, the prohibitively favored AFC West
champion Broncos were knocked out of the playoffs by the
Jacksonville Jaguars right here in Mile High Stadium, where the
team had won all eight of its regular-season games and was starting
to feel invincible.
</P>
<P>
   There were many reasons for the 30-27 Jacksonville victory, most
notably 245 yards and two touchdown passes by quarterback Mark
Brunell and 140 yards rushing and one touchdown by battering ram
Natrone Means. But to those reasons Denver coach Mike Shanahan adds
one more.
</P>
<P>
   The fans didn't do their job.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think there's any question about it,'' he says. ``In
that Jacksonville game two years ago, we had a very nonchalant
crowd. I was very surprised. But I don't anticipate that happening
again this time.''
</P>
<P>
   Let the record show that the Broncos haven't lost a game in this
venerable Den of Din since that day. They have gone 8-0 at home in
each of the last two regular seasons and they added a 42-17 revenge
triumph over the Jaguars in the wild-card game last season. You can
make a compelling case that no team in the NFL operates from a
better position of strength than the Denver Broncos at Mile High
Stadium.
</P>
<P>
   Though nobody in the Broncos' camp speaks openly of payback, the
simple truth is that this game has a little bonus for the defending
champs. On the night of Dec. 21, the Broncos went into Miami's Pro
Player Stadium and got spanked. The final score was 31-21, and it
was probably a bit more authoritative than that.
</P>
<P>
   Shanahan &AMP; Co. say that is a matter of greater interest to the
media and fans than to his team. Even if his team had beaten the
Dolphins by three touchdowns that evening, he would be looking at
Miami strictly as a quality opponent. What happened Dec. 21, he
says, will be of little consequence Saturday. His team would have
needed a big effort no matter who had shown up.
</P>
<P>
   Shanahan is one of the great I-dotters and T-crossers in the
game, and he says his team is ready to go. Oh, there is the matter
of return specialist Vaughn Hebron and a hamstring boo-boo (there
is little likelihood he will play), and 2,008-yard rusher Terrell
Davis will play with a flak jacket to protect tender ribs, and
veteran defensive end Neil Smith is banged up, and a bunch of other
guys have assorted owies, but, says Shanahan, ``This is pro
football, and these things are to be expected.
</P>
<P>
   ``I thought we got a lot of work done this week,'' he adds.
``The intensity was there.''
</P>
<P>
   Two years ago, the Broncos finished 13-3 and were rewarded with
the much-coveted first-round bye. Big deal. They lost, anyway. Last
year they started out as a wild card and ended up as world champs
by defeating Green Bay in one of the great Super Bowls ever. So
what's the moral of that story?
</P>
<P>
   According to Shanahan, there is none. You'd better be ready to
play; that's all.
</P>
<P>
   One thing the Broncos do not have is doubt. Nobody writes any
Carrollian stories in Denver on the subject of questionable
leadership. Being a highly successful NFL coach is a matter of
having that elusive ``It,'' and there is unanimous agreement that
whatever ``It'' is, Mike Shanahan is in possession of same. And you
really can't win the whole thing without having ``It'' _ unless, of
course, your name is Barry Switzer and you have about 18 potential
Pro Bowlers on your team.
</P>
<P>
   ``You must believe in the coach and his staff,'' reports
fullback Howard Griffith. ``If you don't, you can't win. If you
didn't believe in the coaching staff, that would mean you wouldn't
have faith in the offensive schemes, the defensive schemes, or the
special teams. You have to believe in them. Look at Bill Parcells.
Those players believe in what he says. He brings out the best in
people.''
</P>
<P>
   (Ed. note: I swear on every available religious work imaginable
that Mr. Griffith brought up the subject of The Tuna spontaneously.
He was absolutely, positively not coached).
</P>
<P>
   ``It is not possible to win unless you believe in the coach and
the staff,'' agrees safety Steve Atwater. ``People can have
opinions, but in the end, you must believe that the coach is
putting the best players on the field and giving you the best
possible game plans. As players, you want someone to take the
pressure off you, and that's what a good coaching staff does. We
have that here.''
</P>
<P>
   The Broncos believe they can win because they have won, and
because they believe they are better technically than they were
last year. But they also know they must win with their bodies and
heads and not with their mouths and hearts. They must stop Dan
Marino and they must find a way to score at least two touchdowns
against a very rugged and aggressive Miami defense. They also know
they can't expect the crowd to win the game for them, although they
would appreciate it if the crowd would live up to its reputation.
</P>
<P>
   It is time to play. The champs are primed for battle. ``I think
we're ready, but we'll find out on Saturday,'' says Shanahan. ``Our
football team has had a great week of practice. But talk is cheap.
We'll find out how ready we are Saturday afternoon.''
</P>
<P>
   And God help the crowd if they let Mike Shanahan down again.
Have you ever seen the serial-killer look in this man's eyes?
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(Bob Ryan is a Globe columnist.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
