<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BOX-JONES-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FRAZIER OUTGUNNED AGAINST JONES 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By RON BORGES  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Normally, Ricky Frazier tries to prevent muggings. Saturday
he'll be involved in one.
</P>
<P>
   It would be nice to say that a 39-year-old New York cop has a
chance to beat World Boxing Association and World Boxing Council
light heavyweight champion Roy Jones Jr. at the Pensacola (Fla.)
Civic Center, but that would be accurate only if you conceded that
Jones also has a chance to be hit by a meteor on the way into the
ring.
</P>
<P>
   Both are true. Neither will happen.
</P>
<P>
   Take the word of the people televising the fight.
</P>
<P>
   ``Ricky Frazier should not be fighting Roy Jones,'' HBO Sports
senior vice president for programming Lou DiBella admitted
recently, even though he's the guy paying for the fight. ``He does
not have an iota of a chance to win. He's not a worthy opponent for
Roy.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's not Ricky's fault. It's not Roy's fault. It's not our
fault. It's a mandated mismatch.''
</P>
<P>
   Indeed it is, courtesy of the alphabet organizations that foist
such fights on both the public and world champions who have no
choice but to show up or lose the titles they worked so hard to
win. That is why Jones is in Pensacola and also why lightweight
champion Shane Mosley will fight Golden Johnson on the undercard.
If either is challenged, someone should check their water bottles.
</P>
<P>
   This has been been Jones's fate for a time now and will continue
for at least one more fight. After this match, he has already been
told, he must fight another mandatory challenger, Dario Mattioni,
before he can try to unify the 175-pound title against
International Boxing Federation champion Reggie Johnson.
</P>
<P>
   As for Frazier's fate, it is simply this: Before this night is
out, he will know what it means to be NYPD blue. Black-and-blue, as
a matter of fact.
</P>
<P>
   Frazier (18-3-1) is a cop from Harlem who boxes on the side when
given the opportunity. He is a man who can take care of himself,
but not in this fight, because he is in the kind of predicament all
cops try to avoid. He's facing someone with a lot more weapons than
he has.
</P>
<P>
   Even his fellow officers have been ribbing him unmercifully
about this undertaking, because cops know trouble when they see it,
and what Frazier's friends see in Jones is a lot of trouble for
their man.
</P>
<P>
   ``I wanted Ricky to put my photos on the bottom of his shoes so
when he hits the canvas, I could see myself on TV,'' said Francis
Seguinot, who works with Frazier in the 26th Precinct.
</P>
<P>
   That is not the kindest thing that could be said about you, but
Frazier is used to it. He has come to work and found posters of
Jones staring back at him from his locker. He has seen a message
from ``a Mr. Jones'' pinned to a bulletin board asking for him to
call because Mr. Jones has an extra-strength can of whip-ass
waiting for him.
</P>
<P>
   Frazier has heard these skeptical points of view ever since he
turned pro at the advanced age of 32 following a foray into
kickboxing and a brief spell as New York Golden Gloves champion as
both a middleweight and light heavyweight. Since then, he has had
to scuffle to make a living with his fists, never earning more than
$12,000 until promoter Don King got him a No. 1 ranking (wonder
how?) and a $400,000 payday.
</P>
<P>
   That will be hard-earned money. It will likely also be blood
money, because Frazier's blood seems destined to stain his trunks
and probably the floor before he collects. It is highly likely King
will collect more than Frazier does and just as likely Frazier will
have to collect his wits after Jones (38-1, 30 knockouts) scatters
them around the ring.
</P>
<P>
   Yet this is Ricky Frazier's moment, and he hopes to seize it. It
is his moment even if it lasts only a moment. It is his moment
until Roy Jones Jr. makes clear it is not . . . which should take
only a moment, by the way.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
