<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-01-08 19:32 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5403 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-TV-COLDWAR-GARDNER-NY     01-08 1266
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TV-COLDWAR-GARDNER-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ARMS RACE HAD MOMENTUM, BUT IT'S NOT THE WHOLE STORY
</HEADLINE>
   (See TV-COLDWAR-INTRO, TV-COLDWAR-RADOSH, TV-COLDWAR-GADDIS) 
Lloyd C. Gardner teaches history at Rutgers University.  
(dw) 
 By LLOYD C. GARDNER   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   The opening sequence in CNN's first episode of ``Cold War''
takes viewers on a tour of the secret underground rooms where the
business of government was to be carried on in case of nuclear war.
In a subsequent episode, Robert S. McNamara tells an interviewer
that when he became Secretary of Defense in 1961, he knew almost
nothing about nuclear weapons. Learning quickly, he said, he
dedicated his life to making sure that they would never be used.
``It's not mad,'' McNamara says quietly of the nuclear stand-off
and the policy of mutual assured destruction (MAD); it was the best
way to keep the peace.
</P>
<P>
   There is a meditative sense of inevitability in McNamara's
reflections on the arms race. As the still familiar events of the
Cold War appear on the television screen, crisis begets crisis, and
the superpowers threaten each other with ever larger weapons.
Certainly the arms race created its own powerful momentum.
</P>
<P>
   Interviews with U.S. and Russian citizens engaged in this
patriotic endeavor offer an example of the ways the external Cold
War reshaped the entire society inside the superpowers, favoring
certain geographical areas and occupations, shortchanging others.
Eventually the strain of keeping up caused the Soviet Union and its
Eastern European empire to collapse with an astounding rapidity.
</P>
<P>
   Not surprisingly, CNN retells the Cold War story from the
perspective of knowing how it all came out, emphasizing systemic
Soviet weaknesses while faulting the United States mainly for
miscalculations.
</P>
<P>
   The enterprise is successful in many ways. Episodes devoted to
the ``domestic'' side of the Cold War often provide insight into
the Soviet leaders' halfhearted struggle to find a way out of the
grim Stalinist legacy and into the racial and social upheavals in
the United States during the 1960's.
</P>
<P>
   Understanding what the Cold War was about, however, and why it
developed in the ways it did to become a global confrontation is
not easily accomplished. And it is here that the conceptual and
editorial problems are not always so well met. Choices must be made
from rough cuts of interviews and then placed in the framework of
the scripts produced by several authors. But were they always the
best choices?
</P>
<P>
   Postwar Europe, where the Cold War began, is presented in the
narrative as a ravaged landscape fought over by two non-European
powers, one invited in to save the ancient civilizations, the other
a brutal dictatorship with crude aggressive intentions.
</P>
<P>
   Ambassador W. Averell Harriman recalls that Stalin shrugged off
a compliment to the Red Army's victories with an unsmiling comment
that Czar Alexander got to Paris. To U.S. policy makers worried
about the state of postwar Europe, Stalin's shadow did seem to
reach to Paris.
</P>
<P>
   What is missing here, though, is commentary on the prewar
differences between Eastern and Western Europe, whether in terms of
resources or of political organization, and the heritage of the
anti-Soviet cordon sanitaire policies practiced by France and
Britain. Also missing is a discussion of the abortive secret
surrender negotiations that prompted Stalin's protests to Roosevelt
that the West's plan was to see the war end as far East as
possible.
</P>
<P>
   Were there, then, any legitimate Russian concerns at the wartime
conference, or just evidence of Stalin's paranoia? The series is
ambivalent.
</P>
<P>
   In one episode we are told that the postwar division of Europe
into spheres of influence was essentially a product of the 1943
Tehran Conference, the unhappy result of teaming up with the
Russians to fight Hitler, while in the following episode the
division is presented as the tainted result of appeasement at the
1945 Yalta Conference.
</P>
<P>
   Given the special place Yalta plays in interpretations of the
origins of the Cold War, perhaps much more ought to have been
included about the Big Three debates over other issues _ Stalin's
argument for reparations, for example, or Roosevelt's efforts to
inaugurate the United Nations before territorial issues were
settled.
</P>
<P>
   Post-Yalta negotiations were stymied on all fronts, while doubts
grew about the future of the Grand Alliance. Still pending,
however, were the agreements on Russian entrance into the Far
Eastern war, only briefly mentioned in the series. With the
successful atomic bomb test, President Harry S. Truman decided at
Potsdam that he could strike out on a new path to check Russian
advances. No time is devoted to the continuing controversy over the
implications of this decision and to countervailing views on
``atomic diplomacy.''
</P>
<P>
   Even so, after the Berlin blockade ended in 1949, the Cold War
wasn't foreordained. The Chinese Revolution triggered a new phase
in the conflict. Throughout the series, policy makers exclaim over
and over that they were shocked or surprised at each turn of
events, a subtheme that underwrites the conclusion that the Cold
War was about one thing only: resistance to Soviet expansionism.
</P>
<P>
   But the attempts of America's Western allies to regain their
colonies and the joint decision to divide Korea, a temporary
expedient, set in motion forces that would produce the limited hot
wars and draw in the superpowers.
</P>
<P>
   American concern and postwar planning had always been about
stabilizing the world economy and restructuring Germany and Japan
into peaceful workshops for Europe and Asia. Eastern Europe was
sacrificed but still served the containment policy well as a
stimulus to Western unity under American leadership.
</P>
<P>
   In the Far East, however, the boundaries were not as easily
established. China's revolution finally undid the Yalta Far Eastern
agreement, not an adventurist Stalin. The series also neglects the
decision to go ahead without Russia in writing a peace treaty after
the Japanese surrender, and the building of atomic-capable air
bases on Okinawa as influences on the Stalin's decision to give Kim
Il Sung a green light for his plan to unify Korea.
</P>
<P>
   Instead the series stresses Soviet recklessness and China's
intervention to halt Gen. Douglas MacArthur's march to the Yalu
River, as if there were no other explanations than Communist
aggression. After Korea it proved impossible to limit the Cold War
to one part of the world. Gen. Andrew J. Goodpaster confirms that
Eisenhower understood that genuinely free elections in Vietnam
would have brought Ho Chi Minh to power, an unacceptable solution
to that problem. What viewers are not told is why; that Eisenhower
thought a Communist victory would destroy American plans for safely
reintegrating Japan into the world economy.
</P>
<P>
   By the time the series takes up the Vietnam War in the 1960s,
however, credibility has replaced political economy as the crucial
focal point. If you like what the United States has done in Europe,
Dean Rusk preached to skeptical NATO policy makers, you must
support us in Vietnam.
</P>
<P>
   The Cold War consensus came apart for a time. But Russia's
constantly threatening presence in Eastern Europe and its war in
Afghanistan eased the potential problems of mobilizing the nation
for a new campaign against the ``Evil Empire'' after Richard M.
Nixon's failure to make detente an acceptable alternative.
</P>
<P>
   CNN has effectively recounted the events of the Cold War era.
Their various meanings, however, could still use further
examination.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-01-08-99 1932EST &QL; 
