</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-SHAUGHNESSY-COLUMN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TASKMASTERS ON BOTH SIDES OF THE FIELD 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By DAN SHAUGHNESSY  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   HEMPSTEAD, N.Y. _ The Jacksonville Jaguars play the New York
Jets in the Meadowlands Sunday which means Bill Parcells and Tom
Coughlin will meet again. It must be like looking in the mirror.
</P>
<P>
   ``They are almnost identical, really,'' said Glenn Foley, who
played quarterback for Coughlin at Boston College and now plays
backup quarterback for Parcells with the Jets. ``They are very
similar. They have identical styles. They're both really intense
and great coaches. Behind the scenes and on the field, they're
basically the same. They're both maniacs.''
</P>
<P>
   Parcells and Coughlin can't seem to get away from one another.
When he was head coach of the New York Giants, Parcells hired
Coughlin as his wide receivers coach in 1988. Coughlin was with
Parcells in Tampa when the Giants beat the Bills in Super Bowl XXV
in January 1991.
</P>
<P>
   In 1993, Parcells and Coughlin both worked in Greater Boston.
Coughlin was in his final year at Boston College, going 9-3 and
coming within one fumble of taking the Eagles to the Sugar Bowl.
Down in Foxborough, Parcells was in his first year of resurrecting
a moribund Patriot franchise for owner James Orthwein.
</P>
<P>
   Two years ago, Parcells's Patriots beat Coughlin's Jaguars,
20-6, to put New England in the Super Bowl. Now they are meeting
again, and the winner plays the winner of Sturday's Denver-Miami
game for the right to represent the AFC in the Super Bowl.
</P>
<P>
   Parcells hired Coughlin after a 15-minute chat at the Senior
Bowl in 1988.
</P>
<P>
   ``We had quite a bit in common,'' remembered the Tuna. ``We're
both Northeastern guys. We have a little Irish in our background.
He went to Syracuse. I know what that's about. I've been around
guys like Tom my whole life, so I basically understood him him
right away.''
</P>
<P>
   Coughlin remembered, ``I had been an admirer of his team in the
way in which they played, but I really didn't know him then. But
when I got to know him a bit better, I had a great deal of
admiration for the way in which he went about things, like his
focus, for his tunnel vision, and for his intensity which he brings
to the table.''
</P>
<P>
   Parcells acts like he invented intensity. Coughlin makes it a
way of life. Players, beware. These guys are no barrel of laughs on
the job. Parcells cut his teeth coaching at West Point (when Bobby
Knight was the Army hoop coach). Coughlin is equal parts Patton and
Dean Wermer. Neither man allows his asssistant coaches to speak
with the media. It's one voice only, something Parcells started.
</P>
<P>
   Think Parcells was nasty for belittling Terry Glenn by calling
him ``she''? Get this one: Two Jacksonville players this week
miraculously escaped injury when they rolled their BMW four times
while rushing to get to a team meeting on time. Coughlin greeted
them with the news that they'd been fined $500 for tardiness.
Rules, you know.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's a lesson to be learned here, and the fines are
consistent with my policies,'' explained Coughlin.
</P>
<P>
   Both Parcells and Coughlin left a legacy in New England.
Parcells bequeathed the Patriots a string of sellouts and a team
good enough to stagger back to the playoffs in successive seasons.
Coughlin left behind enough good players to beat Notre Dame and a
monstrous new configuration of BC's Alumni Stadium.
</P>
<P>
   Thave have something else in common: Both go into the game on
the heels of a rout of the Patriots.
</P>
<P>
   As a workaholic and disciplinarian, Coughlin may have topped the
Tuna. There's a well-worn story from their days together with the
Giants about when Parcells called the Giants' office on Christmas
morning and heard Coughlin's voice on the other end of the phone.
</P>
<P>
   Parcells chuckled at the memory and said, ``Every time now when
I catch him where he doesn't answer the phone, I always leave a
message about `when you get done with your 18 holes, when you get
back from the beach, give me a call,' because I obviously know
that's not where he is.''
</P>
<P>
   Foley rolled his eyes at the memory of Coughlin at BC.
</P>
<P>
   ``In college, he had you,'' said the QB. ``It was amazing what
we did. You were getting drilled into the ground physically,
regardless. And if you screwed up, it was doubled. One year guys
had a little fun filling out the recruiting card they gave us. That
was it. They were up at 6 a.m. running. If you missed one class,
you ran for a week at 5:30 or 6 in the morning.
</P>
<P>
   ``You should have seen our practice sheet. There were 24
periods, six or seven minutes each. He's meticulous.''
</P>
<P>
   Parcells thus far has been a bigger winner, but Coughlin is five
years younger and building a nice team in Florida. John Calipari
wants to be Rick Pitino and Bob Kraft wants to be Jerry Jones, but
Coughlin is comfortable being Coughlin.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was able to study the guy that I think is the master at what
he does and how he maneuvers the things that put you in a position
to win,'' said Coughlin.
</P>
<P>
   Parcells had to coach against his pal Bill Belichick when the
Patriots made their first playoff appearance in eight years back in
1994. Now the Jets are playing their first home playoff game in 12
years, and Parcells finds himself facing Coughlin for the second
time in three years.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'd rather we didn't have to do this,'' said Parcells. ``This
happens in this industry. You have guys that go on, and I'm very
proud of what Tom has done. I'd just prefer to play against
somebody else. But he's the opponent and I'm the opponent for him.
If we can't win, then there isn't anybody I'd rather see win than
him. It's like playing against family.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(Dan Shaughnessy is a Globe columnist.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
