<HEADLINE>
WILLIAM LEONARD SHEARER III, 92; FORMER FURNITURE EXECUTIVE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By TOM LONG  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   William Leonard Shearer III of Dublin, N.H., the former
president of the Paine Furniture Co., a Boston fixture owned and
operated by his family for more than 160 years, died Monday in
Sarasota Memorial Hospital in Florida. He was 92.
</P>
<P>
   Mr. Shearer, who enjoyed yachting and skiing in his youth, also
was a champion sled dog racer. As a major in the Army during World
War II, he trained dog teams and commanded a unit that rescued
downed fliers from northern Maine to Greenland. On Feb. 17, 1949,
he won the 90-mile International Dogsled Derby in Ottawa.
</P>
<P>
   He was the great-grandson of Leonard Shearer, a cabinetmaker who
opened a shop at 77 Blackstone St. in Boston in 1835.
</P>
<P>
   Leonard Shearer contracted with local farmers to tap New
England's old-growth pine and maple trees to fashion furniture in
home workshops that was shipped to his business for painting,
finishing, and distribution.
</P>
<P>
   He employed John F. Paine of Uxbridge, Mass. as an apprentice.
Paine served as a wagon driver, cabinetmaker, and salesman.
</P>
<P>
   In 1854, Paine married Eliza Ann Shearer, the sister of the
founder. This brought about a partnership, and the firm became
Shearer &AMP; Paine.
</P>
<P>
   In 1864, after the founder's death, Paine operated the business
under his name.
</P>
<P>
   William Leonard Shearer III was born in Swampscott, Mass. and
graduated from Harvard College. He was president of the company
from 1936 until his retirement in 1981.
</P>
<P>
   He was a member of the Harvard Club of Boston, the Union Club,
and the Dublin Lake Club.
</P>
<P>
   He leaves his wife, Constance (Murphy); two sons, Daniel H. and
Jonathan C.; two daughters, Michaele Shearer Osgood and Abigail
Shearer Robinson; and six grandchildren.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-01-08-99 1934EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
