<DOCNO> NYT19990108.0322 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-01-08 19:36 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5409 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u k &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-WALKER-COLUMN-BOS &LR;      01-08 0812
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-WALKER-COLUMN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LITTLE BITE LEFT IN WATCHDOGS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By ADRIAN WALKER  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   A new governor has been inaugurated. Freshman legislators have
been welcomed by the House speaker and the Senate president.
Boston's mayor will deliver his State of the City speech Monday,
with the City Council on hand.
</P>
<P>
   All these newly minted, or reminted, leaders will have their
agendas, their plans, their dreams. But there's one thing they
won't have _ anything to fear from the agencies that are supposed
to protect the integrity of government. Because most of those
agencies have become invisible. Or sclerotic. Or both.
</P>
<P>
   Inside and outside government, agencies that used to advocate
good government, demand fiscal accountability and pursue corruption
have been brought to their knees, unemboldened by the chore of
policing their political benefactors and suffering from the same
malaise that afflicts so much of government.
</P>
<P>
   Remember the State Ethics Commission? The Inspector General's
Office? When was the last time you heard from the Boston Finance
Commission? Do you recall anything about the state Auditor's
Office, other than the auditor's fondness for midweek tee times? Do
we still have an Office of Campaign and Political Finance or a
Boston Municipal Research Bureau?
</P>
<P>
   Many of them seem to be in a persistent vegetative state.
</P>
<P>
   Anyone wondering whether some of those agencies should be busier
need look no further than the office of Representative Philip
Travis, the House banking chairman, who pressured banks into
contributing $20,000 for an Indian tribe in his district last
spring _ just as his committee was debating automatic teller
legislation that has since provided banks with a huge windfall.
</P>
<P>
   Travis returned the money only after the Globe started asking
about it. But that was months after he collected it, apparently
heedless of the oversight of agencies charged with safeguarding
clean governmment.
</P>
<P>
   Lousy government and dishonest officeholders haven't disappeared
from the landscape. But agencies that were once devoted to keeping
a critical eye on them nearly have.
</P>
<P>
   The public spends millions of dollars on watchdogs _ $12 million
a year on the state auditor's office alone _ but has less and less
to show for it.
</P>
<P>
   The Office of Campaign and Political Finance cannot even file a
lawsuit. When politicians refuse to file reports or respond to
questions about questionable practices, the agency is reduced to
writing polite letters asking them to please, if it's not too much
trouble, obey the law. They send out thousands of these letters
every year.
</P>
<P>
   For years, Senator Dianne Wilkerson of Roxbury refused to file
campaign reports, or to respond to scores of letters. Even when
thousands of dollars of reimbursements to Wilkerson were
challenged, all the agency could do was beg a reluctant attorney
general's office to file a lawsuit. After Wilkerson's other legal
woes caught up with her in 1997, it fined her committee and
Wilkerson herself. The committee missed its last payment.
</P>
<P>
   The auditor, Joseph DeNucci, points to his audit of the Lawrence
School Department nearly two years ago as one of his signal
accomplishments in recent years. (He looked into misallocation of
education reform funds, after dozens of news stories pointed out
exactly where to find the wrongdoing.)
</P>
<P>
   Samuel R. Tyler, the long-time president of the Boston Municipal
Research Bureau, whose reports were once feared by city officials,
admits that his business-funded group has lost some of its
missionary zeal. He attributes that to a lack of concern by many of
the companies that give the bureau $400,000 in annual funding.
Increasingly, he said, the companies are headquartered elsewhere
and don't really care about anything in Boston that doesn't affect
the corporate bottom line.
</P>
<P>
   The Boston Finance Commission, a state-appointed overseer of the
city, has not noticeably raised an eyebrow since it did a report on
overlapping duties by Boston's Fire and Emergency Medical Services
departments. That was in 1994 _ well before Bill Clinton met Monica
Lewinsky.
</P>
<P>
   To be fair, some of the watchdog agencies are casualties of
Beacon Hill combat. After the Ethics Commission fined a slew of
legislators, including Senate President William M. Bulger in 1992,
its budget was promptly slashed. OCPF has essentially been
level-funded for most of its 25-year existence _ by the very
legislators who are most likely to run afoul of the campaign
finance law, which, not incidentally, they have progressively
weakened.
</P>
<P>
   And nothing is about to change. So wish the best for your newly
enshrined leaders. Given what's become of the watchdogs, they are
effectively the only judges of their own behavior.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(Adrian Walker is a columnist with The Boston Globe.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
