<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-01-08 19:37 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5411 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FBN-FALCONS-49ERS-BOS     01-08 1093
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-FALCONS-49ERS-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DIRTY BIRDS WILL GIVE 49ERS NO QUARTER 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By RON BORGES  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ If there is to be a new world order in the National
Football League, it could begin Saturday.
</P>
<P>
   That's when the perennial NFC powerhouse San Francisco 49ers
come to the Georgia Dome to try to reassert themselves in the face
of upstart challengers who call themselves the Dirty Birds and made
quite a mess of the NFC this season.
</P>
<P>
   The Atlanta Falcons marched through their schedule the way
General Sherman once marched through downtown, burning and
pillaging nearly everything in their path, including the once-proud
49ers. Just three years ago, the Falcons were a dismal 3-13 and
going nowhere. But Dan Reeves arrived the following season and has
led them to the second-greatest turnaround in NFL history (plus-7
from last year's 7-9 finish) and to 20 wins in their last 24 games.
</P>
<P>
   There are many who still believe the Falcons are more mirage
than miracle. But there is no denying they have won nine straight,
10 of their last 11 in their division, and went 11-1 against NFC
opponents this season, running their conference record to 14-2 in
their last 16 such games. One of those losses came against these
same 49ers, but that was an 11-point setback three weeks into the
season that was avenged by a 31-19 rout six games ago that the
Dirty Birds insist was a mess with a message.
</P>
<P>
   ``What beating them did for our team was tell our guys we can
play with those guys and win,'' said veteran Pro Bowl safety Eugene
Robinson, who made a habit of beating these same 49ers while
anchoring the Green Bay Packers' defense before leaving for Atlanta
this season. ``That does a lot for the psyche of our team. We're
playing with consistency, and things are clicking. We're not the
lowly Falcons anymore.''
</P>
<P>
   No, they are not, and the 49ers know it. If they questioned
that, the Falcons ended all doubt Nov. 15 when they survived a
second straight onslaught from Steve Young (684 passing yards in
the two games) and Jerry Rice (18 receptions for 331 yards and
touchdowns of 66, 65, and 26 yards) by ramming the ball down their
throats with running back Jamal Anderson, throwing it over them to
Terance Mathis, and harassing them with a defense that has few
familiar faces but a habit of producing turnovers.
</P>
<P>
   Anderson rushed for 1,846 yards and scored 16 touchdowns and is
the key to everything Atlanta tries to do on offense. Meanwhile,
the defense has shut down the run so effectively that it finished
second in the NFL in that category after allowing just 3.3 yards a
carry and 75.2 a game. When the latter is coupled with the fact San
Francisco running back Garrison Hearst comes into this game with a
bad hamstring, it is further food for thought.
</P>
<P>
   Yet so, too, is the fact that despite all the numbers, a doubt
remains, and that is Young's demonstrated ability to shred
Atlanta's defense. Even in victory, Atlanta allowed 307 passing
yards and won only because the defense scored one touchdown and set
up a second.
</P>
<P>
   While some look at that game and suggest it was a fluke, you
can't discount those defensive plays, because the Falcons have been
making them all season. They have scored six touchdowns, compiled
the leading takeaway/giveaway ratio in the league (plus-16), and
made their bones by crushing the bones of running backs, which is
why they are favored and believe they can survive another assault
from Rice, Young, and Terrell Owens.
</P>
<P>
   ``Beating them before . . . you have more confidence in your
ability,'' said veteran linebacker Jessie Tuggle, who has been here
10 years and well remembers that the 49ers owned his team not so
long ago. ``We're going to be the ones to try and set the tempo
this time.''
</P>
<P>
   If they do, the 49ers expect it will be done by Anderson, who is
so commanding a force that since Reeves arrived, Atlanta is 19-2
when he has carried 20 times or more, including 14-0 this season.
Considering that he has already carried a record 410 times, it is
obvious to the Niners what they must deal with _ a battering ram.
</P>
<P>
   To combat that, 49ers coach Steve Mariucci has said his team
will often put seven or eight men at the line of scrimmage, using
safety Tim McDonald as a counterweight to Anderson. If that works
and quarterback Chris Chandler is forced to carry too much of the
load, it could mean a revival for the aging 49ers. But if it fails,
Mariucci knows what could follow.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Falcons have big-play capability,'' he said. ``Their
passing game is based on selling the run. Then they'll throw in
some trick passes and it's bombs away.''
</P>
<P>
   No one knows that better than McDonald, who watched helplessly
while he was trapped at the line of scrimmage pursuing Anderson as
Mathis three times burned man-to-man coverage for touchdowns, all
more than 31 yards. In those two games, Mathis had eight receptions
for 208 yards, a fact that normally would cry out for double
coverage. But if Atlanta gets Anderson rolling, the Niners would be
forced to take their chances and hope they can pressure Chandler
(10 sacks in the two games) enough to save themselves. If that
fails, McDonald understands the consequences.
</P>
<P>
   ``Because they have a legit running back, it makes it tough,''
McDonald said this week from San Francisco. ``Do you commit an
extra guy to try to contain Jamal Anderson or do you keep him back,
which could be to Jamal's advantage? They can always stick you with
a big play if you do.''
</P>
<P>
   The same is true of the Niners. San Francisco has won eight of
the last 11 meetings and has outscored the Falcons, 622-349, in the
'90s. But those numbers may be merely history now because the
Falcons' defense led the NFL in fumble recoveries (25) and
takeaways (44), was second in rushing yards allowed per carry
(3.33) and rushing yards allowed per game (75.2), fourth in points
allowed (18.1 a game), and eighth in total yards allowed per game
(295.9). It has not allowed more than 20 points in eight of its
last nine games, not allowed a 100-yard rusher during its nine-game
winning streak, and has 14 interceptions and 21 sacks during that
stretch.
</P>
<P>
   In fact, during the Falcons' 20-4 run, that defense has allowed
only one rusher to gain 100 yards and held Hearst to averages of
3.2 and 3.5 yards in this season's meetings.
</P>
<P>
   Which brings the 49ers fate back to an old guy named Young, who
will be trying to beat a team that is unwilling to believe 1998 is
anything but the dawning of a new age.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-01-08-99 1937EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
