<DOCNO> NYT19990108.0325 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-01-08 19:41 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5415 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BUSH-STRUHS-BOS &LR;      01-08 0469
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BUSH-STRUHS-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BAY STATE OFFICIAL TAKES ENVIRONMENTAL JOB IN FLORIDA 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By PETER J. HOWE AND SCOTT ALLEN  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ David B. Struhs, the Massachusetts Department of
Environmental Protection commissioner who once worked for President
Bush, is going back to work for the Bush family _ as chief
environmental aide to the former president's son, Jeb Bush, the new
governor of Florida.
</P>
<P>
   Struhs, who had been happily settling in for another four years
running one of the state's most influential agencies, stunned DEP
employees Friday by announcing he was headed to Tallahassee next
month to become secretary of environmental protection.
</P>
<P>
   ``During the Christmas and New Year's holiday, I got an
unexpected, out-of-the-blue, quite remarkable invitation to travel
to Florida for a few days and meet with then governor-elect Jeb
Bush,'' Struhs said in an interview from Florida.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was immediately taken by the size of the opportunity and
also impressed by their interest in trying to break the mold and
bring in some new ideas,'' Struhs said. Florida is pursuing a
massive restoration of the Everglades and a $3 billion open-space
protection program.
</P>
<P>
   Although Struhs served as chief of staff at the White House
Council on Environmental Quality under President Bush, he said he
had never met Jeb Bush and did not know anyone in the governor's
administration personally.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was really a call (from Jeb Bush) based on the
Massachusetts environmental management record. As far as I can
decipher here, it had absolutely nothing to do with my working in a
staff position in Washington'' for the governor's father, said
Struhs, a 38-year-old father of four.
</P>
<P>
   News of Struhs's departure came so suddenly that Beacon Hill
insiders were hard pressed to speculate on who might succeed him.
</P>
<P>
   State officials and environmental activists said two people who
were considered for environmental affairs secretary, former state
senator Lucile Hicks of Wayland and Boston attorney R.J. Lyman, who
ran the state's environmental review office, might be considered.
</P>
<P>
   Several current top DEP aides, including legal counsel Ralph
Childs and water resources chief Arleen O'Donnell, are also seen as
possible successors. The deputy director of the Massachusetts Water
Resources Authority, Thomas B. Powers, formerly held top positions
at the DEP and could also be considered.
</P>
<P>
   Governor Paul Cellucci's administration has tapped several
former legislators and political operatives for administration
posts. But Jack Clarke, a top lobbyist for the Massachusetts
Audubon Society, said, ``We're hoping they'll put a lot of effort
into it and make it not a patronage position but an
environmental-professional position.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
