<HEADER>
A5417 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FILM-AWARDS-ART-NYT &LR;      01-08 1249
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FILM-AWARDS-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
IN THE POLITICS OF FILM AWARDS,   CANTANKEROUSNESS HAS A ROLE
</HEADLINE>
   (dw) 
 By PETER APPLEBOME    
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   And the winner was . . . ``Out of Sight''?
</P>
<P>
   A fair number of filmgoers must have scratched their heads when
the National Society of Film Critics picked the George Clooney and
Jennifer Lopez film, which disappeared virtually unseen soon after
opening last summer, as the best film of 1998 in voting on Sunday.
Its director, Steven Soderbergh, won for best director, and the
film also won for best screeplay.
</P>
<P>
   ``Saving Private Ryan'' is viewed as the year's likely awards
steamroller. And other films like ``Happiness,'' ``The Thin Red
Line,'' ``Affliction'' or ``Shakespeare in Love'' might seem more
likely critic's favorites.
</P>
<P>
   But both the nature of the National Society of Film Critics, a
famously contrarian bunch, and the convolutions of awards politics
can conspire to make the unconventional choice the conventional one
these days. As awards for such endeavors as films and books
continue to proliferate and take on wider commercial importance,
choices increasingly appear to be made on grounds that have as much
to do with politics and personalities as with merit.
</P>
<P>
   In fact, ``Out of Sight'' won less as the critics' favorite
movie and more as a compromise candidate favored by critics voting
against ``Saving Private Ryan.''
</P>
<P>
   ``A lot of critics feel they don't want to just second what
others have done,'' said Owen Glieberman, the lead film critic for
Entertainment Weekly and one of the 51 members of the film critics
society. ``They want to make some kind of statement of their own.
But it's a slippery slope. You shouldn't vote for something just
because it's popular, but you shouldn't vote against something
because it's popular either.''
</P>
<P>
   This award season already has seen its share of surprise
choices. In film, the New York Film Critics Circle raised eyebrows
by giving its best-actress award to Cameron Diaz for her role in
the popular gross-out movie ``There's Something about Mary.'' In
books, ``Charming Billy'' won the National Book Award for fiction,
which many people had already conceded to Tom Wolfe for his
much-ballyhooed ``A Man in Full.''
</P>
<P>
   All the surprises had their advocates, and ``Out of Sight''
received warm if not necessarily ecstatic reviews and turned up on
a smattering of critics' Top 10 lists for the year. But awards
today can reflect a broader agenda than just honoring superior
books or films, and they can mean millions of dollars for the
winners.
</P>
<P>
   The choice of Ms. Diaz was seen by some as quirky populism and
by others as a reflection that the sexy Ms. Diaz would make a
better trophy guest at the awards dinner than the other main
contender, the 69-year-old Brazilian actress Fernanda Montenegro.
Others argued she just deserved to win.
</P>
<P>
   ``Judges aren't operating in a vacuum,'' said Neil Gabler, the
author and cultural critic whose most recent book is ``Life The
Movie.'' ``They know when they're making a declaration, a contrary
act. In some ways, the process of giving awards is like everything
else in American life; it becomes a form of entertainment in
itself. When the awards create controversy, it's a way for a
seemingly nonentertainment institution like high literature to get
a piece of the entertainment swag. People may not care about
`Charming Billy,' but put it in competition with `A Man in Full,'
and you've got a story.''
</P>
<P>
   Of course, one need only view the Oscars, the most heavily
politicked award of them all, to remember that there was never a
time when awards were meted out for pure merit, whatever that might
be. Groups like the National Society of Film Critics, founded in
the late '60s as a hip, opinionated alternative to less adventurous
critics' groups, are in the business of dispensing prickly,
unexpected opinions. The film critics society consists mostly of
writers for large newspapers, major weekly magazines like Newsweek
and Time, and alternative weeklies like The Village Voice.
</P>
<P>
   The group named ``Babe,'' the original charming sow movie, as
its film of the year a few years back, and, Gabler notes, its
members would probably feel like fools if they ever picked the same
best picture as the Oscars did.
</P>
<P>
   The awards of the film critics society tend to be skewed as well
by the nature of the publications represented, by the fact that
they are announced after the other critics' awards and by the open
voting, so everyone can see how everyone else votes.
</P>
<P>
   Members of the group said that on Sunday, ``Out of Sight''
trailed both ``Saving Private Ryan'' and ``Affliction'' when the
critics cast their first votes. A film seldom gets the needed
plurality on the first vote, and subsequent rounds play out like a
demolition derby with voters as conscious of which film they don't
want to win as which one they do.
</P>
<P>
   When ``Out of Sight'' appeared to be the most likely film to
beat ``Saving Private Ryan,'' it attracted enough votes to win,
like the compromise candidate at a political convention. Some
critics simply were underwhelmed by ``Saving Private Ryan.'' Some
thought after being cited as best film by critics groups in Los
Angeles and New York, it had won enough awards and did not need any
more help in its march toward the Oscars. Others simply resented
the power and clout of Steven Spielberg, the movie's director, and
chose to cast a vote for a David rather than for Goliath.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think people genuinely liked the film, even if it didn't
have the passionate support that some other films had,'' John
Anderson, a film critic for Newsday, said of ``Out of Sight.'' He
said he cast his first vote for the Japanese film ``Fireworks,''
and then switched to ``Out of Sight'' when it appeared the most
likely alternative to ``Saving Private Ryan.''
</P>
<P>
   He continued: ``If people resent Spielberg because he has every
resource in the world at his disposal and still ends up making
middlebrow movies, they'll want to use the award to give
recognition to someone else. If you accept the idea that these
critics' awards can have an impact on the Oscars, you want to throw
your support to something that won't get the recognition
otherwise.''
</P>
<P>
   It is not at all clear that the award will do much for ``Out of
Sight,'' although one result is that the film is being re-released
in New York and Los Angeles.
</P>
<P>
   ``The film's been dead for months,'' said Dave Kehr, a New York
critic most recently with The Daily News. ``It's not going to do
the movie any good. It's certainly not going to redeem it in the
eyes of the academy enough to get it a nomination. Maybe it will be
good for Soderbergh, who's more of a critics' darling than a
popular filmmaker. But I think the vote was mostly an honest
attempt to reward achievement.''
</P>
<P>
   The makers of ``Out of Sight'' certainly hoped the award would
do them some good. Universal Studios immediately took out a
two-page color ad on the inside cover of the trade publication
``Variety,'' hoping to attract the attention of Oscar voters.
</P>
<P>
   Still, if there's a contrary mentality in the awards world, even
National Society members said that their group had a strong dose of
it.
</P>
<P>
   ``This group has been the one to do it from way back,'' said Jay
Carr, film critic for The Boston Globe. ``We've voted for
`Drugstore Cowboy,' `Babe,' films no one else voted for. If you're
going to find a counter-Oscar mentality, this is the group to look
for it.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
