<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NY-HUNTER-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PARKER AND HUNTER GROOVING AT BIRDLAND  
(DW)
</HEADLINE>
  By BEN RATLIFF    
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Musicians mostly want to make music that feels stout,
with a sturdy glow, but sometimes they enjoy stripping the veneer
off themselves. From the drummer Leon Parker, we're used to this;
his hard slap on the snare and hypnotizing patterns on the ride
cymbal produce a stock-quality sound that swings yet seems almost
pre-jazz. From Charlie Hunter, we're not used to this at all.
</P>
<P>
   Hunter's 10-string guitar usually is heard in his group pumping
out grooves for dancers, and he likes to make it seem as if it's
more than a guitar: he inflates it with a swelling vibrato effect,
as if it were an organ, and while he improvises he plays
simultaneous bass lines on the low strings.
</P>
<P>
   The two of them played together at Birdland on Thursday night as
part of a double bill with the singer Kurt Elling, announcing that
they had just made a recording for Blue Note. (The label is
blanketing the city's jazz clubs with its own artists this month in
honor of its 60th anniversary.)
</P>
<P>
   When they were grooving, in a shuffle or a montuno or a
slow-building wave of cymbal noise from Parker, they were at their
best. When they were being delicate, simple sometimes tipped over
into lackluster: a version of Brian Wilson's ``Don't Talk (Put Your
Head on My Shoulder),'' a clever choice of material, was played
absolutely straight, with no particular feeling, and ``You Don't
Know What Love Is'' featured some skillful but dry improvising.
</P>
<P>
   Both Hunter and Parker are jamming-oriented musicians with
renegade notions about jazz; one almost gets the sense that they'd
be better suited to performing one long song, or a suite of
interconnected rhythmic ideas, allowing themselves to ebb and flow.
</P>
<P>
   Kurt Elling is an actor as much as a singer, and he comes almost
overprepared for a jazz show; he brings with him a beatnik-angel
persona and a ton of words. In front of an impressive trio _ the
pianist Laurence Hobgood, the bassist Essiet Essiet and the drummer
Lewis Nash _ he sang Wayne Shorter's ``Night Dreamer'' with his own
words, fitting one to each of the hundreds of notes Shorter had
sprayed out in his own version of the song.
</P>
<P>
   That was a piece he was performing last year; among the fresh
material was a performance of an Ishmael Reed poem stuck in the
middle of a racing Charlie Parker piece. Elling has excellent pitch
and breath control, and even in ballads he made his middle-range
voice bellow and crack without losing notes; it was good, battering
entertainment.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
