<SLUG> BC-AIRTOUCH-MCI-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MCI BOWS OUT OF AIRTOUCH RACE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By RONALD ROSENBERG  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   MCI Worldcom Inc. Friday bowed out of the bidding to acquire
AirTouch Communications Corp., leaving Bell Atlantic Corp. and
Vodafone Group PLC to battle for ownership of the West Coast
wireless telephone company.
</P>
<P>
   ``After reviewing the possibility of a combination with AirTouch
Communications Inc., MCI WorldCom has determined not to pursue a
bid for the company at this time,'' MCI Worldcom said in a
statement.
</P>
<P>
   MCI Worldcom did not explain the reasons for its decision,
which, according to Bloomberg News, followed a verbal offer for the
San Francisco-based wireless carrier. AirTouch received a $54
billion offer from Vodafone this week after Bell Atlantic bid $43
billion. MCI's bid was less than Vodafone's, Bloomberg reported.
</P>
<P>
   Wall Street seemed to approve of MCI Worldcom's decision to exit
the fray. Its stock dropped 5 1/2 points before the announcement
helped it climbed back to close at 75, down 1/8 for the day. More
than 36 milion shares were traded Friday, _ triple its average
trading volume.
</P>
<P>
   ``Owning AirTouch just did not make sense for MCI Worldcom
because there was not much strategic value and to find the cost
savings to justify the high cost of the deal would be difficult,''
said Crispin Vicars, director of Yankee Group's wireless/mobile
communication planning service.
</P>
<P>
   Jackson, Miss.-based MCI Worldcom, created through last year's
merger of MCI Communications and Worldcom, is the nation's second
largest long-distance company after AT&AMP;T, and it also provides
local phone and Internet services. But it owns no major mobile
telephone facilities.
</P>
<P>
   Acquiring AirTouch would require significant additional
investments before MCI Worldcom could effectively compete equally
with AT&AMP;T and Sprint PCs. Industry and Wall Street analysts agreed
that AirTouch would fit nicely with Bell Atlantic, which is looking
to expand its wireless operations nationwide to better compete
against AT&AMP;T and Sprint PCS.
</P>
<P>
   Vodafone, the large British-based wireless provider, with 9.1
million customers, primarily wants AirTouch for its European mobile
phone investments in Italy, Portugal, Germany, and Spain. Both
companies have joint ventures in Egypt and Sweden.
</P>
<P>
   AirTouch shares closed down 3 at 79. New York-based Bell
Atlantic gained 5/8 to close at 56 5/8. Vodafone's US-listed ADRs
slipped 3/8 to 17 3/8
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
