<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ECONOMY-JOBS-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ECONOMY PACKS ON NEW JOBS IN LAST MONTH 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By PETER G. GOSSELIN  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ The US economy capped a year of strong employment
growth by adding a spectacular 378,000 jobs last month and driving
the unemployment rate back down to a generation-low 4.3 percent,
the government said Friday.
</P>
<P>
   More than 100,000 of the new jobs were the result of the last
month's abnormally warm weather that allowed building to continue
at a time when construction workers are usually laid off. But even
taking that into account, the economy has produced far more jobs
and proven far more resilent than almost anyone had expected.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're into some new territory here, no question about it,''
said Paul E. Harrington, associate director of Northeasten
University's Center for Labor Market Studies.
</P>
<P>
   December's decline in the jobless rate from November's 4.4
percent matched the 28-year low reached last April, the
government's Bureau of Labor Statistics said. For the year,
unemployment average 4.5 percent, its lowest annual rate since
1969.
</P>
<P>
   Analysts said that the nation's ability to churn out new jobs
last year was especially striking given the Asian crisis that
dampened demand for US exports and drove down US manufacturing
employment. Overall, the economy added 2.9 million jobs in 1998,
down from 1997's 3.4 million level, but still a powerfully large
number. The fraction of Americans who work outside the home set a
record for the third year in a row at 64.1 percent, according to
BLS.
</P>
<P>
   ``These are good numbers. They show the economy continues to be
strong,'' said Michael J. Montgomery, an economist with Standard &AMP;
Poor's DRI in Lexington, Mass.
</P>
<P>
   Analysts are deeply divided over how much longer the good times
can last. Despite being repeatedly contradicted by the economy's
sterling performance, most predict that growth will slow this year
and, with it, job creation.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's going to be a reluctant slowdown, but it's still going to
happen,'' predicted Nicholas S. Perna, chief economist of Fleet
Financial Group in Boston.
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps, but for now the boom in jobs, output and investments
continues rolling along. The stock market climbed on news of the
new employment figures Friday, sending the Dow Jones industrial
average up 105.56, or 1.1 percent, to 9643.332, its first ever
close above the 9600 mark. Other market measures also hit new
highs.
</P>
<P>
   Analysts said that the one dark spot in the latest figures was
manufacturing, where employment tumbled 13,000 in December bringing
the loss of factory jobs since March to 272,000. Traditionally,
such losses would have been considered a portent of coming
recession. But with the shift to services jobs in recent years,
they have seemed less and less important to the economy as a whole.
The government said that the manufacturing losses were offset by
the addition of 104,000 construction jobs and another 290,000
service positions.
</P>
<P>
   For the sixth year in a row, the economy created more new jobs
than it did new workers, a trend that analysts said has created
some othe highest job vacancy rates the country has ever
experienced. ``In some industries like bio-tech and software
development, there are 25 percent vacancy rates,'' said Harrington,
the Northeastern labor economist. ``There are a lot of unfilled
jobs out there.''
</P>
<P>
   Despite that, the latest government figures show that labor
costs continue to rise only modestly. Workers' average hourly
earnings, a closely watched indicator of whether the economy is
overheating, rose only five cents, or 0.4 percent, in December to
$12.98, according to BLS.
</P>
<P>
   The nation's unemployment rate has been below 5 percent, a level
that most analysts thought until recently could not be sustained
without inflation, since June of 1997. During the recession of the
early 1990s, it was as high as 7.8 percent.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
