<HEADLINE>
THOMPSON CITES MARITAL WOES, RESIGNS COACHING JOB 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JOE BURRIS  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ He probably didn't go out the way he would have
wanted. No, that's not true _ Georgetown coach John Thompson
departed Friday from basketball exactly as he wanted.
</P>
<P>
   But perhaps not as he would have hoped. Ask any coach and he'll
tell you he wants to resign after leading his team to victory in
the final game of any season.
</P>
<P>
   That didn't happen to Thompson. Friday he stepped down midway
through his 27th year at Georgetown, citing marital problems and
leaving behind a team mired in its worst Big East start (0-4) since
he took over as coach in 1972.
</P>
<P>
   But most coaches know that retiring as a national champion is
about as rare as viewing lunar eclipses and cicadas on the same
day. So Thompson, 57, settled for what he surely wanted, what every
person in one of the most unpredictable and tenuous professions in
the working world wants.
</P>
<P>
   To leave at his own time and on his own terms.
</P>
<P>
   Thompson, a former backup center with the Celtics, departed from
coaching after compiling a 596-239 mark at Georgetown _ which named
19-year assistant Craig Esherick, a former player under Thompson,
head coach, starting with Saturday's game against Providence _
Thompson's alma mater.
</P>
<P>
   ``For 27 years, I was at Georgetown, working as hard as I
possibly could. I probably made far more mistakes than I ever had
success, because we attempted to do things,'' said Thompson,
flanked by many of his former players, including Patrick Ewing and
Alonzo Mourning. ``And any time you attempt to do things, you're
going to fail far more than you ever succeed.
</P>
<P>
   ``So when you tabulate the record, don't worry about the
numbers. I did fail at more things than I ever succeeded at. But
the thing that is very important is that we tried. And in trying to
do those things, we tried to always emphasize to those students
that it was important for them to get an education.
</P>
<P>
   ``But any time a player's academics interfered with his ability
to go through Georgetown, we tried to stop him and let him deal
with what he had to deal with personally and privately pertaining
to his academics. So I had to follow my own advice. Basketball is a
24-hour job, a seven-day-a-week job, and I do not have the ability
at this time to address the things in my personal life and do my
job at the level of excellence I feel it should be done.''
</P>
<P>
   The coach who intimidated many with his size and stature
struggled to fight back tears, as did many of his former players.
``I am going through a problem with my marriage right now,''
Thompson said. ``And I owe it to my family to address that, not
just to myself and to my wife.''
</P>
<P>
   Big East commissioner Mike Tranghese, in a prepared statement,
called Thompson's resignation ``a huge loss for Georgetown and a
huge loss for the Big East. His contributions to the university and
college basketball are immense. I hope John feels he is making the
right decision for himself.''
</P>
<P>
   Thompson leaves behind a program he transformed from nondescript
status into one of the most prolific in college basketball in the
1980s, capturing the national championship in 1984 and finishing as
runner-up in 1982 and '85.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, his program became a hallmark for academic
excellence: 97 percent of the Hoyas who stayed with the program
four years earned degrees.
</P>
<P>
   The dynasty has faded over the last few years. This season the
Hoyas are 7-6. Last year they had a 15-14 regular-season record and
were invited to the NIT in part because of their reputation, and in
recent years, some players have been the subject of ugly headlines.
Yet Thompson ranked 10th among active coaches in victories and is
considered one of the game's best teachers.
</P>
<P>
   ``He tries to prepare you for life,'' said Ewing, who added that
he and Thompson had talked about the resignation for a couple of
weeks and that the topic left him at a loss for words. ``He always
taught me how to grow, not only as a basketball player but as a
person.''
</P>
<P>
   Georgetown's success on and off the court drew enormous
attention to Thompson, and he used the spotlight to speak out on
various academic, social, and racial issues. Many of his
uncompromising stances drew Thompson favor and disfavor, and his
unrelenting control over his program and his players (particularly
regarding their relationship with the press) made the coach an
enigma to some and a pain in the neck to others.
</P>
<P>
   ``Whether you agreed with his stance on issues, I always
respected the fact that he stepped forward and expressed his
opinion,'' Duke coach Mike Krzyzewski said. ``His opinion opened up
dialogue about issues that maybe would not have been discussed. As
a result, action was taken. We need more people like that. He is
not afraid to tell you what he thinks.''
</P>
<P>
   The coach embraced the same traits on the way out the door
Friday.
</P>
<P>
   ``What am I most proud of? Someone once told me I wore my
blackness well. I think that was the greatest compliment I ever
received,'' said Thompson, who made it clear he was resigning, not
retiring. He added he has not tired of the sport, nor has he tired
of coaching Generation X players.
</P>
<P>
   And he stated quite emphatically that his resignation has
nothing to do with health. ``I've got some boxing gloves in the
back and a ring if you want to go a couple of rounds,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Thompson intends to remain at Georgetown in some unspecified
official capacity and struck down notions that he will pursue the
vacant Los Angeles Clippers coaching job now that the NBA lockout
has ended.
</P>
<P>
   When a reporter asked about the Clippers job, Thompson shot
back, ``Some of you-all called out to the Clippers and asked them,
and didn't they tell you, `Hell, no'? It's not about that. If that
was something I was doing, I would tell you. When I was talking to
pro teams a few years ago, I told you. So how in the hell is a 6-10
black man going to sneak out to LA?''
</P>
<P>
   Thompson said he received a call from Temple coach John Chaney
suggesting that he take a sabbatical instead of resigning. ``I
said, `Do you ever lend somebody a toothbrush to use?' '' recalled
Thompson. ``It's either their toothbrush or your toothbrush. You
don't lend a team.''
</P>
<P>
   Thompson, who during the preseason was enthusiastic about next
season's recruits, said he will be backstage to allow Esherick to
put his stamp on the program. Yet Esherick said not to expect him
to change much.
</P>
<P>
   ``I would be an absolute fool if I did anything different
basketballwise,'' said Esherick. ``I think what (Thompson) has done
has worked. We have been very successful, and I would be more than
an absolute fool if I didn't take what I learned and put it to
use.''
</P>
<P>
   Mourning said he feels the program will be in good hands under
Esherick. But he said it will be difficult not seeing Thompson on
the sideline. ``This is definitely a decade of change. It was
similar to when Dean Smith retired,'' said Mourning. ``I was
shocked when I found out, but I'm pleased because he's going to get
some rest.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
