<HEADLINE>
HIGH COURT ACCEPTS CASES ON DISABILITY LAW AND FEDERALISM
</HEADLINE>
 
(ATTN: Fla., N.J., Colo., Calif., Fla.)   (bl)  
By LINDA GREENHOUSE   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Taking up an issue that could substantially extend
the reach of federal disability law, the Supreme Court on Friday
agreed to decide whether someone with a correctable condition, like
high blood pressure or nearsightedness, falls within the law's
protection against discrimination.
</P>
<P>
   The lower federal courts have been divided over whether to
assess a person's asserted disability with or without regard to any
``mitigating measures,'' as courts in these cases typically refer
to high blood pressure treatment or other medications, as well as
glasses and other devices that allow a person to function normally.
</P>
<P>
   While few of the millions of Americans who wear glasses face
discrimination on that account, the issue comes up in specialized
settings like the airline and trucking industries.
</P>
<P>
   Evidently eager to conduct a broad review, the justices Friday
took the relatively unusual step of accepting not just one case
with which to resolve the issue but also three cases, each with a
different twist.
</P>
<P>
   The court also announced Friday that it would take up an
important federalism issue, the question of whether Congress had
the constitutional authority, in a pair of laws enacted in 1992, to
open the federal courts to suits against states for patent and
trademark violations. This issue reached the court in a longrunning
dispute between the state of Florida and the College Savings Bank,
based in Princeton, N.J., over competing college savings investment
plans.
</P>
<P>
   The Americans with Disabilities Act defines disability as an
``impairment that substantially limits one or more of the major
life activities'' or being ``regarded as'' having such an
impairment.
</P>
<P>
   The 1990 law bars discrimination against a person with a
disability who can perform a job with reasonable accommodation. But
the 1992 law does not specify whether the limitation itself, the
factor that brings a person within the law's protection in the
first place, should be judged with or without corrective measures.
</P>
<P>
   In one of the cases the court accepted Friday, identical twin
sisters, both nearsighted but with 20/20 vision or better when
wearing glasses, were turned down for jobs as pilots by United Air
Lines because their uncorrected vision did not meet the airline's
standard of 20/100. Both women, Karen Sutton and Kimberly Hinton,
fly as pilots for regional carriers.
</P>
<P>
   They sued the airline and lost, first in U.S. District Court in
Denver in 1996 and the next year in the 10th Circuit U.S. Court of
Appeals, also in Denver. The appeals court said that because the
sisters' vision was correctable, their suit had no legal basis
because they did not suffer from a substantial limitation. The
appeal is Sutton vs. United Air Lines, No. 97-1943. United Air
Lines is a subsidiary of UAL Corp.
</P>
<P>
   In the second case, a mechanic for United Parcel Service, whose
job regularly required him to drive a truck, suffered from high
blood pressure that was controlled with medication. He sued after
the company dismissed him. He also lost in U.S. District Court in
Kansas City, Kan., and in the 10th Circuit, which ruled that his
normal functioning when taking his medication meant he was not
disabled. This case, Murphy vs. United Parcel Service, No. 97-1992,
raises the additional question of whether the plaintiff was
``regarded as'' disabled by the company, which would bring him
within the law whether he was disabled or not by some objective
standard.
</P>
<P>
   In the third case, Albertsons Inc. vs. Kirkingburg, No. 98-591,
the 9th Circuit U.S. Court of Appeals, in San Francisco, went the
other way and ruled that a truck driver with a vision impairment
might qualify as disabled.
</P>
<P>
   The federal government's position, as expressed in a brief filed
in December at the court's invitation, is that the existence of a
disability _ even a correctable vision impairment _ should be
assessed without regard to any mitigating measures. That was the
intent of Congress as well as the long-held view of the Equal
Employment Opportunity Commission, the brief said.
</P>
<P>
   The College Savings Bank cases the court accepted Friday, one a
patent infringement case and one a false advertising claim under
federal trademark law, bring the justices back to a potentially
far-reaching issue they last examined three years ago, the extent
of state immunity from suit in federal court.
</P>
<P>
   In a 1996 case, the court ruled that Congress lacked
constitutional authority to permit Indian tribes to sue states in
disputes over setting up casinos. That decision, Seminole Tribe vs.
Florida, was issued as the College Savings Bank was in the midst of
suing Florida on charges that the state's program of offering a
savings plan for college costs was an illegitimate copy of the
program the private bank initiated in 1987.
</P>
<P>
   At that point, Florida moved to dismiss the bank's two lawsuits,
claiming immunity from suit.
</P>
<P>
   Eventually, the trademark case was dismissed but the U.S. Court
of Appeals for the Federal Circuit ruled last year that the College
Savings Bank was entitled to protect its ``property'' _ its patent
on its investment plan _ by pursuing its lawsuit.
</P>
<P>
   Florida, backed by 24 other states, is arguing that the federal
law authorizing a patent infringement suit against a state is
unconstitutional. The case is Florida vs. College Savings Bank, No.
98-531. The trademark case, which the court also accepted, is
College Savings Bank vs. Florida, No. 98-149.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
