<SLUG> BC-IMPEACH-DEAL09-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Senate agreement to advance trial relays `sense of relief,'
camaraderie
 &HT;    By Mark Sherman
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Senators hailed their unanimous agreement Friday to
move ahead with President Clinton's impeachment trial as the latest
example of the camaraderie that distinguishes the Senate from the
House of Representatives.
</P>
<P>
   They generously ladled out praise for their colleagues in the
other party, spoke of mutual trust and talked about the importance
of acting in the nation's interest on this grave matter.
</P>
<P>
   But the hurdle that they surmounted Friday was not terribly
high. And the roll call vote Friday afternoon that drew 100
``ayes'' does not preclude a furious fight in two weeks time over
the same issue that has continued to elude resolution, the calling
of witnesses.
</P>
<P>
   In short, the Senate decided, as it often does, that there is no
reason to argue today over what can be argued tomorrow.
</P>
<P>
   ``I hope we've got 100 happy campers,'' Sen. Slade Gorton
(R-Wash.) said. ``We probably won't after we start the trial.''
</P>
<P>
   Sen. Charles Schumer (D-N.Y.), a new senator and a veteran of
the partisan wars in the House, said he was pleased with the
outcome. But he was less certain that it represented a solution.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is a sort of timetable agreement that puts off the major
confrontation. We'll start the process and see if there can be some
kind of arrangement,'' Schumer said.
</P>
<P>
   The deal that emerged from Friday's closed-door session in the
old Senate chamber grew out of a realization that Senate rules
would not allow Democrats to foreclose the possibility that
witnesses could be called to testify in the impeachment trial.
</P>
<P>
   But Democrats will retain the right to move to dismiss the
charges against Clinton after just a handful of days of
presentation by Republican House prosecutors and the president's
lawyers.
</P>
<P>
   For their part, many Republicans in the Senate are not eager to
have Monica Lewinsky, Betty Currie, Vernon Jordan and Kathleen
Willey, among other potential witnesses identified by House
Republicans, troop through their work place.
</P>
<P>
   ``The big concern on everyone's part is that there is no need to
turn this into a circus, that we not have evidence that refers to
the sexual materials,'' Sen. Pete Domenici (R-N.M.) said.
</P>
<P>
   What made the agreement so unusual is that it came during a rare
meeting of all 100 senators in the chamber that was the Senate's
home until 1858, not as a result of an impromptu huddle of a few
key senators or an exchange of telephone calls by senior aides.
</P>
<P>
   Several senators said the consecutive presentations by one of
the Senate's most conservative members, Sen. Phil Gramm (R-Texas),
and one of its most liberal, Sen. Edward Kennedy (D-Mass.), made
them take note that, other than the witness dispute, there was
little that separated Democrats from Republicans.
</P>
<P>
   In fact, the document that was read on the Senate floor gives
each side three days to present its case, rather than the two days
a piece that the Democrats proposed.
</P>
<P>
   After Gramm and Kennedy spoke, Sen. Mitch McConnell (R-Ky.)
said, ``Everyone sort of smiled and said, 'What are arguing
over?'''
</P>
<P>
   More important than the details, senators said, were the candid,
respectful exchanges that made compromise more likely.
</P>
<P>
   ``What's important is the body language in people and the
sincerity of what they're saying. That's what this kind of thing
allowed us to do,'' said Sen. Dianne Feinstein (D-Calif.).
</P>
<P>
   Sen. Robert Byrd (D-W.Va.) spoke about the Senate's history of
consensus, particularly at difficult times.
</P>
<P>
   ``He reminded us that on certain occasions that people are
required to rise above the ordinary course of conduct ... and this
is one of those moments. He set the tone,'' Sen. Fred Thompson
(R-Tenn.) said.
</P>
<P>
   In recent days, several senators expressed a growing concern
that they were beginning to look like House members who engaged in
openly hostile, sometimes insulting public exchanges.
</P>
<P>
   They feared the public would view the Senate's proceedings with
the same distaste. Their concerns flowed as much from the potential
public reaction as from the belief that is universal in the Senate
that it is a less confrontational body than the House and better
able to keep partisan politics and emotions in check.
</P>
<P>
   To that end, Friday's meeting produced a ``sense of relief,''
Sen. Bill Frist (R-Tenn.) said.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's almost like the top of a boiling pot coming off and all
the little bubbles simmering down,'' Frist said.
</P>
<P>
   Sen. Joseph Biden (D-Del.) said he and his colleagues recoiled
at ``the idea that the Senate would degenerate into a pit bull
ring.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
