</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-POLLARD-SENTENCE-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SPY, LAW ENFORCEMENT AGENCIES OPPOSED TO REDUCTION OF POLLARD
SENTENCE  
(JT)
</HEADLINE>
   By DAVID JOHNSTON    
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Law enforcement and intelligence officials said
Friday that they remain adamantly opposed to shortening the life
sentence of Jonathan Pollard, a former Navy intelligence analyst
convicted of spying for Israel.
</P>
<P>
   Last month, the White House asked the agencies to submit their
recommendations on whether Pollard should be granted clemency after
demands for his release were made by Israel in October at the
Middle East peace negotiations in Wye, Md.
</P>
<P>
   But the agencies' opposition to granting Pollard leniency, which
has never wavered during Clinton's presidency, may not end the
debate over the case, the officials said. The president has
exclusive power to grant clemency, and the officials said Clinton's
aides could seek to reduce Pollard's sentence or give him a release
date from prison.
</P>
<P>
   The State Department and the Justice Department have yet to
submit their views, and officials said that Clinton and his aides
are not likely to make a decision soon. The officials said that
while they agree that Pollard's crimes are ``reprehensible,'' as
several described them, not all are convinced that Pollard should
never be released.
</P>
<P>
   The agencies have until Monday to provide their evaluations to
Charles Ruff, the White House counsel. Last month the White House
sent letters to Attorney General Janet Reno, Secretary of State
Madeleine Albright, Defense Secretary William Cohen and the
director of central intelligence, George Tenet, asking for their
views on the Pollard case.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have begun to receive recommendations from the president's
advisers,'' said David Leavy, a White House spokesman. ``The
president will review the information. He may want further
information. He may ask additional questions and will move forward
in a careful and timely manner.''
</P>
<P>
   Under heavy pressure from Israel and supporters of Pollard in
the United States, Clinton reviewed the case in 1993 and again in
1996. Each time, the president decided against clemency after
receiving recommendations from Cabinet officials and agencies
involved in the case.
</P>
<P>
   Most of the officials have long been on record as opposing
clemency for Pollard. During the peace talks in October, Tenet
bluntly told Clinton that he would resign if the president agreed
to turn over Pollard as part of the agreement.
</P>
<P>
   The CIA and the other U.S. intelligence agencies are known to be
strongly opposed to any consideration of leniency toward Pollard.
They have said in the past that his spying inflicted the gravest
damage to national security by revealing secret codes and
communications methods, endangering the ability of intelligence
officers to communicate and gather information in secret.
</P>
<P>
   In Israel, conservatives have championed the release of Pollard
for years. Prime Minister Benjamin Netanyahu of Israel has pressed
the administration for Pollard's release and the case became a
central issue in the peace talks. On the last of nine days of
negotiations, Netanyahu demanded Pollard's release in exchange for
his support for an agreement.
</P>
<P>
   Although Clinton denied Netanyahu's demands, he did agree to
reconsider the case even though there was little likelihood that
any of the agencies involved would support a reduction in Pollard's
life sentence.
</P>
<P>
   Pollard was arrested in 1985 after spying for Israel for at
least 18 months. He turned over a huge quantity of classified
documents to the Israelis. He pleaded guilty and was sentenced to
life in prison.
</P>
<P>
   Much of the material Pollard sold to the Israelis involved
Soviet weapons systems, information that had been obtained at
enormous risk by spies working inside the former Soviet Union, who
were compromised as a result of the case.
</P>
<P>
   Pollard argued that he was punished too severely because he was
spying for an ally that should have been given the information that
Washington had withheld. But U.S. officials said he had betrayed
vital secrets to the Israelis, who, they said, had never fully
cooperated with investigators or even returned all of the documents
Pollard supplied them.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
