A5439 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-UN-TROUBLESHOOTER-BOS     01-08 0699
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-UN-TROUBLESHOOTER-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EX-SOVIET FOE OF US GIVEN ADVISORY ROLE AT UN 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By COLUM LYNCH  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ In a move that is likely to increase Russia's
influence in the United Nations, Secretary General Kofi Annan has
appointed a senior Russian official _ and former US Cold War
adversary _ to serve as his diplomatic troubleshooter.
</P>
<P>
   The appointment of Yuli M. Vorontsov, Russia's outgoing
ambassador to Washington, has generated anxiety among US officials,
already upset with Annan over leaks about US espionage in Iraq
under UN auspices.
</P>
<P>
   Vorontsov has been an adept diplomatic foe of Washington in
Afghanistan and during the end of the Cold War _ emerging later as
an adversary over conflicting US-Russian policies in Iraq.
</P>
<P>
   UN officials sought to portray the appointment as one not
designed to rankle Washington, but US officials reacted
suspiciously.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is the consummate survivor in the old Soviet system,'' a
US official who has tracked Vorontsov said Friday. ``Whether that
is the sort of person we want in the United Nations Secretariat is
a fair question.''
</P>
<P>
   UN officals insisted Friday that there is nothing unusual in the
appointment. Secretary Generals have always enlisted the services
of prominent diplomats.
</P>
<P>
   Former US secretaries of state Cyrus Vance and James Baker have
served as diplomatic envoys for the United Nations from the Balkans
to Western Sahara. Many of Annan's current diplomatic
troubleshooters, including the current UN-East Timor mediator,
Jamsheed Marker of Pakistan, have previously served as an
ambassador at UN headquarters in New York.
</P>
<P>
   Vorontsov, Russia's ambassador to the United Nations from 1990
to 1994 has accepted the post for a token annual salary of a
dollar. He will hold the rank of undersecretary general, carrying
out diplomatic missions for the UN chief.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's an old pro and he was at the UN for many years.'' the
Amerian official said. ``So he is certanly qualified, but he's an
old Soviet.''
</P>
<P>
   Russian specialists say Vorontsov could actually be a
conciliatory influence for relations between the United States and
the United Nations, which have degenerated to their worst state
since Annan came to office two years ago.
</P>
<P>
   Vorontsov, a close ally of Russia's former spymaster, current
Prime Minister Yevgeny Primakov, has headed key Russian embassies
in France, India, and Afghanistan.
</P>
<P>
   The arrival of Vorontsov will place witin Annan's inner circle
another advocate of softening the UN's policy on Iraq. Annan's
closest closest advisers have already pressed the UN secratary
general to ease economic sanctions on Iraq and weaken the
international weapons inspection team responsible for ridding Iraq
of its nuclear, chemical and biological weapons.
</P>
<P>
   Some observers say that Vorontsov may prove useful to the United
States, which is seeking to smooth relations with Moscow over
Washington's disision to launch air strikes gainst Iraq without
Russian backing.
</P>
<P>
   Jeffrey Laurenti, an analyst at the United Nations Association,
said while Vorontsov often has clashed with the Americans in the
past he has also worked with the United Nations during the most
cooperative period of US-Russian relations.
</P>
<P>
   He said that it may advantageous to have Russia play a more
active role in conflict resolution, as long as it doesn't involve a
part of the world where Washington and Moscow are at loggerheads.
</P>
<P>
   ``Giving him an assignment in Iraq or Yugoslavia would be
damaging to Washington's trust,'' he said. ``But it is not an
inherently bad thing to keep the Russians engaged in a constructive
way.''
</P>
<P>
   Stephen Cohen, a Russian Studies professor at New York
University, said Verontsov is among the more pro-Western diplomats
in the Russian foreign ministry.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Russian Foreign Ministry is divided between those who are
suspicious of the West,'' Cohen said. `` And there are those
Russians who feel Russia's destiny is in the West. Vorontsov would
be among those people.''
</P>
<P>
   ``If there is going to be a Russian in that position,'' he
added, ``It's hard to imagine anyone we would prefer over him.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
