<SLUG> BC-IRAQ-DAMAGE-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PENTAGON SAYS IRAQ BOMBINGS CAUSED MORE DAMAGE THAN REPORTED
EARLIER
</HEADLINE>
 (bl) 
By STEVEN LEE MYERS   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Almost three weeks after the bombing stopped, the
Pentagon's senior commanders said Friday that the U.S. and British
raids on Iraq had caused more damage than initially reported.
</P>
<P>
   The chairman of the Joint Chiefs of Staff, Gen. Henry Shelton,
and the commander of U.S. forces in the Persian Gulf, Gen. Anthony
Zinni, described President Saddam Hussein as isolated and
desperate, and less able to build missiles.
</P>
<P>
   The generals said they based their assessments on intelligence
information that went beyond aerial or satellite photographs of the
damage done in four nights of air and missile strikes. But they
offered little detail and even less evidence to support their
conclusions, which, they conceded, were based on incomplete and, in
some cases, unverifiable reports.
</P>
<P>
   Shelton, the senior military adviser to President Clinton and
Defense Secretary William Cohen, said for the first time Friday
that the raids had killed ``several key individuals'' in the Iraqi
military hierarchy. He declined to elaborate or name the officials.
</P>
<P>
   He also said unconfirmed intelligence reports suggested that the
raids had killed 600 to 1,600 members of the Republican Guard,
troops that Saddam uses to maintain internal control. Although the
guard has 30,000 troops, Shelton said, the casualties would
undercut Saddam.
</P>
<P>
   ``He lost a lot,'' Shelton said at a breakfast meeting with
reporters in Washington.
</P>
<P>
   In separate briefings, they also cited reports of summary
executions in Iraq as signs that Saddam's control had been shaken.
</P>
<P>
   The updated and upbeat assessments came in the wake of Iraq's
renewed defiance of the United Nations and the U.S. and British
enforcement of ``no flight'' zones over much of Iraqi territory.
</P>
<P>
   Four times in the last two weeks Iraqi warplanes or
anti-aircraft have challenged U.S. or British planes, proving that
four nights of strikes had not stopped Saddam from being an
irritant, at the least, to the Clinton administration.
</P>
<P>
   The president's national security adviser, Samuel Berger, said
in an interview Friday that Saddam was ``flailing,'' having counted
on but not received support from the Arab world. He cited Saddam's
vitriolic attacks on Arab leaders in a speech Tuesday and the
equally pointed reaction since then from those leaders, including
Egyptian President Hosni Mubarak.
</P>
<P>
   ``The military purpose of the strike was not to bring down his
government,'' Berger said, ``but I think it has weakened it,
politically as well as militarily.''
</P>
<P>
   At the Pentagon on Friday, Zinni said new information now showed
that the attacks on Iraq's military and industrial infrastructure
had caused ``far more severe'' damage than first thought. He and
other officials had initially estimated that Iraq's missile
development had been set back one year by the strikes; Friday he
said it might be two years.
</P>
<P>
   Pointing to sketchy new reports on damage inflicted inside the
buildings struck, he said ``unique pieces of equipment'' involved
in making missiles, like metal presses and test stands, had been
destroyed. He said that Iraq may not have been able to protect as
much equipment as he and other commanders expected.
</P>
<P>
   ``As we look deeper and we have more detail, reports on our
intelligence and other means that verify this, we're seeing that
the effectiveness was even greater than we first thought,'' Zinni
said.
</P>
<P>
   Shelton and Zinni also cited unconfirmed reports suggesting
internal dissent inside Iraq, if not rebellion. That suggested,
they said, an erosion of Saddam's control. They said Saddam had
reportedly ordered the execution of army officers and civilians in
the south, where Shiite Muslims have long chafed under Saddam's
power.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've seen a number of unusual things internally that I think
clearly demonstrate that he was shaken and the regime was shaken,''
Zinni said. ``We have seen executions in the South; one division in
particular lost its commander and several others.''
</P>
<P>
   Despite these signs, there has been no reports of significant
dissent since the bombing. Nor have there been any uprisings on the
level of those that followed Saddam's rout in the Persian Gulf war.
Back then Saddam, though reeling, crushed rebellions by Kurds in
the north and Shiites in the south. The United States and its
allies created the ``no flight'' zones afterwards to help protect
the ethnic populations in those regions.
</P>
<P>
   ``It would be wrong to assume the house of cards is about to
crumble,'' an intelligence official said Friday.
</P>
<P>
   The United States also increased its forces in the gulf for the
first time since last month's raids. Zinni announced that eight
more F-16 fighters would go to the region. The jets, along with
four aerial tankers, will joint 182 aircraft jets already there,
mostly in Saudi Arabia and Kuwait and aboard the aircraft carrier
Carl Vinson.
</P>
<P>
   The F-16 jets carry radar-seeking missiles, called HARMs, which
are designed to attack surface-to-air missile launchers and other
anti-aircraft weapons, like those that have threatened U.S. and
British jets patroling the ``no flight'' zones over southern and
northern Iraq.
</P>
<P>
   Britain also announced that it would dispatch an aircraft
carrier, the Invincible, and it would set sail for the gulf on
Saturday.
</P>
<P>
   The United States and Britain have not ruled out launching new
attacks.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
