<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MUTFUND-JUNK-ART-$ADV10-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
YES, THOSE JUNK-BOND FUNDS ARE STILL CHEAP, BUT GO ON TIPTOES 
</HEADLINE>
   (ART ADV: Graphic is being sent to NYT graphic clients.
Non-subscribers can make individual purchase by calling (888)
603-1036 or (888) 346-9867.)  
 (FOR RELEASE SUNDAY, JAN. 10)  
 (af)  
 By ABBY SCHULTZ   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Although prices of junk bonds, have risen since their tumble
late last summer, it still costs less to buy mutual funds that hold
this high-risk, high-return corporate debt than at any time since
1990.
</P>
<P>
   With junk bonds yielding surpassing 10 percent, Martin Fridson,
chief high-yield strategist at Merrill Lynch, reported that as of
Dec. 31, yields were a stunning 5.55 percentage points higher for
junk bonds than for comparable 10-year Treasury notes. That is down
from a spread of 6.2 percentage points on Oct. 31, but still far
above the 3.73-point spread of late July.
</P>
<P>
   Junk bonds can give a portfolio diversity and extra income, but
they are riskier than other commonly traded securities _ and that
makes picking the right fund paramount. And given the typical
$25,000 price tag for an individual holding, as well as the
difficulties in assessing credit quality, funds are the way to go
for most individual investors who are interested in junk bonds.
</P>
<P>
   In choosing a fund, an investor should look first at how long it
has been around. The relatively strong performance of high-yield
securities for much of this decade has prompted a host of new
funds: Nearly 40 percent of the high-yield funds tracked by
Morningstar are no more than three years old.
</P>
<P>
   Stephen P. Barnes, a certified financial planner in Phoenix,
prefers funds with track records of at least five years so he can
gauge whether a fund's management team has been true to its stated
objectives.
</P>
<P>
   He steers a lot of clients, all of them affluent, into Northeast
Investors, which began in 1950. Northeast, which has returned 10.35
percent over the last five years, did not have a superb 1998 _ it
lost 0.24 percent _ but Barnes is not concerned. ``They've been
around forever with the same basic philosophy,'' he said. ``We are
comfortable there are not going to be any surprises with their
investment style.''
</P>
<P>
   Steve Chung, a Morningstar analyst, recommends that investors
buy a fund only if it has a good long-term record and has had the
same manager or management team in place for more than six months.
If management has changed recently, the fund may no longer be
operating in the way ``that created the good long-term record,''
Chung said.
</P>
<P>
   The best way to test a manager is to see how he or she has done
when the market goes awry, he added. Last year afforded a perfect
opportunity: In the first half, the average junk fund was up 4.62
percent. Then in summer and fall, Russia went into default, the
Long Term Capital Management hedge fund had to be rescued and
President Clinton's troubles deepened; institutional investors
quickly shed risky assets and fled to the safety of Treasuries. The
high-yield market tumbled.
</P>
<P>
   Funds that did relatively well in this bearish period are worth
a look. The average high-yield fund lost 10.07 percent from Aug. 1
to Oct. 31, according to Morningstar. But Columbia High-Yield, for
example, a five-year-old fund with about $57 million in assets,
lost 2.73 percent in that period and ended 1998 with a return of
6.02 percent.
</P>
<P>
   Credit quality is another factor. Dreyfus High Yield, which
ended 1997 in the top 6 percent of all high-yield funds, stumbled
badly, losing 23.89 percent, from Aug. 1 until Oct. 31, 1998, and
ended the year down 15.84 percent. More than a third of Dreyfus
High Yield's assets were in securities with credit ratings of B or
below, said Sarah Bush, a Morningstar analyst. That contrasts with
about 7 percent for the average high-yield fund, Ms. Bush said.
</P>
<P>
   Generally, a fund with higher-quality junk bonds will have an
average credit rating of BB; a fund with lower-quality junk bonds
will have an average rating of B. In choosing a fund, investors
should consider how much risk they are willing to assume. A fund
like Vanguard High-Yield Corporate, with an average credit rating
of BB, tends not to be hit as hard when the high-yield market
stumbles, Chung said. It lost only 1.54 percent in the
third-quarter down market. On the other hand, ``they don't capture
as much of the up side as some of the more aggressively positioned
funds,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Another consideration is how much the fund holds in other types
of securities, like convertible bonds or emerging-markets debt. An
investor who already owns an emerging-markets debt fund would
probably want to steer clear of a junk-bond fund heavily invested
in these securities.
</P>
<P>
   Most junk-bond funds are allowed to invest up to 25 percent of
their assets in emerging-markets debt. One clue as to whether a
fund has such holdings can be performance: Funds that did badly in
the late summer may have been holding more than the average amount
of emerging-markets debt, Chung said.
</P>
<P>
   If all this sounds complicated, it is, but making the effort to
sort it out can pay off. ``A high-yield subportfolio will typically
add value over time,'' Barnes said.
</P>
<P>
   If economic growth is moderate this year, investors in junk
bonds can at the very least count on receiving interest payments
from their investments, which would leave them with a total return
of about 10 percent to 12 percent, says Peter Anderson, manager of
Conseco High Yield, a year-old $45 million mutual fund based in
Carmel, Ind. The fund returned 6.55 percent in 1998.
</P>
</TEXT>
