<SLUG> BC-IMPEACH-POLITICS-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GOP SENATORS WALK A TRICKY POLITICAL TIGHTROPE DURING IMPEACHMENT
TRIAL 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By BENNETT ROTH 
c.1998 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ If Senate Republicans are trying to avoid the
partisan slugfest that characterized the House impeachment
proceedings against President Clinton, it may be because they
understand political math.
</P>
<P>
   The risks of proceeding with a lengthy and messy impeachment
trial are particularly great for the Republicans in the Senate
because they must defend 19 seats in the 2000 election as compared
to 14 for the Democrats.
</P>
<P>
   Further exacerbating matters for the GOP, 13 of the seats they
must defend are in states that Clinton carried in 1996, including
Maine, Michigan, Minnesota, Pennsylvania, Rhode Island and
Washington.
</P>
<P>
   Republicans hold a 55-45 margin majority in the Senate.
</P>
<P>
   The GOP senators walk a trickier political tightrope than their
House counterparts, who represent districts that are often
overwhelmingly Republican.
</P>
<P>
   To retain the seats in Democrat-leaning states, Republican
senators must carry the bulk of the independent swing voters who
polls have consistently shown do not want the president ousted.
</P>
<P>
   At the same time, the lawmakers must be careful not to offend
the party's increasingly conservative base, which is clamoring for
the president's ouster and could make trouble for Republican
candidates in a primary.
</P>
<P>
   ``If they do let the guy off too easy, their base just goes
ballistic,'' said Charles Cook, a Washington-based political
analyst.
</P>
<P>
   But he and others added that a prolonged Senate trial could
merely reinforce increasingly negative perceptions of the GOP among
independent voters and Democrats.
</P>
<P>
   Polls found that during the rancorous House proceedings, voter
approval ratings of congressional Republicans plummeted to their
lowest levels in years.
</P>
<P>
   Some analysts argue that if the Senate repeats the House
experience, voters may conclude that the party has no other agenda
than ousting the president.
</P>
<P>
   ``The problem the party has, it is perceived with a negative
agenda. It is not perceived as a party that comes up with solutions
that confront the problems of the nation,`` said Terry Madonna, a
political science professor at Millersville University in
Pennsylvania.
</P>
<P>
   Madonna said Pennsylvanians will be watching Sen. Rick Santorum,
who was elected in the Republican tidal wave of 1994 but who is
considered more conservative than most of the state's voters.
</P>
<P>
   Madonna said the risk for Santorum is that a vote to convict
Clinton would make it easier for Democrats to portray the senator
as an extremist.
</P>
<P>
   He said Santorum could survive even if he votes to convict
Clinton if the senator comes across as ``judicious, fair,
senatorial.'' Although he is a persistent Clinton critic, Santorum
has not yet said if he will vote to convict the president.
</P>
<P>
   Madonna also noted that Santorum has in recent years moved to
the center of the political spectrum and has embraced issues such
as Social Security reform that resonate with voters.
</P>
<P>
   Texas Republican Sen. Kay Bailey Hutchison, who is also up for
re-election in two years, has steered a cautious approach in the
impeachment debate.
</P>
<P>
   She has been reluctant to embrace House Republicans' demands
that witnesses, including former White House intern Monica
Lewinsky, be summoned to testify before the Senate.
</P>
<P>
   Hutchison is not in as difficult predicament as some of her
colleagues. State voting trends have favored Republicans in recent
years; Clinton was unable to carry the state in his two
presidential races.
</P>
<P>
   Furthermore, a weakened state Democratic organization has yet to
field an opponent who could give Hutchison trouble.
</P>
<P>
   Nevertheless, she still must cope with the competing political
forces. While the senator said that overwhelming majority of the
42,000 calls and e-mail messages to her office have favored
conviction of the president, statewide polls have consistently
shown that Texans do not want the president removed.
</P>
<P>
   If Hutchison were to vote against conviction, she could stir up
religious conservatives in the state who have never viewed her as
an ally.
</P>
<P>
   Martin Belforte, the acting executive director of the American
Family Association of Texas, an Austin-based conservative group,
warned that ``virtually all conservatives here in Texas expect her
to vote for his removal from office. There would be repercussions
if she were to vote against.''
</P>
<P>
   Belforte said his group had hoped that Hutchison would take a
``much more outspoken, committed position'' on impeachment, much as
they believe the state's other GOP senator, Phil Gramm, has done.
Gramm has pushed for a full trial and said he would accept
witnesses if that is what the House managers want.
</P>
<P>
   If Hutchison were to vote for conviction after a long, messy
trial, she could also energize now-dormant Democrats.
</P>
<P>
   Texas Democratic Party chairwoman Molly Beth Malcolm said
impeachment could be an issue in the next Senate election.
</P>
<P>
   ``Texans, just like all other Americans, are sick and tired of
partisan Republican attempts to drive the president from office,''
she said.
</P>
<P>
   Hutchison, however, said she is not factoring her next election
into impeachment decisions.
</P>
<P>
   ``I am not worried about the politics of it at all,'' she said.
``I believe I will be judged by how we conducted this trial, if the
Constitutional precedents were set that were responsible, and if we
are fair to both sides.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
