<SLUG> BC-MUTFUND-PORTFOLIOS-ART-$ADV10-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THESE PILOTS SEE A BUMPY FLIGHT 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Attn: Calif., Ill., N.Y., Mass., Fla.)   (ART ADV: Graphic is being sent to NYT graphic clients.
Non-subscribers can make individual purchase by calling (888)
603-1036 or (888) 346-9867.)  
 (FOR RELEASE SUNDAY, JAN. 10)  
 (af)  
 By CAROLE GOULD   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Although most mutual fund investors closed out 1998 with gains,
the road was rocky, with their climb hampered by sharp dips and the
summer selloff.
</P>
<P>
   The five professional money managers who have built hypothetical
retirement portfolios over the last five years for The New York
Times expect volatility to increase in 1999.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm expecting a very rugged year,'' said Jack A. Brill, a San
Diego adviser who hews a ``socially responsible'' course. ``My
guess is that the market will break 10,000, with a 15 percent
meltdown during the year,'' he said. ``I'd expect 10 to 15 percent
growth at best.''
</P>
<P>
   Brill tied for first place among the five advisers in the fourth
quarter. His portfolio rose 20.34 percent, lifted by its bias
toward large- and mid-capitalization stocks. It was handicapped
only by an investment in Vanguard GNMA, which rose less than 1
percent.
</P>
<P>
   He is whittling some holdings to make room for the Citizens
Index fund, but is otherwise sitting tight. He figures _ as do the
other four advisers _ that a diverse portfolio is the best weapon
against market volatility. That, and a stiff upper lip. ``I think
individual investors should play the market for the long term,
looking past the daily hype and focusing on solid growth,'' he
said.
</P>
<P>
   What, of course, is not always easy to do. Susan Dziubinski,
editor of Morningstar Fund Investor, a newsletter, noted wryly that
while diversification remained her touchstone, it did not pay off
in 1998. ``This certainly wasn't a good year for a contrarian
portfolio like mine,'' she said. ``Small value continued to lag,
and so did emerging markets. And nearly nonexistent inflation
hammered Oppenheimer Real Asset, my portfolio hedge.''
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Dziubinski came in right behind the two leaders for the
quarter, with a gain of 17.01 percent, and has tinkered only a bit
with her portfolio.
</P>
<P>
   Among the minor adjustments, she is condensing her large-cap
international funds by scuttling Ivy International in favor of
EuroPacific Growth, which has lower expenses. Similarly, she is
jettisoning Small Cap World, a global fund with a large chunk of
small domestic stocks, and buying Founders Passport, a small-cap
fund with less than 3 percent of assets invested in the United
States.
</P>
<P>
   She is also selling the Fidelity Fund, which she concedes is a
top performer, and buying TIAA-CREF Growth and Income. About 80
percent of the TIAA-CREF fund tracks the Standard &AMP; Poor's
500-stock index. ``Over the long term,'' she added, ``I question
the ability of active managers to really add value when it comes to
large-cap investing.''
</P>
<P>
   Sheldon Jacobs, who edits the No-load Fund Investor in
Irvington, N.Y., was tied with Brill for first place in the quarter
and retains the lead among the five managers over all, with a
cumulative gain of 129.69 percent since July 7, 1993, when the
contest began.
</P>
<P>
   In that time, the five portfolios have risen an average of
107.09 percent, compared with a 212.16 percent return for the
Vanguard 500 Index fund, which mimics the S&AMP;P 500.
</P>
<P>
   The performance of the hypothetical portfolios is tracked each
quarter by Lipper Inc. of Summit, N.J. It excludes sales charges,
transaction costs and taxes because most retirement money is held
in tax-deferred accounts. The five managers can choose any fund
open to new investors and can shift money quarterly. They were
asked to pick portfolios intended to grow for 20 years.
</P>
<P>
   All the portfolios earned double-digit returns in the quarter _
a period in which Morningstar Inc., the financial publisher,
calculates that diversified domestic equity funds rose an average
of 18.73 percent.
</P>
<P>
   Jacobs is adding to his holdings in Vanguard 500 Index formerly
called Vanguard Index Trust 500, bringing it to 15 percent of
assets from 12.5 percent. This change, plus the 35 percent
weighting in Vanguard Total Stock Market, enables him to reach his
goal of being 50 percent invested in index funds. The extra money
for the Index 500 fund comes from selling a small chunk of Baron
Growth and Income, lowering it to 10 percent of the portfolio.
</P>
<P>
   He is also replacing American Century/20th Century International
Discovery, a small-cap fund, with Montgomery International Growth,
a large-cap blend fund, because he thinks big stocks will
outperform smaller ones overseas.
</P>
<P>
   Eric M. Kobren, president of Kobren Insight Group and editor of
Fidelity Insight in Wellesley, Mass., finished next to last in the
quarter, with a gain of 15.68 percent. His portfolio, made up
entirely of Fidelity funds, was held back by a 20 percent
investment in Fidelity Spartan Government Income, which slipped
0.23 percent. Even so, he is increasing his position in the fund to
25 percent from 20 percent. He is adding to the bond holdings, he
said, ``because strong corporate earnings growth will remain hard
to achieve in 1999.''
</P>
<P>
   Kobren is doubling his position, to 20 percent, in Fidelity
Contrafund II, which he calls ``a fund with the flexibility to go
anywhere in the market in search of good stocks.'' He is reducing
his position in Fidelity Small-Cap Stock to 15 percent from 20
percent. And he sold his entire 10 percent holding in Fidelity Real
Estate, because, he said, the bond fund provides sufficient
diversification.
</P>
<P>
   Harold R. Evensky, a financial adviser in Coral Gables, Fla.,
finished last in the quarter, with a portfolio gain of 14.44
percent.
</P>
<P>
   In a departure from his usual practice of making few changes,
Evensky is giving his portfolio a new look this quarter. He is
selling his position in Cohen &AMP; Steers Realty Shares and using that
money to start an 8 percent position in Vanguard Extended Market
Index, to give added exposure to smaller stocks.
</P>
<P>
   He is replacing Warburg Pincus International Equity, which
gained 12.88 percent in the last quarter, with Montgomery
International Growth. He is also exchanging Blackrock Small Cap
Growth for Undiscovered Managers Behavioral Growth.
</P>
<P>
   ``It remains tough,'' he said, ``to preach intelligent
diversification in long-term investing in an environment like
this.''
</P>
</TEXT>
