<DOCNO> NYT19990108.0347 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-01-08 20:01 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5451 &Cx1f; taf-z
s f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-MUTFUND-NEWSLETTERS-A     01-08 0818
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MUTFUND-NEWSLETTERS-ART-2TAKES-$ADV10-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CONSERVATIVE STEPS, LIBERAL GAINS 
</HEADLINE>
   (ART ADV: Graphic is being sent to NYT graphic clients.
Non-subscribers can make individual purchase by calling (888)
603-1036 or (888) 346-9867.)  
 (FOR RELEASE SUNDAY, JAN. 10)  
 (af)  
 By MARK HULBERT   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Mutual funds used to be sold as one-decision investments. If
they weren't held for a lifetime, at least they were held for many
years. And because they were so diversified, in theory you needed
only one fund. Life was simple.
</P>
<P>
   Today's fund arena could hardly be more different. Many
supposedly diversified funds are so narrowly focused that some
investors could achieve greater diversification by buying the stock
of a single multinational, multiline corporation, like General
Electric.
</P>
<P>
   And almost no one these days considers mutual funds to be
lifetime holdings. Instead, they chase short-term performance,
switching in and out of funds with about as much abandon as they
show for individual stocks.
</P>
<P>
   Not surprisingly, an entire industry has sprung up to respond to
investors' needs in this brave new hyperkinetic world: mutual fund
advisory newsletters. These publication often advise subscribers
about when to jump in or out of the market, as well as which funds
to buy when it's time to be invested.
</P>
<P>
   This industry has grown rapidly. As recently as 20 years ago, no
more than one or two newsletters even mentioned mutual funds.
Today, at least half of the 160 newsletters monitored by the
Hulbert Financial Digest focus on funds.
</P>
<P>
   How have these fund newsletters performed? It depends on how you
look at it.
</P>
<P>
   I calculated their returns for the last 10 years through Nov. 30
by following their model portfolio advice exactly, executing
transactions on the very day that subscribers could act upon it.
Fund loads, redemption fees and distributions were all taken into
account. Only three of the 47 portfolios with sufficient records in
my database, Fundline's $100,000 Aggressive Portfolio and two from
Fidelity Monitor _ Select System and Growth Model _ outperformed
the 17.6 percent annualized gain of the Wilshire 5000 index on an
absolute basis, returning 18.7 percent, 21.8 percent, and 18.4
percent, respectively. All three portfolios use aggressive-growth
or growth strategies.
</P>
<P>
   But while pure performance may be all that many fund
shareholders care about, it is an overly simplistic way to look at
investing. Smart investors will also look at the risk entailed in
achieving their returns. To adjust performance for risk, I
calculated what a newsletter portfolio's return would have been if
its volatility had matched the market's. This meant adding cash to
portfolios that were riskier than the market, and buying on margin
_ using leverage _ when it came to portfolios that were less risky.
</P>
<P>
   On a risk-adjusted basis, the newsletters did better; 10
portfolios outperformed the market. And by examining what these top
performers have in common, you can learn a lot about how to invest
in funds.
</P>
<P>
   The most surprising pattern is that the majority of the top
portfolios pursued conservative strategies. In fact, of the last
decade's top 10 newsletter portfolios, five are best characterized
as income oriented, and two more are best described as being of the
growth-and-income variety. (The three more aggressive portfolios
that beat the index before risk adjustment also made the cut.)
</P>
<P>
   This pattern is nothing short of remarkable. We might have
expected it had the market declined over the last decade _ but not
during the strong bull market we have witnessed. The last 10 years
should have been tailor-made for higher-risk approaches; even after
adjusting for risk, more aggressive strategies should have worked
better. Nevertheless, the newsletters that used them didn't lead
the pack.
</P>
<P>
   The pattern has profound implications. It means that you should
increase exposure to more conservative portfolios of funds that are
intended to produce income or a combination of growth and income.
This recommendation holds regardless which way you think the market
is headed.
</P>
<P>
   Following this tack will lower your overall portfolio's risk,
not a bad thing per se, but something you may not have intended.
You can easily counteract this by increasing the allocation of
money you make to the market through your fund portfolios, but
using conservative strategies rather than aggressive ones.
</P>
<P>
   Say you allocate 50 percent of your money to relatively more
aggressive fund portfolios that equal the market's risk, putting
the rest into cash. To duplicate that overall risk exposure while
seeking a better risk-adjusted return, you can simply allocate 75
percent of your money to the more conservative strategy. If history
is any guide, you will make more money than you would by pursuing
the more aggressive approach.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   Another important pattern emerges from the ranks of the top
performers: Asset allocation is a better bet than market timing for
getting the optimal mix of risk and performance. (By asset
allocation, I mean the division of one's portfolio among the
various asset classes, like stocks, bonds, gold and cash. By market
timing, I mean the attempt to time a single market's gyrations so
as to be invested during rallies and in cash during declines.)
</P>
<P>
   Five of the last decade's top 10 fund newsletter portfolios
follow asset-allocation approaches. The others follow a variety of
strategies, from buy and hold to moving in and out of industry
sectors.
</P>
<P>
   Why is asset allocation a better risk reducer? Consider the
country's best-known market timing newsletter: the Fabian Premium
Investment Resource, edited by Douglas Fabian. That newsletter has
had moderate success with its market timing over the last decade,
reducing by 12 percent the risks otherwise associated with the
stock market itself.
</P>
<P>
   However, it has paid a price in the process. While the Wilshire
5000 returned an annualized 17.6 percent over the 10 years,
Fabian's model portfolio of United States equity funds gained just
13.6 percent a year, on average. After adjusting this return for
its below-market risk, it did not beat the market, which explains
its absence from the table accompanying this article.
</P>
<P>
   Contrast Fabian's portfolio with another that did not use market
timing and instead focused on asset allocation: the so-called
Master Retirement portfolio of the No-Load Fund Investor, edited by
Sheldon Jacobs. Although this portfolio was 40 percent less risky
than Fabian's, it produced almost as much profit: 12.5 percent
annualized. On a risk-adjusted basis, though, Jacob's was good
enough to beat the market.
</P>
<P>
   Which of these two portfolios is more likely to repeat? I
believe that the probabilities favor Jacobs'. After all, Fabian's
portfolio must successfully anticipate the stock market's swings in
order to duplicate its achievement, getting subscribers out of
stocks before extended declines and getting them back in before
rallies. That's no mean feat _ even without considering tax or
expense issues.
</P>
<P>
   But investors who follow the Jacobs portfolio need only to keep
following the asset-allocation strategy. This will automatically
lead to reduced risk so long as the various asset classes do not
move in lock step with one another.
</P>
<P>
   The lesson from this is that successful market timing requires a
lot of fancy footwork. It is impressive that any advisers are
capable of it. Asset allocation, however, requires no fancy steps;
it is the lazy person's path to similar results.
</P>
<P>
   That explains how the top-performer list is dominated by asset
allocaters. It's not that the editors of these letters have higher
IQs; the point is that they don't have to.
</P>
<P>
   In other words, don't fall into the trap of thinking that stocks
are the only game in town. The incredible strength of the bull
market has led many people to think that it is. But by ignoring
bonds, gold and other asset classes, you take away tools that could
help you reduce risk without forfeiting return. Why make investing
any harder than it already is? &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Mark Hulbert is editor of the Hulbert Financial Digest, a
newsletter based in Alexandria, Va. E-mail may be sent to:
strategy(AT)nytimes.com. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
