<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-01-08 20:03 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5455 &Cx1f; tad-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-UGA-RACECASE09-COX     01-08 0899
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-UGA-RACECASE09-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    UGA's old race-based admission policy was unconstitutional,
judge rules
 &HT;    By Bill Rankin and Doug Cumming
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ A federal judge has ruled that a racial dual-track
admission policy at the University of Georgia in 1995 was
unconstitutional and resulted in the illegal rejection of a white
applicant.
</P>
<P>
   The ruling covers only part of a major reverse-discrimination
lawsuit against the Board of Regents. It does not address the
suit's attack on policies that shape enrollment in the University
System's three historically black colleges, nor does it say
anything about UGA's admission policy since 1995, which uses race
as a factor but does not use separate admission standards for
blacks applicants.
</P>
<P>
   Still, the ruling is the first indication of how the U.S.
District Judge B. Avant Edenfield of Savannah frames important
questions about race-conscious admission policies raised in this
case. Edenfield rejected all arguments justifying UGA's previous
admission policy that had lower admission standards for blacks. He
ruled that just because UGA no longer has that policy, it is not
moot, because UGA could revert to it in the future. He cited
Chancellor Stephen Portch's intention ``to continue using race as a
factor in admissions until otherwise directed by a court order.''
</P>
<P>
   A spokeswoman for Portch said because the case is still pending,
the chancellor could not comment. But UGA President Michael Adams
said the ruling, issued Wednesday, reflects a decision on policies
the university abandoned about five years ago. ``We have respect
for the law and the courts and believe that our current policies
are legal and reflect a desire to continue to aggressively recruit
qualified African-American students,'' Adams said.
</P>
<P>
   The current admission policy at UGA, the only public campus in
Georgia that admits to using race as an admissions factor, is to
accept most freshmen applicants strictly on academic record. Last
year, 90 percent were accepted that way, said UGA spokesman Tom
Jackson. The remaining 10 percent were accepted on a combination of
academic factors plus any of 12 characteristics, including race,
being male or being related to a UGA alumnus.
</P>
<P>
   ``This case is far from over, but the judge's order validates
our claim that an unconstitutional race-based admissions policy was
in place at UGA,'' said Atlanta attorney Lee Parks, who represents
the seven white and black plaintiffs in the suit.
</P>
<P>
   Edenfield must now decide how much, if any, damages must be paid
to Kirby Tracy, who filed suit after being denied admission to UGA.
From 1990 to 1995, UGA held black applicants to lower minimums,
including a score of 800 on the SAT and a grade-point average of
2.0. Non-black applicants needed a minimum SAT score of 980 and a
minimum GPA of 2.5 grade-point average.
</P>
<P>
   Tracy had a 3.47 grade point average and scored 830 on the SAT
when he applied to UGA in the fall of 1995. Tracy was prevented
``solely on the basis of his skin color from competing on equal
footing for a spot in UGA's 1995 freshman class,'' the judge said.
</P>
<P>
   Tracy then applied to and was admitted at Georgia College and
State University in Milledgeville, which he attended for two years
before being accepted in 1997 as a transfer student at UGA, where
he remains enrolled.
</P>
<P>
   Edenfield also threw out claims by a white female plaintiff who
was denied admission to UGA in 1996 and sued on reverse
discrimination grounds. He noted the plaintiff did not meet minimum
academic standards and race played no role in UGA's denial of her
application.
</P>
<P>
   Parks expressed confidence that the remaining plaintiffs will
prevail on the rest of the claims. Parks said that for the 1997-98
freshman class, about 30 African-American applicants were granted
admission at UGA almost solely on the basis of their race.
</P>
<P>
   The diversity that race-conscious admission seeks to promote is
also threatened by fierce competition, fueled in recent years by
the fact that the lottery-funded HOPE scholarship covers tuition
for 95 percent of the in-state freshmen. Stiff competition has
dramatically driven up the academic standards for admitted
students, regardless of these nonacademic factors. The percentage
of black enrollment, now down to about 6 percent, has also been
falling in recent years, Jackson said.
</P>
<P>
   The Board of Regents did not try to defend the dual-track
admissions policy, which it had abandoned at the recommendation of
the state attorney general. Instead, it argued that Kirby had no
standing to sue since the policy was no longer in effect and
because Kirby was later admitted. Edenfield rejected those
arguments.
</P>
<P>
   The judge also rejected arguments by the NAACP Legal Defense and
Education Fund, which was allowed to become a party in the lawsuit,
that the 1990-95 admission policy promoted diversity at UGA and was
targeted to remedy the effects of past discrimination in UGA
admissions.
</P>
<P>
   ``However noble this general goal is, a court must scrutinize
the specific policies which seek to achieve diversity,'' Edenfield
wrote. ``Abstractions aimed at marginally increasing diversity
simply cannot carry the day because such benefit is far outweighed
by the stigmatizing, polarizing costs imposed by racial
classifications.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
