<HEADLINE>
TEXAS REVENUE WINDFALL HITS $5.6 BILLION 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By R.G. RATCLIFFE 
c.1998 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   AUSTIN, Texas _ Texas Comptroller Carole Keeton Rylander gave
policy-makers a silver cloud with a dark lining Friday _ a record
state revenue windfall that is smaller than expected.
</P>
<P>
   Rylander said legislators and Gov. George W. Bush will have an
additional $5.6 billion to spend for the two-year budget cycle that
begins Aug. 1. Deputy Comptroller Billy Hamilton said that is the
biggest pot of new money the state has seen since he began working
on revenue estimates in 1976.
</P>
<P>
   But the estimated increase is also $700 million less than what
former Comptroller John Sharp projected last July.
</P>
<P>
   When that revenue drop is combined with about $3.3 billion in
additional spending that will be required to cover such basics as
increased student enrollment, the amount of increased discretionary
money left available to Bush and legislators will be somewhere in
the ballpark of $2 billion.
</P>
<P>
   That left politicians like Bush _ who promised $4.6 billion in
tax cuts and new spending programs during his re-election campaign
last year _ scrambling Friday to figure out ways to pay for their
programs.
</P>
<P>
   ``Less money is available and the only conservative, fiscally
responsible response is for all of us to adjust our budget
proposals accordingly,'' Bush said. ``The reduction in the amount
of money available may require some changes in the specific dollar
amounts of everyone's proposals.''
</P>
<P>
   Bush said he still plans to increase funds for public schools,
give school property taxpayers a major break, and cut consumer
sales taxes and business taxes.
</P>
<P>
   But Bush said he will not be able to say whether he can fulfill
his promise of delivering a $2 billion property tax cut until
shortly before he gives his proposed budget to state lawmakers at
the end of this month.
</P>
<P>
   ``I am committed to significant tax cuts,'' Bush said.
</P>
<P>
   Bush Budget Director Albert Hawkins said some of the governor's
proposals will fit in with the required spending increases. For
instance, he said almost $1.1 billion in new spending for public
school equalization programs can be used in part to trigger local
property tax cuts.
</P>
<P>
   Hawkins said Bush should still be able to come close to
fulfilling his campaign promises in a balanced budget.
</P>
<P>
   Lt. Gov.-elect Rick Perry said the drop in the revenue
projection should act as a cautionary note to legislators as they
draw up the next state budget.
</P>
<P>
   ``The estimate underscores the need for state leaders to set
clear priorities, look for efficiencies in state programs and work
together in a bipartisan, fiscally conservative way,'' Perry said.
</P>
<P>
   Rylander said the record revenue increase has resulted from a
generally strong state economy that is largely tracking the
national economy. She said Texas also has enjoyed economic strength
because the local economy is more tied to trade with Latin America
than with the Far East, which has been suffering an economic
downturn this year.
</P>
<P>
   But she said the major economic indicators that represent gross
state product _ while continuing an upward trend _ are down
slightly from where they were when the July estimate was made.
</P>
<P>
   ``Instead of being at a dizzying pace, we're now at a moderate
pace,'' Rylander said.
</P>
<P>
   Rylander said the July estimate done by Sharp projected that
sales tax revenues for the state would increase 10.3 percent, but
the projection now is for an increase of 5.2 percent.
</P>
<P>
   Rylander estimated that total money available to the state from
all sources, including federal funds, during the next budget cycle
will be $94 billion, up from the current $90.6 billion.
</P>
<P>
   The comptroller said her estimate of increased general revenues
does not include $1.1 billion the state will receive as the first
installment of its $15.3 billion settlement with the tobacco
industry. Key legislators have agreed to urge the Legislature to
spend that money on health and human services.
</P>
<P>
   Rylander said she set aside $471 million of the budget surplus
for a transfer to the state's Economic Stabilization Fund, more
commonly known as the ``rainy day fund.'' She said if legislators
do not take action to spend that money, it will be automatically
transferred into the fund next September.
</P>
<P>
   Once money is in the fund, she said, it would require a
two-thirds vote of each house of the Legislature to spend the
money. At present, there is $60 million in the fund.
</P>
<P>
   ``Just like any Texas family knows, it's not prudent to spend
for today without preparing for tomorrow,'' Rylander said.
</P>
<P>
   ``We celebrate good times and prosperity. That's why I am
pleased to take these steps to make sure today's harvest of plenty
continues well into the future,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   The rainy day fund was set up during the 1980s in a period of
economic downturn. Lawmakers had wanted the fund to grow to cover
shortages without tax increases like the one they were forced to
pass in 1986 when oil prices suddenly dropped dramatically and left
the state with a deficit of more than $1 billion.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
