<HEADLINE>
FOREIGN BRIEFS
</HEADLINE>
  (bl)  
c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   AFRICA
</P>
<P>
   SOUTH AFRICA: AMNESTIES MIGHT CONTINUE
</P>
<P>
   Deputy President Thabo Mbeki suggested that granting amnesties
in cases of political violence during apartheid might continue.
Addressing the African National Congress, Mbeki said, ``We will
have to continue to pay particular attention to the question of
amnesty so that we do not tear the country apart.''
</P>
<P>
   _ Suzanne Daley
</P>
<P>
   MIDDLE EAST
</P>
<P>
   LIBYA: U.N. MISSION ON LOCKERBIE BOMBING
</P>
<P>
   The United Nations announced that Prince Bandar bin Sultan, the
Saudi ambassador to Washington, and Jakes Gerwel, chief of staff to
South African President Nelson Mandela, would go to Libya on
Tuesday to try to persuade Moammar Gadhafi to turn over two Libyans
suspected of bombing the Pan American World Airways jet over
Scotland in 1988. U.N. Secretary-General Kofi Annan was
unsuccessful in a similar mission in December.
</P>
<P>
   _ Barbara Crossette
</P>
<P>
   THE AMERICAS
</P>
<P>
   MEXICO: 2 AMERICANS BANNED
</P>
<P>
   Officials have banned two Americans from returning for two
years, saying they broke the immigration laws when they visited
Zapatista rebel communities in the state of Chiapas. The two, Ana
Jean Brown and Michelle Magnini, were summoned to appear at
immigration offices but instead left Mexico, prompting the ban.
</P>
<P>
   _ Julia Preston
</P>
<P>
   PERU: POLICE OFFICIALS SUSPENDED
</P>
<P>
   Thirty-one senior police officials, including nine colonels,
have been suspended on charges that they falsified their resumes to
obtain promotions. Prosecutors said up to 15 others were being
investigated.
</P>
<P>
   _ Clifford Krauss
</P>
<P>
   CANADA: PLANS FOR NEW TERRITORY
</P>
<P>
   The interim commissioner of Nunavut, Jack Anawak, resigned to
run for the local legislature, which will select a member as
premier of the new territory. Anawak has overseen the formation of
the territory, which will come into being April 1.
</P>
<P>
   _ Anthony DePalma
</P>
<P>
   JAMAICA: COSTS OF DRUG TRAFFICKING
</P>
<P>
   Canadian Foreign Minister Lloyd Axworthy and Jamaican officials
discussed how to lessen the human costs of drug trafficking, a plan
proposed at the Summit of the Americas in Chile. Axworthy arrived
here after a one-day visit to Havana, where he signed a
prisoner-exchange treaty with the Cubans.
</P>
<P>
   _ Anthony DePalma
</P>
