<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-01-08 20:16 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5470 &Cx1f; tad-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-SALTLAKE09-COX     01-08 0953
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SALTLAKE09-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    2 top Olympic officials step down amid bribery charges
 &HT;    By Karen Rosen
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Gaining momentum like an avalanche, charges of Olympic
bribery brought down two top Salt Lake City officials Friday and
continued to undermine the Games.
</P>
<P>
   The scandal, which erupted from the city's winning campaign for
the 2002 Winter Games, began in November with the revelation of
scholarship payments to six relatives of International Olympic
Committee members. Now, it involves cash payments of as much as
$70,000 to voting members.
</P>
<P>
   ``We deplore it,'' Utah governor Mike Leavitt said. ``This
corner of Olympic corruption did not begin in Salt Lake City. But
let it end here.''
</P>
<P>
   At least one sponsor has expressed public disapproval, telephone
company U.S. West, which withheld a $5 million payment until it is
satisfied with answers from the committee. The company had pledged
$50 million for the Games.
</P>
<P>
   The Salt Lake Tribune reported that Salt Lake companies hired at
least three relatives of IOC members during the bid, with the bid
commitee paying most of the the salary of one of them.
</P>
<P>
   Four investigations into the bribery allegations are proceeding.
In additon to an ethics panel convened by the Salt Lake Organizing
Committee, the U.S. Olympic Committee, the U.S. Justice Department
and the IOC are conducting their own probes. The IOC is focusing on
wrongdoing by its own members.
</P>
<P>
   However, the IOC repeated that it has no intentions of moving
the 2002 Winter Games and that it believes they will be a ``total
success.''
</P>
<P>
   Planning for the Games will proceed without Frank Joklik,
president of SLOC and the volunteer chairman of the bid committee,
and Dave Johnson, a senior vice president who was the point man
determining IOC members' likes and dislikes during the bid process.
</P>
<P>
   Joklik, 70, said the actions ``besmirch our reputation break my
heart.'' He denied any knowledge of improper payments but resigned
because ``changes must be made for the Games to proceed.'' Joklik,
a retired copper-company executive, will stay on his
$280,000-a-year job until a replacement is found. SLOC said it is
planning an international search.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is clear that these disturbing actions were taken in an
effort to win friends for the bid,'' Joklik said, but he added that
he didn't believe that bid votes were promised in exchange.
</P>
<P>
   ``A handful of IOC members seem to have seriously abused our
generous impulses and expected _ and received _ more than they
should have been given,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Johnson, 40, was the No. 2 man on the organizing committee who
was responsible for coordinating and managing functional aspects of
the Games. Joklik asked Johnson, a former car salesman, to resign
from his $200,000 a year job.
</P>
<P>
   The organizing committee also will stop paying a $10,000-a-month
consulting fee to Tom Welch, who resigned as SLOC president in 1997
after allegations against him of spouse abuse. Welch was the head
of Salt Lake's Olympic bids for both 1998 and 2002.
</P>
<P>
   Two other senior SLOC employees who were part of Salt Lake's
winning bid _ Kelly Flint, senior vice president of marketing and
legal affairs, and licensing director Rod Hamson _ were placed on
paid leave pending the outcome of the investigations.
</P>
<P>
   A member of the Salt Lake committee, Ken Bullock, called on
Samaranch to resign because bribery apparently occurred ``on his
watch.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Until president Samaranch follows Frank's example, the Olympic
movement will not be able to move forward,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Samaranch has admitted receiving from Salt Lake two expensive
shotguns that exceeded the $150 limit on gifts to IOC members.
</P>
<P>
   But Samaranch, who has claimed that the rule does not apply to
him because he doesn't actually vote on bid cities, said that
refusing the gifts ``would have been a real insult.''
</P>
<P>
   About Friday's resignations, Samaranch said, ``They had to do
it.''
</P>
<P>
   Joklik declined to call the misdeeds ``bribes,'' but he told
reporters that IOC members received cash payments; payments for
housing, travel, and education expenses for their relatives;
expensive gifts and free health care to IOC members and their
families; and assistance in making a Utah land deal that afforded
influential IOC memberJean Jean-Claude Ganga of the Republic of
Congo a $60,000 profit.
</P>
<P>
   Among the 89 voting IOC members in 1995, 18 were from Africa and
12 were from South America, the areas to which payments were made.
Salt Lake received 54 votes to win on the first ballot. Ostersund,
Sweden and Sion, Switzerland _ the 2006 front-runner _ garnered 14
votes apiece and Quebec had 7.
</P>
<P>
   Joklik said that some of the payments might have legitimate
explanations.
</P>
<P>
   The IOC probably will change its voting procedures, which now
involve all of the more than 100 members. Samaranch has forbidden
IOC members from visiting the candidates for the 2006 Winter Games,
which will be awarded later this year.
</P>
<P>
   IOC director general Francois Carrard told Swiss television
Friday that the IOC had heard rumors of corruption for years but
had not been able to get hard proof until now. ``We have to clean
up our act,'' Carrard said.
</P>
<P>
   Samaranch said he would visit Salt Lake City this spring.
</P>
<P>
   ``We all want things to return to normal as soon as possible,''
Samaranch told the Associated Press.
</P>
<P>
   Carrard said Salt Lake's bid was ``of exceptional quality'' and
the city would have won the games on merit anyway.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is absolutely certain that Salt Lake City didn't need to do
this sort of thing to win. The value of the bid was absolutely
incontestable.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
