<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-01-08 20:18 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5473 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-WARSH-COLUMN-$ADV10-B     01-08 1509
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-WARSH-COLUMN-$ADV10-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THE NEXT 25 YEARS 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (For release Sunday, January 10, 1999)   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By DAVID WARSH  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   It has been more than 25 years since, entering upon the vast sea
of discontent that was the 1970s, a group of graduate students at
Yale University set in motion the events that led to the formation
of the Committee on the Status of Women in the Economics Profession
of the American Economic Association _ and so began to infiltrate
one of the last untroubled shores of male dominance.
</P>
<P>
   There had been women in economics in the 1950s and 1960s, but
they were discouraged from entering a field that was thought to be
too difficult for them. They didn't teach ordinarily at research
universities, perform research, or hold down leadership positions
in their professional associations.
</P>
<P>
   Mostly they tended to undergraduate education in women's
colleges, and endured such gibes as the memorable one recorded by
Caroline Shaw Bell: ``An economics department at Wellesley? What do
you do? Teach the girls how to balance their checkbooks?''
</P>
<P>
   Since the early 1970s, the trend has been encouraging. Colleges
and universities _ none more than Wellesley under the leadership of
the now-retired Bell _ have turned out a steady steam of talented
professionals for the business world: MBAs, lawyers, and PhD
economists. During the 1990s in particular, a large new cohort of
women economists ascended to top jobs, especially in Washington.
</P>
<P>
   Alice Rivlin (director of the Office of Management and Budget),
Anne Krueger (World Bank chief economist), Laura D'Andrea Tyson
(chairman of both the Council of Economic Advisers and the National
Economic Council), Janet Yellen (chairman of the Council of
Economic Advisers), Alicia Munnell and Rebecca Blank (Council of
Economic Advisers members), June O'Neill (director of the
Congressional Budget Office), Janet Norwood and Katharine Abraham
(successive commissioners of the Bureau of Labor Statistics), and
Barbara Fraumeni (director of the Bureau of Economic Analysis): all
have served and made headlines during the Clinton administration.
</P>
<P>
   With the exception of Marina Von Neumann Whitman, who served for
a time on the Council of Economic Advisers under Richard Nixon, no
woman before had broken through to the top ranks of Washington
policy advisers. And when the first Caroline Shaw Bell Award to a
high-achieving woman was announced last week in New York, it went
to Alice Rivlin, the first woman to have served as president of the
AEA (in 1986!)
</P>
<P>
   She was too busy overseeing the city government of the District
of Columbia as chairman of its financial control board _ and
serving as vice chairman of the Federal Reserve Board in her day
job _ to accept the plaque.
</P>
<P>
   Progress? There can be no doubt about it. Yet the situation may
not yet be as the arch-conservative Milton Friedman described it
the other day in a comment on the history of the Committee on the
Status of Women: ``The pendulum has probably swung too far so that
men are the ones currently being discriminated against.'' At least
not in the aggregate. The 118 American PhD-granting institutions
boast a total of only 116 female professors, compared with a couple
of thousand men.
</P>
<P>
   The membership list of the Econometric Society is especially
revealing of the problems of the next frontier. Of the 545 fellows
of this elite organization, only 10 are women. None of the women
who gained their fame in Washington are fellows. And only a couple
of the fellows _ Krueger of Stanford and Claudia Goldin of Harvard
_ are even slightly famous.
</P>
<P>
   Krueger and Goldin were recognized by their peers entirely for
their contributions to the formal body of economic knowledge, not
for policy work. The same goes for the other female members of the
Econometric Society _ Beth Allen of the University of Minnesota,
Anne Carter of Brandeis University, Gabrielle Demange of the
University of Paris, Birgit Grodal of the University of Copenhagen,
Rosa Matzkin of Northwestern University, Margaret Meyer of Oxford,
Jennifer Reinganum of Vanderbilt, and Nancy Stokey of the
University of Chicago _
</P>
<P>
   Special attention, therefore, is being paid to the cultivation
of today's brightest young female minds. Economics is a science,
after all. Its theorists, pure and applied, are its most
conspicuous citizens, and economics won't be more equal until more
of its top thinkers (as opposed to do-ers) are women. Here, too,
the numbers are changing, though not quickly. The National Bureau
of Economic Research is considered the cutting edge of applied
research. Among its 582 research associates _ virtually all of them
university professors _ 81 are women, or 14 percent.
</P>
<P>
   And coming up for tenure at the nation's leading universities is
a something new to the profession: a class of divas in their early
30s and late 20s, scholars whose voices can be expected to be among
those dominating the professional chorus in the coming years. A
short alphabetical list of the most prominent includes:
</P>
<P>
   _ Susan Athey of the Massachusetts Institute of Technology. A
Stanford PhD, Athey works on problems in the economics of
organizations: the logic of mentoring, the preconditions for price
collusion among competitors; the allocation of decision-making
authority within firms. The mechanics of timber auctions is a
specialty; so is the culture of risk-averse firms.
</P>
<P>
   _ Judith Chevalier of the University of Chicago's Graduate
School of Business. An MIT PhD, Chevalier studies aspects of the
relationships between corporate finance and product markets. How do
mutual fund managers sort themselves out? Do supermarkets taken
private in leveraged buyouts charge higher prices than other
chains? Why do managers undertake acquisitions? Chevalier last week
won CSWEPS' first Elaine Bennett Research Prize.
</P>
<P>
   _ Dora Costa of MIT. A University of Chicago PhD, Costa has been
working as an economic historian. Her first book, ``The Evolution
of Retirement: an American Economic History 1880-1990,'' won a
prize for outstanding writing on lifelong financial security given
by the huge university professors' pension fund. With her mentor,
Robert Fogel, Costa has been propounding a theory of ``technophysio
evolution,'' which is parallel but quite distinct from genetic
change..
</P>
<P>
   _ Caroline Hoxby of Harvard. An MIT PhD, Hoxby went to Oxford as
a Rhodes scholar out of Harvard College. As an applied theorist she
has been studying education _ vouchers, the competition between
public and private schools, and the effect of teachers' unions on
public education.
</P>
<P>
   _ Chris Shannon of the University of California at Berkeley. A
Stanford PhD, Shannon is a high-brow general equilibrium theorist.
already tenured at the age of 31, she operates in a realm far
removed from economic policy, dealing with the sensitivies of
individual decisions and market equilibria to the institutional
settings in which they occur.
</P>
<P>
   The problem continues to be what those who have studied the
problem know as ``the rule of two.'' That is, only half of all
women who receive PhDs get university teaching jobs. Only half of
these get tenure, and only half of them rise to real distinction.
There are papers to be finished, children to be had, dual-career
decisions with husbands to be reached.
</P>
<P>
   Thus to produce one Beth Allen, Glaudia Goldin, Christina Romer,
Nancy Stokey, or Myrna Wooders _ all figures of well-established
standing in economics in their 40s and 50s _ it ordinarily takes
two highly promising young professors. Or at least it has in the
past.
</P>
<P>
   ``The trouble is that there is no dominant pattern,'' says Susan
Poso, a Western Michigan University professor who helped judge the
Bennett Prize contest. ``Women are going to graduate school a
little later these days. She comes up for tenure in her 30s. Each
one must keep an eye on her biological clock.''
</P>
<P>
   Efforts are continuing to smooth the path of women into
economics. The National Science Foundation, mindful that for many
years economics was thought to be as ``inappropriate'' for women as
mechanical engineering, has several projects underway. The
Committee on the Status of Women has begun its second 25 years with
a series of mentoring workshops designed to put one senior figure
together with five younger women for two days at a time.
</P>
<P>
   Clearly it is the work of several generations _ but the future
is promising. Avinash Dixit of Princeton University notes: ``I
teach a very hard mathematical course in microeconomics to
undergraduates. It used to be thought that women shied away from
the harder subjects....But the composition of the class is 30-40
percent women now, and they do at least as well in the grade
distribution.''
</P>
<P>
   The first 25 years in which women were encouraged to enter
technical economics were good, in other words. The next 25 years
should be better.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (David Warsh writes about economics for The Boston Globe. His
e-mail address is warsh(at)globe.com)
</P>
</TEXT>
