<SLUG> BC-IMPEACH-SCENE-630&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SENATE SEEKS TO MAINTAIN DIGNITY AS TRIAL LOOMS 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Vt., Ala., N.Y., Ga., Ky., Texas)  (See related IMPEACH, IMPEACH-CLINTON, IMPEACH-ASSESS,
IMPEACH-CAUCUS, IMPEACH-CANING) 
(lb) 
 By FRANCIS X. CLINES   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Down the corridors the lawmakers fairly danced,
their mood approaching giddiness, as the Senate rallied on Friday
around its own need for dignity.
</P>
<P>
   Having sought sanctuary from the maddening politics of
impeachment in a hallowed gaslight-era chamber of the Capitol, the
senators emerged three hours later exulting in the rarest of news:
The clash of President Clinton and his House Republican accusers
was far from settled, but at least the nation would be treated to a
moment of bipartisan unanimity _ an armistice day of sorts _ in the
yearlong battering from the president's scandal over truth telling
and sex.
</P>
<P>
   ``The ayes are 100 and the nays are zero,'' the clerk read out
firmly in confirmation of this exceptional day, as if the issue
were the annual Mother's Day resolution and not the momentous trial
procedure for deciding whether Clinton should be banished from the
presidency.
</P>
<P>
   The Senate sat silent at the unanimous result, unanimously
pleased that in their very first impeachment struggle they avoided
a nakedly partisan vote count that would have signaled the nation
that the bitterness of the House impeachment clash was leaching
into the Senate.
</P>
<P>
   ``If we went to the rancor of the House, we'd have totally
failed,'' said Sen. Patrick Leahy of Vermont before the vote. ``I
think most of us, Republicans and Democrats, know the House failed
miserably.''
</P>
<P>
   Yet the agreement was clearly tinged with procrastination, with
the most sensitive issue of calling witnesses to be put off until
the first showdown test of whether there are 67 votes to convict
and remove the president. For all the procrastination, at least it
is dignified procrastination, both sides emphasized.
</P>
<P>
   ``What we are interested in is dignity in the Senate,'' said
Sen. Richard Shelby of Alabama as the senators broke from their
meeting and headed for the vote in a mood of high hope. ``We are
not interested in a pornographic movie,'' he added, delighted that
the Senate's opening image offered no repeat of the House's
ceremonial caravan delivery of boxes of salacious evidence.
</P>
<P>
   Far from indulging an early rereading of the accusatory
``narrative'' of Whitewater independent counsel Kenneth Starr, the
Senate found inspiration in its private morning gathering from a
cautionary allusion to Chaucer's Pardoner's Tale of ruination among
schemers.
</P>
<P>
   Across a corridor milling with senators upbeat in their
fellowship, Charles Schumer of New York gave a cautious read-out to
the agreement but concluded, ``There is a genuine feeling at this
point in time, at least, on each side, that the Senate loses and
the country loses by a partisan donnybrook.'' So the senators
decided to agree not to disagree right now, he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``In other words, the beginning happened,'' he said, trying to
outline the political finesse of the day, in which plans were
firmly set for hearing the opening arguments and motions. ``And
then after that happens, we see what happens,'' the senator added
with a smile and a shrug of hope.
</P>
<P>
   On this day of Senate unanimity, Chief Justice William Rehnquist
was resummoned from the judiciary branch to take up the Senate
trial gavel. As if in checks-and-balances payback, he had to
journey for the second day from a court that once unanimously ruled
that the president's troubles in the Paula Jones sexual misconduct
civil suit could go forward with no great disruption of the
operations of the federal government likely. Now all three branches
find themselves deeply involved in the aftermath of the Jones suit.
</P>
<P>
   With the unanimous vote, the Senate gravely set the calendar and
procedures in place for the trial of the president. Rehnquist was
free to head back across the Capitol grounds to his own court to
await the trial next week.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE _ OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   The House Republican members prosecuting the impeachment were
put on notice to begin addressing the Senate promptly on Thursday.
``A compelling case'' was promised by Rep. Henry Hyde of Illinois,
the chief prosecutor, who took care in a statement to allude to the
unsettled issue in the Senate agreement.
</P>
<P>
   One of the prosecutors, Rep. Bob Barr, R-Ga., had openly
questioned the Senate's impeachment resolve last October. ``How
little interest, how little backbone they have to really take on
tough issues,'' declared Barr of the Senate.
</P>
<P>
   But senators seemed unanimous in the positive pleasure of
letting House, White House and nation know that, on Friday at
least, they had the backbone to go on record against partisanship
in deciding the fate of the president.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Senate itself was on trial,'' explained Sen. Mitch
McConnell of Kentucky. His fellow Republican, Phil Gramm of Texas,
saw the day's meaning as a moment of deliverance from the grueling
past year. ``Democracy is not a zero-sum game,'' he insisted.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
