<DOCNO> NYT19990108.0366 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-01-08 20:21 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5478 &Cx1f; taf-z
u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-IMPEACH-CAUCUS-600&AMP;AD     01-08 1173
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-IMPEACH-CAUCUS-600&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SENATORS HOPE `GHOSTS OF HISTORY' WILL GUIDE THEM 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: W.Va., Conn., Texas, Mass., Kan., N.J., Mich., Va., Miss.)   (See related IMPEACH, IMPEACH-CLINTON, IMPEACH-ASSESS,
IMPEACH-SCENE, IMPEACH-CANING)  
(mk) 
 By KATHARINE Q. SEELYE and LIZETTE ALVAREZ   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Sen. Robert Byrd, D-W.Va., guardian of dignity and
decorum, warned ominously that the Senate was on the verge of
tumbling into a ``black pit of partisan self-indulgence.'' Sen.
Christopher Dodd, D-Conn., recalling the brutal caning of a senator
by a House member, raised the emotional stakes. And then the
unlikely political duo of Sens. Phil Gramm, R-Texas, and Edward
Kennedy, D-Mass., joined the 100 separate egos of the Senate in
what many called the Gramm-Kennedy Miracle, a pragmatic agreement
on how the Senate should proceed, at least for now, with the
impeachment trial of President Clinton.
</P>
<P>
   In an extraordinary session held in secret in the crimson and
gold-swathed amphitheater of the Old Senate Chamber, the nation's
100 senators were stirred by the ghosts of history Friday as they
sought to rise above the food fight over impeachment in which their
House counterparts had engaged.
</P>
<P>
   ``A little bit of providence entered the old chamber, and we
achieved a nonpartisan spirit and accommodation,'' said Sen. Pat
Roberts, R-Kan.
</P>
<P>
   Dodd said, ``We had a chance to allow the spirits of the
Websters, Calhouns and Clays to maybe infect us a bit.''
</P>
<P>
   They met in the ornate room last used as the Senate chamber in
1859, when the nation sat on the brink of a civil war brought on in
large measure by a conflict left unresolved for more than a
generation _ the place where the Missouri Compromise and a series
of famous side steps were sealed. And in that chamber the senators
agreed Friday to preserve bipartisan comity by leaving unresolved
their central conflict of whether witnesses would be allowed to
testify in the impeachment trial of Clinton.
</P>
<P>
   The historical resonance was so vivid, it overshadowed a concern
by some Democrats that they had left open the possibility for
witnesses, something the White House adamantly opposes. ``There was
some disappointment at the quick resolution,'' said Sen. Frank
Lautenberg, D-N.J. ``No witnesses would have been the best for most
of us.''
</P>
<P>
   Others agreed and said Kennedy had moved too fast. ``Some were
surprised he jumped in so quickly to agree with Gramm on that,''
said one Democrat. ``We perhaps gave up a tactical advantage.
Republicans had more to lose than we did. If we had held firm on
witnesses, they would have looked like partisan movers.''
</P>
<P>
   But agreement came when both sides, illuminated by Gramm and
Kennedy, decided they could at least start the process.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was seeing that there was very little difference between the
two positions,'' Kennedy said, recalling the moment. ``The idea
gets us on first base and second base.''
</P>
<P>
   Sen. Spencer Abraham, R-Mich., said there was some concern on
his side too about not definitely providing for witnesses. He said
some Republicans were worried that ``we would be asked to
administer impartial justice without having adequate evidence to
make that decision.''
</P>
<P>
   Both sides agreed Friday to decide by Jan. 26 whether to call
witnesses, but that seemed a fluid goal. ``On the basis of today's
discussion, I find it very difficult to believe that by Jan. 26
there will be agreement'' on whether to call witnesses, said Sen.
Paul Wellstone, D-Minn.
</P>
<P>
   While Wellstone predicted an outbreak of acrimony when the
Senate is forced to resolve the witness issue, he said he was
encouraged by the tone set by Friday's two-and-a-half-hour
discussion.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'd still rather start out with positive atmospherics than
with a straight party vote,'' Wellstone said.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Many senators attributed their accord, however temporary, to a
desire to rise to the dignity imposed by the Old Senate Chamber.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're all, in a minor way, products of history,'' said Sen.
John Warner, R-Va. ``When you stop to think of how many great
decisions that were before this nation were resolved in that
chamber, it definitely had something to do with it.''
</P>
<P>
   The chamber, built in 1819 and home to the Senate for the next
40 years, was the scene of sweeping debates of the 19th Century,
including those over slavery, the Missouri Compromise and states'
rights.
</P>
<P>
   As the size of the republic expanded, so did the size of the
Senate, and in 1859, the Senate moved to its current, more spacious
setting. The Old Senate Chamber was given over to the Supreme
Court, which met there until 1935.
</P>
<P>
   The Old Senate Chamber has been used periodically since then for
ceremonial functions and private discussions that senators want to
hold without the probing eye of the media. The Senate last convened
in the room on April 24, 1997, to discuss the chemical weapons
convention, which was secret for national security reasons.
</P>
<P>
   Sen. Trent Lott, R-Miss., the Republican leader, chose the old
chamber for Friday's meeting for both privacy and decorum. And
leaders of both parties asked Byrd, the foremost expert on Senate
rules, to prepare opening remarks.
</P>
<P>
   Byrd set a tone that many senators credited with uniting them in
the common goal of preserving the dignity of the Senate.
</P>
<P>
   He said, according to a transcript from his office: ``The White
House has sullied itself. The House has fallen into the black pit
of partisan self-indulgence. The Senate is teetering on the brink
of that same black pit.''
</P>
<P>
   He said he believed the Senate ``can restore some order to the
anger which has overtaken this country and the chaos which
threatens this city,'' but added: ``At this moment, we look very
bad. We appear to be dithering and posturing and slowly
disintegrating into the political quicksand.''
</P>
<P>
   Byrd then told the story of the Pardoner's Tale from Chaucer's
Canterbury Tales. It involves three men who find a pot of gold and
in their selfish zeal to grab the gold each for themselves, end up
killing each other.
</P>
<P>
   Dodd recalled some of the more dramatic moments that had taken
place in the old chamber, including the 1856 caning of a senator,
an event that he said signaled the end of an era of comity. He
evoked his awe for the institution, recalling that as a boy, he
watched his father, Sen. Thomas Dodd of Connecticut, sworn into
office. The elder Dodd was censured in 1967 by the Senate for
spending campaign contributions for personal purposes.
</P>
<P>
   Friday's turning point came when Gramm stood and asked his
colleagues if anyone would deny the president the right to call
witnesses. There was silence. He then said the House prosecutors
should not be denied the same right.
</P>
<P>
   Kennedy then jumped in, proposing that the Senate delay for
another day the thorny question of witnesses.
</P>
<P>
   The others yelled out: ``So moved! Here! Here! Seal the deal!''
Several senators pounded their desks.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
