<SLUG> BC-FBN-DOLPHINS-BRONCOS09-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Around the corners: Ends key to both teams
 &HT;    By Len Pasquarelli
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   DENVER _ From the Miami Dolphins' first defensive play of
today's AFC divisional-round matchup here, cornerback Sam Madison
will be in the faces of Rod Smith and Ed McCaffrey. It's only when
Madison can get inside the heads of the Denver Broncos wide
receivers that he will be satisfied.
</P>
<P>
   In just his second season, Madison finished second in the NFL
with eight interceptions and unofficially led the league in verbal
assault. The two, he insists, go hand-in-hand.
</P>
<P>
   ``No malice intended, but I have taken trash-talk to new
heights,'' an unabashed Madison said earlier this week. ``When I
was a kid, my mouth was my equalizer against bigger guys in the
neighborhood. It's just something I've always done. It's not
personal, but it has a purpose. The way I see it, if I can disrupt
a receiver's concentration, get him worried more about my yappin'
than a route he's supposed to be running, I've already won half the
battle.''
</P>
<P>
   Madison and cornerback partner Terrell Buckley comprise a
filibuster duo unmatched in the league. But they might require
megaphones to deliver their sharp-tongued jabs to the Broncos
receivers, who have significant height and weight.
</P>
<P>
   Smith (6 foot, 195 pounds) and McCaffrey (6-5, 215) will attempt
to outmuscle Madison (5-11, 180) and Buckley (5-9, 182). And when
the Broncos run tailback Terrell Davis, the wide receivers
typically provide effective downfield blocking.
</P>
<P>
   When the Dolphins defeated the Broncos 31-21 Dec. 21, they held
Davis to 29 yards on 16 carries. Defensive coordinator George Hill
used some unusual defenses in that game, but mostly the Dolphins
relied on penetration from the line and middle linebacker Zach
Thomas.
</P>
<P>
   Broncos coach Mike Shanahan has been candid about the urgency to
get Davis started quickly today. Against a Miami defense that
arguably ranks as the quickest in the league _ but is playing
without tackle Tim Bowens and end Jason Taylor _ the Broncos want
to set a physical tone.
</P>
<P>
   That plan includes the wideouts being aggressive with the
Dolphins cornerbacks.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have to run to be effective,'' McCaffrey said. ``And to be
effective, Rod and (I) have to block well on the edge. Their
corners want to come up on us and get into our bodies in the
passing game. In the running game, we want to get into them. If we
can toss 'em around some in the running game, those corners will
wear down.''
</P>
<P>
   What the Broncos aren't likely to erode, though, is Madison's
confidence.
</P>
<P>
   ``People who haven't seen me all year,'' Madison said, ``are
going to be saying, `Who is that No. 29 playing for Miami?' And
I'll be only too happy to tell them.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
