<DOCNO> NYT19990108.0369 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-01-08 20:22 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5481 &Cx1f; taf-z
s f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-ABOUT-CARS-FERRARI-AR     01-08 0797
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ABOUT-CARS-FERRARI-ART-$ADV10-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A PERFORMANCE EDGE, AND THERE'S NO CLUTCH 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchase by calling (888) 603-1036 or (888)
346-9867.) 
(FOR RELEASE SUNDAY, JAN. 10) 
(af) 
 By PETER PASSELL   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Selling Ferraris to Americans is no longer just a matter of
flattering the customers and wearing Armani suits really well.
While the current models are knock-down gorgeous, they are also far
more expensive than the Porsches, BMWs and Jaguars that can be
nearly as alluring.
</P>
<P>
   Besides, Ferraris have a reputation for being difficult to drive
and needing service every third time they circle the block.
</P>
<P>
   The latter criticism is simply unfair. Though expensive to
maintain, Ferraris are hardy, well-built cars. And while the most
famous Ferrari of the modern era _ the Testarossa _ was dangerously
overpowered, the road manners of the current lineup have been
greatly improved.
</P>
<P>
   In 1997, Ferrari began offering a Formula One-style transmission
on its entry-level eight-cylinder, 375-horsepower, rear-engine
355s. And it is now available on all three 355 models _ the Spider
convertible, the TS targa top and the B coupe.
</P>
<P>
   Traditionalists may dismiss the new technology as a $9,500
gimmick. But I expect that just about everyone else will be
delighted with this hybrid that combines the best features of
manuals and automatics.
</P>
<P>
   Drivers who crave control _ not to mention maximum acceleration
_ overwhelmingly opt for manual transmissions. The catch, of
course, is that stick shifts require some skill to use well, and
they are a pain to operate in heavy urban traffic.
</P>
<P>
   With the large majority of car buyers preferring automatics,
many manufacturers are making theirs smoother and more versatile.
The current flavor of the month is the Tiptronic-style automatic
transmission, which can be shifted at the touch of a lever or
button. This simulates a manual without the bother of a clutch.
</P>
<P>
   Ferrari first tried its hybrid transmission on race cars in
1989, and competing Formula One teams all subsequently adopted
similar technology. The idea is simple: Electrically driven
hydraulic pumps, controlled by a computer, operate an otherwise
conventional clutch and gearbox. To shift gears, the driver simply
flicks either of two paddles mounted behind the steering wheel.
</P>
<P>
   This eliminates the need to take one hand off the wheel to
change gears, and it reduces the time engine power is denied to the
axle. And the computer eliminates the risk that the driver will
accidentally skip a gear when downshifting, which can destroy an
engine.
</P>
<P>
   What works so well on the track also works on the street.
Steering wheel-mounted paddles run the 355F1 up and down through
all six gears at the driver's discretion. But the transmission is
fail-safe, automatically opting for a lower gear when the engine
speed goes below 1,300 revolutions per minute, or a higher gear
when the engine exceeds the red line at 8,600 rpm. If the clutch
overheats from excessive use, a warning buzzer sounds.
</P>
<P>
   Touch both paddles simultaneously and the engine goes into
neutral. A separate, console-mounted lever shifts gears from
neutral to reverse.
</P>
<P>
   In ``normal'' mode, the computer eases out the clutch slowly to
minimize the jerk. In ``sport'' mode, the clutch engages very
rapidly, reducing the shift time to a quarter-second _ roughly half
what professionals need to change gears manually. Drivers always
have the option of ``automatic'' mode, in which the computer
chooses the shift points as well as operating the clutch.
</P>
<P>
   Drivers who generally use their Ferraris to see and be seen
around town won't get much from the F1 transmission. The throttle
seems oddly leaden from a slow start as the computer engages the
clutch. And while downshifting is improved at any speed _ you
barely feel the gears change _ upshifting comes with a bit of a
thud.
</P>
<P>
   In aggressive driving, though, the new transmission is a
delight. The most pronounced difference is the ease and speed of
shifting under full throttle: no missed gears, no flirting with
damage to the engine at the red line, no-brainer acceleration from
zero to 60 in an astonishing 4.6 seconds.
</P>
<P>
   More important virtues include seamless downshifting at very
high engine speeds, along with the better control that comes with
keeping both hands on the wheel at all times.
</P>
<P>
   Is the F3551 Spider worth $147,615? (Or $144,265 for the TS
version, $137,725 for the B version?) Only your psychiatrist and
your stockbroker can say for sure. What is clear is that the F1
transmission is a major innovation, one that gives Ferrari a real
performance edge in the rarefied world of street-legal supercars. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
