<HEADER>
A5483 &Cx1f; taf-z
s f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-MUTFUND-MANAGE-ART-$A     01-08 1150
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MUTFUND-MANAGE-ART-$ADV10-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WHO FOUND A 4TH-QUARTER FEAST 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Attn: Calif.)   (ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchase by calling (888) 603-1036 or (888)
346-9867.)  
 (FOR RELEASE SUNDAY, JAN. 10)  
 (af)  
 By CAROLE GOULD   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Rebounding from the nasty summer selloff, managers of United
States diversified stock funds breathed a sigh of relief in the
fourth quarter. On average, their funds returned a gratifying 18.8
percent. The strong close pulled their average returns up to 15.1
percent for 1998, though that was still far behind the 24 percent
of 1997.
</P>
<P>
   But the top-performing equity managers whistled an even happier
tune, with quarterly returns of up to 70 percent.
</P>
<P>
   Here, four winners for the quarter look back at what made them
such standouts _ and offer a glance ahead. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``We got a double whammy this year,'' said Douglas S. Foreman,
who manages the $256.6 million Morgan Stanley Dean Witter TCW
Mid-Cap Equity Trust from Los Angeles. The fund returned 49.2
percent in the fourth quarter, landing in third place among United
States diversified stock funds.
</P>
<P>
   ``We had companies that met or beat earnings expectations when
many companies were falling short, so the value of our predictable
growth went up measurably during the year,'' Foreman said. ``Also,
falling interest rates boost stock prices for companies which are
exceeding earnings expectations, because the earnings are worth
more as investment alternatives become less attractive.''
</P>
<P>
   Yahoo, at 6.1 percent of assets, was his biggest hit for the
quarter and for the year, up 584.3 percent in 1998. ``We think the
company is unbelievably well positioned to capitalize on the
Internet, which is a paradigm shift in technology and in the way
people communicate,'' he said. He sees annual earnings gains
topping 50 percent for the next three years.
</P>
<P>
   Another good performer was Best Buy, a consumer electronics
chain, at 3.2 percent of the fund. It rose 231.8 percent. ``New
management has engineered a terrific turnaround,'' Foreman said. He
expects the company to exceed consensus earnings forecasts of $2.25
a share for its fiscal year ending in February 2000, up from $1.98
this year.
</P>
<P>
   Foreman does not expect the economic troubles of Southeast Asia
to end until late 1999. But he does not see further interest-rate
cuts in the United States. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   --- &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   For Jim D. Oelschlager, who manages the $57 million Pin Oak
Aggressive Stock fund, technology is the bellwether sector for his
fund _ and for the nation. Pin Oak returned 44 percent in the
quarter, capturing eighth place among United States diversified
funds.
</P>
<P>
   ``We believe that what's occurring in technology today is
equivalent to the Industrial Revolution in the late 1800s,'' he
said.
</P>
<P>
   So it is not surprising that the 24 stocks in Pin Oak are mostly
technology companies. One of his biggest fourth-quarter winners, up
69.1 percent, was Applied Materials, which makes semiconductor
manufacturing equipment. ``When the Asian contagion started in late
1997, no one thought anybody would build another plant,''
Oelschlager said. That pessimism has faded. He expects earnings
growth of 20 percent to 30 percent a year for the next three to
five years.
</P>
<P>
   He also made money in Cisco Systems, the networking hardware
giant, which rose 50.2 percent in the quarter. ``There's a lot of
questions as to who will be the big Internet winners, but we know
Cisco will, because they're building the infrastructure used by the
Amazon.coms and other Internet companies,'' he said. He expects
earnings to grow more than 30 percent annually over three to five
years.
</P>
<P>
   As for 1999? ``I'm a raging bull,'' he said. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   --- &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The third-quarter turmoil spelled fourth-quarter opportunity for
Frederick R. Kobrick, who runs the $41.4 million Kobrick Capital
fund, formerly Kobrick-Cendant Capital. He found much value in
1998, the fund's first year of operation, as stocks were
periodically beaten down.
</P>
<P>
   The fund, which owns 65 stocks, returned 40.3 percent for the
quarter, placing 13th among United States diversified stock funds.
</P>
<P>
   ``When financials were chewed up in late summer, we bought a lot
of banks and brokerages,'' which accounted for about 20 percent of
the fund at the peak, he said.
</P>
<P>
   Kobrick made money with Chase Manhattan, which he bought in
early October at $40 a share. It finished the year at $71. He likes
the company for its diversified income sources. ``Chase does
banking around the world and is expanding rapidly in Europe as it
embraces the euro,'' Kobrick said. He expects per-share earnings
growth of 30 percent in 1999.
</P>
<P>
   Among his other fourth-quarter winners was the EMC Corp., which
he called the leader in mass data storage.
</P>
<P>
   ``Management is brilliant, and the company is run
conservatively, so they usually beat earnings estimates,'' Kobrick
said. He called EMC ``a great long-term growth company'' and
expects EMC's stock price and sales to double in the next two and a
half years. He sees a 40 percent increase in per-share earnings in
1999.
</P>
<P>
   Kobrick said he was optimistic about 1999. ``Profits will be
better than the consensus thinks,'' he said. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   --- &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Sandra K. Durn, who runs the $265.5 million Nicholas-Applegate
Convertible Income Shares from San Diego, returned 19.9 percent in
the fourth quarter, finishing in first place among taxable bond
funds. She attributes the strong finish to the equity-type analysis
she uses to buy convertible bonds.
</P>
<P>
   ``We own convertibles where the underlying company has strong
fundamentals and a positive outlook, which makes us different from
other convertible managers, who focus more on yield than company
prospects,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   In general, she expects convertible bonds in her portfolio to
give her 80 percent of any upward movement of the common stock, but
50 percent or less of any downward movements. That is what kept her
out of trouble in 1998, she said: ``By focusing on these criteria,
we've missed the big blow-ups in convertibles this year.''
</P>
<P>
   Among her top money makers were convertible preferred shares in
Cox Communications, a cable company. ``They have a growing
subscriber base and are adding new services,'' Ms. Durn said. She
projects a 15 percent annual earnings growth rate over five years.
</P>
<P>
   She also made money with the convertibles of Costco, the
warehouse retailer. The chain has posted what she described as
``very impressive'' sales growth of about 12 percent. ``And they
recently launched a new regional store in Chicago which is doing
very well,'' she added.
</P>
<P>
   In general, Ms. Durn is optimistic. ``We feel that the market
will continue to be strong, at least for the first part of 1999,''
she said. ``Interest rates should stay low, which should prevent a
slump in corporate profits.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
