<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-JETS-MOLEWIS09-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Lewis plays big _ but not too big
 &HT;    By Len Pasquarelli
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ When the two first met in the spring of 1997, New York
Jets linebacker Mo Lewis made a weighty impression on his new
coach. Nearly two years later, and with Lewis 30 pounds leaner than
at that forgettable minicamp, the impression Bill Parcells has now
is that he inherited one of the top linebackers in the NFL.
</P>
<P>
   ``The first time I saw him, I thought, `This can't be the guy
everyone has been telling me about,''' Parcells said. ``He looked
like a walrus. I thought he was a lineman and not a linebacker. He
looked like he had the mumps or something. But now he looks like a
Pro Bowl linebacker.''
</P>
<P>
   Which is exactly what the long-deserving Lewis officially has
become.
</P>
<P>
   For eight seasons, Lewis, who played at J.C. Murphy High in
Atlanta and the University of Georgia, has been one of the NFL's
best-kept secrets. His teammates twice voted him the Jets most
valuable player. Similar recognition, however, eluded Lewis when it
came to the league-wide Pro Bowl and All-Pro balloting. In both
1994 and 1997, Lewis' play was superior to the linebackers in the
Pro Bowl.
</P>
<P>
   That oversight ended last month when Lewis, 29, was chosen as a
starter on the AFC squad for the first time and also was selected
first-team All-Pro.
</P>
<P>
   Ironically, the honors came as Lewis was becoming less
interested in individual trappings and more determined to help the
Jets reach the Super Bowl.
</P>
<P>
   ``There was nothing I could do about the Pro Bowl voting,''
Lewis said. ``But I had control over how this team performed. There
are a lot of of guys who would trade in all their Pro Bowl trips
for one Super Bowl ring. I can buy me and my family a trip to
Hawaii, but I can't buy a championship.''
</P>
<P>
   A victory against Jacksonville Sunday will move Lewis and the
Jets one step closer to a Super Bowl berth.
</P>
<P>
   The surprising New York defense under Bill Belichick features a
distinctly Georgia flavor. End Anthony Pleasant was a backup with
the Falcons in 1997. One tackle, Ernie Logan, is a former Atlanta
draft pick; the other, Jason Ferguson, was a standout at Georgia.
Hard-hitting strong safety Victor Green is a native of Americus.
Dwayne Gordon, a key backup linebacker, played his first two NFL
seasons in Atlanta. Although he has played the strong side during
Parcells' two seasons, Lewis has been a model of versatility since
joining the Jets as a third-round choice in 1991. Early in his
career, he lined up on the weak side. On occasions, when injuries
forced it, he played in the middle. And Lewis also has played end
in nickel situations.
</P>
<P>
   This season was testimony to his all-around abilities. Lewis was
second on the team in tackles (81), led in sacks (seven) and had
two interceptions, nine deflections and a fumble recovery.
</P>
<P>
   ``Unlike a lot of linebackers, he doesn't come off the field,''
linebackers coach Al Groh said. ``The guy is a legitimate
playmaker. Really, he's our 'glue' guy.''
</P>
<P>
   But there were times during the regime of Rich Kotite that Lewis
became a 'goo' guy, letting his weight get into the 270s, looking
sluggish and playing hard only when the spirit moved him. At 258
pounds, he remains one of the NFL's bigger linebackers, but he
carries the weight well. He can run through running backs when they
are in pass protection and run with them when they swing out of the
backfield as receivers.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm a smarter player now, too, in every way,'' said Lewis, who
comes home during the offseason and spends much of his time here
bass fishing.
</P>
<P>
   Groh, while agreeing that Lewis has become more analytical, said
he thinks a bigger reason for Lewis' ascent is his emotional
maturity. Too often in the past, Lewis and Groh said, he would play
out of control and free-lance.
</P>
<P>
   ``The big question Mo had to answer was, 'How can I keep my cool
but still keep the heat up?''' Groh said. ``There were times he
just let his anger override his brain. Now, he'll still get steamed
about something, but it won't boil over and affect his performance.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
