<HEADLINE>
SHORT ITEMS ON PERSONAL BUSINESS  
(FOR RELEASE SUNDAY, JAN. 10)
</HEADLINE>
  (af) 
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   FOR SMALL BUSINESSES, CREDIT CARDS ARE HANDY &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   It is almost a rite of passage for struggling independent film
makers, six months out of school and a week away from bagging
groceries for a living, to finance a movie on a credit card. Well,
perhaps their example has helped inspire a generation of business
owners.
</P>
<P>
   According to a survey of 504 small and midsized businesses by
Arthur Andersen's Enterprise Group and National Small Business
United, a trade group, 47 percent of the owners said they had used
credit cards to finance their businesses in the previous 12 months.
That was up from 34 percent in 1997 and 17.3 percent in 1993.
</P>
<P>
   Credit cards are now the leading financing instrument used by
these businesses, the survey said; commercial loans were second, at
45 percent.
</P>
<P>
   The proportion of owners who used their cards only occasionally
to make ends meet dropped to just 10 percent of respondents,
compared with 24 percent in 1997. Moreover, the number who paid off
card balances each month fell sharply, to 38 percent from nearly 60
percent. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   _ Daniel M. Gold &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ROOM IN THE BOARDROOM &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Got time on your hands? Looking for a part-time job? You could
always follow the example of Newt Gingrich and consider membership
on a corporate board.
</P>
<P>
   You won't find these spots in the want ads, but they're out
there. According to Craig L. Fuller, chairman of global board
services for Korn/Ferry International, the executive recruiting
firm, more than 75 percent of the nation's 500 largest companies
will have at least one board vacancy in the coming year.
</P>
<P>
   A few years ago, a chief executive might have served on four or
five boards. Now, many chiefs are cutting back on board
memberships, usually limiting themselves to their own boards and
one other.
</P>
<P>
   Despite their prestige in the business world, some of these
spots may not be easy to fill. For one thing, Fuller said,
Korn/Ferry's annual directors study showed that the average outside
director spent 159 hours a year on board meetings and preparation.
No wonder that lack of time is the main reason people give for
turning down board positions.
</P>
<P>
   Still, if you join a corporate board, prepare for real work.
``It used to be a private club, but those days are history,''
Fuller said. Many chief executives are looking for candidates with
a knowledge of technology to help companies keep current. Members
from abroad are also sought, Fuller said, because they have
networks of relationships overseas. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   _ Jan M. Rosen &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
