<SLUG> BC-BKC-GATECH-FLAST09-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Jackets making the grade
 &HT;    By Norman Arey
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Counting the opening game of the ACC Tournament,
Georgia Tech will play at least 30 games this season, and with a
10-5 record at midseason, the Yellow Jackets have surprised some
people.
</P>
<P>
   Tech suffered through three ``character builders'' _ a 41-point
embarrassment vs. Kentucky, a 61-42 debacle against Hofstra and a
41-point defeat at Duke _ but it also has shown that it can play.
The Jackets beat a decent West Virginia team, surprised Georgia and
North Carolina in Atlanta and beat Iona, a team that could make it
to the NCAAs.
</P>
<P>
   Bobby Cremins' team also was in position to beat N.C. State, but
lost in the final minute.
</P>
<P>
   After half of the season, here's how the Jackets stand, with
most of their conference schedule in front of them, including
Florida State at home at noon today.
</P>
<P>
   Backcourt: C-minus. Cremins is trying to teach his fifth point
guard in five years. Tony Akins will be an adequate point guard
before it's all over, but he's going through growing pains now.
Akins has 74 turnovers and 76 assists, an unacceptable ratio.
Off-guard Jason Floyd, despite two games of more than 30 points and
three others in the 20s, is the weak link. Floyd has trouble
creating his own shot and disappeared in big games.
</P>
<P>
   Frontcourt: B. In nine games, Indiana transfer Jason Collier
leads Tech in scoring and rebounding, averaging 17.2 points and 6.1
rebounds. Jon Babul grabs 7.5 rebounds a game, is the team's best
defender, takes the charge, goes to the floor for loose balls and
makes the extra effort.
</P>
<P>
   Center: B-plus. Alvin Jones can score _ he had 23 against N.C.
State _ averages 10.6 rebounds a game and is second in the nation
in blocks with 68.
</P>
<P>
   Bench: B. T.J. Vines has given the Jackets a lift, averaging 6.6
points. Darryl LaBarrie, the Florida A&AMP;M transfer, has been a
pleasant surprise, scoring 4.5 and handling the ball.
</P>
<P>
   Other: C. Cremins might be doing one of his better jobs with
this group, which has little experience and no senior leadership.
Injuries have hurt the Jackets. Star Dion Glover is missing the
season with a knee injury. Babul lost four games to an ankle
injury, Akins has a strained ACL, Collier lost 18 pounds because of
a bleeding ulcer and Jones has been hobbled by ankle and knee
problems. This team is not a tough one, either mentally or
physically, but it could get better in both areas.
</P>
<P>
   Overall: B-minus. With a 10-5 record, Tech already has surprised
some critics. If Collier, Jones and Akins continue to improve, and
with the ACC somewhat down this season, Tech could finish in the
middle of the pack.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
