<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Turnovers are Driesell's main concern now
 &HT;    By Earnest Reese
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Georgia State coach Lefty Driesell saw enough in an
86-70 loss to Central Florida in Orlando five days ago to know that
his Panthers will have a tough game at home today against the
Golden Knights.
</P>
<P>
   ``They led us by 23 points in the second half,'' Driesell said.
``They're a talented team that's big and deep. It's going be a
tremendous challenge for us.''
</P>
<P>
   Georgia State avenged a seven-point loss to Florida Atlantic by
knocking off the Owls 87-70 Thursday night and will try to do the
same against the Knights, who have won three straight Trans America
Athletic Conference games.
</P>
<P>
   Brad Traina, a 6-foot-5 senior forward who scored a game-high 25
points in Central Florida's 16-point victory over the Panthers,
scored 33 Thursday night in a 90-79 win over Campbell.
</P>
<P>
   Driesell is concerned about Traina, but not as much as he is
about his team taking care of the ball. Against Florida Atlantic,
the Panthers had 23 turnovers. Point guard Kevin Morris, who scored
a game-high 31 points, had 11 of the turnovers, including 10 in the
first half.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's no question that we've got to do a better job of
limiting our number of turnovers,'' Driesell said.
</P>
<P>
   Florida Atlantic apparently realized that Morris, who played 37
minutes, was the only Panther who would put the ball on the floor.
The Owls constantly tried to trap the 6-foot sophomore.
</P>
<P>
   In the second half, when off-guard Anton Reese returned after
sitting for 14 minutes because of foul trouble, Morris was
effective running the offense and scoring.
</P>
<P>
   In other action, Clark Atlanta (5-6) and struggling AU Center
rival Morris Brown (1-7) play in the first of two regular-season
meetings, at 8 p.m. today in CAU's gym. The women play at 6 p.m.
</P>
<P>
   West Georgia (11-2, 2-0), sitting atop the East Division of the
Gulf South Conference, will battle state rival Valdosta State (5-8,
0-2) on the road at 7:30 p.m. today in the first of their two
regular-season meetings.
</P>
<P>
   On Sunday at the Centerplex in Macon, Fort Valley State's women
and men play rival Albany State, at 3 p.m. and 5 p.m.,
respectively.
</P>
<P>
   SCOUTING REPORT: GA. STATE VS. CENTRAL FLORIDA
</P>
<P>
   When; where: 3:30 p.m. today; GSU's Sports Arena.
</P>
<P>
   Radio: WRAS-FM (88.5 FM).
</P>
<P>
   Coaches: Kirk Speraw is 74-80 in his sixth year at Central
Florida; Lefty Driesell is 22-20 in his second year at Georgia
State, 705-355 overall.
</P>
<P>
   Records: Central Florida 7-6 (3-0); Georgia State 6-8 (1-2).
</P>
<P>
   Series: Central Florida leads 7-3.
</P>
<P>
   Central Florida update: Against Georgia State five days ago,
senior forward Brad Traina was hot, going 8-for-12 from 3-point
range and finishing with 25 points in an 86-70 victory. Traina had
33 points in a 90-79 win at Campbell on Thursday night. The Golden
Knights feature former Georgia Tech post player Bucky Hodge, who
fouled out of Monday night's game against GSU after scoring only
four points and getting three rebounds.
</P>
<P>
   Starting lineups: Central Florida _ guards, D'Quarius Stewart
(6-2, jr.) and Cory Perry (5-11, jr.); forwards, Mario Lovett (6-7,
jr.) and Brad Traina (6-5, sr.); center, Bucky Hodge (6-9, sr.);
Georgia State _ guards, Kevin Morris (6-0 so.), and Anton Reese
(6-3, jr.); forwards, Quincy Gause (6-6, sr.) and Maurice Robertson
(6-5, sr.); center, Markeal King (6-9, jr.).
</P>
<P>
   Injuries: None reported.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
