<HEADER>
A5503 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FBN-NFL-REPORT-TEX     01-08 1565
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-NFL-REPORT-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ROAD-WEARY WILD CARDS HAVE SLIM SUPER BOWL HOPES
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By MIKE FISHER 
c.1998 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   The following is wisdom from The Official NFL Column Of The New
Millennium (yes, I've filed for trademark rights) concerning a
major issue for this second weekend of the NFL playoffs:
</P>
<P>
   Can a wild-card win another Super Bowl?
</P>
<P>
   A nondivision winner capturing the Vince Lombardi Trophy has
only happened three times. The 1969 Chiefs and the 1980 Raiders
made the leap from regular-season also-ran to postseason titlist.
And then, most recent, the Broncos turned the trick last year.
</P>
<P>
   ``How do you do it?'' asks cornerback Ray Crockett, who hopes
his Broncos eliminate wild card Miami, from the postseason today in
a second-round meeting at Mile High Stadium. ``For starters, you
can't be the inferior team.''
</P>
<P>
   But wild-cards face an uphill battle that goes beyond supposed
inferiority. It certainly can be argued now that surviving wild
cards Arizona, Miami and San Francisco are in the same class with
division titlist Dallas, right? And because the 49ers beat the
Falcons and the Jets in the regular season, and because
Jacksonville had its ups and downs, the wild cards might even be on
par with those two regular-season divisional champs.
</P>
<P>
   No, the challenge comes in playing three games rather than the
two appearances required by each of the conferences' top two seeds
in order to get to the Super Bowl. And the challenge comes in
playing predominantly road games.
</P>
<P>
   Two trends to consider:
</P>
<P>
   1) Playing at home isn't the huge factor it once was, but it
remains an important edge. From 1980 to 1989, home teams won 16 of
the 20 AFC/NFC Championship Games. Since 1990, home teams have won
just 10 of 16 AFC/NFC Championship Games.
</P>
<P>
   The four home teams featured this weekend, the Jets, Falcons,
Vikings and especially the Broncos, have created daunting
home-field histories. The Broncos, for instance, have won 24
consecutive home games.
</P>
<P>
   ``You really take the approach,'' says Vikings coach Denny
Green, ``that somebody is breaking into your house trying to take
something that's yours.''
</P>
<P>
   Also notable here: Minnesota won its eight home games by an
average score of 35-12; Denver won its eight home games by an
average score of 35-23.
</P>
<P>
   2) Entering this season, since 1990, when the NFL playoffs were
expanded to 12 teams, a total of 64 clubs played on the first
weekend. Of those teams, only the Broncos won the Super Bowl. And
only one other team, the 1992 Bills, qualified for the Super Bowl.
</P>
<P>
   ``Guys get worn down,'' says 49ers guard Kevin Gogan. ``When I
was with the Cowboys, it was like an annual event to play five
preseason games, then 16 regular-season games, then three
postseason games, counting the Super Bowl. Skipping one game in
there somewhere would've helped, I guarantee you.''
</P>
<P>
   And, it seems, the game most advantageous to skip would be the
first-rounder. Again, start with that total of 64 clubs. Note the
Broncos and Bills, who went to the Super Bowl. That leaves 30 other
first-round winners, and what happened to them?
</P>
<P>
   Well, it's bad news for Arizona, Jacksonville, Miami and San
Francisco, the four clubs with a game already under their belts: 26
of the 30 lost in the second round.
TRIVIAL PURSUIT
Maybe it's parity, maybe it's luck of the draw, or maybe it's just
plain good football. But did you know that never before have teams
with records as great as Minnesota's 15-1, Atlanta's 14-2 and
Denver's 14-2 qualified for the playoffs in one season.
</P>
<P>
   Since the merger, the only comparable seasons were 1973 and
1975, when trios of 12-2 teams made the playoffs.
NUMBERS GAME
1972 _ That, of course, is the season the Miami Dolphins completed
their undefeated season. Don't tell this to Jimmy Johnson, trying
to top legendary predecessor Don Shula in so many ways but today a
two-touchdown underdog at Denver, but guess what else 1972 is?
That's the last time Miami's won a road playoff game.
QUOTABLE
</P>
<P>
   Mike Holmgren on Packers offensive coordinator Sherm Lewis, the
bridesmaid of NFL head coaching candidates: ``I would tell any
owner that he is the most qualified assistant in the league right
now, bar none, to be a head coach.''
CHECK OUT ...
</P>
<P>
   Ex-NFL referee Ben Dreith's pithy comments about the state of
officiating this season. The remarks received big exposure; you
can't suggest some refs aren't able to help old ladies cross the
street, as Dreith does, and go unnoticed. But anti-ref types play
up the comment without asking Dreith the tougher question: Is he
saying that 30 years ago, 20 years ago, 10 years ago, there did not
exist less-than-competent officials? Baloney.
</P>
<P>
   NFC BUZZ
</P>
<P>
   Randall Cunningham's new five-year contract extension would seem
to create a logjam at quarterback for the Vikings. But while coach
Denny Green is keen on the idea of having the quality depth the
combination of Cunningham and Brad Johnson offers, don't be
surprised if, this off-season, Minnesota listens to offers for
either QB if a deal can move the Vikings into the top 10 spots in
the April draft. ... In the last nine months, eight Saints players
have been arrested for various offenses ranging from DUI to assault
to heroin possession. Where is the national outrage? Why isn't Tom
Benson being held accountable? Why aren't the Saints being derided
for failing to fulfill their role-modeling obligations? ... 49ers
at Falcons: Atlanta was having trouble selling tickets to Georgia
Dome games earlier this year, but have now won 10 consecutive games
at home. ... The Vikings can become the first team to ever win 22
games in a season. They were 4-0 in the preseason, 15-1 in the
regular season and will need to go 3-0 in the postseason to do it.
The 1976 Raiders won 21 games. ... Eagles owner Jeffrey Lurie still
doesn't get it. Officially, operations director Tom Modrak's
contract gives him the power to choose the head coach.
Unofficially, Lurie has veto power. Which means officially, Modrak
has no authority to fix anything. ... Looking for an unusual place
for an unusually hot player? Try Minnesota punter Mitch Berger,
good in the first eight games of the year (42.3 yard average),
great in the next eight (47.2 average) and a career-long 67-yard
punt in the regular season's final week against the Oilers. ... If
the playoffs are about playmakers, it's tough to rule out the
49ers. They had two 1,000-yard receivers, a running back with four
touchdowns of 70 yards or more, a quarterback who threw for a
franchise-record 36 touchdowns, a defensive end with 15 sacks, and
a defense that led the NFC in interceptions, featuring four guys
with four apiece. ... ... Every team believes if it keeps it close,
it can win in the end. But the Cardinals have evidence: Their 7-1
record this year in games decided by three points or fewer is an
NFL record. ... Ex-Eagles coach Ray Rhodes' explanation of what
happens when players go down the drain: ``All of the sudden a guy
reverts to how he was coached at Savannah State.''
AFC BUZZ
</P>
<P>
   When Bills owner Ralph Wilson learned his club had renegotiated
a deal with QB Doug Flutie to give him a $500,000 raise, Wilson
threw in another $250,000. Combine that with Flutie's selection to
the Pro Bowl, and no wonder he's feeling loved. ``It means I'm
accepted,'' says Flutie, long notable mostly for his lack of size
and viewed as a keeper despite Buffalo's first-round playoff loss
in Miami. ``I'm no longer a novelty.'' ... Mike Riley is the
Chargers' new coach. Mike who? He's a former USC offensive
coordinator and CFL coach who was 8-14 in two seasons at Oregon
State. ... The Chiefs are apparently committed to quarterback Elvis
Grbac (they aren't negotiating with free-agent-to-be Rich Gannon),
but there are those in Kansas City who still wonder if Grbac is
committed to the program. ... Ray Sherman is out as Steelers'
offensive coordinator. Pittsburgh tight ends coach Mike Mularkey
was a candidate to replace him before this week's hiring of
ex-Chargers coach Kevin Gilbride as the offensive boss. So now,
would Chan Gailey like to be in the market to hire Mularkey, a pal
of his, to help out in Dallas? ... The Jaguars have been in
existence for just four seasons, with a 3-2 playoff record. Their
opponent today, the Jets, have been in existence since 1960, yet
have a playoff record of just 5-6. ... The 8-8 Seahawks haven't had
a winning year since 1990; the Oilers have finished 8-8 for three
straight years. ... How the mighty have fallen: Chiefs pass-rush
great Derrick Thomas had six sacks in Week 1 of this season. Now,
Kansas City finds itself having to fend off rumors of wanting to
trade Thomas or even expose him in the Feb. 9 expansion draft.
Could the Cowboys picture Thomas, a crony of Deion Sanders', in a
Dallas uniform? ... The Dolphins are the only playoff team still
alive without a 1,000-yard rusher. ... If the Jets get ahead today
against Jacksonville, history says they'll stay ahead. Bill
Parcells-coached teams are 48-0 when leading entering the fourth
quarter. ... Miami at Denver: This pits the two active coaches with
the highest winning perentages in the playoffs, Dolphins boss Jimmy
Johnson (8-2, .800) and Broncos boss Mike Shanahan (4-1, .800). ...
The Patriots' proposed site for a new stadium in Hartford is
contaminated with toxic materials. Oops.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
