<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Hawks will have tough mini-camp
 &HT;    By Jack Wilkinson
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ There's much fan fence-mending to do, free agents to
sign and tickets to sell, all in a relative nanosecond. Yet time
will be more critical once Hawks training camp opens, even more
come the abbreviated NBA season. Then what's a coach to do?
</P>
<P>
   Lenny Wilkens vows to get players in shape, not injured, in
training camp, then get off to a quick start in a short season. And
if key players need to rest less and play more, so be it.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm not concerned about the short training camp,'' the Hawks
coach said Friday. ``I'm concerned about the short season.''
</P>
<P>
   Concerned that the Hawks, after what Wilkens vows will be a
typically strenuous _ if barely two-week _ training camp, get off
to a strong start in a 50-game season. ``When you cram 50 games in
a short time, with four games in five nights, the key thing is for
us not to come out of the blocks slow,'' Wilkens said. ``If you do,
you're in trouble. The other thing that worries me is injuries. You
can't have guys come up lame.''
</P>
<P>
   Wilkens, Hawks President Stan Kasten and general manager Pete
Babcock spoke at a news conference Friday, one day after the NBA
lockout ended. All three spoke about reconnecting with
``disaffected'' fans and about the free-agent mad scramble that
should ensue Jan. 18 when teams can begin negotiations and
signings. But Wilkens' concerns will be more practical that day, if
training camp opens then.
</P>
<P>
   ``We won't experiment as much,'' he said. ``You go to regular
training camp, you have 18, 20, 22 guys. You get to look at guys.
We don't have time to do that.''
</P>
<P>
   Not with only four Hawks currently under contract and the rights
to two draft picks. Wilkens said the Hawks could open camp with as
few as those six players, while other teams might start with 12.
But the Hawks will sign more players quickly, and Wilkens expects
two other factors to enhance training camp: his team's veteran
nucleus and his own training-camp regimen.
</P>
<P>
   ``The three or four starters (Steve Smith, Dikembe Mutombo and
Mookie Blaylock) help tremendously,'' Wilkens said. ``They know
what to expect in camp. They'll help us to get going''
</P>
<P>
   It will be ``a tough camp,'' he said. ``I plan to do the same
thing. I just have to be careful we don't get anyone hurt. I told
my staff there's going to be 10 pairs of eyes _ the coaches,
trainers, everyone _ on (players). At the same time, I have to get
them in shape. That'll help us get off to a good start.''
</P>
<P>
   Once the short season begins, Wilkens isn't sure if his regular
substitution patterns will be affected. ``We'll see how it goes,''
he said. ``Because it is a short season, I don't think you have to
care about wearing guys out. You have to watch guys, make sure they
don't get hurt. And you probably won't be worrying about saving
guys for the end of the year.''
</P>
<P>
   Just the facts
</P>
<P>
   The 50-game schedule, set to begin Feb. 5, will be split, Kasten
said, with 25 home games and 25 away. From 42 to 44 of the games
will be against Eastern Conference foes. The NBA might finish the
revamped shedule next week.
</P>
<P>
   Of those 25 home dates, Kasten estimates two-thirds will be
played at the Georgia Dome, with the rest at Georgia Tech. The
Hawks will hold at least one open-to-the-public scrimmage once camp
begins and will play one free exhibition game.
</P>
<P>
   As for reduced ticket prices or new packages or promotions,
Kasten reiterated the NBA's intention to have a bloc of $10 tickets
available for every game. ``But that's nothing new in Atlanta,'' he
said. ``Part of our disadvantage is we're already at the bottom of
the pack in NBA ticket prices.''
</P>
<P>
   On time
</P>
<P>
   As eager as the Hawks are to re-sign some of their free agents
and sign new ones, Kasten stressed that Atlanta won't start that
process prematurely, or illegally.
</P>
<P>
   ``I can promise you that's the way we'll be,'' he said. ``We
always are. I can't say that for everybody.''
</P>
<P>
   Kasten intends to cry foul on any team negotiating early with
free agents, or reaching agreements before the league sets a date _
probably Jan. 18 _ to open talks. ``I won't hesitate to blow the
whistle,'' he said. ``That stuff makes me nuts, and it's unfair.''
</P>
<P>
   He recalled previous free-agent dealings in which other teams
jumped the gun in negotiations. An example was Mutombo, who had
been approached by other teams but who still signed with the Hawks.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
