<SLUG> BC-BKW-WOMEN'S-BASKETBALL-REPORT-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SPLIT HURTS SURVIVING WAC TEAMS MOST
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By MAC ENGEL 
c.1998 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Quick, name the best NCAA Division I 16-team conference last
season. You're right, it's the WAC.
</P>
<P>
   Now name the best Division I 16-team conference going the way of
Ginger Spice. Two-for-two, the WAC again.
</P>
<P>
   This weekend marks the beginning of the end of the WAC's great
salvation of the abandoned Southwest Conference schools and some
Big West conference programs as league play begins for all 16
programs.
</P>
<P>
   ``This split does not benefit us,'' SMU coach Rhonda Rompola
said. ``This eight-team WAC isn't nearly as strong as the 16-team
WAC. And, in all honesty, I don't think there will be an eight-team
WAC beyond next year.''
</P>
<P>
   In June, New Mexico, Utah, Air Force, San Diego State, Wyoming,
Colorado State, Brigham Young and Nevada-Las Vegas will leave to
form the Mountain West Conference based in Colorado Springs, Colo.
That leaves TCU, SMU, Rice, Tulsa, UT-El Paso, San Jose State,
Fresno State and Hawaii in the WAC.
</P>
<P>
   While much of the focus is on finances and football, the breakup
has distinct effects on women's basketball, where the conference
was beginning to make large strides.
</P>
<P>
   ``The last two years, our conference play has truly been helpful
to us and our RPI \RRatings Percentage Index\S for the first
time,'' Utah coach Elaine Elliot said. ``Now we will have to
re-establish that. Next year we'll need two or three other programs
to step up to get us to the level of national recognition where we
are now.''
</P>
<P>
   The RPI is a system that ranks teams by weighing records,
conferences and strength of schedule.
</P>
<P>
   Last season, the WAC had a conference-record five NCAA
Tournament teams _ New Mexico, Hawaii, SMU, Colorado State and Utah
_ plus Rice in the Women's National Invitation Tournament.
</P>
<P>
   The schools forming the MWC have a combined record of 59-38,
with No. 8 Colorado State leading the way with a 16-1 mark. Next
season's WAC is 41-52 with Tulsa and San Jose State's combined
record of 4-21 dragging down what should be a decent conference.
</P>
<P>
   ``In terms of impacting our schedule and our RPI, this isn't
that big of a deal,'' TCU coach Mike Petersen said. ``We had four
or five tournament teams last year; now we'll have two or three.''
</P>
<P>
   What is left for the WAC is Hawaii, SMU and Rice trying to be
the standard bearers on a national level. Those three programs are
the only ones in the top 130 in the RPI among next year's WAC. What
will be the MWC has four teams ranked in the top 100 in the RPI.
</P>
<P>
   ``This new WAC doesn't make sense financially or geographically.
Where is the common link for the schools?'' Rompola asked. ``We
don't even have a league schedule yet.''
</P>
<P>
   As the logistics are worked out, what will be left for most
schools are long trips to the West Coast and a 14-game conference
schedule, as there is now. What won't be there however, is the
quantity of quality teams.
</P>
<P>
   ``This doesn't even hit recruiting really,'' Petersen said. ``We
still have Hawaii, and I don't ever recall selling to a kid that
great Fort Collins-Laramie trip.''
ABL NOMADS
</P>
<P>
   With the collapse of the American Basketall League, most of its
former players are now looking for jobs.
</P>
<P>
   Don't worry, you aren't likely to hear, ``Hi, this is Jennifer
Azzi, would you like to try one of our gorditas today?'' on your
next fast-food run.
</P>
<P>
   Most of the upper-echelon ABL stars such as Azzi, Katie Smith,
Jen Rizzotti and Kara Wolters will likely sign with WNBA teams
shortly.
</P>
<P>
   However, the ABL castoffs are waiting for their release from the
league and its bankruptcy proceedings. If players aren't approached
by the WNBA, most will try to sign with teams in Europe.
</P>
<P>
   ``If I just came out of college, I might be devastated, but I
believe if I just keep working hard, I'll get an opportunity,'' New
England Blizzard forward Dale Hodges told ``The Boston Globe/.
NEW WAC TO HAWAII?
</P>
<P>
   What the WAC really lacks _ other than frequent flyer miles - is
more headaches.
</P>
<P>
   The WAC is seeking a waiver for next season on an NCAA bylaw
that states at least six of its members must be in the same
conference for five academic years to qualify for an automatic NCAA
Tournament berth.
</P>
<P>
   With the makeup of the WAC for next season, five of the eight
schools have not been together that long. If the rule is upheld,
both the men and women will be without an automatic berth until the
2001 tournament.
</P>
<P>
   As an additional kick to a down conference, the new Mountain
West Conference meets those guidelines and will likely have an
automatic berth.
</P>
<P>
   The league also must find a site for its annual basketball
tournament.
</P>
<P>
   Las Vegas is currently the site for the tournament but, with
UNLV jumping to the Mountain West, commissioner Karl Benson needs
another site.
</P>
<P>
   Earlier this week ``The Tulsa World/ reported that the
tournament will be likely be held in Hawaii. The WAC isn't so sure.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are having discussions with the state of Hawaii about a
combo deal for our bowl site and our tournament,'' WAC associate
commissioner Jeff Hurd said. ``But it would be premature to say we
are going anywhere just yet.''
FREE BASKETBALL
</P>
<P>
   On Wednesday, Bowling Green and Ball State hooked up in a
statistician's worst nightmare. The Falcons defeated the Cardinals,
106-105, in four overtimes.
</P>
<P>
   It's the eighth time in NCAA Division I history that a game has
gone to four overtimes.
</P>
<P>
   Bowling Green won despite shooting 29 fewer free throws. Center
Jacki Raterman's 34 points and 12 rebounds overcame that disparity.
She played 58 of the game's 60 minutes.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is just incredible that she could play that well for 58
minutes,'' Falcons coach Deanne Knoblauch said. ``We made some
miraculous plays just to keep the game alive.''
THERE ARE OTHER POLLS
</P>
<P>
   The latest Top 25 NAIA Division I poll features four Texas
teams.
</P>
<P>
   Wayland Baptist is fourth with a 13-2 record; East Texas Baptist
ranks 11th with a 10-1 record; Incarnate Word is 16th with a 12-3
mark; and St. Edward's is 18th at 8-6.
</P>
<P>
   In the latest NCAA Division II poll, Abilene Christian ranks
third in the South Central region. Texas A&AMP;M-Kingsville is eighth
at 8-3.
POSTPONEMENT OF THE WEEK
</P>
<P>
   With the recent snowstorms in the Midwest, several games were
postponed. Not to be outdone, New York Tech's game against American
International on Sunday was postponed due to ... flooding.
</P>
<P>
   Over the weekend 4 inches of rain fell in two hours. NY Tech's
gymnasium is the lowest point on its campus, meaning much of the
excess water drained onto the basketball court.
</P>
<P>
   The game was eventually played at C.W. Post College, where
American International defeated NY Tech, 86-41.
</P>
<P>
   It's not killer bees, but it's more interesting than snow.
SCORE OF THE WEEK
</P>
<P>
   Regis defeated Kansas Wesleyan, 80-41. Wonder if Regis could
defeat Kathy Lee?
GAMES TO WATCH
TODAY
</P>
<P>
   SMU (5-7) at TCU (8-4), 7 p.m.
</P>
<P>
   In the Metroplex nonrivalry, TCU hasn't defeated SMU since 1991,
and SMU has won 15 consecutive in the series.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't care what the records show, I don't want to see it
broken,'' SMU coach Rhonda Rompola said. ``And whenever you play
against \RTCU coach\S Mike Petersen, it's fun. He's entertaining to
watch.''
TOMORROW
</P>
<P>
   No. 2 Tennessee (12-1) at No. 1 Connecticut (13-0), 3 p.m.,
KTVT/Channel 11
</P>
<P>
   UConn ranks first in the nation offense, Tennessee is third;
UConn is first in field-goal percentage, Tennessee is second; the
Huskies are first in scoring margin, the Lady Vols are fourth. What
this game really lacks is hyperbole.
</P>
<P>
   Oregon (11-2, 2-0) at No. 10 UCLA (9-4, 1-0), 2 p.m.
</P>
<P>
   The Ducks' defense is second in the nation, and if they upset
the Bruins, they will have a web-foot up on the wide-open Pac-10.
TUESDAY
</P>
<P>
   Northwestern at No. 3 Purdue, 6:30 p.m.
</P>
<P>
   Someone in the rugged Big Ten will upset the Boilers. Too bad it
won't be the Wildcats.
THURSDAY
</P>
<P>
   Montana at Northern Arizona, 8 p.m.
</P>
<P>
   Unless Cal State-Northridge can upset one of these two teams
away from the Matadome, the Big Sky champions will most likely be
either the Grizzlies or Ladyjacks. /
</P>
