<SLUG> BC-IMPEACH-ASSESS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ANALYSIS: SENATE'S BIPARTISANSHIP WILL FACE SEVERE TESTS 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Mass., Texas., W.Va.)  (See related IMPEACH, IMPEACH-CLINTON, IMPEACH-CAUCUS,
IMPEACH-SCENE, IMPEACH-CANING) 
(JT) 
 By ADAM CLYMER    
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ The Senate achieved bipartisanship _ for now.
</P>
<P>
   Democrats abandoned their diehard opposition to hearing any
witnesses in exchange for a schedule that defers the question until
the Senate may be nearly as tired of the Monica Lewinsky scandal as
is the American public.
</P>
<P>
   Republicans avoided beginning a momentous impeachment proceeding
with a party-line victory that could have left them looking like
the House _ a concept that all senators find intrinsically
demeaning.
</P>
<P>
   The road to a result the country will consider adult, and fair,
still has some rickety passages ahead. Votes pretty much along
party lines can still come on motions by the White House and the
House next week. The unaccustomed tedium of sitting silently for
hours at a time can fray tempers as the trial proceeds.
</P>
<P>
   And in the end, Republicans will cast all, or almost all, of the
votes to convict President Clinton and remove him from office,
while Democrats will cast most of the votes to acquit him and keep
him.
</P>
<P>
   Yet if Friday's decision satisfied the Senate, it almost
certainly displeased the House managers and the White House. Each
of them would have been pleased if the Republicans had used their
majority to jam through, on a 55-45 vote, procedures and schedules
that would have allowed the prosecution to range far beyond the
evidence presented last month in the House and to call witness
after witness.
</P>
<P>
   The House managers would have liked the freedom that would have
given them.
</P>
<P>
   The White House would have preferred no possibility of
witnesses. But if it had to risk Ms. Lewinsky's testimony, it would
have liked to face it after a vote it could portray as the will of
a Republican Party consumed by partisan hatred, not as the result
of a two-party compromise.
</P>
<P>
   But the 100 jurors are not only Democrats and Republicans, they
are senators. Some, in each party, put loyalty to the Senate, its
history and its traditions, much higher than loyalty to party or
president.
</P>
<P>
   For all the time-wasting, disorder and endless quorum calls that
make the Senate seem silly on a television screen, the underlying
fact about the place is that the filibuster rule, and its
requirement of 60 votes to get to a decision, train successful
senators in bipartisanship. They simply cannot get things done
without help from the other party.
</P>
<P>
   One of the two senators who were instrumental in Friday's deal,
Edward M. Kennedy, D-Mass., has built a career on that
understanding, winning victories over three decades on civil
rights, election law, health care, crime and other subjects, in a
series of alliances with key Republicans from Howard Baker to Bob
Dole to Hugh Scott to Strom Thurmond.
</P>
<P>
   Friday's other key player, Phil Gramm, R-Texas, has less history
of working with the other party, although he came to Congress as a
Democrat. But Friday he seized on another dominant Senate strain, a
sense of history.
</P>
<P>
   Gramm spoke near the end of the morning caucus, affected as most
senators were by Robert Byrd's opening speech on the Old Senate
Chamber, where the trial is being held, and the Senate's place in
history. Byrd, D-W.Va., cited Daniel Webster's classic appeal to
national feeling, his March 7, 1850, speech on ``The Constitution
and the Union.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I wish to speak today,'' Webster said in debate over the
extension of slavery to the territories, ``not as a Massachusetts
man, nor as a northern man, but as an American, and a member of the
Senate of the United States ... I speak today for the preservation
of the Union. Hear me for my cause. ''
</P>
<P>
   Gramm said that the Senate had to meet that test again. He
argued that no senator would deny the president a chance to call a
witness, so it was equally unfair to deny the House any chance. And
he reminded senators that under the ``ancient rules of the
Senate,'' they could not avoid votes unles they could reach across
party lines.
</P>
<P>
   Kennedy, who proudly holds Webster's seat, said later that the
room itself, where another Massachusetts senator, Charles Sumner,
was caned by Andrew Butler, a South Carolina representative, over
the issue of slavery, has a powerful impact on ``anyone that
respects history and anyone who holds a senator's seat from
Massachusetts.'' He said he felt that not just President Clinton
but the Senate, too, was on trial, and argued that many of the
differences between the parties' proposed procedures were trivial.
</P>
<P>
   He suggested that the areas of agreement and near-agreement
could get the Senate to first base and second base, and that if
senators sat down to talk, ``we could see later on how we're going
to get to third.''
</P>
<P>
   On most important issues, Gramm and Kennedy vote on opposite
sides. Gramm gets a zero rating from Americans for Democratic
Action; Kennedy gets the same grade from the American Conservative
Union. And they had disagreements as they and their respective
party leaders, Trent Lott and Tom Daschle, worked on the details of
the procedures Friday afternoon.
</P>
<P>
   But in an institution like the Senate, where everyone knows
everyone else, and, as Norman Ornstein, a congressional scholar at
the American Enterprise Institute, said, ``You have to view your
colleagues as people who will be adversaries one day and allies the
next,'' they managed, finally, to agree.
</P>
<P>
   And not just among themselves. In the Senate the rules
ordinarily make it easy for one senator to delay anything. So
almost every action, from ending a quorum call to taking a vote, is
achieved by unanimous consent.
</P>
<P>
   That is why Friday afternoon, before the roll call whose result
he anticipated, Lott spoke as if 100-0 was not quite good enough.
He asked unanimous consent ``that if the resolution is agreed to by
the Senate, it be considered to have the dignity of a unanimous
consent agreement.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
