<HEADLINE>
TEXAS OFFICIALS SEEK ANSWERS TO MYSTERY OF 31 UNEARTHED GRAVES 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By JAMES PINKERTON 
c.1998 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BROWNSVILLE, Texas _ State highway officials are trying to track
down the descendants of 31 people whose graves were unearthed by
workers alongside a busy country road.
</P>
<P>
   The location is near the site of the first battle of the Mexican
War, but a prominent Brownsville historian said the graves are more
likely from one of the many, small private cemeteries maintained on
ranches along the Rio Grande.
</P>
<P>
   The graves were found next to and beneath Alton Gloor Boulevard,
a two-lane country road on the north side of Brownsville, which is
3 miles from the Palo Alto battlefield. Gen. Zachary Taylor, who
marched a federal army into South Texas to establish the Rio Grande
as the international boundary, first engaged defending Mexican
troops at Palo Alto in early 1846.
</P>
<P>
   Behrooz Badiozzamani, the deputy district engineer for the Texas
Department of Transportation, said a project to widen the road to
four lanes has been put on hold until the origin of the graves can
be determined.
</P>
<P>
   ``But our archaeologists, from what they see on the ground, they
don't think they are graves related in any way to the Mexican
American War,'' Badiozzamani said. ``They haven't found any
evidence that would link them to the military _ medals, (uniform)
buttons, or rifles.''
</P>
<P>
   The engineer said the graves were not found by accident, but
located by highway department workers following up on a 1979
department memorandum that reported several apparent graves next to
the roadway. The first graves were found Dec. 18 as highway workers
prepared to bid out the job, Badiozzamani said, and the last seven
were found Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   None of the graves has been excavated, and Badiozzamani said the
agency is searching country deed records and placing advertisements
in local newspapers seeking descendants of those interred along the
roadway. He said the graves were located because the soil above
them had become discolored. Several appear to be smaller graves,
perhaps of children.
</P>
<P>
   Brownsville historian Bruce Aiken, a member of the Texas
Historical Commission, noted those buried in the roadside cemetery
were interred in some type of casket, and U.S. military forces in
1846 did not bring any with them on the campaign.
</P>
<P>
   ``We think it's a ranch cemetery on a ranch called the Lucero,''
Aiken said. ``I think when they (archaeologists) get in there
they're going to find some children, which would definitely rule it
(military cemetery) out.
</P>
<P>
   ``In fact, they found a bottle near one of them (graves) from a
Brownsville bottling company, which would pretty much make it 20th
century.''
</P>
<P>
   Chula Griffin, a Brownsville woman who has researched the area's
old cemeteries, agreed it is probably a small ranch cemetery.
</P>
<P>
   ``God, they're all over the place,'' she said. ``Just the known
ones _ and this one was unknown _ we have over 100 little ranch
cemeteries in Cameron County alone.''
</P>
<P>
   Highway department officials said the remains will be moved to
another location.
</P>
<P>
   Aiken said another unidentified cemetery was recently uncovered
a few miles away on U.S. 281, the so-called Military Highway that
runs next to the Rio Grande where many of the region's first
ranches were established.
</P>
<P>
   ``I guess this is just another mystery,'' Aiken said.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY &QL;
</P>
