<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NY-HILLARY-POLITICS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DEMOCRATS EXCITED BY IDEA OF HILLARY CLINTON IN N.Y. SENATE SEAT 
</HEADLINE>
  (mk) 
 By ADAM NAGOURNEY   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ When Sen. Charles Schumer, D-N.Y., wanted a
compelling figure to campaign with during the final hours of his
Senate race last year, he turned to a Democrat who has never even
lived in New York state: Hillary Rodham Clinton. Mrs. Clinton flew
in for a clamorous reception at a Schumer rally in midtown. After
the votes were counted, Republicans and Democrats agreed that her
four visits here had a lot to do with why Schumer defeated Alfonse
D'Amato by nearly 10 percentage points.
</P>
<P>
   All of which accounts for why an apparently unauthorized
political trial balloon floated by the chairman of the Democratic
Senatorial Campaign Committee on television last weekend _ that
Mrs. Clinton might run for the Senate seat from New York in 2000 in
a bid to replace the retiring Daniel Patrick Moynihan _has stirred
such interest. Polls indicate there is virtually no public figure
who is as popular as the first lady among New York voters these
days, and Mrs. Clinton clearly demonstrated her skill at political
warfare with her relentless attacks on D'Amato through the fall.
</P>
<P>
   ``This woman is just an exceptional human being with a broad
breath of knowledge on national and international politics,'' Rep.
Charles Rangel, D-N.Y., and one of Mrs. Clinton's most enthusiastic
promoters, said Friday. ``I've seen her on the campaign trail and
as a witness in Congress. Her ability to do most anything well is
unbelievable.''
</P>
<P>
   By most accounts, the prospect of Mrs. Clinton seeking the
Senate nomination is, at this point, only the hopeful figment of
the imagination of Democrats contemplating the difficult task of
keeping Moynihan's seat under their party's control. The first
lady's associates say that Mrs. Clinton has shown little interest
in moving to New York and entering partisan politics, and that in
any case, she has other things on her mind these days besides a
Senate race two years away in a state where she has never lived.
</P>
<P>
   It will probably be months before Mrs. Clinton offers a final
word on her political plans. But the excitement stirred by these
whispers is evidence of something else: the underlying weakness of
New York's Democratic Party, notwithstanding the party's strong
showing in November when Democrats won the Senate seat and the
state attorney general and comptroller jobs.
</P>
<P>
   Andrew Cuomo, the secretary of housing and urban development and
son of former Gov. Mario Cuomo, announced Friday that he is
skipping the contest. That, it would seem, has left the Democratic
Party with a weak bench of backup candidates to to replace Moynihan
in a race where the Republican candidate might be New York Mayor
Rudolph Giuliani, an accomplished and well-financed politician.
</P>
<P>
   The Democrat that Moynihan had hoped would run for his seat, H.
Carl McCall, the state comptroller, declined, calling the
fund-raising demands too exhausting.
</P>
<P>
   Cuomo's decision is sure to be interpreted, by some, as
testimony to Giuliani's strength, even though many Democrats were
skeptical of how the younger Cuomo, who has never before run for
public office, might do in a race against someone of Giuliani's
guile and aggressiveness.
</P>
<P>
   As of now, while there are a number of lesser-known public
officials who are thinking about running _ like Rep. Nita Lowey of
Westchester and state Assemblyman Michael Bragman of Syracuse _
there does not appear to be another Schumer out there. Schumer, who
served nine terms in the House of Representatives, quietly devoted
years to raising money and building a case to run for the Senate.
</P>
<P>
   Many Democratic leaders are concerned. When Judith Hope, the
state party chairwoman, said earlier this week that she doubted
Mrs. Clinton was going to run, she was scolded by Democrats,
including Rangel, not to say anything that might discourage the
first lady from running ``if there was the remotest possibility of
her making this race.
</P>
<P>
   ``Obviously, the prospect of the first lady considering a race
for Senate from New York is a very exciting one,'' Ms. Hope said
Friday. ``I know that certain political leaders from New York are
encouraging her to give it serious consideration. I know that six
months ago she suggested to me that such speculation was a
distraction for her at that period in time.''
</P>
<P>
   The Democrats who are looking to Mrs. Clinton to protect the
``Moynihan seat,'' as Ms. Hope called it, are taking solace from
the fact that Mrs. Clinton has declined to rule that out she might
run.
</P>
<P>
   The only requirements to run for the Senate is that a candidate
must be at least 30 years old and a citizen of the United States
for at least nine years, and have a residence in the state where
they intend to run.
</P>
<P>
   ``Clearly, there's a lot of speculation about what she would
do,'' said Marsha Berry, the first lady's press secretary. ``To the
question of elective politics, she says she has no plans.''
</P>
<P>
   Rangel said that Mrs. Clinton, in a conversation the other day,
said nothing to dissuade him from advancing her candidacy. ``The
first lady told me that we should put any discussion of this
subject on hold, until after the president is done with impeachment
proceedings in the Senate,'' Rangel said. ``Me being an optimist, I
consider that very favorable. Yes, I still have my hopes there.''
</P>
<P>
   Still, while such carefully parsed statements are often intended
to signal that a public official is thinking about running, some of
Ms. Clinton's associates say that is not the case here; the first
lady and her friends are simply trying to keep her options open,
for any possibility. This not is not a particularly good time, one
friend said, for Mrs. Clinton to contemplate her own career. She
told one friend that she would be more inclined to think about a
Senate race in 2002 than in 2000, when she expects she will be just
moving out of the White House.
</P>
<P>
   One thing is for certain: The longer she holds herself in
abeyance, the more potential she has to shape the field. And that
is not necessarily a good thing for the Democrats. Contributors are
not likely to begin giving money to some of the lesser-known
possible candidates and other candidates might decide to sit out
the race. And the specter of Mrs. Clinton as an outsized political
figure inevitably reduces the stature of the other Democrats.
</P>
<P>
   As time passes, she is going to come under more pressure to
declare her intentions _ all the more so now, with Cuomo out of the
race. ``I think it would be very exciting if she were a candidate;
she would be a very strong candidate,'' said John Marino, the
former state Democratic chairman who had pressed the younger Cuomo
to enter the race. ``But I would urge that if she were seriously
thinking about doing this, I would encourage her to do it sooner
rather than later.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
