<HEADLINE>
SHORT ITEMS ON PEOPLE AND PERSONALITIES  
 (FOR RELEASE SUNDAY, JAN. 10) 
</HEADLINE>
   (af)  
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   As a holiday tribute to the late restaurateur Joseph Baum was
winding down at Town Hall, the Manhattan theater, David Rockefeller
invited everyone to the Rainbow Room, the nightclub at 30
Rockefeller Center that Baum had run for more than a decade. About
750 people showed up _ but it is probably just as well that
Rockefeller, who still owns 5 percent of Rockefeller Center,
didn't.
</P>
<P>
   As they gazed out on a glittering city from the Rainbow Room's
65th-floor perch, guests like Edward I. Koch, the former mayor;
Hugh Hardy, the architect, and David Liederman, the restaurateur,
bewailed the fact that Baum had been turned out of the Rainbow Room
by Rockefeller Center's owners after a 25-year career at the
complex, operating The Forum of the 12 Caesars, Charlie O's, the
Power Suite, and, finally, the Rainbow Room.
</P>
<P>
   When Baum refused to pay a steep rent hike, the center turned
the space over to the Cipriani family, which plans to convert it
into a catering hall that will be mostly closed to the public.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was a bit creepy that Rockefeller invited everyone to say
goodbye to Joe, when they nearly threw him out of the Rainbow
Room,'' Liederman said. ``Most of us are skeptical that Cipriani
would capture the magic Joe brought to the place.''
</P>
<P>
   Charles V. Bagli &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   --- &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Twelve years ago, David A. Duffield, chairman of Peoplesoft, a
California software maker, ``fell in love'' with a miniature
Schnauzer named Maddie _ and as the result, millions of dogs and
cats can breathe easier today. The memory of Maddie's impish
personality inspired Duffield and his wife, Cheryl, to pledge $200
million in 1997 to the cause of finding homes for stray or
abandoned pets, though word of the donation is just now getting
out.
</P>
<P>
   Duffield, 58, says the couple acquired Maddie after realizing
they couldn't have children. At the time, he was going through a
rough patch in a former career, and their new companion ``became a
refuge,'' he says. He especially remembers her exploring the hills
outside their home, ``getting into the cow patties and burrs,'' and
her fearless assaults on larger dogs. ``I promised her that if we
ever made any money, we'd give it back to her kind,'' he recalled.
</P>
<P>
   He has made plenty: His 51 million Peoplesoft shares are worth
close to $1.22 billion. One-sixth of that will go to the Duffield
Family Foundation, soon to be renamed in honor of Maddie, and be
disbursed to humane societies and animal shelters to find homes for
dogs and cats that might otherwise be put to sleep. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   --- &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   It was only by chance, he says, that he got 10 rows of seats to
himself and his date at the Sony Loews Theater at 67th and
Broadway. Donald Trump likes to think of himself as a man of the
people, and stands in line for tickets and popcorn at his favorite
movie haunt just like everybody else.
</P>
<P>
   But when he popped in during the opening scene of ``Elizabeth''
recently and saw the front rows roped off _ apparently because of a
roof leak _ he took the manager up on an offer to let him and his
companion, Melania Kanauss, plop down in the forbidden zone. ``They
said, `Mr. Trump, if you'd like to sit up there, go ahead,' '' he
said. ``So I had about 200 seats to myself.'' Trump called the
film, about the English queen, ``excellent,'' adding: ``It's a
shame it didn't do better. I've never seen such a glut of bad
movies as I have in the last six months.'' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Abby Ellin &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   --- &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   If he doesn't watch out, Bill Gates could get a second serving.
All that Gerrit Zalm, the Dutch Finance Minister, could think to
say after getting hit in the face with two custard pies on the
Amsterdam Stock Exchange on Monday was: ``This is
incomprehensible.'' One of the two attackers, who were protesting
the introduction of the euro, Europe's new currency, was grabbed by
George Moller, the exchange's president.
</P>
<P>
   The culprits apparently belonged to an offshoot of a movement
run by the Belgian anarchist Noel Godin, who has made a career out
of throwing pies at authority figures _ including Gates, the
Microsoft chief, during a visit to Brussels last February.
</P>
<P>
   According to The Financial Times, Godin has again put Gates at
the top of its list, followed by President Clinton and Tony Blair,
the British prime minister. Given that a Belgian court last week
fined two of Gates' pie throwers a mere 3,000 Belgian francs each _
$86 or, if you wish, 74 euros _ the world's richest man might want
to take his next trip to Asia.
</P>
<P>
   Sarah Lyall
</P>
</TEXT>
