s f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BIZ-DIARY-$ADV10-NYT &LR;      01-08 0539
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BIZ-DIARY-$ADV10-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
IN FRANCE, IT'S ZONE EURO; OUI; EUROLAND, NON  
 (FOR RELEASE SUNDAY, JAN. 10) 
</HEADLINE>
   (af)  
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Everywhere else in the world, ``Euroland'' has caught on as a
brief and handy collective nickname for the 11 countries that are
phasing out their national currencies in favor of the euro.
Everywhere else in Europe, nobody much cares what people call the
single-currency area.
</P>
<P>
   But everywhere else is not France. Besides an easily wounded
pride, France possesses a self-selected body called the Academie
Francaise that defends the French language against neologisms and
coinages that do not meet its standards for euphony, consistency
and, well, Frenchness.
</P>
<P>
   Last week, the academy gave le veto to ``Euroland.''
</P>
<P>
   Nobody says ``Dollarland'' or ``Poundland,'' the academy said.
Besides, spoken with a French accent, that last syllable can come
out sounding like ``lande,'' which in French can connote a barren
wasteland.
</P>
<P>
   The academy said it ``declares therefore that it is the term
`zone euro' which must be employed in France and in French-speaking
countries'' (declared in French, naturally).
</P>
<P>
   Though the academy did not say so, its allergy to ``Euroland''
seems to arise from the term's having originated with American
investment banks. Any expression that imperialist America applies
to something connected with France must be meant as an insult, one
way or another &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   --- &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   With deregulation prompting a flood of new mutual fund offerings
in the Japanese market, fund managers anxious to stand out from the
crowd have abandoned the traditional nomenclature of fund names _
``equity,'' ``growth,'' ``global,'' ``strategic'' and so on _ in
favor of a new trend, naming funds after Italian classical and
Renaissance icons.
</P>
<P>
   Recent months have seen new funds named for Galileo, Marco Polo,
Christopher Columbus, Leonardo da Vinci and even Mona Lisa.
</P>
<P>
   Never mind what's in the fund's portfolio, the thinking goes.
Give it a name that conveys depth, wisdom, prestige, foresight,
searching intelligence. For example, a Goldman, Sachs spokesman in
Tokyo said the firm named its global equity fund Marco Polo to
convey the exploratory feeling of a vehicle that invests in various
instruments around the world.
</P>
<P>
   But what about Mona Lisa? ``Some funds don't have exact meanings
but are meant to set off a noble sort of image,'' the spokesman
said.
</P>
<P>
   Of course, famous long-dead people have another great advantage:
they work cheap. Living celebrities and the estates of the lately
departed usually require payment for use of their names and
likenesses, but Leonardo et al. are in the public domain.
</P>
<P>
   Not every historically named fund invokes a European personage.
The Daiwa Asset Management Co. named an equity fund for Musashi,
the 17th-century Japanese swordsman whose ``Book of Five Rings''
was (in English, naturally) a favorite of Western business
strategists in the 1980s. Keizo Mizude, a spokesman for Daiwa, said
Musashi, a two-sword fencer, lends the fund an air of versatility.
</P>
<P>
   Which of Japan's dead-Italian funds is closest to being the
country's Magellan? So far, it's Galileo, with 300 billion yen
($2.7 billion) in assets. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-01-08-99 2055EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
