<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-EMBASSY-CROWE-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
REPORT CALLS FOR CLOSING OF VULNERABLE EMBASSIES 
</HEADLINE>
  (See also EMBASSY-BOMBS) 
(JT) 
 By PHILIP SHENON    
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Special panels set up by the State Department to
investigate the bombings of two U.S. embassies in Africa called on
the department Friday to consider closing a number of embassies
around the world that are vulnerable to terrorist attack and
replacing them with regional ``super-embassies.''
</P>
<P>
   In a joint report to Secretary of State Madeleine Albright, the
two panels harshly criticized the department for an ``institutional
failure'' to recognize the threats posed by international terrorist
groups and by truck bombs like those that destroyed the embassies
in Nairobi, Kenya, and Dar es Salaam, Tanzania, last August.
</P>
<P>
   It also recommended that the department seek an extra $1.4
billion a year over the next decade to upgrade security at scores
of diplomatic posts _ a figure far higher than any discussed
publicly by the Clinton administration in the past.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is every likelihood that there will be further large
bombs and other kinds of attacks,'' the report said. ``We must face
this fact and do more to provide security or we will continue to
see our people killed, our embassies blown away, and the reputation
of the United States overseas eroded.''
</P>
<P>
   The report, which was prepared by panels led by Adm. William
Crowe, the retired chairman of the joint chiefs of staff and a
former U.S. ambassador to Britain, provided new detail about the
chaos that followed the nearly simultaneous bombings in East
Africa, in which more than 220 people were killed.
</P>
<P>
   One panel investigated the attack in Nairobi, while the other
studied the bombing in Dar es Salaam.
</P>
<P>
   Their joint report noted that the first government jet ferrying
relief supplies from the United States to Nairobi did not arrive
until nearly 40 hours after the bombing _ 15 hours late, because
the first plane broke down _ and that it took almost two days for
the Air Force to arrange the first medical evacuations, in part
because of a ``misunderstanding'' over how long the Air Force crew
needed to rest in Kenya before flying out again.
</P>
<P>
   The report suggested that in Kenya, many employees of the
embassy died because they had never been trained in how to react to
warnings of a terrorist attack.
</P>
<P>
   It noted that after hearing grenades and gunshots fired by the
terrorists, many embassy employees went to the window to watch the
firefight instead of hitting the ground, as they should have known
to do; several were decapitated as a result of the subsequent
explosion of a truck bomb, which sent glass flying into the
embassy.
</P>
<P>
   It also criticized the Kenyan government for having repeatedly
refused an embassy request before the bombing for a special radio
frequency dedicated to embassy security.
</P>
<P>
   Private guards hired by the State Department to protect the
embassy were never trained in how to detect car bombs or how to
raise an alarm if they were found. Even so, the report said, the
guards ``performed valiantly and their courageous refusal to permit
the terrorists access to the embassy's garage prevented an even
greater disaster.''
</P>
<P>
   The report identified ``an institutional failure of the
Department of State and embassies under its direction to recognize
threats posed by transnational terrorism and vehicles bombs.''
</P>
<P>
   At the department, it said, policy-making and operational
officers ``were remiss in not preparing more comprehensive
procedures to guard against massive truck bombs. This combined with
lack of resources for building more security facilities created the
ingredients for a deadly disaster.''
</P>
<P>
   In introducing Crowe at a news conference at the State
Department, Albright did not directly address the report's detailed
criticism of the department, focusing instead on its other finding
that there was a ``collective failure'' by several agencies of
government over decades to provide adequate security to American
embassies.
</P>
<P>
   ``The report suggests that responsibility for this failure must
be shared broadly, including by the Secretary of State, and I
accept that,'' she said. ``It reminds us all that no matter how
much we care, no matter how much we do, we can always do more when
the lives of our people are on the line.''
</P>
<P>
   She suggested that while she supported a much larger budget for
embassy security, the State Department had to be realistic about
how much money it could obtain from Congress, which has repeatedly
sought to cut the its budget.
</P>
<P>
   ``As secretary of state, I have a broader mandate to insure the
effective promotion of U.S. interests and values around the
world,'' she said. ``We will continually have to make difficult and
inherently subjective decisions about how best to use the resources
we have and how to reconcile security imperatives with our need to
do business overseas.''
</P>
<P>
   Senior department officials are expected to resist a central
conclusion of the report, which found that the department should
``consider reducing the size and number of our embassies through
the use of modern technology and by moving, in some cases, to
regional posts in less threatened and vulnerable countries.''
</P>
<P>
   Under such a plan, regional embassies _ ``super-embassies,'' as
they are known within the department _ would take over management
of diplomatic affairs for several countries.
</P>
<P>
   ``Let me be very candid,'' Crowe said. ``That's a tender subject
at the State Department, because it has always been an American
principle that we will fly the flag in as many locations as
possible overseas.''
</P>
<P>
   State Department officials noted that the embassy in Nairobi
served as just such a regional hub. The ambassador to the Sudan and
his staff had moved to Nairobi because the embassy building in
Sudan was thought to be vulnerable to attack.
</P>
<P>
   The department provided new details of the extent of the
deficiencies, revealing Friday that a security review prompted by
the bombings in Africa had found that 88 percent of all U.S.
embassies did not meet architectural standards that require
diplomatic compounds to be set back at least 100 feet from the
street.
</P>
<P>
   David Carpenter, assistant secretary of state for diplomatic
security, said at the news conference with Crowe that the State
Department's headquarters in Washington is among the buildings that
do not meet the 100-foot standard.
</P>
<P>
   The department recently installed heavy concrete barriers around
the building, but he acknowledged that the State Department was
still vulnerable to attack. To increase security further, he said,
the department was considering closing the central public entrance
in Washington, on C Street, N.W.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
