<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GORTON-ROLE-SPI </SLUG>
  
 GORTON CLEBRATES ROLE IN SENATE COMPROMISEx  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By MICHAEL PAULSON  
 c.1999 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Sen. Slade Gorton would have spent Friday
celebrating anyway _ it was his 71st birthday.
</P>
<P>
   But Gorton, R-Wash., was also celebrating what he called ``one
of the most rewarding experiences I've had in the Senate,'' his
central role in developing the bipartisan plan for proceeding with
the impeachment trial of President Clinton.
</P>
<P>
   Gorton was one of four senators who drafted the final compromise
plan approved unanimously by the Senate Friday. Senators from both
parties said it was his month-long effort to hammer out a proposal
with Sen. Joseph Lieberman, D-Conn., that made the deal possible.
</P>
<P>
   ``He and Joe Lieberman, in a bipartisan way, put their heads
together, they started thinking about it, they started coming up
with ideas, and we moved forward and it led to what we have here
before us,'' said Senate Majority Leader Trent Lott, R-Miss.
</P>
<P>
   Lott said he talked to Gorton daily over the past few weeks.
``So I want to thank Slade for being willing to do that and for
enduring praise and criticism that he has had to live with over the
past few days.''
</P>
<P>
   Ultimately, Gorton and Lieberman failed to sell their own plan,
which might have led to an abbreviated trial proceeding, to the
full Senate. It was one of the plan's most vocal critics, Sen. Phil
Gramm, R-Texas, along with Sen. Ted Kennedy, D-Mass., who found a
way to alter the plan to win approval by allowing senators to vote
on each proposal to bring in a witness or discuss new evidence.
</P>
<P>
   But senators said Gorton and Lieberman played a critical role
both in laying the groundwork for a bipartisan plan and in writing
the final agreement. After a closed-door meeting at which Gramm and
Kennedy verbalized the final compromise, Gorton and Lieberman, both
former state attorneys general, joined them in Lott's office to
write the language that was approved.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have enjoyed cussing and discussing him (Gorton) and his
proposals for the last week,'' said assistant majority leader Don
Nickles, R-Okla. ``He has shown great courage and leadership, and
he has worked with all of us ... Republicans and Democrats, to try
to forge a bipartisan resolution to this challenge. And I
compliment him for his legislative skills in doing so.''
</P>
<P>
   Gorton has been working with Lieberman to come up with a plan
for a Senate trial after the House impeached Clinton on perjury and
obstruction of justice charges for his alleged effort to conceal
his affair with White House intern Monica Lewinsky.
</P>
<P>
   ``As a formal plan, it became outmoded fairly quickly, but it
triggered a wide range of conversations among Republicans and among
Democrats and most importantly between members of the two
parties,'' Gorton said. ``All of us are elated that we did not
start out with a partisan vote.''
</P>
<P>
   Gorton said that he wound up at the center of the firestorm
because of his close relationships with Lieberman, which dates back
two decades, and with Lott, for whom Gorton is counselor and
confidant.
</P>
<P>
   ``I feel a great sense of gratification that we started the
procedures that brought members together on both sides of the
political aisle and ended in this result,'' Gorton said. ``My
colleagues are delighted with me, and it's hard to get a better
feeling than that.''
</P>
<P>
   The impeachment issue carries risks for Gorton, who says he
plans to run for re-election to a fourth term in the Senate next
year. Removing Clinton from office _ a step Gorton says he is
inclined to support _ is likely to be unpopular in Washington,
where a plurality of voters supported Clinton in 1992 and 1996. And
his work for a bipartisan handling of the trial is alienating some
conservatives in his own party.
</P>
<P>
   But Gorton said he had no choice but to take a position on
impeachment, and as a lawyer who delights in nitty-gritty legal
debates, he jumped into the fray.
</P>
<P>
   ``I am a United States senator, (and) even if I sat still like
the bump on a log, I'm going to have to vote at some point or
another on it,'' he said. ``But more importantly than that, I'm a
United states Senator under the Constitution of the United States,
and the Constitution calls for these procedures, and to me it is
the inevitable duty that one do the best that one can. ... I think
it's my duty to try to see to it to the best of my ability that the
Senate does do impartial justice.''
</P>
<P>
   Gorton said the Senate trial is a political process, not a
judicial process.
</P>
<P>
   ``I feel a tremendous burden, and I guess part of the reason
that I feel that burden is that this is only the second time this
has ever taken place in our history,'' Gorton said.
</P>
<P>
   ``The nature of the burden is more the importance of the issue
and the weight of the oath (of impartiality) than it is some
abstract conception of history. ... Will it be a part of history?
Yes it will be. But the real burden is doing impartial justice.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
