<SLUG> BC-TV-TOUR-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MIDSEASON OFFERS FROM THE WB AND UPN 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By JOHN LEVESQUE  
 c.1999 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   PASADENA, Calif. _ The Ritz-Carlton Huntington Hotel &AMP; Spa here
is again the setting for TV's ritual re-enactment of ``Crime and
Punishment.''
</P>
<P>
   The crime: An uninspiring fall season. The punishment: Two weeks
in a hotel with producers, stars and network executives who promise
to do better with their midseason replacements.
</P>
<P>
   OK, it beats having to undergo dental surgery. And what better
way to begin than with a tale of two networks going in opposite
directions?
</P>
<P>
   At The WB, smiles are broad and thumbs are up as critical
acclaim and rising viewership make it easy for CEO Jamie Kellner to
repeat something he said four years ago: ``Is there room for six
networks? The answer is no.''
</P>
<P>
   Never mind that there are now seven, if you count Pax TV. At
UPN, where CEO Dean Valentine has watched viewership plummet by
almost half this season, the rebuttal to Kellner was defiant and
predictable: ``UPN will be here way past the time that these
conferences in Pasadena are here.''
</P>
<P>
   UPN is pinning its hopes on an animated version of the comic
strip ``Dilbert'' (premiering Jan. 25), even though another of its
animated entries, ``Home Movies'' (April 26), might be funnier.
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, a glut of prime-time animation projects is the most
noticeable trend this midseason as producers try to divine what it
is that viewers want. More on that in the days to come.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, some early observations from Pasadena:
</P>
<P>
   _ At The WB, where crossing over from TV to feature films is
standard procedure for the network's photogenic young hotties,
people still wonder about the private lives of movie stars. So,
sometime this spring, The WB will give a trial run to _ ta da! _
``Movie Stars,'' a comedy that claims to have an insider's view.
</P>
<P>
   Harry Hamlin (``L.A. Law'') and Jennifer Grant (``Beverly Hills,
90210'') play Reese Hardin and Jacey Wyatt, a Hollywood power
couple whose Malibu property is also home to three kids, Reese's
Juilliard-trained but unemployed brother and Jacey's mother.
</P>
<P>
   Though she had to audition for a part, Grant seems a natural:
She's the daughter of Dyan Cannon and the late Cary Grant. But the
idea of acting scared her at first _ still does _ so she went to
Stanford and planned to become a lawyer.
</P>
<P>
   Realizing she had no passion for the bar, she tried other
avenues after graduation _ cooking at Spago, working for an
advocacy firm _ until a friend suggested she take acting lessons.
Acutely aware of her parents' genes, Grant said: ``I was afraid of
following in their footsteps.'' But after a few classes, she knew
she'd found herself.
</P>
<P>
   ``I finally felt my whole body kind of settle,'' she said, ``and
I thought, `This is what I want to do.' ''
</P>
<P>
   _ Robert Urich, Capt. Jim Kennedy III on UPN's ``Love Boat: The
Next Wave,'' says he's never had the good fortune to be on a
long-running series. Still, his face is one of the most familiar on
TV. His reason: ``I've taken just about everything I've been
offered.''
</P>
<P>
   More seriously, Urich added: ``I guess I have a certain ability
that works on television.''
</P>
<P>
   Urich, who survived a battle with a rare type of cancer, says
his health is excellent, aside from a lack of sleep since the birth
of a daughter eight months ago.
</P>
<P>
   _ It started out as ``Zoe Bean,'' but now it's ``Zoe, Duncan,
Jack &AMP; Jane'' to reflect the ``ensemble'' nature. The WB would love
it if viewers think of it as ``Seinfeld, the Early Years'' or
``Friends, Before They Got Nice Apartments,'' and executives hope
it brings to a half-hour comedy the sensibility that critics have
admired in some of The WB's dramas, specifically, ``Buffy the
Vampire Slayer,'' ``Dawson's Creek'' and ``Felicity.''
</P>
<P>
   Sadly, the ``ZDJ&AMP;J'' ensemble, while purporting to reflect
reality, skews it to fit the common TV network perception of same.
Thus, we have four white teens (real ages: 17, 24, 26 and 26)
living in melting-pot Manhattan where their encounters with people
of color set up the uncomfortable conclusion perpetuated for years
on ``Seinfeld'' and ``Friends,'' that is, that white people are
normal and non-whites aren't.
</P>
<P>
   The WB, already considered the little network that could, would
take a giant leap forward by flouting such a pernicious convention.
</P>
<P>
   _ Heartthrob emeritus Greg Evigan (remember ``B.J. and the
Bear,'' ``My Two Dads''?) is another survivor who always seems to
get work. Evigan returns to the sitcom format in a UPN series
called ``Family Rules,'' in which he plays the single parent _
there's a unique concept _ of four teenage girls.
</P>
<P>
   Though a prime-time series (premiering March 9), ``Family
Rules'' has the juvenile look and feel of Saturday morning fare.
(Think ``Saved by the Bell'' without Screech.) Creator Russell
Marcus, who admits the premise isn't exactly original, is banking
on the different levels of maturity in males and females.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's a study they've done where 40-year-old guys actually
think of themselves as 28 to 32, and 17-year-old girls think of
themselves as 25. So, essentially,'' he said, ``we have a household
run by 27-year-olds.
</P>
<P>
   And people say TV is running out of fresh and funny ideas ...
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
