<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CLINTON-IMPEACH-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SENATORS UNANIMOUSLY APPROVE GUIDELINES IN IMPEACHMENT TRIAL OF
CLINTON 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By GREG McDONALD 
c.1998 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Senators gave their unanimous approval Friday to
guidelines for the impeachment trial of President Clinton following
an extraordinary gathering in the Old Senate Chamber.
</P>
<P>
   After more than two hours of lofty and anxious debate they
struck a complicated deal to begin the case with opening arguments
Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   By a vote of 100-0, the 55 Republicans and 45 Democrats also
agreed to limit the prosecution's opening presentation to the
evidence contained in the public record of the House impeachment
hearings. The House proceedings last month resulted in two articles
of impeachment, charging Clinton with perjury and obstruction of
justice in his alleged cover up of an affair with White House
intern Monica Lewinsky.
</P>
<P>
   The senators, however, put off a crucial decision on whether to
allow the 13-member House prosecution team, made up of Republicans,
to call witnesses and present so-called ``new evidence'' in the
case that has not been made public.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think today we have acted in the very best tradition of the
Senate, and it is an appropriate approach for this historic, very
solemn event,'' said Senate Majority Leader Trent Lott, R-Miss. He
praised his colleagues for coming up with a bipartisan compromise
on rules to govern what is the first impeachment trial of a
president in nearly 131 years.
</P>
<P>
   ``The message to the White House and the whole country is we
have a process that will be expeditious and fair,'' said Senate
Minority Leader Tom Daschle, D-S.D.
</P>
<P>
   The vote on the agreement, which took place with Chief Justice
William Rehnquist presiding over the Senate, also authorized
dispatch of a summons to the White House on Friday night informing
Clinton to ``abide by'' and ``obey'' the trial rules and asking him
to provide any pretrial motions to the Senate by 5 p.m. Monday.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton, traveling in Chicago, was not present when the summons
was hand-delivered by Senate Sergeant-at-Arms James W. Ziglar.
</P>
<P>
   But White House special counsel Greg Craig said Clinton's legal
team planned to mount a ``successful and complete defense'' that
would prove the charges against Clinton ``do not justify or warrant
conviction or removal from office.''
</P>
<P>
   House Judiciary Committee Chairman Henry Hyde, R-Ill., who will
serve as the chief prosecutor in the case, expressed disappointment
that he and his colleagues would not be allowed to call witnesses
or offer new evidence to bolster their initial presentation. But he
said House prosecutors would still make ``a compelling case'' for
convicting Clinton and would likely make a motion as the trial
proceeds ``to call witnesses in support of the evidence.''
</P>
<P>
   The agreement ended days of uncertainty over just what blueprint
would be used to guide the senators through their ``court of
impeachment,'' which will determine whether the 42nd president of
the United States should be removed from office.
</P>
<P>
   The deal was hammered out following an unprecedented closed-door
meeting of all senators in the historic Old Senate Chamber, where
they were reminded in a stirring speech by Sen. Robert Byrd,
D-W.Va., of their grave responsibilities not only as lawmakers but
now as jurors sworn to deliver ``impartial justice.''
</P>
<P>
   Byrd, a 41-year veteran of the Senate, appealed to his
colleagues not to allow partisan bickering to consume the
institution, which he described as hallowed ground. He called on
them to act like historical giants of the Senate _ Daniel Webster
and Henry Clay, to name two _ and consider ``higher things'' in
their deliberations.
</P>
<P>
   ``The White House has sullied itself,'' he said in his remarks,
which were released later by his office. ``The House has fallen
into the black pit of partisan self-indulgence. The Senate is
teetering on the brink of that same black pit.''
</P>
<P>
   Afterward, Sen. Phil Gramm, R-Texas, who joined with Sen. Edward
M. Kennedy, D-Mass., to fashion the bipartisan compromise that was
eventually ratified by unanimous vote, said Byrd ``set the tenor
for what we have achieved.''
</P>
<P>
   Under the Gramm-Kennedy trial plan the impeachment court will
convene Wednesday to hear any motions that the prosecution and
defense teams might offer. Opening arguments would begin the
following day, with the House prosecution team leading off. Both
sides will be given up to 24 hours each to make their case _ spread
out over a number of days.
</P>
<P>
   Once the presentations are over, the senators would then have up
to 16 hours _ again, spread out over a few days if necessary _ to
ask questions through Rehnquist.
</P>
<P>
   When the question phase of the trial ends, the prosecution and
defense teams would be given a chance to offer motions to present
witnesses or evidence not in the public record. But senators also
would be allowed to make motions of their own either to adjourn the
trial or censure the president.
</P>
<P>
   The motions would all be debated at the same time and then voted
on separately. A majority of 51 votes would be required for
approval. If a motion to hear from witnesses succeeds, then a
Senate panel of three Democrats and three Republicans would depose
them. The Senate then would vote again on allowing the appearance
of each witness.
</P>
<P>
   If a motion to adjourn or censure the president succeeds, then
the trial would end without a final vote on the impeachment
charges. If that final vote occurs, it would take a two-thirds vote
of the senators, 67, to either convict or acquit the president of
the charges against him.
</P>
<P>
   If everything goes smoothly, the trial could be wrapped up by
the end of January or early February.
</P>
<P>
   ``We believe that this is a very fair process,'' Gramm told
reporters after he and Kennedy had hammered out the final details.
</P>
<P>
   Before the meeting in the old chamber, which has not been used
for official Senate deliberations in 141 years, the Democrats and
Republicans were floating different plans. The Democrats, joined by
a few Republicans, were against the idea of testimony from
witnesses or evidence that had not been made part of the public
record. They argued that the Republicans had a chance to call
witnesses in the House hearing and chose not to.
</P>
<P>
   ``The House did a poor job,'' said Sen. Patrick Leahy, D-Vt.
``It's like they flunked the high school exam and now they want to
make it up in the Senate.''
</P>
<P>
   Republicans for the most part were willing to concede to Hyde's
demand that he be allowed to present witnesses in his opening
presentation, beginning with Lewinsky.
</P>
<P>
   Gramm, one of the most conservative members of the Senate, and
Kennedy, one of the most liberal, are normally miles apart on
issues. But they were lauded for coming up with the plan that
appeared to satisfy all on the question of witnesses.
</P>
<P>
   ``Stranger things have happened in politics, but the
Kennedy-Gramm alignment is one of the strangest. It was
remarkable,'' said Sen. John McCain, R-Ariz.
</P>
<P>
   McCain said the Gramm-Kennedy deal grew out of the fact that
members were beginning to feel an ``extreme discomfort'' about
``the way this thing was headed.''
</P>
<P>
   ``The prime motivating factor was that we saw that we were not
going to be able to carry out our constitutional responsibilities
unless we carved out some kind of bipartisan agreement,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Still, McCain noted that despite the bipartisan rules, there
would likely be problems as the trial proceeds because ``we are
still feeling our way on this thing.''
</P>
<P>
   ``This is a minefield. Things can blow up the whole process even
starting tomorrow. But the reality is that what we did today I
think was of ... great importance,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
