<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SCHOOL-SUICIDE09-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Girl, 15, killed; boy, 17, critically wounded after suicide pact
school shooting
 &HT;    WITH PHOTO
 &HT;    By Anne Cowles and Ralph Ellis
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   CARROLL COUNTY, Ga. _ A 15-year-old Carroll County girl was
killed and her boyfriend wounded Friday in a high school bathroom
shooting authorities describe as a suicide pact.
</P>
<P>
   Andrea Garrett, 15, was prounced dead at a nearby hospital. Her
boyfriend, 17-year-old Jeff Miller, was airlifted to Crawford Long
Hospital in Atlanta where he was listed in intensive care.
</P>
<P>
   The teen-agers were students at Central High School in
Carrollton, the county seat of Carroll County, 40 miles west of
Atlanta. They were shot in a girl's bathroom during first period
with a .22 caliber pistol that had been taken from a locked gun
safe at the girl's home, according to Carroll County Sheriff Tony
Reeves.
</P>
<P>
   ``For whatever reason, it seemed to be planned,'' Reeves said.
``We do know each of them intended on dying today. It was a suicide
pact.''
</P>
<P>
   Reeves said the shootings are still under investigation, and he
could not confirm whether the teens shot themselves, how the
shootings occurred or who brought the gun on campus. The sheriff
said investigators also are still looking into the possibility of a
suicide note. ``This is where they chose to do this for whatever
reason,'' Reeves said. ``There's nothing anybody could have done to
have stopped this.''
</P>
<P>
   The boy and girl were found by a janitor making a routine stop.
Student Tiffany O'Steen said the victims stayed to themselves.
Recently, Garrett had shown up in class crying, and Miller had made
statements to other students that he might not be around much
longer, said O'Steen, a 17-year-old senior who shared a class with
Garrett and a homeroom with Miller.
</P>
<P>
   ``He was always trying to get attention, so I guess nobody
really thought anything of that. He didn't have (many) friends,''
she said.
</P>
<P>
   Reeves said he didn't know what motivated the couple but
students said the two were under parental pressure to break up.
</P>
<P>
   ``The parents didn't agree on the age difference,'' said Central
Carroll senior Kenon Parham, 17.
</P>
<P>
   Garrett's parents and other relatives in both families said
Friday they did not want to talk to reporters.
</P>
<P>
   Parham, who said he had known Miller for several years, said the
couple started dating last summer.
</P>
<P>
   Garrett was a sophomore, a member of the school band, and made
good grades, he said. Miller, a senior, had the reputation of being
odd, Parham said.
</P>
<P>
   ``He was humorous,'' said Crystal Kelly, 17, a junior. ``He
always made weird noises.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Most people would see him as a weird person,'' Parham said.
``But from what I knew of him, he was one of the smartest people I
know. If he wanted good grades, he could have had them.''
</P>
<P>
   School officials said Miller was not at school Thursday. Friends
said the boy no longer lived at home, but the boy's grandparents
said he had been living with his parents and with friends. The
parents could not be reached for comment.
</P>
<P>
   Reeves, the sheriff, said he had heard that Miller and Garrett
had each given away favorite possessions to friends before the
shooting _ Andrea, a CD collection, and Jeff, his guitar.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've heard those rumors, but we haven't been able to confirm
them yet,'' Reeves said.
</P>
<P>
   Following the morning shootings, two dozen counselors and about
seven school psychologists brought in from across the school system
went to the school to help students and faculty cope with the
tragedy. Almost immediately, parents began picking up their
children.
</P>
<P>
   ``Monday we will attempt to have school as normal, providing
guidance and support as needed,'' Principal Scott Cowart said.
</P>
<P>
   Friday's shootings marked the first time since school started in
the fall that a student had brought a weapon on campus.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
