<SLUG> BC-MARKET-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DOW SOARS 105.56 TO CLOSE AT NEW RECORD: 9,643.32
</HEADLINE>
  (EDS: in references to E(ASTERISK)Trade, replace the word,
including parentheses, with the symbol) 
(bl)  
By JONATHAN FUERBRINGER   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ The stock market took a volatile ride to new highs
Friday, finishing a week marked by an Internet stock frenzy, a
surge in other technology stocks and new economic data that showed
the U.S. economy is refusing, so far, to slow down.
</P>
<P>
   The Dow Jones industrial average, which seesawed all day,
rallied in the late afternoon to gain 105.56 points, or 1.1
percent, closing at a record 9,643.32.
</P>
<P>
   The Standard &AMP; Poor's 500-stock index rose 5.36 points, or 0.4
percent, to 1,275.09. The technology heavy Nasdaq index climbed
18.32 points, or 0.8 percent, to 2,344.41. Both were also records.
</P>
<P>
   While some of the highfliers of the technology sector, including
Microsoft, Dell Computer, IBM and Netscape Communications, slipped
Friday, the overall sector rose, lead by Cisco Systems and its
promise of a new voice and data modem. The broader market was paced
by Alcoa, which accounted for about one-third of the Dow's surge,
after the company announced better than expected earnings, a stock
split and a dividend increase. The S&AMP;P 500's performance was held
back by declines in drug and consumer stocks, including Pfizer, Eli
Lilly, and Coca-Cola.
</P>
<P>
   The Internet frenzy cost some investors a lot of money Friday.
Amazon.com surged 40\, or 25.3 percent, to 199[, and then gave up
almost all its gains, finishing up 1] at 160\. E(ASTERISK)Trade,
was up 10 13/16, or 16.9 percent, to 74~, before giving back all
but 3 9/16 of the day's gain. Still, for the first week of the year
Amazon.com was up 49.7 percent and E(ASTERISK)Trade 44.6 percent.
</P>
<P>
   ``Today was a good indication of why you have to be pretty
careful,'' said Henry Blodget, senior analyst at CBIC Oppenheimer.
``These stocks are incredibly volatile. They have spiked here
massively and if your time horizon is longer than five minutes you
are taking an inordinate amount of risk buying in at this level.''
</P>
<P>
   For some, the technology rally is creating a worrisome two-tier
market. Douglas Cliggott, U.S. equity strategist at J.P. Morgan
Securities, is positive on technology stocks but concerned about
the rest of the market. ``We are getting real close to the levels
of overvaluation we had in July of last year,'' he said. ``While we
are real enthusiastic about tech, we are recommending caution about
the rest of the market.''
</P>
<P>
   He argued that the tech rally, not including the Internet mania,
is powered by several credible forces. One is the improvement in
expected demand for computer products since last August. Another is
the billions of dollars of cash that portfolio managers and retail
investors have on hand to invest. The third is that technology
stocks seem to fit nicely into the two possible economic outlooks
for this year. In one, the economy slows and interest rates fall
but the key technology stocks still produce healthy earnings. In
the other, the economy fools most forecasters and does not slow.
Technology stocks are perfect here also, Cliggott said.
</P>
<P>
   The increase of 378,000 nonfarm payroll jobs in December
reported Friday by the Labor Department supports the idea that the
economy remains stubbornly strong, despite many forecasts of a
slowdown. The job growth was far stronger than the 200,000
consensus forecast.
</P>
<P>
   While the news was welcomed in the stock market, it contributed
to weakness in the bond market, where evidence of economic strength
often hurts prices. The Treasury's 30-year issue lost 21/32, to 99
24/32; its yield, which moves in the opposite direction, rose to
5.27 percent from 5.22 percent _ its highest in nearly two months.
</P>
<P>
   For the week the Dow was up 5 percent. However, for the last
four weeks, the Dow was up 9.3 percent while the S&AMP;P 500 was up 9.3
percent. And the Nasdaq beat both, rising 15.5 percent.
</P>
<P>
   But the real sign of the market's torrid pace _ and why a
breather may be in store _ was the surge since the lows in 1998.
The Nasdaq was up 65.2 percent since its Oct. 8 low, while the Dow
gained 27.9 percent since Aug. 31 and the S&AMP;P 500 advanced 33.2
percent since the same date.
</P>
<P>
   But the story of the week was Amazon.com, Tuesday, it announced
that it still had not made a penny in profit. In fact, losses are
expected to rise to 18 cents a share in the fourth quarter report,
three times the losses a year ago.
</P>
<P>
   That makes no difference, apparently to investors. They are
betting the online book and music seller is going to be a big
winner in the future.
</P>
<P>
   So all they cared about in Tuesday's announcement was the
projection that fourth-quarter sales would jump to $250 million,
well above forecasts of $175 million.
</P>
<P>
   But those who got in last year have nothing but profits. From
the bottom of the technology selloff Oct. 8, the Nasdaq 100 index,
which includes the biggest of the technology heavyweights, has
soared 74.8 percent. But Amazon.com was up 457.8 percent.
</P>
<P>
   ``The frenetic buying of Internet stocks is going to make the
tulip buyers of the 17th century look like value players,'' said
Rick Berry, director of equity research at J.P. Turner &AMP; Co. in
Atlanta. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
