<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GORE-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GORE, IN IOWA, ACCENTUATES THE POSITIVE  
(JT)
</HEADLINE>
   By MICHAEL JANOFSKY    
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   SIOUX CITY, Iowa _ As the Senate debated how to conduct an
impeachment trial, the chamber's nominal president, Vice President
Al Gore, was 1,000 miles away Friday, talking about hogs,
methamphetamines and Social Security.
</P>
<P>
   Continuing an apparent White House strategy to focus on policy
as a way to divert attention from events that could drive President
Clinton from office, Gore spent the day immersed in highly scripted
appearances designed to reflect an administration hard at work. For
all the words he uttered about the trial or its potential
consequences, he might as well have been a million miles away.
</P>
<P>
   ``What I'm hearing is that families here in Iowa, and around the
country, for that matter, are concerned about the issues that
affect their families,'' he said in response to a question about
Iowans' view of the Senate procedures. ``They want to see continued
progress in the country.''
</P>
<P>
   And so, another day of congressional action on the Clinton
scandal passed without Gore publicly expressing much of an opinion,
a tack that serves the dual purpose of promoting the administration
as well as the vice president, who has already begun raising money
for his 2000 presidential campaign.
</P>
<P>
   On Wednesday, he took a symbolic step of distancing himself from
the trial by declining to swear in Chief Justice William Rehnquist,
who will preside over the impeachment trial. The task was passed to
Sen. Strom Thurmond, the South Carolina Republican who, as the
chamber's longest-serving member, is Senate president pro tem.
</P>
<P>
   Despite Gore's reluctance to address the trial issue openly or
participate in its proceedings, his aides said Friday that he
continued to receive daily updates from members of his staff and,
between appearances, from telephone conversations with senators he
regarded as friends.
</P>
<P>
   One aide insisted, however, that Gore had made no effort to
lobby senators as a way of influencing their vote on any issue
relating to the trial, asserting that he would consider that
inappropriate.
</P>
<P>
   Here in Iowa, where caucuses in presidential election years
provide the first test for aspirants, Gore made hearty use of his
status on his first visit as a declared candidate by announcing
several budget items that would benefit state residents and by
serving as host at three community discussions.
</P>
<P>
   In Des Moines, Gore said the Department of Agriculture would pay
hog farmers $50 million to help compensate for falling pork prices
and would spend $80 million to slaughter 1.7 million hogs infected
with the contagious virus pseudo-rabies.
</P>
<P>
   The vice president also told about 300 people listening to a
forum on methamphetamine, a highly addictive illegal drug, that the
government was taking steps to fight its distribution and abuse,
efforts that would include a $1.2 million grant to the Sioux City
Police Department. Iowa has been hit especially hard by the growing
popularity of methamphetamine, which Gen. Barry McCaffrey,
Clinton's chief drug adviser, characterized at the forum as ``the
worst drug that ever hit America.''
</P>
<P>
   In Sioux City, Gore led a forum on Social Security, in which he
echoed the administration's long-held position that the system
should be protected before any taxes are cut. Later, he joined a
round-table discussion with a dozen women, considering issues
related to domestic violence.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
