<DATE_TIME> 1999-01-08 21:06 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5565 &Cx1f; tad-z
u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-IMPEACH09-COX     01-08 1078
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-IMPEACH09-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Bipartisian agenda promised in Clinton trial, but witness
question lingers
 &HT;    By Ken Foskett
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ With the shadow of history upon it, the Senate on
Friday unanimously agreed to a bipartisan framework to conduct the
impeachment trial of President Clinton.
</P>
<P>
   The agreement effectively dodges the most contentious issue
between Republicans and Democrats _ how to handle witnesses _ but
assures that the first and only presidential impeachment trial of
this century will at least begin under a spirit of relative unity
and cooperation.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think it'll be fair to the Senate on both sides of the
aisle, to the House, and to the White House,'' said majority leader
Trent Lott (R-Miss.). ``I think today we have acted in the very
best tradition of the Senate, and it is an appropriate approach for
this historic, very solemn event.''
</P>
<P>
   Under the plan, the trial would begin next Wednesday with
motions by the two sides, followed the next day by opening
presentations. House prosecutors and presidential lawyers would be
given until 5 p.m. EST on Monday to file any pretrial motions.
</P>
<P>
   The plan calls for giving House prosecutors and Clinton's legal
team 24 hours each _ over several days _ to make their
presentations. Senators would then have 16 hours _ again spread
over more than one day _ to ask questions through Rehnquist, who
presides over the trial.
</P>
<P>
   Under the timetable adopted Friday, the House managers or
prosecutors will open their case against Clinton next Thursday and
proceed for three days. Clinton will have three days to present a
defense beginning Jan. 19, to be followed by 16 hours of questions
from senators.
</P>
<P>
   House prosecutors, who have been pressing to call witnesses to
make their case, would have to wait until after the opening
presentations and questions to learn whether senators would permit
any such witnesses.
</P>
<P>
   After the question period, senators would be free to make
motions _ either to adjourn the trial and move to censure or to
call witnesses and produce evidence not in the House record.
</P>
<P>
   In a brief statement to reporters at the White House following
the Senate agreement, special counsel Gregory Craig promised a
``vigorous, successful and complete defense'' on behalf of Clinton.
``We are optimistic that senators, once they see and hear this
defense ... will conclude the articles do not justify or warrant
conviction or removal from office,'' Craig said.
</P>
<P>
   Friday's sudden agreement on how to proceed with the trial,
which on Thursday had seemed a distant reality, was produced in a
closed meeting of senators in the Senate's old Senate chamber
Friday morning.
</P>
<P>
   Senators met for more than two hours in the chamber that
produced the Missouri Compromise of 1820 and the Senate's most
violent internecine attack. In 1856, an angry South Carolina
congressman named Preston Brooks caned Sen. Charles Sumner of
Massachusetts in the chamber.
</P>
<P>
   Senators on both sides of the aisle delivered impassioned
speeches on the need for the Senate to work together, rise above
partisan conflict and put the interests of the country first. They
quoted Alexander Hamilton, Benjamin Franklin and even Chaucer.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was statecraft at its best,'' said Sen. Max Cleland
(D-Ga.). ``It was an auspicious moment.''
</P>
<P>
   In addition to what is spelled out in the agreement, there
appeared to be broad consensus that none of the testimony heard on
the Senate floor, even from the official impeachment record,
include graphic details of Clinton's sexual relationship with
Monica Lewinsky.
</P>
<P>
   While consideration of witnesses will not now come until at
least two weeks into the trial, under the Senate framework, the
agreement does erect several hurdles. The Senate will effectively
have to vote twice on whether to allow a witness to testify, first
to subpoena a witness and have he or she deposed and then again to
actually permit that person to testify on the Senate floor.
</P>
<P>
   In another potential break for Clinton, the agreement also
requires Senate approval for House prosecutors to introduce
evidence outside the public impeachment record. This means, for
example, that the managers cannot introduce evidence about other
``Jane Does'' who claim to have had sexual encounters with the
president in their opening presentations.
</P>
<P>
   House Judiciary Chairman Henry Hyde (R-Ill.) said the House
managers would use the three days allotted to them to ``present a
compelling case on the serious charges pending against the
president.'' Hyde reiterated the House managers' intention to call
witnesses, with Senate agreement.
</P>
<P>
   Rep. Bob Barr (R-Ga.), another House manager, was not pleased
with the agreement. ``We don't have a choice,'' he said about the
deal. ``It seems to me that it's highly inappropriate. I think the
Senate ought to rely on our judgment. We ought to be free to call
who we want.''
</P>
<P>
   Even as they congratulated themselves on their work, leaders in
both parties acknowledged that spirit of bipartisanship created
Friday could fall apart further down the road.
</P>
<P>
   ``Nothing, nothing ever can replace members of this body being
alone with each other and talking to each other,'' said Sen. Chris
Dodd (D-Conn). ``This made a difference. Whether or not it is a
sustainable difference only time will tell.''
</P>
<P>
   Democrats and Republicans also continued to disagree over
whether the Senate would ever hear from live witnesses. Sen. Jim
Inhofe (R-Okla.), one of the Senate's most conservative members,
said he personally reviewed the proposed agreement with House
managers specifically to insure that the option of calling
witnesses was safeguarded.
</P>
<P>
   Inhofe said both he and the House managers were satisfied they
could call witnesses. ``You can't have a trial without witnesses,''
Inhofe said.
</P>
<P>
   Democrats acknowledged that they may not have the votes to
prevent witnesses, but they argued that by the time the Senate
reaches the point when witnesses may be called they trial may
already be over.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're going to have 60,000 pages of evidence entered to the
record. The House will present its side. The White House will
present its side,'' said Sen. Patrick Leahy (D-Vt.). ``(Senators)
are going to see, No. 1, you don't need witnesses and, No. 2 ,
what's the point?''
</P>
<P>
   Washington Bureau reporter Rebecca Carr contributed to this
article.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
