A5576 &Cx1f; tta-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-NY-READING-TEST-NYT &LR;      01-08 1226
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NY-READING-TEST-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NEW YORK'S 4TH GRADERS PREPARE TO TAKE `THE TEST' 
 (DW)
</HEADLINE>
   By RANDAL C. ARCHIBOLD  
 
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Linda LoPresti paid a price for her anxiety: $120.
</P>
<P>
   The anxiety came from New York State's new fourth-grade English
exam, known in elementary schools simply as The Test, which is to
be given for the first time next week. The money went to hire a
tutor for her daughter, Lindsay Rose, who like 300,000 peers will
take a three-day exam that even state officials predict many
students will not pass.
</P>
<P>
   ``This test is an unknown quantity, and I wanted her to have a
leg up,'' said Ms. LoPresti, a studio musician whose daughter
attends the Manhattan School for Children, a highly regarded
alternative public school.
</P>
<P>
   Unlike other standardized tests, this one, aside from
traditional multiple-choice questions, requires students to take
notes on passages and write critiques and essays based on what they
heard. Spelling, grammar and punctuation all count.
</P>
<P>
   Fourth grade hasn't been the same.
</P>
<P>
   New York City Schools Chancellor Rudy Crew plans to visit two
schools on Monday to hear concerns about the exam, which will be
given over nearly three hours in the city on Tuesday, Wednesday and
Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   Anxiety of some parents and students is largely misplaced: the
schools, teachers and principals have a lot at stake, because they
will be judged by Crew and the State Education Department on the
basis of how students do on the tests. The test results will not
have a direct impact on any student's standing, on promotion into
fifth grade or anything else, other than, in some cases, getting
into a middle school of a student's choice. Crew has proposed using
the test as a key factor in determining whether students move into
the next grade, but that would not take effect until next year.
</P>
<P>
   Adding to anxiety in some school districts was the late delivery
of the exam because severe snowstorms in the Middle West, where the
printing plants are located, hampered delivery.
</P>
<P>
   Most schools have devoted extra class time to preparing for the
test, some held classes over the winter break and after school, and
a few scheduled tutorials for Saturday. At least one test
preparation publishing company, Princeton Review, expects to have a
study guide in stores next fall. Some parents have put their trust
in private tutors.
</P>
<P>
   Sylvan Learning Centers, a for-profit agency where a typical
nine-month program costs at least $200 a month, estimated it had
experienced a 25 percent increase in enrollment of fourth-graders
this year, a trend it attributes to both a national advertising
campaign and test anxiety.
</P>
<P>
   Testquest, a private company that charges $30 an hour, said
business is up 15 percent at its 17 sites across the city, largely
because of concerns about this test, which New York City may start
using next year to determine whether children should be held back a
grade. Results also may determine whether a school is placed on the
state's list of failing schools. Some selective middle schools may
use the grade as a factor in admissions decisions.
</P>
<P>
   ``Many of their children will do well on this test without a
tutor, but parents want double insurance,'' said Annie Han, a tutor
who runs Saturday preparation classes for the test. Her son,
Matthew, is one of her students.
</P>
<P>
   Han, who teaches mathematics part time at Baruch College and
runs three Kumon private tutoring centers in Manhattan, said 35
parents signed up for her four Saturday sessions after she placed
an advertisement in school newsletters and a community newspaper.
The sessions were not part of Kumon, which does not plan to offer
specialized lessons. But like its programs, Han emphasized grammar,
spelling and writing, she said.
</P>
<P>
   Several tutors contend that students who take their lessons
improve their scores on other standardized tests, such as the
California Achievement Test.
</P>
<P>
   The Princeton Review said that later this year it would prepare
a study guide for teachers and another to be sold in stores for
about $12.
</P>
<P>
   John Katzman, president and founder of the company, said any
standardized test is ``coachable'' and predicted heavy demand for
materials related to this one, especially if the prognostications
that many students will do poorly ring true. The Princeton Review,
which sells materials for the SAT and other college-oriented exams,
published study guides last year for 10 of the 11 New York State
Regents exams, which are usually taken by the college-bound but
will be required for most prospective high school graduates within
five years.
</P>
<P>
   ``The running joke around here is that we figured out how to do
test prep well, now how do we help mainstream education,'' Katzman
said. ``Well, we don't have to, because mainstream ed has moved
into test prep. These tests really are going to wag the dog.''
</P>
<P>
   Richard P. Mills, the state education Commissioner, said Friday
that he had expected tutors and others to capitalize on concerns
about the exam. ``I'm not surprised and I'm not dismayed,'' said
Mills, setting aside criticism that high-stakes exams like New
York's and the SAT often unfairly favor those who can afford
private preparation programs.
</P>
<P>
   Nevertheless, he said he was heartened that even low-performing
schools, generally in low-income areas where parents may find it
difficult to afford a private tutor, were providing supplemental
help to students.
</P>
<P>
   Beverly Lewis, principal of Public School 129, which in 1996 was
on the Schools Under Registration Review list, the state's roster
of failing schools, wrote her own study guide with the help of
staff, using children's storybooks for sample reading passages but
writing their own questions, based on the sample test provided by
the state. The 110 fourth-graders in the Harlem school practice at
home , as well as in school with practice time every morning at 9.
</P>
<P>
   ``When we heard about the new test we were very concerned, but
we are also excited because it's a new challenge,'' said Lewis.
</P>
<P>
   PS 75 in Brooklyn, began a ``Breakfast Club'' last fall for
fourth-graders that meets every morning before school, from 7:30 to
8:30, so teachers can help students with their reading. About 30 of
the school's 90 fourth-graders showed up steadily, said Felicita
Santiago, the principal, whose school was placed on the Schools
Under Registration Review list in 1996.
</P>
<P>
   ``My hope is that we show progress,'' Ms. Santiago said. ``We've
been working hard, so I know my fourth-graders are used to
pressure. I hope we don't slide.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE _ OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Patricia Stewart, a South Bronx nutritionist, said she is not
relying solely on her school, Harbor Academy, an alternative public
school.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Stewart said she signed April up for Han's tutoring, paying
half price because April already had been attending one of Han's
Kumon centers. Ms. Stewart said she was alarmed last year when
April scored in the 51st percentile on the city reading exam, far
below the 85 needed for entrance to the top competitive middle
schools.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Stewart said April is doing better on her English
assignments and practices at home for the new test. April has
advice for her fellow fourth graders: ``It's not going to be really
hard if you just practice.''
</P>
</TEXT>
