<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BASS-LONDON09-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Top executives of Bass' hotel unit moving to London
 &HT;    By Shelia M. Poole
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Dunwoody, Ga.-based Bass Hotels &AMP; Resorts said Friday
it was relocating its top brass to London, essentially moving the
headquarters of the largest operating unit of global conglomerate
Bass PLC.
</P>
<P>
   ``Frankly, this will be much more efficient,'' said Chairman and
Chief Executive Officer Thomas R. Oliver, one of the senior
executives making the move.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's not really a matter (of Bass PLC) gaining greater
control,'' Oliver said. ``It has been the objective of the company
for some time to get the headquarters into London. When you're
running a company like this, it's more efficient when you have the
key people running the company in close proximity to one another.
You can engage in conversations without there being formal
presentations, if you will. The major benefit will be the way we
communicate with one another.''
</P>
<P>
   The reorganization takes effect Monday.
</P>
<P>
   The company's headquarters for its Holiday Inn brands in North
America will continue to be based in Dunwoody. The international
Holiday Inns, however, will be operated out of London, as will the
company's Crowne Plaza and Inter-Continental Hotels division.
</P>
<P>
   In addition to Oliver, Andrew E. MacFarlane, chief financial
officer, and Robert D. Hill, general counsel, will relocate.
</P>
<P>
   Craig H. Hunt, who was promoted to vice chairman, reporting
directly to Oliver, also will make the move.
</P>
<P>
   In his new role, Hunt, formerly president of Holiday Inn North
America, will assume global responsibility for corporate
development, human resources, corporate affairs and performance
planning. Corporate development will include driving development of
related business outside of the current hotel brands, such as
vacation ownership.
</P>
<P>
   In all, about 50 staffers are relocating. However, Bass Hotels &AMP;
Resorts' 850 other employees in Atlanta will remain.
</P>
<P>
   By midsummer, the company plans to establish a global strategic
management team that will be based in London.
</P>
<P>
   As part of the changes, John T. Sweetwood, formerly president of
Holiday Inn Express, North America, has been named president,
Holiday Inn Brands, North America. In this position, Sweetwood will
assume responsibility for the three major Holiday Inn brands:
Holiday Inn hotels and resorts, Holiday Inn Express and Staybridge
Suites by Holiday Inn.
</P>
<P>
   Bass Hotels &AMP; Resorts owns, operates or franchises more than
2,700 hotels in 95 countries. The overwhelming bulk of those
properties, 2,052, are in North America.
</P>
<P>
   The announcement is ``not overly surprising,'' said David
Leibowitz, managing director of Burnham Securities in New York.
``Bass (PLC) clearly wants to consolidate as much as they can under
one roof, and this move would be in keeping with that.''
</P>
<P>
   The relocations and the naming of Oliver to the Bass board of
directors last March seem to underscore the parent company's
commitment to the lodging industry. Bass Hotels &AMP; Resorts
constitute 40 percent of Bass PLC's operating earnings. The
remaining holdings are in branded drinks, pubs and restaurants.
</P>
<P>
   ``They're growing their investment in the hotel industry,'' said
Mark Woodworth, executive vice president of PKF Consulting in
Atlanta. ``If you're going to be successful in today's hotel
market, you have to think globally. Companies are going to have to
take a more global view in the next five to 10 years when there
will be far greater opportunities outside of the U.S. for all
brands, particularly Inter-Continental and Crowne Plaza.''
</P>
<P>
   Over the last few years, the lodging industry has become
extremely competitive and Bass has become a leader, particularly in
the North American market. With the acquisition of
Inter-Continental Hotels last year, the company has solidified its
global presence in the higher-end tier of hotel properties.
</P>
<P>
   Additionally, the company has embarked upon an aggressive
program to spruce up the image of Holiday Inn brands and has
required franchisees to make significant improvements in the
physical structure and service of hotel properties.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
