<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-IMPEACH-KENNEDY-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
UNLIKELY COLLABORATION FINALLY GETS TRIAL OVER HURDLE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By ANNE E. KORNBLUT  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ When Senator Edward M. Kennedy addressed his 99
colleagues in a private conference Friday, proposing the compromise
that would finally dislodge the impeachment blockade, he aligned
himself with someone he resembles least: Republican Senator Phil
Gramm of Texas.
</P>
<P>
   The two had not discussed a plan. Indeed, after decades at
opposite ends of the political spectrum, Kennedy and Gramm never
attempt to collaborate at all. But as Kennedy listened to Gramm's
speech suggesting that Democratic and Republican proposals for the
impeachment trial were similar in many ways, Kennedy decided he
agreed. Minutes later, Kennedy spontaneously echoed his
conservative colleague, forging an alliance almost as rare as
impeachment itself.
</P>
<P>
   ``Trent jumped up and down, and said, `We have a Kennedy-Gramm
agreement here?' '' said Senator James M. Jeffords, a Republican
from Vermont, referring to the majority leader, Trent Lott.
</P>
<P>
   ``We ended up laughing,'' said Senator Mitch McConnell, a
Republican from Kentucky. ``We called it the Kennedy-Gramm
proposal. And it stuck.''
</P>
<P>
   The detente gave birth to a bipartisan agreement on how the
impeachment trial will proceed, and it quickly led to a boisterous
spirit in the hallways, as senators on both sides emerged from the
meeting claiming victory.
</P>
<P>
   As the day wore on, the details were hammered out in smaller
sessions in Lott's office, where Kennedy and Gramm joined Senators
Slade Gorton, a Republican of Washington, and Joseph I. Lieberman,
a Democrat of Connecticut, in comparing the proposals from both
sides.
</P>
<P>
   But unlike Lieberman and Gorton _ who last week crafted and
advocated their own bipartisan proposal, only to see it shot down
by conservatives _ Kennedy and Gramm did not portray their
agreement as part of a larger, shared philosophy. Gramm, 56, even
sounded uncomfortable with the moniker, and by the end of the day
appeared to be distancing himself from it.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think people are overdoing the Gramm-Kennedy part of it,''
Gramm said. ``I think this was a deal with 100 members
participating.''
</P>
<P>
   The names have never been publicly linked before _ except in
arguments. They hold starkly different views of the world, agreeing
on policy matters as rarely as two senators could. They box over
legislation at least once a year. They are hardly more than civil
colleagues, aides said Friday.
</P>
<P>
   Kennedy, a lifelong liberal devoted to education and welfare
issues, has repeatedly blocked legislative efforts by Gramm, a
committed economic and social conservative who rarely softens his
remarks when he disagrees.
</P>
<P>
   Aides from both staffs said the two senators have fought on
nearly everything: HMO reform, tobacco, affirmative action,
education. As recently as October, Kennedy held up a Gramm
legislative proposal to grant $233 million to the Customs Service
to fight drugs, over concerns that components of the bill were
unfavorable to organized labor.
</P>
<P>
   ``They are not personal friends,'' said Larry Neal, a spokesman
for Gramm. ``They hold quite different views and are serious in
their quite divergent philosophies. They don't believe in the same
things, and they often find themselves in conflict. They view the
world in fundamentally different ways.''
</P>
<P>
   Yet Kennedy, 66, is a consummate dealmaker who enjoys stopping
crises before they unfold, even when the solution requires
negotiating across the aisle, aides and colleagues said. His most
recent, and high-profile, bipartisan effort came as a result of his
alliance with Senator Orrin Hatch, a Republican of Utah, to hammer
out a tobacco deal in 1997.
</P>
<P>
   Jeffords, a Republican who has worked closely with Kennedy since
taking over the Democrat's former role as chairman of the Labor and
Human Resources Committee, said Kennedy is a natural liberal but
``senses the time'' to negotiate instinctively.
</P>
<P>
   ``He understands when the common interest is to move ahead, to
bring calm in the storm and make decisions on important issues,
like what we're dealing with now,'' Jeffords said.
</P>
<P>
   Kennedy said the rough outlines of the final proposal _
particularly how to resolve the main dispute over calling witnesses
_ had been percolating since the night before. In Friday's meeting,
Gramm articulated the central roadblock, one that Kennedy and other
Democrats knew for days: Regardless of what agreements were reached
ahead of time about calling witnesses, the Republican majority
could still override that arrangement during the trial.
</P>
<P>
   It was Kennedy's turn to speak. Seizing on a suggestion by
Gramm, Kennedy proposed the Senate decide everything but the
witness issue _ leaving the most contentious element unsettled, but
agreeing on everything else.
</P>
<P>
   ``Ted Kennedy stood up and said, `Look, why can't we work this
thing out?' '' said Senator Joseph R. Biden, a Democrat from
Delaware. ``We're in agreement on how to get from home plate to
second base. Let's lock that in. And then let's worry about how to
get from second base to home later.'''
</P>
<P>
   Later, Kennedy admitted that questions remain. He said there
will be ``a lot of issues, sidebar questions'' he and Gramm will
differ over, particularly those involving the White House. And he
indicated their union was little more than a one-time arrangement _
an unusual solution to an even more unusual crisis.
</P>
<P>
   ``I differ with Phil, and I argue with him,'' Kennedy said.
``But he had an interest in getting this worked out, and I did
too.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
