<SLUG> BC-MUTFUND-STATEMENTS-2TAKES-$ADV10-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MY ACCOUNT STATEMENT IS BETTER THAN YOURS  
(FOR RELEASE SUNDAY, JAN. 10)
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: N.Y., Mo.)  (af) 
 By ERIC HUBLER   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   As part of an unceasing quest to find new ways to show that I am
right and my wife is wrong, I recently took haranguing to a new
level. I found fault not with her Spanish _ or with the fact that
she has been working on a sweater for me for six years and has only
one sleeve finished _ but rather with the cluttered presentation of
her mutual fund statements.
</P>
<P>
   To be blunt, I think my fund company's statements are better
than her fund company's statements.
</P>
<P>
   While this feud is unlikely to land us on ``The Jerry Springer
Show,'' it does involve the kind of nagging issue that can do
serious damage to a relationship. How am I supposed to keep track
of how much I love her if I can't tell how much she's worth?
</P>
<P>
   My wife invests with Fidelity Investments, the country's largest
fund company and I have money with the second-largest, the Vanguard
Group. Right off the bat, I should state that both seem to have an
extraordinary commitment to shareholder communication; if you never
read a glossy financial magazine or watched Louis Rukeyser as long
as you lived, but did read the marketing and educational materials
offered by either of these companies, you could still develop an
above-average financial IQ.
</P>
<P>
   Yet when it comes to the single most important point of contact
between the fund company and the investor _ the quarterly statement
_ the two companies part company. I could never put my finger on
it, but something about my wife's Fidelity statements makes me not
want to read them, whereas my Vanguard statements are easy to
glance at, digest and file.
</P>
<P>
   Enter an outfit called Siegel &AMP; Gale, a New York consulting firm
that specializes in the specialized field of document
simplification _ and its credentials are impeccable. It helped
develop the 1040 EZ form for the Internal Revenue Service, for
example, as well as plain-English securities prospectuses for the
Securities and Exchange Commission and individual fund companies.
</P>
<P>
   Now it is taking aim at the ways financial services statements
try so hard to communicate vital information but only increase
misunderstanding and frustration. In fact, Siegel &AMP; Gale is the
firm responsible for Vanguard's statements, and I decided to ask it
what makes some statements easier to read than others
</P>
<P>
   First, a confession. I had always assumed that statements from
credit card issuers, banks, insurers, mutual fund companies and the
like were intentionally written poorly _ the idea being that a
confused customer is a complacent customer. That view is too
uncharitable, said Irene A. Etzkorn, group director of simplified
communications at Siegel &AMP; Gale. (Yes, Ms. Etzkorn is a dapper
dresser and keeps her desktop admirably bereft of clutter. ``I'm an
expert packer,'' she added.)
 &UR;  &LR;  The people who mind money for us are not evil, she said, just a
little confused sometimes. They want to communicate clearly, but
they often need a nudge in the right direction.
</P>
<P>
   Sometimes the problem is not bad intentions, but antiquated
systems, Ms. Etzkorn said. There are statements that list
securities in order of their Cusip numbers, a securities industry
standard that is meaningful mostly to mainframes. Others show the
number of shares that the investor owns but not the dollar value.
Such things are nobody's fault in particular, which is part of the
problem.
</P>
<P>
   In other cases, language that was perfectly comprehensible to
the generation writing and reading it has been preserved by the
next generation, innocently but ignorantly, turning the monthly
statement into a linguistic time capsule. Sometimes these documents
have a history that predates anyone currently working at the
company.
</P>
<P>
   Phone companies seem to be some of the biggest culprits.
Acronyms and phrases that should be kept in-house, like USOC (for
universal service order code, a standardized table of designations
for various services, like call waiting) show up on bills, leading
confused customers to call the company for translations _ a waste
of time for both sides.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
