<SLUG> BC-FBN-HOLMGREN09-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Holmgren settles in with Seahawks
 &HT;    By Len Pasquarelli
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Even after the longest goodbye in NFL history was over
_ sealed by the longest green ever awarded a coach _ Mike Holmgren
had some trouble Friday believing that a departure that began 50
weeks ago at Super Bowl XXXII finally was consummated.
</P>
<P>
   ``This job,'' Holmgren said hours after accepting the position
of football czar for the Seattle Seahawks, ``really is the answer
to a dream that I've had for a long time.''
</P>
<P>
   Soon enough it may turn into a wakeup call for Holmgren. But for
at least a few hours Friday, before he settled into the business of
cobbling together his Seahawks staff, there was satisfaction tinged
with memories of what he had accomplished with the Packers.
</P>
<P>
   In seven seasons, Holmgren, 50, had a record of 84-42, including
postseason. The team went to the last two Super Bowls and captured
the championship in 1997.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'll be proud if we can duplicate that (Packers) organization
here,'' Holmgren said.
</P>
<P>
   If he can't, Holmgren need only look in the nearest mirror to
find the source of failure. To take over the operation of a
franchise that has typically underachieved, Holmgren gets
near-absolute control of the Seahawks.
</P>
<P>
   His eight-year contract will pay him nearly $40 million, by far
the largest salary ever for an NFL coach. In addition to general
manager-coach responsibilties, he also will hold the title of
executive vice president. Joked Seahawks owner Paul Allen, the
billionaire software magnate who began pursuing Holmgren nearly a
year ago: ``We wanted to make sure he earns his keep.''
</P>
<P>
   Holmgren's restructured contract with the Packers, which had one
season remaining, paid him approximately $2 million annually.
Seattle must compensate the Packers with their second-round choice
in this year's draft. With the biggest domino now off the coaching
market, other hires may fall into place. Pittsburgh defensive
coordinator Jim Haslett, who interviewed with Seattle earlier in
the week, is the clear front-runner in Philadelphia. The Baltimore
Ravens could turn to Minnesota offensive coordinator Brian Billick.
</P>
<P>
   Green Bay GM Ron Wolf could choose from a group that includes
Billick, former Eagles coach Ray Rhodes and defensive coordinators
Bill Belichick (Jets) and Dick Jauron (Jaguars).
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-01-08-99 2115EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
