<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990108.0418 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-01-08 21:15 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5584 &Cx1f; taf-z
s f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-MUTFUND-STATEMENTS-2N     01-08 0585
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MUTFUND-STATEMENTS-2NDTAKE-$ADV10-NYT </SLUG>
  
 UNDATED: both sides.  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   An unclear statement can go beyond annoyance; it can cost real
money and even disrupt lives. Ms. Etzkorn recalls a case in which a
corporate letter led a couple to believe their children's student
loans were in order; when the children arrived on campus, they were
barred from classes for nonpayment of tuition. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   But back to me. I placed examples of both the Fidelity and the
Vanguard statements before Ms. Etzkorn, and she explained what was
going on.
</P>
<P>
   Individually, the differences sometimes seem trivial.
</P>
<P>
   My wife's Fidelity statements are printed ``landscape'' style,
with three binder holes at the top of the sheets; Vanguard prints
them ``portrait'' style, with the holes at the left. Hers use
uncoated, ruled paper with a green background, and the lines of
type do not always fall where they are supposed to; mine uses
heavier, white paper with a faint wave background, like that found
on checks, that I find easier on the eye.
</P>
<P>
   Most important, her Fidelity statements cram transaction
details, share price and change in value for all six of her funds
onto a single page, whereas Vanguard statements take things nice
and easy, lavishing an entire page on each of my five funds. That
leaves plenty of space for a tear-off investment slip at the bottom
of each page _ a convenience that benefits both me and my fund
company.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm confused,'' Ms. Etzkorn said while reading my wife's
statements, making my vindictive heart leap. ``This fund is in
which account? One thing I'm confused about, and this surprises me,
is the names of the funds are so small.''
</P>
<P>
   For the record, Stephen Cone, president of retail and corporate
marketing at Fidelity, disagreed strongly with my assessment,
pointing out that customers invariably want information on as few
pages as possible. ``We send 14 million people a statement a month
and we get very few people saying they don't like our statements,''
he said. Fidelity is nevertheless unveiling what Cone described as
``a major improvement'' to its statements in a few months. But he
said the issue of financial statements is likely to become less
important as more investors monitor accounts on the Internet.
</P>
<P>
   Vanguard must spend a lot of money on printing and mailing its
statements, because of the extra paper involved. Undoubtedly, that
was a tough decision for the company, which is known for its
parsimony. If the design of a seemingly simple piece of paper can
help bring in assets, however, it must be worth it.
</P>
<P>
   Nice as my Vanguard's communications are, though, they do not
represent the latest in shareholder statements.
</P>
<P>
   During the first six months of this year, Edward D. Jones, a
brokerage firm in St. Louis and a big seller of load mutual funds,
plans to introduce not just one new-and-improved statement, but
three. As a result of feedback from focus groups, each client will
have the choice of three types of statements: the ``at-a-glance,''
the ``preferred'' or the ``in-depth'' statement, in ascending order
of detail.
</P>
<P>
   The at-a-glance statement does little more than list account
activity, assets, balance and previous-month and previous-year
comparisons. The in-depth statement showers investors with
graphics, and includes Standard &AMP; Poor's ratings for bonds and
analyst recommendations for stocks. The ``preferred'' statement
falls somewhere between those two.
</P>
<P>
   No word yet on whether Siegel &AMP; Gale is willing to take on my
sock drawer.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
