A5585 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-IMPEACH-GRAMM-TEX     01-08 0745
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-IMPEACH-GRAMM-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SEN. PHIL GRAMM MAY NOW BE MR. NICE GUY
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service Clients) 
By MARIA RECIO 
c.1998 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Sen. Phil Gramm's comeback may now be complete.
</P>
<P>
   The Texas Republican, once labeled ``Senator Spite'' for his
mean-spirited attacks on colleagues, helped craft the bipartisan
compromise that will enable the Senate trial of President Clinton
to go forward next week.
</P>
<P>
   In a surprising twist, the ``new'' Gramm was joined by his
ideological opposite, Sen. Edward Kennedy, D-Mass., in finding the
middle ground in a partisan dispute over the appearance of
witnesses that threatened to polarize the chamber.
</P>
<P>
   According to Senate Majority Leader Trent Lott, R-Miss., the
breakthrough came when the 100 senators met yesterday morning in
the historic old Senate chamber.
</P>
<P>
   ``Comments by Senator Gramm followed by Senator Kennedy actually
revealed to us the way to proceed,'' said Lott after the session
was over. Later, at a news conference with Gramm and others, Lott
introduced the Texan and said, ``He was the one who touched the
point that turned the whole thing around.''
</P>
<P>
   The Gramm-Kennedy compromise would allow the trial to go forward
while setting a format that would make House managers present the
case they developed before the House Judiciary Committee before any
vote would be taken on witnesses. Moreover, a vote to end the trial
would be taken before a witness vote.
</P>
<P>
   Gramm described the session in an interview as an
``extraordinary event. When it came his turn to speak, the Texan
said he began on a historical note. ``One hundred and fifty years
ago, Daniel Webster had risen to speak in this same chamber and
said, `I rise today not as a New Englander but as an American. Hear
me for my cause,' '' Gramm said.
</P>
<P>
   Gramm, who holds a doctorate in economics, was self-effacing
about his ability to see a solution in a Senate replete with
lawyers. ``I got to speak last,'' said the Texas Republican,
explaining that had had the advantage of listening to both sides.
``It became obvious to me that the proposal the Democrats were
making did not alter the underlying rules of impeachment. Our
proposal did not alter the underlying rules and so, that in
reality, the two proposals were identical.''
</P>
<P>
   When Kennedy rose and agreed with Gramm, the stage was set for
the two lawmakers to work out the details with Sen. Joseph
Lieberman, D-Conn., and Sen. Slade Gorton, R-Wash.
</P>
<P>
   ``Too much is being made of Kennedy and me,'' Gramm said. ``It
was really 100 members of the Senate.''
</P>
<P>
   The conservative Gramm and the liberal Kennedy are frequently at
odds over legislation but the compromise shows a possible mellowing
of both men.
</P>
<P>
   Gramm's role as power broker is one he has grown into since he
had to abandon his lifelong presidential ambitions after his dismal
showing in the 1996 primary campaign. Gramm, who withdrew from the
race just before the New Hampshire primary, was re-elected to the
Senate the same year and has refocused his energies on being a
legislator.
</P>
<P>
   But this being Gramm, known for grand gestures, or
``Gramm-standing,'' he has not been shy or retiring about it.
Instead, he has made his mark on contentious issues such as
Medicare by reaching across to Democrats. In the last two years he
has made unlikely alliances with Sen. Bob Kerrey, D-Neb., on cuts
in entitlements and Sen. Robert Byrd, D-W.Va., on preserving
highway spending.
</P>
<P>
   Gramm credited Byrd yesterday for ``setting the tenor for what
we have achieved'' in his opening remarks during the private Senate
session. Byrd, who has an almost regal air, is the acknowledged
historian of the chamber but not a universally liked figure.
</P>
<P>
   And he is not someone who was exactly simpatico with the Gramm
of old.
</P>
<P>
   Gramm, 56, has been one of the most partisan Republicans in the
House or Senate despite having been originally elected as a
Democrat to the House in 1978. A fiscal conservative, Gramm ran
afoul of then-House Majority Leader Jim Wright, D-Fort Worth, who
was enraged that his fellow Democrat was conspiring with the Reagan
White House on a budget deal.
</P>
<P>
   Wright threw Gramm off of the House Budget Committee and Gramm
promptly switched parties, resigned his seat and ran for the post
as a Republican. He won easily in the 1983 special election and was
re-appointed to the panel.
</P>
<P>
   (Visit the Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide
Web: www.star-telegram.com)
</P>
</TEXT>
