<HEADLINE>
49ERS VS. FALCONS CAPSULE
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By MITCHELL KRUGEL 
c.1998 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO (13-4) at ATLANTA (14-2) Time 11:35 a.m. today
</P>
<P>
   TV/Radio: KDFW/Channel 4; KTCK/1310 AM
</P>
<P>
   Line: Falcons by 3.
</P>
<P>
   Series record: 49ers lead 40-23-1.
</P>
<P>
   Last time: Falcons topped 49ers, 31-19, on Nov. 15 in Atlanta.
</P>
<P>
   Postseason records: 49ers 24-14, Falcons 2-5.
 &LR; subheds:THE STORYLINES San Francisco Talk about a Catch-22. The
49ers are coming off a dramatic last-second victory against Green
Bay on Sunday, but have had five days to prepare and travel to
Atlanta, where the Falcons are 10-0 in the Georgia Dome this
season.
</P>
<P>
   Then there is the running-game issue. Running the ball is the
way to beat the Falcons, but Garrison Hearst, who had 128 yards on
Sunday, is questionable because of a pulled hamstring.
</P>
<P>
   The 49ers have far more playoff experience and they have the
second-best playoff record of all time with 24 victories. They are
playing better than the team that lost in Atlanta on Nov. 15.
Atlanta The common thought is the Falcons have the edge because of
their Nov. 14 victory against the Niners. But in the two games
combined, Atlanta outscored San Francisco 51-50, only because the
49ers went for a two-point conversion and failed in their 31-19
loss in Atlanta.
</P>
<P>
   The Falcons haven't lost a game since October _ when they played
at the Jets without Chris Chandler. They've won nine consecutive,
are undefeated at home and are coming off a bye week.
</P>
<P>
   Chandler should be able to put up some serious passing yards
against the 49ers corners. The Falcons' ability to control the
clock _ and their considerable advantage on special teams _ could
be the difference.
 &LR; subheds:ONE TO STOP San Francisco Wide receiver J.J. Stokes The
Falcons cornerbacks are strong, but they will be preoccupied with
all-time playoff receiving leader Jerry Rice and last week's hero,
Terrell Owens. Stokes had 15 catches for 188 yards in the playoffs
last season, and could do more of the same against single coverage.
Atlanta Running back Jamal Anderson Not exactly a secret, but
Anderson accentuates the Falcons' speed advantage. If he gets 130
yards on 25 carries, Atlanta is off to the NFC Championship Game.
 &LR; subheds:THE QUARTERBACKS San Francisco: Steve Young Playoff
record: 7-5 as a starter
</P>
<P>
   Young had one of his best regular seasons ever, throwing for
4,170 yards and a career-high 36 touchdowns. Atlanta Chris Chandler
</P>
<P>
   Playoff record: First career playoff game in 11 seasons
</P>
<P>
   Chandler had his best season ever with career highs of 3,154
yards passing and 25 touchdowns. His 9.65 yards per attempt led the
league.
 &LR; subheds:INJURY REPORT San Francisco Questionable: RB Garrison
Hearst (Hamstring); TE Irv Smith (calf) Probable: G Tim Hanshaw
(neck); WR Mark Harris (shoulder); CB R.W. McQuarters (knee); WR
Jerry Rice (knee); LB Winfred Tubbs (pectoral); LB James Williams
(calf); LB Lee Woodall (leg). Atlanta Questionable: CB Ronnie
Bradford (shoulder); TE Brian Kozlowski (ankle); LB Craig Sauer
(hamstring)
</P>
<P>
   Probable: DE Lester Archambeau (thumb)
 &LR; subheds:THE CHECKLIST San Francisco run offense (159 yards per
game, No. 1) vs. Atlanta run defense (75.2 yards per game, No. 2)
</P>
<P>
   Edge: Atlanta
</P>
<P>
   San Francisco pass offense (266 yards per game, No. 2) vs.
Atlanta pass defense 295.9 yards per game, No. 21)
</P>
<P>
   Edge: San Francisco
</P>
<P>
   Atlanta run offense (131.3 yards per game, No. 6) vs. San
Francisco run defense (100.6 yards per game, No. 9)
</P>
<P>
   Edge: Atlanta
</P>
<P>
   Atlanta pass offense (211.6 yards per game, No. 11) vs. San
Francisco pass defense (233.2 yards per game (No. 29)
</P>
<P>
   Edge: Atlanta
Special teams San Francisco (Terry Kirby 20 yards per kickoff
return; R.W. McQuarters 8.6 yards per punt return) vs. Atlanta (Tim
Dwight 27 yards per kickoff return, 8.5 yards per punt return)
</P>
<P>
   Edge: Atlanta
Coaching San Francisco (Steve Mariucci 2-1 in playoffs) vs. Atlanta
(Dan Reeves 8-7 in playoffs)
</P>
<P>
   Edge: Atlanta
The pick Atlanta, 27-21
</P>
