<HEADLINE>
DOLPHINS VS. BRONCOS CAPSULE
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By MIKE FISHER 
c.1998 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   MIAMI (11-6) AT DENVER (14-2) When: 3:15 p.m. today, Mile High
Stadium, Denver
</P>
<P>
   TV: KTVT/Channel 11. Radio: KTCK/1310 AM
</P>
<P>
   Line: Broncos by 13 1/2.
</P>
<P>
   Series record _ Dolphins lead 6-2-1.
</P>
<P>
   Last time: Dolphins beat Broncos, 31-21, on Dec. 21 at Miami.
THE STORYLINES Miami Dan Marino ``had the best game he's had since
I've been here,'' said third-year Dolphins coach Jimmy Johnson of
his QB, who threw for 355 yards and four TD passes in the Dec. 21
victory against Denver.
</P>
<P>
   Miami has lost all six of its road playoff games since it won
the 1972 AFC Championship Game at Pittsburgh.
</P>
<P>
   The differences between this game and the Dolphins victory three
games ago are location (Mile High Stadium instead of Pro Player
Stadium) and health (now the Dolphins are beat up, with Jason
Taylor and Tim Bowens out and O.J. McDuffie and Troy Drayton
hurting). Denver Denver has won 17 consecutive at Mile High Stadium
and has scored more than 30 points a game in 13 of their past 16
home games.
</P>
<P>
   The Broncos were frustrated by the way Miami's defense
completely shut down their offense Dec. 21. Or were they? Coaches
who have played the Broncos in the past month maintain that Denver
has stripped its offense down to the basics. Why would the Broncos
do that? Coach Mike Shanahan hasn't wanted to reveal anything
before the playoffs, and when Denver locked up home-field advantage
throughout the postseason, he figured why risk giving away strategy
unnecessarily. Ones to stop Miami: Wide receiver O.J. McDuffie
McDuffie had a team-record and NFL-leading 90 receptions this
season. He is Marino's crutch, and if McDuffie plays, Denver must
especially control him on third down. Denver: Running back Terrell
Davis You know the numbers: 2,008 yards, 23 touchdowns. But look
what happened when Miami held Davis to 29 yards on Dec. 21. The
quarterbacks Miami: Dan Marino Playoff record: 6-7
</P>
<P>
   Marino needs 24 yards to reach 4,000 for his playoff career and
one TD pass for 31 to move past Terry Bradshaw for second place on
the career postseason list. Denver: John Elway Playoff record: 11-7
</P>
<P>
   Elway is 7-2 at home all-time in the playoffs and he has six
career postseason fourth-quarter comeback victories. Injury report
Miami: Out _ DE Tim Bowens (biceps-injured reserve), LB Larry Izzo
(knee). Doubtful _ TE Troy Drayton (ankle), TE Frank Wainwright
(shoulder); Questionable _ WR O.J. McDuffie (foot), T Richmond Webb
(triceps); Probable _ RB Karim Abdul-Jabbar (toe/quadricep), RB
John Avery (quadricep), S Brock Marion (groin)
</P>
<P>
   Denver: Questionable _ RB Vaughn Hebron (hamsting). Probable _
WR Justin Armour (hamstring); S Steve Atwater (shoulder); S Tyrone
Braxton (shoulder-hamstring); S Eric Brown (groin); LB Keith Burns
(thigh-toe); CB Ray Crockett (ankle); RB Terrell Davis (side); G
David Diaz-Infante (knee); QB John Elway (ribs); CB Darrien Gordon
(shoulder); RB Howard Griffith (knee); DT Harald Hasselbach
(ankle); T Tony Jones (knee); WR Ed McCaffrey (back); G Dan Neil
(knee); P Tom Rouen (shoulder); G Mark Schlereth (knee); TE Shannon
Sharpe (knee); DE Neil Smith (abdomen). The stats Miami run offense
(95.9 yards per game, No. 24) vs. Denver run defense (80.4 yards
per game, No. 3)
</P>
<P>
   Edge: Denver
</P>
<P>
   Miami pass offense (212.2 yards per game, No. 10) vs. Denver
pass defense (228 yards per game, No. 26)
</P>
<P>
   Edge: Miami
</P>
<P>
   Denver run offense (154.3 yards per game, No. 2) vs. Miami run
defense (94.4 yards per game, No. 6)
</P>
<P>
   Edge: Denver
</P>
<P>
   Denver pass offense (226.5 yards per game, No. 7) vs. Miami pass
defense (182.8 yards per game, No. 6)
</P>
<P>
   Edge: Denver
</P>
<P>
   Special teams. Miami (Terrell Buckley 12.2 yards per punt
return, third in AFC) vs. Darrien Gordon (11.1 yards per punt
return)
</P>
<P>
   Edge: Denver
</P>
<P>
   Coaching. Miami (Jimmy Johnson, 8-2 in playoffs) vs. Denver
(Mike Shanahan, 4-1 in playoffs)
</P>
<P>
   Edge: Denver
</P>
<P>
   Prediction: Denver 30, Miami 17
</P>
