<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-AT&AMP;T-ACQUIRE-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
AT&AMP;T ALTERS PART OF PLAN FOR TCI ACQUISITION
</HEADLINE>
  (bl)  
By SETH SCHIESEL   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   AT&AMP;T on Friday changed a major part of its $31.8 billion plan
for acquiring Tele-Communications Inc., the No. 2 cable television
company, saying it would not issue a new stock to track the
combined company's consumer operations.
</P>
<P>
   The change reflected a shift in how the market perceives AT&AMP;T's
prospects. Last summer, when the two companies announced their
deal, AT&AMP;T executives, concerned that some investors might not
understand how different parts of the new company would work
together, wanted to offer separate shares in those parts.
</P>
<P>
   But now, as its stock soars, AT&AMP;T is touting the synergies among
the two companies' operations and believes it has the momentum to
combine them under a single equity.
</P>
<P>
   ``By merging with TCI, we plan to create an advanced broadband
network that can deliver an array of communications, entertainment
and information services directly to millions of U.S. households,''
said AT&AMP;T Chairman C. Michael Armstrong in a letter to
shareholders. ``We consider this a critical step toward our goal of
becoming the `total communications source' for our customers _
supplying complete packages of local telephone, long-distance,
wireless, Internet, entertainment and next-generation digital
services.''
</P>
<P>
   Having bought back $3 billion of its stock last year, AT&AMP;T said
Friday that it would repurchase an additional $4 billion worth of
shares by the time the TCI acquisition was finished. After the
acquisition is done, the company said Friday, it will split its
stock 3 for 2, AT&AMP;T's first stock split since a 2-for-1
distribution in 1964.
</P>
<P>
   Exuding yet more optimism, the company also said it would earn
more money in its core business than had been previously expected:
between $4.20 and $4.30 a share in its continuing operations
(excluding the impact of the TCI deal), up to 5.1 percent more than
the $4.09 a share estimate of analysts polled by First Call, a
financial research firm.
</P>
<P>
   But AT&AMP;T, the nation's No. 1 communications company, said
acquiring TCI would reduce its per-share earnings by about $1,
assuming the deal closes at the end of March. The analysts had
predicted post-TCI earnings of $3.41 a share, for a consensus
dilution estimate of 68 cents a share. AT&AMP;T would not say when the
deal would add to its earnings.
</P>
<P>
   The increased dilution seemed to be a result of AT&AMP;T's plans to
accelerate spending to upgrade TCI's cable television systems. The
company said it planned to use TCI's network to offer telephone,
video and data services in 10 markets around the country this year
and telephone service in most TCI markets in 2000.
</P>
<P>
   Intensifying its focus on the cable business, AT&AMP;T also said it
had reached deals to offer telephone service over the wires of five
small cable companies: Bresnan Communications, Falcon Cable TV,
Insight Communications, Intermedia Partners and Peak Cablevision.
Combined, the five companies have about 3.2 million customers.
Executives close to the negotiations have said that a deal between
AT&AMP;T and Time Warner Inc., the No. 1 cable carrier, might be
reached within weeks.
</P>
<P>
   The raft of announcements boosted AT&AMP;T's stock Friday, sending
the shares, the most widely held in the country, up $2.8125, to
$85.0625, on the New York Stock Exchange. (On the day the deal was
announced last June, AT&AMP;T's shares closed at $60.) TCI's shares
gained $1.1875, closing at $62.25 in Nasdaq trading.
</P>
<P>
   When AT&AMP;T and TCI announced the acquisition in June, AT&AMP;T said
that as part of the deal it would issue a new stock to track the
combined company's consumer services, including cable television
and long-distance. Executives close to the deal, however, said
Friday that late last year some people at AT&AMP;T began to believe
that having the tracking stock (instead of AT&AMP;T common stock)
represent the consumer long-distance business would only confuse
investors because long-distance has been such a core part of AT&AMP;T's
operations.
</P>
<P>
   The executives close to the deal said AT&AMP;T considered having the
tracking stock represent only AT&AMP;T's wireless operation and the
cable television business. They added that AT&AMP;T decided to scrap
the tracking stock altogether as recently as last weekend. (Liberty
Media Group, the television programming unit that will be run by
John Malone, now TCI's chairman, will still be issued its own
tracking stock.)
</P>
<P>
   The fundamental goal behind keeping all of the new AT&AMP;T
operations under one stock was avoiding the creation of rifts among
the company's different units, in the interest of delivering
integrated bundles of services to consumers. That choice was made
possible partly by the strong recent performance of AT&AMP;T's stock,
which convinced some executives that investors could properly value
a company with as broad a range of operations as AT&AMP;T's.
</P>
<P>
   A tracking stock tied to less-profitable operations, however,
would have given AT&AMP;T a currency that could help the company pursue
future acquisitions. Analysts at Friday's meeting said that Malone
hinted that AT&AMP;T could consider issuing a tracking stock in the
future.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
