</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SIXTY-MINUTES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MARINE CORPS SUBPOENAS TAPES FROM `SIXTY MINUTES'  
(JT)
</HEADLINE>
   By FELICITY BARRINGER    
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   CBS Friday filed a motion to quash a subpoena by a Marine Corps
prosecutor seeking tapes the program ``60 Minutes'' made of an
interview with the pilot of the jet that sliced through cables
supporting a ski gondola, killing 20 people.
</P>
<P>
   The subpoena, issued in late December, said the tape, which has
not yet been broadcast, might contain statements that could help in
the prosecution of the case.
</P>
<P>
   The newsman Mike Wallace said Friday that he had interviewed the
pilot, Capt. Richard Ashby, several times in preparation for a
report about the Marine Corps' handling of the case. The interview
was to be broadcast on Jan. 24 or Jan. 31, he said; the court
martial of Ashby and Capt. Joseph Schweitzer, the navigator on the
Feb. 3 flight in the Italian Alps, is scheduled to start the first
week of February.
</P>
<P>
   In filing its motion with the officer presiding over the court
martial, CBS said the subpoena violated the news program's
privileges under the First Amendment and that, under the code of
military justice, it constituted an ``unreasonable and oppressive''
action.
</P>
<P>
   Floyd Abrams, the lawyer representing ``60 Minutes,'' said
Friday, ``This is a really extraordinary situation,'' involving not
only a request for material that has not been broadcast _
``outtakes,'' in the jargon of television news _ but in which ``the
party seeking the outtakes is the very party about whom the
broadcast may revolve.''
</P>
<P>
   Wallace said, ``I still cannot understand how they could ask us,
in effect, to help them make their case against Rich Ashby.'' He
added that his interview with a senior Marine officer has not yet
taken place, and speculated that the Marine Corps wanted to review
the other interviews before its officer spoke to the program.
</P>
<P>
   But Lt. Col. Katie Haddock said that the request from Lt. Col.
Carol Joyce _ the trial counsel, or prosecutor _ was made
independently of the Corps' command structure. If the material
being subpoenaed is evidence, she said, ``it is not available'' to
any officers outside the prosecution and defense teams.
</P>
<P>
   Abrams said it is extremely rare for any prosecutor to subpoena
the raw information that goes into a news report before the report
is made public.
</P>
<P>
   He also pointed out, in an interview and in the motion to quash
the subpoena, that Justice Department guidelines require that,
before Federal prosecutors can subpoena journalists, they must have
``reasonable grounds to believe, based on information obtained by
non-media sources, that the information sought is essential of a
successful investigation.''
</P>
<P>
   The prosecutors are also seeking a ``60 Minutes'' interview with
Capt. Chandler Seagraves, who was in the back seat of the jet, an
EA-6B Prowler, at the time of the accident. He was not charged.
</P>
<P>
   Ashby and Schweitzer each have been charged with 20 counts of
involuntary manslaughter and 20 counts of homicide. Any one count
of involuntary manslaughter carries a maximum sentence of 10 years'
imprisonment.
</P>
<P>
   In addition to the involuntary manslaughter and homicide
charges, the pilot and the navigator face charges of obstruction of
justice and conduct unbecoming an officer in connection with the
alleged disappearance of a videotape made during the fatal flight.
</P>
<P>
   Schweitzer declined to be interviewed by ``60 Minutes.''
</P>
<P>
   At least one officer, who supervised the public hearing that led
to the charges, indicated that the prosecution's case may be weak,
in part because the Marine Corps, the Air Force and a Pentagon
map-making agency had made systematic errors that contributed to
the accident. There is evidence that the jet's crew was given
inaccurate information when they planned the flight.
</P>
<P>
   The commander of the jet squadron involved in the accident, Lt.
Col. Richard Muegge, was relieved of command in August. Maj. Max
Caramanian, who was the director of standardization and safety for
the squadron, received a letter of reprimand.
</P>
<P>
   Charges were dismissed against two other officers.
</P>
<P>
   The accident provoked strong protest in Italy and strained
relations between it and the United States.
</P>
<P>
   The plane, an electronic warfare jet, was on a low-altitude
training mission out of an air base in Aviano, Italy, when it hit
the cables about 370 feet from the ground.
</P>
<P>
   At the time of the accident, local rules set a minimum height
above ground level of 2,000 feet, but everyone in the Marine
squadron said that they believed it was 1,000 feet, and some
material on file in the flight operations center gave an even lower
number for some areas.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
