<SLUG> BC-FBN-BRONCOS-DOLPHINS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BRONCOS THINK JOHNSON IS UP TO HIS OLD TRICKS
</HEADLINE>
 (bl) 
By CHARLIE NOBLES   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   DENVER _ Forget Marino against Elway. Never mind Shannon
Sharpe's braggadocio. Dolphins coach Jimmy Johnson has elbowed his
way onto center stage for Miami's American Football Conference
divisional game Saturday against the Denver Broncos.
</P>
<P>
   Johnson became an object of ridicule nationwide last week when
he peppered the Dolphins' locker room with Flutie Flakes after his
team's 7-point victory over Buffalo, not mindful that proceeds from
the sale of the cereal named for Bills quarterback Doug Flutie help
autistic children. Flutie and Dolphins quarterback Dan Marino have
autistic children.
</P>
<P>
   Johnson later wrote a letter of apology to Flutie, but his
celebration stomp still prompted one contributor to The Denver Post
online message board to wonder this week what Johnson will do if
Miami happens to upset Denver at Mile High Stadium: ``Would Jimmy
bring in a bunch of the Sesame Street characters that Terrell Davis
sang with and beat the stuffing out of them with a tire iron?''
</P>
<P>
   The Broncos have also questioned Johnson's veracity in
describing his team's latest injuries, a sprained right ankle for
tight end Troy Drayton and a sprained right foot for wide receiver
O.J. McDuffie. They noticed on film, as Marino threw the
game-winning touchdown against Buffalo with 3 minutes 42 seconds
left, both Drayton and McDuffie running full-speed pass patterns.
</P>
<P>
   The Broncos (14-2) are left to believe Johnson is playing mind
games with them, making them think they will not have to beat
Miami's best. ``Well, it's not going to be that way at all,''
Denver linebacker Bill Romanowski said. ``We're going to get their
best 11 and we're going to play our tails off. His mind games
aren't working with us.''
</P>
<P>
   Johnson's team is apparently going to get one break. Even though
it snowed lightly Friday, temperatures for the game are expected to
be in the 40s.
</P>
<P>
   ``When you have a young team, which we have, that type of thing
can be a problem if you let it,'' Dolphins defensive end Trace
Armstrong said of the potentially icy weather. ``A lot of guys,
it'll be the first time they see that stadium or been in this type
of game. So all those things _ temperatures, stadiums, crowds _ can
be a factor if you let them.''
</P>
<P>
   Besides cereal-stomping and weather forecasting, there are other
subplots to this game, which determines one berth in next week's
AFC title game against the winner of Sunday's Jets-Jacksonville
Jaguars game.
</P>
<P>
   There are the veteran quarterbacks, the 37-year-old Dan Marino
against the 38-year-old John Elway. The two had faced each other
only once in their storied careers _ back in 1985 _ but will now
duel twice in a one-month span. The Dolphins (11-6) handed the
Broncos their second loss of the season in a 31-21 victory in Miami
on Dec. 21.
</P>
<P>
   Elway picked up his first Super Bowl championship ring last
season; Marino is still looking for his first. Elway is leaning
toward retirement after this season; Marino expects to play at
least several more years.
</P>
<P>
   In the event this winds up being Elway's final game, a columnist
in the Denver area has suggested that Bronco fans show their
appreciation. As the fourth quarter begins and the sun is setting
over the Rockies, fans are being asked to give some light _ a
candle, a match, a lighter, a flashlight _ in Elway's honor.
</P>
<P>
   The idea is for at least 50,000 to make such a gesture,
symbolizing a light for every yard thrown by Elway in his 17-year
Bronco career.
</P>
<P>
   Just the same, Marino seems to be the sentimental choice outside
of Denver in this matchup because he has only been to one National
Football League title game _ Super Bowl XIX in 1985 _ and he does
not have a championship ring. But Elway said he would not feel even
a twinge of sorrow for his longtime pal if Denver beats Miami.
</P>
<P>
   ``When it comes down to who moves on and who doesn't,'' Elway
said, ``you have to get a little selfish.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
