<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-01-08 21:24 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5597 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-RELIGION-COLUMN-ART-N     01-08 0978
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-RELIGION-COLUMN-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
RELIGIOUS BOOKS HAVE TWO VIEWS OF CLINTON'S MISDEEDS 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchase by calling (888) 603-1036 or (888)
346-9867.) 
(lb) 
 By PETER STEINFELS   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   For the first half of 1998, religious leaders and theologians
had a low profile in the national debate over President Clinton's
sexual and legal misdeeds.
</P>
<P>
   But starting on Sept. 11, when Clinton chose a breakfast meeting
with religious leaders as the occasion for his fullest admission of
wrongdoing and expression of remorse, the situation began to
change.
</P>
<P>
   And as the president's trial begins in the Senate, two brief
books have appeared in which widely respected religious thinkers
offer larger frameworks for evaluating the issues. The books are
strikingly different in style and conclusion, but in some ways
complementary.
</P>
<P>
   The Rev. Dr. Philip Wogaman, pastor of Foundry United Methodist
Church in Washington where Clinton, a Southern Baptist, usually
worships with the first lady, a Methodist, has defended Clinton in
more than one television interview. Now he has written ``From the
Eye of the Storm'' (Westminster John Knox Press, $12), subtitled
``A Pastor to the President Speaks Out.''
</P>
<P>
   Wogaman is not only a pastor. For 26 years he was also a
professor of Christian ethics whose books on the topic are used as
standard texts in Protestant seminaries throughout the United
States.
</P>
<P>
   ``The immediate question of whether the president should be
removed from office,'' Wogaman writes, forces the nation to address
other questions: the nature of the presidency, the relationship of
an officeholder's private behavior to public responsibility and
leadership, the demands of repentance, healing and punishment, the
way in which the mass media define reality.
</P>
<P>
   ``The debate pushes us toward consideration of profound issues
of law and morality,'' he adds, ``that will be around long after
the present crisis has been fully resolved.''
</P>
<P>
   Wogaman does not condone Clinton's sexual sins or dishonesty,
and insists that the United States must be a nation of law and
``social discipline.'' But law and discipline, he argues, must be
in the service of love and compassion.
</P>
<P>
   Wogaman builds his case around a contrast between two events
last Sept. 11: the White House prayer breakfast in the morning and
Congress' release of the Starr report that afternoon. One
emphasized ``the moral acts of repentance and forgiveness,'' he
writes; the other focused ``on judgment and condemnation.''
</P>
<P>
   The prayer breakfast is, in fact, the starting point for the
other book, ``Judgment Day at the White House'' (William B.
Eerdmans, $12), which contains essays by some of the nation's
leading religious scholars and ethicists. A large number of them
obviously prefer the bluntness of the Starr report to the sentiment
of the prayer breakfast.
</P>
<P>
   Convinced by the breakfast that Clinton and his defenders were
manipulating the language of repentance and forgiveness for
political purposes, several theologians composed a Declaration
Concerning Religion, Ethics and the Crisis in the Clinton
presidency, which continues to circulate and gain signatures.
</P>
<P>
   The book reprints this declaration and develops its concerns in
essays insisting that personal and public morality cannot be
separated and that the president's talk of repentance and
forgiveness does not relieve him of political accountability or the
acceptance of consequences for his sins.
</P>
<P>
   The contributors, it should be underlined, do not come from the
religious right but largely from mainline Protestantism, and many
make clear their sympathy with Clinton's moderate liberalism.
</P>
<P>
   In terms of style, Wogaman certainly wins the face-off. His book
is conversational, he admits to uncertainties and suggests that
many judgments rest on matters of degree and proportion, although
sometimes his sentences beginning ``I wonder whether ...'' are just
ways of sidling up to conclusions that he doesn't wonder about at
all.
</P>
<P>
   By contrast, many essays in ``Judgment Day at the White House''
are academic and more than slightly high and mighty. The arguments
are substantial but they are weakened by their tight focus on
Clinton to the exclusion of all the surrounding context _ from
Linda Tripp's taping and the work of the independent counsel to the
politics of the House Judiciary Committee.
</P>
<P>
   Yet one sign of the book's value is its inclusion of critical
estimates on the declaration. In one of the dissenting essays, for
example, Nicholas Wolterstorff, the Noah Porter professor of
philosophical theology at Yale University, expressed amazement at
the declaration's worry ``that the president might escape without
punishment.''
</P>
<P>
   ``He has been placed in our model global equivalent of the
stocks of an old New England town,'' Wolterstorff writes.
</P>
<P>
   ``President Clinton has been humiliated,'' the professor adds,
``to a degree beyond the humiliation ever wreaked on any other
president.''
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, Wolterstorff says he finds himself deeply troubled by
this deliberate shaming _ and by the declaration's silence about
the moral questions it raises.
</P>
<P>
   In the end, which of these books one finds more convincing on
the subject of repentance and consequences may depend on whether
one is convinced that Clinton is, as one of the declaration's
signers suggests, a political manipulator ``all the way down.'' The
president's pastor does not think so. His religious critics, along
with many of the inside-the-Beltway correspondents and
commentators, do.
</P>
<P>
   But also in the end, one wonders why it took two relatively
small religious publishing houses, rather than the trade publishers
who dispense millions for inside gossip, to produce these two
thoughtful, useful books.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
