</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BIZ-TELECOM-Q&AMP;A-2TAKES-$ADV10-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BUYING IN TO `COMMUNICOPIA,' A RICH   NEW DATA LANDSCAPE  
 (FOR RELEASE SUNDAY, JAN. 10) 
</HEADLINE>
   (af)  
 By KENNETH N. GILPIN   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   One week it is a white-hot debut for a new business on the
Internet. The next it's a telephone company breaking a taboo by
buying a cable network. Last week, a spirited bidding war broke out
over a major wireless phone company.
</P>
<P>
   Like pixels lighting up one by one on a flat-screen display,
these seemingly disjointed events add new clarity and detail to a
developing picture of what analysts at Goldman, Sachs seven years
ago called ``communicopia'': an intertwined landscape of data and
voice communications, entertainment programming and electronic
commerce.
</P>
<P>
   But for all its complexity, this world is rapidly converging.
More and more of the companies in these industries are doing more
and more of the same sorts of things.
</P>
<P>
   In a conference call, Richard P. Simon, a managing director and
media analyst at Goldman, Sachs, and Oscar A. Castro, co-manager of
the Montgomery Global Communications fund, sorted out the
investment implications of the latest developments. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Q. (italics)Have these diverse electronic businesses evolved the
way you thought they might in 1992?(end italics) &QL;
</P>
<P>
   SIMON ``Communicopia'' sprang from a conversation I had with
people at Time Warner, when we started talking about things like
band width, twisted pair compression technology and other things
outside my traditional industry framework. I walked away from that
meeting thinking how lost I was, that there was a broad cross
section of knowledge I didn't have.
</P>
<P>
   So a group of us at Goldman set out to write about this thing
without knowing what it was. But as we explored, we realized there
was a significant convergence taking place, and ended up concluding
that cable, not the telephone, is the advantage technology to
deliver information, because of its broad-band capability. The cost
of doing the same thing for telephone companies would be
exceedingly high.
</P>
<P>
   During the mid-1990s, it looked like our conclusion might be
wrong. But things like AT&AMP;T's purchase of TCI and Microsoft's
investment in Comcast illustrate cable's dominance. Of course, back
in the early 1990s, we didn't consider the Internet. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   CASTRO I have no problem with that conceptual construct. Cable
owns the last mile to the consumer. But I am not so enthusiastic
about cable companies as investments, because they don't express
their goals clearly, and until recently did not seem to be
interested in maximizing shareholder value.
</P>
<P>
   But there is no doubt that convergence is happening. The model
is more advanced in Britain and Australia and has been developing
in the same vein in Germany and France. In the United States, we
have not been so quick. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   SIMON Only one of the companies I cover, Time Warner, is a cable
company. But over the last two to three years, they have directly
focused on building shareholder value. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Q. (italics)What difference has the Internet's rise made in the
developing picture?(end italics) &QL;
</P>
<P>
   SIMON The Internet has broadened and enhanced things. It is
taking another product and offering it over the phone lines, but
the advantages of offering it over cable are numerous. For one
thing, it is easier and faster to use.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   Also, the Internet has brought in a lot of players, from
advertisers to content providers to portal creators, that were not
around before. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Q. (italics)Without specialized knowledge, how can investors
spot companies that can best take advantage of convergence?(end
italics) &QL;
</P>
<P>
   CASTRO Investors need to be looking at those companies that have
the right management, ones who have proven they can execute and are
flexible enough to take advantage of opportunities.
</P>
<P>
   Worldcom is an example. These guys were basically second-tier
long-distance providers who moved on to be competitive access
providers and went international. After that they became one of the
largest Internet providers. And now they have MCI, a long-distance
provider with a very strong Internet position. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   SIMON Oscar noted earlier he does not like the News Corp.
because they do not appear interested in maximizing shareholder
value. But Rupert Murdoch has a very clear vision of how to build
global distribution and provide content for those distribution
platforms. He has that with the Fox network here, B Sky B in
Britain and Star TV in the Pacific. He owns a lot of content,
whether it is children's cartoons or the Los Angeles Dodgers, which
makes him less vulnerable than others. He makes big, long-term
bets.
</P>
<P>
   At one of our Communicopia conferences a few years ago, John
Malone from TCI was asked which competitor he most feared and
admired. He said, ``Rupert Murdoch.'' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Q. (italics)Last week MCI Worldcom's name came up in connection
with the battle over Airtouch. Should they be interested?(end
italics) &QL;
</P>
<P>
   CASTRO Well, voice communications is definitely moving to a
wireless world. But Bernie Ebbers has shown no interest yet in a
wireless strategy, and MCI failed to have a clear cellular
strategy, so it is outside their core competence.
</P>
<P>
   On the other hand, when they identify a business they want to
get in to, they buy a company and its management. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Q. (italics)If MCI Worldcom isn't interested, which company,
Vodaphone or Bell Atlantic, does Airtouch fit best with?(end
italics) &QL;
</P>
<P>
   CASTRO The best fit is with Vodaphone. If they got Airtouch,
they would control a big part of the wireless market.
</P>
<P>
   Bell Atlantic bought Nynex and is buying GTE; if it succeeded in
acquiring Airtouch, that could create some digestion problems.
Also, Bell Atlantic does not have one of our favorite management
teams. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Q. (italics)AT&AMP;T made headlines last week with announcements of
a split, a big buyback plan and some new thinking about how to
digest its own recent acquisitions. Is its chief executive, C.
Michael Armstrong, on the right track?(end italics) &QL;
</P>
<P>
   CASTRO Armstrong has definitely established a clear leadership
role at the company, and the pickups of Teleport and TCI have been
very smart acquisitions. Their agreement to merge international
operations with British Telecom surprised a lot of people, but they
could be a formidable competitor internationally. The challenge he
has now is to deliver on the expectations that have been built up
on the Street. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Q. (italics)Which stocks in the world of communicopia do you
like?(end italics) &QL;
</P>
<P>
   SIMON Time Warner and Viacom are two of the stocks I like.
However, they have performed very well and are selling at record
multiples. So to some degree degree they are dependent on positive
developments to push their prices higher. We also like Newscorp,
which traditionally has been undervalued versus other media
companies. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   CASTRO We like Global Telesystems, a European company based in
Virginia, and Colt Telecom, a British company. We also like
Telephonica and Teleitaliana, because they have articulated a clear
international strategy. Airtouch is a company we love, but the
stock is too rich. Orange, another British company, we also like.
And China Telecom.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-01-08-99 2125EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
