u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FBN-FALCONS-MAIN09-CO     01-08 1427
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-FALCONS-MAIN09-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Loss made Birds of feather ...
 &HT;    By Matt Winkeljohn
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ As the Atlanta Falcons slogged to the locker room at
halftime on Sept. 27 in San Francisco, no one could have predicted
the good that lay ahead. Glassy-eyed, battered and bewildered, they
were too busy trying to figure out what had just hit them.
</P>
<P>
   Any notion of winning the NFC West, any notion of facing the
49ers in a huge January playoff game in the Georgia Dome, had been
trampled into the soggy turf at 3Com Stadium, where the 49ers raced
to a 31-7 halftime lead in the rain.
</P>
<P>
   ``My psychiatrist told me I should forget that game,'' running
back Jamal Anderson said. ``Steve Young and Jerry Rice looked like
a video game on us.''
</P>
<P>
   But the Falcons managed to extract something of value from the
muck, pulling to within 31-20 by game's end. In a way, the team's
mindset started to mature under a deluge of big plays by the 49ers.
</P>
<P>
   It was a critical point in a remarkable season in which the
Falcons went 14-2, the offense and defense set a number of records,
Anderson made All-Pro, five Falcons made it to the Pro Bowl and Dan
Reeves was chosen Associated Press Coach of the Year three weeks
after open-heart surgery.
</P>
<P>
   When the 49erse (13-4) visit Atlanta today in the Falcons' first
home playoff game in 18 years, the Falcons will lean on confidence
that has grown steadily since the middle of last season. The
Falcons are 20-4 in that span, the NFL's best mark.
</P>
<P>
   This season, the second half of that game in San Francisco
propelled them.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have never quit,'' Reeves said. ``I didn't think the 49ers'
intensity in the second half was what it was in the first half, but
the way we played in the second half showed a lot to our football
team.''
</P>
<P>
   The Falcons went 12-1 after that game, losing 28-3 to the Jets
in New York, when quarterback Chris Chandler, defensive tackle
Travis Hall and linebacker Henri Crockett were sidelined with
injuries.
</P>
<P>
   The Falcons have won nine consecutive games, tying a franchise
record, and 10 in a row at home, a team best.
</P>
<P>
   But the first 49ers game was the watershed moment, when this
team's greatest intangible revealed itself. The difference in these
Falcons, the players and coaches say, is a special chemistry formed
in the locker room, uncommon in the age of youth and free agency.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think there are a lot of inflated egos on this team,''
Chandler said. The quarterback signed a four-year, $25 million
contract extension two days before the season opener, then passed
for career highs of 3,154 yards, 25 touchdowns and compiled a 100.9
passer rating that ranked fourth in the NFL.
</P>
<P>
   ``Guys try to make each other feel special,'' he said. ``It
might come in forms of joking at each other's expense, but ... we
act more like brothers rather than teammates. That kind of evolved
out of training camp.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think it's becoming more and more rare in professional
sports, especially with guys moving around so much (because of free
agency). Then, when you throw in some guys who think they should
make more money, or their egos are getting bruised _ (but) we
haven't had a lot of that.''
</P>
<P>
   Reeves concedes that some luck was involved in finding 56
players who meshed as these Falcons have.
</P>
<P>
   ``One of the great surprises has been the chemistry of this
team,'' he said earlier this season. ``Certainly, you strive for a
balance of personalities, but there was no way of knowing these
guys would come together quite like they have or that their
relationships with the coaches would be this solid.''
</P>
<P>
   Thirty-nine of 53 active players have joined the team since
Reeves was hired two years ago this month. But just four starters
changed from last season _ free-agent free safety Eugene Robinson;
former reserve defensive tackle Shane Dronett; rookie right
offensive tackle Ephraim Salaam, a seventh-round draft choice; and
wide receiver Tony Martin, acquired in a June trade with San Diego.
</P>
<P>
   Another newcomer helped the Falcons get back on track after the
loss at San Francisco. The next week, rookie Tim Dwight, a
fourth-round draft choice, returned the opening kickoff 93 yards
for a touchdown against Carolina. That play was the first salvo in
a 51-23 blowout of the Panthers.
</P>
<P>
   It helped convince Martin, who went to the Super Bowl with the
Chargers after the 1994 season, that something was up with a team
that had only seven winning seasons in its first 32 years.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was more important for the Falcons to bounce back than it
would be for a team like the 49ers, because they're expected to
bounce back,'' he said. ``We're a team that's been on the downside.
Even before that, though, I always felt this was a special team.''
</P>
<P>
   Atlanta won its next two games, but Chandler was injured in the
first half against New Orleans, and missed the Jets game. He was
replaced by Steve DeBerg, 44, the subject of many age jokes before
the season. DeBerg, who played and coached with Reeves, had retired
after the 1993 season. He looked his age against the Jets, and the
Falcons returned to earth.
</P>
<P>
   But after that, running back Jamal Anderson took control,
rushing for a career-high 172 yards and two touchdowns in a 37-15
victory against the Rams. His finished the season with an
NFL-record 410 carries, and franchise records of 16 touchdowns and
1,846 rushing yards, the ninth-highest total in league history.
</P>
<P>
   Anderson rushed for 100 or more yards in an NFL-best 12 games
behind the blocks of left tackle Bob Whitfield, left guard Calvin
Collins, center Robbie Tobeck, right guard Gene Williams, Salaam,
tight end O.J. Santiago and fullback Bob Christian.
</P>
<P>
   ``(Anderson) can run, catch, block,'' Reeves said. ``He is a
complete football player.''
</P>
<P>
   Just don't ask him to pass. His two wounded ducks the next week
at New England were about the only things that went wrong against
the Patriots. The highlight was defensive end Chuck Smith's 71-yard
return of a Drew Bledsoe fumble caused by left defensive end Lester
Archambeau, as the Falcons won 41-10 and served notice that they
were for real.
</P>
<P>
   They reaffirmed it the next week with a 31-19 victory at home
against the 49ers that put the Falcons alone in first place in the
NFC West.
</P>
<P>
   Two weeks later, at St. Louis, the Falcons won without Chandler,
who was sidelined with an ankle sprain. Second-year quarterback
Tony Graziani started, but was replaced at halftime by DeBerg with
the Falcons leading 3-0.
</P>
<P>
   DeBerg's 27-yard touchdown pass to Mathis in the third quarter
regained the lead for the Falcons. Anderson had 188 rushing yards,
hitting the Rams with a career high for the third time in two
seasons. Most important, the Falcons moved to 4-1 in games Chandler
missed or left with an injury. In 1997, they were 0-6 in such
games.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was good for our football team,'' DeBerg said, ``that our
team could win without Chris.''
</P>
<P>
   The Falcons kept winning, but Christian, a crucial blocker for
Anderson, was lost for the season Dec. 13 with a knee injury during
a 27-17 victory at New Orleans.
</P>
<P>
   After that game, Reeves complained to team internist Charlie
Harrison about chest pains and underwent quadruple bypass surgery
the next day. With defensive coordinator Rich Brooks taking over as
interim coach, the Falcons were all business for the final two
regular-season games.
</P>
<P>
   A 24-17 victory the next Sunday at Detroit clinched the second
NFC West title in team history. The Falcons then returned home and
squashed Miami, an AFC playoff team, 38-16 in the season finale.
</P>
<P>
   Chandler, Anderson, Buchanan, Robinson and Tuggle made the Pro
Bowl, but the overriding theme of 1998 was teamwork.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's no formula you can easily repeat,'' Chandler said.
``For example, bringing Eugene Robinson in _ he fit so well with
Ray and all the guys in the secondary. We just have a lot of fun.''
</P>
<P>
   And most believe the fun began during a reality-check trip to
San Francisco.
</P>
<P>
   ``Historically at 3Com or Candlestick, it just snowballed and
got worse, ending up in a 45-3 blowout or something,'' Anderson
said. ``We were like, 'We can't have this happen to us.' We didn't
come back and win, but we made it close.''
</P>
<P>
   ``At halftime, most of us looked across the field and saw those
guys elated,'' Bennett said. ``We thought, `We're a talented
football team, too, and if we play the way we're capable and trust
each other, we can do something.'''
</P>
<P>
   Like win the West.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
