</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-FALCONS-RESPECT09-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    NFL will pay respect after playoff success
 &HT;    By Len Pasquarelli
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Far from the madding crowd, Arizona Cardinals
offensive tackle Lomas Brown leaned against a wall in the trainer's
room under Texas Stadium on Saturday evening, a silent but amused
witness to the raucous celebration that accompanied the team's
first playoff victory in half a century.
</P>
<P>
   As defensive ends Simeon Rice and Andre Wadsworth slapped
high-fives, wide receiver Eric Metcalf fired up an expensive Cuban
victory cigar and quarterback Jake Plummer performed a
rhythm-challenged Chicken Dance, the 14-year veteran smiled wryly
and shook his head.
</P>
<P>
   ``One of the reasons we won this game (over the Dallas
Cowboys),'' Brown said, ``was because half this team is too young
to realize we weren't supposed to win. Take a guy like Wadsworth,
who was accustomed to always winning in college. He thinks this is
how it's supposed to be. The young players like him came in here
without any preconceived notion of failure. But they'll find out it
takes more than one playoff win to have the 'all that' attitude. In
the playoffs, you earn respect by doing it and then doing it
again.''
</P>
<P>
   That is a league dogma most Atlanta Falcons veterans know, as
the team continues its improbable Super Bowl quest with this
afternoon's rubber match against the San Francisco 49ers. The
Falcons earned a spot this season among the league's elite by
becoming one of only 15 teams to post 14 victories since 1970.
</P>
<P>
   Of those 12 teams that enjoyed 14-victory seasons before 1998 _
when the Falcons, Denver Broncos and Minnesota Vikings joined the
group this year _ only one, the 1986 Chicago Bears, failed to
advance to a conference championship game. Nine of the clubs played
in the Super Bowl, and seven won it.
</P>
<P>
   In a weak NFC West, and even with a more difficult schedule than
they faced in 1998, the Falcons aren't likely to regress in 1999.
An offense based on a power running game and play-action passing,
and a defense that creates turnovers and doesn't surrender the big
play, represents the formula for success in the NFL. Coach Dan
Reeves has said he is building a team for the long haul, and it
appears he has succeeded.
</P>
<P>
   An upset loss today, however, would transform the Falcons
quickly from championship contenders to pretenders.
</P>
<P>
   ``What we've accomplished this year was a big step,'' said
linebacker Cornelius Bennett, one of several veterans who spent
some time this week addressing the younger players about the
intensity of playoff football. ``But we need to keep going.
Anything less than a win (today) would be one step back.''
</P>
<P>
   The last thing the Falcons want in this magical season is to
find out they were simply an overhyped disappearing act. A playoff
victory against the 49ers, still perceived as an elite franchise
despite aging, would answer the few remaining skeptics in the
league.
</P>
<P>
   Reeves is respected around the NFL and his experience in
preparing a team for the playoffs is a huge plus. Even with 20
veterans totaling an aggregate 76 games of postseason experience,
and the presence of Bennett and free safety Eugene Robinson, the
Falcons remain an unknown playoff commodity.
</P>
<P>
   In comparison with the other 14-victory teams since 1970,
Atlanta's rise was meteoric and with much less foundation. Only
five teams since the merger improved by more than the Falcons'
plus-8 from 1997 to this season. Of the 14-victory teams, only the
Redskins of 1983 can approximate Atlanta's speedy ascent. Eleven of
the teams had double-digit victories the season before they notched
14.
</P>
<P>
   ``But no one around here,'' tailback Jamal Anderson said,
``feels what we accomplished is a fluke. If there's still anyone
out there who thinks it was, we can take care of that in the
playoffs. That's where you want to demonstrate your staying
power.''
</P>
<P>
   Former Falcons defensive end Tim Green, an NFL analyst for Fox,
said, ``It would be tough for them to undo all the good, but a
(playoff) loss at this point (would make) the people who were
turned onto them locally this year climb back on the fence again.''
</P>
<P>
   The history of the NFL is full of teams that turned out to be
one-year wonders.
</P>
<P>
   The highlight of Bobby Ross' professional football resume is
taking San Diego to Super Bowl XXIX in 1994. But the Chargers were
a .500 team the next two seasons, and Ross was dismissed.
</P>
<P>
   In just their fourth season of existence, the Tampa Bay
Buccaneers went to the 1979 NFC Championship Game and lost 9-0 to
the Los Angeles Rams. The Bucs, 10-6 during that dizzying season,
then qualified for the playoffs twice in the next 17 years and had
a league-record stretch of a dozen seasons with double-digit
defeats. ``That we went to the (conference) championship game ...
was like some asterisk in the history of the team,'' said Grambling
coach Doug Williams, the Bucs quarterback in '79. ``We became the
best example of 'What have you done for me lately?' in the
league.''
</P>
<P>
   This year, even though Minnesota enters the playoffs with the
best record and is the NFC favorite to go to the Super Bowl, coach
Dennis Green knows that a loss to Arizona will expunge the Vikings'
15 victories.
</P>
<P>
   Green took the Vikings to the playoffs in five of the previous
six seasons and won the NFC Central in 1992 and '94. But Minnesota
is just 1-5 in the playoffs during that stretch. In both years that
they won division titles, they were knocked out in the wild-card
round.
</P>
<P>
   ``Until you do it, the people have a right to question you,''
Green said. ``Our 15 wins aren't going to scare anyone at this
point. We're starting again from scratch, like everybody else. We
have to re-earn all those stripes.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
