<HEADER>
A5614 &Cx1f; tad-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-ATL-CRIMESTATS09-COX     01-08 0831
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ATL-CRIMESTATS09-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Atlanta police improperly listed hundreds of unsolved crimes,
probe reveals
 &HT;    By Lyda Longa
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ An audit by the Georgia Bureau of Investigation to
determine whether Atlanta police manipulated crime statistics to
reflect a lower crime rate did not reveal any criminal wrongdoing
by the department, but did highlight hundreds of mistakes by
investigators in improperly classifiying unsolved crimes.
</P>
<P>
   Atlanta Police Chief Beverly Harvard defended her department
Friday afternoon, saying the number of reports questioned by GBI
and FBI auditors is insignificant in light of the thousands of
crimes reported during the period the study focused on.
</P>
<P>
   ``The report clearly vindicates the police department and the
city in the face of these clearly irresponsible allegations,''
Harvard said. ``All along we knew there were some problems, but the
allegations were that there was a 'gross' underrepoprting of crime.
And the audit clearly disputes that.''
</P>
<P>
   Harvard referred to allegations leveled at department brass in
1997 by then-Deputy Chief Louis Arcangeli. In a series of
strongly-worded memos, Arcangeli alleged that Harvard and deputy
chiefs Bobby Rocker and Carter Jackson pressured officers and
investigators to reclassify some violent crimes to lesser crimes
and to improperly classify unsolved crimes as baseless reports.
</P>
<P>
   The report was conducted by 13 auditors from the Georgia Crime
Information Center, the agency that compiles crime statistics from
the state's law enforcement agencies. The GBI said the audit was
never intended as a criminal investigation, but a ``narrowly
focused effort to determine whether Atlanta police was in
compliance with federal crime reporting guidelines.''
</P>
<P>
   The probe shows that especially in the category of robberies,
several hundred incidents were left out of the total number of
robberies reported to Atlanta police in 1996.
</P>
<P>
   According to the audit, 498 robberies were incorrectly omitted
from the 5,191 robberies reported to police in 1996. That was more
than half of the 885 robberies that were deemed ``unfounded'' by
investigators. In a series of investigative hearings held by the
city's Public Safety Committee in May, Arcangeli told committee
members that he believed roughly 500 robberies had been incorrectly
omitted from the grand total.
</P>
<P>
   Omissions by investigators in the categories of rape and motor
vehicle theft _ the other two crimes highlighted by the audit _
were lower, however.
</P>
<P>
   Of 10,790 motor vehicle thefts reported to police in 1996,
investigators incorrectly ommitted 108. Of 553 rapes reported to
police in 1996, investigators incorrectly omitted 56 from that
total.
</P>
<P>
   GBI and FBI auditors also highlighted these findings:
</P>
<P>
   _ ``Homelsss victims cases were unfounded due to the fact the
investigator could not locate them.''
</P>
<P>
   _ Rape cases were unfounded when the victim refused to
cooperate. Several attempts were made by the investigator to to
talk with the victim, however, because the victim never showed up,
or failed to contact the investigator, the case was not placed in
an ``inactive status.'' If the victim refuses to cooperate, the
case is not to be unfounded.
</P>
<P>
   _ Regarding car thefts, incident reports indicate that vehicles
reported stolen and recovered in the same day were improperly
discounted.
</P>
<P>
   Harvard said she would immediately implement recommendations for
further training for investigators to overcome the problem with the
improper reports. She also agreed to further audits by the GBI and
the FBI.
</P>
<P>
   ``The report vindicates our police department and confirms what
we already knew _ that crime is down because the men and women who
wear blue have worked hard to make community policing a reality,''
Mayor Bill Campbell said in a written statement Friday.
</P>
<P>
   City Council President Robb Pitts was less supportive. ''I would
reserve judgement on that until I have a chance to read it myself
because I don't know how extensive the investigation was that was
conducted by the GBI, and whether or not they talked to Arcangeli
and others in the department that have indicated that there are
problems.''
</P>
<P>
   Arcangeli, who has since been demoted to captain, showed up for
Harvard's press conference, but was escorted out before the results
of the audit were released. He said he has not received a copy of
the report and would not comment on it until then.
</P>
<P>
   The city council public safety committee, meanwhile, still
hasn't released a report of its findings that resulted from the
June hearings.
</P>
<P>
   Councilman C.T. Martin, chairman of committee, said Friday the
report may be ready by the group's meeting Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   He said the committee will have to review the report and decide
``whether everybody's in agreement with its recommendations.''
</P>
<P>
   Staff Writer Carlos Campos contributed to this report.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
