<HEADER>
A5615 &Cx1f; taf-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FBN-49ERS-FALCONS-NYT     01-08 0637
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-49ERS-FALCONS-NYT </SLUG>
 
DESTINY AND FALCONS CONFRONT 49ers 
(bl) 
By THOMAS GEORGE   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   After San Francisco had sent Green Bay tumbling in a wild-card
playoff thriller last Sunday, the 49ers hugged and celebrated and
then quickly turned to the next task _ the Atlanta Falcons.
</P>
<P>
   Or, as 49ers cornerback Marquez Pope put it, ``Going down there
to Atlanta to get us some dirty bird.''
</P>
<P>
   As soon as the Falcons saw receiver Terrell Owens leap and grab
Steve Young's pass to miraculously beat the Packers, 30-27, with
three seconds left, the Falcons knew, too. Destiny was calling.
</P>
<P>
   ``Us and San Francisco _ I guess it was just meant to be,''
Falcons running back Jamal Anderson said. ``We kind of knew it
would be us and them.''
</P>
<P>
   The Falcons and 49ers play Saturday afternoon for the third time
this season, with this meeting before more than 71,000 fans in the
Georgia Dome being the one that matters most. The winner advances
to the National Football Conference championship game. The winner
is one victory away from playing in Super Bowl XXXIII.
</P>
<P>
   It will be an emotional game for the 49ers.
</P>
<P>
   They are longtime rivals with the Falcons in the NFC West. The
49ers saw the Falcons rule the division this season with a 14-2
record and earn a bye in the first round of the playoffs. Though
San Francisco beat the Falcons at home, 31-20, Atlanta won on its
field, 31-19, and the 49ers finished with a 12-4 record and entered
the playoffs as a wild card.
</P>
<P>
   Before playing Green Bay, the 49ers were anxious. Green Bay had
had much success against them, and the future of the 49ers'
coaching staff looked in jeopardy.
</P>
<P>
   Now the 49ers are soaring in confidence. Their victory over
Green Bay gave them reason to believe that this is meant to be a
special season for them. As in going to the Super Bowl. And,
certainly, the 49ers want to show Atlanta who remains king in their
series, in which San Francisco has won eight of the last 11 games.
</P>
<P>
   But it also will be an emotional game for the Falcons.
</P>
<P>
   They have set so many franchise records this season that their
fans can hardly keep count. This is the most successful Falcons
team ever, it has won nine straight and it is 8-0 in the Georgia
Dome this season, where it has 10 straight victories. The Falcons
have enjoyed plenty of fun this year, scoring touchdowns and then
offering a dance called the dirty bird _ with players flapping
their arms like birds flapping their wings.
</P>
<P>
   It is a great emotional release for the Falcons after so many
years of frustration. But their greatest emotion will be having Dan
Reeves, their head coach, back with them.
</P>
<P>
   On Dec. 14, Reeves underwent quadruple heart bypass surgery. He
was expected to miss the final two regular-season games and
possibly the playoffs. Then that was upgraded to a possibility that
he could attend this playoff game, but remain upstairs in a booth.
Now Reeves will be on the sideline, though in a reduced role. But
on the sideline nonetheless.
</P>
<P>
   Quite a recovery in less than a month.
</P>
<P>
   Reeves has worked wonders on the Falcons since becoming their
coach last season. They were a 3-13 team in 1996, but have won 20
of their last 24 games. No NFL team has done better during that
span.
</P>
<P>
   Watch the running of the 49ers' Garrison Hearst (1,570 rushing
yards) and the Falcons' Anderson (1,846 rushing yards). Anderson is
the better pass catcher out of the backfield, and that will likely
be what separates their performances.
</P>
<P>
   And will the 49ers' defense match the Falcons'? Atlanta is tops
among the remaining playoff teams in rushing defense (allowing an
average of only 75.2 yards per game compared with San Francisco's
100.6 yards). This Falcons defense also set a club record by
scoring six defensive touchdowns.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
