<HEADER>
A5616 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-GA-SCHOOL-SHOOTING-AR     01-08 0348
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GA-SCHOOL-SHOOTING-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TEEN-AGERS WHO FEARED BREAKUP ARE FOUND SHOT 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: Locator map is being sent to NYT graphic clients.
Non-subscribers can make individual purchase by calling (888)
603-1036 or (888) 346-9867.) 
(lb) 
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   CARROLLTON, Ga. _ A 15-year-old girl was found shot to death in
a high school restroom here and the 17-year-old boyfriend whom she
had apparently been forbidden to see was seriously wounded.
</P>
<P>
   The authorities are trying to determine whether the two shot
themselves or whether the boy, Jeff Miller, 17, shot Andrea
Garrett, Sheriff Tony Reeves of Carroll County said.
</P>
<P>
   The sheriff said the weapon was a .22-caliber pistol that had
been taken from a safe in the Garrett home. A key had been used to
open the safe.
</P>
<P>
   The teen-agers, who were shot in the head, were found about 9
a.m. Friday by a custodian in the girls' restroom at Central
Carrollton County High School. Miller was taken by helicopter from
this town of 16,700 people, about 50 miles west of Atlanta, to
Crawford Long Hospital in Atlanta, where he was in intensive care
Friday night.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Garrett had said her parents had told her to stop seeing
Miller, friends of the two said.
</P>
<P>
   ``They told everybody if they couldn't be together, they were
going to kill themselves,'' said Pam Frasure, 17, a friend of Ms.
Garrett. ``She told me that. She was crying yesterday. We all
thought she didn't mean it.''
</P>
<P>
   A crowd of parents rushed to the school after hearing of the
shooting, and about half of the 1,050 students were allowed to go
home. More than 35 counselors were on the scene to help grieving
students.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Garrett was a good student and played the clarinet in the
band, school officials said.
</P>
<P>
   ``She was nice and she was very smart,'' Ms. Frasure said.
</P>
<P>
   Miller, who worked as a dishwasher at a local nightclub, was
known for his sense of humor.
</P>
<P>
   ``No matter how bad you felt, he could make you laugh,'' said
Holly King, 16, a sophomore at Central High. ``He was always
kidding, a funny person.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
