<SLUG> BC-INTERNET-STOCK-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SURGING INTERNET STOCK'S TRADING HALTED FOR A TIME
</HEADLINE>
 
(ATTN: Texas) (bl) 
By JERI CLAUSING   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   In the latest twist on highflying Internet stocks, the Nasdaq
exchange Friday temporarily halted trading of Broadcast.com, a
Dallas-based Internet company, after a more than 70 percent jump in
the price of its shares _ then allowed trading to resume even
though the company declined to comment on what might have caused
the surge.
</P>
<P>
   ``They basically said that they don't comment on unusual market
activity, and we didn't see any information out there, so we
resumed trading,'' said Mike Shokouhi, a Nasdaq spokesman.
</P>
<P>
   The company also declined to comment when reached by a reporter.
</P>
<P>
   Although several analysts said it was unusual for an exchange to
accept a no-comment response from a company, Shokouhi said: ``We
basically let the markets do what they do. And you know, it seems
like it's a brave new world with these Internet stocks.''
</P>
<P>
   Nasdaq halted trading on Broadcast.com stock at 11:51 a.m. after
the stock surged as high as $230.50 for no apparent reason after
opening at $131, Shokouhi said. When trading resumed at 1:20 p.m.,
it fell as low as $175 but closed at $197.50, up $65.50. In all,
2.7 million shares changed hands _ most in lots of between 100 and
500 shares, indicating the kind of retail buyers who have been
fueling the meteoric rise in Internet stocks.
</P>
<P>
   The frenzy caused some transaction delays, with one trader
reporting canceling an order after waiting 10 minutes for a sell
order, during which the price dropped 17 points.
</P>
<P>
   The wild ride capped another week of astronomical gains by
Internet stocks and preceded a meeting called for Monday by the
National Association of Securities Dealers, Nasdaq's board, with
securities firms to discuss market volatility in technology stocks,
some of which have recently seen 50-point daily swings.
</P>
<P>
   Kathy Smith, an analyst with Renaissance Capital Corp. who
follows Broadcast.com, said: ``The market is crazy over the
Internet. But that's a pretty amazing leap in value, so it must be
related to something. It's beyond anything the Internet is
producing.''
</P>
<P>
   As for Nasdaq's resumption of trading after the company's
refusal to comment, Ms. Smith said, ``That makes it all the more
interesting.''
</P>
<P>
   Broadcast.com, which has about 250 employees, transmits over the
World Wide Web sound and video of events ranging from sports and
news to corporate shareholder meetings.
</P>
<P>
   Among other popular Internet stocks that posted $30 gains Friday
were Amazon.com, CGI Group, Yahoo and Geocities. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
