</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BOX-JONES-FRAZIER-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
POLICEMAN HOPES TO BEAT WORLD BOXING CHAMP
</HEADLINE>
 (bl) 
By TIMOTHY W. SMITH   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   PENSACOLA, Fla. _ Richard Frazier, a New York City police
officer in the 26th Precinct, is way out of his jurisdiction down
here in this Gulf Coast town. And some would argue that he is also
way of out his league, challenging Roy Jones Jr., arguably the best
boxer in the sport, for Jones' World Boxing Council and World
Boxing Association light heavyweight titles.
</P>
<P>
   Frazier understands the skepticism. ``I'm a cop,'' he said. ``I
don't believe too much.''
</P>
<P>
   If Frazier were not the one fighting Jones, who turns 30 on Jan.
16, he would find it unbelievable that he is the No. 1 contender
and in this position. Although he was a very good amateur boxer,
winning three Golden Gloves championships, there is nothing on his
professional boxing resume that would indicate that Frazier should
be here. He has only seven knockouts on his 18-3-1 record. His most
noteworthy opponent was William Guthrie, a former light heavyweight
champion who knocked Frazier out in the sixth round.
</P>
<P>
   Frazier will probably suffer the same fate against Jones (38-1)
in a scheduled 12-round bout that will be broadcast on HBO at 10
p.m. as part of its ``Championship Boxing'' series.
</P>
<P>
   On the undercard, Shane Mosley (30-0, 28 knockouts), the
International Boxing Federation lightweight champion, will defend
his title against Golden Johnson (15-2-2), a former short order
cook. With the vocations of Frazier and Johnson in mind, this show
has been billed ``Law and Order.''
</P>
<P>
   Frazier said his resume was light on quality opponents because
all of the good boxers pulled out of bouts before signing
contracts. Grant Phillips, Frazier's manager, said at one time or
another that they had agreements with Michael Nunn, Lou Del Valle,
Merqui Sosa and Dario Matteoni, but they all backed out.
</P>
<P>
   Murad Muhammad, Jones' promoter, made light of that.
</P>
<P>
   ``All these guys pulling out on you, you're a monster,''
Muhammad said. ``You'll have to prove it Saturday night.''
</P>
<P>
   Frazier is in this position because Phillips and his promoter,
Don King, know how to work the ratings systems of the various
boxing organizations. Frazier benefits because this will be his
biggest payday. His previous high was $12,000, and he will earn
$350,000 for this bout. It is a pittance compared to the $3.6
million that Jones will earn for the bout.
</P>
<P>
   ``People travel long and far for a lottery ticket,'' Muhammad
said.
</P>
<P>
   Before he turned pro, Frazier was a very good amateur boxer. In
May 1991, a week before he was to accompany a group of amateur
boxers to a meet in Russia, Frazier became embroiled in the
controversial death of a Haitian street artist in Greenwich
Village.
</P>
<P>
   Frazier, who was off duty at the time, and some of his friends
got into an argument with the man, Grady Alexis. During the
confrontation, Alexis was punched in the head and died at the
scene. Frazier and another man, Terry Presley, were indicted on
third-degree assault charges, although witnesses gave police
conflicting reports of what happened. The charges against Frazier
were later dismissed twice, and he never faced administrative
charges by the Police Department. Presley, who was a student at the
John Jay School of Criminal Justice at the time, was convicted and
served weekends in jail for four months.
</P>
<P>
   Frazier still walks a beat on 126th Street between Amsterdam
Avenue and Broadway. ``I'm a cop, so no one has ever taken me
seriously as a boxer,'' Frazier said. ``It's as if you have to be a
street bum to be a good boxer. I have a dual career. I'm a boxer
who just happens to be a cop.''
</P>
<P>
   Frazier, 39, said he had not had any special privileges for this
bout. He trains in his spare time and has taken vacation time to
prepare for Jones. He sparred 50 rounds with Bernard Hopkins, the
IBF middleweight champion. And since this bout was announced, his
fellow officers in his precinct have been giving him extra ribbing.
</P>
<P>
   They have probably been tougher on Frazier than Jones will be.
His latest modus operandi is that he takes it easy on opponents
that he likes. And he likes Frazier. Jones had to be admonished by
the referee to box in his last bout against Otis Grant, after he
got Grant in trouble.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
