<SLUG> BC-FBN-JETS-JAGS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BAD WEATHER? NOT FOR THE JETS
</HEADLINE>
 (bl) 
c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   HEMPSTEAD, N.Y. _ The New York Jets take a six-game winning
streak into their first playoff game in seven years on Sunday, when
they face the Jacksonville Jaguars. And Sunday's weather forecast
for Giants Stadium _ temperatures in the mid-20s to the very low
30s, with gusty winds _ seems to be just what Jets coach Bill
Parcells was looking for.
</P>
<P>
   It was 70 degrees Friday in Jacksonville, Fla., good for
practicing pass plays but not for getting ready for a game in which
the wind chill is expected to hover near zero. So suddenly, but not
surprisingly, the weather is looming as a factor in this
second-round game.
</P>
<P>
   The Jets, with a coach who relishes hard-nosed, wintry football,
already have what they refer to as their ``cold-weather'' plan.
That probably means an increased emphasis on the run and a shorter
passing game.  &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
