Tele-Communications, Inc. (TCI) in June. Armstrong led AT&AMP;T towards
diversification into cable television systems and programming by
acquiring TCI. (Ozier Muhammad/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT24) WASHINGTON -- Jan. 8, 1999 -- RELIGION-COLUMN, 1-8 --
Rev. Philip Wogaman at the Foundry United Methodist Church where
President Clinton and his family attend services. Wogaman, the
church pastor, has defended Clinton vigorously. Now he has written
``From the Eye of the Storm'' subtitled ``A Pastor to the President
Speaks Out.'' (Paul Hosefros/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT23) NEW YORK -- Jan. 8, 1999 --NY-READING-TEST, 1-8 --
Robert Trinidad works on a practice exam at a public school in
Manhattan's Upper West Side on Friday. New York State's new
fourth-grade English exam, known in elementary schools simply as
``The Test,'' will be given for the first time next week. Unlike
other standardized tests, this one requires students to take notes
on passages and write critiques along with personal essays based on
what they heard. (Ruby Washington/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT22) GALVESTON, Texas -- Jan. 8, 1999 -- MUSSOLINI-BOAT-HNS,
1-8 -- The 120-foot yacht once owned by Italian dictator Benito
Mussolini is docked on the waterfront of this island resort city
about 50 miles southeast of downtown Houston. In another
incarnation, the boat had a role in the 1968 children's movie
``Chitty Chitty Bang Bang.'' Now the ship is being prepared as a
floating bed-and-breakfast inn. (Houston Chronicle Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT21) CARROLLTON, Ga. -- Jan. 8, 1999 -- GA-SCHOOL-SHOOTING,
1-8 -- John Noland consoles his 16-year old daughter Amanda Noland
outside Central High School after a shooting on Friday. A student
was seriously injured and another died after in an apparent double
suicide attempt shortly after the school day started. (John
Spink/New York Times Photo) *LITE
</P>
<P>
   (NYT20) UNDATED -- Jan. 8, 1999 -- IMPEACH-CANING, 1-8 -- Sen.
Christopher Dodd (D-Conn.), talks to reporters after a rare joint
caucus in the Old Senate Chamber on Friday. Appealing for a sense
of harmony among his colleagues, who met on how to proceede with
the trial of President Clinton, Dodd urged senators to avoid a
civil war by reminding them that the Old Senate Chamber was the
site in the 1850s of the slavery-related caning of Sen. Charles
Sumner of Massachusetts by Rep. Preston Brooks of South Carolina.
(Lonnie Schlein/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT19) WASHINGTON -- Jan. 8, 1999 -- IMPEACH-6, 1-8 -- Senators
speak to reporters after reaching agreement on how to proceed in
the trial of President Clinton on Friday. At top, Democratic
senators from left are: Senate Minority Leader Tom Daschle, Sens.
Joe Biden, Joe Lieberman, Paul Sarbanes, Ted Kennedy and Patrick
Leahy. At bottom from left are: Sen. Phil Gramm, Senate Majority
Leader Trent Lott, Sens. Slade Gorton and Don Nickles. (Stephen
Crowley/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT18) WASHINGTON -- Jan. 8, 1999 -- IMPEACH-5, 1-8 --
Television crews outside the White House on Friday just after the
summons on President Clinton's impeachment trial was delivered.
Senators reached general agreement on Friday on how to proceed with
the trial following a rare joint caucus. (Paul Hosefros/New York
Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT17) WASHINGTON -- Jan. 8, 1999 -- IMPEACH-4, 1-8 -- Sens.
Ted Kennedy and Phil Gramm leave the Senate floor after voting on
an agreement named after them on how to proceed with the trial of
President Clinton. Following a rare joint caucus in the Old Senate
Chamber on Friday the Kennedy-Gramm agreement was approved by a
majority of senators. (Stephen Crowley/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT16) WASHINGTONVILLE, N.Y. -- Jan. 8, 1999 --
WINERY-FIRE-FLOATER , 1-8 -- The Grand Banquet Hall is seen
destroyed by fire on Friday at the Brotherhood Winery. Two
buildings at the 159-year old winery, the nationUs oldest, were
destroyed by a fire which started Thursday night. Founded in 1839,
The Brotherhood Winery has operated continuously because
sacramental wine production kept it open during Prohibition.
(Suzanne DeChillo/New York Times Photo) *LITE
</P>
<P>
   (NYT15) DETROIT -- Jan. 8, 1999 -- CAR-SMART-SHOW-4, 1-8 -- The
Chrysler PT Cruiser at the North American International Auto Show
in Detroit. Robert J. Eaton, chairman of DaimlerChrysler, calls the
Chrysler PT Cruiser - a high-roofed small sedan with minivan-style
cargo flexibility and a profile out of the 1930s - a
``segment-breaker too cool to categorize.'' The car will go on sale
in about a year, starting below $20,000. (Peter Yates/New York
Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT14) DETROIT -- Jan. 8, 1999 -- CAR-SMART-SHOW-3, 1-8 -- The
(My) Mercury at the North American International Auto Show in
Detroit. J. Mays, Ford's vice president for design, calls the (My)
Mercury, a concept vehicle ``that blurs the boundaries between a
car, a truck and a sport-utility vehicle. (Peter Yates/New York
Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT13) DETROIT -- Jan. 8, 1999 -- CAR-SMART-SHOW-2, 1-8 -- The
Hyundai Santa Fe - one of the vehicles making their debuts here
last week at the North American International Auto Show in Detroit,
either as products soon to be sold, as prototypes of future
offerings, or as design studies that may - or may not - find their
way into showrooms in some modified form. (Peter Yates/New York
Times Photo) *LITE
</P>
<P>
   (NYT12) DETROIT -- Jan. 8, 1999 -- CAR-SMART-SHOW-1, 1-8 -- The
Mercedes Vision SLR at the North American International Auto Show
in Detroit. The car is a design study for a high-style,
super-high-performance sports car that draws on the Formula One
look. (Peter Yates/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT11) WASHINGTON -- Jan. 8, 1999 -- IMPEACH-3, 1-8 -- Senate
Majority Leader Trent Lott walks with his minority counterpart Sen.
Tom Daschle, center, while followed by reporters following a news
conference at the Capitol on Friday. The Senate convened a rare
joint caucus in the Old Senate Chamber on Friday trying to navigate
the details of President Clinton's trial. (Shana Raab/New York
Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT10) NEW YORK -- Jan. 8, 1999 -- ADV. FOR SUN., JAN. 10 --
REDMAN-SHOPPING, 1-8 -- Attuned to the demands of his own taste,
Joshua Redman, the jazz saxophonist and band leader, says a sense
of relaxed intensity drives his approach to both music and
clothing. ``I might see something appealing, but if there's one
thing about it I don't like, I reject it,'' says Redman, shown with
Ola Itanli, his personal shopper at Prada. ``I'm really, really
picky.'' (Nicole Bengiveno/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT9) WASHINGTON -- Jan. 8, 1999 -- IMPEACH-2, 1-8 -- Senate
Majority Leader Trent Lott speaks to reporters as his minority
counterpart Sen. Tom Daschle looks on Friday. The Senate convened a
rare joint caucus in the Old Senate Chamber trying to navigate the
details of President Clinton's trial. (Paul Hosefros/New York Times
Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT8) OLDSMAR, Fla. -- Jan. 8, 1999 -- ADV. FOR SUN., JAN. 10
-- RUSSIAN-ICEDANCER, 1-8 -- Debbie Koegel and her Russian partner,
Oleg Fediukov, took second place last month in a competition in
Florida. Debbie's mother, Susan Clayman, says she and her husband,
Martin Clayman, pay most of the $60,000 in training and living
expenses for the couple. ``Oleg is not paid to skate with my
daughter,'' says Mrs. Clayman. ``Oleg wants to skate with my
daughter.'' (Gary Rothstein/New York Times Photo) *LITE
</P>
<P>
   (NYT7) WASHINGTON -- Jan. 8, 1999 -- IMPEACH-1, 1-8 -- From
left: Sens. Patrick Leahy (D-Vt.), Robert Byrd (D-W.Va.) and John
Warner (R-Va.), leave a joint caucus on Friday. The Senate convened
a rare joint caucus in the Old Senate Chamber, trying to navigate
the details of President Clinton's trial. (Lonnie Schlein/New York
Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT6) NEW YORK -- Jan. 8, 1999 -- ADV. FOR SUN., JAN. 10 --
BIZ-HEALTHCARE, 1-8 -- Carol Levine and her husband, Howard, who
was severly injuried in an auto accident, are among those who would
benefit from a $1,000 a year tax credit proposed by President
Clinton last week for long-term health care costs. ``The tax credit
will be a welcome benefit, a tangible benefit, for many people,''
says Mrs. Levine. (William C. Lopez/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT5) UNDATED -- Jan. 8, 1999 -- ADV. FOR SUN., JAN. 10 --
ABOUT-CARS-FERRARI-2, 1-8 -- Gears in 355 line Ferraris can be
changed with ``up'' and ``down'' paddles near the steering wheel.
Selling Ferraris to Americans is no longer just a matter of
flattering the customers and wearing Armani suits really well. (New
York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT4) UNDATED -- Jan. 8, 1999 -- ADV. FOR SUN., JAN. 10 --
ABOUT-CARS-FERRARI-1, 1-8 -- Ferrari offers its hybrid
transmission, which combines manual and automatic features, on all
models in the 355 line: the B coupe, the TS targa top and the
Spider convertible. While the current models knock-down gorgeous,
they are also far more expensive than the Porsches, and Jaguars
that can be nearly as alluring. (New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT3) NELSONVILLE, Ohio -- Jan. 8, 1998 -- ADV. FOR SUN., JAN.
10 -- WEALTH-GAP-3-COX, 1-8 -- Lauren Oliver is an admissions
counselor at Hocking College, a two-year technical school founded
in 1968 and occupying 1,600 acres in the eastern end of town.
``Good-paying jobs are just hard to find around here,'' she says.
Ms. Oliver, an Ohio University graduate, was working for $7 an hour
at the local newspaper, before getting the offer from Hocking.
(Shannon O'Brien/Cox News Service Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT2) NELSONVILLE, Ohio -- Jan. 8, 1998 -- ADV. FOR SUN., JAN.
10 -- WEALTH-GAP-2-COX, 1-8 -- Charlie Smith, owner of The Coffee
Cup restaurant, moved here with his family from West Virginia in
1968 when he was just a year old. ``We've been forgot,'' says
Smith. ``We're hard-working people, and we should be rewarded.''
Smith, like others, sees the growing gap between the rich and poor
in America. (Shannon O'Brien/Cox News Service Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT1) NELSONVILLE, Ohio -- Jan. 8, 1998 -- ADV. FOR SUN., JAN.
10 -- WEALTH-GAP-1-COX, 1-8 -- The historic passenger coaches of
the Hocking Valley Scenic Railway sit idle in the downtown of
Appalachian foothill community. The railroad won't haul tourists
again until Memorial Day. (Shannon O'Brien/Cox News Service Photo)
</P>
