<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-01-08 21:57 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5638 &Cx1f; tta-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-OLY-BRIBERY-1STLD-WRI     01-08 1164
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-OLY-BRIBERY-1STLD-WRITETHRU-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TWO OLYMPICS ORGANIZERS QUIT IN SALT LAKE CITY 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Eds: Rewrites 2nd to 5th grafs. Adds sentence to end of graf that
begins ``Joklik also ...'' and inserts new graf after this.)  (lb) 
 By JERE LONGMAN   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   SALT LAKE CITY _ The top two local organizers of the 2002 Winter
Olympics resigned Friday as new details continued to emerge in a
mushrooming bribery scandal.
</P>
<P>
   One of the two, Frank Joklik, resigned under pressure as
president of the Salt Lake Organizing Committee, and Joklik asked
for the resignation of the other, Dave Johnson, the senior vice
president of the committee.
</P>
<P>
   Joklik, 70, has not been linked to the scandal and will remain
in his position until a successor is found.
</P>
<P>
   Joklik, 70, has not been linked to the scandal and will remain
in his position until a successor is found. The pressure came from
Gov. Mike Leavitt of Utah, a member of the board of trustees of the
Salt Lake Organizing Committee, and U.S. Olympic officials, who
were concerned about public embarrassment and about wavering
confidence by corporate sponsors.
</P>
<P>
   He acknowledged that the Salt Lake City bid committee had paid
housing, travel and education expenses to relatives of members of
the International Olympic Committee; had provided expensive gifts
to IOC members; had provided free health care to IOC members and
their families; had aided an IOC member in a profitable Utah land
deal; and had made direct cash payments _ apparently exceeding
$70,000 in one case _ to ``a number'' of IOC members and their
families.
</P>
<P>
   Investigators said Thursday that the payments had been made to
IOC members from Africa and Latin America. Speaking on the
condition of anonymity, investigators said Friday that Jean-Claude
Ganga, an IOC member from Congo Republic, had received a series of
payments totaling about $70,000, in a period leading up to the June
1995 vote in which Salt Lake City won the 2002 Winter Games.
</P>
<P>
   The investigators said that there did not appear to be any
justification for the payments, but that they were still being
examined. Efforts to reach Ganga on Friday and in recent weeks were
unsuccessful.
</P>
<P>
   Joklik also announced Friday that a monthly $10,000 consulting
fee paid to the former president of the Salt Lake City organizing
committee, Tom Welch, would be discontinued. Welch headed the bid
committee that secured the Games, but resigned his Olympic position
in 1997 after pleading no contest to a misdemeanor charge of
spousal battery. Welch and Johnson were the two most visible
members of the bid committee.
</P>
<P>
   Two other employees of the local organizing committee took
administrative leave pending the outcome of the inquiry: Kelly
Flint, senior vice president for marketing and legal affairs, and
Rod Hamson, the licensing director, who worked as finance director
of the bid committee.
</P>
<P>
   While an international search will be conducted for Joklik's
replacement, some of the potential candidates being mentioned here
include Dave Checketts, the chief executive officer of Madison
Square Garden and a native of Utah whose name surfaced as a
possible replacement for Welch in 1997; Jon Huntsman Jr., vice
chairman of Huntsman Chemical Corp.; Bill Marriott of Marriott
Corp.; Brent Scowcroft, the former national security adviser to
President Bush; David Gardner, former president of the University
of Utah; and Henry Marsh, a former Olympic steeplechaser.
</P>
<P>
   Anita DeFrantz, one of two members of the IOC from the United
States, said here Friday that some IOC members involved in the Salt
Lake City scandal would be asked to resign at a meeting Jan. 23 and
24 at IOC headquarters in Lausanne, Switzerland. The IOC also
reiterated Friday that it would not take the 2002 Winter Games away
from Salt Lake City.
</P>
<P>
   Asked if any IOC heads would roll, DeFrantz said, ``I don't
think we will have executions, but we will have fewer members.'' It
was the strongest indication yet from the IOC that some of its 114
members would be pressured to relinquish their positions.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are a few individuals who have abused their privilege,''
DeFrantz said. ``We must have them removed from the Olympic
movement.''
</P>
<P>
   One who has come under scrutiny is Ganga, 64, who holds
influence as president of the national Olympic committees of
Africa. According to Olympic officials, the Salt Lake City bid
committee targeted African votes in their attempt to win the Games.
</P>
<P>
   Ganga received free medical treatment for hepatitis in Salt Lake
City during the bid process, and profited in a land deal arranged
by Bennie Smith Jr., a member of the bid committee, several months
after the Games were awarded to Salt Lake City, investigators have
said.
</P>
<P>
   Ganga has long been a controversial figure in the Olympic
movement as one of the organizers of the African boycott of the
1976 Summer Games in Montreal. A former ambassador to China, he is
currently Congo Republic's minister for tourism, sports and
leisure, as well as president of the country's Olympic Committee.
He was recently removed from the IOC's commission on new sources of
financing.
</P>
<P>
   Unless investigators can prove that Ganga received excessive
payments, gifts or services while acting in his official government
capacity, and not as an IOC member, it seems unlikely that Salt
Lake City officials would be subjected to charges of violating the
Corrupt Foreign Practices Act, said Jeffrey Weiner, a Miami
attorney who was formerly president of the national association of
criminal defense lawyers.
</P>
<P>
   Four investigations, including those by an internal Salt Lake
City ethics panel, the USOC, the IOC and the U.S. Justice
Department, are examining vote-buying charges first leveled last
month by Marc Hodler, a senior IOC official from Switzerland.
</P>
<P>
   He said that as many as 25 of the 114 IOC members sold their
votes in recent elections to name Olympic sites. He has also said
that Salt Lake City was a victim of so-called agents who demanded
exorbitant fees for delivering blocs of votes. The report by the
Salt Lake City ethics panel could be made public as early as next
Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   On Friday, Leavitt said that he deplored the misdeeds of the
Salt Lake City bid committee ``and we revolt at being associated
with them.'' He also sternly criticized a ``sinister and dark
corner of corruption'' in the Olympic movement that exists because
of what the governor called a lack of accountability in the IOC.
</P>
<P>
   He called on Juan Antonio Samaranch, president of the IOC, to
institute reforms in the bidding process and to restore the
integrity associated with the five interlocking Olympic rings.
</P>
<P>
   ``We expect the Olympics to move forward in an ethical, honest
way,'' Leavitt said. ``It is clear to us that the mistakes by a few
have very seriously damaged this movement and our Games, and for
that, we have deep regret.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE _ OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   Until Friday, Salt Lake City Olympic officials had acknowledged
only that $400,000 had been spent on tuition assistance and
athletic training programs that benefited 13 people, including six
relatives of IOC members, most from Africa. Officials had defended
the programs as humanitarian assistance, not bribery. Welch had
also said that items such as shotguns and skis had been given to
IOC members, which exceeded a limit of $150 on gifts.
</P>
<P>
   Referring to cash payments and other irregularities acknowledged
on Friday, Joklik said: ``It is clear that these disturbing actions
were taken in an effort to win friends for the bid. It is clear
that they were done in an atmosphere in which at least some IOC
members expected such gifts.''
</P>
<P>
   Joklik said that as a member of the Salt Lake City bid committee
he had been unaware of any improper payments. He said the bid
committee's board of trustees had been screened from such
information and had been assured by auditors that all expenditures
were proper.
</P>
<P>
   ``While I do not believe that anyone promised us a vote in
exchange for our expenditures, nor that our actions influenced the
outcome of the bidding process, a handful of IOC members seem to
have seriously abused our generous impulses and expected _ and
received _ more than they should have been given,'' Joklik said,
reading from a prepared statement.
</P>
<P>
   Joklik said he was ``deeply dismayed'' by the revelations of
recent weeks and felt that it was necessary to resign to give the
organizing committee a chance to make a fresh start with the Games
only three years away.
</P>
<P>
   His resignation was welcomed by the USOC, which still must raise
more than $250 million in a joint marketing effort with Salt Lake
City to achieve the privately-financed budget of $1.45 billion for
the 2002 Winter Games. Corporate sponsors have become jittery in
recent weeks as details of the scandal became public, and US West
even withheld a $5 million sponsorship payment.
</P>
<P>
   Without Friday's resignations to signal to sponsors that the
scandal was being handled quickly and thoroughly, it would have
been ``extremely difficult, perhaps impossible, to raise funds
necessary for these Games,'' said John Krimsky Jr., the USOC's
chief fund-raiser.
</P>
<P>
   While the resignations of Joklik and Johnson, 40, may have
provided relief in a public relations sense, Salt Lake City is now
left without the two people who possess the greatest knowledge in
organizing the 2002 Winter Games.
</P>
<P>
   Fortunately for Joklik's successor, most of the sports
facilities are completed or are well under construction. Major
projects remaining include enclosing the Olympic speed-skating oval
and constructing the 120K hill for ski jumping. All sports
facilities are expected to be completed by November 2000, so they
can be tested in competition long before the Games open on Feb. 8,
2002.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our reputation has been tarnished around the world,'' said
Salt Lake City Mayor Deedee Corradini. ``We will make it right
again.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
