<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-01-08 21:58 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5642 &Cx1f; taf-z
s f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BIZ-PROFILE-BIJUR-ART     01-08 0981
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BIZ-PROFILE-BIJUR-ART-$ADV10-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
KEEPING COOL IN A VERY HOT SEAT 
</HEADLINE>
   (ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchase by calling (888) 603-1036 or (888)
346-9867.)  
 (FOR RELEASE SUNDAY, JAN. 10)  
 (af)  
 By AGIS SALPUKAS   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   HARRISON, N.Y. _ If he had followed his initial inclination,
Peter I. Bijur might be peddling bathroom tissues and paper towels
to supermarkets these days. Fresh out of Columbia Business School
in 1966, he accepted a marketing job at the Scott Paper Co. at
$12,000 a year.
</P>
<P>
   Before he could pack his bags, though, Bijur was persuaded by
the school's dean to have lunch with a recruiter from Texaco Inc.
Texaco offered him a marketing job for only $10,000, but the
recruiter told him the company would give anybody with talent and
drive the chance to move high up the corporate ladder. ``I thought
that was a pretty neat opportunity, and so I turned down the other
job,'' he recalled.
</P>
<P>
   Today, of course, Bijur occupies the ladder's top rung, as
Texaco's chairman and chief executive. But the prospects for
advancement aren't nearly as rosy for ambitious business school
graduates in 1999 as they were in the company's glory days.
</P>
<P>
   Since Bijur took over in July 1996, the price of oil has plunged
from about $19 a barrel to below $13, casting a pall on the
industry. In response, Texaco has gone through a wrenching
reorganization, shedding thousands of jobs. Bijur says he plans
more layoffs as part of a plan to shave $600 million in annual
costs by 2000.
</P>
<P>
   Jobs at the sprawling concrete-and-glass headquarters here have
already been slashed in half, to 900, from the boom days of the
1980s, leaving rows of offices and cubicles empty. And breaking
with the tradition of scheduling holiday parties in local
restaurants for the various corporate divisions, Bijur held a
single _ and relatively inexpensive _ event on Dec. 16 in the
company cafeteria.
</P>
<P>
   With balloons festooning the walls and a Christmas tree, menorah
and Kwanzaa decoration on display, the celebrants stood around
nibbling hors d'oeuvres and sipping drinks. They also watched a
video that tried to raise their spirits by poking fun at the
company and at its boss.
</P>
<P>
   Now, with little fat left to cut, Bijur is coming under pressure
from employees, analysts and shareholders to bolster the company's
fortunes by seeking a merger with another oil giant, along the
lines of British Petroleum-Amoco and Exxon-Mobil. ``People are
asking me all the time: `Well what about you? What are you gonna
do?' '' he said.
</P>
<P>
   For now, he is silent on the subject. But he's proceeding as
though Texaco will remain independent, and for all the job cuts he
has engineered, he says he is determined to keep the lines of
communication open with the company's 20,000 employees. He solicits
e-mail advice from them, and personally answers most of the 30 or
so messages he receives each day. Some missives are sharply worded
_ and his replies can be equally candid.
</P>
<P>
   ``E-mail is the most wonderful thing in the world,'' Bijur said.
He frequents the company cafeteria, he said, because ``I want to
see people in the lunch line; I want to hear what they have to
say.'' One of his favorite meals _ in the cafeteria or anywhere
else _ is hot dogs.
</P>
<P>
   His office, which looks out on wooded hills and Long Island
Sound, is adorned with photographs of his wife, Ann, and their
daughter and two sons. On a coffee table are a catalog of Degas
paintings shown recently at the Metropolitan Museum of Art and a
replica of the Cessna single-engine plane that Bijur flies on
weekends.
</P>
<P>
   One of his first acts after taking over two and a half years ago
was to replace the thick oak doors separating the executive suites
with glass _ a move that some saw as a symbolic break with the
style of his predecessor and mentor, Alfred C. DeCrane Jr.
</P>
<P>
   Three months into his new job, Bijur faced a baptism by fire
with the publication of secretly recorded tapes in which some
Texaco executives made some apparently disparaging remarks about
blacks (one of the most publicized was later found to be innocuous)
and discussed the possible destruction of documents being sought in
a racial-discrimination lawsuit against the company.
</P>
<P>
   To deal with the crisis, he turned the third-floor executive
suite into a war room, where scores of employees ate sandwiches and
pizza late into the night as they planned the company's legal
defense. Texaco settled the discrimination suit out of court in
1997 for $140 million.
</P>
<P>
   ``Most companies would have overreacted and basically gone into
their shell,'' said J. Robinson West, the chairman of the Petroleum
Finance Co., an energy consulting group based in Washington. Bijur,
he added, is ``a guy who took over a company which had lost its
momentum and he's giving it back.''
</P>
<P>
   In a separate dispute, the company agreed last week to pay $3.1
million to 186 women in the largest ``glass ceiling'' settlement
ever reached with the federal Department of Labor.
</P>
<P>
   It hasn't been all smooth sailing with his top executives,
either. In beefing up his management team, he has bruised numerous
egos, bypassing insiders to recruit John J. O'Connor from BHP
Petroleum to oversee exploration, for example, and William M.
Wicker from Credit Suisse First Boston to take charge of corporate
development. ``It's important to go out and get fresh blood,'' he
said.
</P>
<P>
   Bijur says he encourages subordinates to challenge his
decisions, and sometimes makes outlandish proposals in meetings
just to provoke debate. ``I expect confrontation,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   And he relishes digs at the only company he has worked for. A
framed photograph on his office wall shows a Texaco station with a
sign reading ``No Gas'' and an inscription by a Texaco manager:
``Peter, we sense there is a problem here.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
