<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Ohio set for eventful inauguration of Gov.-elect Bob Taft
 &HT;    By Debra Jasper
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   DAYTON, Ohio _ Get ready for the glitter.
</P>
<P>
   Gov.-elect Bob Taft is throwing a three-day bash beginning
starting Sunday to celebrate his inauguration.
</P>
<P>
   The kickoff begins at noon when Taft and lieutenant
governor-elect Maureen O'Connor attend the Ohio Family Celebration
_ a free public event that features a tour and hands-on learning
experience about Ohio government and the office of governor.
</P>
<P>
   The event also will feature two Dayton groups. The Kids Voting
Performing Troupe will perform a skit in the Statehouse atrium
about the importance of voting. And two members of Movin' On, a
Dayton dance group made up of adults with developmental
disabilities, also will perform.
</P>
<P>
   Marcia Miller Holmes, who teaches the dance company, said
Daytonians Kathy Ostermann and Julie Porter will dance to jazz and
then boogie-woogie music.
</P>
<P>
   Performing at the Statehouse will be a real thrill, she said.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think it's great that they've asked for a diversity of
people and we will have that exposure,'' Miller Holmes said.
</P>
<P>
   Later on Sunday, the Motown singing group Mary Wilson and the
Supremes will headline the Ohio Republican Party's Inaugural eve.
</P>
<P>
   The gala is $50 per person and also will feature the Cincinnati
Boychoir and the Richens/Tim Irish Dance Troupe.
</P>
<P>
   Beverly Martin, executive director of the Taft-O'Connor
Inaugural Committee, said all of the events are expected to attract
large crowds. She said so many youths asked to come to the
Celebration of Youth Breakfast on Monday morning, for example, that
the event was moved from a 400-person hall at the Adams Mark hotel
in downtown Columbus to a 1,000-person hall at the downtown
convention center.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're hoping the general public will come and is interested in
being a part of the gubernatorial inauguration,'' Martin said.
``It's a great way to involve the family.''
</P>
<P>
   Of course, not all events are free and open to the public.
</P>
<P>
   After Taft's official swearing-in ceremony Monday afternoon,
Taft and his wife, Hope, will attend various private parties.
</P>
<P>
   One of them, the governor's ball, is a $1,000 per-person,
black-tie affair at the Hyatt on Capital Square.
</P>
<P>
   Those who want to celebrate Taft's election, but aren't eager to
cough up quite so much cash, can make do with the Capitol Ball,
which at $250 per person is billed as ``black-tie optional.''
</P>
<P>
   Others can attend the Buckeye Bash, a $25-per-person, ``business
attire party.''
</P>
<P>
   The final inaugural event will be Tuesday for state employees
who want to join the governor, his wife and O'Connor for a free
boxed lunch.
</P>
<P>
   Privately funded corporations and individuals will pay the tab
for the three-day party, Martin said. Guests at the dances are
being asked to bring children's books that will to be contributed
to schools, she said.
</P>
<P>
   Martin said she expects the events to be fun, but added that
planning so much in such a short time has been hectic.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is like planning a wedding, graduation party and 50th
anniversary party, all rolled into one,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
