<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-EDIT-TRUMP-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EDITORIAL: THE SCALE OF DONALD TRUMP'S DREAMS  (DW)
</HEADLINE>
   c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   The New York Times said in an editorial Saturday, Jan. 9:
</P>
<P>
   The normally loquacious Donald Trump quietly has amassed enough
real estate and air rights to build an 861-foot-high skyscraper
near the United Nations. What he touts as the world's tallest
apartment project is too lanky, even for the architectural mishmash
of Manhattan's East 40s. His bronze-glass monolith, the equivalent
of 90 stories, would dwarf the 39-story U.N. Secretariat and its
waterfront park. The project should be scaled back. But for the
moment, Trump appears well positioned to put his signature on New
York's skyline anew since his project is as-of-right, or not
subject to extensive public review.
</P>
<P>
   The project's legal pedigree does not mean the Giuliani
administration should remain on the sidelines. As-of-right status
shields a project from a full public review of its impact on air,
light and traffic and from assessing wind shear and shadows. But
City Hall may have grounds to scale it back, and the Planning
Commission can forestall a recurrence.
</P>
<P>
   City Hall should review the Buildings Department's approval of
Trump's use of zoning rules that are as tough to decipher as
Sanskrit. The agency found that the way he assembled air rights
across zoning district boundaries fell within a mid-1980s exception
to the ban on such mergers in the city's 1961 zoning code. At issue
is whether Trump merely took maximum advantage of the rules, or
flexed them. It should not require months for the city to review
whether that judgment was reasonable and in line with how
developers operate.
</P>
<P>
   The far thornier task of safeguarding the city's skyline and its
neighborhoods falls to the Planning Commission. It should revise
the antediluvian zoning code to prohibit any developer from
exploiting air rights, plaza bonuses and other zoning tools to
create a structure that does not fit the scale of a neighborhood,
while allowing reasonable use of air rights to save landmarks, help
neighborhoods and promote economic development. Such zoning
decisions must remain the province of city government, not
neighborhoods or developers.
</P>
<P>
   A Trump executive thinks his boss' project will someday be
lauded as a landmark. But Trump's musings suggest an awareness of
the mismatch between the building's scale and the U.N. environs. He
said he believed that, had he boasted about his goal before buying
the site and air rights, zoning would have been altered to stop
him. His intuition should galvanize City Hall and the commission.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
