<SLUG> BC-IMPEACH-1STLD-WRITETHRU-ART-910(2TAKES)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SENATE VOTES TO APPROVE PLAN FOR IMPEACHMENT TRIAL 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Eds: Changes graphics advisory.)  
 (ATTN: Vt., Ky., Conn., N.J., Texas, Mass.)  (See related IMPEACH-CLINTON, IMPEACH-ASSESS, IMPEACH-CAUCUS,
IMPEACH-SCENE, IMPEACH-CANING) 
(ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Graphic showing
impeachment deadlines is being sent to NYT graphic clients.
Non-subscribers can make individual purchase by calling (888)
603-1036 or (888) 346-9867.) 
(lb) 
 By ALISON MITCHELL   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ After an extraordinary bipartisan caucus that
lasted about three hours, the Senate voted unanimously Friday to
approve a plan for President Clinton's impeachment trial that calls
for opening arguments next week and defers a decision on whether to
summon witnesses until later in the month.
</P>
<P>
   The agreement averted further confrontation over rival
Republican and Democratic trial plans that had threatened to send
the Senate into the same partisan spiral as the House. The two
sides had been deeply divided over whether to allow witnesses.
</P>
<P>
   In a brief session presided over by Chief Justice William
Rehnquist late Friday afternoon, the senators approved the plan
they had outlined earlier in the Old Senate Chamber, where the
Senate had met throughout the early 19th century.
</P>
<P>
   An official summons directing Clinton to respond to the two
articles of impeachment against him was delivered to the White
House by James Ziglar, the Senate sergeant-at-arms.
</P>
<P>
   Although some Democrats were wary of the blueprint, many
senators from both parties reveled in institutional pride at
maintaining a conciliatory tone that had eluded the House.
</P>
<P>
   ``You know, we didn't ask for this trial,'' said Sen. Patrick
Leahy, D-Vt. ``We didn't ask for the president to conduct himself
the way he did, and we didn't ask for the House to make a mishmash
of this thing. But all that's happened and now we have to preserve
the Senate and give the country a sense of credibility.''
</P>
<P>
   Sounding the same note, Sen. Mitch McConnell, R-Ky., said: ``I
think there's a feeling in this situation that the Senate is on
trial.''
</P>
<P>
   The White House, in a terse, carefully worded statement, said
Friday afternoon that it respected the Senate's decision. ``In
accordance with the procedures adopted by the Senate, we plan to
present on behalf of the president a vigorous, successful and
complete defense,'' said Gregory Craig, the special White House
counsel, in an appearance in the White House drive shortly after 5.
</P>
<P>
   The White House had hoped that the Senate would settle on an
abbreviated trial without witnesses, confined to the material
submitted by Kenneth Starr, the independent counsel. White House
aides waited anxiously while the senators met privately on Friday,
and some acknowledged disappointment at the procedure that emerged.
</P>
<P>
   But Craig said the White House was confident that the Senate
would move to cut off the proceeding after the opening
presentations, rather than extend the trial and call witnesses.
``We remain hopeful that this matter can be resolved expeditiously
and fairly,'' he said, before turning his back and walking
resolutely away from shouted questions.
</P>
<P>
   Under the Senate plan approved Friday, the trial of Clinton on
charges of perjury and obstruction of justice stemming from his
efforts to hide his affair with Monica Lewinsky would get under way
in earnest on Wednesday with arguments on any procedural pretrial
motions by House prosecutors or White House lawyers.
</P>
<P>
   Beginning the next day, the House has 24 hours to present its
case against the president. Clinton's legal team follows with its
allotted 24 hours. Both sides are precluded from introducing new
evidence unrelated to the impeachment record established in the
House.
</P>
<P>
   Senators then will have 16 hours to question the two sides by
sending written queries to Rehnquist, who will be at the presiding
officer's chair in the front of the chamber.
</P>
<P>
   At that point _ expected to be either Jan. 25 or Jan. 26 _
senators plan to debate and vote on two separate motions, first a
motion to adjourn the trial and next a motion on whether to call
witnesses. Those votes would be simple majority votes.
</P>
<P>
   If witnesses are approved, the House prosecutors or the White
House would question them first in a deposition. Sen. Tom Daschle,
the minority leader, said a second majority vote would be required
to have witnesses testify before the full Senate.
</P>
<P>
   Democrats, who had previously stood adamantly against witnesses,
are taking solace in the fact that witnesses would have to be
approved en bloc, which they believe would discourage the House
from seeking to call too many witnesses. They also anticipate that
the senators _ sitting as jurors under a vow of silence _ will have
a diminishing appetite for witnesses after listening to the House
and White House for two weeks.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's one thing the Senate can't tolerate and that's
remaining quiet for very long,'' said Sen. Christopher Dodd,
D-Conn. ``And the idea they are going to sit there day after day
and listen to House managers and White House counsels, with their
inability to respond, is not going to last very long.''
</P>
<P>
   Rep. Henry Hyde, the leader of the House impeachment managers,
said, ``We intend to use the time we have been provided to present
a compelling case on the serious charges pending against the
president. We also look forward to the opportunity _ with Senate
concurrence _ to call witnesses in support of evidence. The House
managers have said they want to call anywhere from five to 15
witnesses ranging from Ms. Lewinsky to an array of current and
former White House advisers.
</P>
<P>
   The Senate vote brought to an end weeks of uncertainty and
contention over how the first presidential impeachment trial since
1868 should proceed. On Thursday the two sides had scheduled votes
on competing Republican and Democratic plans, but then pulled back.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE _ OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   And so Friday began with a last attempt to reach across party
lines in the ceremonial room that served as the Senate chamber
between 1810 and 1859, when some of the great debates and
confrontations over slavery took place. The chamber was placed
under heavy security. Folding chairs supplemented the permanent
seats to accommodate the senators, whose number was greater than
that of their counterparts in the 19th century.
</P>
<P>
   A few Republicans assured Democrats that despite the House
prosecutors' insistence on witnesses, they too did not want a
sordid discussion of sex to take place in the Senate chamber.
``What was helpful in the room was for the Democrats to learn there
are a whole lot of Republicans who are not anxious to have a bunch
of witnesses either,'' McConnell said.
</P>
<P>
   Some senators said the sense of the history of the room helped
foster an atmosphere where they could come together. ``Every
senator knows the level of oratory and the weight of the issues
discussed here,'' said Sen. Robert Torricelli, D-N.J. ``It helped
all the senators put this in perspective.''
</P>
<P>
   Dodd reminded his colleagues that ``one of the saddest moments
in Senate history'' had taken place in the room _ the caning of
Sen. Charles Sumner of Massachusetts by Preston Brooks of South
Carolina. ``Many historians feel that was when the comity in the
Senate broke down, leading three and a half years later to the
commencement of the Civil War,'' he said later.
</P>
<P>
   According to Sen. Trent Lott, the majority leader, breakthrough
came when an unusual pair _ Edward M. Kennedy, a Massachusetts
liberal, and Phil Gramm, a Texas conservative _ made back-to-back
statements. ``I describe it as the Kennedy-Gramm or the
Gramm-Kennedy proposal,'' Lott told reporters. He then stressed the
bizarre notion of these two ideological opposites working together,
by saying with relish, ``Did you hear what I said?''
</P>
<P>
   Other senators said Gramm pointed out that under Senate
impeachment rules a vote on witnesses could always be demanded by
any party _ there was no way around it. Kennedy agreed that the
Texan was right and started suggesting ways to make the witness
situation more palatable to Democrats.
</P>
<P>
   In the end, it was the Democrats who moved the most, to accept a
proposal much like the one the Republicans had originally drafted.
And some Senate Democrats expressed private annoyance that Kennedy
had been so quick to support Gramm because they thought he gave
away a tactical advantage stemming from the Republicans'
unwillingness to look as partisan as their House counterparts.
</P>
<P>
   One Democrat close to the developments said the White House as
well had been trying to get Democrats to forgo the display of
bipartisanship. But Senate Democrats said they felt they had won
the best deal they could from the majority Republicans. Some also
made clear that they had more allegiance to the Senate as an
institution than to Clinton.
</P>
<P>
   ``Too bad,'' Sen. Joseph Biden, said, when asked about White
House grumbling. ``They have no say.'' He added, ``We're not here
to defend either the White House or the House of Representatives.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
