<DOCNO> NYT19990108.0464 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-01-08 22:09 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5655 &Cx1f; taf-z
u k &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-EDIT-IMPEACH-SENATE-N     01-08 0611
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-EDIT-IMPEACH-SENATE-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EDITORIAL: AT LONG LAST, LEADERSHIP  (DW)
</HEADLINE>
   c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   The New York Times said in an editorial Saturday, Jan. 9: &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Every now and then sanity breaks out, even in Congress. Through
bipartisan effort the Senate has devised something that was missing
in the House, a system for planning and managing the inquiry into
President Clinton's offenses in an orderly way. The essence of the
agreement is that it sets up a multi-vote hurdle to prevent the
wholesale calling of witnesses, and it sternly limits the
fire-breathing House prosecutors to arguing the existing record
developed in that body's Judiciary Committee.
</P>
<P>
   The senators were full of self-congratulation after adopting the
complex rules of procedure, and they had a right to be. What the
Republican Slade Gorton called ``the mighty accomplishment'' on
knitting the Republican right and the Democratic left into unified
agreement was just that. The Senate devised what Sen. Phil Gramm
called ``a road map'' that was designed to lead in a matter of a
few weeks to a preordained destination: the punishing of Clinton
through censure, not removal from office.
</P>
<P>
   What the Democrats and the White House got out of the deal was a
set of formidable firewalls against the possibility of live,
embarrassing testimony about Clinton's sexual activities. As Gramm
explained, the House could propose witnesses only to provide
information that is not already on the record. A motion to call a
witness would be subject to debate, and even if it passed, the
witness would first be deposed in private.
</P>
<P>
   Another vote would be required before a witness could give live
testimony before the Senate. ``We now have a process that will
allow the case to be made without witnesses,'' said Tom Daschle,
the minority leader. The rules do not say that flat-out, of course.
But by building so many hurdles, the Republicans were signaling
strongly that there will probably not be 51 votes for an extended
round of new testimony.
</P>
<P>
   What the Republican majority got out of the deal is a reputation
for judgment not enjoyed by the House GOP. The majority leader,
Trent Lott, obviously decided weeks ago that a long trial would
damage his party and his personal reputation. Using Gorton as a
cat's-paw, he began his caucus toward putting House prosecutors on
a short leash. In a week of smart moves by Lott, the smartest may
have been the avoidance of a partisan vote to impose rules on the
Democrats.
</P>
<P>
   By setting up a format that allows the White House and the
prosecutors a total of 48 hours of opening argument and sets 16
more hours of questions from the floor, Lott has devised a safety
valve. Its value will become clearer as time goes on.
</P>
<P>
   Everyone can let off steam for a few days, and then the Senate
may be in a mood to entertain a motion to bring matters to a
conclusion. That could come through a motion to vote on the
articles of impeachment and then move to a censure resolution, or
through a motion to adjourn the trial and move directly to censure.
Either course would require a simple majority and would show there
are not the 67 votes needed to remove the president.
</P>
<P>
   Unlike so many in the House and at the White House, Lott and his
Democratic counterpart, Daschle, exhibited leadership that rose to
the demands of the occasion. Well-known partisan warriors such as
Gramm and Sen. Ted Kennedy on the Democratic side responded to
their example. As a result, the senators found the proper
legislative response to the situation. That is, they have figured
out a plan for punishing Clinton, rather than themselves or the
nation.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
