<DOCNO> NYT19990108.0470 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-01-08 22:17 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5662 &Cx1f; tta-z
u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-ECON-REPORT-1STLD-WRI     01-08 1138
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ECON-REPORT-1STLD-WRITETHRU-ART-380&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
U.S. JOBS GROWTH CONTINUED IN DECEMBER; UNEMPLOYMENT DOWN TO 4.3
PERCENT
</HEADLINE>
  
 (SUBS 11th graf, beginning: Most economists x x x, to change x x x
rate x x x to x x x annual rate x x x)  (ART ADV: Graphic on December employment is being sent to NYT
graphic clients. Non-subscribers can make individual purchase by
calling (888) 603-1036 or (888) 346-9867.) 
(bl) 
By SYLVIA NASAR   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   Despite an unsettled global economy, lower corporate profits and
a new round of layoffs, the U.S. economy keeps creating jobs at an
astonishing pace.
</P>
<P>
   In December, the number of workers on U.S. payrolls grew by
378,000, the biggest gain in more than a year, the Labor Department
reported Friday. The unemployment rate edged down to 4.3 percent,
matching last April's 28-year low. The unemployment rate for all of
1998 was 4.5 percent.
</P>
<P>
   Other than during 1969, the height of the Vietnam War, the last
time unemployment was this low for any significant period was 1957,
when the first baby boomers were in fifth grade and Dwight
Eisenhower was in the White House.
</P>
<P>
   Some of December's increase was helped by balmy weather in the
North and East, which postponed the construction layoffs usual for
that time of year. Further, a few statistical flukes probably
inflated the figures a bit. But signs of strength were impressive
and widespread, reflecting robust spending by consumers and
homebuyers who account for nearly three-fourths of economic
activity.
</P>
<P>
   ``If the economy is an eight-cylinder car, it's running on
nine,' said David Blitzer, chief economist at the Standard &AMP; Poors
Corp. ``A little may be special factors like weather, but there's a
lot of strength there.''
</P>
<P>
   The job market's strength, which shows that the widely
anticipated economic slowdown has yet to happen, caught forecasters
off guard. After a wave of corporate layoff announcements and a
surge in first-time claims for unemployment insurance in the last
half of December, economists had expected job growth to weaken and
unemployment to edge up. Even President Clinton's chief economic
adviser, Janet Yellin, admitted she is amazed by the economy's
momentum. ``I'm surprised. It's great. It's just extraordinary,''
she said. ``There's no obvious reason we can't continue down this
path.''
</P>
<P>
   The president, speaking in Detroit, took credit for the
economy's performance and for the 93-month old expansion, now the
longest in peacetime though still more than a year shy of the
record set by the 1960s expansion. Clinton called this a time ``of
American renaissance.''
</P>
<P>
   Stock investors celebrated with a market rally that pushed the
Dow Jones average and other key measures to records.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   The December jobs report capped a year in which, contrary to
predictions, net job growth was nearly 3 million, unemployment
hovered between 4.3 and 4.5 percent, wage gains adjusted for
inflation were the best in a generation, and productivity growth
picked up instead of slowing as it usually does as economic
expansions age.
</P>
<P>
   Moreover, some of the most disadvantaged workers have enjoyed
substantial job and pay gains in the past two years. In December,
for example, while the jobless rate for most major demographic
groups was largely unchanged, the unemployment rates for black
workers and teen-agers, typically multiples of the white and adult
rates, dropped sharply. ``We're finally back to the kind of tide
that lifts all boats,'' said Dr. Yellin.
</P>
<P>
   Most economists are still predicting a sharp slowdown in 1999,
starting in the current quarter, although at least one admitted
Friday that there is scant evidence so far. Along with recent data
showing that retail sales, homebuying and car purchases remained
strong through year-end, Friday's jobs report suggests that the
economy may have been expanding at a 4 percent annual rate in the
final quarter of 1998, which is considered exceptionally strong.
</P>
<P>
   Gail Fosler, chief economist at the Conference Board, a private
research organization, said, ``We're going into 1999 with
fundamentals better than in 1998.''
</P>
<P>
   There are good reasons for expecting some moderation of growth,
though. Much of the rest of the world is either in recession or
slowing down. Consumers have been spending much of their income at
an unsustainable rate. Homebuying is at a record pace.
</P>
<P>
   Still, economists say job growth would have to fall below the
rate of 100,000 or so a month for unemployment to start rising.
</P>
<P>
   Factory employment, which fell during most of last year,
declined by another 13,000 jobs. But that's a fraction of the
losses in recent months. Factory employment has fallen by 272,000
jobs since last March, as recessions in Asia and Latin America have
hurt U.S. exports. Despite record car sales, employment in Detroit
is down 12,000 from a year ago. On the other hand, manufacturers of
anything related to the housing market _ from bricks and glass to
furniture and hardware _ continue to thrive and did lots hiring
last month, as they've done all year.
</P>
<P>
   Weather was partly responsible for construction jobs surging by
104,000 last month, the biggest monthly gain since February 1984.
Most of the gains were in outdoor work like highway construction
and roofing as contractors were able to continue working longer
than usual. But construction hiring has been strong all year. With
state treasuries bulging and mortgage rates down to the lowest
level in 30 years, public works and housing are both booming.
</P>
<P>
   The main engine of job growth remained the service economy _
everything from fast food chains to schools _ which added 290,000
jobs. Business services like public relations, consulting and
computing did extensive hiring. Temporary help firms saw the
biggest jump in headcounts since August. With companies and
government agencies scrambling to fix their year 2000
computer-clock problems, hiring by computer services firms was
brisk; jobs in that industry swelled by more than 13 percent in
1998.
</P>
<P>
   Jobs in the retail industry rose by 53,000 in December, bringing
total job gains for the year to nearly one half million.
Restaurants added 33,000 workers. Department stores hired a lot of
extra holiday help. A surge in renovation, building material and
garden supply stores added 9,000 jobs, the biggest increase of the
year. Most services related to the building business expanded
payrolls last year.
</P>
<P>
   The demand for workers is fattening paychecks. Hourly earnings
jumped 5 cents, to $12.98. That is a 3.8 percent gain for the past
year, about the same as in each of the two previous years. Pay is
growing fastest in financial services, mining, services and retail
trade, where workers are in especially short supply.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
