<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-EDIT-BLACK-FARMERS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EDITORIAL: RECOMPENSE FOR BLACK FARMERS  
(DW)
</HEADLINE>
   c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   The New York Times said in an editorial Saturday, Jan. 9: &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The proposed settlement of a class-action lawsuit brought by
black farmers against the U. S. Department of Agriculture for
racial discrimination in farm loans probably will not curb the
decline of independent black farmers, who now account for only 1
percent of the farming force. But it provides some redress to many
who have had their livelihoods destroyed by illegal practices.
</P>
<P>
   The 1997 lawsuit was filed on behalf of more than 1,000 black
farmers. Under the settlement, farmers who can produce some
evidence that they suffered discrimination in the loan programs
between 1981 and 1997 would receive $50,000 tax-free and be
forgiven their federal farm debts. Those who can document with
precision that they suffered greater financial harm can get a
higher recovery from an arbitrator. Others can continue their
suits.
</P>
<P>
   The loan programs, which are supposed to aid farmers who fail to
get commercial bank loans, were administered by local county
committees. In some Southern states, the disparity in loans to
whites and blacks was large. It often took three times longer to
process an application from a black farmer than from a white
farmer. Agriculture Secretary Dan Glickman has attacked this
shameful history by, among other things, taking away the power of
local committees to approve loans.
</P>
<P>
   Bipartisan leaders in Congress helped make restitution to the
farmers possible by waiving the two-year federal statute of
limitations that would have barred many from recovering in court.
The settlement will not make whole those who already have lost
their farms, but it will give desperately needed help to those
still hanging on.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
