<SLUG> BC-NY-TIMESSQUARE-SUBWAY-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FIRST CONTRACT AWARDED FOR TIMES SQUARE SUBWAY OVERHAUL
</HEADLINE>
 (bl) 
By THOMAS J. LUECK   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ New York City Transit has awarded an $82.8 million
contract for the first phase of a Times Square subway station
renovation project to a consortium of companies headed by Slattery
Skanska Inc., a Swedish-owned construction company.
</P>
<P>
   The award was approved in December by the board of the
Metropolitan Transportation Authority, the parent of New York City
Transit. It is part of the $180 million project to rebuild the
entire Times Square station, the city's largest subway hub, where
500,000 people converge on eight subway lines every day.
</P>
<P>
   Al O'Leary, a New York City Transit spokesman, said work on the
first phase of the project would begin in the spring and was
scheduled to be completed by the end of 2002. The transit agency
has not disclosed when it expects to complete the whole project.
</P>
<P>
   According to New York City Transit documents describing the
competitive bidding process that led to its selection of Slattery
Skanska, 25 construction companies expressed interest in the job,
and 5 were asked to submit detailed bids.
</P>
<P>
   Two bidders were selected as finalists, including A.J. Pegno
Inc., a New York City firm that last year oversaw the rebuilding of
the Lenox Avenue subway line between 110th and 116th Streets.
</P>
<P>
   In that project, A.J. Pegno won widespread praise _ and a bonus
from the transit agency _ for finishing its work ahead of schedule
and under budget.
</P>
<P>
   But the documents said Slattery Skanska had been selected for
the Times Square project because its bid was $2.7 million below
A.J. Pegno's, and because Slattery Skanska had suggested ``an
innovative approach'' in which it would do much of its work during
the day, working around the crowds of subway riders. A.J. Pegno had
insisted on doing almost all of its work at night, the documents
said, which would have pushed back the completion date.
</P>
<P>
   Although it is owned by Skanska Ltd., based in Stockholm,
through its United States subsidiary, Skanska U.S.A., the winning
consortium includes Slattery Associates, which is based in Queens
and has considerable experience with large construction projects
for the MTA. The other member of the consortium is Robert Gottlieb,
a New York City builder.
</P>
<P>
   According to the documents, the first phase of the Times Square
project is to include rebuilding and enlarging the mezzanine that
stretches from 41st Street to 42nd Street under Seventh Avenue;
reconstructing the platforms for the Seventh Avenue trains (the
Nos. 1, 2, 3 and 9 lines) and the Broadway trains (the N and R
lines); installing four elevators suitable for people with
disabilities, and rebuilding floors, stairs and ceilings throughout
the station.
</P>
<P>
   Other work, including renovation of the platforms for the Times
Square shuttle and the No. 7 train, is to be completed during the
second phase of the project, transit officials said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-01-08-99 2222EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
