<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-01-08 22:24 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5669 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-IMPEACH-CLINTON-BOS &LR;      01-08 1404
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-IMPEACH-CLINTON-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SENATE ACCEPTS COMPROMISE ON IMPEACHMENT RULES
</HEADLINE>
  (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By BOB HOHLER AND ANN SCALES  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Ending a critical impasse, the Senate Friday agreed
during a remarkable, closed-door session to temporarily forsake
partisan politics and adopt a blueprint for President Clinton's
impeachment trial.
</P>
<P>
   The last-minute agreement _ inspired by what Senator Edward M.
Kennedy portrayed as ``a certain magic'' in the Old Senate Chamber
where the nation's great orators once debated _ calls for the trial
to begin next Wednesday and puts off for at least two weeks a vote
on whether Clinton's accusers or his lawyers can call witnesses.
</P>
<P>
   The pact also cleared the way for the Senate sergeant-at-arms,
James Ziglar, to serve Clinton a summons Friday &UR;  &LR; night formally
notifying him of the trial. Clinton was not in the White House when
the summons arrived.
</P>
<P>
   White House lawyers praised the agreement, but vowed to wage ``a
vigorous, successful, and complete defense'' on Clinton's behalf.
``We are optimistic that senators, once they see and hear this
defense, will conclude the articles do not justify or warrant
conviction or removal from office,'' said Gregory B. Craig, a White
House special counsel.
</P>
<P>
   The 13 House Republicans who will serve as managers, or
prosecutors, in the trial expressed guarded optimism that the
Senate will permit them to present as many as 15 witnesses against
Clinton. Representative Henry J. Hyde, the lead manager as chairman
of the House Judiciary Committee, said the team would present ``a
compelling case'' against Clinton.
</P>
<P>
   The Senate unanimously approved the pact, ending days of
wrangling. The agreement narrowly averted the threat of having the
historic proceedings begin amid partisan rancor, and appears to
prevent the process from turning into a monthslong ordeal
</P>
<P>
   Under the blueprint, the trial could end late this month or
early in February.
</P>
<P>
   The Senate majority leader, Trent Lott, called the deal a
``magnificent conclusion'' to the rare, private session involving
100 senators who often yield little ground in defending their
diverse beliefs. Lott called the meeting after struggling
unsuccessfully to resolve the procedural issues since the House
approved two articles of impeachment against Clinton on Dec. 19.
</P>
<P>
   ``Today, we have acted in the very best tradition of the
Senate,'' Lott said.
</P>
<P>
   Under the plan, which Kennedy helped to forge as time was about
to expire in the two-hour meeting, both parties said they made
concessions to promote fairness and protect the dignity of the
Senate.
</P>
<P>
   The House managers and Clinton's lawyers have until 5 p.m. on
Monday to file any pretrial motions, which the Senate will consider
on Wednesday. The pact then calls for the House managers to present
their case over three days, beginning Thursday. Clinton's lawyers
will be given three days for a rebuttal, starting Jan. 19. The
Senate would then have two days to pose questions to both sides
through the presiding officer, Chief Justice William H. Rehnquist.
</P>
<P>
   In a boon to Clinton's lawyers, the House managers will be
restricted during their three-day presentation to evidence that was
made public during the House impeachment process. The House team
has indicated it might try to introduce additional allegations
against Clinton that were not raised in the House proceedings.
</P>
<P>
   Under the pact, the managers will be barred from calling
witnesses or presenting new evidence unless the Senate approves the
requests after the two-day question period.
</P>
<P>
   The Senate will then vote on a motion to dismiss the impeachment
articles before the votes on witnesses or additional evidence. If
the motion to dismiss the charges passes, the trial would end, and
the Senate could move to censure Clinton.
</P>
<P>
   But if the motion fails, and senators decided to call witnesses,
the trial could stretch out for an indefinite period.
</P>
<P>
   Kennedy said the agreement permits the Senate ``to respond the
way it should to one of the great challenges it has faced in this
country's history.''
</P>
<P>
   Senator Robert C. Byrd, a West Virginia Democrat who is one of
the chamber's most gifted orators, began the session with a
30-minute speech invoking the memories of some of the famous
statesmen who held forth in the chamber in the buildup to the Civil
War: Daniel Webster, Henry Clay, and John C. Calhoun.
</P>
<P>
   Byrd said the House had fallen into ``the black pit of partisan
self-indulgence'' in its impeachment process. ``I ask everyone here
who might harbor such feelings to abandon any thought of
mean-spirited, destructive, vengeful, partisan warfare,'' Byrd
said, according to a transcript released later by his office.
</P>
<P>
   Byrd also told a parable from the Canterbury Tales ``about each
side killing each other and nobody winning.''
</P>
<P>
   The deal emerged soon after Senator Phil Gramm, a Texas
Republican, invoked Daniel Webster, who was a Massachusetts senator
with New Hampshire roots, saying, ``I stand not as a partisan, not
as a New Englander, but as a senator.''
</P>
<P>
   Gramm argued that the differences were minimal between the first
stages of competing Republican and Democratic plans for the trial.
Kennedy, one of Gramm's most ardent political foes, rose to support
him. ``The reference to Daniel Webster kind of caught me a little
bit,'' Kennedy said he told his colleagues.
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, Senator Patrick J. Leahy, a Vermont Democrat, said he
told Gramm: ``Phil, you mentioned Daniel Webster, and Ted got all
dewey-eyed.''
</P>
<P>
   Senator John F. Kerry said the agreement sprang from ``a sense
of urgency that the nation is watching and we have a responsibility
to prove that the Senate can fulfill its duties well.''
</P>
<P>
   Once Gramm and Kennedy had agreed, Lott quickly seized on the
unlikely alliance, declared the ``Gramm-Kennedy plan'' viable and
cut off the meeting.
</P>
<P>
   The agreement, which could spare the GOP majority a backlash
from presiding over partisan proceedings, also gives the White
House what it most wanted: The opportunity to file a motion to
dismiss the charges before witnesses are called.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a fair deal,'' said former White House special counsel
Lanny Davis, who is informally advising the president's defense
team.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton faces impeachment charges that he committed perjury and
obstructed justice in trying to cover up an affair with Monica S.
Lewinsky, a former White House intern.
</P>
<P>
   The feeling among White House lawyers is that they can win the
legal arguments, and raise enough doubt that Clinton committed the
offenses to persuade senators to dismiss the impeachment articles.
</P>
<P>
   ``I honestly today for the first time have confidence that this
is not going to be a party-line judgment,'' Davis said. ``I have
confidence that they will listen to the evidence, and they will
suddenly realize this is an incredibly weak case.''
</P>
<P>
   Although Kennedy gave no indication he was working in concert
with the White House, it is no secret that he is a key supporter of
Clinton and close friend of Gregory Craig, who was Kennedy's
foreign policy adviser from 1984 to 1988. In 1991, Craig, serving
as a defense lawyer, prepped Kennedy for his testimony in the Palm
Beach, Fla., rape trial of the senator's nephew, William Kennedy
Smith.
</P>
<P>
   But Kennedy's attempt to forge the agrement did not end with the
closed-door session. He spent several more hours negotiating with
Gramm and two other senators whose original proposal the deal was
modeled after: Joseph I. Lieberman, a Connecticut Democrat, and
Slade Gorton, a Washington Republican.
</P>
<P>
   At one point, Kennedy said, Gramm insisted the House managers
should be permitted to present new evidence during their opening
presentation. ``He said, `You can't muzzle the House,' '' Kennedy
quoted Gramm as saying.
</P>
<P>
   Kennedy told Gramm the initial agreement precluded the
introduction of new allegations. ``That's not the way we're going
to deal with it,'' he said, and then walked out of the meeting.
</P>
<P>
   When Kennedy returned with a new draft proposal, Gramm said,
``This doesn't look right,'' according to Kennedy. ``So we had
Daschle and Lott come in and work it out,'' Kennedy said.
</P>
<P>
   Gramm declined to discuss details of the negotiations. But he
said he was proud to take part in resolving the impasse.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL; 
Anne E. Kornblut of the Globe staff contributed to this report.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
