</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-PLANES-COLDWEATHER-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
120 TWIN-ENGINED JETS UNDER CAUTION AFTER 3 HAVE TROUBLE IN FLIGHT 
 (DW)
</HEADLINE>
 
(ATTN: Brazil, Tex., Ohio, N.J., Ill., Minn., Fla., Mich.)   By MATTHEW L. WALD   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Three twin-engine jets have had an engine shut down
in flight in the last week, probably because a seal weakened by
cold let oil leak out, the Federal Aviation Administration said
Friday. The agency issued an emergency order requiring special
tests on about 120 planes with the engines any time the oil
temperature is below 32 degrees, and prohibiting flight if
excessive leaks occur.
</P>
<P>
   The order affects Embraer 145's, a new model of 50-seat regional
jet built in Brazil that is used heavily by American Eagle and
Continental Express. It also affects Cessna 750s, which are
business jets. All the planes use Allison turbofan engines.
</P>
<P>
   The FAA said further orders might be needed as its investigation
proceeds.
</P>
<P>
   Continental Express flies 38 EMB 145's, from its hubs in
Houston, Cleveland and Newark, N.J. On Tuesday the crew of one of
them, on a flight from Cleveland to Minneapolis, shut down an
engine and diverted to Grand Rapids, Mich., when a sensor in the
cockpit warned of low oil. On Thursday the same problem occurred on
an American Eagle flight from Chicago to Cleveland; it made an
unscheduled landing in Toledo.
</P>
<P>
   Details of the third incident could not be determined, but the
FAA said all three planes landed safely. Marty Heires, a spokesman
at American, said the airline had begun on Thursday to keep its 20
EMB-145's indoors at night, or have mechanics start the engines
every few hours during the night. Ned Walker, a spokesman for
Continental, said his airline was performing the checks of the oil
level every morning.
</P>
<P>
   This is the first winter that American has flown the planes.
Continental used them last winter, but this winter has been much
colder in places Continental flies, especially in the Midwest. The
airlines have been buying jets like the EMB-145 for routes where
they previously used turboprop planes, partly because of customer
perceptions that the propeller planes were less reliable,
especially in cold weather, when they are prone to accumulate ice
in flight.
</P>
<P>
   A switchboard operator at Embraer's headquarters in Sao Jose dos
Campos, Brazil, said that no one was in the office there; company
representatives in a sales office in Fort Lauderdale, Fla., did not
return phone messages.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
