<DATE_TIME> 1999-01-08 22:39 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5686 &Cx1f; taf-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BKC-RHODEN-COLUMN-NYT     01-08 0776
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKC-RHODEN-COLUMN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SPORTS COLUMN: RESIGNATION DOESN'T MEAN RETIREMENT
</HEADLINE>
  (bl)  
By WILLIAM C. RHODEN   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ For most of a snowy flight Friday morning, I
considered what was about to unfold, and I couldn't comprehend it.
The Georgetown University sports information director had called
Thursday evening and left a not-so-cryptic message: a major news
conference was scheduled for Friday morning involving coach John
Thompson.
</P>
<P>
   Off to the airport, off to Washington for what could only be a
retirement. But why? Health? Thompson had collapsed several years
ago. Recently he had some back problems. The only thing wrong now
was his team.
</P>
<P>
   But when Thompson spoke to the news media Friday morning, it
became clear that this was no ride into the sunset. This was not a
retirement, he stressed. ``I'm resigning.''
</P>
<P>
   On a Washington sports talk radio show, caller after caller
seemed stunned and expressed ambivalence to the news. There were
platitudes and detractors. One caller compared Thompson to Adolph
Rupp. ``They both won championships and both were racists,'' he
said. The next caller took exception to the racist
characterization. ``He cared about kids in the inner city,'' the
caller said. ``I appreciated everything he's done for the game.''
</P>
<P>
   At a more immediate level, one caller expressed concern that
Thompson's successor, Craig Esherick, who began as Thompson's
assistant in 1979, wasn't high-profile enough. ``I was hoping for
somebody like Mike Jarvis or Tommy Amaker,'' the caller said.
</P>
<P>
   At McDonough Arena, marketing director Brian McGuire sat behind
his desk in a state of shock. McGuire has spent the last 30 years
at Georgetown. He was an undergraduate at the university and worked
in the alumni relations department.
</P>
<P>
   When the Hoyas reached the regional championship of the National
Collegiate Athletic Association tournament in 1980, everyone was
happy and content with 4,000 fans in McDonough. Then Patrick Ewing
signed with the Hoyas and ``everything was different,'' McGuire
said. ``Fourteen thousand, 15,000 fans were showing up to see us
play. There was really no growing period. We did not have slow
growth,'' he said. ``We went to the final eight, then Bingo! _ the
Final Four.''
</P>
<P>
   So, what now? McGuire looked across his desk with heartfelt
bewilderment. ``I don't know. This is all new territory for us.
Since 1981-82 we've been big-time basketball, and it's all been
John Thompson.''
</P>
<P>
   I left McGuire's office and went through the doors leading to
the coaches' wing. In Thompson's office sat three generations of
his coaching progeny: Patrick Ewing, Othella Harrington, John
Duren, Michael Jackson, Jaren Jackson, Ralph Dalton. The agent
David Falk sat on the couch nearest to Thompson.
</P>
<P>
   The players reminisced and told war stories. Finally, Ewing
asked what time the players were going to start practicing because
he had to start running. ``Two o'clock,'' someone said. ``I'll be
back at 3,'' Ewing said.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's a big union president now and he has appointments,''
Thompson said. ``I remember when I said to be here at 3, he'd be
here at 2:45.'' Ewing smiled and said sheepishly, ``I'm still like
that.''
</P>
<P>
   As the office cleared out I thought that this was part wedding
and part wake. This blustery day marked the sudden end not simply
of an era but of a large chunk of each of their lives. After 27
years, their coach had resigned. Resigned, not retired. Thompson
will continue to work at Georgetown, helping on various projects.
Odds are that he will resurface as a coach, but not at Georgetown.
</P>
<P>
   When the room cleared, I asked Thompson how he felt. Fine, he
said. Health wasn't the issue.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm going through a divorce,'' he said. The process of the
divorce was pulling at him in a way he could no longer ignore. Last
season was a disaster; this season was becoming more stressful. ``I
felt like Dagwood,'' he said, evoking the image of the comic strip
character who always seems to be torn in different directions.
``Part of me was running after the bus, the other part was reaching
back to grab my hat. I was going in opposite directions. This year
I was stretching myself like a rubber band.''
</P>
<P>
   So Thompson decided before the Seton Hall game Monday to stop
the stretching. He would resign and turn his entire attention to
his personal life.
</P>
<P>
   Practice was getting ready to start, and Thompson was beginning
his new, yet to be determined, career. ``I'll be all right,'' he
said. ``Don't worry about me. You'd better worry about Craig.''
</P>
<P>
   Save the syrupy sentiments for a clearer day. This career isn't
over. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
