<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BIZGLANCE-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BUSINESS AT A GLANCE 
</HEADLINE>
  (mk) 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   ECONOMY REWARDS WORKERS WITH A BOOM IN U.S. JOBS
</P>
<P>
   Despite an unsettled global economy, lower corporate profits and
a new round of layoffs, the American economy kept creating jobs at
an astonishing pace in December, adding about 378,000 new
positions. Unemployment fell to 4.3 percent, matching the 28-year
low set last April. Signs of strength in the economy were
impressive and widespread, showing healthy gains in employment and
wages among disadvantaged demographic groups.
</P>
<P>
   For 1998 as a whole, net job growth was nearly 3 million and
unemployment hovered between 4.3 and 4.5 percent. Except for a
period at the height of the Vietnam War, the last time unemployment
was this low for any significant length of time was in 1957.
</P>
<P>
   American consumers scaled back their rate of borrowing in
November, adding $3.9 billion in new debt, the Federal Reserve
reported, compared with $11.9 billion in October. Revolving loans,
which include credit card borrowing, decreased, but auto loans rose
sharply.
</P>
<P>
   HYUNDAI PLANS TO SELL DIVISIONS
</P>
<P>
   Hyundai Group, South Korea's largest conglomerate, said it would
sell 11 of its affiliates in an effort to raise more than $5
billion. Hyundai, the largest of the giant family-dominated
conglomerates that dominate the nation's economy, is under pressure
from the government to bring down its debt, now estimated at $36
billion.
</P>
<P>
   LUCENT PREDICTS A ONE-TIME GAIN
</P>
<P>
   Lucent Technologies, a maker of telecommunications equipment,
predicted a one-time gain of 97 cents a share in its first quarter,
which ended Dec. 31. The gain reflects an accounting change that
better represents benefit expenses, and almost matches Wall Street
earnings estimates for the quarter.
</P>
<P>
   FAA ORDERS TESTS ON PLANES
</P>
<P>
   The Federal Aviation Administration issued an emergency order
for special tests on Embraer 145s, Brazilian-built regional jets
heavily used by some U.S. airlines, and Cessna 750s, which are
business jets. The order followed three instances of engine
shutdowns because of suspected oil leaks.
</P>
<P>
   WILD DAY FOR BROADCAST.COM SHARES
</P>
<P>
   Trading of shares in Broadcast.com, a Dallas Internet company,
was stopped temporarily Friday on the Nasdaq stock market after the
stock had jumped more than 70 percent in value by 11:51 a.m.
Trading resumed at 1:20 p.m. even though the company declined to
comment on what might have caused such a remarkable surge. The
stock opened at $132, rose to a high of $230.50, and closed at
$197.50, up $65.50 for the day.
</P>
<P>
   MENTOR ENDS PURSUIT OF QUICKTURN
</P>
<P>
   Mentor Graphics abruptly dropped its unsolicited offer for
Quickturn Design Systems Inc., clearing the way for Quickturn to
merge with Cadence Design Systems Inc. in a stock swap valued at
about $268 million, or $15 a share. Cadence and Mentor are bitter
rivals in the market for the electronic automated design software
used to fashion new computer chips. Quickturn is a leader in the
related market for computers that can emulate new chip designs.
</P>
<P>
   MCI WORLDCOM WON'T BUY AIRTOUCH
</P>
<P>
   MCI Worldcom said it had decided not to pursue a bid for
Airtouch, the nation's leading wireless telephone company. Airtouch
has been in merger talks with Bell Atlantic, the nation's largest
local phone concern, which wants to buy the company in a stock deal
valued at about $45 billion. Vodafone Group PLC, a British wireless
carrier, has also proposed buying Airtouch, suggesting a deal worth
$54 billion in cash and securities.
</P>
<P>
   CUBA SCOFFS AT EASING OF SANCTIONS
</P>
<P>
   In the first official Cuban reaction to President Clinton's
decision on Monday to ease a few elements of the United States'
economic embargo against Cuba, Jose Luis Rodriguez, Cuba's economy
minister, dismissed Clinton's changes as ``crumbs.'' The president
had said U.S. companies would be permitted to sell food and farm
supplies to nongovernmental organizations in Cuba. Most elements of
the sanctions would remain unchanged.
</P>
</TEXT>
