<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-01-08 22:58 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5694 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-HKN-ROBITAILLE-LADN     01-08 0915
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HKN-ROBITAILLE-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ROBITAILLE'S TOP 20 CLASSICS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By KAREN CROUSE  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   INGLEWOOD, Calif. _ The Los Angeles Kings' Luc Robitaille has
scored so many huge goals during his 13-year NHL career his name
should be Luc Robiwin.
</P>
<P>
   Sixty-four of his 500 goals have been regular-season
game-winners. He has 47 more in the postseason and two have come
courtesy of penalty shots.
</P>
<P>
   He is the only left wing in NHL history to produce eight
consecutive 40-goal seasons, and he's currently on a 47-goal pace,
which would be his highest total since he scored 63 in 1992-93.
</P>
<P>
   Robitaille, who turns 33 next month, has a sharpshooter's eye
and a fuzzy memory. He can recall his first goal just fine. But ask
him about his 200th? His 400th? His favorite? and he flails like a
beaten goalie.
</P>
<P>
   Pinning Robitaille down on any particular goal is like asking
the rest of us to describe one specific sneeze. Scoring goals is a
reflex action for the player who became the sixth left winger and
the 27th skater in NHL history to reach the 500-goal milestone. He
got there with two goals in the Kings' 4-2 win over Buffalo on
Thursday night at the Forum.
</P>
<P>
   His latest victim, backup goaltender Dwayne Roloson, can take
solace in the fact it wasn't the first time the Sabres had been
buffaloed by Robitaille. The 6-foot-1 forward hasn't reached all of
his milestones against the Sabres, it just seems that way.
</P>
<P>
   His 50th goal (and 100th point) of the 1992-93 season came
against Buffalo on March 15, 1993.
</P>
<P>
   The Sabres also gift-wrapped his 400th goal, on Feb. 19, 1995,
which Robitaille scored with 20 seconds left to draw the Penguins
even at 3.
</P>
<P>
   And No. 300? The Sabres saw that one up-close-and-personal, too.
On Nov. 7, 1992, Robitaille, taking advantage of a Kings 5-on-3,
chased down his own rebound and launched another shot at goalie Tom
Draper. The puck skipped into the back of the net off the skate of
Doug Bodger, now a Kings teammate but then a mortified Sabres
defenseman.
</P>
<P>
   From the memory banks where those three goals were stored we've
withdrawn 17 more, all 20 of them made priceless by No. 20's
Hall-of-Fame-validating score:
</P>
<P>
   _In the first period of his NHL debut on Oct. 9, 1986,
Robitaille beat St. Louis goaltender Rick Wamsley for the goal that
got things rolling. Marcel Dionne picked up his 1,600th career
point with the first assist.
</P>
<P>
   _Robitaille recorded his first game-winning goal and reaped a
sprained right knee, too, on Nov. 29, 1986, in the second period of
a 9-6 win over visiting New Jersey.
</P>
<P>
   _On Oct. 25, 1987, Robitaille was hooked from behind on a
breakaway in Winnipeg. Never mind that the Kings hadn't scored on a
penalty shot in three years and it had been a good decade since
Robitaille last had tried one (and missed), Cool-Hand Luc skated in
on Jets goalie Eldon Reddick and smacked the puck inside the left
post for the deciding goal in a 2-1 win.
</P>
<P>
   _It's no small feat to overshadow a mega-star's premiere, but
Robitaille pulled it off on Oct. 6, 1988, when he collected his
99th, 100th and 101st career goals in Wayne Gretzky's first game as
a King, an 8-2 win over Detroit at the Forum.
</P>
<P>
   _Gretzky dropped a pass for Robitaille in at the Forum on April
18, 1991, and Robitaille did the rest, beating Edmonton goalie Bill
Ranford in overtime for the Kings' first victory in a second-round
playoff game in nine years and a dozen tries.
</P>
<P>
   _The script never would read any better for the Kings than when
Robitaille returned to his native Montreal on June 1, 1993, and
scored twice to ice Game 1 of the Kings' best-of-seven Stanley Cup
Final against the Canadiens. Who knew Marty McSorley would get
caught with an illegally curved stick and Montreal would win the
next four games and the Kings would miss the playoffs the next four
years?
</P>
<P>
   _The Kings likely would have bowed out before Montreal if not
for Robitaille's goal on May 27, 1993, which drew the Kings even
with Toronto in a Stanley Cup semifinal Game 6 that the Kings had
to win (and did, 5-4 in overtime) to avoid elimination.
</P>
<P>
   _A touch of flu couldn't unglue Robitaille on April 15, 1993; he
scored his career-high 63rd goal in an 8-6 loss to Vancouver at the
Forum and added three assists to surpass Kevin Stevens as the NHL's
all-time leader for points scored in a season (with 125).
</P>
<P>
   _Robitaille didn't look right with a Penguin on his chest and
New York wasn't his kind of town so there was joy all around on
Oct. 12, 1997, when he returned triumphantly to the Forum for his
second go-around as a King.
</P>
<P>
   Robitaille marked the occasion by knocking an Ottawa player off
the puck and converting a pass from Aki Berg at the other end for
the deciding goal in a 7-4 win.
</P>
<P>
   _The crease is Robitaille's castle, as Hartford goalie Jeff
Reese was rudely reminded on Feb. 16, 1995, when Pittsburgh
teammate Jaromir Jagr set Robitaille up on four goals in 40
minutes. Robitaille remembers that two of the goals went in off his
skates. The record shows it was the 12th hat trick of Robitaille's
career. He continues to look for his lucky 13th.
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps he'll find it tonight against Edmonton. Stranger things
have happened.
</P>
<P>
   Luc's flukiest goal? That would have to be the one he scored off
Mike Vernon years ago while sliding across the Forum ice on his
stomach. Robitaille amazed even himself with that one, just as he
continues to impress everybody else.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
