<SLUG> BC-HKN-KINGSNOTES-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FISET IS BACK
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By ROGER PHILLIPS  
 Long Beach Press-Telegram  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Stephane Fiset's season of fits and starts will resume tonight,
when the Los Angeles Kings' No. 1 goalie is expected to play for
the first time in nearly four weeks.
</P>
<P>
   Fiset, who has battled groin injuries all season, is expected to
be in goal at 7 tonight when the Kings play host to the Edmonton
Oilers.
</P>
<P>
   He had said that if asked to play, he would beg off of the
assignment because of the fine play recently of Jamie Storr. But he
said goaltending consultant Don Edwards convinced him that it was
time to get back into action.
</P>
<P>
   The last time Fiset played, in a loss to the Mighty Ducks on
Dec. 13, the Kings (15-21-3) were in a tailspin. But they begin
play tonight with five consecutive wins and seven victories in
their last eight games.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's easier (to come back) knowing the team is playing good in
front of you,'' Fiset said. ``You know you just have to do your
job. It's harder when the team is not doing well. You think you
have to save the team.''
</P>
<P>
   Time for a breather (subhed)
</P>
<P>
   Assuming Fiset plays, it will end a career-high stretch of 10
consecutive starts for Storr, who went 7-3 in those games.
</P>
<P>
   Does Storr feel he's proven something with his strong play?
</P>
<P>
   ``I think people believed in me,'' Storr said. ``As long as the
team and general manager believed in me, that's all that mattered.
The main thing is, I believed in myself.''
</P>
<P>
   But Coach Larry Robinson said he has seen greater maturity this
season from Storr, 23.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think he's gotten stronger mentally,'' Robinson said. ``He's
starting to understand himself and the game better. That goes with
experience. The one thing we were always questioning was how well
he could keep his concentration over an extended period of time.''
</P>
<P>
   The question appears to have been answered.
</P>
<P>
   Honors for Luc: The Kings will honor Luc Robitaille, who scored
his 500th career goal Thursday night against Buffalo, with
ceremonies during the first intermission of tonight's game.
</P>
<P>
   There will be presentations from the NHL, Robitaille's Kings
teammates and the organization. The Kings flew Robitaille's
parents, Claude and Madeleine, to Los Angeles from Montreal on
Friday.
</P>
<P>
   The team also flew former Kings star Marcel Dionne to Los
Angeles from Buffalo on Friday. As a 20-year-old rookie in 1986-87,
Robitaille lived in Dionne's house. Dionne scored 731 goals during
his NHL career.
</P>
<P>
   Loose pucks: The Kings placed right wing Glen Murray (torn knee
ligament) and center Ray Ferraro (torn knee cartilage) on injured
reserve. ... Winger Donald Audette missed practice because he has a
cold. ... There's an outside chance defenseman Doug Bodger will
play after missing four games with a cervical strain and a bruised
shoulder. ... Individual tickets to Tip-A-King '99, the team's
annual charity event, go on sale Wednesday at the Forum and at all
TicketMaster outlets. The event will be held from 6 to 9:30 p.m. on
Feb. 7 at The Hangar at Merv Griffin Productions in Santa Monica.
All proceeds benefit the Kings Care Foundation. General admission
tickets, priced at $75, include food and drinks. VIP packages range
from $2,500-$5,000. For more information, call (213) 996-0118.
</P>
</TEXT>
