<SLUG> BC-HKN-COYOTES-NOTEBOOK-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DRAKE SIDELINED BY ELBOW  
 HOPES TO PLAY AGAIN VS. SABRES ON MONDAY 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By BOB MCMANAMAN  
 c.1999 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   ANAHEIM _ Missing four games due to a suspension was a pain in
the back to Dallas Drake. A mysterious pain in the elbow, it turns
out, prevented him from returning to the Coyotes' lineup Friday
night.
</P>
<P>
   Drake was all set to make his return against the Mighty Ducks of
Anaheim, but a sore left elbow, apparently bruised Wednesday during
practice, swelled up badly on Thursday and didn't improve Friday.
The result: an infected bursa, which is a sac of fluid that reduces
friction between tendons and bones.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's not like he did anything at home,'' Coach Jim Schoenfeld
said. ``He just banged it the other day and it was one of those
residual affects. He called (trainer) Gordie (Hart) and told him
his elbow was sore. Gordie told him to ice it and take some Advil.
A couple hours later, he called again and said it was really
starting to bother him.''
</P>
<P>
   Drake had to have the elbow drained of fluid. He accompanied the
team to Anaheim, but the elbow was still too sore for him to play.
Although he is listed as day to day, he hopes to play Monday, when
the Coyotes return home to meet the Buffalo Sabres.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't even know what happened. Seriously,'' Drake said. ``We
didn't even have any contact in practice Wednesday. I don't know if
I fell down or what. If I did, I don't remember falling down.''
</P>
<P>
   Asked if the injury could have occurred when he and other
teammates took turns pulling Jeremy Roenick and Oleg Tverdovsky
apart during two scraps that day, Drake shook his head.
</P>
<P>
   ``Nope. I'm a second-bout guy. I just stood there and more or
less watched,'' he said. &QL; 
Block that shot &QL; 
During their 7-1 rout at the hands of Edmonton on Thursday, the
Coyotes were credited with blocking only five shots, while the
Oilers had 11. Usually, though, Phoenix averages in double figures
in that department, a testament to teamwork.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think shot blocking is becoming a lost art. There aren't too
many people who do it _ or do it well, anyway,'' Schoenfeld said.
``It should be a last-ditch effort. I don't think it's ever the
first thing you want to do. But it can be a big play.
</P>
<P>
   ``If blocking a shot is the last resort to preventing the other
team from scoring, you've got to make that play. And we've got guys
who can do it extremely well.
</P>
<P>
   ``Mike Sullivan is a very good shot blocker. Jeremy Roenick is a
pretty good shot blocker. Dallas Drake is a guy who will pay the
price to block shots. From time to time, we've had all of our guys
willing to pay that price. If you're looking at a team that's
trying to win a championship, you have to pay a physical price, and
our team is willing to do that.''
</P>
<P>
   Earlier this season, Anaheim's Teemu Selanne made a flippant
remark after diving to the ice to block an opponent's shot, saying
it was his annual first and last attempt of the season. In other
words, the Ducks pay him to score goals, not sacrifice his body.
</P>
<P>
   Schoenfeld's response?
</P>
<P>
   ``Our skill players pay the price, so I don't have to worry
about it,'' he said. ``The thing is, if you think it's somebody
else's job and your job is only this, there are going to be nights
when you don't do your job and that player might come up and score
a big goal. But there are nights when the team may need you to
block a shot, nights when it needs you to throw a big body check.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think every hockey player should play the entire game as
well as he can. Obviously, some guys are going to be better at some
aspects than the other. Dallas Drake is a better body checker than
you, but you might be a better goal scorer. But you should still
try to check, and he should still try to score.'' &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
