<HEADLINE>
VIKINGS' GREEN AS GUTSY AS TEAM 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By DAN BICKLEY  
 c.1999 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   EDEN PRAIRIE, Minn. - Everyone loves you when you're 15-1.
</P>
<P>
   Which, of course, means nothing to Dennis Green. Because nobody
loves Dennis Green more than Dennis Green. This is the way it's
always been.
</P>
<P>
   News flash: Revelations that Green paid a former lover to have
an abortion in January 1993, leading to lawsuits and red faces in
the Vikings' hierarchy.
</P>
<P>
   News flash: Allegations of sexual harassment against Green after
the 1994 season.
</P>
<P>
   News flash: In a controversial autobiography, Green claims he's
been unfairly criticized because of his race and complains that
members of the team's ownership group deliberately have undermined
him. He threatens to sue two of the owners for allegedly contacting
Lou Holtz in an attempt to change coaches, thereby harming his
future, unless they sell him their share of ownership. He also
details a plan to buy the entire franchise, upsetting everyone in
Minnesota, including four other NFL owners who want him out of the
league on the next available flight.
</P>
<P>
   News flash: Green, who has led the Vikings to six playoff berths
and 69 wins in seven years, is only 1-5 in the postseason.
</P>
<P>
   News flash: Green threatens to resign before the 1998 season.
</P>
<P>
   News flash: In September, Green receives a three-year contract
extension from the new owner.
</P>
<P>
   Observation: You have to be a damn good football coach to pull
this off.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've got guts,'' Green said Friday. ``One thing I would never
do is quit or give up. We've always been a scrappy, fighting team.
And I've always been that kind of coach.''
</P>
<P>
   In fact, over a coaching career that spans 27 years, one that
started in the basement at Northwestern University, where he
snapped a 34-game losing streak, one that landed him at the table
of Bill Walsh disciples in San Francisco, one that led to a
tumultuous tenure in Minnesota, Green hangs on to one irrefutable
piece of evidence.
</P>
<P>
   He has never been fired.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm very proud of that because it's a tough business,'' Green
said. ``You have to be lucky because some of the best coaches in
the business have been fired many times.'' &QL; 
Strong motivator &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Where does Green fit in this mix? Well, he is excellent at
deferring blame, more than once comparing his results to the lack
of financial commitment from the previous ownership. He is
well-versed in his own accomplishments, and when asked about the
effect of a week layoff, this rattles off his tongue in machine-gun
force:
</P>
<P>
   ``We're a football team that earned a bye. We have the best
record going in and out of byes in the National Football League
over a seven-year period of time. So we know how to do the bye.''
</P>
<P>
   Nevertheless, for all the digressions, bravado and icy
relationships with the local media, for all the time he spends
dancing around his own land mines, this much is undeniable:
</P>
<P>
   Green is a masterful motivator. A coach who relates to his
players, defends his players, understands their mind-set and blends
it all into a common cause.
</P>
<P>
   ``He treats every man like a man, sometimes when they don't
deserve to be treated like men,'' Vikings receiver Cris Carter
said.
</P>
<P>
   On nearly every wall of the Vikings' training complex is a
slogan preaching the virtues of oneness. He is a coach who excels
at chemistry experiments. He doesn't just know the pulse of his
team, he creates it. And every Sunday, there is no team that plays
with more spirit or passion than his Vikings.
</P>
<P>
   ``We like to play football, we like to play hard, we try to be
consistent,'' Green said. ``We have a team that has a mentality
that football is what we like doing, and we're always going to lay
it on the line.''
</P>
<P>
   On his toes &QL;
</P>
<P>
   While the locals in Minnesota treat the Cardinals as a warm-up
act, Green has been very careful to keep his players focused. After
all, there is this awful playoff legacy trailing Green, a coach who
needed a Hail Mary ending to beat the Giants last year in his first
postseason victory.
</P>
<P>
   If he loses this one . . .
</P>
<P>
   Yes, you have to be lucky to hang around for 27 years and never
get whacked. But for all his talents, Green is a master at staying
ahead of the curve, plotting and planning, making sure his options
are open. In the wake of Mike Holmgren's mind-numbing deal to coach
the Seahawks comes a report that Green has a similar out clause in
his contract; that he may be able to leave the Vikings if another
team offers him the dual responsibilities of coach and general
manager.
</P>
<P>
   If I were Jeff Diamond, the current vice president of football
operations, I'd worry.
</P>
<P>
   ``More and more coaches are looking for that blend between the
responsibilities of what takes place on Sunday, which is very, very
demanding _ witness the number of coaches that have been fired the
last five or six or seven years _ and the ability, in the words of
Bill Parcells, to get your own shopping list,'' Green said. ``So I
think that has to be a concern for the future.''
</P>
<P>
   A future that has never caught up to Green, a coach who somehow
has shed much poundage and much baggage, a man who knows all about
survival of the fittest. &QL; 
Dan Bickley can be reached at 602-444-8253 or at
dan.bickley(at)pni.com via e-mail. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-01-08-99 2330EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
