<DOCNO> NYT19990108.0498 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-01-08 23:35 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5811 &Cx1f; tic-z
r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FBN-CARDS-UPSETS-AZR &LR;      01-08 1274
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-CARDS-UPSETS-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ANYTHING CAN HAPPEN  
 UPSETS MAKE MARK IN ANNALS OF NFL 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By TIM TYERS  
 c.1999 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   TEMPE, Ariz. - The colonists did it to England. Truman did it to
Dewey in '48. The '69 Mets did it to the baseball world. And the
'80 U.S. Olympic hockey team did it to the Big Bad Russians.
</P>
<P>
   Can the Arizona Cardinals hand a major upset to the Minnesota
Vikings on Sunday?
</P>
<P>
   The oddsmakers, who have installed the Vikings (15-1) as
15{-point favorites, say no, even though one is never wise to give
his grandmother more than 10 points in any NFL game, much less a
playoff game.
</P>
<P>
   But history tends to support the oddsmakers.
</P>
<P>
   Since 1990, when the NFL began its playoff seeding system, only
two of the 64 teams to play in the first round of the playoffs have
reached the Super Bowl. Buffalo did it in 1992, as did Denver,
which won last year.
</P>
<P>
   But even their wild rides came with an asterisk. Buffalo and
Denver each hosted first-round games.
</P>
<P>
   For the record, yes, the 1980 Oakland Raiders won Super Bowl XV,
but at the time each conference supplied only two wild-card teams
and Oakland entered the playoffs with an 11-5 record, which was
tied with four others for the AFC's best mark.
</P>
<P>
   The simple fact is the best teams tend to win, save for those
rare occasions that could be called ``historic upsets,'' a category
in which a Cardinals win Sunday would fit easily.
</P>
<P>
   When major NFL playoff upsets come to mind, perhaps the first on
the list is Joe Namath's ``guaranteed'' 16-7 win over the Baltimore
Colts, a 17{-point favorite in Super Bowl III. Or perhaps Kansas
City's 23-7 romp over Minnesota in Super Bowl IV.
</P>
<P>
   But were they truly upsets? Was it a disparity of talent that
made them upsets, or did their underdog status stem more from the
public's old-line NFL prejudice against the upstart American
Football League, which became the AFC after a merger?
</P>
<P>
   Think about it. In retrospect and being of sound mind, would you
give a solid team quarterbacked by a healthy Namath 17{ points
against one led by Earl Morrall, with a sore-armed Johnny Unitas
held in reserve?
</P>
<P>
   ``For two weeks we were told how we were going to lose,'' Namath
recalled about his prediction that the Jets would win. ``When you
keep hearing your team isn't going to win, you get angry and
frustrated. Then anger festers. Anger is a good thing to have.''
</P>
<P>
   Namath's prediction came at a Miami Touchdown Club meeting that
wasn't even on his agenda that night.
</P>
<P>
   ``We laughed and thought it was a joke,'' recalls Baltimore's
Hall of Fame tight end John Mackey. ``That was our problem. We had
the wrong attitude and decided he was just a quarterback running
his mouth.''
</P>
<P>
   In Super Bowl IV, Minnesota (12-2) was favored by 14{ points but
fell behind Len Dawson-led Kansas City (11-3) by 20 points at
halftime and never challenged. &QL; 
1940 shocker &QL;
</P>
<P>
   While the Jets' upset is indelibly etched in history, Cardinals
owner Bill Bidwill says it still takes a back seat to the Chicago
Bears' 73-0 win in the 1940 championship game over a Washington
Redskins team that had beaten it during the season. Bidwill
attended the title game as a 9-year-old.
</P>
<P>
   ``The score alone makes it the biggest upset,'' he said. ``This
was the two good teams in a championship game. It was bitterly
cold, and my family and I left at halftime.
</P>
<P>
   ``After that Sammy Baugh gave his famous quote. Someone asked
him after the game if an apparent touchdown pass he threw but was
dropped on Washington's first drive would have made a difference.
Baugh said, `Yeah, it probably would have been 73-7.' ''
</P>
<P>
   Nor, according to Bidwill, should the famed 1934 championship
game, historically known as the ``Sneakers Game,'' be overlooked.
The New York Giants (8-5) beat the Bears (13-0) by a 30-13 count on
a frozen field at the Polo Grounds. The Giants tossed the Bears a
curve by ditching their cleats at halftime and donning sneakers. &QL; 
Bad Broncos memories &QL;
</P>
<P>
   In modern times, the biggest playoff upset has to be expansion
Jacksonville's 30-27 wi over Denver (13-3) in 1996.
</P>
<P>
   Denver tight end Shannon Sharpe said, ``It's a loss that will
take until the year 2000 to overcome.''
</P>
<P>
   Wrong. Due to the hangover that loss provided, the Broncos
dubbed last year's playoff season the ``Revenge Tour.'' Starting
with Jacksonville in the first round, they also exorcised ghosts by
beating Kansas City and Pittsburgh, which beat them during the
year.
</P>
<P>
   The memory still stings so deeply that nobody in the Broncos
organization would agree to an interview this week to talk about
it.
</P>
<P>
   ``It had been one of the most successful years in their history
after missing the playoffs,'' said Cardinals vice president of
player personnel Bob Ferguson, who came to Arizona from the same
position in Denver that year. ``I don't know if Denver took them
lightly, but I think Tom Coughlin and those guys believed more in
what they could do.
</P>
<P>
   ``Denver talked about that game for a whole year. I don't know
if they would have won the Super Bowl last year if they had won
that game.'' &QL; 
Colts came close &QL; 
If that isn't enough to give the Cardinals hope, then Coach Vince
Tobin can present them with another example.
</P>
<P>
   Tobin was the Colts defensive coordinator during their
improbable drive to the AFC championship game in 1995, where they
lost to Pittsburgh, 20-16, when a Hail Mary pass fell incomplete on
the game's last play.
</P>
<P>
   The week before, the Colts (9-7 in regular season) went into
Kansas City (13-3) and knocked off a team favored by 12, by a 10-7
count.
</P>
<P>
   ``That whole deal was very similar to the year we've had,''
Tobin said. ``We had to struggle to get into the playoffs and had
to win our last game. We had to play San Diego on the road and then
had to go to Kansas City, which had the best record in the
conference and the home-field advantage . . . a lot of similarities
to our situation now.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was a tough, physical game and we played extremely well on
defense. Our mindset was that we could win, because we thought we
were a pretty good team even if our record didn't indicate it. It's
very similar to now. Our team is confident we can win, even though
nobody else thinks so. Our quarterback, Jim Harbaugh, was nicknamed
`Comeback Jim' for leading so many comebacks, just like Jake has
done.''
</P>
<P>
   Ironically, Minnesota, a four-time Super Bowl loser, also staged
one of the top modern upsets in 1987.
</P>
<P>
   Saddled with three losses from strike-team players, and losers
of three of their final four regular-season games, the Vikings
(9-7) played at San Francisco, a 14-point favorite that went 13-2
in the regular season and was armed with Joe Montana. The Vikings
won, 36-24.
</P>
<P>
   ``We had a hard time that week,'' said Vikings Coach Dennis
Green, then a 49ers assistant under Bill Walsh. ``It had rained all
week and we didn't practice well and we were sluggish. Anthony
Carter was fabulous and set an NFL playoff record for receiving
yards that stood until (Buffalo's) Eric Moulds broke it last
week.''
</P>
<P>
   San Francisco owner Eddie DeBartolo was so incensed by the loss
that he stripped Walsh of the team presidency, which most NFL
insiders say is the reason Walsh resigned after winning the Super
Bowl the next year.
</P>
<P>
   Before their miracle run ended in a 46-10 Super Bowl thrashing
by the Bears in 1985, New England shocked the LA Raiders, 27-20, in
the first round, then stunned a heavily favored Miami Dolphins team
that had beaten them twice that year, 31-14, in Miami, where they
hadn't won since 1966.
</P>
<P>
   See, it can be done. Just not often. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
