<HEADLINE>
NBA SCHEDULES FAR FROM READY 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By BOB YOUNG  
 c.1999 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   PHOENIX - The Suns and the 28 other NBA teams are awaiting word
from the league about their lockout-shortened season, and the
50-game schedules for teams, which initially were expected next
week, may not be released until training camps begin.
</P>
<P>
   And even the schedule for exhibition games and scrimmages still
must be worked out. The Suns will hold some open practices when
training camp begins, probably on Jan. 18.
</P>
<P>
   The league also announced that each team will play two
exhibition games, where possible, with one on the road and one at
home. And there will be no charge for admission to those games.
</P>
<P>
   However, Suns General Manager  &UR; Bryan Colangelo said those games
are subject to availability of buildings. America West Arena is
booked until right before the announced start of the season, Feb.
5, but Colangelo said the club is working on the problem.
</P>
<P>
   ``I have to tell you, it's going to be tough because our
building is so booked up,'' Colangelo said, citing a Disney on Ice
show, a pro wrestling event and others.
</P>
<P>
   The Suns don't want to toss  &UR; Mickey Mouse, and Colangelo said
the wrestling shows are big money makers for a building that is
owned by the city, managed by the Suns and also occupied by the NHL
Coyotes.
</P>
<P>
   ``If a signed contract is in place, it would be very difficult
to change,'' he said. ``And it would be self-serving to try and
kick someone out. Believe it or not, those wrestling events are
very profitable and successful for the building.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're looking for a date that may be available, and trying to
determine if one of the other events can change their load-in
plans. We may have to go to another facility. We're looking at
that, too.'' &QL; 
The KJ question &QL; 
Although the NBA's salary-cap rules have changed, and thus the Suns
are having to adjust their plans for putting together their team
for the upcoming season, one thing hasn't changed:  &UR; Kevin Johnson
won't be part of it.
</P>
<P>
   The club and KJ announced a parting of the ways after last
season.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think it was made pretty clear . . . that he'll be playing
somewhere else or he won't be playing,'' Colangelo said. ``I saw
that he was in New York, so I assume he's going to play.''
</P>
<P>
   Reached during the lockout, KJ would not comment on the labor
lockout or his plans. &QL; 
Another viewpoint &QL; 
Although fans have been victimized by the now-settled lockout, Suns
Coach &UR; Danny Ainge said they'll eventually benefit from the new
agreement.
</P>
<P>
   ``There shouldn't be as much need to raise ticket prices,'' he
said. ``They've had to do it because of the rising costs, but if
they can control spending it shouldn't hurt the fans, it should
help them.'' &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
