<DATE_TIME> 1999-01-08 23:40 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5822 &Cx1f; tic-z
r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BKC-NOTEBOOK-COHN-AZR     01-08 1166
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKC-NOTEBOOK-COHN-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EVANS GRATEFUL TO THOMPSON 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By BOB COHN  
 c.1999 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   PHOENIX - R &UR; ob Evans remembers riding the bus from the Kingdome
in Seattle in April 1984 after Georgetown and  &UR; Patrick Ewing beat
Houston and  &UR; Hakeem (then known as Akeem)  &UR; Olajuwon to win the
Final Four. The bus was filled with assistant coaches, and Evans
was one of them. Now the first-year head coach at Arizona State
after six years at Mississippi, Evans was at Texas Tech back then.
</P>
<P>
   Evans recalled the pride he and other African-American coaches
felt, while also understanding the significance of what just
happened. Which was this:
 &UR; John Thompson had just become the first Black coach to lead a team
to college basketball's national championship.
</P>
<P>
   ``I can't tell you how many of those coaches were beaming,''
Evans said Friday, shortly after Thompson announced he was
resigning as Georgetown's coach after 27 years.
</P>
<P>
   Right then, Evans said, he and other minority coaches knew that
if anyone had any lingering doubts about anyone's qualifications,
they were dispelled for good.
</P>
<P>
   ``I felt like, `Now people can see we can coach the game,' ''
Evans said. ``Now people can see we can do it right and discipline
kids. Now there are going to be some doors open.''
</P>
<P>
   Evans became the first Black coach at Ole Miss after 24 years as
an assistant. His first coaching job was at his alma mater, New
Mexico State, and he said he first became acquainted with Thompson
by watching Thompson's high school team in Washington, D.C., play.
That began a long friendship.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's always been around to encourage me, to give me insight
into what to expect,'' Evans said. ``Being a new coach, being an
African-American coach, on and on. He and  &UR; Nolan Richardson and
 &UR; John Chaney and  &UR; George Raveling are really good friends and have
really helped me through some troubling times.
</P>
<P>
   ``A lot of times I'd call John or drop him a line, seek his
counsel or advice, and he always responded. He doesn't always say
what you want to hear, but that's what I wanted.''
</P>
<P>
   Like others, Evans said he was shocked at the news. But, hearing
that Thompson said he was quitting to devote attention to his
troubled marriage, Evans said he understood.
</P>
<P>
   ``In this business, you can't have distractions and be
successful,'' Evans said. ``It's a 24-hour-a-day, seven-day-a-week
job.'' &QL; 
Different sport &QL; 
Hyped right here, in addition to there and everywhere, after
beating North Carolina, the California Golden Bears promptly went
into hibernation.
</P>
<P>
   Cal lost at home to Oregon in overtime, then played even worse
before escaping with a two-point victory over Oregon State.
</P>
<P>
   It took  &UR; Michael Gill's layup with 3.5 seconds left to beat the
Beavers, 54-52. Cal shot 22 percent in the first half, 29 percent
for the game.
</P>
<P>
   A pregame talk in which Coach  &UR; Ben Braun cited the San Francisco
49ers' last-second win over the Green Bay Packers in the NFL
playoffs didn't seem to help much.
</P>
<P>
   ``I told them to really understand what  &UR; Steve Young said,''
Braun said. ``That he didn't hesitate to to go to  &UR; Terrell Owens
just because he dropped four passes. . . . You still have to have
confidence in yourself and in your teammates.'' &QL; 
Declawed &QL; 
The young UCLA Bruins still have a lot of growing up to do. Coming
off their overtime victory over ASU in the friendly confines of
Pauley Pavilion, the bear cubs ventured north to play ostensibly
the weakest team in the Pac-10, Oregon State. They lost, 65-63.
</P>
<P>
   The amazing thing, in addition to the result, was that UCLA took
41 more shots than the Beavers. 41! But they made fewer than 29
percent, shooting 4 for 27 from three-point range. Freshman forward
 &UR; JaRon Rush was 0 for 7 from beyond the arc. Freshman  &UR; Dan Gadzuric
1 of 9 from the field.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was our first time on the road, and I think it got to us
tonight,'' Rush said. &QL; 
Stormy weather &QL; 
No, the Weather Channel didn't televise the game between the Red
Storm of St. John's and the Miami Hurricanes. But the way St.
John's approached the game, the forecast was bleak.
</P>
<P>
   The Red Storm was so flat prior to its 84-79 loss that even a
security guard working at Miami Arena noticed. The guard mentioned
to Coach  &UR; Mike
 &UR; Jarvis that this wasn't the same scrappy, hustling team he saw on
television. Jarvis then suggested the fellow tell the players
himself.
</P>
<P>
   ``He came in here and said, `I thought you guys were all that,'
'' forward
 &UR; Ron Artest told the ``New York Daily News.'' ``I don't think he
ever played basketball, but he knew that we had no fire in our
eyes.''
</P>
<P>
   The loss snapped St. John's nine-game winning streak. But let's
not sell the Hurricanes short. This is a talented team, and Miami
Coach  &UR; Leonard
 &UR; Hamilton told them they were playing as well as anyone in the Big
East.
</P>
<P>
   It's a sure thing St. John's will be more inspired for the Feb.
3 rematch in New York. Artest said he saw some Miami players
``laughing and stuff, disrespecting us,'' he said, citing  &UR; Dwayne
Wimbley as the main culprit.
</P>
<P>
   ``I can't wait to see him again,'' Artest said. &QL; 
Standing up to Spartans &QL; 
Just when you think Michigan State has turned the corner, the
Spartans run into a roadblock. In this case, it was Wisconsin.
</P>
<P>
   Michigan State is like the neighborhood bully, picking on the
little guys but running away when someone rough and tough stands up
to it. The 12th-ranked Spartans' seven-game winning streak ended
when they lost to the No. 24 Badgers, the fourth defeat in four
games against ranked opponents.
</P>
<P>
   It was the Spartans' first Big Ten game and the third for
Wisconsin, which provided a ready-made excuse.
</P>
<P>
   ``Wisconsin, they played hungry,'' Spartans forward  &UR; Morris
Peterson said. ``They had played two Big Ten games, and I felt like
they had a little advantage.''
</P>
<P>
   Preseason All-America point guard  &UR; Mateen Cleaves, who started
slowly this season but had come on strong of late, was 3 for 11
with two assists and four turnovers. &QL; 
No show &QL; 
DePaul is inducting its 1978-79 Final Four team into the school's
athletic Hall of Fame today, but  &UR; Ray Meyer won't be there.
</P>
<P>
   That's like holding an ``Andy Griffith Show'' reunion without
 &UR; Don Knotts.
</P>
<P>
   Meyer was the head coach of that team, and a lot of other DePaul
teams. He was the Blue Demons' coach for 42 years, retiring in 1984
with 724 victories, currently the 10th-highest total in NCAA
Division I history.
</P>
<P>
   But he never has gotten over the firing of his son,  &UR; Joey, who
succeeded him as coach. Joey Meyer was fired in 1997 after
successive losing seasons.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's just too hard for me at this time,'' Ray Meyer explained
to the ``Chicago Tribune.'' ``I know it's (strange) I won't be
there, but that's only one night of my life. I have to live my
whole life. There's no animosity anymore. It would be uncomfortable
for me. . . . So I don't want to subject myself to that.'' &QL; 
Bob Cohn can be reached at 602-444-8256 or at bob.cohn(at)pni.com
via e-mail. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
