<HEADLINE>
DAVIS PICKING UP DEVILS WITH HIS `GAR BAGE GAME' 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By BOB COHN  
 c.1999 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   TEMPE, ARIZ. - Derrick Davis, Arizona State's junior swingman,
is called ``Smooth'' by his teammates for his mellow, quiet
demeanor off the court.
</P>
<P>
   That makes sense because the name fits his playing style like a
very large person who goes by ``Tiny.''
</P>
<P>
   Davis is no klutz, but he isn't the picture of grace, either.
He's a digger, a hard-nosed grinder who likes to play defense and,
at 6-foot-4, mix it up inside with the big guys.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's tough,'' ASU Coach Rob Evans said. ``A tough country
kid.''
</P>
<P>
   Davis is ``kind of a throwback, in a sense,'' assistant Coach
Tony Benford said. ``He does a lot of intangibles.''
</P>
<P>
   Things such as diving on the floor for loose balls and
rebounding and defending, which ASU will need in its game tonight
against scrappy Washington State. Scoring? That's a bonus. But in
Monday's overtime loss to UCLA at Pauley Pavilion, someone
resembling Davis and wearing Davis' No. 14 scored 16 points and
generally impersonated a go-to guy. It was, in fact, Derrick Davis,
whose previous ASU high was nine.
</P>
<P>
   ``I knew I could do it,'' said Davis, who made two three-point
baskets, which matched his total for the previous 13 games. ``I had
to step it up. They were playing hard on Eddie (House). A lot of
people are going to be crowding him, so I figured it was my
opportunity to step it up. Do whatever it takes to win. But we
didn't win.''
</P>
<P>
   Thursday against Washington, Davis was scoreless until he
connected on another three-pointer with 4:08 remaining. That came
in the midst of nine straight points after the Huskies got to
within 12. ASU ended up winning by 24.
</P>
<P>
   ``You're not looking for him to come out and start shooting
three-point jump shots,'' Evans said. ``That's not his game. His
game is slashing to the basket, his game is defending. It's a
garbage game, really.''
</P>
<P>
   Evans means that as a compliment. He loves players like Davis.
He might wish they had more talent, but he appreciates and respects
their effort and willingness to get their noses bloodied.
</P>
<P>
   Or their jaws smacked. Against Southern California last week,
USC guard Jeff Trepagnier was so irked at Davis' cloying defense,
he hit him in the jaw. Trepagnier was called for an intentional
foul, although an ejection probably was warranted.
</P>
<P>
   ``He caught me with a cheap shot,'' said Davis, who thought
better of retaliating.
</P>
<P>
   ``You can't do that,'' he said. ``You've got to keep your
head.''
</P>
<P>
   That's how sensible, small-town folks think, and Davis is from a
small town _ Abbeville, Ala., located near the Florida panhandle.
It's so small it doesn't have a Web site. He attended Cowley County
Community College in Kansas after failing to register the necessary
ACT score and was a pretty good scorer there last year, averaging
more than 17 points.
</P>
<P>
   But with House, Mike Batiste and Bobby Lazor handling most of
the offense for the Sun Devils, Davis went back to concentrating on
the type of defense his old high school coach instilled in him and
adhering to the fundamentals preached by his father and uncle, both
of whom were high school coaches. He has guarded players that range
from 6-8 forward Alex Jensen of Utah to UCLA guard Earl Watson, who
goes about 6-1.
</P>
<P>
   Like fellow juco transfers Alton Mason and Lohnnie Tape, Davis
has found the transition to Division I challenging, both in the
classroom and on the floor.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's been kind of rough,'' he said. ``In junior college,
everybody wasn't good. Here, everybody's good. But I know now I can
be more aggressive. I'm feeling more comfortable.'' &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
