<SLUG> BC-BKC-ARIZONA-KERR-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WILDCATS TO ADMIT KERR TO EXCLUSIVE CLUB TODAY 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By BRIAN J. PEDERSEN  
 c.1999 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   TUCSON _ Arizona's healthy crop of talented freshmen have seen a
lot this season, but today they'll witness the rarest of events in
Wildcats sports history.
</P>
<P>
   Prior to today's 4 p.m. game against Washington, former Wildcats
great Steve Kerr will become only the second Arizona basketball
player to have his jersey hung from the rafters at McKale Center
and just the fourth athlete in any sport to earn the honor.
</P>
<P>
   At most colleges, having your uniform number retired is the
reward for having an outstanding career, one filled with dozens of
memorable events that grandfathers might tell their grandchildren
some day. But at Arizona, the criterion is simplified yet
incredibly stringent.
</P>
<P>
   Only those players who have been named NCAA Player of the Year
in their respective sport can have their number retired. That short
list includes baseball player Terry Francona, softball great Susie
Parra and Sean Elliot, Kerr's teammate on the Wildcats' 1988 Final
Four team. Softball pitcher Nancy Evans is also on the list, but
her number has yet to be retired.
</P>
<P>
   Kerr, who never did better than being a Second Team AP
All-American but was named the NCAA's Most Courageous Player in
'88, was given a special exception by Arizona athletic director Jim
Livengood because of what he meant to the program.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think it's a great decision,'' said freshman Richard
Jefferson, one of a handful of current players that might someday
join Elliot and Kerr above the court at McKale. ``I know a lot
about Steve Kerr and the impact he had on his team.''
</P>
<P>
   Kerr was never the best player on the court, from his time at
Arizona when he was called ``Opie'' by Coach Lute Olson and others,
to his pro days where he has won three NBA championship rings with
the Chicago Bulls, hitting the winning shot in the '97 finals.
</P>
<P>
   He never scored more than 30 points in a game, but has been
remembered as one of the most beloved players in school history.
Part of that came from his performance against Arizona State in
'88, just days after his father was killed in the Middle East.
Jefferson considers Kerr an inspiration to himself and his
teammates.
</P>
<P>
   ``You look at a guy like Steve Kerr, whose not exactly the most
gifted of players, but he comes out and plays the best that he
can,'' Jefferson said.
</P>
<P>
   Freshman Michael Wright often watched Kerr on television with
the Bulls while growing up in the Chicago area. He said he believes
it was a good decision to go away from Arizona's strict policy in
this case.
</P>
<P>
   ``He deserves it because of all the things he did when he was
playing here,'' Wright said.
</P>
<P>
   Kerr is 12th all-time on the school's scoring list with 1,445
points, and eighth on the assists list with 443. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
