<SLUG> BC-FBN-CARDS-FACILITY-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CARDINALS PLAN TO KEEP TEMPE TRAINING FACILITY  
 NEW STADIUM WOULD FORCE RENT INCREASE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By BOB PETRIE  
 and STEVE SCHOENFELD  
 c.1999 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   TEMPE, ARIZ. - The Cardinals have no plans to move from their
Tempe training facility, even though their rent will increase
significantly if they move from Sun Devil Stadium to the proposed
multipurpose domed stadium at Rio Salado Crossing.
</P>
<P>
   Team Vice President Michael Bidwill said the economic penalty
for the team moving its games out of Tempe will be addressed in the
lease agreement of the new stadium.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're very happy and proud of our relationship with Tempe and
happy with the facility,'' Bidwill said. ``We appreciate the things
the Tempe City Council and (former) Mayor Harry Mitchell did 11
years ago.''
</P>
<P>
   If the Cardinals move from Sun Devil Stadium but continue to
train at their Tempe facility, rent payment will zoom from zero to
$675,000 a year for the remainder of the 25-year lease, which ends
in 2015.
</P>
<P>
   As part of the use agreement being negotiated between the
Cardinals and the Rio Salado Crossing Stadium District, the team
wants the district to pay the rent of the Tempe training facility
from sales-tax surplus money raised from the project.
</P>
<P>
   State law allows the stadium district to keep 50 percent of
state sales taxes generated by the project within the district for
up to 10 years.
</P>
<P>
   The team can use sales tax money only if there is a surplus
after the district has paid operating and maintenance costs for
that quarter of the fiscal year, according to the agreement.
</P>
<P>
   Pat Gilbert, a Rio Salado board member, said he would be
amenable to letting the team use surplus sales taxes to pay the
Tempe lease.
</P>
<P>
   Tempe paid $6.5 million to help build the $11.3 million training
facility in 1990, with the team picking up the remainder.
</P>
<P>
   Right now, the Cardinals technically pay $181,000 in annual rent
to Tempe, but get all of that back from the city in lieu of the
$4.8 million the team invested in the building, Tempe Deputy City
Manager Pat Flynn said.
</P>
<P>
   ``They've not paid us a nickel'' in rent, Flynn said.
</P>
<P>
   Should the stadium vote fail and the Cardinals continue to train
and play in Tempe, the rent will rise to $266,000 a year in 2000,
with the team paying $85,000.
</P>
<P>
   But if the vote passes and the team moves its games to Mesa,
Flynn said, the higher training-facility rent payments will help
make up lost sales-tax money from ticket sales and game day
business from fans.
</P>
<P>
   ``The reason they have such an attractive lease vs. a higher
amount if they do their games elsewhere is because of the sales tax
they generate,'' Flynn said.
</P>
<P>
   If the Cardinals try to move training headquarters out of Tempe,
the lease calls for the team to pay the city a lump sum of $2.3
million, Flynn said.
</P>
<P>
   ``Why would anyone want to train elsewhere if you've got a
world-class facility?'' Flynn asked. &QL; 
Includes information from reporter Robbie Sherwood. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
