<DATE_TIME> 1999-01-08 23:49 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5830 &Cx1f; tic-z
r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FBN-CARDS-VIKES-GMS-A     01-08 1015
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-CARDS-VIKES-GMS-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HIGH WIRE TO PLAYOFFS  
 CARDS MADE RIGHT MOVES OVER 3 YEARS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By STEVE SCHOENFELD  
 c.1999 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   TEMPE, Ariz. - The blueprint to the Cardinals' success could
have been torn up in a hurry three years ago.
</P>
<P>
   Had All-Pro cornerback Aeneas Williams gone to Jacksonville and
not re-signed with the Cardinals, the first month of Coach Vince
Tobin's tenure might have been a disaster.
</P>
<P>
   Tobin and Bob Ferguson, who was assistant to the president at
the time, not only got Williams to return but also persuaded
defensive tackle Eric Swann to re-sign.
</P>
<P>
   ``No one gave us a chance to sign either,'' Tobin said. ``It
sent a message to the rest of the football team that the Cardinals
were committed to turning the past around. It was huge for both to
come back.''
</P>
<P>
   Three years later, the Cardinals are in the second round of the
NFC playoffs and will meet the Minnesota Vikings on Sunday at the
Metrodome in Minneapolis.
</P>
<P>
   The Vikings, meanwhile, were in disarray at this time a year
ago. But even without stable ownership, they managed to persuade
defensive tackle John Randle, offensive tackle Todd Steussie and
running back Robert Smith to re-sign.
</P>
<P>
   ``Minnesota chose to spend money on their own guys and spent
wisely,'' Tobin said. ``They weren't just run-of-the-mill players.
They are great players.''
</P>
<P>
   The credit for the Vikings' signings goes to Jeff Diamond, the
senior vice president of football operations. He also didn't stop
Coach Dennis Green from picking Randy Moss, the controversial
Marshall wide receiver who was the 21st pick overall.
</P>
<P>
   Ferguson said Diamond insisted on re-signing the players because
he knew it would affect the value of the team, which was up for
sale.
</P>
<P>
   The Vikings finished the regular season with the NFL's best
record and are considered the favorite to get to the Super Bowl.
</P>
<P>
   Before this season, the Cardinals hadn't won a playoff game
since 1947, hadn't been to the playoffs in a non-strike season
since 1975 nor had a winning record since 1984.
</P>
<P>
   Now they're the feel-good story of the playoffs. They have the
youngest defense in the league and a second-year quarterback, Jake
Plummer, who is considered a budding star.
</P>
<P>
   Thanks to a blockbuster trade they made with San Diego last
March, they also have the eighth pick in this April's draft along
with their own selection, No. 21 overall.
</P>
<P>
   ``We can't let up,'' Ferguson said. ``We have to stick with the
plan. Just because we re-signed Jake Plummer, we can't stop there.
We have to continue to build through the draft. The continuity of
what we're trying to do is keeping the philosophies together.''
</P>
<P>
   Ferguson was out of work when the Cardinals hired him. But he
had helped build Buffalo into a Super Bowl team and laid the
groundwork in Denver for the team that beat Green Bay in Super Bowl
XXXII last year.
</P>
<P>
   His first personnel move with the Cardinals was to sign
seven-time Pro Bowl offensive tackle Lomas Brown, whose friends in
Detroit told him he was crazy to join a perennial loser.
</P>
<P>
   The Cardinals then went to find a quarterback and brought in
Boomer Esiason and Kent Graham. But before they entered the 1996
regular season, the Cardinals had to solve serious salary cap
problems.
</P>
<P>
   To sign first-round pick Simeon Rice, they had to dump two of
three high-priced veterans _ running back Garrison Hearst,
linebacker Seth Joyner and defensive end Clyde Simmons _ because
none wanted to restructure their contracts.
</P>
<P>
   They chose to keep Joyner.
</P>
<P>
   ``We loved Seth's leadership ability,'' Ferguson said. ``We
would have liked to have kept Seth to this day. . . . Garrison
wasn't healthy yet. He was healthy enough to pass physicals, but he
wasn't himself.''
</P>
<P>
   The Cardinals surprised many by finishing 7-9 in Tobin's first
season, but they were far from being a playoff contender.
</P>
<P>
   Quarterback remained a question mark. Running back also was a
concern. Leeland McElroy, a second-round pick in '96 at running
back, proved to be a bust.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're going to make mistakes,'' Ferguson said. ``We've made
some, and we're going to make some more. We try to hold them to the
minimum, but you can't be afraid.''
</P>
<P>
   Several teams were afraid of Plummer's slight build and passed
on him in the first round. The Cardinals took him with the 11th
choice in the second.
</P>
<P>
   ``The day we picked Jake, the perception of the team changed,''
Ferguson said. ``We talked about it a long time. Everyone had to be
on the same page. We wondered, `What if he didn't play well? What
if we wasn't what we thought he'd be?' ''
</P>
<P>
   An injury to Graham allowed Plummer to start the final nine
games last season. Teams aren't very successful with a rookie
quarterback, and the Cardinals finished 4-12.
</P>
<P>
   But everything changed the day last March that the Cardinals
traded down one spot in the draft (from second overall to third)
and picked up San Diego's second-round pick, wide receiver Eric
Metcalf, linebacker Patrick Sapp and a 1999 No. 1.
</P>
<P>
   ``What made the deal happen was there were two franchise
quarterbacks (Peyton Manning and Ryan Leaf), and there were enough
people who needed them and willing to pay whatever it took,''
Ferguson said.
</P>
<P>
   The Cardinals used the Chargers' pick on Florida State's Andre
Wadsworth, considered the best defensive player in the draft. Then
they added Vanderbilt defensive back Corey Chavous in the second
round and Arizona State safety Pat Tillman in the seventh. Chavous
has started the past six games and Tillman the first 11.
</P>
<P>
   In addition, running back Adrian Murrell, a 1,000-yard rusher,
was acquired from the New York Jets for a third-round pick.
</P>
<P>
   They helped the Cardinals end the NFL's longest playoff drought
at 15 seasons.
</P>
<P>
   Ferguson gives the credit to owner Bill Bidwill.
</P>
<P>
   ``Mr. Bidwill was willing to listen and take a new direction in
the image of the football team,'' Ferguson said. ``What's really
gratifying is watching Mr. Bidwill's reaction and his family's
reaction and all their smiles.'' &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
