<HEADER>
A5835 &Cx1f; tic-z
r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CAR-PARSONS-RETIREMEN     01-08 0642
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CAR-PARSONS-RETIREMENT-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PARSONS ENJOYS POST-CAREER LIFE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By MARK ARMIJO  
 c.1999 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   After 21 seasons, 526 starts, 21 wins, 20 pole positions and one
NASCAR Winston Cup championship,  &UR; Benny Parsons, deservedly
selected one of the sport's top 50 drivers during last season's
50-year celebration, decided enough was enough.
</P>
<P>
   He retired.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was the perfect time for me to call it a career,'' said
Parsons, who walked away at 47 in 1988.
</P>
<P>
   Parsons, one of stock-car racing's greatest storytellers, didn't
fade into obscurity. Over the past decade, he has solidified a
reputation as being one of the top radio and television analysts in
the racing business, a career that includes an annual six-week
NASCAR Winter Heat Series stint at Tucson Raceway Park.
</P>
<P>
   ``You see a lot of talent at these (Winter Heat) races,''
Parsons said.
</P>
<P>
   Two years ago, Parsons saw a talent named  &UR; Greg Biffle and
recommended the driver to  &UR; Jack Roush.
</P>
<P>
   Today, Biffle drives for Roush on the NASCAR Craftsman Truck
Series circuit.
</P>
<P>
   As for Parsons, he has no desire to return to the driver's seat.
</P>
<P>
   ``I could make more money driving, but I enjoy what I'm doing
now and I'm in a position to make a good living at it,'' Parsons
said. ``Besides, I'm 57. I can't drive anymore.''
</P>
<P>
   If Parsons can't drive, what does that say about today's older
generation still suiting up on Sundays along the Winston Cup trail?
</P>
<P>
   ``They need to read your story,'' Parsons quipped.
</P>
<P>
   Everyone else can read what Parsons has to say about various
other topics, such as his top three picks for the upcoming season's
driving title:
</P>
<P>
   ``It would be easy to pick  &UR; Jeff  &UR; Gordon, but I like  &UR; Dale
Jarrett,'' Parsons said. ``Let's face it, if you had to bet money
on it, you've got to pick (Gordon). But I can make sense picking
(Jarrett).''
</P>
<P>
   Parsons' picks for second and third are Gordon and  &UR; Mark Martin.
</P>
<P>
   ``Other teams have to look at what Gordon's team is doing,''
Parsons said. ``Wasn't it last year about this time when (Gordon)
and (chief mechanic)  &UR; Ray
 &UR; Evernham sat down and mapped out what they wanted to do?
</P>
<P>
   ``Other teams have to do that. They have to say, `With hard
work, we can get it done.' ''
</P>
<P>
   Although Martin put together a terrific 1998 season, a season
that would have put him on the throne in many years, he still
finished runner-up to Gordon by nearly 400 points. Can Martin top
it? Or was the past season his last shot at glory?
</P>
<P>
   ``If you look at the situation, Martin's team ought to get even
better,'' Parsons said. ``Basically, it was a new team with a new
pit crew. They still had phenomenal success.''
</P>
<P>
   Parsons' sleeper pick?  &UR; Bobby Labonte.
</P>
<P>
   ``Does he count as a sleeper?'' Parsons asked. ``They stunk up
the show a couple of times, but on several occasions, they also ran
well. Right now, they're just lacking consistency.''
</P>
<P>
   Parsons on the next venue to receive a much coveted Winston Cup
race:
</P>
<P>
   ``If you go out and give Phoenix a second race, does that look
good for NASCAR?''
</P>
<P>
   Phoenix International Raceway is one of several Winston Cup
facilities owned by International Speedway Corp., whose leader is
NASCAR President  &UR; Bill France
 &UR; Jr.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think Kansas City is the next site, and after that, there's
going to have to be some decisions made,'' Parsons said.
</P>
<P>
   Parsons on the the next racetrack to possibly lose one of its
two races:
</P>
<P>
   ``I think if France can say, `Look, I took a second race from
one of our tracks,' then that would look good for NASCAR.''
</P>
<P>
   If NASCAR does pull a second race from one already on the
existing schedule, Parsons hinted it could be Darlington (S.C.)
Raceway.
</P>
<P>
   ``Who really knows,'' Parsons said. &QL; 
Mark Armijo can be reached at 602-444-8323 or at
mark.armijo(at)pni.com via e-mail. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
