<DOCNO> NYT19990108.0514 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-01-08 23:57 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5837 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FBN-BLINEBURYCOL-HNS &LR;      01-08 0804
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-BLINEBURYCOL-HNS </SLUG>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
Dolphins, Broncos talking good game
<TEXT>
<P>
   &QL; 
By Fran Blinebury &QL; 
Houston Chronicle
</P>
<P>
   DENVER _ Talk is cheap.
</P>
<P>
   Which is why you probably couldn't get $1.98 for the Dolphins'
chances of swimming out of Mile High Stadium with a win.
</P>
<P>
   After all, who can do the backstroke in frozen water? And the
weather forecast is calling for a high of 28 degrees at kickoff.
</P>
<P>
   Which is probably what coach Jimmy Johnson was saying this week
when he pointed out that his team didn't like living in the cold,
practicing in the cold or playing games in the cold.
</P>
<P>
   After all, Johnson was pointing to a map of the United States at
the time and showing us geographically challenged NFL followers
that Miami is way down there at the end of the ponytail called
Florida.
</P>
<P>
   Maybe Jimmy was just being helpful to those of us who might have
other things to do during the three-hour window when the
Dolphins-Broncos playoff game is on TV today. Because his team is a
13{-point underdog to Denver with good reason.
</P>
<P>
   Never mind Marino-Elway III. Suddenly, this has become Mind
Games.
</P>
<P>
   Johnson has been saying all week that his tight end Troy Drayton
is doubtful for the game because of a sprained ankle and his most _
maybe only _ dependable wide receiver O.J. McDuffie is questionable
with a sprained foot. These offensive injuries are on top of holes
left in the defense by linemen Jason Taylor (fractured clavicle)
and Tim Bowens (torn biceps).
</P>
<P>
   JJ back up to his old tricks
</P>
<P>
   But just when the Broncos might have been starting to feel like
they would be accused of running down Tiny Tim with a
tractor-trailer as they piled too many touchdown onto their side of
the scoreboard, a funny thing happened. Denver looked at the game
films from last week's playoff victory by Miami over Buffalo and
noticed that in the final minutes of play Drayton and McDuffie were
running their pass patterns at full speed.
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps a bit of subterfuge by Jimmy? Maybe old helmet head
figures that it never can hurt to play the poor-mouth mind games
and catch the Broncos by surprise?
</P>
<P>
   After all, remember the golden days of Jimmy in Dallas, when he
always seemed to have something extra up his sleeve for the
playoffs. If he wasn't complaining about one thing, he was lighting
a firecracker under the Cowboys in another way to get them going.
Remember the time he called up a Dallas talk-radio show on the eve
of an NFC Championship Game against San Francisco and guaranteed a
win?
</P>
<P>
   Then-49ers coach George Seifert said that stunt took brass
ornaments by Jimmy. But it worked, and the brass turned into
another set of gold Super Bowl rings.
</P>
<P>
   So here is Johnson back in the postseason and maybe he is up to
his old tricks. Or maybe he is trying to do anything to soften up
the Broncos, who figure to be hungry for revenge against his
Dolphins after losing that 31-21 decision on Dec. 21 on Monday
Night Football.
</P>
<P>
   Broncos not to be outdone
</P>
<P>
   Speaking of intrigue, there is another theory circulating
through the Mile High City and this one comes compliments of the
Broncos' owner. Pat Bowlen has been telling people he thinks Denver
coach Mike Shanahan held back the Broncos in the Dec. 21 loss.
</P>
<P>
   The basis for Bowlen's theory is the Broncos didn't have
anything to play for in that game. They had clinched home-field
advantage through the AFC playoffs and, with their hopes for a
perfect season having been ruined the week before by the Giants,
didn't want to unnecessarily give away any extra pages from their
playbook for future opponents.
</P>
<P>
   ``Mike has shown that when he gets into these types of
situations that he's got things in reserve,'' Bowlen said. ``Things
that he hasn't used yet.''
</P>
<P>
   He is hardly a secret weapon, but one of the things Shanahan
might have held back against the Dolphins was a certain Terrell
Davis, the Broncos' 2,000-yard rusher on the season. Davis gained a
season-low 29 yards on 16 carries against Miami but was given the
ball only three times in the second half.
</P>
<P>
   Surely, the shivering Dolphins can expect to see a lot more of
Davis amid the expected snow flurries at Mile High.
</P>
<P>
   Which might explain why Denver tight end Shannon Sharpe
scrutinized the rosters and the matchup the other day and
proclaimed the Broncos were ``10 to 14 points better'' than Miami.
</P>
<P>
   This, of course, produced the predictable reaction. Sharpe's
comments were quickly labeled ``bulletin-board material,'' hung up
in the Miami locker room and were said to have infuriated some
Dolphins.
</P>
<P>
   So perhaps that's what got ol' Jimmy playing mind games when he
began to talk about crippling injuries, broken-down lineups and a
team that was afraid to go out into the cold.
</P>
<P>
   Or maybe he was just telling the truth.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-01-08-99 2357EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
