<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-01-08 23:58 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5838 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FBN-ROBERTSONCOL-HNS &LR;      01-08 0866
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-ROBERTSONCOL-HNS </SLUG>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
With chips off shoulders, Chandler soars with Falcons
<TEXT>
<P>
   By DALE ROBERTSON &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Houston Chronicle
</P>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Now that the Oilers, as we knew them, have passed into
the yellowed pages of history, let it be noted that the most nearly
perfect performance by a quarterback in the 39 seasons they wore
the derrick decals on their helmets was not delivered unto us by
the ageless George Blanda, the volatile Dan Pastorini nor the
prolific Warren Moon.
</P>
<P>
   Rather, the distinction forever belongs to Chris Chandler, whose
brief Oilers tenure _ two seasons _ began with low expectations and
ended with utter ambivalence toward the oft-traveled,
success-starved sulkmeister.
</P>
<P>
   But in between, on one early-fall afternoon in Cincinnati,
Chandler found magic in a football. He attempted 26 passes against
the Bengals and completed 23 of them for 352 yards. Two of the
incompletions were outright drops, and the other was a
what-the-heck, clock-killing bomb at the end of the first half.
Four of the completions, in turn, went for touchdowns.
</P>
<P>
   ``And the next week,'' Chandler whined, ``they were handing out
Steve McNair posters. I mean, what did I have to do to get them to
throw a bone my way?''
</P>
<P>
   No dog jokes here, please.
</P>
<P>
   In truth, Chandler should be most grateful for young McNair,
whose throne he was, from the get-go, only keeping warm. The
following season, the Oilers' last in Houston, ended with Chandler
in a deep mope on the bench, suffering ostensibly from a case of
mononucleosis while McNair prepped for the job he was destined to
inherit no matter what Chandler accomplished.
</P>
<P>
   Deeming McNair properly primed for their arrival in Tennessee,
the Oilers were delighted to dump Chandler off to the Falcons for
fourth-and sixth-round draft choices, and he was equally delighted
to go. So what if Atlanta would be his sixth dead-end stop in less
than a decade? So what if the Falcons were yet another
laughingstock outpost, a franchise certain to bring out the worst
in Chandler's ``why is everybody always out to get me''
personality.
</P>
<P>
   The team and the quarterback were a matched set _ a loser for a
loser.
</P>
<P>
   But then a mystical convergence occurred. The Falcons had just
hired a coach, Dan Reeves, who had an inkling of what winning was
all about, and Chandler simultaneously experienced a sudden,
unexpected epiphany. In a blinding flash, it occurred to him that
the chips he kept lugging around on both shoulders just might be
part of the problem.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was always angry,'' he admits. ``It was like I couldn't wait
to get into a fight with someone to pout or just blow up. You want
to know when I really became a good NFL player? The day I stopped
trying to prove anything to anyone. I'd dug myself into a hole, and
I decided to dig myself out.''
</P>
<P>
   He could because under many layers of emotional baby fat lurked
a highly buffed athlete. Chandler always had oodles of ability, as
that day in Cincinnati revealed. Jerry Rhome, the offensive guru
who did the most to tap his potential, once told him: ``Chris,
you've got talent, but you don't understand the game.''
</P>
<P>
   Anyway, you know the rest. Today, shortly before noon Houston
time, Chandler finally will attempt his first postseason pass after
11 years in the NFL. He will attempt it, of course, against the
49ers, who epitomize exactly what the Falcons and Chandler never
have been.
</P>
<P>
   Champions.
</P>
<P>
   Atlanta can claim two playoff wins in its 32 previous seasons;
San Francisco possesses five Lombardi Trophies, that thing they
give to the Super Bowl's victors. But pending the outcome of this
afternoon's NFC semifinal, the Falcons appear to be the stronger
outfit.
</P>
<P>
   The Niners are old and injured, although not too old and injured
to have shoved Green Bay out of the way last week in arguably the
greatest wild-card matchup since the NFL invented the concept. San
Francisco had to participate in that high-profile prelim, of
course, because Atlanta finally had wrested the West title, and
with it, the Georgia Dome-field advantage. The Falcons are 8-0 at
home this season.
</P>
<P>
   They took the most recent meeting here convincingly _ 31-19 _
and they go to war once more behind a general who seems to be at
least the equal of the venerable, venerated Steve Young. Based on
their vastly disparate pasts, comparing Young and Chandler appears
laughable, but Young and Chandler produced almost identical regular
seasons, finishing with respective ratings of 101.1 and 100.9.
</P>
<P>
   The latter was the highest of Chandler's checkered career. Yes,
it must be said Chandler, 33, has arrived, unless he shows us
otherwise in his playoff baptism, which he shouldn't seeing as how
his support system in Atlanta is virtually failsafe between Reeves'
cautious play-calling and Jamal Anderson's prodigious ground
support.
</P>
<P>
   The Falcons, 20-4 since the middle of last season, have won nine
in a row, most recently a shocking rout of AFC semifinalist Miami,
and no longer wear a fluky look about them. They are a for-real
team with, by all accounts, a for- real quarterback.
</P>
<P>
   Stranger things have happened? Maybe, but maybe not.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
